<HEADLINE>
L.A. NEEDS THERAPY TO LOVE LAKERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Doc, Los Angeles here. Can we talk?
</P>
<P>
   It's about the Lakers. I thought we had turned a corner in our
relationship this past month. I was letting myself trust them and
it felt terrific.
</P>
<P>
   I trumpeted our relationship. I was loud and proud. I wore
Shaquille O'Neal's jersey; I was sure this was the year he was
going to give me a ring.
</P>
<P>
   I'd pull up next to Robert Horry at a stoplight and I'd gaze at
him with such pure anticipation he wanted to tape to his window a
cue card that read: ``Yes. We're going to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   I'd run into A.C. Green at the gas station and I wouldn't
pretend I didn't see him, as I was inclined to do earlier in the
year. I didn't bother acting all aloof so he couldn't see how much
I cared. I felt connected enough to him to make eye contact, to
make conversation.
</P>
<P>
   I'd say, ``You aren't going to let me down this year, are you?''
</P>
<P>
   A.C. would just smile. He didn't take my doubting personally. He
understood I was carrying around a decade of emotional baggage.
</P>
<P>
   Of course he did. He was around in the 1980s when I was so close
to the Lakers, it was hard to tell where Showtime ended and my
identity began.
</P>
<P>
   God, those were gratifying years. But it all started to change
after the Lakers suffered that setback to Phil Jackson's Chicago
Bulls in the 1991 Finals. The Lakers after that became cavalier.
They couldn't be trusted as far as Nick Van Exel could sneer.
</P>
<P>
   They were full of so many empty promises and false hope, I
learned not to expect too much so I wouldn't be let down.
</P>
<P>
   But old affections die hard. I let myself think the Lakers
finally were going to do right by me in 1998. I bought all their
sweet talk. They restored my confidence in them.
</P>
<P>
   I was naive enough to assume they had matured, that they were
sincere.
</P>
<P>
   So I couldn't help but feel betrayed when they succumbed to Utah
in the Western Conference finals without winning a game.
</P>
<P>
   They took my faith in them and twisted it until it looked
grotesque.
</P>
<P>
   Embarrassment was all I felt last year when the Lakers lost to
San Antonio in the second round of the playoffs. I was mad at
myself for allowing them to hurt me again.
</P>
<P>
   What kind of fool did they take me for, anyway?
</P>
<P>
   I have Hollywood, I have the coastline, I have the mountains, I
have the Dodgers and the Kings and the Galaxy and the upcoming
Democratic National Convention, for goodness' sake.
</P>
<P>
   I was the first to wear sunglasses at night and lacy camisoles
in broad daylight. People everywhere feed off my style, my energy,
my imagination. I didn't need the Lakers to win to feel good about
myself.
</P>
<P>
   That's what I told myself, anyway. I vowed to remain emotionally
detached from them forevermore. If they wouldn't change, I was
going to have to.
</P>
<P>
   My resolve started to unravel last June when Jackson was named
the head coach. He had effectively ended the Lakers' dynasty in
1991 so why shouldn't he be the one to restore the franchise to its
previous glory?
</P>
<P>
   The regular season started and the wins stacked up and I felt
myself succumbing, slowly but surely, to the Lakers' debonair
appeal.
</P>
<P>
   Their winning streaks of 16 and 19 games were intoxicating. I
became drunk on the possibilities. My judgment became impaired.
</P>
<P>
   Little signs that would have raised red flags for me before I
simply ignored, such was my euphoria.
</P>
<P>
   You'd have thought I would have sobered up in a hurry when
Sacramento extended the Lakers to five games in the first round of
the playoffs. That should have been a flashing neon sign that the
team was toying with my emotions again.
</P>
<P>
   When the Lakers couldn't put Phoenix away in four games in the
second round, it ought to have been painfully obvious I was being
set up for more disillusionment.
</P>
<P>
   I so wanted to believe it was going to be different this time, I
turned a blind eye to the telltale signs I've come to know and
dread.
</P>
<P>
   Now the Lakers have lost two consecutive games at home to
Portland, they've squandered one of their triple-match points and
I'm feeling featherbrained for ever believing that investing all my
emotions in the Lakers could end any other way but badly.
</P>
<P>
   All I want is to get back those old feelings again. I want it to
be the way it was in 1980, in 1982, in 1985, in 1987, in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   Tell me, Doc, is that so wrong? &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Karen Crouse's columns appear in the Daily News four days a week.
She can be reached at (818) 713-3619. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
