<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-BLAZERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT SEEMS LAKERS NEED ADVERSITY TO PLAY WELL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE DILBECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   EL SEGUNDO, Calif. _ So we've learned this much about the
Lakers: They can't play fat.
</P>
<P>
   Give them some sense of urgency, tighten the vise, make them
squirm and sweat ... and now you've got some basketball team.
</P>
<P>
   Just don't give them three games to eliminate their playoff
opponent 'cause they're just not going to get it done early.
</P>
<P>
   For these would-be Lords of the NBA, it's just so pedestrian.
</P>
<P>
   Call it overconfidence or lacking the killer instinct, say it's
being lazy or due to a a strange alignment of the stars, but the
Lakers have been at their best in the postseason when the situation
was most difficult.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers could have wiped out the Trail Blazers in five quick
games on Tuesday night, but instead suffered a 96-88 eyesore that
leaves them having to win in Portland on Friday, or be forced into
an anything-can-happen seventh game at Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, they won what should have been their two toughest
games of the series in their two previous playoff games at
Portland.
</P>
<P>
   Now, those were difficult if not unexpected. Those were right
down their we-never-do-it-the-easy-way alley.
</P>
<P>
   ``It definitely doesn't guarantee a win, but it seems so far in
these playoffs that until we feel uncomfortable, we don't really
perform the way that we should,'' Lakers guard Derek Fisher said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It almost seems instead of us having a natural sense of
urgency, we have to be put into a situation where we're forced to
have that feeling. And I think we're in that situation now.''
</P>
<P>
   This could be bad news for the Blazers. Winning three
consecutive playoff games at Portland, now there's a challenge that
should warm the Lakers' little competitive hearts.
</P>
<P>
   This should all sound familiar. The Lakers won their first two
playoff games in the opening round against the Kings, stumbled
around in Sacramento and had to go to a decisive fifth game to
advance. And they won that one 101-88.
</P>
<P>
   They had a chance to sweep the Suns in the second round, lost
and then won 87-65.
</P>
<P>
   They lost their home-court advantage with a Game 2 loss to the
Blazers at Staples Center, won consecutive games in Portland and
then flopped back at home.
</P>
<P>
   That's three consecutive times they could have closed out a
series early but stumbled.
</P>
<P>
   ``Growing pains,'' said Lakers forward Rick Fox. ``We've had
knockout punches this year in the playoffs. We know how to deliver
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now it's just doing it when it needs to be done and not
messing around. In the case of a team as good as Portland is, you
give them life and they gain confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   Mostly, the Lakers grow weary of talk about their lack of killer
instinct. Yet until they demonstrate one, they're doomed to keep
hearing it like some unwanted mantra.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can keep debating our killer instinct all the way to the
championship,'' said Lakers guard Kobe Bryant. ``We talk about
killer instinct every series, and we always seem to bounce back. We
just have to do the same thing this series.''
</P>
<P>
   To do it on Friday, they'll likely need a healthy Bryant, shoot
better than .380 percent from the field, take fewer than 27 3-point
attempts and rediscover their bench production.
</P>
<P>
   Bryant sprained his right foot Tuesday in the first half of a
miserable night for the shooting guard. He had treatment Wednesday
and is expected to be at full strength for Game 6 at Portland.
</P>
<P>
   Winning on the road has become the unexpected staple of the
Western Conference finals. The oddity of this series was the Lakers
actually winning the opener at home. The visiting team won each of
the next four. And the Lakers hadn't lost consecutive games at home
all season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think at times it's been a lack of respect on both sides
when it comes to defending their home court,'' said Fox. ``There's
no excuse for it. In the case of Portland, they knew they were
going to be eliminated and we knew had three games to eliminate
them, which is the wrong attitude.''
</P>
<P>
   Coach Phil Jackson _ never exactly shy to criticize the Lakers _
eschewed any theories that they had failed to show an ability to go
for the throat when the opportunity to close out Blazers presented
itself Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``This game didn't have anything to do with our lack of killer
instinct,'' Jackson said. ``It had a lot to do with Portland, it
had a lot to do with how the refereeing was done in the ballgame,
and how it put us on our heels and we didn't adjust in the process.
But I can't throw aspersions at our ballclub for this game.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers are operating under the
what-doesn't-kill-us-makes-us-stronger theory. They're no good at
being Team Comfy, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Immediately after Tuesday's loss, Jackson was already talking of
how the team might even be better off for having gone through a
difficult series like the one against Portland.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll let you know,'' Bryant said, ``when it's over.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
