<HEADER>
A1475 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKN-KNICKS-PACERS-ART     06-01 1036
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-PACERS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EWING RETURNS, BUT PACERS PREVAIL OVER KNICKS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT36 and NYT37 are being sent to NYT photo
clients. Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ The cruelty of Patrick Ewing's return to the New
York Knicks after the team pulled off two playoff victories without
him was punctuated with just under four minutes left in Game 5 of
the Eastern Conference finals Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   With his aching body creaking like old floorboards, Ewing
lumbered out too slow and too late to reach Sam Perkins in the left
corner of the floor. The Indianapolis Pacers' old-timer had all
night to line up a 3-pointer that took the air out of the Knicks'
plans to right their miserable second quarter with a late comeback.
</P>
<P>
   Perkins turned a six-point lead into a nine-point edge. That's
all the Pacers needed. Although Ewing was only a bit player in the
Knicks' 88-79 loss Wednesday night, he will surely receive a large
part of the criticism. The Knicks are just one game from
elimination after falling behind the Pacers 3-2. Game 6 will be
played on Friday at Madison Square Garden.
</P>
<P>
   It was Ewing's dream return at first. He made his first three
shots and sent the Knicks off to an 18-point lead early in the
second quarter, only to watch the team unravel during a nightmarish
second quarter. The Knicks scored just eight points, went 1 for 15
during the last 10 minutes and 42 seconds of the quarter and
trailed 42-40 after the Pacers' 23-3 run.
</P>
<P>
   No matter how hard they tried to repair their spirits, there was
Jalen Rose (17 points), Reggie Miller (16 points) and Travis Best
(24 points) to snuff out their comeback hopes. Allan Houston (25
points) could not pull the Knicks along by himself. The heros from
Game 3 and 4, Latrell Sprewell (4 for 14, 10 points) and Larry
Johnson (6 points), could not shake off a furious defensive effort
by Rose and Dale Davis.
</P>
<P>
   Ewing was in no shape to help either. He seemed fit in the
opening quarter, but grew increasingly out of breath as the game
continued. He finished the game with 13 points and seven rebounds
and missed five of his last seven shots.
</P>
<P>
   For almost a week, Ewing watched his team win two playoff games
without him while listening to his critics argue how the Knicks
were better when he was seated on the bench. That was enough
motivation for Ewing Wednesday night. But if he needed one more
incentive to push him through the pain during Game 5, he received
it from Jeff Van Gundy Wednesday morning.
</P>
<P>
   A blissfully unaware Rik Smits ambled into a hallway Wednesday
only to find that an indignant Van Gundy had turned his honest
replies about playing against Ewing into a gauntlet for the Knicks'
aging and injured center. On Tuesday, Smits said he preferred to
play against Ewing because he felt the 37-year-old center was
easier to score on. Ewing played him from behind, while Chris
Dudley and Kurt Thomas fronted him and denied him the ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I was Rik Smits, personally, I would not have said that,''
Van Gundy said before his team's shoot-around at Conseco
Fieldhouse. ``I've never heard anybody ask to play against Patrick.
This is a first for me. Not many guys ask to play against a Hall of
Famer at his position.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how Patrick will respond. I know one thing: he's
not usually motivated by external forces, but I've never seen
someone basically call him out.''
</P>
<P>
   Ewing responded by humiliating Smits in the opening quarter, and
leading the Knicks to a 32-17 first-quarter lead. Then the Pacers,
with Smits on the bench and Travis Best guiding their way,
responded by embarrassing the Knicks right back. In one surreal
second quarter, the Pacers unleashed a frenzied rebounding effort,
pressured the Knicks into a four turnovers and made up an 18-point
deficit. With an overpowering 23-3 run, the Pacers grabbed an
amazing 42-40 halftime lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks scored just eight points in the quarter, shot only
12.5 percent and, after holding a 37-19 lead, finished the last
10:42 of the half by shooting an abysmal 1 for 15. Once the Knicks
guards were shut down on the perimeter by Miller, Rose and Best,
they turned to Ewing, but he missed 3 of 4 jumpers in the second
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Still, their shooting effort wasn't even the worst part of their
collapse. It was their rebounding. With Camby getting beaten to the
boards by players like Austin Croshere, Best and Derrick McKey, the
Knicks were outrebounded in the second quarter, 16-8. On one play,
Best hit a 3-pointer on a third chance after two misses by Miller.
The 3-point opportunities haunted the Knicks. They gave up 4 for 9
from 3-point range in the second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   To start the third quarter, the Knicks exited the locker room
determined but unable to put up a roadblock to the momentum the
Pacers had on their side. After Houston tied the game, 45-45, on a
3-pointer, the Pacers started to barge their way inside the lane
and drew fouls along the way. With 3:55 left in the third, the
Knicks were in the penalty and Mark Jackson was at the free-throw
line after Chris Childs committed a foul away from the ball.
Jackson hit both free throws to give the Pacers a 60-51 lead.
Jackson then posted up Childs and dumped the ball in a hook shot.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks did not let the game get too far away at this point.
They clamped down on defense with Childs on Miller, forced the
Pacers into a turnover and were down just 63-55 after two free
throws by Camby with three-tenths of a second left in the third
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks had time to pull themselves together and reclaim the
edge they had when they began the night. There was such fire in the
Knicks at the start. While Smits missed baby hook shots and botched
jumpers, Ewing found his niche in the Knicks' uptempo system. He
wasn't the focus of the Knicks' offense, he was just the safety
net. Twice, he was in position for put-backs. Once, he was fouled
by Smits and converted on the 3-point play.
</P>
<P>
   As Ewing left the floor with 2:53 remaining in the first
quarter, he exited 3 for 3 with nine points and four rebounds.
Smits was 0 for 5.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
