<HEADLINE>
LANGENBRUNNER OUT FOR GAME 2
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ The Stars list winger Jamie
Langenbrunner as day to day with a sprained right knee. His
gingerly skating in practice, though, makes a month-to-month
prognosis seem more likely.
</P>
<P>
   He's hardly putting any pressure on that leg, and forget digging
for pucks in corners.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel better,'' Langenbrunner said. ``I mean it's definitely
getting better.''
</P>
<P>
   Langenbrunner hasn't played since injuring his knee in Game 5 of
the Western Conference Finals against the Colorado Avalanche. Stars
coach Ken Hitchcock said Langenbrunner won't play tonight in Game 2
of the Stanley Cup Finals.
</P>
<P>
   ``He skated \RTuesday\S, and he came up sore,'' Hitchcock said.
</P>
<P>
   Langenbrunner said Hitchcock isn't just trying to throw off the
Devils.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't be out there skating if I didn't think I could
return,'' Langenbrunner said. ``I don't know when, but I'm doing
the things I need to do to try to get back.'' Yuck Stars defenseman
Richard Matvichuk held nothing back in his assessment of why the
Stars lost Game 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``We weren't really focused. We weren't ready. For some odd
reason, we just weren't there,'' Matvichuk explained. ``Our jump
wasn't there. Our strong puck play wasn't there. Our defensive-end
coverage wasn't there. Our forecheck was horrible.'' Carbonneau a
finalist Stars center Guy Carbonneau is one of three finalists for
the 2000 William Masterton Memorial Trophy, given annually to the
player who ``exemplifies the qualities of perseverance,
sportsmanship and dedication to hockey.''
</P>
<P>
   The other finalists are New Jersey defenseman Ken Daneyko and
New York Rangers winger Adam Graves.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, it's a great honor. Any time you are mentioned for
a trophy, it means you did something,'' Carbonneau said. ``I am
sure my age had something to do with it. I've always said I enjoy
playing and I enjoy competition, and I think that's what writers
look for.''
</P>
<P>
   The winner, as selected by the Professional Hockey Writers
Association, will be announced June 15. \Nsubheds:Bouck signs
contract Right wing Tyler Bouck signed a three-year contract with
the Stars yesterday. Terms were not disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   Bouck, 20, who was selected in the second round of the 1998
entry draft, had 30 goals and 33 goals last season for Prince
George in the Western Hockey League. Bouncing back Stars defenseman
Sergei Zubov had as bad a night as goalie Ed Belfour. Zubov, who
missed the first five games of the playoffs with an injured knee,
entered last night's game a plus-6. He left a plus-2.
</P>
<P>
   He was on the ice for the game's first six goals, five of which
were scored by the Devils.
</P>
<P>
   ``Zubov was the victim of trying to do too much once we got down
a little bit,'' Stars coach Ken Hitchcock said. ``But if there is
anybody who can shake it off, it is Zuby.'' Sixth sense Backup
goalie Manny Fernandez did not know that Ed Belfour was not feeling
well, but Fernandez suspected something was wrong after the first
period.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was showing signs that he doesn't show usually,'' said
Fernandez, who replaced Belfour with a little less than 17 minutes
remaining. ``I could tell there was something wrong. If it would
have been a regular-season game, they probably would have made me
play, but it's the playoffs, and he's going to battle through it.''
Road trip This is the first time since 1995 that the Stars haven't
had home-ice advantage. The Stars are 10-9 in road playoff games in
the 1999 and 2000 playoffs and have lost the first road game in
each of their four series this year. Counting on Guy Stars center
Guy Carbonneau, 40, quit counting a long time ago. Every time
someone tells him he has moved up the NHL's record book again, he
shrugs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like statistics that much, so I'm not the guy that
looks at the things that I do,'' Carbonneau said. ``I wouldn't know
how many games or how many goals I have.''
</P>
<P>
   Carbonneau has played in 226 playoff games, one behind
second-place Larry Robinson, now the Devils' coach, and 10 behind
Mark Messier.
</P>
<P>
   ``It means I've been lucky to play for good teams,'' Carbonneau
said. ``I've always said that this is the best time of the year. To
be able to play that many games means that you've been successful
throughout your career.'' Quotable ``I find, myself, I'm bad for
the newspaper business. Because I don't buy newspapers when we get
drilled like that.'' _ Stars coach Ken Hitchcock Compiled by staff
writers Jennifer Floyd, Charean Williams and Mac Engel.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
