<HEADLINE>
DEVILS CONTINUE TO SHOW DISCIPLINE IN PLAYOFF RUN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By J. DOUGLAS FOSTER 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ Fluid skating. Pinpoint passing.
Precision shooting.
</P>
<P>
   The New Jersey Devils were given deserved credit for all of the
above after their 7-3 beating of the Stars in Game 1 of the Stanley
Cup Finals. After all, they did outskate and outshoot the Stars,
and limited their turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   What went slightly unnoticed _ but equally important _ was the
Devils' discipline, something that's been a strength throughout the
playoffs in spite of New Jersey's reputation for physical play. The
Devils were not penalized in Game 1.
</P>
<P>
   Devils coach Larry Robinson found that, in the face of Dallas'
physical play, to be extremely important.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know our guys took a lot of whacks and high sticks and
elbows and everything last night, and I thought we kept our
composure very well,'' Robinson said. ``We are going to have to
continue doing that.''
</P>
<P>
   It's something New Jersey has done well throughout the
postseason. In 18 playoff games, the Devils have given the
opposition only 51 power plays. Dallas, by comparison, has been
short-handed on 90 occasions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got whacked pretty good at times, but took the punishment
and answered with goals,'' Devils winger Claude Lemieux said.
``That's the best way to answer.'' \Nsubheds:Role reversal Nobody
could stop talking about Scott Stevens' hit on Philadelphia's Eric
Lindros in Game 7 of the Eastern Conference Finals, or about
Stevens' physical play in general.
</P>
<P>
   Well he showed them. Stevens, it seems, is more than just a
hitter. He can hit the net, too. In Game 1, Stevens had more goals
(one) than hits (zero), showing how versatile the Devils' captain
can be.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every game is different,'' Stevens said. ``That game was more
positional. There wasn't a lot of hits either way. It was more of a
skating game and checking game.'' \Nsubheds:Scoring machines Martin
Brodeur has seen the offensive capabilities of the line of Jason
Arnott, Petr Sykora and Patrik Elias many times in practice. So
their four goals and seven assists in Game 1 _ even against a
goalie the caliber of Ed Belfour _ didn't completely surprise him.
</P>
<P>
   ``They love to score,'' Brodeur said. ``It is tough when you go
out every time and they just love to score and they brag about it
and they laugh about you when you can't stop them. It gets annoying
at times. That is why they are successful.'' \Nsubheds:Madden to
play Devils center John Madden reinjured a knee in Game 1 but said
there's no question about his status for Game 2: He's definite.
</P>
<P>
   ``The brace moved on me and tweaked my leg a little bit, nothing
serious,'' Madden said. ``It will happen throughout the rest of the
season. I could have come back, but the score was 7-3 with about
three minutes left, so why chance it?''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
