<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-SANDERS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COWBOYS HAVE TO CUT SANDERS BEFORE SATURDAY OR PAY UP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CLARENCE E. HILL JR. 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Sometime in the next two days, Deion Sanders
will be released by the Cowboys, and he is expected to become the
league's most coveted free agent again.
</P>
<P>
   Washington, Tampa Bay and Denver already are expected to be the
leading bidders for the perennial All-Pro cornerback, who is
reportedly looking for a multiyear deal and a signing bonus of no
less than $8 million.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys had to wait until today to make any move with
Sanders to lessen the impact on the 2000 salary cap. Fullback Daryl
Johnston, who is expected to retire because of a neck injury, is
expected to have his contract terminated for the same reason.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys have to cut Sanders before Saturday or his money for
the next two seasons _ a $10 million roster bonus and $500,000 in
base salary this season, and a $13 million salary next season _
will be guaranteed.
</P>
<P>
   Sanders, 32, has anticipated becoming a free agent again since
the end of the 1999 season. Yet, as the deadline approaches, the
normally chatty Sanders wanted no part of the speculation that
surrounds his plans.
</P>
<P>
   He declined to comment on ``where I'm going or what I'm going to
do.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to talk about football,'' Sanders said.
</P>
<P>
   Sanders, however, would say that he is healthy, has no regrets
or lasting disappointments about his failed baseball comeback or
his failure to join the Rangers, and is ready to be a full-time
football player again.
</P>
<P>
   Sanders says his injured knee, which required surgery after the
Cowboys' playoff loss to the Minnesota Vikings and hampered him
during his baseball stint with the Cincinnati Reds, is fine.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel good,'' Sanders said. ``My health is good.''
</P>
<P>
   Sanders, who has missed 10 games because of injuries the past
four years, says he feels better than he has in several years and
credits nationally renowned speed coach Tom Shaw. Sanders has
worked exclusively with Shaw since being cut by the Reds about
three weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   He also says he _ not the Reds _ ended his baseball comeback.
Despite his .200 batting average with the Triple-A Louisville
Riverbats, Sanders said the Reds were interested in his staying and
that other teams were interested in acquiring him.
</P>
<P>
   His wishes, however, were to play in the majors and play for the
Rangers. The Rangers, who were shopping for outfield depth and a
leadoff hitter, never made a serious bid for Sanders.
</P>
<P>
   He said the main reason he gave up on baseball was to spend more
time with his children before football season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't crushed that it didn't work out,'' Sanders said. ``I
accomplished what I wanted. I wanted to give it a shot and see if I
could make a comeback. I didn't want to wait until I was too old
and wonder what if. In the end, I did what was best for me and my
family.''
</P>
<P>
   Sanders' decision also was best for his future in football. He
would have been hard-pressed to get the money he wants if he had
played a full season of baseball. Football teams will be more
inclined to pay Sanders at his market value knowing that he will be
in training camp and play a full season.
</P>
<P>
   Washington is probably the last place that Cowboys owner Jerry
Jones wants Sanders to end up. However, there's seemingly little
Jones can do about it.
</P>
<P>
   Jones was unavailable for comment yesterday. He is expected to
take the Cowboys coaches on a three-day trip to Las Vegas today.
</P>
<P>
   Even after being released, Sanders will count $2.2 million
against the Cowboys' salary cap in 2000. However, if they had cut
him before today, his contract would have counted $5.4 million
against the cap because of signing bonus money. Now, the Cowboys
can split that money up over two seasons, with $3.2 counting
against the cap in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Cutting Sanders and Johnston will free up $1 million under the
cap by eliminating the $500,000 base salary of each. Johnston still
will get $466,700 in 2000 and 2001 because of bonus money.
</P>
<P>
   Jones hasn't totally ruled out the possibility of Sanders'
returning to Dallas. But that's only if Sanders doesn't get the
money he expects on the open market and decides he would rather
stay here for less money than go elsewhere for less money.
</P>
<P>
   Both scenarios are unlikely. Sanders, who has said in the past
that his career as a Cowboys player is over, declined to comment
yesterday on whether he had reconsidered playing for the Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   The Redskins are considered the front-runners for Sanders'
services. Owner Daniel Snyder, who has already added a number of
prominent free agents to the roster, has said he will do whatever
it takes to get Sanders. Longtime standout cornerback Darrell Green
even has agreed to relinquish his starting job to Sanders without a
fuss.
</P>
<P>
   The past also has shown that Sanders, who considers himself a
hired gun, has no problem playing for a rival. He left Atlanta in
1994 to join NFC West Division competitors San Francisco. The San
Francisco 49ers won the Super Bowl that year, while ending the
Cowboys' quest for three consecutive Super Bowl titles.
</P>
<P>
   A year later, he broke the hearts of San Francisco fans when he
joined the rival Cowboys and helped them regain the Super Bowl
title.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
