<HEADLINE>
KENNEDY GETS ANOTHER DAY TO RECHARGE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.2000 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ Second baseman Adam Kennedy was not in the starting
lineup for the second game in a row Wednesday, but he'll be back on
Friday when the Angels begin a three-game series against the
Dodgers at Edison Field.
</P>
<P>
   Giving Kennedy the final two days of the month off seemed to be
a good idea considering the month Kennedy had. He hit .192 in May
after a .318 April. Kennedy had more RBI in one game _ eight on
April 18 at Toronto _ than in the entire month of May (five).
Overall, Kennedy is hitting .257.
</P>
<P>
   His problem at the plate isn't anything that can be corrected
simply by looking at videotape and making a few adjustments,
hitting coach Mickey Hatcher said.
</P>
<P>
   ``When a young guy struggles, most of it is in his head,''
Hatcher said. ``Right now, he's battling himself more than anything
he's doing mechanically. We know he can play. Right now he's
beating himself up fundamentally and mentally.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best thing sometimes is just to take a couple of days off
and clear your mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy said he has tried to remember how he felt and what he
was doing when he got off to such a hot start in April.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest picture from that time was I remember how the ball
was so big,'' Kennedy said. ``I could slow everything down. Now,
everything's happening so fast. I need to get back to everything
happening at a slower pace.''
</P>
<P>
   ON FINLEY: Wednesday's game was not the first time manager Mike
Scioscia has seen Chuck Finley pitch. Scioscia caught Finley in
1990 when the two were part of an All-Star team touring Japan.
</P>
<P>
   He said he understands the ties Finley has to many in the Angels
organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since 1986 (when Finley joined the Angels) the pitching staffs
have evolved and the only constant was Chuck Finley,'' Scioscia
said. ``He was !ital!the!off! Angel starter for that long. He has
close friends here, but the game transcends that once you get on
the field.''
</P>
<P>
   SHORT HOPS: Pitcher Tim Belcher threw about 40 pitches during a
three-inning simulated game Wednesday and felt fine. He will go to
Fresno on Monday to pitch for Triple-A Edmonton on a rehab
assignment. He underwent offseason elbow surgery. He's expected to
make two rehab starts for the Trappers before joining the Angels
rotation around June 15.... Shortstop Benji Gil snapped an 0-for-24
slide with a single in the sixth inning Wednesday.... The Angels
are off today, then begin a six-game homestand against the Dodgers
and Giants starting Friday. &QL;
</P>
