<SLUG> BC-TWA-INQUIRY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PENTAGON TEST-FIRES MISSILES TO FINISH TWA INQUIRY 
</HEADLINE>
   By MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Federal crash investigators had the Pentagon
test-fire Stinger missiles last month off the coast of Florida to
see if the resulting streaks resembled those described by witnesses
to the explosion of TWA Flight 800, a spokesman for the National
Transportation Safety Board said on Wednesday evening.
</P>
<P>
   The board has already concluded that the plane, a Boeing 747
that blew up off the coast of Long Island minutes after it left
Kennedy International Airport for Paris in July 1996, was not
brought down by a missile. And the spokesman said last month's test
did not change their conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing here should be construed to show that there's been any
new finding or change in the wreckage that we've been studying,''
said Ted Lopatkiewicz, the board's spokesman. ``This is part of our
effort to close all the open parts of the investigation.'' The
tests were first reported in Thursday's Washington Post.
</P>
<P>
   The Safety Board plans to meet on Aug. 22 to consider a report
on the cause of the crash, which killed all 230 people aboard.
</P>
<P>
   The board has already said that the cause was an explosion in
the center fuel tank, and has conducted extensive laboratory work
demonstrating that an explosive atmosphere often develops in such
tanks.
</P>
<P>
   The board's investigation has also shown that wiring defects
could, in theory, introduce a spark that would set off an
explosion. But it has not established precisely what set off the
tank, according to investigators.
</P>
<P>
   Lopatkiewicz said the board could issue a final report without
identifying the precise source of ignition.
</P>
<P>
   The board has already said that there is no hold in the wreckage
that would indicate a missile entry, and no metal bent by high
explosives of the kind used in a missle or a bomb.
</P>
<P>
   In major crashes, the safety board routinely prepares a report
on what witnesses saw, but in this case the investigators got a
very late start on that element of the investigation, because it
was handled by the FBI until only recently.
</P>
<P>
   Because it is unusual for an airplane to explode in flight,
investigators immediately after the crash looked hard for signs of
a bomb or missile, but eventually ruled out both possibilities.
</P>
<P>
   Last month's tests were conducted at Eglin Air Force Base in
Florida at a time of day when the sun was at an elevation similar
to its position at the time the plane exploded, and in similar
weather conditions. The team postponed the test on several
occasions until visibility was similar to the haze at dusk at the
time of the crash, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Stinger is an Army missile. Civilian experts say its range
is probably insufficient to have reached Flight 800.
</P>
<P>
   There were 244 witnesses to the crash who said they saw streaks
of light.
</P>
<P>
   At hearings after the crash, board investigators said that after
an explosion severed the front part of the airplane, the remaining
part of the plane, including the wings and the bulk of the
fuselage, would have pitched up and climbed steeply, causing an
upward streak of light.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-01-00 0034EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
