<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-WISE-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON BASKETBALL: JACKSON AND PACERS EXPROPRIATE KNICKS' SWAGGER
</HEADLINE>
  By MIKE WISE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ It was the middle of the third quarter, and Mark
Jackson, having been outplayed by the most maligned starting point
guard in pro basketball for much of the series, had had enough.
</P>
<P>
   He backed Charlie Ward into the post for the second straight
time, pounding the ball hard to the floor before releasing another
soft jump hook that rolled around and down.
</P>
<P>
   The Indiana Pacers, who were out of this game _ and very likely
out of the Eastern Conference finals Friday night _ had startlingly
recovered from an 18-point first-half deficit to lead by seven.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson, fed up with the posing and posturing of Larry Johnson
and those renegade New York Knicks, mockingly flashed the ``Big L''
sign toward the Knicks' bench after he scored.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, Reggie Miller finished a 3-pointer over Allan Houston
by staring down the Knicks guard as if he had committed some
heinous act against a close relative.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks often live to display their cocksure behavior, preen
for America and NBC, bump chests until the cameras stop rolling.
But this is what their swagger sometimes begets, this is the other
half of showing people up on their home floor.
</P>
<P>
   They collapsed at the Conseco Fieldhouse Wednesday night, 88-79,
blowing a grand opportunity to go up by 3-2 in the best-of-7 series
and maybe close out the Pacers at Madison Square Garden less than
48 hours from now.
</P>
<P>
   It was not a complete meltdown, because they came back in the
fourth quarter and made it a tremendous game. But the music
performed over the weekend in New York _ the jazzy syncopation that
made them so entertaining and efficient _ was gone.
</P>
<P>
   The return of Patrick Ewing was not to blame as much as an
almost arrogant attitude that seemed to take hold of the Knicks
midway through the second quarter. Did you see that eyesore? The
Pacers went on a 23-3 splurge, taking a halftime lead because the
Knicks suddenly got comfortable with their confidence.
</P>
<P>
   Indiana showed heart, especially Miller, Jalen Rose and Travis
Best, who finally looked for the open man before he dribbled the
shot clock away or took a bad shot. The Pacers showed the kind of
resolve the Knicks did over the weekend. But that run said so much
about the Knicks' ability to deal with prosperity, the feeling that
they got so far under Indiana's skin that the series was all but
over after their devastating 32-17 first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   They genuinely thought they had this game won. That's the only
way to explain how the Pacers somehow grabbed three offensive
rebounds on one possession in the second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   When the Pacers began giving it back, going after loose balls,
flying through the lane without a care for their health, the Knicks
were suddenly the frustrated, poor-shooting team unable to find a
rhythm.
</P>
<P>
   Look, it's hard to completely knock this crew about what they
have been through. Rewind to that Game 5 loss in Miami that seemed
so long ago, and it is clear they do their best work when their
tank is flickering on empty.
</P>
<P>
   But the numbers don't lie. Latrell Sprewell, dribbling furiously
with the shot clock running out, throwing up junk that amounted to
a 3-for-13 night. Johnson, invisible in the post after basking in
self-congratulatory fashion in Games 3 and 4, putting up a 2-for-8,
four-point line. The Knicks' bench, unable to put up enough offense
or defense to push the Pacers and make them think about going to
the Garden with their season on the line.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who watched Derrick McKey hunt down an errant rebound on
the right baseline in front of the Knicks' bench with 4 1-2 minutes
left Wednesday night had to wonder how much those two victories at
the Garden last Saturday and Monday convinced the Knicks they were
finals-bound.
</P>
<P>
   For all the great play Ward has summoned in this series, neither
he nor Childs had an answer for Best and Jackson, who combined for
32 points and 10 assists to the Knicks backcourt's 12 points and
eight assists.
</P>
<P>
   A little anecdote from practice on Tuesday told you a lot about
these guys. Johnson began laughing, breaking up over the newfound
celebrity of a former teammate. It was not enough that they were
chanting Ward's name last weekend at the Garden. But holding court
in the rotunda after the game, using sarcasm and wit in front of
the cameras?
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, C. Ward, I heard you were up at the podium yesterday,''
Johnson said. ``Man, that's just like Florida State.''
</P>
<P>
   Ward grinned, mimicked that crazy, left-handed running shot
Johnson somehow flicks in and tried to make an inconspicuous exit
to the locker room at SUNY-Purchase. Before he stepped off the
court, he was engulfed by bright lights, notebooks and
microcassette recorders.
</P>
<P>
   C. Ward, the former Heisman Trophy winner, was the big man on
campus again, sacrificing his body, quarterbacking another
nationally ranked team toward a crucial game.
</P>
<P>
   It was a nice moment, but there was something altogether
premature about it, as if they didn't realize the series was
knotted at 2-2 and not 3-2, New York.
</P>
<P>
   At any rate, rather than building a relationship with success,
they seem to treat it as some weekend fling that means nothing
until they're faced with an ultimatum. Win or book a flight to the
Bahamas.
</P>
<P>
   Somehow, they have once again set themselves up for such a
predicament in Game 6 at the Garden Friday night. If Mark Jackson
is flashing the ``L'' sign toward their bench then, consider their
swagger and their resolve tapped out. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-01-00 0035EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
