<HEADLINE>
STRUGGLING CLAYTON FINDS WAYS TO HELP RANGERS WIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ Royce Clayton's offensive contributions have been
almost negligible the past two weeks. So the Rangers' slumping
shortstop went out last night and helped his team win by simply
playing the game right.
</P>
<P>
   He beat out a hit on what should have been a sacrifice bunt. He
went hard into second base to break up what could have been a
double play. On another play, he took second base when he noticed
the catcher couldn't find a ball that had rolled only a few feet
away. He had a bloop single and drew two walks that helped mount
big rallies.
</P>
<P>
   All those little things kept coming up big on a night when the
Rangers' offense overcame pitcher Darren Oliver's continuing
physical problems, leading to a 13-5 pounding of the Detroit Tigers
at Comerica Park. The victory allowed the Rangers to take two of
three from the Tigers and finish their three-city tour of the
Midwest with a 4-5 record.
</P>
<P>
   ``Little big things,'' outfielder Rusty Greer said. ``I think
that's what Royce is good at. We count on him making that little
big play and doing what it takes to win.''
</P>
<P>
   But any euphoria about the victory has to be tempered by
Oliver's situation. He complained of a dead arm after his previous
start against the Minnesota Twins and said it wasn't much better
last night, even though his radar-gun readings were back to normal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I might have to miss a start,'' said Oliver, who is scheduled
to pitch Monday against the Los Angeles Dodgers. ``We'll see
Friday. Instead of getting stronger, it was getting weaker. I don't
care what the radar gun says; I know what my body says.''
</P>
<P>
   Oliver gave up five runs on eight hits and five walks with two
strikeouts. He is 2-3 with a 5.98 ERA and was fortunate the Rangers
broke out the bats last night.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers finished with 16 hits. Rafael Palmeiro went 3-for-6
with a home run and four runs batted in, Rusty Greer had four RBI,
Ruben Mateo went 3-for-5 and Luis Alicea had a two doubles, a
triple, two walks and four runs scored.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tonight was the best we've swung the bats in a week,'' Rangers
manager Johnny Oates said.
</P>
<P>
   Clayton hasn't swung the bat well in a couple of weeks. He was
2-for-3 Tuesday, which helped slow down a 1-for-28 skid, and had
two more hits last night, but it has been a struggle for him
lately.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't say it's just been a couple of weeks,'' Clayton
said. ``The toughest thing was I lost my grandma a couple days ago,
other things outside baseball. I'm just looking forward to getting
back home, seeing my family and putting some stuff behind me. Hot
streaks, colds streaks, they come and go. Things outside baseball
are more important.''
</P>
<P>
   Clayton is someone who loves to have fun in baseball, but that
doesn't seem to be the case right now.
</P>
<P>
   ``I come here, do my job and go home,'' Clayton said. ``That's
how it's going to be.''
</P>
<P>
   And the fun part?
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe one day it will come back,'' Clayton said.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers will have to settle for hard-nosed play. They were
leading 2-1 in the second when, with the bases loaded and one out,
Greer hit a double-play grounder to second baseman Jose Macias. But
Clayton went hard into shortstop Deivi Cruz, and his relay went
flying into the Rangers' dugout. Two runs scored, giving the
Rangers a 4-1 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``From no runs to two runs,'' Oates said. ``Royce made it tough
for him. That's what you want everybody to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Clayton: ``Even if you're not going well, you can still do
something to help the team win. It may not go big in the box
scores, but there are other ways to help a team win.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
