<SLUG> BC-OSTLER-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 FINE EXAMPLE OF HOW S.F. WORKS  &HT;     By SCOTT OSTLER 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ I just got back from the Hallidie Mystery Plaza,
and the city is really blowing it there.
</P>
<P>
   This place, marketed correctly, could be San Francisco's biggest
attraction. Guided tours of the hole in the ground that confounds
science and bureaucracy! An amazing harmonic convergence where
nothing works!
</P>
<P>
   Tourists and locals alike will be amazed, astounded and injured!
</P>
<P>
   The plaza, being next to the cable car turnaround, a major
BART/ &QL; 
Muni station, major shopping and the tourist information center,
already has a zillion visitors a day, seeing all this stuff for
free. It's a cash cow sauntering around unmilked!
</P>
<P>
   I volunteer to be the barker.
</P>
<P>
   See the mysterious shifting stairway! The steps, granite slabs,
apparently were improperly installed. They have shifted, creating
tiny and large steps. It's a great spot for watching people slip
and trip.
</P>
<P>
   The DPW tells me they'll have the steps fixed soon; maybe Mayor
Brown could stall 'em.
</P>
<P>
   See the mysterious nonescalating escalators! They work as often
as my uncle Fred.
</P>
<P>
   The elevator repairmen tell me the problem is that the city
hoses off the plaza every day, and sometimes the drains clog and
the water backs up into the escalator mechanism and poof, another
month or two on the fritz.
</P>
<P>
   See the mysterious elevator, stalled by mysterious bureaucracy!
It's been out of action for a month or more.
</P>
<P>
   The 'vator belongs to the Department of Real Estate, but it
doesn't have the cash to fix it, the city's real estate being in
the horrible slump it's in.
</P>
<P>
   So they're handing off the problem to the DPW, but that handoff
could take who knows how long. And the DPW tells one merchant in
the plaza that the DPW doesn't have the money to fix the elevator.
</P>
<P>
   See the elderly, the large and the variously disabled claw their
way up the stairway I call Mt. Hallidie!
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, within minutes, I saw several people stumble, at
least two almost going down. I saw one woman crawl up the steps,
using her hands. Moms with baby carriages really work out! It's
like boot camp for civilians!
</P>
<P>
   I laughed so hard I had to rush through one of the few working
BART turnstiles to get to the men's room. It was out of order.
</P>
<P>
   WHAT ARE the odds? (Note to mathematicians: That's just an
expression; I don't really want to know.)
</P>
<P>
   At Tuesday night's Giants-Phillies game, Lance Greenfield saw a
fan seated just in front of the press box catch a foul ball. Very
next pitch, to the same Phillie batter, another foul ball, same
place, this one snagged by the first guy's pal, in the very next
seat.
</P>
<P>
   I tell you, that is a house of miracles.
</P>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO: The city that doesn't hound celebrities.
</P>
<P>
   Seriously. I hear it often: Big star comes to town, is able to
walk streets, eat in restaurants without being smothered by gushing
fans.
</P>
<P>
   Either we're terribly cool, or not cool enough to know a star
when we see one. (Although a Mark McGwire, for instance, is hard to
miss.)
</P>
<P>
   Latest example: Ze lovely Charlize Theron (``Cider House
Rules'') and the lovely Stephan Jenkins (lead singer, Third Eye
Blind) have been hanging out in the Mission, at Foreign Cinema and
the newly reopened Brunos, giggling and snuggling, and nobody
bothers 'em (except me, in this item).
</P>
<P>
   CONVERSELY, this city treats should-be celebs like celebs.
</P>
<P>
   Example: The Mabel Mercer Foundation's annual Cabaret Convention
(415-441-5232) hits town for a week starting Monday, and about 90
talented performers, many of whom toil in semi-obscurity, will sing
for packed houses at USF's Gershwin Theater.
</P>
<P>
   Catch a preview Sunday when cab legend Billy Stritch performs at
a brunch/live KKSF broadcast at the Anza Restaurant in the Hotel
Nikko.
</P>
<P>
   COPS AND a TV crew riddled a Muni bus with automatic weapons
fire.
</P>
<P>
   Why? Because it was cool. This one has NRA fund-raiser potential
written all over it.
</P>
<P>
   NEXT RELIC for bid: A first-printing copy of the Declaration of
Independence.
</P>
<P>
   The Declaration will be auctioned off, online, on June 29 by
Sothebys. There are 25 known copies, 24 of which are in
institutions or headed to same.
</P>
<P>
   So this is your last chance to have the Dec for your rec room,
hanging between your bowling trophy and your mounted trout.
</P>
<P>
   The famed document will be on display this morning at Buck's
restaurant in Silicon Valley. Soon available, no doubt: Silk
jackets _ ``Declaration of Independence In-Yer-Face-John-Bull
National Tour '00.''
</P>
<P>
   Put your hands together, fans, for our country's nuttiest piece
of parchment.
</P>
<P>
   Me, I'm saving my money to bid on a George Washington rookie
card.
</P>
<P>
   SO WHAT if the S.F. cops shot the smithereens out of that Muni
bus?
</P>
<P>
   The important thing is that they finally ended the crime rampage
of Bonnie and Clyde.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-01-00 0041EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
