<SLUG> BC-WORKPLACE-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE DEBATE RAGES: CULTIVATING VS. IMPORTING A WORK FORCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE STAFFORD  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY: Is there a shortage of high-tech workers in the
United States?
</P>
<P>
   The question dominates the H-1B debate in Congress, Silicon
Valley and all the Silicon Valley wannabes from coast to coast.
</P>
<P>
   If H-1B sounds like a new immunization recommended for infants,
you're not alone in your confusion. Unless you're involved in
immigration law or hiring high-tech workers, H-1B visas may not be
on your radar screen.
</P>
<P>
   They could be on your neighbor's, though. Consider the letter I
received Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The wife of an Overland Park, Kan., man, who had earned a
bachelor's degree in electronic engineering technology and later
returned to school to add an associate degree in information
technology, wonders how he ``fell through the crack in this `good'
economy.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite his degrees, more than 20 years of job experience and
further work on an Microsoft certified systems engineer credential,
he makes less than $30,000 a year and has been downsized from
several jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Workers like these have trouble understanding the high-tech
industry's current push to increase _ or remove entirely _ limits
on the number of H-1B visas. These are three-year, renewable visas
that allow skilled, college-degreed foreign workers to work in the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   Several high-tech industry trade groups are lobbying Congress to
raise H-1B limits. This year, U.S. employers reached the fiscal
year H-1B limit of 115,000 workers before the year was half over.
They say they desperately need foreign workers because they can't
find enough skilled workers domestically.
</P>
<P>
   On the other side, those who oppose raising H-1B visa quotas say
there are plenty of willing and trainable workers in the United
States. They accuse employers of looking for cheap, temporary fixes
to fill jobs rather than investing in education and training for
Americans.
</P>
<P>
   As usual, both sides trot out statistics to support their
assertions. Also as usual, the truth lies somewhere in the middle.
</P>
<P>
   But seeping out of the high-tech office parks and oozing out of
my mail is persistent anecdotal evidence that America's older
workers aren't getting or keeping jobs in the high-tech world.
</P>
<P>
   Is it bald-faced age discrimination? Is it older workers'
inability to adapt to the high-tech pace of business? Inadequate
up-to-date skills? A problem of older workers expecting too much
pay?
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the reason, worker resentment is building against
allowing into America more young computer jockeys from, say, India
(which supplies the largest share of H-1B visa workers).
</P>
<P>
   It costs employers considerable time and money to wade though
the paperwork required to sponsor H-1B visas. One bill before the
U.S. House would double the H-1B filing fee.
</P>
<P>
   If, as many employers contend, it costs more to hire H-1B
workers (about $10,000 to $15,000 per worker, according to a
Microsoft hiring executive), why isn't it possible, if not more
sensible, to use that sum to train U.S. workers instead?
</P>
<P>
   I have no beef with welcoming more productive immigrants to
American soil. I'd just like to know we're cultivating the workers
already planted here.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-01-00 0042EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
