<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCAIN-CAMPAIGN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 MCCAIN TOUTS GOP CANDIDATES IN BAY AREA VISIT  &HT;     By CAROLYNE ZINKO 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Arizona Sen. John McCain made his first visit to
the Bay Area Wednesday since the GOP presidential primary, boosting
Republican congressional candidates while only mildly stumping for
his former opponent, Texas Gov. George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   In a swing through California on behalf of four candidates,
McCain appeared at a morning town hall meeting and a luncheon
fund-raiser for California Assemblyman Jim Cunneen, R-San Jose. He
also endorsed Tom Campbell for U.S. Senate. Campbell is leaving his
South Bay congressional seat to run against Democratic Sen. Dianne
Feinstein.
</P>
<P>
   Cunneen is running against Assemblyman Mike Honda, D-San Jose,
for Campbell's 15th Congressional District seat, one of a handful
of seats around the nation that both political parties consider key
to controlling the House of Representatives.
</P>
<P>
   Republican strategists hoped that McCain's appearance would help
both Cunneen and Campbell draw the independents and Democrats who
voted for McCain in the March primary.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very pleased with the campaign that we had and the things
we were able to accomplish,'' McCain told more than 100 supporters
at a luncheon at the Santa Clara Marriott, which raised $50,000 for
Cunneen.
</P>
<P>
   McCain noted he was able to draw to the polls voters who usually
do not vote Republican.
</P>
<P>
   Citing the Michigan primary, which he won, McCain said 38
percent of those who participated had never voted before &LR; . McCain
said he also won 20 percent of the African American vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gov. Bush and I showed you can galvanize a group of voters to
vote that never voted before,'' McCain told the luncheon crowd.
</P>
<P>
   McCain said his message of reform and integrity connected with
disenchanted voters, and that Cunneen and Campbell have the same
appeal.
</P>
<P>
   McCain praised Cunneen as a candidate with the enthusiasm and
intellect to represent Silicon Valley, a district that is
influential in the House because of the valley's emergence as the
engine of economic growth for California and the nation.
</P>
<P>
   He also took a page from his presidential campaign in lauding
Cunneen for integrity and independence.
</P>
<P>
   Cunneen was a co-author of a measure to require disclosure of
campaign financing on the Internet, and he was one of the few
Republicans to support Proposition 208. The voter-approved 1996
state initiative included limits on campaign contributions, but was
struck down by a federal judge.
</P>
<P>
   At both Cunneen events, McCain added praise for Bush, but it was
clearly secondary to the business that brought him to the Bay Area.
</P>
<P>
   ``The time is obviously now to unite our party to elect George
W. Bush to president of the United States,'' he said at the
luncheon.
</P>
<P>
   Across town, the Democrats' Honda got a lift from House Minority
Leader Richard Gephardt, D-Mo., who joined California Democratic
Reps. Anna Eshoo and Zoe Lofgren in a rally with Million Mom March
participants and students at Santa Clara High School. Honda did not
attend, staying in Sacramento to vote on gun control measures in
the Assembly.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, at a Burlingame news conference to endorse Campbell,
McCain urged Bush to campaign heavily in California, saying it was
a ``very serious mistake'' for Republicans to concede the state in
1992 and 1996.
</P>
<P>
   But McCain said he did not know if he would campaign again in
California for Bush, although he will return to the state in
September or October for congressional candidates.
</P>
<P>
   McCain said his staff and Bush's are negotiating where he will
campaign, and that it appears he will spend more time in the
Northeast.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, McCain had appeared at a fund-raiser on behalf of
Rep. James Rogan, R-Calif. Rogan, one of the House members who
prosecuted President Clinton's impeachment, faces a re-election
struggle against state Sen. Adam Schiff, D-Burbank, in the 27th
Congressional District.
</P>
<P>
   McCain also is scheduled to make appearances this week in the
36th Congressional District on the Palos Verdes peninsula, where
first-term incumbent Republican Steve Kuykendall faces a stiff
November challenge from Democrat Jane Harman, and in the 49th
Congressional District on the Southern California coast, where
two-term Republican incumbent Brian Bilbray is being challenged by
Assemblywoman Susan Davis, D-San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   (Chronicle staff writer Marc Simon contributed to this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-01-00 0046EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
