<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CASINO-SALE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MISSOURI GAMING COMMISSION APPROVES SALE OF KANSAS CITY CASINO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICK ALM  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ The sale of the Flamingo Hilton Casino to
Mississippi-based Isle of Capri Casinos Inc. was unanimously
approved Wednesday by the Missouri Gaming Commission, and the
casino will change hands Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Commissioners meeting in Kansas City also proposed $500,000 in
fines against five casinos _ including all four in Kansas City _ in
the wake of an undercover sting operation resulting in allegations
that gamblers were being allowed to skirt the state's $500 loss
limit rules.
</P>
<P>
   The commission also proposed suspending four fraternal
organizations' bingo licenses for up to a year for multiple gaming
law violations, including operating illegal slot machines on the
premises. The Eagles club in Poplar Bluff is accused of running a
small casino in a back room that was accessible only by electronic
key card.
</P>
<P>
   All those fined have 30 days to appeal the action and force a
public hearing that would be conducted like a trial.
</P>
<P>
   As for the Flamingo, patrons won't notice the ownership change
until this fall.
</P>
<P>
   Although the sale is to close Monday, the casino will remain
open under the Hilton Hotels Corp.'s Flamingo banner until the $15
million physical remodeling of the facility and conversion to
Isle's procedures are completed around Sept. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City Mayor Kay Barnes urged commissioners to ratify the
sale and license the company, the nation's eighth-largest gambling
firm.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor noted the casino's 800 jobs and millions of tax
dollars it pumps into the city's coffers each year. ``I am
confident this Isle of Capri will be what we want in Kansas City,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Isle of Capri officials last month unveiled the casino's new
look at a Kansas City Port Authority meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Outside, pink and purple flamingos, neon lights and other
flourishes will give way to the traditional look of a Missouri
River paddle-wheeler, said Kevin Mullally, deputy director of the
commission. ``We are clearly moving closer to a more appropriate
design,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But in a mild defense of the oft-maligned Flamingo's decor,
Mullally said river historians acknowledged that the old
paddle-wheelers were major entertainment destinations of their day
and typically were brightly colored and well lit at night to
attract customers.
</P>
<P>
   Capri President Jack Gallaway said a 150- to 200-room hotel
attached to the casino is likely to be announced within a year or
so. ``We're being careful not to commit to that,'' he told
commissioners, ``but that is a standard way we operate.''
</P>
<P>
   The Kansas City casino will be the 11th for Isle of Capri. It is
building No. 12 in Boonville, Mo., and is seeking commission
approval for No. 13 in south St. Louis County.
</P>
<P>
   Isle of Capri's founder and chairman, Bernard Goldstein, and
members of his family control about one-third of Isle's common
stock.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview Wednesday after the commission's vote, Goldstein
said the company's expansion into Missouri was fueled partly by the
public's approval of casino gambling _ at the polls in several
elections and in record revenue still being logged by the state's
14 riverboat casinos.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kansas City is a terrific market,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   At hearings earlier this year, Goldstein was described as the
``godfather'' of modern riverboat gambling.
</P>
<P>
   He was a key player in winning the Iowa legislature's approval
of riverboat gambling in 1989. He subsequently operated two of the
nation's first modern-era riverboat casinos there in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   He said Wednesday that he is surprised by the rapid growth of
the industry over the past 10 years. ``I thought it would just be
in Iowa,'' he said of the then-novel idea of picturesque gambling
boats plying the state's rivers.
</P>
<P>
   Illinois and other states quickly followed Iowa's lead, which
saw legalized gambling as an economic shot in the arm to help the
recovery from recession.
</P>
<P>
   Goldstein, a scrap metal and river barge tycoon, founded Casino
America Inc. in 1990. The company changed its name in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Goldstein also is chairman of the board of the Alter Cos.,
including Alter Barge Line Inc. and Alter Trucking.
</P>
<P>
   Isle of Capri owns or has majority interest in riverboat casinos
in Iowa, Mississippi, Louisiana and Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   The company also owns the Pompano Park harness racing track and
poker club in Florida, and 50 percent of the Enchanted Capri cruise
ship that sails from New Orleans on Caribbean excursions. An Isle
of Capri casino is on board.
</P>
<P>
   In other action Wednesday:
</P>
<P>
   - The commission made final its order for a $10,000 fine against
St. Jo Frontier Casino managing partner Bill Grace for misconduct
in May 1999 involving verbal profanity in public and his
unauthorized consumption of alcohol on the premises. Grace appealed
the original $15,000 proposed penalty, and several other charges
were dismissed after a formal hearing.
</P>
<P>
   - The commission proposed $100,000 fines apiece for Kansas
City's four casino companies and Harrah's in St. Louis. A two-day
undercover sting operation in March led to allegations that the
casinos violated loss limit rules.
</P>
<P>
   The commission offered no details about any of the infractions.
</P>
<P>
   John V. Finamore, Midwest president for Station Casinos Inc.,
was upset over the lack of information made public.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't know what we're guilty of,'' he said. ``The thing
that concerns us is the perception that we're flaunting the loss
limit rule.''
</P>
<P>
   Station has spent more than $500,000 on computers and employee
training designed to monitor loss limit compliance, Finamore said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The loss limit rule is very challenging to enforce,'' he said.
``People make mistakes.''
</P>
<P>
   - The commission also proposed bingo license suspensions for VFW
posts in Lemay and Poplar Bluff, and Eagles clubs in Sikeston and
Poplar Bluff.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
