<HEADLINE>
AMC FOURTH-QUARTER LOSSES EXCEED WALL STREET'S EXPECTATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JENNIFER MANN  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ AMC Entertainment Inc.'s reported loss of
$1.24 a share for its fourth quarter far exceeded the 75-cent to
99-cent loss Wall Street expected.
</P>
<P>
   Dragging the company down was its money-losing international
division; its older, obsolete multiplex theaters; and money spent
on building costly new megaplexes in an industry that's heavily
overbuilt.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1990, the number of movie screens in the United States has
increased three times as fast as attendance, and fewer movie
tickets were sold last year than in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Company Chairman Peter Brown said in a conference call Wednesday
morning that 1999 was challenging for the industry and a year of
transition for AMC.
</P>
<P>
   Brown said the movie exhibition industry was navigating choppy
seas.
</P>
<P>
   ``But fortunately for us, we've got a great crew, we have a
wonderful ship, and in fact we view ours as a battleship on the
waters,'' Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   For the company's fourth quarter, which ended March 30, losses
totaled $29.1 million, compared with a loss of $19.1 million, or 82
cents a share, for the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
   Those losses came on record revenue of $262 million, compared
with $233 million for the same period a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   AMC's adjusted cash flow for the fourth quarter was $8.7
million, down 18 percent from the same period a year ago. Adjusted
cash flow excludes costs for theater pre-opening and closure
expenses, which totaled $4.3 million for the quarter.
</P>
<P>
   For the year, AMC lost $55.2 million, or $2.35 a share after a
restructuring charge, compared with a loss of $16 million, or 69
cents a share, the previous year.
</P>
<P>
   Those losses came on record revenue of $1.17 billion, compared
with $1 billion in the previous year. Though attendance for the
year was down, revenue was helped by increases in AMC's ticket
prices, which averaged $4.93 in North America.
</P>
<P>
   The $4.93 a ticket is more than a share of the company's stock,
which closed Wednesday at 4 3//4, up 7//16.
</P>
<P>
   The good news is that the company closed 279 multiplex screens
during the year and plans to close about 175 during this fiscal
year. However, AMC also plans to add about 120 screens.
</P>
<P>
   AMC's chief financial officer, Craig Ramsey, reviewed some
balance sheet concerns during the conference call:
</P>
<P>
   - The company has complied with all the covenants of its
financial agreements.
</P>
<P>
   - AMC has reduced its net debt to $703 million.
</P>
<P>
   - The availability of cash and access to its revolving credit
agreement stood at $207 million at the end of its fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
   The company plans net capital spending of $100 million this year
and expects its debt to be flat to slightly down by the time it
reaches the end of fiscal 2001.
</P>
<P>
   The number of movie screens in the United States now is between
35,000 and 37,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``The industry would be a lot healthier if the count was around
20,000,'' Brown said. ``It's going to take many, many, many years
to get there.''
</P>
<P>
   Daniel O'Neill, an analyst with Credit Suisse First Boston, said
he wasn't completely surprised by AMC's fourth-quarter loss because
he had recently drastically revised his estimate of losses.
</P>
<P>
   ``But at the same time, there's a lot to chew through in their
numbers,'' he said. ``I think AMC has the best circuit and should
do fairly well when and if things turn around. But it's going to be
some tough going for AMC and the industry.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
