A1494 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-TURTLES-EXINCTION-SFC     06-01 0761
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TURTLES-EXINCTION-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 LEATHERBACKS, LARGE SEA TURTLES, ENDANGERED BY COMMERCIAL FISHING  &HT;     By GLEN MARTIN 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Leatherback turtles, the world's largest sea
turtle and the only ones found off California, have plummeted in
numbers in the past two decades and could be extinct within a few
years, according to a study published Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The study, which appears in the scientific journal Nature,
concluded that leatherback turtles have declined primarily as a
result of commercial fishing activities. Large nets used for fish
and shrimp often entrap sea turtles, and long fishing lines can
snag them.
</P>
<P>
   In 1982, there were 115,000 adult female leatherback turtles in
the world's oceans, according to the study by scientists from
Drexel University in Philadelphia and the Center for Marine
Conservation. That number declined to 34,500 by 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The authors predict that the turtles may disappear entirely
unless comprehensive measures are taken to change fishing practices
and protect nesting beaches.
</P>
<P>
   Leatherback sea turtles differ from other marine sea turtles in
that they have smooth, leathery shells rather than the horny
carapaces typical of their relatives. They may reach a ton in
weight, and are often found far offshore, where they subsist on
jellyfish, crustaceans, fish and seaweed.
</P>
<P>
   They are the only marine turtle that habitually visits the cool
waters of the North Pacific. Until a few years ago, they were
commonly spotted off the Monterey coast and have been observed as
far north as Alaska.
</P>
<P>
   Leatherbacks have already disappeared from waters off India, Sri
Lanka and Malaysia, areas where they were once common. The
scientists also noted dramatic declines in nesting colonies in
Mexico and Central America.
</P>
<P>
   In Mexico, the number of nesting leatherbacks declined from
70,000 in 1982 to fewer than 250 in 1998 and 1999.
</P>
<P>
   At Playa Grande, Costa Rica, the world's fourth-largest
leatherback nesting colony, egg-laying females declined from 1,367
for  &LR; in the 1988-89 nesting season to 117 for  &LR; in the 1998-99
season.
</P>
<P>
   The authors predict that Playa Grande's nesting population will
drop to 50 by 2003 unless comprehensive protective measures are
taken.
</P>
<P>
   The adult female leatherback population for the entire eastern
Pacific Ocean, the authors estimate, now stands at 1,690 _ down
from 91,000 in 1980.
</P>
<P>
   Because leatherbacks are long-lived  &LR; live 30 years or longer and
are slow to mature, continuity in breeding generations is needed to
assure species survival. The low numbers of mature females, the
authors conclude, means Pacific leatherbacks are on the brink of
extinction.
</P>
<P>
   Commercial fishing appears to be the cause of the decline.
Several types of fisheries kill sea turtles, including drift nets,
gill nets and long lines. The authors estimate that gill nets and
long lines alone  &LR; killed 1,500 mature female leatherbacks a year in
the Pacific through the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Eichenberg, a program counsel for the Center for Marine
Conservation who consulted on the article, said the federal
government has been ignoring the plight of leatherbacks and other
sea turtles.
</P>
<P>
   ``The National Marine Fisheries Service estimated there are
85,000 mature females left in the Pacific Ocean, when our best
research indicates no more than 5,000 are left,'' Eichenberg said.
</P>
<P>
   A lawsuit filed by the center against the fisheries service last
year resulted in the closure of a vast stretch of ocean off Hawaii
to long-line fishing while the agency prepares a new study on the
status of the area's sea turtles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before our suit, there were 15 million hooks running each year
in that fishery,'' said Eichenberg. ``Some of the sets were 30
miles long. It was destroying a tremendous amount of non-target
species, including turtles.''
</P>
<P>
   Fisheries service representatives could not be reached for
comment.
</P>
<P>
   John McCosker, a marine biologist and senior scientist with the
California Academy of Sciences in San Francisco, said the
technology exists to prevent widespread turtle mortality _ but that
global trade agreements have hindered its employment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Turtle exclusion devices have been developed for shrimp and
fish nets that work very well,'' McCosker said, ``and fishermen are
generally willing to use them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, many countries are reluctant to require them,
because the World Trade Organization views any attempt to impose
environmental regulations on the taking and marketing of seafood as
a trade barrier,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
