<SLUG> BC-CANCER-SYSTEMS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KANSAS CITY PROVIDERS TO COMBINE CANCER TREATMENT PROGRAMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JULIUS A. KARASH  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ In a move that could improve treatment for
area cancer patients, longtime rivals Health Midwest and St.
Luke's-Shawnee Mission Health System have signed an agreement to
combine their cancer programs.
</P>
<P>
   Leaders of the two health systems said on Wednesday that they
plan to complete a feasibility study within 90 days, finish an
unprecedented agreement shortly thereafter and begin joint
operations early next year.
</P>
<P>
   The move comes amid a broader effort to make Kansas City a
national center for life sciences research.
</P>
<P>
   Plans call for the combined program to give area residents
access to more sophisticated equipment and expanded treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Program leaders also intend to apply within two years to the
National Cancer Institute for designation as a regional
comprehensive cancer center _ the first in the four-state area.
This designation would likely lead to greater funding from the
National Institutes of Health and other sources.
</P>
<P>
   ``Working together, we want to build upon our individual
strengths in a way that will enhance the delivery of cancer
services to the community,'' said Richard W. Brown, president and
chief executive officer of Health Midwest, and G. Richard Hastings,
president and chief executive officer of St. Luke's-Shawnee
Mission, in a joint statement.
</P>
<P>
   The health systems intend to share the cost of upgraded
technology and equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Cranshaw, senior vice president of strategic planning for
Health Midwest, said reducing unnecessary duplication in cancer
programs would ``free up funds for investing in new pieces of
equipment not already in the community, thereby increasing quality
and reducing the need for patients to leave the area for
treatment.''
</P>
<P>
   Health Midwest includes 15 hospitals and St. Luke's operates
eight, making the health systems the largest in the Kansas City
area.
</P>
<P>
   Health care consultant Gail Shafton, president of Cue Resources
Inc. in Overland Park, said she was stunned by the announcement of
cooperation..
</P>
<P>
   ``They have been rivals in every conceivable way for at least
the last decade,'' said Shafton, who has worked in the area
health-care arena since the 1980s. ``Their whole point in
organizing delivery systems has been to capture market share from
each other. I'm thrilled that they are finding a place to establish
common ground....''
</P>
<P>
   The combined program could pose a competitive threat to services
offered by the University of Kansas Medical Center, both for
patients and national funding, Shafton noted.
</P>
<P>
   But Mary Ball, a spokeswoman for KU Medical Center, said the
area will always need the type of research and patient care that is
performed by a teaching hospital such as KU.
</P>
<P>
   ``The incidence of cancer continues to increase, and KU Med
believes the expansion of services for cancer patients helps
everyone in the community,'' Ball said. ``As the region's academic
medical center, KU Med physicians and research scientists are
developing new cancer diagnostic and treatment methods. And KU
Med's patients have access to these and other leading national
clinical trials.''
</P>
<P>
   The combined program would come under the direction of a
governing board that would be established later. The health systems
are studying the needed regulatory approvals.
</P>
<P>
   Brown and Hastings said they want to develop a first-class
cancer center on par with the M.D. Anderson Cancer Center in
Houston and the Dana-Farber Cancer Institute in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``While the Kansas City community is rich with excellent
oncology practitioners and cancer services, there is no single
comprehensive program to which cancer patients and their families
may turn,'' the two leaders said in their joint statement. ``In
fact, no such center is available within the four-state region of
Kansas, Missouri, Nebraska and Iowa.''
</P>
<P>
   On its Web site, the National Cancer Institute says its
comprehensive cancer centers ``are the major source of new
knowledge relating to the nature of cancer and the major source of
new and more effective approaches to prevention, detection,
diagnosis and therapy.''
</P>
<P>
   Such centers also engage in community outreach and education
efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's announcement was made at the Stowers Institute for
Medical Research, which plans to begin work late this year. Brown
and Hastings said the Health Midwest-St. Luke's program would work
with Stowers, which is spearheading heightened interest in life
sciences research in the Kansas City area.
</P>
<P>
   William B. Neaves, president of Stowers, said in a prepared
statement that ``by laying the foundation for the first
NCI-designated comprehensive cancer center in this region of the
U.S., Health Midwest and St. Luke's-Shawnee Mission Health System
demonstrate the spirit of cooperation that will make Kansas City a
national center of excellence in biomedical science.''
</P>
<P>
   Neaves said Stowers would use its cancer-related research to
help obtain the comprehensive cancer designation for Kansas City.
Other area institutions also should cooperate, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Brown and Hastings said there were no plans on the table to
build new facilities for the combined program, which would continue
to offer services at various locations operated by the two health
systems.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're looking at program integration,'' Hastings said. ``The
facility component is secondary. This will be a cancer center
without walls.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-01-00 0056EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000601.0021 </DOCNO>
