<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWSPAPERS-TRIAL-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANTITRUST SUIT JUDGE TO DETERMINE FATE OF TWO SAN
FRANCISCO  NEWSPAPERS
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By REYNOLDS HOLDING 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The judge commanded the spotlight during closing
arguments Wednesday in Clint Reilly's lawsuit to block the Hearst
Corp. from buying The Chronicle, pointedly questioning lawyers on
the terms of the sale, Reilly's standing to sue and the legality of
the Fang family's acquisition of the Hearst-owned Examiner.
</P>
<P>
   After more than four hours of argument, U.S. District Judge
Vaughn Walker took the case under submission and, without
specifying a date, pledged to try to reach a ``prompt decision'' in
an antitrust suit with far-reaching implications for the nation's
newspaper industry.
</P>
<P>
   It is the first case ever to challenge the attempted dissolution
of a joint operating agreement, an exemption to federal antitrust
law that allows competing newspapers such as The Chronicle and the
Examiner to split profits and share printing and other business
operations while maintaining editorial independence.
</P>
<P>
   Reilly, a real estate investor and former mayoral candidate,
filed the lawsuit in January, claiming that Hearst intended to
create an illegal monopoly by purchasing The Chronicle and giving
the Examiner _ plus up to $66 million in subsidies over three years
_ to the Fangs, publishers of the San Francisco Independent.
</P>
<P>
   Walker's ruling in the case could make it more difficult for
newspapers publishing under joint operating agreements in 12 other
cities to dissolve or amend those agreements. In recent years, 15
joint operating agreements have been dissolved, most with little
opposition.
</P>
<P>
   Reilly's lawyer, Joseph Alioto, opened the proceedings Wednesday
by insisting that Hearst is using the joint operating agreement as
``a stepping stone to monopoly.'' He argued that Hearst could sell
the Examiner with its share of the joint operating agreement, or
close the Examiner after the agreement expired in 2005, but could
not buy The Chronicle ``because that would be a monopoly.''
</P>
<P>
   Alioto did not get far, though, before Walker peppered him with
questions about how Hearst's deal with the Fangs would violate
antitrust laws _ and cause Reilly ``economic'' harm, a prerequisite
to filing an antitrust suit.
</P>
<P>
   Alioto responded that the Examiner deal is ``a sham and a
farce'' that furthers Hearst's monopoly scheme because the company
knows the paper cannot survive under Fang ownership.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be kind,'' said Alioto, ``it is a down and dirty bribe. ...
Don't make this paper work and we will reward you'' with $66
million.
</P>
<P>
   Pressed further by Walker, Alioto contended that the deal is
anticompetitive because it stops Hearst and The Chronicle from
competing after the joint operating agreement expires in 2005,
something that internal emails show the papers clearly intended to
do, said Alioto.
</P>
<P>
   Walker then questioned Alioto on two provisions of the joint
operating agreement that Alioto contends are illegal. One
essentially blocks the sale of either newspaper to a competitor
within 60 miles of San Francisco, and the second gives each paper
the right to match any offer for the other paper.
</P>
<P>
   Alioto argued that the provisions hurt Reilly and other
consumers because Hearst does not ``have to worry about another
competitor coming into the market'' to buy the Chronicle and
driving down advertising and subscription rates with increased
competition.
</P>
<P>
   When Alioto explained further that, even though The Chronicle
and the Examiner together fix advertising rates, nothing in the
joint operating agreement specifically allows them to do so, Walker
caught him by surprise.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the parties have fixed prices,'' asked the judge, ``and
that is not covered by the joint operating agreement, is it
out-and-out (illegal) price fixing?''
</P>
<P>
   After a pause, Alioto responded with a laugh, ``It wasn't until
now, judge.''
</P>
<P>
   Following Alioto to the podium was The Chronicle's attorney, J.
Thomas Rosch, who said his client ``now knows what it is like to
live between the Hatfields and the McCoys,'' or, in this case,
Reilly and Hearst.
</P>
<P>
   Walker immediately asked Rosch why Hearst's deal with the Fangs
_ and particularly the $66 million subsidy _ was not a wasteful and
anticompetitive attempt to preserve a failing newspaper that should
be allowed to die.
</P>
<P>
   Rosch responded that there was no proof that the Fang's
acquisition of the Examiner would reduce competition, but Walker
pressed the issue by asking whether there was any reason for the
transaction other than to ``curry favor with (the U.S. Department
of) Justice and local political figures.''
</P>
<P>
   After suggesting that the answer was better left to Hearst,
Rosch discussed the two provisions in the joint operating agreement
that Alioto contended were illegal. Rosch insisted that there was
not ``a shred of evidence'' that either provision affected The
Chronicle's sale price and, in any event, Reilly could not show
that he suffered any injury if Hearst ``got this paper on the
cheap'' _ and so could not have standing to challenge the
provisions under antitrust law.
</P>
<P>
   The judge then returned to the Fangs' acquisition of the
Examiner. He asked why the Department of Justice had claimed in a
press release announcing approval of the deal that a Fang-owned
Examiner would be ``fully competitive'' with The Chronicle when it
was clear the paper would be only a scaled-down product focusing on
San Francisco neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   Rosch explained that the Fangs would be able to operate the
paper in ways that Hearst could not, but Walker was not satisfied.
</P>
<P>
   ``All that supports Mr. Alioto's theory,'' said Walker, ``that
something else is going on here.''
</P>
<P>
   Walker continued this line of questioning with Hearst's
attorney, Gary Halling. Halling responded that Hearst had never
said the Examiner would compete with The Chronicle throughout the
Bay Area and, in any event, ``we did not write the press release.''
</P>
<P>
   The judge then asked why Hearst was willing to give the Fangs
the Examiner and a $66 million subsidy rather than shut the
newspaper down.
</P>
<P>
   ``The answer is,'' said Halling, ``that Hearst could not afford
the delay'' caused by the Justice Department's insistence that a
buyer for the Examiner be found. ``The contract we signed with The
Chronicle had a deadline.''
</P>
<P>
   David Balabanian, the Fangs' attorney, was the last lawyer to
speak. He defended his earlier claims that the ``new'' Examiner
would be ``fully competitive'' with The Chronicle, but said he
``did not suggest in any way'' that it would be a ``metropolitan''
newspaper covering the Bay Area.
</P>
<P>
   Walker, though, responded that there was ``an awful lot said
that does not appear to be forthright.''
</P>
<P>
   In his argument, Balabanian contended that the type of Examiner
planned by the Fangs _ a morning paper with smaller circulation _
is ``the only paper that makes any sense.'' He also explained that
the Fangs wanted the Examiner's share of the joint operating
agreement but were willing to accept the subsidy offered by Hearst
as a substitute.
</P>
<P>
   ``Spending money unwisely,'' he said, ``has never been an
antitrust violation.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
