<SLUG> BC-INDIAN-CASINO-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STILL HOPING TO BUY RACETRACK, TRIBE PRESSES FORWARD ON CASINO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICK ALM  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Kan. _ Workers have begun refurbishing and
converting the nearly century-old Scottish Rite temple in downtown
Kansas City, Kan., into a three-story casino _ with no parking.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coming Soon'' signs announcing the gambling hall should be up
by the end of the week, said Jim Bland, second chief of the
Wyandotte Tribe of Oklahoma, which owns the brick building across
the street from City Hall and police headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've waited as long as we're going to wait,'' said Bland. ``A
casino is coming.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, tribal officials acknowledge that their
announcement is mostly a gambit to force federal, state and local
officials to negotiate a deal that would put the casino at The
Woodlands racetrack in western Wyandotte County.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want to be here,'' said Bland. ``The Woodlands is our
No. 1 choice. But we are going full-bore ahead right now to upgrade
that place and fix it so that a casino can be put in there.
</P>
<P>
   ``In case we finally do go somewhere else, we'll still want to
use that building for other projects _ a museum or a cultural
center or a meeting facility.''
</P>
<P>
   Federal authorities four years ago cleared the way for
high-stakes tribal bingo in the Scottish Rite building _ regarded
as special tribal reservation land. But the tribe has held off on
those plans while hoping to win approval for full-scale casino
gambling at The Woodlands.
</P>
<P>
   State and federal legislation that could allow that to happen
has been stalled for years.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the tribe has appealed to federal tribal-regulatory
authorities to upgrade its reservation bingo gaming license for the
Scottish Rite building to also permit slot machines and other
casino style games.
</P>
<P>
   If everything goes as planned, Bland said, the casino could open
sometime this fall.
</P>
<P>
   If that happens, Dave McCullough, the tribe's Oklahoma-based
lawyer, said the tribe's gambit would have failed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would love to invest that money in another site,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The city certainly won't be happy about the location. We hope
the idea that we're going forward will bring some people to the
table to talk about some options.''
</P>
<P>
   City officials support the tribe's efforts to locate at the
financially struggling racetrack but probably would resist any
effort to operate a casino in the shadow of City Hall.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one thinks the downtown site is an optimum site,'' said
Unified Government Administrator Dennis Hays. ``We will stand with
the Wyandotte Nation in their effort to get gaming at The
Woodlands. That is the best possible solution for everyone and
would be a great economic boom for Wyandotte County.''
</P>
<P>
   Woodlands' managing partner Bill Grace has said he is willing to
sell the track to the tribe and then lease back parts of it to
continue horse and greyhound racing while the tribe operates a
casino.
</P>
<P>
   The Scottish Rite building was erected in 1906 and was largely
rebuilt in 1951 after a fire. Its half-acre site has no room for
parking. If the tribe's casino patrons park illegally downtown,
Unified Government spokesman Don Denney suggested that the city
might be towing a lot of cars.
</P>
<P>
   Bland said the tribe was working on the parking problem and
probably would have patrons park elsewhere and ride shuttle buses
to the casino.
</P>
<P>
   The tribe and its partner, North American Sports Management, a
Maitland, Fla., real estate developer, still face legal hurdles
before opening a gambling parlor anywhere in Wyandotte County.
</P>
<P>
   A federal judge in Topeka, Kan., this year dismissed a lawsuit
filed by Kansas that sought to block the tribe's downtown casino
plan. But the state has appealed, keeping the lawsuit alive.
</P>
<P>
   The Scottish Rite temple site is next to the tribe's historic
Huron Indian Cemetery. A 1997 federal law prohibits the tribe from
using the cemetery grounds for gambling. That law was passed in
response to the tribe's plans at the time for a casino on pillars
that would have occupied the air space over the cemetery.
</P>
<P>
   To compensate the tribe for voiding its cemetery land rights,
legislation is pending in Congress that would permit the tribe to
buy land virtually anywhere else in Wyandotte County for a casino.
</P>
<P>
   That measure, sponsored by Rep. Dennis Moore, a Lenexa Democrat,
was approved by a House committee last summer and awaits floor
debate.
</P>
<P>
   An unrelated federal court case pending in Florida also could
determine whether state government approval is needed for Indian
casinos off-reservation or on special land such as the Scottish
Rite site.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
