A1499 &Cx1f; kan-z
r p BC-CANDIDATE-GOP-KAN &LR;      06-01 0598
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANDIDATE-GOP-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOP CANDIDATE SPEAKS OUT AGAINST REPUBLICAN PARTY LEADERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE KRASKE  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ As national GOP leaders appeared to favor
another latecomer candidate, Republican congressional contender
Teresa Loar charged Wednesday that ``there's no room for women''
inside her party.
</P>
<P>
   Loar, running for the 6th District congressional seat being
vacated by Democrat Pat Danner, said party leaders such as U.S.
House Speaker Dennis Hastert had switched their allegiance to state
Sen. Sam Graves, a new entrant.
</P>
<P>
   Loar, a Kansas City councilwoman, said she got into the race
last year after Hastert encouraged her to run. Back then Danner was
gearing up to campaign for a fifth term, and the race looked far
more formidable for a Republican.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's happened to me in the last week must be indicative of a
party where there's no room for women,'' Loar said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The frustration as a woman in political office is
undescribable anyway. To get kicked around like this by my own
party is so disheartening.''
</P>
<P>
   Although discouraged by the GOP leaders' actions, Loar said she
was energized by Graves' entry and confident she could still win
the Aug. 8 primary.
</P>
<P>
   She said party leaders recruited Graves after Danner announced
last week that she was abandoning her re-election effort. Danner
disclosed earlier this year that she was undergoing treatment for
breast cancer.
</P>
<P>
   House leaders are eager to get Graves into Congress because he's
a ``white conservative male as opposed to a moderate female,'' Loar
said.
</P>
<P>
   Graves would ``help them maintain their power base in
Washington,'' Loar said of the conservative House leaders. ``A
moderate female would erode that base.''
</P>
<P>
   Loar favors abortion rights; Graves is regarded as an abortion
opponent.
</P>
<P>
   Graves said his opponent was off base. He said he was recruited
because as a state senator he represents 16 of the congressional
district's 27 counties in northwest Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't even know why she's saying something like that,''
Graves said. ``It sounds to me like she's just lashing out.''
</P>
<P>
   Graves noted that four of Missouri's six women senators are
Republican.
</P>
<P>
   Missouri officials reopened candidate filing, as required by
law, for five days after Danner withdrew May 22.
</P>
<P>
   ``The truth of the matter is, this isn't the same race,'' Graves
said. ``This is a brand new race. That's the reason we have laws
that open it back up.''
</P>
<P>
   Graves said Hastert was expected to visit the district this
summer to help him raise money.
</P>
<P>
   Besides Hastert, Graves said he was encouraged to enter the race
by House Majority Leader Dick Armey, House Majority Whip Tom DeLay
and Rep. Tom Davis, chairman of the National Republican Campaign
Committee. Republican members of Congress from Missouri also
called, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans are defending a narrow House majority in the fall
elections, and Danner is only the eighth Democrat to retire,
compared with 23 GOP lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   A GOP poll conducted after Danner announced her withdrawal
reportedly showed Graves with better than a 2-to-1 edge over Loar.
It also showed the largely rural district as strongly
anti-abortion.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Wilkinson, a spokesman for the National Republican
Congressional Committee, said the party would not endorse any
candidate in the primary. Individual Republican leaders, though,
can do what they wish, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If some think Graves is the best candidate, so be it,'' he
said. ``She needs to calm down a little bit.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
