<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 01:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1500 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-CANDIDATES-CALIFORNIA     06-01 1209
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANDIDATES-CALIFORNIA-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 BUSH CAMPAIGN HITS CALIFORNIA TRAIL IN GORE'S ABSENCE  &HT;     By CARLA MARINUCCI 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   With the brilliance of Lake Tahoe as a backdrop, Texas Governor
George W. Bush will deliver a high-profile speech on the
environment Thursday _ and tomorrow, he will share a platform on
border issues with Vice President Al Gore's biggest state
supporter, Gov. Gray Davis.
</P>
<P>
   The big visit leads Democrats in California to the big question:
What's up with Al Gore?
</P>
<P>
   With Bush tramping across the nation's most populous state every
two weeks since the March 7 primary, the oft-repeated query
underscores a sobering reality for the vice president.
</P>
<P>
   Even with five months to go before the election, and a
comfortable nine-point lead in California, some Democrats are
starting to get antsy about his chances and worry that his poor
showing in national polls may be threatening the party's chances of
taking back control of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   In California _ a crucial state he has visited 67 times _ Gore's
friends and supporters say the guy they know is funny, warm and
smart as a whip. But his repeated attacks on Bush, they say, not
only fail to sell Gore's strengths, they have resulted in erosion
in polls, especially among women.
</P>
<P>
   Recent polls, such as the ABC News /Washington Post poll this
month, have given Bush a five-point edge nationally, and a Harris
Interactive poll released Wednesday shows a distinct edge for Bush
in the congeniality department: Americans ranked him the candidate
they'd most like to go to dinner with, have a drink with, go to a
baseball game with and be stranded on a desert island with.
</P>
<P>
   News reports from Washington this week suggest that even
President Clinton has made a behind-the-scenes attempt to lighten
up Gore's attacks and stress a more positive message for the party
in the last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the most prepared guy ever to run for president,'' said
one Gore friend and leading state supporter. ``I'd have him parked
in front of the media. I don't think it's to his advantage to
appear to be inaccessible to real people.''
</P>
<P>
   GOP insiders insist that Gore's campaign has already done its
damage, turning off many female voters who appear to be gravitating
to a warmer appeal from Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm getting calls from Democratic women who are saying, `I'm
interested in knowing more,''' said Kristin Heuter, one of the
nation's powerhouse GOP fund-raisers, who marvels how potential
donors are jamming the phones to participate in upcoming Bush
fund-raisers.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're looking at Gore and saying `there's nothing special
about this man' ... (but) when they meet Bush and look in his eyes,
they like him _ and they trust him. There's a warmth. He's
genuine.''
</P>
<P>
   Other Republicans say it's more than personality _ and that
Bush's positive approach is resonating with voters.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats ``have tried to run a campaign to do two things: tear
down their opponent and paint them in a corner as extremist,'' said
Leslie Goodman, a GOP communications consultant who has worked in
the past with the Bush campaign. ``And they can't do that this time
around (because) the messenger doesn't fit. In Bush (Republicans)
have a bold vision ... and Gore has been a follower for eight
years.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush is hoping to take advantage of any opening in California.
He is appearing tomorrow at the Border Governors conference in
Sacramento alongside Davis, who is hosting the event. And he is
coming back June 19 for events and fund-raisers in Silicon Valley.
</P>
<P>
   With Bush on such a roll, even Gore's most loyal supporters
admit they'd like to see a different tactic.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are very few people in the insider group who agree that
Al Gore should be using such a heavy hand in his attacks,'' said
one high-level Gore supporter who declined to be named. ``They
continue to believe it doesn't serve him well. He doesn't need
that.''
</P>
<P>
   State Controller Kathleen Connell, who has appeared alongside
Gore on numerous occasions, is one of many state Democrats who
maintain that Gore, in person, is genuine, ``very warm, and very
concerned'' about issues that matter to women.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I'd like to see him do more of is talk about the vision
for the 21st century,'' she said. ``As a mother, an executive, an
elected official, what would resonate with me is: Where are we
going to be 10 years from now?''
</P>
<P>
   Other Democrats, like campaign consultant Gale Kauffman, also
profess to be confounded by Gore's strategy. ``You don't really see
a consistent set of tactics,'' said Kauffman, who helped shape Bill
Bradley's challenge to Gore in California. While she cautioned that
it is still early in the campaign, ``good Democrats are saying
they're for Gore ... but there doesn't seem to be a lot of
passion.''
</P>
<P>
   This week, the Gore campaign has signaled it is making changes _
fast.
</P>
<P>
   The story of Gore's life, his devotion to family and his
personal history _ from being a divinity student to his service in
Vietnam _ will be the subject of ads and campaign material in the
next weeks, campaign insiders say. The goal: humanizing a man who
has been publicly depicted as a cautious politician too eager to
pander.
</P>
<P>
   Gore himself has taken to a more positive message, stressing
initiatives on the environment in recent days while accepting the
endorsement of the League of Conservation Voters. He is also
unveiling a family-friendly agenda, talking Thursday about
cancer-fighting initiatives. Wednesday, he made an unusually
emotional joint appearance with his wife, Tipper, to unveil a
mental health initiative. Tipper Gore also held a conference call
with regional medical reporters last Thursday on the issue of
mental health, signaling her increased visibility on issue-related
efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Friends and supporters say such changes are welcome.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing people are unaware of is how much Gore is a
demonstrated, committed family man,'' said Martha Whetstone, a
friend of both the Gores and the Clintons. `` ``People haven't seen
that side of them. It's very positive, and it will resonate.''
</P>
<P>
   Garry South, the consultant who advised Davis on his landslide
1998 victory, warns that Republicans shouldn't be overconfident
about their candidate's appeal to voters. And Democrats, especially
women, he said, need to shake off the nervousness.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Bush) has had a good two-month run, I wouldn't deny it,''
South said. ``But he's gotten a free ride so far. ... Even moderate
Republican women, when they find out where he stands on issues, are
aghast.''
</P>
<P>
   Voters simply have not focused their attention yet on the
election, South said, and they won't really be paying attention to
the issues until after Labor Day.
</P>
<P>
   But South also argued that the Gore campaign will not _ and
should not _ easily give up the attack mode on Bush's record in
Texas as the campaign heads into the fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``The election is not a personality contest,'' South said.
``Someone has to take the state of Texas and hold it up like a
mirror, and say, `Look folks,' '' on issues ranging from child care
and environment to guns and abortion.
</P>
<P>
   ``And when that happens,'' said South, ``you will see this guy
Bush melt like a pat of butter on a hot driveway.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-01-00 0106EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
