<HEADER>
A1501 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-LIBRARY-EXHIBIT-KAN &LR;      06-01 0617
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIBRARY-EXHIBIT-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIBRARY OF CONGRESS EXHIBITS WILLIAM `THE MISSOURI KID' RUDOLPH
STORY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN MURPHY  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Historians describe him as the most notorious
Missouri bank robber and killer of his time _ but his name wasn't
Jesse James.
</P>
<P>
   William ``The Missouri Kid'' Rudolph became a featured exhibit
Wednesday at the Library of Congress, which is displaying a portion
of 88 years of records recently received from the famed Pinkerton
detective agency.
</P>
<P>
   Pinkerton archivist Jane Adler said Rudolph's story was one of
the most interesting she uncovered in three years of sorting
through thousands of Pinkerton files from 1850 to 1938.
</P>
<P>
   Rudolph and an accomplice, George Collins, robbed a bank in
Union, Mo., near St. Louis at midnight on Dec. 26, 1902. Rudolph
relied on the blasting skills he developed as a miner to blow up
the bank safe and steal $12,000.
</P>
<P>
   A posse tracked Rudolph, 20 at the time, using only a boyhood
picture. Rudolph and Collins were holed up in a cabin near Stanton,
Mo., when a young Pinkerton agent posing as a hunter knocked on the
door.
</P>
<P>
   ``He very obviously was not a hunter. He was a detective and
they shot him in the head,'' Adler told library officials.
</P>
<P>
   The inexperienced detective, Charles Schumacher, was the son of
a popular Pinkerton superintendent. From that moment, Rudolph
became the target of the most intense manhunt in Pinkerton history,
Adler said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He only killed one man, but it was the wrong man to kill,''
Adler said.
</P>
<P>
   Frightened of being captured, Rudolph got himself arrested and
jailed in St. Louis County on a lesser offense. He hoped he
wouldn't be recognized as Schumacher's killer and that the manhunt
would end by the time he got out of jail.
</P>
<P>
   The ruse failed, and Rudolph was held on the murder charge.
Adler said Rudolph then decided the best way to escape execution
was to throw himself on the mercy of Pinkerton head William
Pinkerton.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't only ask this of you for myself, but for my dear old
mother's sake,'' Rudolph pleaded in one of two neatly written
letters from April and May 1903. ``I beg you to use your powerful
influence with the governor to have my sentence commuted.''
</P>
<P>
   Getting no response, Rudolph's next option was to escape, which
he did on July 6, 1903, a week before his trial. That set off
another manhunt that ended in his recapture on Feb. 25, 1904.
</P>
<P>
   Newspapers kept close track of Rudolph's story.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the start of yellow journalism, and he was the first
celebrity criminal,'' Adler said. Jesse James lived and died before
newspapers were as widespread, and the fame of outlaws like Butch
Cassidy and the Sundance Kid peaked after they died, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Collins also was captured, put in Franklin County Jail with
Rudolph, tried and sentenced to death. Rudolph was forced to
witness the hanging on March 26, 1904.
</P>
<P>
   ``They took him to a building overlooking the courtyard to
watch,'' Adler said. ``He cried.'' On May 8, Rudolph also was
hanged.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the letters from Rudolph to Pinkerton, the
Library of Congress received pictures, wanted posters, news
clippings, criminal records sheets and other documents.
</P>
<P>
   Some of those were displayed for reporters Wednesday, along with
pictures and records on Butch Cassidy and the Sundance Kid. In all,
Pinkerton donated 92 boxes of materials to the library that had
been private for up to 150 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``This piece of history is preserved here, where it will always
be available to the citizens of the United States and around the
world,'' said James H. Billington, who heads the Library of
Congress.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-01-00 0107EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
