<HEADER>
A1505 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKN-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT     06-01 0799
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: HOLZMAN HAD THE FORMULA FOR WINNING 
</HEADLINE>
   By HARVEY ARATON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ He would listen in as the news media know-it-alls
argued over dinner and drinks, the debate raging over the
establishment of the half-court game against the need to get out
and run. Twenty years ago, and probably 20 years before that, the
extreme strategic positions were all the source of comic amusement
to the sagacious basketball lifer.
</P>
<P>
   Red Holzman would invariably begin his arbitration with a
perfectly timed heh-heh, and then he would say, ``Fellas,
basketball is basketball.'' Which was his way of sermonizing that
the game was no more a track meet than it was a tractor pull. It
was and always would be about execution and effort, about reacting
to the moment at hand.
</P>
<P>
   You can pretty much guarantee that the team seeking to redefine
itself in the playoffs is the team that lost the last game. So the
Pacers, back home at Conseco Fieldhouse on Wednesday night, were
suddenly enveloped in the same identity crisis the Knicks have
often mired themselves in on successive playoff campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw what Larry Bird said, `When you lose, the players always
say you should do something else,''' Jeff Van Gundy said before the
Pacers shocked the Knicks, rallying from 18 down in the first half
and winning Game 5, 88-79, for a 3-2 lead in the Eastern Conference
finals.
</P>
<P>
   From management on down, the Pacers had come into this game
offering more propositions than a California voting booth. The
Pacers' ownership stooped to the bush-league level of begging
ticket brokers to not supply the cast of Spike Lee's next film with
prime courtside real estate. Yet the most troubling of signs for
the home team were the complaints that this series was slipping
away on account of an offensive pace that, in New York, too often
looked like a match race between Sam Perkins and Rik Smits.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, you want to push the ball when you get the
opportunity,'' Van Gundy said. ``But how many easy baskets you get
stems from how you defend and how you rebound.''
</P>
<P>
   Basketball, fellas, is basketball, and it wasn't until the
Pacers were about to be run and booed out of their own gym that
they reached down for something few people in the building thought
they had. They played defense like their playoff lives depended on
it. They were in a state of despair, losing 37-19 when Allan
Houston hit a 3 with 10:42 left in the first half. Then it was if
the script was torn up and tossed in the fire. The Knicks made one
more field goal the rest of the half. They lost the lead and went
off trailing 42-40, a 23-3 Indiana run.
</P>
<P>
   Don't blame Patrick Ewing for this one. Smits practically begged
for him to play and then Ewing proceeded to abuse him as the Knicks
staged a first-quarter clinic. Ewing was on the bench when the
Knicks' drought started, when the Pacers finally stopped worrying
about expectations and conspiracies and responded to the moment at
hand.
</P>
<P>
   Holzman, coach of the only two Knick champions, was right _ the
game is about execution and effort, in half-court and full-court _
and in Game 5, the Pacers did it both ways. The championship
demands nothing less. From the second quarter on, the Pacers played
with purpose and resiliency. There was a point where they outscored
the Knicks 44-14. Their point guards, Mark Jackson and Travis Best,
played the second half with a vengeance. Jackson had a big third
quarter and did a little showboating, Larry Johnson-style, crossing
his arms, ``thanking God,'' each time he scored.
</P>
<P>
   L.J., incidentally, was the latest of the Knicks' game-time
decisions, showing up with a sore right foot. The Knicks' injury
reports are getting to be stranger than fiction. By Friday night,
Game 6, we may get one that says, ``Van Gundy, receding hairline,
may coach.''
</P>
<P>
   The Pacers didn't fall for the mind games, not this time. The
series was in their hands last Saturday in New York when Marcus
Camby went down with his sprained knee. They were overwhelmed with
the finals right in front of them. They spent the next seven
quarters playing as if they didn't believe another opportunity was
coming.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, they settled into their defensive stances and created
one themselves, building a bridge back into the series, defensive
stop by stop, Knick brick by brick.
</P>
<P>
   Did the Pacers on this night stop obsessing on what the Knicks
were doing, how many of them were hurting, and just play like a
team worthy of the finals? Do they really believe they can beat the
Knicks? Hard to say, but the Pacers were as out on their feet in
the second quarter Wednesday night as the Knicks were Saturday in
New York. As the Knicks well know, cheating death can be carried a
long way.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
