r a BC-HEALTH-COSTS-2NDTAKE-     06-01 0557
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEALTH-COSTS-2NDTAKE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
   
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ of the country.
</P>
<P>
   Those low payment levels have already become a frustrating issue
among doctors, said Richard Hellman, a physician and president of
the Metropolitan Medical Society of Greater Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   Insurance companies have offered doctors as little as $7 per
month to take care of individual patients, Hellman said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's reached a point where doctors are not going to be able to
do it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   - On most measures, the health of Kansas City residents was on a
par with that of residents of the other benchmark cities.
</P>
<P>
   A lower proportion of area residents had work disabilities
compared to the benchmark cities and to the United States
population overall.
</P>
<P>
   Rates of lung, prostate and colon cancer in Kansas City were
higher than in the other cities. And Kansas City had more deaths
from liver disease and chronic obstructive pulmonary disease.
</P>
<P>
   The most glaring problems the report found were enormous racial
and geographic disparities in the health of area residents.
</P>
<P>
   Residents of Wyandotte and Jackson counties generally had the
most health problems, such as physical disabilities and
communicable diseases such as influenza, pneumonia and AIDS.
Johnson County residents experienced the fewest health problems.
</P>
<P>
   African-American residents of the Kansas City area were more
likely than whites to live in poverty, have low-birthweight babies,
contract sexually transmitted diseases, die at a relatively young
age, and die of chronic conditions such as heart disease.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's intolerable,'' said Kansas City Health Department
director Rex Archer, after hearing the report. ``This report will
help us deal with that.''
</P>
<P>
   Ford and the UAW have begun distributing copies of the
assessment on CD-ROM to members of the health-care community. And
they have set up a Kansas City office that will continue work on
the Health Care Initiative.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll meet with community leaders and groups who have
expressed interest. We'll hold forums, so priorities can be set by
the community, and not by us,'' said Cathy Davis, co-director of
the initiative. ``It's important that this be a community
initiative.''
</P>
<P>
   Some hospitals and insurance companies did not provide data to
the initiative. And the initiative met with some skepticism from
some who heard the presentation of the report's findings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know that it goes anyplace new people aren't already
going,'' said E.J. Holland Jr., assistant vice president for
corporate benefits at Sprint. ``The major employers in town decided
10 years ago to work with...and collaborate with (health care)
providers.''
</P>
<P>
   But most who expressed opinions at the meeting gave the
initiative a glowing review:
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got gobs of competition in this community and precious
little cooperation. This offers the opportunity to cooperate,''
said Tom Bowser, chief operating officer of Blue Cross and Blue
Shield of Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Metropolitan Medical Society is very supportive of this,''
Hellman said. ``Really, you're providing a service to the
community.''
</P>
<P>
   The Community Assessment Factbook can be viewed on the Greater
Kansas City Health Care Initiative's Web site at http:
</P>
</TEXT>
