<HEADLINE>
HEALTH-CARE COSTS HIGHER IN KANSAS CITY, STUDY SHOWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALAN BAVLEY  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ The Kansas City area has almost 1,000 more
hospital beds than it needs, area patients spend more time in the
hospital than patients in similar cities, and their health-care
costs appear to be high, a new report concludes.
</P>
<P>
   Those were among the findings of a massive report assessing
health care in Kansas City. Commissioned by Ford Motor Co. and the
United Auto Workers union, the report was released Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The report, which garnered some skepticism but broad support
upon its release, is the first step in a long-range initiative by
the union and the auto company to improve the health of area
residents and the quality of the services they receive.
</P>
<P>
   Organizers of the UAW-Ford Community Health Care Initiative plan
meetings with community leaders in the fall to develop improvement
projects, using the report's findings to set priorities.
</P>
<P>
   The initiative is part of a 6-year-old industrywide effort by
the UAW and auto manufacturers to lower health-care costs in cities
with large auto factories by improving health care.
</P>
<P>
   Ford has 8,600 employees and retirees in the Kansas City area.
The company's Claycomo, Mo., plant produces the F-150 pickup truck.
</P>
<P>
   The initiative also is supported by General Motors, which has
8,500 employees and retirees in the area.
</P>
<P>
   ``The auto companies spend a tremendous amount on health care.
It's a big part of the compensation package,'' said Bob Alpert,
executive director of the UAW's Center for Community Health Care.
</P>
<P>
   ``The key to improving the cost-effectiveness of these programs
is looking at quality of care. If you improve health status, you
decrease disability. That gives a bottom-line improvement.''
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City is the sixth city with a union-industry health-care
initiative, and the first sponsored by Ford. The other cities with
initiatives involving either General Motors or DaimlerChrysler are
Flint, Mich.; Anderson and Kokomo, Ind.; the Warren-Youngstown area
of Ohio; and Wilmington, Del.
</P>
<P>
   The initiatives already have led to a number of projects to
improve care:
</P>
<P>
   - In Anderson, two asthma clinics have been set up to help
patients care for themselves. They have succeeded in reducing
hospitalizations.
</P>
<P>
   - In Youngstown, a community effort to signed up children for
the federally funded Children's Health Insurance Program.
</P>
<P>
   - And in Flint, hospitals have been collaborating to create
centers of excellence for specialized services to avoid costly
duplication. That meant one hospital closed its heart surgery
program to let another hospital concentrate on those procedures.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to sound Polyannaish, but there is evidence that
this (initiative process) works,'' said Raymond Baxter, executive
vice president of the Lewin Group. The Fairfax, Va.-based health
services consulting firm has advised the union and auto industry on
the initiatives.
</P>
<P>
   In each city, the initiative started with an assessment of the
health of area residents and the cost and quality of local
health-care services.
</P>
<P>
   The Kansas City area Community Assessment Factbook, compiled by
the Lewin Group, took two years to complete and fills more than 700
pages.
</P>
<P>
   The report covers Clay, Platte and Jackson counties in Missouri
and Wyandotte and Johnson counties in Kansas. It uses data from a
variety of industry and government sources. And it draws
comparisons between the Kansas City area and several other similar
benchmark cities: Wichita, St. Louis, Indianapolis, Minneapolis-St.
Paul and Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   Among its key findings, presented Wednesday at a meeting with
community and health-care leaders:
</P>
<P>
   - Hospitals in Clay, Platte and Jackson counties had 618 more
beds than they needed to maintain optimum occupancy levels;
hospitals in Johnson and Wyandotte counties had 345 excess beds.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a more than ample supply of hospital beds, and if use
were the same as in other (benchmark) communities, that surplus
would be even greater,'' Baxter said.
</P>
<P>
   The number of excess beds would be as much as twice as high if
Kansas City patients had hospital stays as short as those of
patients in the benchmark cities, the report said.
</P>
<P>
   The average length of stay of a hospital patient in Kansas City
was 5.6 days, compared to 4.9 days in St. Louis and 4.2 days in
Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   Hospital stays also cost more in the Kansas City area than
elsewhere. On average, commercial insurance companies paid $6,135
per hospital admission in the area. That was 55 percent more than
the $3,970 average payment nationally.
</P>
<P>
   Corinne Everson, spokeswoman for St. Luke's Hospital, one of the
region's largest, said she had not had time to review the report,
but suggested its statistics be compared to those from other
sources, such as government Medicare data, and not used alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``We always encourage the public and employers to not rely on
one source of information, but to get multiple sources of data,''
Everson said.
</P>
<P>
   - The Kansas City area has about 4,600 physicians, more for its
population than other benchmark cities.
</P>
<P>
   But area residents who were privately insured didn't use
physician or other professional health services _ particularly
pathology, psychiatric and podiatry services _ as often as people
living in most of the benchmark cities.
</P>
<P>
   The exception: Kansas City area Medicare patients. They used
professional services at a higher rate than Medicare recipients in
other cities.
</P>
<P>
   Private health insurance plans also paid health-care
professionals less for their services than the going rates in most
parts of the country. MORE
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
