<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-INDIANS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINLEY GETS IT DONE AGAINST ANGELS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.2000 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ The uniform jersey was different, but the man and
the pitcher were all too familiar to the Angels.
</P>
<P>
   Chuck Finley, who signed a three-year, $27 million contract with
the Cleveland Indians during the winter, pitched the way he had so
many times in his 14 seasons with the Angels. He wasn't spectacular
but found a way to get the job done, earning the victory in the
Indians' 7-3 win Wednesday night in front of 41,637 at Jacobs
Field.
</P>
<P>
   Finley gave up a two-run homer to Tim Salmon in the first inning
and was charged with an unearned run in the seventh. In all, he
went 62/3 innings and allowed three runs (two earned) and nine
hits, striking out eight and walking three.
</P>
<P>
   ``His game he threw tonight, we've been on the other side so
many times,'' Salmon said. ``It seemed so many times we'd start to
get a rally going and it stalls out. It was a typical Finley
performance. He teases you a little and shuts you down.''
</P>
<P>
   The start of the game was delayed 57 minutes by rain, making
Finley a bit antsy. But after Salmon's homer in the first, Finley
danced and darted his way out of potentially big Angels innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were hitting me pretty decent,'' said Finley (4-4). ``I
don't like to practice that, it's just the way I was born. God gave
easy games to someone else, I guess. ... Every inning, I looked
around and they had people on base. It was a battle for me.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a battle Finley won.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why I came to Anaheim,'' said Mo Vaughn, who struck out
three times against Finley. ``I came here so I wouldn't have to
face him. That was the whole purpose of coming here. He threw as
well as I've ever seen him throw, even when I was in Boston.''
</P>
<P>
   Salmon and Keith Luuloa had the most success against Finley,
each getting three hits. Salmon's fourth hit of the game came in
the ninth off Steve Karsay.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was weird,'' Salmon said. ``From playing behind him, I felt
like I had a pretty good scouting report. But he's still got good
stuff. It's one thing to know what he's going to throw and another
thing to try to hit it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When you face your old team you think they know how you pitch,
but you've got to stay with your strengths,'' Finley said. ``We
switched some (pitch) sequences around, pitched backwards, threw
more breaking balls. It was a chess game, really.''
</P>
<P>
   Finley earned his checkmate and sent his former teammates home
with their second consecutive loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``You look at all the premier pitchers in the league, (Pedro)
Martinez, (Roger) Clemens and a guy like Finley,'' Angels manager
Mike Scioscia said. ``These guys very rarely get in trouble, but
when they do, they turn it up a notch to make pitches and get out
of it. That's a common denominator for any pitcher that's going to
be successful.''
</P>
<P>
   Going into the game, the Angels were third in the American
League in runners left on base, and they were at it again
Wednesday. They left 14 runners on and went 1 for 10 with runners
in scoring position.
</P>
<P>
   They had at least one hit in all nine innings, but never more
than two in any inning. They out-hit the Indians 14-10, but the
Indians made their hits count, getting a season-high five homers in
the game, including three in the decisive sixth inning. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
