<HEADER>
A1513 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKN-KNICKS-PACERS-HNS     06-01 0898
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-PACERS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By MICHAEL MURPHY &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 2000, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
INDIANAPOLIS _ The Pacers do it so often you have to figure it's
part of the game plan. The ``Gasoline Rally,'' that is.
</P>
<P>
   You know the routine _ fall behind by double digits and then
stage a remarkable comeback. Sometimes they manage to pull it off,
sometimes not.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday night, the Pacers pulled it off.
</P>
<P>
   Rallying from an 18-point first-half deficit, the Pacers downed
the Knicks 88-79 in Game 5 of the Eastern Conference finals, which
was played before 18,345 in Conseco Fieldhouse and thousands more
who were milling about outside, straining to catch glimpses of the
action on video screens.
</P>
<P>
   So the series not even the Amazing Kreskin could predict will
resume Friday at Madison Square Garden with the Pacers leading 3-2,
just one victory away from advancing to the NBA Finals for the
first time.
</P>
<P>
   Even for the Knicks and the Pacers, Wednesday's game represented
a milestone of unpredictability.
</P>
<P>
   In the previous two games, played at Madison Square Garden, the
Pacers quickly fell behind by huge margins. Of course they rallied,
coming back from a 13-point deficit to lose Game 3 by three points
and then rallying from 17 points down in Game 4, only to come up
just two short.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Larry Bird addressed his team's poor starts, hoping to
avoid the first-quarter blues the Pacers had endured in New York.
So, of course, they promptly went out and fell behind by 15 points
in the opening period.
</P>
<P>
   And just like the previous two games, the Pacers rallied.
</P>
<P>
   The difference was that this time they succeeded.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glad they didn't put their heads between their legs and
worry about how the crowd was reacting (after their poor start),''
Bird said of the Pacers' horrible start. ``I really believe that
the guys had it in their minds that they were going to give a full
48-minute effort, and they did that.''
</P>
<P>
   And this came against a Knicks team that was at full strength _
or at least what amounts to full strength for them.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Ewing, who had missed the previous two games with a foot
injury, was back on the floor. Larry Johnson, who was allegedly
suffering from plantar fasciitis in his right foot, an injury
suffered in the final minutes of Game 4, also played. Latrell
Sprewell refused to let a broken bone in his left foot keep him off
the floor.
</P>
<P>
   So, of course, the Knicks played miserably after a superb start.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even at halftime, after being up 18 and losing the lead, still
you're only minus-two on the road at that point,'' said Knicks
coach Jeff Van Gundy. ``But we have to try to put that (the Pacers'
rally) aside and come out and play a strong second half and find a
way to win. And we didn't get that done.
</P>
<P>
   ``There can't be any carryover or hangover effect (for Game 6).
If there is, we're going to be in a hole to start Game 6, and we
can't afford to be in a hole. We have to learn from this, move on
and play one great home game to try and force a deciding game
here.''
</P>
<P>
   Travis Best led the Pacers with a playoff career-high 24 points,
outdueling New York's Allan Houston, who was one of the few Knicks
to play well in this game, finishing with 25 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just trying to be aggressive,'' Best said. ``I didn't
think they could check me. I was feeling good, and I was able to
stay in the game. I thought that the two games in New York (where
he had 21 points total) I got in foul trouble and had some calls go
against me.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today, with the fans here and in a game that was so important,
I just wanted to come out and put up some shots. Things worked out
for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Jalen Rose added 18 points and Reggie Miller 16, while Derrick
McKey grabbed nine rebounds and played strong defense, especially
on Johnson, who finished with four points and four rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   Sprewell played like someone trying to gut out a broken foot,
scoring 10 points while making only four of his 14 shots. Ewing
played like a guy with two (broken) left feet, scoring 13 points _
but only four after the first period.
</P>
<P>
   Don't be surprised to hear the anti-Ewing sentiment again.
Against the Pacers in the conference finals the last two years, the
Knicks are 5-1 without Ewing and 1-5 with him.
</P>
<P>
   While the Pacers led by only two points at halftime, the Knicks
looked like a defeated team.
</P>
<P>
   After falling behind by 18 in the opening minutes of the second
period, the Pacers used a Twilight Zone-worthy second quarter to
rally, deflating the Knicks in the process.
</P>
<P>
   After scoring 32 points and shooting 63 percent from the floor
in the first period, the Knicks wound up with just eight points in
the second, making only two of 16 field-goal attempts (13 percent),
and the Pacers were more than willing to take advantage.
</P>
<P>
   Indiana, which was behind by double digits for much of the first
half, still trailed by 11 points with four minutes to play in the
half when Marcus Camby hit a free throw.
</P>
<P>
   Indiana then put together a 13-0 run to close the period, with
four Pacers scoring, to take a 42-40 lead at the half.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't worry about the ups and downs and the emotional joy
ride,'' Rose said of the Pacers' propensity for poor starts. ``We
know that we have what it takes to come back. We just have to stay
in there mentally and get the job done.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
