<P>
   EMAIL-POLITICS (Undated) _ Hour by hour, the e-mail arrives like
digital daggers from the candidates and their parties. Catty,
pithy, weighty, gossipy, the messages materialize via the open
cyberfaucet of the 2000 campaign. ``Bush's Million Mom
Manipulation,'' began a message from the Democrats. ``Democrat Fat
Cat Discriminates Against Those Who Flee Castro's Clutches,'' read
one from the Republicans. Only by extension is the target of the
computer missives the American voter. The more immediate audience
is the American journalist. By Peter Marks.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON _ (Moved in ``w'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   DRUG-PRICES _ More and more in recent years, private insurance
has been picking up the cost of prescription medicine. Only about
one-quarter of the total drug costs of Americans are now paid out
of pocket. That explains why there is no general political uproar,
even though drug prices in the United States have been rising by as
much as 15 percent a year, the pharmaceutical manufacturers are
among the most profitable businesses in the world and many new
drugs in Canada and Europe cost a fraction of what they do here.
Imagine the political swivet Americans would be in if that were the
case with gasoline or some other staple of daily life. The elderly,
of course, are up in arms. Those who are completely dependent on
Medicare, which does not cover the cost of outpatient
prescriptions, bear the brunt of the skyrocketing prices. But most
Americans never face these high drug prices. They pay no more than
$5 or $10 for each prescription. By David E. Rosenbaum. (1400
words)
</P>
<P>
   MINN-WELFARE _ Large-scale study of Minnesota welfare reform
finds extremely positive effects: higher earnings and income, less
poverty, an increase in marriage rates and marital stability and
improvements in children's behavior and school performance _ a
combination never seen before. By Robert Pear.
</P>
