<P>
   AUSTIN-HOUSE (Hartford, Conn. _ Arthur Everett Austin Jr., or
Chick, as he was known from childhood, managed to have the last
word on himself, by getting the first one in. ``The house is just
like me,'' he told critics and admirers of the 86-foot-wide,
one-room-deep, painted-wood Palladian villa with the Venetian
baroque and International style interiors. ``All facade.'' After 20
months and half a million dollars of cosmetic labor, the
``pasteboard palace,'' as local grandees dubbed it, will greet
Hartford society again. The Atheneum, which now owns the Austin
house and has restored it, will unveil it to trustees next
Thursday. By William L. Hamilton.
</P>
