<HEADER>
A1517 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a BC-GONZALEZ-BIO-LADN     06-01 0620
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GONZALEZ-BIO-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAMILY, FRIENDS MOURN WOMAN WITH PROMISING FUTURE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREG GITTRICH AND LISA VAN PROYEN 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Lori Gonzalez's family and friends mourned the
slain 20-year-old Tuesday, describing her as a young woman with a
promising future who taught Bible study classes for children.
</P>
<P>
   Bright, attractive, hard-working and caring, Gonzalez, the
granddaughter of Police Chief Bernard C. Parks, had left her
community college in Mission Viejo just a few weeks ago to visit
her parents and friends in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday night, she was killed at a Popeyes Chicken
drive-through restaurant in the Jefferson Park area of South Los
Angeles by bullets police said were intended for a man described as
an acquaintance.
</P>
<P>
   Family members and friends said Gonzalez chose her friends
carefully.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's devastating. Everyone's in shock. I think everybody can't
believe this has happened,'' said the Rev. Eric Nachtrieb,
Gonzalez's pastor and a spokesman for her grieving family.
</P>
<P>
   She had three semesters behind her at Saddleback College. In
recent weeks, she was training for an entry-level job at Pacific
Bell.
</P>
<P>
   Nachtrieb called Gonzalez ``one of the key leaders'' of a
ministry serving children at Coast Hills Community Church in Aliso
Viejo. She regularly attended church with her father, Joe, and her
stepmother, Debbie. Each Sunday morning, she taught a group of
about 15 children, reading them Bible stories, leading them in
group singing, and introducing them to religious crafts.
</P>
<P>
   She also participated in mission trips to Mexico, where she and
other church members would build homes for disadvantaged children,
her pastor said.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was very warm, loving and friendly,'' he said. ``It was
not uncommon to see her on the floor with a couple kids in her lap.
She was very faithful with the kids and they loved her.''
</P>
<P>
   For the past year, Gonzalez had lived with her father in Mission
Viejo.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was really sad to hear what happened. It really hit me this
morning,'' said Goy Casillas, vice principal of Redondo Union High
School, where Gonzalez graduated in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was a very bright, genuine young lady who worked hard. She
was attractive and had a very nice, open personality. She was a
person who you could make friends with very easily,'' Casillas
recalled without a pause.
</P>
<P>
   When Gonzalez attended the Redondo Beach high school, she lived
mostly with her mother in the beachside community south of Los
Angeles. But about two months before she was set to graduate, she
moved down to Mission Viejo to be with her father. Her parents have
been divorced for 18 years and shared custody of their daughter,
family friends said.
</P>
<P>
   ``She moved, but she really wanted to graduate from Redondo,''
Casillas said. And she did.
</P>
<P>
   Administrators from the two schools allowed Gonzalez to finish
her Redondo Union classes in Mission Viejo. At the end of the year,
she returned to Redondo Beach and walked in the graduation line
with her friends and former classmates, Casillas said.
</P>
<P>
   Those who knew Gonzalez from high school - including teachers,
administrators and even a campus security guard - said she was a
hard-working student who volunteered to be a teacher's assistant
and enrolled in the Marine Corps ROTC program for a little more
than a year.
</P>
<P>
   Since the summer of 1999, Gonzalez attended Saddleback College,
where she majored in English. Gonzalez was close to completing a
three-week training program to be a Pacific Bell operator in
Anaheim. She previously worked at a Sav-On Drug Store in Mission
Viejo after becoming a beautician.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
