<HEADER>
A1518 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBN-DODGERS-NOTEBOOK-     06-01 0726
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-NOTEBOOK-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT TO DO WITH SHAW?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Dodgers general manager Kevin Malone wouldn't rule
out closer Jeff Shaw being put on the disabled list, but it's not
in the immediate plans. For now, manager Davey Johnson will use a
bullpen by committee in tight situations while Shaw sits.
</P>
<P>
   Shaw has blown 5 of 16 save opportunities, opponents are hitting
.316 against him and his ERA is a robust 7.84 in 22 appearances, so
Johnson said he's going to ease off him. Shaw is experiencing
weakness in the back of his pitching (right) shoulder, and Johnson
said he'll rest him for a while.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him I was going to stay off him and let him regroup a
little bit,'' Johnson said. ``He's doing some exercises. There's no
question he has some weakness there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I agree with him in it's not like he's been getting totally
hammered. It's ground-ball base hits, but he's not throwing it like
he's been capable of throwing it.''
</P>
<P>
   Shaw, who is owed $5 million this season and $6 million in 2001,
said he doesn't feel like his fastball has its usual zip and his
slider is flat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last week it felt like I was throwing the ball 80 miles per
hour,'' Shaw said. ``The radar gun still said 91, 92, but I don't
feel like the ball is exploding out of my hand.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said he'll rely on his stable of former closers while
Shaw regains his health, which the Dodgers hope leads to him
regaining his form. Mike Fetters, Terry Adams and Antonio Osuna,
depending on the situation, will each be asked to pick up the
slack.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been through (a bullpen by committee) the last five years
in Chicago, but as long as Jeff Shaw is on this ballclub, he's the
closer,'' said Adams, who saved 13 games for the Cubs last season.
``We all go through streaks when we struggle. Like any pitcher, any
kind of ache is going to cause you difficulty. But we have enough
arms down there that somebody can pick somebody up and give (Shaw)
a break.''
</P>
<P>
   PEREZ, DODGERS AGREE: The Dodgers and Carlos Perez reached
agreement on an extension in which the left-hander waived his right
to decline a minor-league assignment despite having five years of
major-league service time.
</P>
<P>
   Perez's representatives, Adam Katz and Tom Reich, met with
Dodgers officials again Wednesday and reached an agreement that is
believed to be similar to the one he signed in late April, though
it wasn't made public until May 1. At that time, it was a 45-day
window in which Perez said he would waive his right to decline an
assignment. That window closed Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   While the Dodgers were seeking another 45-day agreement, Perez's
representatives held out to lessen the deal, and the Dodgers are
believed to have come down substantially from that. It's also the
last such deal that will be worked out, a person familiar with the
process said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Carlos wanted to make sure that if he continued doing what
he's doing, he wouldn't be sent down,'' a source said. ``This
agreement takes care of that.''
</P>
<P>
   Perez is 4-2 with a 5.40 ERA, and he's pitched well in seven of
his nine starts. The Dodgers plan to use Perez cautiously, starting
him against teams he matches up well against.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of tough when you do it for a second time,'' Perez
said. ``We are doing this because (the Dodgers) wanted to do
something. I guess I have to keep doing what I'm doing, just
pitching good.''
</P>
<P>
   If Perez didn't agree to an extension, the Dodgers were prepared
to send him to the minors before Wednesday's game. But that also
could have brought a litany of problems, including a grievance from
the players association.
</P>
<P>
   LODUCA TO ARRIVE: Even before the injury to Todd Hundley, the
Dodgers planned to recall infielder Alex Cora and return
switch-hitting catcher Adam Melhuse to Triple-A Albuquerque.
</P>
<P>
   However, with Hundley going on the 15-day disabled list with a
strained oblique muscle, plans have changed. Melhuse is still
expected to be sent back to Albuquerque before Friday's game at
Anaheim, but catcher Paul LoDuca is expected to join the club.
</P>
<P>
   For the second time this season, catching prospect Angel Pena is
down with a hip flexor injury, so LoDuca gets the call. He's
hitting .299 with no homers and 22 RBI in 41 games with the Dukes. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
