<HEADLINE>
DEFENSE KEY TO SPARKS' VICTORY OVER UTAH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PAMELA LEWIS  
 c.2000 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD _ They talked defense, practiced defense emphasized
defense in the preseason.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday was the first regular-season test, and the Sparks
passed.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a short letup, the Sparks were able to hold off the Utah
Starzz's late charge and finish with a 69-62 victory in front of
6,112 at the Forum.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought our defense was spectacular for 40 minutes,'' said
Michael Cooper, who got his first win as coach. ``If this team
plays up to its ability, you're looking at the next WNBA
champion.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that their offense was much better, but the Sparks limited
the Starzz to 34 percent from the field, had 13 steals and forced
20 turnovers. The Sparks, who shot 33 percent from the field, shot
80 percent (20 of 25) from the free-throw line.
</P>
<P>
   Mwadi Mabika had a game-high 21 points. DeLisha Milton, in foul
trouble much of the game, finished with 11 points and five
rebounds. Lisa Leslie, who fouled out with less than a minute to
play, had 11 rebounds and became the league's all-time leading
rebounder with 810. Her eight points also put past 1,500 and into
third all-time behind Houston's Cynthia Cooper and Phoenix's
Jennifer Gillom.
</P>
<P>
   Utah resurfaced behind UCLA alum Natalie Williams and made a
late charge. She scored seven points in a 9-0 run that cut the
Sparks lead to 64-61.
</P>
<P>
   The Starzz' 7-foot-2 Margo Dydek tried to make it a one-point
game when she attempted a 3-pointer from the top of the key.
</P>
<P>
   ``She can shoot that shot,'' Utah coach Fred Williams said.
``She won two ballgames for us last year with that shot. Those are
good looks for her. She has a good percentage from there.''
</P>
<P>
   Ukari Figgs, who missed two crucial free throws, got a chance to
redeem herself when she made two free throws with 20 seconds to
play as the Sparks went up 68-62.
</P>
<P>
   The Sparks got through much of the first half without Milton,
who picked up her third foul with 15 minutes remaining in the
second half. But the Sparks had enough depth on the bench. Cooper
went 11 deep.
</P>
<P>
   Mabika led the Sparks with 12 points as they took a 35-34
advantage into the break.
</P>
<P>
   Williams had 21 points and 14 rebounds, and Adrienne Goodson had
14 points.
</P>
<P>
   Utah coach Williams, who coached at USC, said the Sparks'
defense was a big factor in the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``They did take away a lot of our looks,'' Williams said. ``They
pressured our wings. That what the Sparks do. I thought we played
very hard, we picked our defense up in the second half. We hung in
there.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
