<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 01:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1520 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BBN-ASTROS-ROCKIES-HN     06-01 0968
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-ROCKIES-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CARLTON THOMPSON  
 c. 2000, Houston Chronicle  
DENVER _ If the Astros were a college football team, they would be
the most sought-after homecoming opponent in the nation.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Alas, they are a major-league baseball team, regardless of how
infrequently they have resembled one this season. Stop if you've
heard this before, but the Astros jumped out to an early lead
Wednesday night, only to watch it disappear in an 8-6 loss to the
Colorado Rockies at Coors Field.
</P>
<P>
   Lance Berkman's seventh-inning two-run homer tied the score and
gave the Astros new life, but the joy was short-lived. Jeffrey
Hammonds put the Rockies on top for good with a massive two-run
homer to straightaway center field off a 98-mph fastball thrown by
Billy Wagner in the eighth inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was right down the middle,'' said Wagner, who has allowed
12 earned runs in his last 10 innings. ``If he misses that one,
he's kicking himself.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros' road losing streak reached nine games, the longest
such skid since the club lost 12 in a row on the road in 1996. They
have lost 12 of their last 16 games overall.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not going to be long before this thing is going to turn
around, and we're going to be jumping all over these teams that are
jumping all over us,'' Wagner said. ``Teams should be wanting to
play us right now. They don't even have to beat us; we're finding
ways to beat ourselves. But we're going to get through this.''
</P>
<P>
   Continuing to test the theories of Murphy's Law, the Astros
discovered yet another thing that could go wrong Wednesday, giving
the Rockies two earned runs that were indirectly the result of
Berkman's losing a ball in the lights in the third inning. A catch
would have been the third out of the inning; the next batter,
Darren Bragg, hit a two-run double.
</P>
<P>
   ``The beat goes on,'' Astros manager Larry Dierker said. ``If we
don't beat ourselves, some sort of quirky thing beats us. We're not
playing in a lot of good fortune right now. We're not playing well,
and a part of it is that we've had no luck. It's a recurring theme,
and it's not a good one.''
</P>
<P>
   The fluky play in the outfield marred another fine night at the
plate for Berkman, who was 3-for-4 with a career-high-tying four
RBIs for the second game in a row. Berkman continues to be one of
the Astros' biggest run producers over the past week, having
tallied 13 RBIs in six games since being recalled from the minors
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't get too high about my hitting, because it doesn't
amount to much in a loss,'' Berkman said. ``I'm swinging the bat
pretty well right now, but there are some other things that I did
that hurt us. I had a baserunning mistake (in the third inning),
and I lost that ball in the lights, and the guy ends up hitting a
double.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros' record dropped to 19-33, third-worst in the majors
ahead of Philadelphia and Tampa Bay. They remained in last place in
the National League Central, which they have won each of the past
three seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you had told me the Astros were going to be a last-place
team, I would have said, `That's unbelievable,''' said Astros
starter Jose Lima, who hasn't won a decision since April 5 _ his
first start of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's game came down to the final innings, but it didn't
appear headed that way from the beginning. The Astros led 4-0 after
2{ innings, but the Rockies tied the score with four runs in the
bottom of the third.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the past, if we score four runs that early, it's a done
deal,'' Lima said. ``But for some reason, nothing is going our
way.''
</P>
<P>
   Lima, who is hardly the Astros' best-hitting pitcher, helped
himself simply by putting the ball in play in the second inning.
His bases-loaded fielder's-choice grounder drove home the Astros'
first run. It was Lima's first RBI of the season, and it came in
his 18th at-bat.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros added three more runs in the third inning, courtesy
of a pair of players who began the season at Class AAA New Orleans.
Berkman, after falling behind 0-2 in the count, drove home two runs
with a single up the middle, and Julio Lugo added an RBI single.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockies' four-run third inning included Jeff Cirillo's
two-out, two-run homer and Bragg's two-run double. However, Bragg
never would have batted if Berkman hadn't lost Hammonds' fly ball
in the lights.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't see that ball for the last 10 feet,'' Berkman said.
``It was freakish.''
</P>
<P>
   Cirillo doubled home another run in the fifth, and Mike
Lansing's solo homer in the sixth pushed the Rockies' lead to 6-4.
</P>
<P>
   Lima didn't make it out of the sixth inning, marking the sixth
time he has failed to complete six innings in his last eight
starts. He failed to complete six innings in just five of his 35
starts last season.
</P>
<P>
   Rockies starter Masato Yoshii didn't appear to be long for
Wednesday's game after the Astros ripped him for four runs on 10
hits through the first three innings. But he settled down and
retired 10 of the last 12 batters he faced, allowing just two more
hits in his 6-inning performance. The 12 hits allowed established a
career high for Yoshii.
</P>
<P>
   Berkman atoned for his error with a towering two-run homer off
righthanded reliever Stan Belinda that tied the score in the
seventh inning. Berkman has hit four home runs in his last five
games, and the Astros have hit at least one homer in a club-record
18 consecutive games.
</P>
<P>
   But in the end, Berkman was upstaged by Hammonds.
</P>
<P>
   ``In that situation, if he gets me with a slider, all you can do
is tip your cap,'' Hammonds said of his confrontation with Wagner.
``I was just looking dead red. I got a pitch to hit. Getting a
pitch to hit and hitting it are two different things. Two weeks
ago, I wouldn't have hit it.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
