<SLUG> BC-MAYOR-LAPD-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
L.A. MAYOR AGAINST FEDERAL CONSENT DECREE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICK ORLOV 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES - Mayor Richard Riordan has come out against any
effort to impose a federal consent decree on the Los Angeles Police
Department or even the appointment of a monitor to oversee the
troubled agency.
</P>
<P>
   In his strongest language to date, Riordan offered a hearty
endorsement of Police Chief Bernard C. Parks and said the
department can clean itself up with federal help but no permanent
control of the LAPD.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is they (federal officials) agree that Chief
Parks is doing a good job in cleaning up the mess,'' Riordan said
Wednesday during his monthly ``Ask the Mayor'' show on radio
station KFWB-AM (980). ``The problem is, in talking to a lot of
people at the Department of Justice we're not sure where they're
coming from or where they want to get.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have the civilian Police Commission and the Inspector
General's Office, all of whom have the same goal of cleaning up the
LAPD and make it even better.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't need to have them sue us. We don't need to have a
consent decree. We don't need to have them monitor us. We are
willing to seek their advice and make this a better department,''
Riordan said.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor's assertion went beyond his earlier statements after a
federal threat last month to sue Los Angeles unless the city enters
a court-supervised agreement, known as a consent decree, to place
LAPD reform in the hands of a court-appointed monitor.
</P>
<P>
   On May 9, for example, Riordan argued local leaders should
continue to control LAPD reform but he declined to take a stand on
a consent decree and refused to say whether he would oppose federal
control if it meant avoiding a civil rights lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor's latest remarks came as city officials are scheduled
to meet Thursday with officials from the Justice Department's civil
rights division in negotiations over whether a consent decree will
be sought.
</P>
<P>
   Riordan's top aide, Deputy Mayor Kelly Martin, is his
representative on the city team headed by City Attorney James Hahn
and includes Chief Legislative Analyst Ron Deaton and LAPD
representatives.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor's remarks Wednesday angered Councilman Mark
Ridley-Thomas, who has been involved in issues concerning the
Police Department since before his election in 1993. Previously,
Ridley-Thomas headed the Southern Christian Leadership Conference
in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the mayor makes remarks like that, you can tell he is not
committed to police reform,'' said Ridley-Thomas, who was among a
number of city officials who welcomed the Justice Department's
efforts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all agree we want the best Police Department -- but the
best Police Department for the public, and not the best Police
Department for the police,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But in his radio remarks, Riordan insisted Parks can make the
changes necessary because of his own high standards and tough
disciplinary action.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bernie Parks has fired more officers in two years for
misconduct than were fired for the 15 years before him,'' Riordan
said. ``He does not tolerate deviant behavior.
</P>
<P>
   ``And, I agree that what happened at the Rampart Division was
wrong, but we can't allow the Police Department to be demoralized.
Crime has gone down for seven straight years,'' Riordan said.
</P>
<P>
   XXX &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
