<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PHONE-CHARGES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TYPICAL PHONE BILL TO FALL IN JULY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JASON Z. COHEN 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Families and some businesses will save money on
their phone bills next month under the restructured long-distance
rate plan announced by the Federal Communications Commission.
</P>
<P>
   The $3.2 billion cost-saving plan, called the largest rate cut
in the history of federal telephone regulation, should have the
biggest impact on the poor and those who use their phones the
least. Rates would be reduced by as much as 50 percent for
Americans who make few or no long-distance calls.
</P>
<P>
   For consumers and businesses that make more long-distance calls,
the government predicted reduced costs, although some consumer
groups and Wall Street analysts disagreed with the government's
estimates, suggesting they were too rosy.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, in announcing the agreement with phone companies
Wednesday, the FCC released an analysis indicating the savings
might not last long and overall charges might actually be higher
within two years.
</P>
<P>
   The plan eliminates $3.2 billion in access charges paid by
long-distance companies to local phone companies. Customers are now
billed for these fees, which are referred to as pass-through
charges.
</P>
<P>
   ``These charges, no matter if you make calls or not, still
appear on your bill,'' said Linda Sherry, editorial director for
Consumer Action, a San Francisco-based consumer advocacy group.
</P>
<P>
   Starting in July, customers will be charged less for
long-distance access and might find lower per-minute costs as well.
</P>
<P>
   The plan is a modified version of a proposal submitted by the
Coalition for Affordable Local and Long Distance Service, an
industry group made up of representatives from AT&AMP;T, Bell Atlantic,
BellSouth, GTE, SBC Communications and Sprint.
</P>
<P>
   The provisions of the plan include the elimination of the
presubscribed interexchange carrier charge -- PICC on phone bills
-- which has cost consumers $1.50 per month. The charge was
scheduled to increase to $2 per line in July, said Matt Miller,
spokesman for SBC Communications.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the charge will be eliminated and partly rolled into
the subscriber line charge, now $3.50 per month. After the change,
the fee will be $4.50, instead of two fees of $3.50 and $2, Miller
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The PICC is going to disappear,'' Miller said. ``We're going
to stop charging that to long-distance companies, and in turn
they're going to stop charging it to their customers.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the per-minute fee that long-distance carriers pay
to local phone companies will be reduced to less than 1 cent per
minute -- 0.55 of a cent -- from an average of 1.5 cents for
Pacific Bell customers.
</P>
<P>
   While the new rules will lower the fees at first, the FCC
projects higher bills for consumers in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   FCC analysts say an average residential customer would have paid
$7.62 in monthly fees for July 2000 under the old rules. The same
customer will pay $6.79 in fees under the new plan.
</P>
<P>
   But in July 2002, that same customer will pay an estimated $7.68
in monthly fees under the new plan, while that customer would have
paid $7.42 under the current rate structure.
</P>
<P>
   And in July 2004, the average customer will pay $7.75 in fees
under the new plan instead of $6.85 in fees if the current rules
had been left in place.
</P>
<P>
   The projected increases probably reflect a scheduled rise in the
subscriber line charge from its initial $4.35 to $6.50 in 2003,
Miller said. The increase must be approved before it takes effect,
however.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before it rises, the FCC must do a cost-showing -- to show
that the rise is necessary,'' Miller said. ``Remember, $3.2 billion
is coming out of the system.''
</P>
<P>
   An additional provision of the agreement is that Sprint and AT&AMP;T
have agreed to eliminate the $3 monthly charge levied on all
long-distance customers who do not make a monthly minimum of calls.
</P>
<P>
   MCI Worldcom, which was not part of the coalition, also
eliminated its monthly minimum charge, spokeswoman Julie Moore
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Worldcom supports the pro-consumer goals of the plan,'' Moore
said. ``In the past, whenever we received any reductions in access
charges, we have passed them along to our customers.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (italics) The New York Times contributed to this story.(end
italics)
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-01-00 0220EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
