<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 02:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1525 &Cx1f; tth-z
r s BC-BKC-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI &LR;      06-01 0829
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EMBATTLED COACH NO KNIGHT IN SHINING ARMOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ I'm hurt.
</P>
<P>
   I wasn't invited to quiz His Tempestuousness, Bobby Knight.
</P>
<P>
   Darn. I would have loved to ask him what his favorite color is,
just like the other media members.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the ESPN interview Tuesday with Roy Firestone and Digger
Phelps, seven print-reporter colleagues were hand-picked by Knight
for a Q-and-A session the same day.
</P>
<P>
   Knight's answers to them, based on their published stories, were
generally similar to what he told ESPN. Which, if I may be so bold
as to summarize, was something like this:
</P>
<P>
   (START ITAL) So I lost my temper a couple times. So have you.
Here's a blanket apology for anyone sissy enough to be offended.
Now watch me prove you wrong, just like I have done to everyone
every single day of my superior life. (END ITAL).
</P>
<P>
   The print-reporter session did elicit one intriguing answer,
published in the Washington Post. Asked if he wished that the
school's president or trustees had taken action against him years
ago, Knight replied:
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't wish that. But if that should have happened, then it
should have happened five years ago or 10 years ago or 15 years
ago, if that in fact was the case. If there was a feeling whenever,
then sit me down and tell me. I don't have any problems with
guidelines.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I've made a mistake, then somebody needs to say something
to me at that point. If I continue to make the mistake, that's no
longer anybody's fault but mine ... I think it's a matter of
saying, `Here's what I don't want. Here's what I want. And now
let's do it.'''
</P>
<P>
   Well, jeez. The man is right. Unless somebody sat down and told
him, how else was he to know that throwing a chair across a
basketball floor in protest of a call was wrong?
</P>
<P>
   Unless somebody else called it to his attention, how else would
he have known that fighting with his athletic director last
February was a violation of standard employer-employee protocols?
</P>
<P>
   Calling an athletic-department secretary a ``f---ing bitch,''
and knocking out the sports-information director? Really, now, how
could anyone know these things are considered impolite unless one
has read a book of guidelines?
</P>
<P>
   After all these years, we are just learning that Knight is a
lonely soul cast adrift, just waiting for a guiding hand who could
help him distinguish between right and wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Knight's victimhood is mindful of the old Steve Martin routine:
</P>
<P>
   ``Is murder illegal? I ... forgot!''
</P>
<P>
   While explaining right from wrong is a task far too formidable
for a simple media hack _ not to mention hopeless, since most of
Knight's earthly disconnects have come when someone has had the
temerity to suggest he was in error _ it is possible to offer up
some questions that might give Knight help in his quest for truth,
justice and the Indiana way.
</P>
<P>
   Such as:
</P>
<P>
   --After you popped the cop in Puerto Rico in 1979, did you
explain to your players that, while they should never do that,
remember that above all you're an American, so local rules do not
apply?
</P>
<P>
   --When you chewed out Indiana's cheerleaders for cheering and
distracting one of your players, did you also demonstrate your
sportsmanship by chewing them out for distracting the opponent?
</P>
<P>
   --When you screamed at and kicked your own son during a game,
causing the Indiana crowd to boo you, should they have known better
and cheered?
</P>
<P>
   --Speaking of your son, how did his nose get in your way on that
hunting trip?
</P>
<P>
   --You said on national TV that if rape is inevitable, one should
relax and enjoy it, but would you stick to the recommendation if
the various assault claims against you turned into convictions and
you served time in prison?
</P>
<P>
   --When a hand is tightly wrapped around another's throat, when
is it not a choke hold?
</P>
<P>
   --While you credit your wife for her cautionary signs around the
house, ``The horse is dead _ get off it,'' who gets credit for
killing the horse?
</P>
<P>
   --When you persist in behavior that your wives, bosses, closest
friends and basketball colleagues have claimed embarrasses you and
the university and undercuts the worthwhile values you convey, what
snappily sarcastic retort renders moot their contentions?
</P>
<P>
   --Are you a bully? And if you say you aren't, does that make you
a liar?
</P>
<P>
   Undoubtedly, Knight has clever answers for all these questions.
He had clever answers Tuesday, as he has had his 29 years at
Indiana.
</P>
<P>
   No wonder he's supremely arrogant about his ability to flick
away this latest lint attack against his big red sweater.
</P>
<P>
   If he's never been held accountable up to now, nothing in his
experience tells him he can't talk _ and win _ his way around even
a ``zero-tolerance'' policy.
</P>
<P>
   Just give him some guidelines.
</P>
<P>
   P-I columnist Art Thiel can be reached at 206-448-8135
</P>
<P>
   or artthiel &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
