<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 02:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1528 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKL-COMETS-FIRE-HNS &LR;      06-01 0595
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKL-COMETS-FIRE-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By W.H. STICKNEY JR.  
 c. 2000, Houston Chronicle  
PORTLAND, Ore. _ Throughout the WNBA exhibition season, one
established franchise after another stepped forward boasting of
intentions to dethrone the three-time defending champion Comets in
2000.
<TEXT>
<P>
   No one asked Linda Hargrove if she thought her expansion
Portland Fire would fit in among Sacramento, Phoenix and Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday night, in a franchise-first WNBA encounter, the Fire
carried the Comets to double overtime and then came face to face
with Sheryl Swoopes.
</P>
<P>
   End of story. Swoopes collected a huge steal and fast-break
basket with 12.6 seconds left and had four of the five Houston
baskets in the second extra period as the Comets survived 93-89 at
the Rose Garden.
</P>
<P>
   Swoopes, in her second consecutive outstanding outing, led all
scorers with 29 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't take anything away from them; they are a very good
team,'' Swoopes said of the Fire. ``We said at halftime (with
Portland leading 38-34) that we were playing like the expansion
team and they were playing like the champions.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the good thing about our team is that regardless of how
many overtimes it went to, we were never going to give up. Win,
lose or draw, we were going to give it our all and at least say we
left it all out on the court. It wasn't a pretty win, but it was a
`W.'''
</P>
<P>
   Although a little off in her shooting (12-for-27 overall,
0-for-3 on 3-pointers), Swoopes was 5-of-6 from the free-throw line
and had seven rebounds, six assists, six steals and one huge
overtime outburst.
</P>
<P>
   Shooting was one of the sore spots all night for the Comets, who
hit just 33 of 82 shots from the floor.
</P>
<P>
   That and interior defense. With Fire starting center Sylvia
Crawley in foul trouble, Alisa Burras came off the bench and raided
the Comets for 19 points, tying Sophia Witherspoon for a team high,
and eight rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   Crawley had only four points at the end of regulation but got 10
more over the two five-minute extra periods to finish with 14.
</P>
<P>
   Cynthia Cooper struggled to 22 points for the Comets, while Tina
Thompson got 17 points and Janeth Arcain 18.
</P>
<P>
   Cooper missed 10 of her first 11 field-goal attempts, finishing
6-of-23. Swoopes also was experiencing a poor night shooting.
</P>
<P>
   The Fire, meanwhile, led by as many as seven points (35-28) and
took a 38-34 lead into halftime.
</P>
<P>
   Only the offense of Thompson, who got 11 of her 17 points, kept
the Comets close.
</P>
<P>
   There were five ties over the final 4:16 of regulation. A layup
by Tully Bevilaqua netted a 73-73 tie and set up the first OT.
</P>
<P>
   Swoopes and Cooper got two baskets each in the OT, a layup by
Cooper with 6.6 seconds left pulling the Comets even at 81-81.
</P>
<P>
   In the second overtime, Swoopes took charge. A Crawley follow
shot had given Portland the edge 83-81. But Swoopes swished a
jumper from the free-throw line to tie. She had an athletic layup
under the arm of Stacey Thomas to put the Comets up 85-83. But
Crawley connected from the top of the key to again bring about a
tie.
</P>
<P>
   Swoopes interrupted her scoring frenzy long enough to allow
Tiffani Johnson to get her only basket of the night.
</P>
<P>
   Then the 6-foot Swoopes stole a pass from Burras and raced the
length of the floor for a layup that gave the Comets a 91-87 lead
with 12.6 seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to be frank,'' said Comets coach Van Chancellor. ``I
thought they (the Fire) would be tough, but I didn't expect them to
carry us to two overtimes.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
