<HEADER>
A1530 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a BC-LITTON-WARSHIP-LADN     06-01 0272
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LITTON-WARSHIP-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LITTON PROFITS, ORDERS SHOW GROWTH SPURT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREGORY J. WILCOX 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WOODLAND HILLS, Calif. _ Litton Industries has reported a 21
percent jump in per-share earnings for the third quarter and said
its Avondale ship building unit received a $477 million Navy
contract for a new warship.
</P>
<P>
   For the quarter that ended April 30, the big defense and
information technology contractor earned $61.8 million, or $1.33
per share, on revenues of $1.4 billion. This compares with net
income of $50.9 million, or $1.10 per share, on revenues of $1.26
billion for the same quarter last year.
</P>
<P>
   Reported income for the 2000 quarter excludes a one-time gain
that Woodland Hills-based Litton received on the sale of some
business units. Including these profits boosts per-share earnings
to $1.35, or a gain of 23 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Litton's third-quarter results met our expectations and
demonstrated double-digit growth in revenue, net income and
earnings per share. We are encouraged by our record backlog and
solid performances in our core businesses,'' said Michael R. Brown,
Litton's chairman.
</P>
<P>
   Last year Litton bought a competitor, Avondale Industries, and
is now the nation's biggest builder of nonnuclear ships for the
U.S. Navy.
</P>
<P>
   That business got a boost Wednesday as the company announced it
received the contract for the third of as many as eight amphibious
assault ships.
</P>
<P>
   The government plans on a 12-ship fleet, with the remaining four
being built by Bath Iron Works of Bath, Maine.
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
