<DOCNO> NYT20000601.0042 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 02:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1531 &Cx1f; tth-z
r s BC-FBN-SEAHAWKS-SPI &LR;      06-01 0833
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SEAHAWKS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HAWKS IN BIDDING FOR YOUNG, BUT SITUATION REMAINS CLOUDY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CLARE FARNSWORTH  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KIRKLAND, Wash. _ Steve Young will announce soon that he is
retiring. No, wait _ the highest-rated passer in NFL history will
return to the San Francisco 49ers. No, that's not it _ Young will
be released by the 49ers and sign with the Denver Broncos. Or will
it be the Seahawks?
</P>
<P>
   The entire football world, it seems, is awaiting Young's
decision _ which he has been pondering for the past 2{ months, when
he also took an extended honeymoon with his wife, Barbara, who is
pregnant with their first child.
</P>
<P>
   Young was expected to announce his verdict Friday, but was
granted an extension until June 10 after a meeting on Tuesday night
with 49ers coach Steve Mariucci. June 3 had loomed as D-day,
because Young was due a $1 million bonus if still on the roster.
The club granted Young the extra time after he signed a waiver on
receiving the bonus.
</P>
<P>
   No one really knows what Young will do _ not even Young,
apparently. Everyone, however, seems to have an opinion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Another day, another rumor,'' one NFC general manager offered
Wednesday. ``Just when you think you've heard it all, another Steve
Young story pops up.''
</P>
<P>
   The immediate future of the future Hall of Famer has been in
limbo since Sept. 27, when Young received his fourth concussion in
the past three years during the 49ers' game against the Arizona
Cardinals. Young blacked out momentarily and later had
post-concussion symptoms that included dizziness, vomiting and
slurred speech.
</P>
<P>
   So what should Young do? What (BEGIN ITAL) will (END ITAL) he
do?
</P>
<P>
   Young's precarious situation is the latest example of sports
spilling over into the reality of life _ or vice versa. He has
undergone every conceivable test, but even the 49ers want Young to
be cleared by more doctors before letting him back on the field.
</P>
<P>
   Here are a few of the opinions and rumors circulating Wednesday,
and the facts behind them:
</P>
<P>
   Opinion: The San Francisco Examiner published an editorial
Wednesday urging Young to retire: ``There's nothing left for him to
prove on the field, and it would be heresy to see him in a Denver
Broncos uniform. He should hang up his cleats.''
</P>
<P>
   Fact: It is highly unlikely that Young can return to the 49ers,
and he has been told as much by Mariucci. The club does not have
room under its salary cap to accommodate Young, no matter how
contorted the attempts to tweak his contract. He will count $4.2
million against the cap if he plays this season, compared to $1.2
million if he retires or is released after June 1.
</P>
<P>
   Opinion/rumor: Young definitely will play for the Broncos this
season, according to a source in Denver.
</P>
<P>
   Fact: Broncos coach Mike Shanahan has been so open about his
desire to obtain Young that 49ers general manager Bill Walsh
accused the Broncos of tampering and had the league office look
into the matter. A league spokesman said there was nothing to the
allegation, and Walsh has since said he regretted involving the
league.
</P>
<P>
   Rumor: If Young is done in San Francisco, Seahawks coach and
general manager Mike Holmgren has told Young he will work a trade
to obtain him.
</P>
<P>
   Fact: Holmgren has talked to Young this off-season. They have
known each other since 1982, when Holmgren coached Young and the
other quarterbacks at Brigham Young University, and they became
friends while Holmgren was quarterbacks coach and later offensive
coordinator with the 49ers from 1986-91. Holmgren called to
congratulate Young on his marriage and impending fatherhood.
</P>
<P>
   Opinion: Young doesn't know what to do.
</P>
<P>
   Fact: He and the 49ers have agreed that no decision will be
announced until after Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Opinion: Young would be crazy to play football again. A
concussion is a bruising of the brain, and he has had too many to
risk playing again.
</P>
<P>
   Fact: Young, 38, does not have to play football. He has a law
degree, is involved in a new business venture and also auditioned
for the analyst job on ABC's ``Monday Night Football.'' Money will
not be a factor in his decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, it's fundamentally about if I want to expand on my
career, and where is that, and is that possible,'' Young told USA
Today this week in his most extensive interview in nine months.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most important thing is that you mature, too, and that you
realize the perfect ending might not be storybook,'' he said. ``It
might actually be other than what you expected.''
</P>
<P>
   HAWK TALK: The Seahawks have not set a deadline for releasing
wide receiver Sean Dawkins if he cannot be signed to a new contract
that will reduce his cap number this season. Sources indicated that
Dawkins had until Thursday to agree to a new deal. But Holmgren
said, ``There is not that much of a deadline.''
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter Clare Farnsworth can be reached at 206-448-8016
</P>
<P>
   or clarefarnsworth &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
