<HEADER>
A1533 &Cx1f; tth-z
r s BC-BKN-NBA-WEST-SPI &LR;      06-01 0756
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBA-WEST-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOME-COURT A DISADVANTAGE IN WILD WEST FINALS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RONALD TILLERY  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORTLAND, Ore. _ Normally, it is paramount for the underdog team
to claim a road game in a long playoff series in order to be
successful.
</P>
<P>
   Don't put the Portland Trail Blazers in that category. It is now
imperative they break a curse and win at home.
</P>
<P>
   Go figure.
</P>
<P>
   On the road is where the Blazers have been most productive in
the Western Conference finals. Home is where they have actually
endured headaches, heartaches and half-hearted performances.
</P>
<P>
   So as Game 6 looms Friday night, the Blazers need only to beat
the Los Angeles Lakers here in order to extend this series to an
anything-can-happen Game 7 on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Easier said than done in the Rose Garden, where the Blazers have
lost their past four conference finals games. The most recent two
defeats were in Games 3 and 4 against L.A.
</P>
<P>
   Portland dominated both games early before succumbing in the
third quarter. The Blazers offset the defeats by winning two in a
row in the Lakers' Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of crazy that it's flip-flopped like this,'' Blazers
guard Steve Smith said. ``But we're going home feeling good about
ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Portland is on the brink of elimination, trailing the
series 3-2. Now home court matters, in a matchup where both teams
have worn out their welcome in the others' digs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think home-court advantage is like it used to be,''
Blazers veteran forward Detlef Schrempf said. ``I don't know why,
but it's just not like it used to be 10 years ago. We know we can
win (at Staples) and obviously they know they can win in Portland.
Maybe we're due to win one at home.''
</P>
<P>
   There is no maybe about it.
</P>
<P>
   The Blazers' home drought in the conference finals dates back to
last year. San Antonio swept Portland out of the 1999 playoffs by
winning twice in the Rose Garden.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the Lakers own home-court advantage in this series,
they acknowledged that the Blazers' fan base gives them an edge.
Portland's crowd has done its part, living up to a reputation as
some of the NBA's most frenzied fans.
</P>
<P>
   Lakers coach Phil Jackson made it clear that the Rose Garden is
not one of his favorite places to visit. He said having to return
to Portland for Game 6 was one of the more disappointing aspects of
the Game 5 loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you have to face the abuse we have to face up in Portland,
you would not want to go back up there again,'' Jackson said.
``It's not fun, and it's a daunting crowd that you have to play in
front of.''
</P>
<P>
   The Blazers realize they haven't lived up to their end of the
bargain.
</P>
<P>
   This deep, talented roster has mostly looked average and
short-handed in its own building. In Games 3 and 4, the Blazers
were outshot 50 to 44 percent, allowed more points off turnovers
(44-22), were outrebounded (77-65) and blew double-digit leads.
</P>
<P>
   When they won Games 2 and 5 in Los Angeles, the Blazers outshot
the Lakers 44 to 38 percent. Portland outrebounded L.A., 92-78, and
committed fewer turnovers (21-30).
</P>
<P>
   Portland's biggest lead in a 106-77 Game 2 blowout was 30
points. The Blazers never trailed in the crucial Game 5.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've wiped out the fact that we've lost those two games at
home,'' Portland forward Scottie Pippen said. `` ... We're going to
outplay them every time we go on the court.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers aren't exactly shaking in their sneakers.
</P>
<P>
   Guard Kobe Bryant said he believes the Lakers have yet to play
their best game. Also,the Lakers would have to lose three
consecutive games _ something they haven't done all season _ to be
eliminated.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel comfortable going back to Portland,'' Bryant said.
``We've been going through a lot of adversity since we've got here
_ getting swept out of the playoffs. So this is nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   Blazers coach Mike Dunleavy reminded the media after Game 5 that
he predicted this is how the series would play out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously you guys don't listen to me when I talk,'' Dunleavy
said. ``I told you from the very beginning that I didn't think
there was a home-court advantage in this series. I thought that
either team was capable of winning every game on the other's home
court; that it was going to come down to how you play every night.
That's been the key.''
</P>
<P>
   So much for walking gingerly in a stranger's house.
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter Ronald Tillery at 206-448-8012
</P>
<P>
   or ronaldtillery &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-01-00 0235EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000601.0045 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 02:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1534 &Cx1f; tth-z
r s BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI &LR;      06-01 0944
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLAME GOES ALL AROUND IN MARINERS' LOSS TO WHITE SOX 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN HICKEY  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The Mariners' defense lost a game Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners' offense lost a game Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners' pitching lost a game Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately for Seattle, it was the same game, which means it
only cost the Mariners one game in the standings.
</P>
<P>
   All those losses left a disproportionate number of long faces in
the Mariners' clubhouse after Chicago's 4-3 victory at Safeco
Field, which knocked the Mariners out of first place in the AL
West.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, third baseman John Mabry's ninth-inning error on a
ground ball was the back-breaker, setting up a game-winning bloop
double by Herbert Perry off Kazuhiro Sasaki.
</P>
<P>
   But given what happened over the first eight innings, Perry's
hit and even Mabry's error were overshadowed.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle left 15 runners on base, including going 0-for-5 with
the bases loaded. The generally accepted idea among hitters is that
batting with the bases loaded is the situation in which the hitter
has the greatest advantage, but you wouldn't think so after seeing
Seattle perform.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a lot of good opportunities to score,'' first baseman
John Olerud said. ``(The White Sox) took advantage of our mistakes.
They definitely had better clutch hitting than we did.''
</P>
<P>
   No kidding. The Mariners had enough base runners Wednesday to
answer a casting call for a road show of Les Miserables. But the
way Seattle executed its offense when confronted with all those
opportunities would have led Inspector Javert to dump the Mariners'
bats in the Paris sewers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Plain and simple, we played like dogs,'' shortstop Alex
Rodriguez said of the Mariners, who are now hitting .222 with the
bases loaded this year after batting .271 in the same situation a
year ago. ``Offensively and defensively, we didn't do much as a
team. It was that way the whole series. The way we played, we were
lucky to win one game.''
</P>
<P>
   Mike Cameron drew a two-out, bases-loaded walk in the first
inning, but John Olerud and Raul Ibanez failed to come through with
three men on. Seattle loaded the bases in the third inning, but
Ibanez grounded into a double play. In the sixth, with the bases
again loaded, Edgar Martinez popped out. With the bases loaded in
the seventh, Rickey Henderson flew out.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners left 12 of their 15 stranded baserunners in those
four innings. Mix in one hit anywhere, and Perry's ninth-inning hit
probably wouldn't have beat them.
</P>
<P>
   Starter Aaron Sele pitched, as they say, well enough to win. But
he also pitched poorly enough to lose, particularly in the seventh
inning, when he squandered a 3-1 lead with a couple of bad pitches
and one poor fielding decision.
</P>
<P>
   After Chris Singleton opened with a leadoff single, Carlos Lee
hit a one-hop comebacker that Sele speared. The double play was
ready to be etched into scorebooks around the stadium, but it never
came. Sele's job was to throw the ball to Rodriguez to start the
double play. But first, he needed to make sure Rodriguez was in
position. Sele needed a bit of patience.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Sele threw to second base too soon. Rodriguez was still
two steps away, and the Mariners were lucky that second baseman
Mark McLemore was backing up Rodriguez behind the bag. McLemore
reacted with the cool demeanor of a veteran, whipping the throw to
first base to at least get one out, but Sele had given the White
Sox life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got to take a little time there,'' Sele said. ``But I was
so focused on getting the double play that I just got the ball and
threw it. I was lucky Mac was there.''
</P>
<P>
   Perry was next up, and Sele came back strong with two quick
strikes. Sele then hit Perry with an 0-2 pitch.
</P>
<P>
   ``No problem,'' Sele said. ``I made a mistake, but I was feeling
good, in control. I just figured we'd get a double play and get out
of the inning.''
</P>
<P>
   Not quite. Catcher Tom Lampkin called for a curve and Sele threw
a fastball. Lampkin, completely fooled, saw the ball go to the
backstop for a wild pitch that let both runners advance a base. It
was a pitch for which Sele was kicking himself two hours later.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't give us a chance,'' Sele said. ``I was so locked into
what I was doing that I crossed him up.''
</P>
<P>
   The wild pitch was all manager Lou Piniella needed to see. He
replaced Sele with Arthur Rhodes on a 1-0 count.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way I pitched, I forced Lou to take me out,'' Sele said.
</P>
<P>
   Pinch-hitter Brook Fordyce, with just one hit all year (in 14
at-bats) took a whack at Rhodes' first pitch and slapped a single
into left. Tie game.
</P>
<P>
   In the bottom of the inning, the Mariners loaded the bases for
the fourth time in the game. They got nothing, with Henderson
flying out. After that, there didn't seem to be much zip in the
Mariners' bats.
</P>
<P>
   Or, for that matter, in their gloves. With one out in the ninth
inning and Sasaki attempting to keep the game tied, Lee hit a
relatively routine grounder to third. Mabry, playing third after
having pinch-hit for starter Carlos Guillen, had the ball go under
his glove. Lee alertly raced all the way to second base. Moments
later, Perry's end-of-the-bat fly ball landed a few feet from the
right-field line for a double and the go-ahead run.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you should win and you don't, that's when it's
frustrating,'' Lampkin said. ``You have to learn from it and then
forget about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Seattle can't forget about this one quickly enough.
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter John Hickey can be reached at 206-448-8004
</P>
<P>
   or johnhickey &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
