<SLUG> BC-BKW-STORM-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEASONED MONARCHS RAIN ON STORM'S WNBA DEBUT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MEREDITH BAGLEY  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO, Calif. _ Seattle's WNBA franchise is off to an 0-1
start, but there's reason for hope.
</P>
<P>
   Playing on the road Wednesday night against a team many pick to
win the league title, the expansion Storm showed grit and
determination, and led for most of the first half. Experience
caught up to them, however, as the seasoned Monarchs pulled away
from the upstart Storm for a 76-60 victory in ARCO Arena.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought 16 points is not indicative of how competitive the
game was,'' Seattle head coach Lin Dunn said. ``We're just
inexperienced. I've got two players who have been in the WNBA
before and the rest are vagabond rookies from all over. But I can't
fault their effort.''
</P>
<P>
   Seattle held 1999 league MVP, All-Star and U.S. Olympic team
forward Yolanda Griffith to just four points in the first half, and
led by as many as seven points in the opening half.
</P>
<P>
   Sacramento came to life in the second half, however, behind the
bruising inside play of 5-foot-11, 206-pound Latasha Byears and the
magical passing of point guard Ticha Penicheiro.
</P>
<P>
   Penicheiro, held to zero points and three assists in the first
half, asserted herself in the second half with 8-for-10 free-throw
shooting and seven assists. Byears finished with 17 points off the
bench to lead the Monarchs, while Griffith, Kedra Holland-Corn,
Katy Steding and former Mead High School star Stacey Clinesmith all
scored 10 for Sacramento.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the characteristic of a great team,'' Dunn said. ``We
contained their star, but they have other stars to step up.''
</P>
<P>
   Byears led the Monarch bench, which accounted for 47 points. By
contrast, Seattle got just eight points from its reserves.
</P>
<P>
   ``The key for this team is the bench,'' Dunn said. ``We've got
to get more scoring.''
</P>
<P>
   Seattle was led by guard Edna Campbell, the WNBA's leading
scorer in the preseason, with 22 points. Kamila Vodichkova also
turned in a strong night, scoring 20 points and grabbing nine
rebounds while withstanding the Monarchs' physical inside play.
</P>
<P>
   Vodichkova hobbled off the floor with 14:14 to play in the
second half after colliding with Penicheiro and re-injuring her
right knee. She returned to the action, only to be knocked out for
good with just over three minutes remaining after a Sacramento
triple-team inside left her with a black eye.
</P>
<P>
   Vodichkova said after the game she felt the Monarchs benefited
from home-court advantage with the officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they felt we could win the fouls helped (Sacramento),''
she said. ``But once it was over and they'd won, it was OK to
whistle anything inside.''
</P>
<P>
   Katrina Hibbert got Seattle on the board and put herself into
the history books with the Storm's first basket at 16:04 of the
first half.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't thinking about it,'' the rookie from Australia
insisted, ``but it's exciting.''
</P>
<P>
   Seattle took a 6-4 lead on Campbell's drive at 14:40 of the
half, and held the advantage for over 10 minutes. The Storm's
biggest lead came at 11:19 when another Campbell jumper made it
15-8 Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   Sacramento clawed back, using a 6-0 run midway through the half
to take a 20-19 lead with 5:28 to play.
</P>
<P>
   ``They came our real aggressive and took us out of our
offense,'' Sacramento head coach Sonny Allen said. ``I saw them
beat L.A. last week _ they will win games.''
</P>
<P>
   Trailing 36-29 as the second half opened, the Storm stayed
close. Seattle forged a 46-46 tie with 11:27 left, and Campbell's
basket with 8:58 to play cut Sacramento's lead to 53-50.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was happy with everything except the last (nine) minutes,''
Dunn said.
</P>
<P>
   Then Penicheiro went to work, driving hard on the Monarchs' next
two possessions and drawing fouls. Four free throws later,
Sacramento led by seven and never looked back. Seattle managed only
10 more points in the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We came out well and stayed with them in their house,''
Hibbert said. ``In the second half, the crowd got into it and we
started missing easy shots.''
</P>
<P>
   There's no rest for the weary Storm, as the team caught a 5:30
a.m. flight back to Seattle and will face the three-time world
champion Houston Comets Thursday night at KeyArena at 7 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have the toughest row to hoe of the expansion teams,'' Dunn
said. ``But it's gonna pay off. We will be better next week than we
are now because of this schedule.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the loss, the Storm earned a large dose of respect from
the rabid Monarch fans. Dunn, for one, is not satisfied.
</P>
<P>
   ``Too bad respect doesn't get me wins,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter Meredith Bagley can be reached at 206-448-8211
</P>
<P>
   or meredithbagley &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
