<SLUG> BC-BKW-STORM-NOTEBOOK-PI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STORM DUO HAVE INSIDE INFO ON COMETS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MEREDITH BAGLEY  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO, Calif. _ Two Storm players, Sonja Henning and Andrea
Garner, will see some familiar faces Thursday night when Seattle
hosts Houston in its home opener. Henning was the Comets' starting
point guard last season and guided the defending champions to their
third consecutive title.
</P>
<P>
   Garner, a rookie from Penn State, was Houston's second-round
draft pick this year and landed in Seattle in a last-minute trade.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be good to see them,'' Garner said. ``There's no hard
feelings between us.''
</P>
<P>
   Facing the Comets juggernaut, Seattle could use any inside tips
either player might provide.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know their plays,'' Garner said, ``but they're great
athletes and it just comes down to defense.''
</P>
<P>
   Henning questioned whether advance notice would even help.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're always coming up with new surprises, and even if you
know what's coming you might not be able to stop it.''
</P>
<P>
   FULL HOUSE EXPECTED: Karen Bryant, senior director of basketball
operations for the Storm, expects a full house for the home opener
Thursday in KeyArena. With over 10,000 tickets sold by the week's
start, Bryant hopes to hit the arena capacity of 12,969.
</P>
<P>
   Of that number, over 5,200 fans are season ticket holders.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to seeing the best team in the WNBA's short history,
Storm fans will get their first glimpse at the new Storm logo and
the Storm Troop dance team.
</P>
<P>
   LOCAL CONNECTION: Two players with Washington ties took the
floor Wednesday for the Monarchs, with Husky alum Rhonda (Smith)
Banchero and Stacey Clinesmith suited up for Sacramento.
</P>
<P>
   Clinesmith, a feisty 5-foot-5 guard from Mead High School in
Spokane, is a backup to starting point guard Ticha Penicheiro and
earned her roster spot by proving intensity can overcome lack of
height. Clinesmith was Sacramento's second-round pick in the May
draft.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was hoping it would be Sacramento,'' Clinesmith said. ``I
wanted anything West Coast, to be near my friends and family.''
</P>
<P>
   After starting for UC Santa Barbara, Clinesmith is adjusting to
a reserve role in the WNBA.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's new for me, but I'm learning a lot from Ticha,'' she
said. ``It's a whole new level and I'm still trying to take it all
in.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinesmith has been compared to fellow Spokane native John
Stockton, both in skills and stature, but doesn't know how the
connection started.
</P>
<P>
   ``John's a great player, and we have similar games since we're
smaller,'' Clinesmith said. ``If I'm compared to him, that's
cool.''
</P>
<P>
   Banchero is making her return to American professional
basketball after three years in the ABL. The ex-Reign forward, who
will back up 1999 league MVP Yolanda Griffith at the point, is
happy just to be on the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll go wherever I fit in,'' Banchero said, ``as long as I'm
contributing to the team.''
</P>
<P>
   Banchero left the University of Washington as the Huskies'
all-time leading scorer but was surpassed by Storm guard Jamie Redd
in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``I figured it would be Jamie,'' Banchero said with a smile.
``When she gets hot, she's good for 40 points.''
</P>
<P>
   The two are good friends who have kept in touch even when
Banchero was playing in Israel this winter.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's not like my little sister anymore,'' Banchero said.
``She's a good friend and she'll do well in this league when she
finds her niche.''
</P>
<P>
   The Monarchs visit Seattle on June 15.
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter Meredith Bagley can be reached at 206-448-8211
</P>
<P>
   or meredithbagley &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
