<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-METS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ELSTER SAVES DAY FOR INJURY-PRONE DODGERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Injuries weren't much a part of the Dodgers'
debacle last season, though everything else was there.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the clubhouse is quiet and united, the well-being of the
team is the primary focus. And an injury is lurking around every
pitch. This time right-hander Kevin Brown was the victim, taking a
line drive off his right leg that eventually chased him from the
game.
</P>
<P>
   So with a rash of injuries and controversy swirling around the
clubhouse the past two weeks, it was ultra-important the Dodgers
beat the New York Mets 4-3 on Kevin Elster's one-out solo homer in
the bottom of the ninth Wednesday at Dodger Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   It was Elster's eighth homer of the season. It came on the first
pitch, an expected slider, he saw from Mets reliever Turk Wendell.
``That's why we play, feelings like that,'' Elster said. ``I was
fortunate because I was looking for the one pitch he threw me. I
went up there thinking about hitting one. He likes to throw that
first-pitch slider. He starts it in and get it over the middle of
the plate.''
</P>
<P>
   With the win in hand and the Dodgers salvaging a 4-5 mark on the
homestand by winning two of three from the Mets, the lingering
issue is whether Brown will make his next start.
</P>
<P>
   He limped through the clubhouse, but he said he plans on making
his next start, which will come against one of his former teams,
the Texas Rangers. However, Brown will be re-evaluated today.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's a matter of anything to check out,'' said
Brown, who allowed one run in six innings. ``It's a matter of
getting rid of the swelling. I think it just missed the bone. Thank
heaven for small favors. I don't have a lot of meat on my legs, but
it got some of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Even on the play in which he was injured, Brown made a
spectacular recovery. Edgardo Alfonzo, who homered in the first
inning, lined a one-out pitch back at Brown. It ricocheted off his
lower leg and toward the first-base line.
</P>
<P>
   Brown raced over, picked it up and threw out Alfonzo, tumbling
and falling again after making the throw. Brown stayed in the game
and retired Mike Piazza on a grounder, but his leg swelled so much
he couldn't continue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Guys were saying they never saw anything swell up so quick,''
Dodgers manager Davey Johnson said. ``I hope it's just a contusion.
... The adversity goes on.''
</P>
<P>
   Any hint that Brown could be injured is reason for the Dodgers
to shriek. He already missed 16 days this season with a broken
right pinkie, and with regulars Adrian Beltre, Todd Hundley and
Devon White already on the disabled list, losing Brown would be
crushing.
</P>
<P>
   But he wasn't the only marquee player to leave with an injury.
Piazza, who still stirs emotions from his days at Chavez Ravine,
left with his forehead covered with blood after getting hit by Gary
Sheffield's bat on a follow-through of a swing in the sixth inning.
</P>
<P>
   Piazza was diagnosed with a slight concussion and one stitch was
needed to close a cut on his forehead. He's expected to play Friday
against Tampa Bay.
</P>
<P>
   Brown left with a two-run lead, but the erratic Dodgers bullpen,
in one of its down cycles, coughed up another late lead as Alan
Mills allowed a pair of eighth-inning runs.
</P>
<P>
   Shortstop Kurt Abbott, who had not driven in a run in 63 at-bats
this season, hit a 3-2 pitch deep over the fence in center field to
pull the Mets within 3-2, and Alfonzo doubled off Matt Herges to
right to tie it 3-3.
</P>
<P>
   In the top of the ninth, Dodgers right-hander Mike Fetters got a
pair of fielder's-choice groundouts with two runners on to end the
inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a ground-ball pitcher, and in that situation I'm trying to
get any ground ball I can get,'' said Fetters, who improved to 2-0.
``I think it's a real big win. We didn't have a great homestand,
but with us playing the Mets and taking two of three, and Elster
hitting the walk-off home run, it's a big win.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
