rooms.''
</P>
<P>
   Often, we are told, these problems can be cured with a few
clicks of a mouse, thereby restoring a hard drive to the marriage.
</P>
<P>
   As its authority, Redbook cites Michele Weiner-Davis, a marriage
and family therapist in Woodstock, Ill., and the author of
``Divorce Busting.'' Her insight: ``With the accessibility of
e-mail, we can take the time to do things we wouldn't ordinarily
do, like sending love letters.''
</P>
<P>
   Love letters survive from 150 years ago when Pony Express
mail-order brides were in vogue. During the Gold Rush years, proper
young ladies sailed in packet boats around the tip of South America
to meet their corresponding wealthy suitors in California.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly a century later, with millions of Americans under arms,
pen-pal exchanges flourished. Without computer assistance, some of
those letter writers from the 1940s became war brides.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to matters of the heart, however, history remains
an imperfect guide. It's not surprising that a good deal of the
advice on how to fall in love on the Internet is to be found ... on
the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   As gleaned from cyberspace, here are four key rules:
</P>
<P>
   _ It's all right to fool around in the forums, but when it comes
to letting someone become really close to you, ask lots of
questions first.
</P>
<P>
   _ Trade photos before you meet. That way you'll know whether
there's some physical attraction to go along with the virtual
stuff.
</P>
<P>
   _ Take it slow and easy. Time will tell if it is to be or not.
</P>
<P>
   _ Don't get romantically involved with a married person, even if
he or she tells you it's over.
</P>
<P>
   Our own Internet bride-to-be, a close friend for 25 years, broke
the last rule. The prospective groom is a divorced father who
uncoupled when she finally said ``yes,'' offline, to becoming his
wife No. 2.
</P>
<P>
   At 50, she's never been married before. But you don't need to go
by the presidential commission that hangs in her stately government
office to know that she's a responsible person.
</P>
<P>
   We've yet to ask her whether Bill Clinton will attend. On the
other hand, we don't need Kenneth Starr to remind us that the
president isn't into e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew J. Glass is a Washington-based columnist for Cox
Newspapers. His
</P>
<P>
   e-mail address is aglass(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
