u v BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN04-COX     06-01 0551
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Household guns won't stave off tyranny
 &HT;    By Tom Teepen
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Just in time for Fathers' Day, the gun crowd is shanghaiing no
less than the Founding Fathers themselves into its service,
bandying about quotes from Jefferson, Franklin and others to the
effect that an armed citizenry is the surest, and an essential,
hedge against tyrannical government.
</P>
<P>
   The quotes are cited in support of an interpretation of the
Second Amendment holding that just about everybody has a
constitutional right to buy any gun they want whenever and wherever
they want and as many at a time as they can afford.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind, apparently, that even conservative jurists, such as
the late Supreme Court Chief Justice Warren Burger, have all but
universally found that the amendment is not absolute and is no bar
to public-interest gun controls.
</P>
<P>
   Too, many of the quotes are little more than revolutionary
boilerplate, uttered to whoop up the cause, and were never a part
of the more sober political debate and congressional deliberations
that were summarized in an amendment pegging the right to bear arms
to the maintenance of a well-regulated militia.
</P>
<P>
   That said, there is no reason to suppose the super dads didn't
mean what they said when they said it, even if the sentiments
weren't pointing directly to the eventual constitutional amendment.
</P>
<P>
   The founders and their compatriots were reacting against an
arbitrary and insensitive British monarchy and compliant Parliament
-- and against a general European history of autocrats, dictators,
kings and aristocrats. For centuries they had treated their
subjects as nothing better than cannon fodder, tax victims and
pressed labor in whatever enterprise the empowered came to fancy.
</P>
<P>
   A yeoman with a gun could claim something approaching parity
with an armed cavalier; an armed citizenry, parity with an army.
</P>
<P>
   But our founders could not have imagined a firearms industry and
traffic of the sort that bedevil us now. Contrary to nurtured
myths, most colonial and revolutionary households were not armed.
Firearms were hand crafted and expensive, beyond the means -- and
in the cities, of no purpose anyway -- to most early Americans.
</P>
<P>
   It seems fair to assume that even the most militant of the
founders would be appalled at a commerce in street-level firepower
that produces, for instance, handguns so cheap (and incidentally of
such dubious quality) that the real but unacknowledged market for
them is in resale to neighborhood thugs, ex-cons and middle-school
impulse buyers.
</P>
<P>
   For the romantic notion of an armed population as a standing
picket against a suddenly tyrannical government to have any hope
today, the Second Amendment would have to countenance private
fighter planes and bombers, automatic weapons, at least tactical
missiles and neighbor tank corps. (SUVs fall just short.)
</P>
<P>
   The surest preservation of our democracy is not in an assault
rifle in the closet or a .38 in the glove compartment. It is in a
politically alert, caring and engaged citizenry.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Teepen is a columnist for Cox Newspapers. He writes from
Atlanta. E-mail: teepencolumn(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
