<DOCNO> NYT20000601.0053 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 10:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1630 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN04-CO     06-01 0723
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Funeral for a mistress; black tie optional
 &HT;    For release Sunday, June 4
 &HT;    By HOWARD KLEINBERG
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON -- The lady wrote in earnest. She had been to the funeral
of her husband's longtime _ and ``very public'' -- mistress after
debating (a) whether or not to go and (b) what to wear. In
retrospect now, she wondered in writing not about her presence at
the funeral but of her attire.
</P>
<P>
   In her query to the Miss Manners-type columnist for The Weekend
Times of London, Mrs. Name and Address Withheld asked if her choice
of navy blue was appropriate inasmuch as it wasn't mourning black
or celebratory white.
</P>
<P>
   The response was more astonishing than the request; it, too, was
sincere: a delicate gray would have been the ideal shade, wrote the
man from the Weekend Times. There also was the mild, almost
obligatory, admonishment: ``How brave, if inappropriate, of you:
good manners quite excuse a wife's attendance at such events.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Name and Address Withheld, of course, was breaking no new
ground in attending the a tryst-tainted farewell. Did not the widow
of French president Francois Mitterand acquiesce to a graveside
appearance by her late husband's mistress as well?
</P>
<P>
   The table had been set for such attendances, what we were
dealing with in this most recent event was attire. Despite her
choice of navy blue, the letter writer complained, ``all eyes
present still switched from the deceased to me,'' thus prompting
her letter to the newspaper as to whether she had the appropriate
wardrobe.
</P>
<P>
   I would have considered that a triumph, not an embarrassment. To
have the old mistress not be the center of the show at her own
funeral should have been celebrated as retribution. I'd have worn a
Hawaiian shirt and white shorts!
</P>
<P>
   Oh, how the world is turning. It is almost acceptable on the
European side of the Atlantic that mistresses are a tolerable part
of daily life. Yes, there is some grouching but reality is reality
to Europeans.
</P>
<P>
   Now, on the U.S. side, mistresses and other things naughty,
while still raising some apoplectic reaction, are becoming more
common. (We give Europe Starbucks Coffee and McDonald's and they
give us mistress tolerance.)
</P>
<P>
   Rudy Guliani withdrawal from the U.S. Senate race in New York
was accepted more to be based on his prostate cancer rather than
his fooling around. The tearful discourse by wounded wife Donna
Hamilton played a secondary role -- and allowed Rudy to retreat
almst protectively into the empathetic arms of his mistress.
(Mistress number 2, that is.)
</P>
<P>
   Also note how quietly Newt Gingrich recently married the woman
with whom he had an affair to break up his second marriage. We're
sort of getting attuned to these things; certainly not at the
Southern Baptist Conventions, but elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Just look at what has filled out plates in recent years: The
chronic Bill Clinton and retrospective revelations about FDR, LBJ
and Ike as well as the fully named Henry Hyde, Dan Burton and Helen
Chenoweth. Throw in a man general hitting on a lady general, a
school teacher having her student's babies, and a female Air Force
pilot having a verbotten penchant for enlisted men, and we're a
nation in transition.
</P>
<P>
   Is there nothing in our lives that does not have a sexual tone
to it? Do we titter or grumble when we read that liver-lipped movie
actress Angelina Jolie calls out for more sex: ``Before I die, I
wanna taste everyone in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   I wonder what those dozens of betrayed wives will wear when
Angelina is ready to be buried?
</P>
<P>
   Sex sells. It sells in stores, at movie theaters, in books, in
newspapers, on TV, just about anywhere. Some think Americans are
too puritanical. We're not. We just haven't been as public about
it, for fear of what our neighbor will think.
</P>
<P>
   Led by European example, some of those barriers are beginning to
crumble _ not so much by choice but by the simple fact that
everyone now knows everyone else's private business.
</P>
<P>
   And that which we don't know, we always can ask by writing to a
Miss Manners.
</P>
<P>
   (Howard Kleinberg, a former editor of the Miami News, is a
columnist for Cox Newspapers. His e-mail address is
hkmiami(at)aol.com.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
