<HEADER>
A1645 &Cx1f; tab-z
u l BC-DISCOVER-BAT-$ADV30-A     06-01 0817
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DISCOVER-BAT-$ADV30-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOUR INNER BAT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use Tue., May 30, 2000, or anytime thereafter.) 
 &HT;    
 ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by DISCOVER NEWS SERVICE clients.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, see end of text. 
 &HT;    
 (Color art is included.) 
 By ERIC HASELTINE 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
 &HT;    Vision so dominates our perception that we give precedence to
what our eyes tell us _ even when that information contradicts more
accurate data coming from other senses.
 &HT;    When you watch television, for example, dialogue seems to emerge
from the actors' mouths, not the set's speakers.
 &HT;    And although many mammals overindulge their eyes as we do, a
few, such as bats and dolphins, navigate by sonar, emitting clicks,
chirps and grunts and using the echoes to determine the location of
things around them.
 &HT;    Sonar may seem a bizarre method of finding one's way, but humans
can be surprisingly good at it. Blind people, for instance,
navigate pretty well by listening to echoes from the tapping of
their canes. We can locate where sounds originate because we have
two ears and a brain that automatically analyzes differences in the
timing and intensity of sounds.
 &HT;    When a noise is closer to one ear than the other, its acoustic
energy will reach that ear faster and louder than the other ear.
Try these experiments to see how well your brain extracts location
from time and intensity cues.
 &HT;    
 EXPERIMENT 1  
 &HT;    With a friend, 10 feet of string, a nine-inch square of
cardboard, a straight pin, a soda straw and some tape, make a
``sound locator'' as shown in the accompanying photo. Make sure the
string rests on top of the cardboard and that the straw and the
string don't touch.
 &HT;    Sit in a large, quiet room with your eyes shut and your head
facing forward, holding the locator in front of you. Your friend
grasps the loose end of the string and stands 10 feet away at seven
different points: directly in front of you at 12 (as on the face of
a clock) and near but not exactly at 9, 10, 11, 1, 2 and 3 _ but in
random sequence.
 &HT;    At each new position, your friend sings a single note _ bong _
for two seconds in the lowest pitch he or she can muster. Be
careful that your friend doesn't tug the string too hard _ it will
give her location away.
 &HT;    Point the short end of the straw in the direction you think the
bong came from. Then open your eyes and note if the straw and the
string agree. The difference between the two marks represents the
degree of accuracy with which you locate each sound.
 &HT;    Now repeat the experiment at each of the seven positions _ only
this time have your partner emit a loud click with his or her
tongue and palate. Switch places with your accomplice and compare
performances.
 &HT;    If you're like most people, your errors were small but probably
increased as the bongs and clicks moved farther away from 12. You
should have done better with the clicks, which carry a wider range
of tones for acoustic neurons to work with.
 &HT;    
 EXPERIMENT 2  
 &HT;    While voicing bongs in experiment 1, you might have noticed that
the person holding the locator tilted his head. Some blind people _
or those who are deaf in one ear _ do this because the head
rotation provides the brain with information about the intensity of
sounds and their arrival times from different positions, making
noise localization more accurate.
 &HT;    Now, have your friend repeat the bong and click experiment while
you hold the locator. Move your head quickly from side to side to
see if this reduces localization errors. Switch positions and
repeat.
 &HT;    Paying close attention to the acoustic world can help you get
around better in the dark and keep your brain healthy by vigorously
exercising seldom-used auditory pathways.
 &HT;    Visit www.discover.com/brainworks for more sound effects that
exploit time/intensity differences _ but with a riveting third
dimension guaranteed to astonish you.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (Eric Haseltine is a contributing editor to Discover magazine.)
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ----
 c.2000 Discover magazine 
