<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CONSTANTINE-ULSTER (Albany, N.Y.) _ Thomas Constantine, a former
DEA head and New York State Police superintendent, says the key to
peace in Northern Ireland will be the development of a police
service ``everyone is comfortable with.'' The Schenectady, N.Y.,
resident is in that war-torn country to oversee implementation of
peace reforms. Constantine will be supervising the transition of
the Royal Ulster Constabulary to the new police service of Northern
Ireland. By MARV CERMAK.
</P>
<P>
   SHRIMP-SHORTAGE (Austin, Texas) _ Wary of a declining shrimp
population, Texas Parks and Wildlife officials have released a
revised set of proposed rules to scale back shrimping operations in
the state's bays and offshore waters. By RUSSELL GOLD.
</P>
<P>
   MOTHER-JAIL (San Francisco) _ A 10-year-old San Mateo County boy
has been reunited with his father after an eight-year ordeal that
began when the man's wife allegedly poisoned him with an
insecticide-laced milkshake and fled to Mexico with their son. The
biggest break in the bizarre case _ which has been featured more
than 20 times on TV's ``Unsolved Mysteries'' _ didn't arrive until
March 15 when the wife, San Francisco native Elizabeth
Fuentes-Ortiz, was arrested near Guadalajara. She was brought back
to the United States to face charges. By DEMIAN BULWA.
</P>
<P>
   O'DONOHUE-OBIT (San Francisco) _ Joseph J. O'Donohue IV, a
former New York socialite who moved to San Francisco after
squandering his fortune, died Wednesday after a heart attack. He
was 88. By RAY DELGADO.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION-SCHOOLS (San Antonio) _ ``Gracious heavenly Father''
and ``amen,'' expressions taken for granted among Christians at
prayer, sometimes seem grating to non-Christians when uttered at
public events. Those words angered a group of Hindu families
attending a graduation ceremony at a San Antonio high school last
weekend, but the school principal is satisfied the prayers fit
current legal guidelines. By J. MICHAEL PARKER.
</P>
<P>
   STROKE-TRANSPLANT (Albany, N.Y.) _ Stroke patient Maribeth Cook
seemed to pass with flying colors an experimental fetal pig brain
cell transplant last September, but she grew worried after
receiving word recently that two other stroke patients in the
clinical trial suffered complications. That created anxious moments
for Cook, 39, of Saratoga Springs, N.Y., who was patient No. 1. By
PAUL GRONDAHL.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   EXAMINER-SALE (San Francisco) _ U.S. District Judge Vaughn R.
Walker, hearing final arguments in Clint Reilly's antitrust suit to
block the Hearst Corp. from buying the San Francisco Chronicle,
pointedly questioned lawyers about Hearst's plan to give the Fang
family a $66 million subsidy to buy its Examiner. By SETH
ROSENFELD.
</P>
<P>
   CAREERS-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ A recent nationwide survey of
1,004 employees by Vault.com, an Internet career site showed that
although 70 percent of employees believe that e-mail improves
communication with their bosses, 51 percent say their tone is
sometimes misinterpreted as angry, abrupt or overly casual. About
five out of six respondents regularly delete their e-mails, and
only one out of seven admit to forwarding sexually explicit or
otherwise improper e-mails to friends and co-workers. By DAVE
MURPHY.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TV-SURVIVOR (Undated) And then there were 15. With one episode
of the massively hyped summer series ``Survivor'' in the can, we
can safely assume that those who watched this reality-voyeur series
about 16 castaways on an island off Borneo will be back again _ and
again. If CBS got any kind of ratings at all Wednesday night for
its ``Lord of the Flies'' meets ``The Real World'' epic, then
expect a kind of mini-``Who Wants To Be A Millionaire'' to sweep
away the summer programming doldrums. By TIM GOODMAN.
</P>
<P>
   FOOD (``d'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BOURBON-RULES (Austin, Texas) _ Rules are everywhere, even in
the distillery. It may come as a surprise just how strict the rules
governing bourbon are. They date to the 19th century and are fairly
inflexible. By JOHN GRIFFIN.
</P>
<P>
   MEAT-GRINDER (San Antonio) _ Having access to an electric meat
grinder has really been a big help in allowing me to try different
game recipes that feature ground meat, stew meat and other
creations. While the hand-cranked grinders like the one passed down
by my wife's grandmother can be used, a three-quarter horse power
motor working for you is a real time saver. By RALPH WININGHAM.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FBN-STEVE-YOUNG (Santa Clara, Calif.) _ The seemingly endless
Steve Young saga will end, seemingly, on or before June 10. San
Francisco 49ers Coach Steve Mariucci said he expects Young _ the
49ers star quarterback _ to make a decision on his playing future
by a week from Saturday, if not before. By JOHN CRUMPACKER.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SALTER-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ Because he was 89 years old and
had not lived in the Bay Area for at least a couple of generations,
Dong Kingman passed from this world last month with minimal notice
in San Francisco. As befits an artist, however, his work _
spirited, evocative, happy watercolors _ ensures that the essence
of the man will command attention for centuries. By STEPHANIE
SALTER.
</P>
