<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 11:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1656 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l BC-FAIRCHILD-COSTUMER-MI     06-01 0975
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAIRCHILD-COSTUMER-MISSION-IMPOSSIBLE-2-HOLLYWOOD-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOMAN WITH A MISSION  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   (To purchase this special ``one-shot'' feature from W magazine,
contact New York Times Syndicate sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT
at (732) 390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697.)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ---------------------FREE ART!----------------------
 &HT;    ONE COLOR SLIDE is available FREE OF CHARGE to purchasers of
this article. The art can be sent ELECTRONICALLY by e-mail. Please
specify that you want the art when you order the article.
 &HT;    ----------------------------------------------------
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``e'' entertainment news and ``l'' lifestyle news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By ROMY DE COURTAY  
 c.2000 Fairchild Publications   
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ There's a lot of fun to be had in ``Mission:
Impossible 2,'' the action-packed John Woo movie.
</P>
<P>
   First, there's the plot, which, unlike that of its predecessor,
actually holds up to scrutiny without the help of a Ph.D.
</P>
<P>
   Second, there are the spectacular special effects and sometimes
breathtaking cinematography.
</P>
<P>
   Third, there's the trio of stars _ Tom Cruise, Dougray Scott and
Thandie Newton _ who cavort, canoodle, conquer and even collapse
while exuding at all times a staggering beauty and confidence.
</P>
<P>
   What a difference four years make. In the 1996 film adaptation
of the famous television series, Cruise's Ethan Hunt was a
clean-cut, close-cropped dandy who dashed about his business of
international espionage in sharp gray suits, french blue shirts and
matching ties without incurring so much as a wrinkle, a rip or a
loose button.
</P>
<P>
   In the 2000 version, Hunt has grown into a man _ a real man,
with a permanent three-day beard.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a different film,'' said ``M:I-2'' costume designer Lizzy
Gardiner. ``It's much rougher, hipper, warmer and more romantic.
It's not about coldness and perfection.''
</P>
<P>
   Australian-born Gardiner, who won an Academy Award for her work
on the 1994 film ``Priscilla, Queen of the Desert'' (and gained
even more notoriety thanks to the American Express-card dress she
wore to the ceremony), spent seven months outfitting the cast of 15
main characters and 15,000 extras.
</P>
<P>
   ```The Getaway,' with Ali McGraw and Steve McQueen, was my
biggest influence,'' she said. ``I wanted it to look like there was
no costume designer. Today, things are rougher, readier and a
little more relaxed in the movies and in costume design.''
</P>
<P>
   For the character of Ethan Hunt, the farmers' son-turned-spy,
``What Tom and I discussed was a shared belief that this was a man
too busy saving the world and the girl to be vain,'' she said. ``We
never wavered from our view of the character, the heterosexual man
saving the world. That will be one of the aspects of the film that
will make it work.''
</P>
<P>
   Hence, Gardiner dressed the star in unkempt, never-ironed
clothes a la Steve McQueen. ``It's difficult for a designer to step
back and let things go,'' she said. ``The film is more about the
character than about fabulous fashion, but at the same time, he had
to look fantastic.''
</P>
<P>
   Gardiner designed and made many of Cruise's outfits, as well as
relying heavily on Prada.
</P>
<P>
   ``Normally I'm very reticent to get involved with fashion
designers, because fashion is dated by the time the film is out,''
she said. ``But Prada gave me complete access to its collection one
year before it was available to the general public.''
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, adds Gardiner, Ethan Hunt ``is a guy who wouldn't
know who Prada was.''
</P>
<P>
   In the adrenaline-charged action scenes, Cruise wears brushed
cottons, washed moleskins and suede in muddy green, taupe and
black. His T-shirts, jackets, cargo pants and jeans are soiled and
frayed as if they had taken a beating from more than the weather.
</P>
<P>
   Dougray Scott's character, Sean Ambrose _ Hunt's strikingly
handsome former fellow agent-turned-adversary in love and war _ is
rather vain, unlike his nemesis.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's more conscious of his image, the way men are in L.A.,''
Gardiner said.
</P>
<P>
   The results prove him right: In gray-and-black cropped jackets,
slim-cut pants, shirts and ties by Gardiner, Prada and Clements
Ribeiro, the 6-foot-tall, black-haired, blue-eyed villain makes
evil look very tempting, indeed _ so tempting, in fact, that one
wonders why the heroine's choice between Hunt and Ambrose (both of
whom she has, to put it delicately, dated) was not more of a
tossup.
</P>
<P>
   In the final scene, which takes up approximately one-third of
the movie, Scott packs a mean punch _ literally and figuratively _
in a highly unusual denim ensemble of Gardiner's design comprised
of a suit, shirt and diagonally striped tie.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was tough coming up with something that would protect
Dougray from the stunts, that was not flammable and that looked
fabulous for such a large amount of time,'' said Gardiner, who made
17 renditions of that particular suit. ``To be able to supply that
number of outfits for the stunts in order to protect active bodies,
you have to make the clothes yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   Scott also wore a padded suit under his clothes to further
insulate him from bumps, bruises and burns.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was trying to stay away from the uptight, polished, preppie
American male,'' said Gardiner of the other male leads _ the
``rough boys'' _ whom she dressed in a mix of her designs, Prada,
Dolce &AMP; Gabbana, Diesel, and Australian labels Mambo and Marcs.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Australia, we call them `rough trade' _ they're dirty,
handsome and gorgeous,'' she said. ``I tried to bring my admiration
and respect for Australian men into the film.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Romy de Courtay is a reporter for Fairchild Publications.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-01-00 1108EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
