<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 11:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1667 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-BOOKS-DOOLITTLE0602-C     06-01 0651
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-DOOLITTLE0602-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Author/illustrator Bev Doolittle shares love of the wilderness
 &HT;    By Meredith Moss
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ She labels the most dramatic change in her life
as ``the whole wilderness thing.''
</P>
<P>
   It happened in 1973 when she and her husband, both landscape
painters, left advertising jobs and spent a year traveling and
living out of a 1957 Chevy pickup they converted into a camper.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was magical for me,'' says Bev Doolittle, who became
fascinated by the animals and American Indians who inhabited the
places they visited _ Yosemite, Sequoia National Park, the Grand
Canyon, Banff and the Canadian Rockies _ while hiking, sketching,
photographing and painting.
</P>
<P>
   She has been exploring the wilderness and sharing it with others
ever since and today is one of the United States' most popular
limited-edition print artists.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Earth Is My Mother'' (Greenwich Workshop Press, $17.95),
the family novel, written by Elise Maclay, is the story of
11-year-old Sarah Stewart, who sets out to save a beloved canyon _
rich with an American Indian legacy and memories of her mother _
from developers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The goal is to acquaint people with the wilderness and how
special it is,'' explains Doolittle. ``It's about the courage one
person can have to make a change by following your own passions.
The bottom line is that everybody should have the opportunity to
follow their passion and enjoy life.''
</P>
<P>
   Doolittle spent a year creating the 16 watercolors and 55
black-and-white drawings that illustrate the book. ``It's all of
the paintings I've done in the past 20 years rolled into one,'' she
says.
</P>
<P>
   And her work is used in an innovative way. When Sarah, the lead
character, sets out on a journey into the canyon with her camera,
the photos she takes are actually Bev Doolittle's paintings. Later,
the smaller ``photos'' combine into a large picture that
communicates the novel's message. That image is bound into the book
as a removable poster as well.
</P>
<P>
   Doolittle is best known for her camouflage paintings. Look
carefully among the wildflowers on the cover of her new book, for
example, and you'll spot eyes, nose, a mouth, a face.
</P>
<P>
   ``Camouflage is something that happens everywhere in nature, you
just have to keep your antennae out,'' Doolittle says. ``It's a
means to an end. It helps me tell the story, it slows down the
process and helps to guide your eye . . . or confuse. I think of it
as a tool, a way to discover what Mother Nature does.''
</P>
<P>
   Doolittle has collaborated with Elise Maclay on five books _
including a children's book, ``The Forest Has Eyes.'' She hopes
readers of all ages will feel connected to nature after reading
these books and will want to ``go out into nature and perhaps
become a little more respectful of it . . . and feel the same
things we feel when we're out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Doolittle grew up in California and always dreamed of being an
artist. A Campfire Girl and Bluebird, she has fond memories of
camping out with her large family. Now she lives in the California
high desert near Palm Springs and paints every day on a porch
that's been converted into her studio.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to get away once or twice a year for the solitude, to
gather my wits and reconnect,'' she notes.
</P>
<P>
   The story of Sarah in her new book originated with her husband,
Jay, who came up with the plot while hiking in the Palm Springs
canyons. ``I fell in love with it because it's about all the things
we care about,'' Doolittle says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sarah learns that each species _ whether it swims or flies or
travels on four feet _ fills a needed space in the whole of the
natural world.''
</P>
<P>
   Doolittle and her publisher have contributed more than $1
million to wildlife organizations and to the Juvenile Diabetes
Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
