<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 11:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1668 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-BORDERS-COLUMN0602-CO     06-01 0733
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BORDERS-COLUMN0602-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDS: Embargoed for Sunday.
 &HT;    Words of advice for a recent college graduate
 &HT;    By Gary Borders
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NACOGDOCHES, Texas _
</P>
<P>
   Dear Kasey:
</P>
<P>
   I can't believe it's already been four years since your high
school graduation. At this rate, I'll be dead in no time. Now
you're a college graduate with highest honors from the University
of Texas at Austin, the second generation of our family to be an
official Texas-Ex. The first generation, namely me, didn't get any
type of ``honor'' appellation next to the diploma. I was just proud
to eke out a master's degree in seven years.
</P>
<P>
   I'm so proud of you. You flew through undergraduate school in
four years, made just two ``B's'' in that time, and now you're off
to face the real world. I became a bit teary-eyed at the ceremony
as I realized:
</P>
<P>
   You are officially grown up now, ready to make your mark in the
world.
</P>
<P>
   Kicking you off my payroll means I will receive a hefty pay
raise.
</P>
<P>
   As to which brought the tears to my eyes, I can't say for sure.
</P>
<P>
   Being your dad, I am full of free advice now that you have a
college degree, though if everything goes according to plan you
will escape into the safe cocoon of graduate school in a year. On
your nickel, of course. I have made that clear, haven't I?
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, here goes:
</P>
<P>
   Don't be surprised if you end up doing something for a living
that has nothing to do with your degree _ and you discover that you
enjoy it. Your plan is to be a speech therapist, like your mom.
That's an admirable profession. But life is full of surprises, so
don't feel guilty or somehow shortchanged if you end up working in
another field. What's important is that you enjoy what you do and
that you believe you're making a contribution. Money is nice, but a
high-paying job that you hate will put you in the grave quicker
than something that doesn't pay as well but provides a great deal
of satisfaction.
</P>
<P>
   Read everything you can get your hands upon. Fiction,
non-fiction, magazines and, of course, newspapers. A fellow
newspaper publisher has threatened for years to rent a billboard
that says: ``Don't be ignorant all your life. Read the newspaper.''
That might be a bit harsh, but just because you're out of college
doesn't mean it's time to stop learning. The world you're entering
changes at a dizzying rate, and it's all middle-aged fogies like me
can do to pretend to keep up. It's going to be even harder for you,
because the changes are going to come more quickly and be even more
complex.
</P>
<P>
   Do some good in the world. Both you and your sister have always
been involved in volunteer activities to help other people. Keep
doing that. You've been blessed in life, and giving something back
is a way to say thanks. Plus, it's fun.
</P>
<P>
   On a related note, get involved in your community, whether it's
through civic groups, neighborhood associations, politics or
however. Big city or small, there are people involved all over in
trying to make where they live a better place. Don't just rely on
them to do the heavy lifting. Do some lifting yourself.
</P>
<P>
   Take care of your little sister. She managed to survive her
first year at UT, and I know you helped her adjust to the big city.
I still cringe every time I think of her driving in Austin, so I
try not to think about it. Keep an eye on Goose. That's what big
sisters do.
</P>
<P>
   Don't jump off, get married and start having babies right away
now that you're out of college. I'm way too young to be a
grandfather.
</P>
<P>
   Find a hobby. Going out on Friday night does not constitute a
hobby, not that it's all bad. Take up golf, tennis, hiking, pottery
_ anything that provides a diversion from work and that you enjoy
doing. As you get older and life gets more stressful, you'll find
that having a hobby will help keep you on an even keel.
</P>
<P>
   There will be disappointments and setbacks. Not getting into
graduate school on the first try was certainly a setback. But
that's life. Few things come easy, and plans don't always work out.
Just keep plugging away. Remember I'm just a phone call away if you
need some moral support or advice.
</P>
<P>
   Just don't ask for money.
</P>
<P>
   Love,
</P>
<P>
   Dad.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Borders is editor and publisher of The Nacogdoches Daily
Sentinel. E-mai: gborders(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
