<HEADER>
A1669 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-MCNEELY-COLUMN0602-CO     06-01 0750
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCNEELY-COLUMN0602-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    DNA question puts Bush's claim on trial
 &HT;    By Dave McNeely
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Ricky McGinn was scheduled to die Thursday. In
1995, McGinn, who had a record of sexual assault, was convicted of
murdering and raping his 12-year-old stepdaughter in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   The evidence against McGinn was strong: blood on his car that
could have come from less than 1 percent of people other than the
victim, and hair that matched the victim's on an ax identified as
the murder weapon.
</P>
<P>
   McGinn's attorneys and death-penalty opponents were pressing
last-minute appeals to try to save him, including pleas for new DNA
tests they say could free him.
</P>
<P>
   But on trial as well is death-penalty advocate and Texas Gov.
George W. Bush, the presumptive Republican nominee for president.
Bush, who has had more prisoners executed during his tenure than
all previous Texas governors combined, just last Friday endorsed
DNA testing if it can help clear up a case one way or the other.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't believe we've executed a single innocent person,''
Bush said from Austin in a teleconference with a Roman Catholic
journalists' organization meeting in Baltimore. ``If the DNA
testing helps to settle a case or erase any doubts or concerns, we
would support that.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush, in another case, made good on that pledge Wednesday. He
pardoned A.B. Butler of Tyler, who spent 16 years in prison
wrongfully accused of the abduction and rape of a Tyler woman,
after new DNA tests caused law enforcement officials and then the
Texas Department of Pardons and Paroles to recommend a pardon.
</P>
<P>
   McGinn's attorneys similarly say DNA testing not available when
he was tried could now clear him. His appellate attorney, Richard
Alley of Fort Worth, said earlier DNA tests were inconclusive.
</P>
<P>
   State District Judge Stephen Ellis, who had presided over
McGinn's final death sentence this year after his appeals were
exhausted, though not McGinn's 1995 trial, on May 25 asked the
Texas Court of Criminal Appeals to allow additional DNA testing.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is evidence before the court for the first time that if
they were retested using modern technology the results might
exonerate the defendant,'' Judge Ellis wrote.
</P>
<P>
   While cautioning that the preponderance of trial evidence still
would seem to show McGinn guilty rather than innocent, Ellis noted
that Texas ``has acknowledged that DNA testing has advanced
significantly since the time of the trial in this case. . . .
</P>
<P>
   ``It appears to this court that the need for finality in this
case although very important is not as important as the need to
ensure that justice is done,'' the judge wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the Texas Court of Criminal Appeals, all
Republicans, on Tuesday denied the request. Three judges _ Steve
Mansfield, Tom Price and Sue Holland _ thought it should be
granted.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just astonishing,'' said Barry Scheck of the Innocence
Project in New York, which has offered to pay the $1,500 to $3,000
cost of the DNA testing by experts of the state's choosing, with
the results reported directly to judicial authorities.
</P>
<P>
   The governor cannot commute a death sentence or grant clemency
without the recommendation of the Texas Board of Pardons and
Paroles. He can, however, make a one-time, 30-day stay to give a
condemned prisoner additional time for court appeals.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the governor would not make a decision on that until after
the Parole Board has met and reviewed the case and ruled,'' press
spokesman Mike Jones said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the appeal to the state Board of Pardons and
Paroles, McGinn's attorneys also appealing to the Fifth U.S.
Circuit Court of Appeals and, if necessary, the U.S. Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   Alley, who has represented McGinn on his constitutional appeals,
said McGinn's case could test the governor's claim ``that we don't
execute innocent people.'' The U.S. Department of Justice and the
American Bar Association, among others, have endorsed
post-conviction DNA testing with new technology, Alley said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't get a chance to do it later,'' Alley said. ``All
we're asking for is the time to get the testing done. The state
doesn't even have to pay for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Late Wednesday, the Board of Pardons and Paroles voted 11-7
against a reprieve. And Bush, campaigning in New Mexico, said he
was ``inclined'' to grant a 30-day reprieve for the new DNA tests.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
