r k BC-MINOR-COLUMN0602-COX     06-01 0539
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MINOR-COLUMN0602-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Private schools no sanctuary from violence
 &HT;    By Emily Minor
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Let's admit it to ourselves just for a
moment.
</P>
<P>
   Private school.
</P>
<P>
   Are you thinking about it, too?.
</P>
<P>
   Jimmy Carter did it, and he has a good heart. So did Clinton,
although he is not exactly our yardstick for moral behavior. And
although I'm a liberal _ I like my son to go to school with
children who speak Spanish at home, children who have survived
divorce, children whose parents are from Romania and Cuba and Haiti
_ right now I'm sad and confused and scared.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, I'm thinking: Wouldn't he be safer at some small,
pricey private school?
</P>
<P>
   Fear does funny things to the common sense.
</P>
<P>
   On the first work day after Barry Grunow's shooting death, I
called Jose Garcia, a principal at Conniston Middle School. Garcia
knows a little something about the heartbreak of a school shooting.
He was assistant principal there when a student was shot dead on
campus in 1997. Tuesday, he pulled his staff together, had a
meeting, sent the folks at Lake Worth Middle School a nice note.
</P>
<P>
   ``We at Conniston Middle School understand what you are going
through. This has reopened some old wounds. No one can ever begin
to understand the horror, pain and loss that incidents like this
cause. Please be strong, support each other and allow for the
healing to begin.''
</P>
<P>
   I guess parents have no choice but to do the same.
</P>
<P>
   But it's not easy. We're afraid to send our kids to school on
the last day of school. I've always worried about car wrecks and
old friendships and the checking account balance, but I've never
worried about sending my son to celebrate the final school day of
the year.
</P>
<P>
   Until now.
</P>
<P>
   Janet Cole is a mother of four children. She does not have the
financial means for their private education, doesn't know that she
would go that route even if she could. So she picks and chooses,
tours campuses and tries, as best she can, to send her children to
places where she feels they're safe.
</P>
<P>
   Cole's next-to-the- youngest daughter just finished her first
year at Roosevelt Middle School in West Palm Beach.
</P>
<P>
   ``You do wonder,'' she said. ``There's a rough element at
Roosevelt, and that may not be P.C. But it's a fact. There are some
tough kids there. She had things stolen from her locker.''
</P>
<P>
   Did she worry about her every day?
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' she said. ``I didn't have that luxury.''
</P>
<P>
   Will she now? Yes.
</P>
<P>
   Bonnie Mutz, the admissions director at The Kings Academy, a
private Christian school, said their enrollment has been pretty
constant the last 10 years, despite our social scares. ``Even when
Columbine happened, nothing really changed,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But that doesn't mean we're not out here thinking about it.
</P>
<P>
   Garcia says I'm brainwashed by my own fear.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have been indoctrinated, so you are associating that the
wealthier environment is safer,'' he said. ``I think a school is a
school is a school. We need to focus on reducing the amount of harm
these young people are going through.''
</P>
<P>
   We need to realize there is nowhere to hide.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
