<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 11:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1671 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-CELEBRITY-STYLE0602-C     06-01 0640
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CELEBRITY-STYLE0602-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A Hollywood insider deconstructs the styles of the celebs you
love to look at.
 &HT;    By Staci Sturrock
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Her response to The Post's recent fashion
survey began, ``For some reason or other I never learned 'to put
myself together' to my satisfaction,'' and ended with, ``I love to
laugh.''
</P>
<P>
   Carmen Mains sounded like a dream candidate for a wardrobe
makeover, demonstrating both desire and good humor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have never given much thought to how I look,'' said Mains, a
bubbly 72-year-old. ``The time has come that I should do something
about it before I die.''
</P>
<P>
   And so image consultant Susan Bigsby plunged into Mains' tidy
Palm City closet, only to find that the Puerto Rico native was
already doing an awful lot right. She just needed a little
encouragement and a few minor tweaks.
</P>
<P>
   Bigsby first assured Mains that she needn't overcomplicate her
retiree's casual wardrobe. If Mains typically wears shorts for her
volunteer work and flowing dresses for church, there's no need to
go above and beyond. Why buy a suit for the sake of buying a suit?
</P>
<P>
   Bigsby also encouraged Mains to rid her closet of several drab
dresses (''You need color, like most mature women who have gone
gray and don't wear a lot of makeup,'' Bigsby said) and a pair of
clunky white sandals from 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``O.J. Simpson shoes,'' Mains said, pointing to the Bruno Magli
label. ``They are out of style,'' said Bigsby, adding that white
tends to make feet look bigger. ``You have all these little beachy
sandals, and you need to have some pretty sandals,'' something a
little more feminine.
</P>
<P>
   For her corporate clients, Bigsby advises neutral separates that
can be easily mixed and matched. That's the wrong approach for
Mains, though, who likes to buy outfits rather than individual
pieces and whose big personality demands vibrant colors.
</P>
<P>
   A cream-colored three-piece knit outfit is banished from the
closet. ``This is so boring for the kind of personality you have,''
Bigsby tells Mains. ``You have more spunk than that outfit does.''
</P>
<P>
   Because Mains tends to carry extra weight around her middle, she
needs long, lean lines. And although she has undeniably great legs,
trying to show them off will ultimately make her look top heavy.
That's why her choice of long dresses works so well. On the day of
Bigsby's visit, Mains came to the door in an ankle-skimming navy
print dress, one of many she owned. ``This is good for you. I think
this suits you wonderfully,'' Bigsby said.
</P>
<P>
   After awhile, Mains starts to pick up what works and what
doesn't. It is she who makes the first move to toss a mint-green
twin set. ``Serves me right for buying it on special at Laura
Ashley,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Also gone, a girlish plaid dress with ruffles down the front.
``Why did I buy this?'' Mains said. ``I don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   Knowing how to build a wardrobe isn't the easiest skill to
acquire, but it's not impossible, Bigsby said. ``If you've never
had anyone show you how to do it, it's hard to learn on your own,''
Bigsby said. ``Somebody's got to teach you.''
</P>
<P>
   And magazines aren't always the answer, for they largely report
trends instead of teach concepts.
</P>
<P>
   Image consultants or well-dressed friends can help you learn the
basics of shaping a wardrobe and finding clothes that flatter your
figure, your lifestyle and your pocketbook.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once you know what to look for, you eliminate half the store
automatically,'' Bigsby said. ``You have to have a reason to have
things in your closet. Otherwise you're just wasting money.
Something could be pretty, but do you need it?''
</P>
<P>
   Bigsby told Mains, ``I try to dress people for who they are, and
this closet is perfect for you.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
