<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 11:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1676 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-ELIAN-RULING-COX     06-01 0737
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELIAN-RULING-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Court delivers a victory to father
 &HT;    By Rhonda Cook
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANMTA _ A federal appeals court ruled today that immigration
officials acted within their rights when they denied an asylum
hearing to 6-year-old Cuban shipwreck survivor Elian Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
   The decision handed down by a three-judge panel of the 11th U.S.
Circuit Court of Appeals apparently clears the way for the boy's
father, Juan Miguel Gonzalez, to take his son back to Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   The Miami relatives have 14 days to ask all 12 judges of the
11th Circuit to review the case, but it is unclear if they can stop
Juan Miguel Gonzalez from taking his child home to Cuba during that
time. If the court refuses to hear the appeal, the relatives would
has 90 days to appeal to the Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   The court said that when the application for asylum was filed,
the Immigration and Naturalization Service had no policy ``to deal
with extraordinary circumstances'' of a relative filing on behalf
of a minor child against a parent's wishes. But INS has since
developed a policy, and it was entitled to do that, the judges said
today.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is the duty of the Congress and the executive branch to
exercise political will,'' the ruling said. ``Although courts
should not be unquestioning, we should respect the other branch's
policymaking powers. The judicial power is a limited power. It is
the duty of the judicial branch not to exercise political will, but
only to render judicial judgment under the law.''
</P>
<P>
   Chris Lehane, press secretary for Vice President Al Gore, said
that Gore ``has long believed the case should have been handled in
family court. However, we should respect the decision rendered by
the appellate court.''
</P>
<P>
   Lehane made the comment after Gore visited the AFLAC Cancer at
Childrens Healthcare of Atlanta at Egleston.
</P>
<P>
   Immigration and Naturalization Service spokeswoman Maria Cardona
said ``preliminarily, through press reports, it looks good, but we
need time to review the whole decison before we go any further.''
</P>
<P>
   The emotional saga of Elian has been building since
Thanksgiving, when the young castaway was plucked from the Atlantic
Ocean where he had been drifting in an inner tube after he, his
mother and other fugitives from Cuba capsized.
</P>
<P>
   Elian's great-uncle, Lazaro Gonzalez; his cousin, Marisleysis
Gonzalez, and other relatives in Miami took him in soon after his
rescue. An international custody battle for the boy soon began with
the relatives insisting that Elian would fare better if they raised
him since his mother was among those who drowned trying to escape
Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   For more than five months, the relatives refused to give up
Elian until federal agents came into Lazaro Gonzalez's home before
dawn April 22, the day before Easter, and whisked him away to
Washington where his father, stepmother and baby brother were
waiting.
</P>
<P>
   Elian and his family have been in the Washington area since
then, because the courts have said they could not leave until
courts ruled on the asylum issue. Playmates have been brought from
Cuba to be with Elian while he waited.
</P>
<P>
   Lazaro Gonzalez filed the petition for political asylum for
Elian, who could not read or write when the request was made. The
relatives argued that if the little boy were returned to Cuba,
Elian's beliefs about the United States will be ``purged'' by the
Marxist government and he would become a ``traumatized'' child.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. law grants special status to Cubans in that they can stay
in this country once they are on ``dry land.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Attorney General Janet Reno, attorneys for the Immigration
and Naturalization Service and the boy's father have argued that
Juan Miguel Gonzalez is a loving parent and only he should decide
what is best for his son, who is too young to make those kind of
decisions.
</P>
<P>
   ``He (Juan Miguel Gonzalez) knows this child better than anyone
in this courtroom, or anyone else on the face of this planet .. .
There is a real family here,'' attorney Gregory Craig told a
three-judge panel _ Judges J.L. Edmondson of Atlanta, Joel Dubina
of Montgomery and Charles Wilson of Tampa _ during arguments in
Atlanta last month.
</P>
<P>
   The court had promised a quick decision, which came three weeks
to the day after the arguments appealing a lower court decision.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
