<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-COMPUTERS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INSTANT-MESSAGING STAKES RISING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By HIAWATHA BRAY   
 c.2000 The Boston Globe   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The Hyatt Harborside Hotel is an easy cab ride from
Logan Airport. The place offers a picturesque view of Boston Harbor
and the city's skyline. The hotel even boasts a water taxi to ferry
guests downtown in Venetian comfort.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the Hyatt Harborside holds little appeal for the executives
of America Online Inc. None of them came to the Instant Messaging
2000 conference held here this week. Too bad. The other guests
would have welcomed AOL _ as a luncheon entree.
</P>
<P>
   AOL is by far the world leader in instant messaging, the
Internet service that lets people fire off snippets of chat to each
other. The company's Instant Messenger and Iservices have about 120
million users between them, giving AOL as big a monopoly in instant
messaging as Microsoft Corp. has in desktop operating systems.
Upstarts like Odigo and CMGI Inc.'s Tribal Voice barely register on
radar.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine MCI telling its customers that they could only place
calls to other MCI subscribers. That's how AOL does instant
messaging. Its two services are incompatible with everybody else's.
That means that a user of, say, CMGI Inc.'s Tribal Voice service,
can't send messages to users of AOL Instant Messenger or ICQ.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet Engineering Task Force, one of the online world's
self-regulatory bodies, is working on a global messaging standard
that'll eliminate compatibility problems. AOL has said that it will
embrace such a standard _ one of these days.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, rival companies have sometimes tailored their
software to work with AOL's, but when they do, AOL rewrites its
code so the other messaging software no longer works. The company
says that allowing access by non-AOL message systems compromises
the security of the AOL network.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Pulver, whose company runs the conference, has a more
cynical explanation _ it's AOL's monopoly and it's sticking to it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look at them more like the old Russia, where they rule with
an iron fist,'' Pulver says.
</P>
<P>
   Tribal Voice has asked the Federal Communications Commission to
intervene in the planned merger between AOL and Time Warner Inc.
The company's goal is to force AOL to open up its system now. Given
the outrage over Time Warner's idiotic decision to block ABC
Television Network programs from its cable TV systems, federal
regulators are already taking a hard look at this merger. The cries
of the instant messengers may fall on attentive ears.
</P>
<P>
   The stakes are getting higher, because instant messaging isn't
just for love-struck high schoolers. Microsoft Corp. and IBM
Corp.'s Lotus Development Corp. unit are building instant messaging
into corporate software to allow teams of workers to keep track of
each other and their customers.
</P>
<P>
   Today there's little corporate use of instant messaging, but
that's changing. It's not just the ability to fire off quick notes
that businesses crave. It's the ability to always know which
employees are plugged in.
</P>
<P>
   Instant messaging systems rely on a piece of client software
that connects to the Internet. This client sends a tiny burst of
data to a server, informing the network, ``He's here.'' The network
doesn't merely know how to reach you _ it knows you're actually
online at that moment, ready for action. It's as if your telephone
knew when you arrived home and notified all your relatives that you
were available to be pestered.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, telephones are the next frontier in instant messaging.
AOL and Tribal Voice are introducing systems that will ``know''
when you switch on your cell phone. As with today's instant
messaging software, you can make yourself invisible to the network,
or visible only to certain people. A colleague will be able to type
an instant message on his computer, and it'll appear on the phone's
display screen. Or he could phone you instead because the network
has shown him that you're accepting phone calls.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind the lowbrow content of most instant message chats.
Instant messaging itself is a triumph of network intelligence.
Someday, all forms of electronic data _ Internet services, phone
calls, eventually even TV and radio _ could be based on the same
concept: customized data, served up by a network that knows us.
</P>
<P>
   It's such a big idea, I can't blame AOL for not wanting to
share. It's such a big idea that in the end, they'll have to.
</P>
<P>
   Hiawatha Bray is a member of the Globe staff. He can be reached
by e-mail at bray(at)globe.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-05-25-00 1455EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
