 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
 &HT;    Web now the best place to get shareware, freeware
 &HT;    By Bill Husted
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Most of us have sampled e-commerce by now, and the
idea of buying something online is no longer strange or
frightening.
</P>
<P>
   But long before there were dot-coms offering items for sale, the
Internet _ and computer Bulletin Board Systems before that _ had
strange little storefronts where the merchandise was free for the
taking.
</P>
<P>
   In the early days, shareware and freeware programs were mostly
found on CompuServe, Prodigy and AOL. That was before these
services became gateways to the Internet. Whether you were looking
for a game or a word processor or a spreadsheet program, it was
pretty easy to find a free or inexpensive one to download and use.
</P>
<P>
   That's still true. It's just that now, the Web is the best place
to find these programs. We'll look at some of the places where
they're available today. But before we start that, you need to
understand the two terms: shareware and freeware. The two types of
programs have a lot in common.
</P>
<P>
   In both cases, instead of being sold in stores, they're mostly
distributed online. That means that people who can't afford to
start a company and sell commercial software can create programs
and distribute them with no marketing or manufacturing costs.
</P>
<P>
   Shareware is a type of program that you use on a free trial
basis. After using it, if you like it, you're supposed to send a
payment. If you don't like it, you simply delete the program and no
money is owed. Freeware is as you'd figure, software that is
distributed with no payment owed. You'll find both types of
programs on the sites we visit today.
</P>
<P>
   Our first stop is www.shareware.com. It's one of the best places
to start. Simply use the opening page just as you would a
conventional search engine such as Yahoo. Fill in the search terms
that describe the program you seek. You'll also need to use the
pull-down menu to tell the search engine the type of operating
system you are using: Windows, Macintosh, Linux, etc.
</P>
<P>
   Once you've filled in all the blanks, the page will search out
software that seems to fit your criteria. Once you find a program
that you want to try, double click on it, and it'll download
automatically to your computer's hard disk. Almost all these
programs are made so that they'll extract and install automatically
_ again you just need to double click on the file you downloaded.
</P>
<P>
   In some cases, you'll need programs that are used to extract the
files for you. If that's the case, you'll be told about how to
download of copy of that extraction program.
</P>
<P>
   If that sounds unwieldy and complicated, read the help sections
you'll find on all these pages. You'll get instructions on how
things work in much more detail than can be offered here.
</P>
<P>
   Now that you know how these sites work _ and all of them work in
an almost identical way _ we can cover ground faster.
</P>
<P>
   The next site to check is Tucows and is at www.tucows.com. This
is a site that specializes in the kind of programs you need to use
the Internet efficiently. You'll find the obvious here: browsers,
newsgroup readers, e-mail programs, FTP (file transfer protocol
programs, used to send and receive files over the Internet) and
tiny utility programs that can tune up your online connection to
make it more efficient. There are also some very specialized
Internet programs here, things that most of us don't need.
</P>
<P>
   One of the best things about this particular site is that _ when
you log on to it _ you are able to select a computer server in your
own area from a list. That means that the downloads generally will
go faster and that there isn't the sort of online congestion you'd
find if one server was trying to handle the load.
</P>
<P>
   Other sites for downloads include, but aren't limited to,
download.cnet.com/, www.softseek.com/ and www
</P>
<P>
   .planetclick.com/cgi-bin/category
</P>
<P>
   .cgi?T &QC; download+software.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-05-29-00 1417EDT &QL;
</P>
