<HEADER>
A1712 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-BOOKS-MITCHELL04-COX     06-01 0930
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-MITCHELL04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Girlhood glimpse of Margaret Mitchell
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, June 4.
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It was almost like discovering the secret diary of
Scarlett O'Hara.
</P>
<P>
   Seven years ago, Jane Eskridge was helping her friend Wailes
Thomas clean out his mother's 60-year-old house in Atlanta when she
came across a crushed, cobweb-covered box.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was really hot, and we were exhausted, and the box was so
dilapidated, we almost tossed it,'' says Eskridge, 60, a middle
school teacher in Greensboro, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then I pulled out something that looked like an address book.
When I opened it up, on the inside flap it said Margaret Mitchell
and her address, and it was dated 1913. Then I saw there were three
story titles on the right, and when I flipped through it and
realized there were stories, I just screamed.''
</P>
<P>
   By the time the box was empty, Eskridge had found two 1910
letters from Mitchell to her father from Summit, N.J.; four
handmade books written between 1912 and 1913; one untitled
shipwreck story; one untitled Civil War story and the beginning
chapters of another; two copybooks with a poem and seven stories, a
play, an essay, and eight journal entries written between 1915 and
1916.
</P>
<P>
   The stories, journals and musings were written by Mitchell on
dime-store notebooks from when she about 8 until she was 17. Since
most of Mitchell's papers were destroyed after her death, how these
writings survived is a mystery.
</P>
<P>
   The house once belonged to Thomas' late aunt, Margueryte
Reynolds Sharp, who was married to the brother-in-law of Mitchell's
brother, Stephens Mitchell. Apparently the notebooks were packed
with other books from Reynolds' library and lay undiscovered for
decades.
</P>
<P>
   Eskridge's discovery is available to the public in an exhibit at
the Margaret Mitchell House and in a new book, ``Before Scarlett:
Girlhood Writings of Margaret Mitchell'' (Hill Street Press,
$21.95).
</P>
<P>
   ``This exhibit provides a unique opportunity in American
literature to trace the evolution of a writer who would later
capture the heart, soul and mind of people all over the world,''
says Mary Rose Taylor, executive director of the Margaret Mitchell
House &AMP; Museum.
</P>
<P>
   The writings reflect the major influence Mitchell's parents had
on her views of the world. Her mother was a leader in the women's
suffrage movement, and her father, who was president of the Georgia
Bar Association, campaigned for an appeal of Leo Frank's
conviction.
</P>
<P>
   Growing up in that kind of activist environment led Mitchell to
favor heroines over heroes in her girlhood stories and ``to portray
characters possessed of the kind of strength and passion she saw in
her own parents,'' Taylor says.
</P>
<P>
   As a child, Mitchell showed talent beyond her years. ``She was a
master of dialogue. The stories move right along with good
transition,'' Eskridge says.
</P>
<P>
   One story, ``Dan Morrison, A Spy for the Confederacy,'' reflects
Mitchell's early interest in the Civil War _ a fascination fueled
by the vivid tales she heard from Confederate veterans and from her
parents.
</P>
<P>
   In a 1936 letter to a friend, Mitchell wrote about visiting
relatives who had fought in the war. ``I sat on the bony knees of
veterans and the fat slippery laps of great-aunts and heard them
talk about ... how Grandpa Mitchell walked nearly fifty miles after
the Battle of Sharpsburg with his skull cracked in two places from
a bullet.
</P>
<P>
   ``They didn't talk of these happenings as history nor as
remarkable events, but just as part of their lives and not
especially epic parts. And they gradually became a part of my
life.''
</P>
<P>
   Other stories of shipwrecks and cowboys reveal Mitchell's wild
imagination and spirit of adventure. And, with the Mexican
Revolution and news of Pancho Villa's exploits fresh in her mind,
Mitchell wrote three Mexican stories. In one, the heroine is
kidnapped by rebels and rescued by a bold Mexican leader, a kind of
Rhett Butler with a Spanish accent.
</P>
<P>
   Eskridge, who wrote the introduction and explanatory material
for the book, says the collection sheds new light on Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   ``Besides being fun to read,'' she says, ``these treasures from
Mitchell's childhood give new insight into the development of her
talents as a gifted writer and storyteller.''
</P>
<P>
   From ``Before Scarlett''
</P>
<P>
   Peggy lay in the sand behind some mesquite bushes, hugging her
father's big rifle to her breast and watching Alvarado's men move
about in the house. Since the late hours of the night before she
had lain there and though now the early Mexican sun was burning her
blue eyes and blistering the little arms that so tightly held the
big gun, no thought of changing her position had entered her mind.
...
</P>
<P>
   She had been in the kitchen spreading sandwiches for Bob, Big
Sister's intended, when Alvarado and his bandits arrived, and the
trampling of hoofs, the noise, the loud voices had brought her to
the door of the living room just in time to see the coolly smiling
Mexican leader shoot down her father. Mother had screamed, thrown
herself beside him, only to receive Alvarado's second bullet.
</P>
<P>
   EXHIBIT
</P>
<P>
   Editor Jane Eskridge will be on hand for a reception at 7-9 p.m.
Wednesday at the Margaret Mitchell House &AMP; Museum, Peachtree and
10th streets. Reservations required. Call 770- 578-3502. Exhibit
will be open 9 a.m.-4 p.m. daily through Nov. 1. $10 for adults, $8
for seniors and students, $7 for children 6-11.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
