<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FISHNET-STOCKINGS04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Get a leg up on the latest with hose that are a breeze to wear
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, June 4.
 &HT;    By Ginger McFarland and Subira Shaw
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   After several seasons of stagnant sales, the hosiery industry is
snapping back. Fishnet stockings _ as well as patterned hosiery,
luxury sheers and colored hose _ are being featured prominently in
stores this spring. And retailers are predicting that by fall women
will be stocking up on styles that stand out.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the fashion leaders begin showing their novelty hosiery,
it will trickle down to the consumer,'' said Joan Kaner, senior
vice president and fashion director for Neiman Marcus.
</P>
<P>
   Top designers such as Miuccia Prada and Gucci's Tom Ford have
spring ad campaigns featuring seductive hosiery, and their message
has reached the street.
</P>
<P>
   Now women who wear fishnets may look out of the ordinary but not
necessarily out of place.
</P>
<P>
   Nineteen-year-old Rondi Scott of Norcross, Ga., typically
injects color into her black-on-black ensembles by wearing opaque
hose in bright shades like fuchsia beneath a pair of open-weave
black fishnets.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm an avid fishnet-wearer,'' said Scott, who's been sporting
them since she was 13. ``If you've got nice legs, fishnets show
them off a lot more.''
</P>
<P>
   That layered look Scott likes to wear is ``the hottest look for
spring,'' according to Shannon Zirkle, who manages the Victoria's
Secret Hosiery Boutique at North Point Mall, Alpharetta, Ga. Zirkle
added: ``It's about expressing your fashion mood.''
</P>
<P>
   When she's in the mood to be noticed, 26-year-old Jessa Holz of
Duluth, Ga., shimmies into some fishnets as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're eye-catching,'' explained Holz, who's worn fishnets
for five years. ``People do double takes when I've got them on.''
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, Holz pointed out, wearing fishnets has
weather-related advantages.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like wearing air-conditioned hose,'' she said. ``The
holes in fishnets make them cooler than regular hose. You still get
the dressy look for a suit without being too hot.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
