<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 12:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1715 &Cx1f; tad-z
r t BC-BOSTON-FAMILY04-COX     06-01 0863
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOSTON-FAMILY04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Six family fun ideas in Boston
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, June 4.
 &HT;    By Paula Crouch Thrasher
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Boston Tea Party
</P>
<P>
   ``Dump the tea! Into the sea!'' is the rallying cry aboard the
Brig Beaver II, a full-size working replica of one of the original
Tea Party ships. First, we gather for a Town Meeting where our
costumed guide teaches us how to be good rabble-rousers: We say
``Fie!'' and thrust our fists to the ground in opposition to taxes
and chant ``Hear! Hear!'' to call for revolt. All fired up, we
dress up as Indians (OK, we tucked a blue feather behind our ear)
and cheer as two volunteers heave rather ratty-looking bales of tea
overboard. OK, it's hokey, but lots of fun. And you really do learn
a lot about what happened on ``The Night of Decision'' _ Dec. 16,
1773. Be sure to visit the museum on the dock and have a cup of
tax-free hot tea on the house. $8; $4 children. Congress Street
Bridge. 617-338-1773; www.historictours.com.
</P>
<P>
   Children's Museum Boston
</P>
<P>
   Just across the Congress Street Bridge is a special place that
engages kids 10 and under with hands-on activities such as a
life-size boat and Kidstage, where kids can let their dramatic
streaks run wild. Fans of Arthur the aardvark will love ``Arthur's
World,'' where they can see themselves on TV. Just head toward the
giant wooden milk bottle _ a 40-foot-tall landmark that is actually
a snack bar. 10 a.m.-5 p.m. daily (until 9 p.m. Fridays). $7; $6
ages 2-15 and seniors; $2 for 1-year-olds; $1 for all 5-9 p.m.
Fridays. 617-426-8855; www.bostonkids.org.
</P>
<P>
   Boston Duck Tours
</P>
<P>
   You'll feel like a total quack rolling through Boston in a World
War II era amphibious landing vehicle. But you'll have a ball as we
did aboard the geranium pink ``duck'' Commonwealth Curley. Each
conDUCKtor (as they're called) assumes a comic persona. Ours is a
Tom Selleck lookalike who goes by ``Magnum DI.'' He wears a
Hawaiian shirt and lei and a Detroit Tigers baseball cap. His
tour-guide patter includes snippets of Boston history. When we pass
a certain point on Boylston Street in the Back Bay, he tells us we
can boast to our friends back home that we crossed the Boston
Marathon finish line. With a mighty blast of the horn, we splash
into the lower basin of the Charles River. Here, Magnum DI explains
how these vehicles were used in Okinawa and Sicily during wartime.
``Remember,'' he says, ``somebody died for us to take this silly
thing around the city.'' Tours leave daily from the Prudential
Center every half hour from 9 a.m. Buy tickets inside at Center
Court. $21; $18 students and seniors; $11 ages 4-12; 25 cents for
age 3 and under. 617-723-3825; www.bostonducktours.com.
</P>
<P>
   New England Aquarium
</P>
<P>
   Whale Watching Tour
</P>
<P>
   You're sure to have a whale of a time shouting ``Thar she
blows!'' as the great sea mammals surface and dive off the
Stellwagen Banks, the rich feeding grounds for whales, dolphins,
other marine life and sea birds about 20 miles offshore. The blue
and white catamaran Voyager III departed from the dock beside the
New England Aquarium (itself a great family attraction) at 10 a.m.
By 11:37, we had a sighting, the first of many during the 3
1/2-hour excursion. Our score card: 15 humpbacks, four finbacks,
one minke, one harbor porpoise and a seal. Granted, these were
fleeting glimpses _ but we did get at least one magnificent dive
that ended with the fluke, or tail, waving high above the surface.
10 a.m. weekdays and 9:30 a.m. and 3:30 p.m. through June; 9:30
a.m., 12:30 and 2:30 p.m. daily July 1-Sept. 4; 1 p.m. weekdays and
9:30 a.m. and 2:30 p.m. Sept. 5-Oct. 9; and 10 a.m. weekends only
Oct. 14-Nov. 5. Call for special trip times July 7-16 during Sail
Boston 2000. $26.50; $21 college students and seniors over age 60;
$19 ages 2-18; $16.50 ages 3-11. Children under 3 not allowed.
Advance reservations recommended. 617-973-5281; www.neaq.org.
</P>
<P>
   Boston by Sea
</P>
<P>
   This lively cruise is more like a floating musical theater.
During a 90-minute harbor tour, Boston's maritime history comes
alive as costumed guides _ a bunch of old salts _ tell stories of
the sea and sing chanteys as you cruise among the harbor islands.
Tours at 1 and 3 p.m. daily through Oct. 9. 617-227-4321;
www.bostonharborcruises.com.
</P>
<P>
   Swan Boats
</P>
<P>
   Lazily circling the lagoon in the Public Garden at the blazing
speed of 2 mph in these pedal-powered craft has been a tradition
since 1877. Big Bertha, the oldest swan in the current fleet, has
been at it since 1918. The original boats carried only one person;
today's hold 20. 10 a.m.-4 p.m. daily through Sept. 10. $2, $1 ages
2-15. 617-522-1966.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Information: For a free copy of the 48-page booklet ``Kids
Love Boston,'' call the Greater Boston Convention and Visitors
Bureau, 1-800-733-2678; www.bostonusa
</P>
<P>
   .com. Also, ask for a Spring-Summer Travel Planner, which
includes a Family-Friendly ValuePASS good for discounts and good
deals at area attractions, restaurants and hotels.
</P>
<P>
   _ Paula Crouch Thrasher writes for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
