<P>
   MINOR-COLUMN _ PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Let's admit it to ourselves
just for a moment. Private school. Are you thinking about it, too?
Jimmy Carter did it, and he has a good heart. So did Clinton,
although he is not exactly our yardstick for moral behavior. And
although I'm a liberal _ I like my son to go to school with
children who speak Spanish at home, children who have survived
divorce, children whose parents are from Romania and Cuba and Haiti
_ right now I'm sad and confused and scared. (Minor, Palm Beach
Post). MOVED
</P>
<P>
   BORDERS-COLUMN _ Dear Kasey: I can't believe it's already been
four years since your high school graduation. At this rate, I'll be
dead in no time. Now you're a college graduate with highest honors
from the University of Texas at Austin, the second generation of
our family to be an official Texas-Ex. The first generation, namely
me, didn't get any type of ``honor'' appellation next to the
diploma. I was just proud to eke out a master's degree in seven
years. (Gary Borders is editor and publisher of the Nacogdoches
Daily Sentinel.) EMBARGOED for Sunday. MOVED
</P>
<P>
   MCNEELY-COLUMN _ AUSTIN, Texas _ Ricky McGinn was scheduled to
die Thursday. In 1995, McGinn, who had a record of sexual assault,
was convicted of murdering and raping his 12-year-old stepdaughter
in 1993. The evidence against McGinn was strong: blood on his car
that could have come from less than 1 percent of people other than
the victim, and hair that matched the victim's on an ax identified
as the murder weapon. McGinn's attorneys and death-penalty
opponents were pressing last-minute appeals to try to save him,
including pleas for new DNA tests they say could free him.
(McNeely, Austin American-Statesman) MOVED
</P>
