<P>
   COXNET ENTERTAIN PAGE
</P>
<P>
   EDs: This is the CoxNet ENTERTAIN page for the current week.
This layout is available now.
</P>
<P>
   COXNET LIFESTYLES 0601 -- It has been two decades since Ted
Turner launched his news operation in the basement of a converted
Atlanta country club. The 20-year period has been marked by highs
such as the Persian Gulf War's ``Boys of Baghdad,'' worldwide
growth into 212 countries and expansion on the Internet. Yet today,
a struggle with ratings, unrest over a major merger and an
uncertain online future challenge the 24-hour news network. (Kloer,
Kempner, Atlanta-Journal Constitution) Art includes a 6-column
color photo of the lobby of the CNN Center, a 2-column color photo
of journalists working in the newsroom, a 1-column color photo of
employees working at CNN INteractive and an 18-pica color photo of
CNN chairman Tom Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   (END OF COXNET ENTERTAIN PAGE)
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS
</P>
<P>
   BOOK-NOTES _ Jane Heller was a publicist for New York publishers
for years, promoting Stephen King in his early years and other
writers on their way to the top. Then she got bored and quit to do
some writing. Now, with several best sellers under her belt and a
recent movie sale to Julia Roberts, Heller has a publicist of her
own. Her latest book, ``Name Dropping,'' is a great beach book
about a kindergarten teacher whose life is disrupted when a
glamorous celebrity magazine writer with the same name moves into
her apartment building. (O'Briant, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
18.
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS-DOOLITTLE _ DAYTON _ She labels the most dramatic change
in her life as ``the whole wilderness thing.'' It happened in 1973
when she and her husband, both landscape painters, left advertising
jobs and spent a year traveling and living out of a 1957 Chevy
pickup they converted into a camper. ``It was magical for me,''
says Bev Doolittle, who became fascinated by the animals and
American Indians who inhabited the places they visited _ Yosemite,
Sequoia National Park, the Grand Canyon, Banff and the Canadian
Rockies _ while hiking, sketching, photographing and painting.
(Moss, Dayton Daily News) WITH PHOTOS. MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS-MITCHELL _ ATLANTA _ It was almost like discovering the
secret diary of Scarlett O'Hara. Seven years ago, Jane Eskridge was
helping her friend Wailes Thomas clean out his mother's 60-year-old
house in Atlanta when she came across a crushed, cobweb-covered
box. Inside, Eskridge found two 1910 letters from Mitchell to her
father from Summit, N.J.; four handmade books written between 1912
and 1913; one untitled shipwreck story; one untitled Civil War
story and the beginning chapters of another; two copybooks with a
poem and seven stories, a play, an essay, and eight journal entries
written between 1915 and 1916. Since most of Mitchell's papers were
destroyed after her death, how these writings survived is a
mystery. Now they're the subject of an exhibit at the Margaret
Mitchell House &AMP; Museum that opens this week and of a new book.
(O'Briant, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 21.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Embargoed until Sunday, June 4.
</P>
<P>
   BOOK-KIDS _ Roundup of the latest children's books. (Bookman,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
