<HEADER>
A1722 &Cx1f; tad-z
r t BC-FREEDOM-FESTIVALS04-C     06-01 0574
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FREEDOM-FESTIVALS04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Festival celebrates freedom
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, June 4.
 &HT;    By Paula Crouch Thrasher
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Let Freedom Ring!'' _ launched during Patriot's Day weekend in
April _ is Boston's three-season celebration of the 225th
anniversary of the American Revolution.
</P>
<P>
   The citywide fest organized by the Freedom Trail Foundation
features more than a hundred free and low-cost activities,
including costumed tours and lectures along the 2.5-mile Freedom
Trail, concerts, exhibits and storytelling.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the programs take place in and around the 16 sites on
the trail. The ``Let Freedom Ring'' umbrella also covers Boston
2000 Millennium Celebration July 3-4 and Sail Boston 2000, a visit
by 80 tall ships from 30 countries, July 10-21.
</P>
<P>
   For a free ``Let Freedom Ring! 2000'' brochure, call
1-888-733-2678 or check www.BostonUSA.com. To contact the Freedom
Trail Foundation, call 617-227-8800; www.thefreedomtrail.org.
</P>
<P>
   Here are some of the highlights:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Independence Day Constitutional: A walk along the Freedom
Trail led by costumed historic interpreters featuring short
Colonial music performances by penny whistle and violin along the
way. Tour begins at Boston Common Visitor Center. 2:30-4:30 p.m.
June 30, July 1, 2, 3 and 4. $10; $5 under 12. 617-227-8800;
www.thefreedomtrail.org.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Paul Revere's Boston'': On Saturday afternoons through
October, the museum hosts special events that illuminate life in
early Boston. Visitors may watch a silversmith, potter or tailor
plying their trades; attend a concert of Colonial tavern music; and
hear dramatic tales about life in revolutionary Boston. Free with
admission: $2.50; $2 students and seniors; $1 ages 5-17 it to the
Bunker Hill Monument, which commemorates the first formal battle of
the American Revolution on June 17, 1775. We hop a water shuttle to
Long Wharf and make a mad dash for the T _ the subway _ for a ride
to our Back Bay hotel.
</P>
<P>
   And as the thunder rumbles, we can't help but be happy that our
jovial Colonial friend James Otis avoided being caught out in the
thunderstorm.
</P>
<P>
   History records Otis died in 1783 _ after being struck by a bolt
of lightning.
</P>
<P>
   GETTING THERE
</P>
<P>
   Fly nonstop to Boston for $91 each way on AirTran or Delta, with
a 14-day advance purchase.
</P>
<P>
   TAKING THE TOUR
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  On your own: All you have to do is start walking _ from either
the beginning of the Freedom Trail at the Boston Common Visitor
Center or the end at the Bunker Hill monument. The trail is
well-marked with signs and maps, information kiosks and brass
medallions marking the trail's 16 historic sites. Allow at least
three hours. The Freedom Trail Foundation offers a free map and
guide at visitor centers. A small admission fee ($3 or less) is
charged to enter some of the sites.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  With the Freedom Trail Players: Regularly scheduled tours
depart from Boston Common during the summer. $10; $5 children.
617-227-8800; www.thefreedomtrail.org.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  With the National Park Service: They don't wear tricornered
hats, but rangers give free guided tours of the Freedom Trail daily
through September. The 90-minute tours depart hourly 10 a.m. to 3
p.m., from the National Park Service Center, 15 State St.
617-242-5642.
</P>
<P>
   Paula Crouch Thrasher writes for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
