r t BC-HISTORIC-SITES04-COX     06-01 0159
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HISTORIC-SITES04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Pilgrimage to Plymouth makes vacation history
 &HT;    By Paula Crouch Thrasher
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PLYMOUTH, Mass. _ As rocks go, it doesn't look like anything
special. It's not nearly as big as Gibraltar. It doesn't glisten
like gold or seal a sepulcher.
</P>
<P>
   But this smooth gray stone must be a big deal, enshrined as it
is under a portico that looks like a classical temple. Then there's
the telltale date carved on it: 1620.
</P>
<P>
   This isn't just aams here in 1620; Plimoth Plantation, a
living-history village that interprets the daily lives of the
colonists in 1627; and Pilgrim Hall Museum, where you can see what
they brought to America and learn about their perilous journey.
</P>
<P>
   The town itself is quite charming, not nearly as touristy as I
had expected, and everything is within easy walking distance. There
are a number of museums and historic homes open for tours,
interesting shops along the waterfro
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-01-00 1228EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000601.0110 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 12:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1762 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-MOVIES-MINIREVIEWS02-     06-01 1593
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-MINIREVIEWS02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mini reviews of current movies
 &HT;    By Eleanor Ringel Gillespie, Steve Murray and Bob Longino
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Grades range from A to F.
</P>
<P>
   ``28 Days'' PG-13 (profanity, substance
</P>
<P>
   abuse and sexuality)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Sandra Bullock
</P>
<P>
   and Viggo Mortensen.
</P>
<P>
   The cinema's chipper girl next door (Sandra Bullock) goes clean
and sober in an addiction and rehab movie that, thankfully, isn't
an appalling clinical ``comedy'' like ``Patch Adams.'' It's a
professional, appealing comedy-drama, but in trying to be all
things to all viewers (to beer-loving Bullock fans as well as
devoted 12-steppers), it never really comes into focus. (SM)1 hour,
43 minutes. C+
</P>
<P>
   ``Across the Sea of Time'' G
</P>
<P>
   3-D Imax film
</P>
<P>
   about New York City.
</P>
<P>
   History comes alive visually in this 3-D Imax movie focusing on
New York City. It's full of big, gloriously detailed ``stereoview''
photographs depicting immigrant life at the turn of the century.
(Bob Longino)51 minutes. B-
</P>
<P>
   ``Battlefield Earth'' PG-13 (intense sci-fi action)
</P>
<P>
   Starring John Travolta.
</P>
<P>
   Teens likely will be unable to stay awake, let alone make any
sense out of ``Battlefield Earth,'' a flat-footed sci-fi epic.
Boring, murky and full of unintentionally funny lines, this pet
project of star John Travolta is based on the 1982 novel by L. Ron
Hubbard, founder of the Church of Scientology, to which Travolta
belongs. (Jane Horwitz, Washington Post)1 hour, 57 minutes. D
</P>
<P>
   ``Beefcake'' Unrated (simulated sex
</P>
<P>
   and lots of nudity)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Daniel MacIvor
</P>
<P>
   and Josh Peace.
</P>
<P>
   A cheerful, campy but empty-headed look at homoeroticism.
Writer-director Thom Fitzgerald (``The Hanging Garden'') takes us
to the world of Hollywood in the1950s. It's a place where handsome,
wide-eyed wannabes could find themselves ushered into a poolside
wonderland of well-muscled men wearing nothing but teeny-tiny
posing pouches. (SM)1 hour, 36 minutes. C+
</P>
<P>
   ``The Big Kahuna'' R (profanity)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Kevin Spacey,
</P>
<P>
   Danny DeVito and Bob Facinelli.
</P>
<P>
   This three-hander is well worth your time for the terrific
acting. Three salesmen _ a corrosive cynic, (Kevin Spacey), a
resigned old-timer (Danny DeVito) and an eager-beaver newcomer (Bob
Facinelli) _ wait in their version of hell, i.e., a hospitality
suite in Wichita, for the chance to land that one all-important
client. Spacey and DeVito's performances are bracing and brainy.
(ERG)1 hour, 31 minutes. B
</P>
<P>
   ``Big Momma's House'' PG-13 (crude humor, sexual,
</P>
<P>
   profanity and some violence)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Martin Lawrence
</P>
<P>
   and Nia Long.
</P>
<P>
   It's one super-sized Martin Lawrence. As an FBI agent on a
neighborhood stakeout to capture a vicious bank robber, Lawrence
dons layer upon layer of prosthetics to impersonate a 325-pound,
small-town granny in Cartersville (the movie, however, was filmed
in Los Angeles). The results may be predictable, but with
Lawrence's manic comedic timing they are also occasionally quite
funny. (Bob Longino)1 hour, 39 minutes. B-
</P>
<P>
   ``Center Stage'' PG-13 (sexuality and language)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Ethan Stiefel,
</P>
<P>
   Amanda Schull and Zoe Saldana.
</P>
<P>
   An old-fashioned show biz fantasy for teenagers with leotards
and plies, ``Center Stage'' is a kind of movie that gets retooled
every 10 years or so. Its antecedents include ``Fame,'' ``Dirty
Dancing,'' ``The Turning Point'' and even ``Flashdance.'' It's the
female version of a sports movie: Sweat and inspiration lead to
love and brief heartache, but ultimately growth, self-worth and
even stardom result. (SM)1 hour, 53 minutes. B-
</P>
<P>
   ``Cider House Rules'' PG-13 (sexuality, nudity,
</P>
<P>
   substance abuse, violence)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Michael Caine
</P>
<P>
   and Tobey Maguire.
</P>
<P>
   John Irving has adapted his own novel. In the first half of the
film, Dr. Larch (Michael Caine) delivers babies and performs
illegal abortions in his Maine orphanage. In the second,
less-engaging half, Larch's protege, Homer Wells (Tobey Maguire),
runs off to learn about the world. An uneven but heartfelt and film
with excellent performances. (ERG)2 hours, 5 minutes. B
</P>
<P>
   ``Dinosaur'' PG (violence)
</P>
<P>
   Starring the voices of
</P>
<P>
   D.B. Sweeney, Della Reese
</P>
<P>
   and Julianna Margulies.
</P>
<P>
   Leapin' lizards! The prehistoric critters in Disney's
years-in-the-making, $200 million-plus computer animation do more
than leap. Alas, the plot is worth about two cents _ something
about an Iguanodon raised by lemurs who helps a herd of dinosaurs
find a fabled nesting ground after a disastrous meteor shower.
Parents be aware: While most of the movie is Barney-tame, the scary
parts are quite scary. (ERG)1 hour, 24 minutes. B
</P>
<P>
   ``East Is East'' R (profanity
</P>
<P>
   and domestic violence)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Om Puri
</P>
<P>
   and Linda Bassett.
</P>
<P>
   Set in working-class Britain in 1971, this uneven but energetic
film focuses on a boisterous Anglo-Pakistani family. The father is
a tyrannical type, while the mother is a grounded fish-and-chips
Englishwoman. And the kids are totally caught up in the exploding
England Swings pop-culture surrounding them. The very good cast,
headed by Om Puri and Linda Bassett, is a huge asset. (ERG)1 hour,
36 minutes. B-
</P>
<P>
   ``The Filth and the Fury'' R (profanity, violence,
</P>
<P>
   sexual and drug content)
</P>
<P>
   A documentary.
</P>
<P>
   Documentarian Julien Temple uses an artful mixture of
interviews, concert footage and archival clips to capture the life
of the controversial band the Sex Pistols. Temple's movie reminds
us what a short, strange trip it's been, taking us through a
spit-smeared looking glass to a time so close and yet so very far
away. (ERG) 1 hour, 45 minutes. A-
</P>
<P>
   ``Final Destination'' R (bloody violence and raw language)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Devon Sawa,
</P>
<P>
   Ali Larter and Kerr Smith.
</P>
<P>
   ``Final Destination'' aims for young audiences with an
``X-Files/The Wonder Years'' science/suspense plot about a kid who
escaped death from a plane crash and learns more than mortals
should about death. Our hero (Devon Sawa) and six others find
they're still targeted for death. The Grim Reaper, feeling cheated,
has plans for them. (Chris Hewitt, Knight Ridder Newspapers)1 hour,
33 minutes. D+
</P>
<P>
   ``The Flintstones
</P>
<P>
   in Viva Rock Vegas'' PG (brief profanity)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Mark Addy
</P>
<P>
   and Stephen Baldwin.
</P>
<P>
   Yabba-dabba-don't. A new, needless, live-action ``Flintstones,''
with Mark Addy as Fred, Stephen Baldwin as Barney, and the
courtship of Wilma and Betty as the plot. Inoffensive and mildly
amusing in spots, but hardly worth a trip to the theater. (Stephen
Whitty, Newhouse News Service)1 hour, 29 minutes. C-
</P>
<P>
   ``Frequency'' PG-13 (violence)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Dennis Quaid
</P>
<P>
   and Jim Caviezel.
</P>
<P>
   John Sullivan (Jim Caviezel) hears dead people. Specifically, he
hooks up to his dad's old ham radio set in 1999 and finds himself
talking to his dad (Dennis Quaid) in 1969. More crucially, John
knows his dad, a fireman, will be killed in a failed heroic rescue
the next day. Although over-plotted, the sentimental film has that
``what if?'' fascination. It's also a mind-bender and especially
savvy about emotional button-pushing. (ERG) 2 hours. B-
</P>
<P>
   ``Gladiator'' R (extreme violence,
</P>
<P>
   perverse sexuality)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Russell Crowe.
</P>
<P>
   Two thousand _ or, if you want to add computer effects, 200,000
_ thumbs up for Ridley Scott's spectacle starring Russell Crowe as
a Roman general, who returns to the Colosseum to take revenge on
the odious Emperor Commodus (Joaquin Phoenix). The battles staged
before the mob of mindless ancient Romans are the film's
centerpieces, but its brave heart (so to speak) is Crowe. (ERG) 2
hours, 33 minutes. A-
</P>
<P>
   ``Held Up'' PG-13 (profanity, violence, sexuality)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Jamie Foxx
</P>
<P>
   and Nia Long.
</P>
<P>
   Jamie Foxx is likable and funny as a Chicago businessman trapped
in a rural gas station who gets caught in the crossfire of would-be
bandits and the local sheriff and his posse of redneck deputies.
It's an amiable cross-cultural comedy bogged down midway through
the film by a big lull and a few static moments. (Kevin Thomas, Los
Angeles Times)1 hour, 31 minutes. C-
</P>
<P>
   ``High Fidelity'' R (profanity and sexuality)
</P>
<P>
   Starring John Cusack,
</P>
<P>
   Iben Hjejle and Jack Black.
</P>
<P>
   Freshly dumped by his longtime girlfriend, record-store owner
Rob (John Cusack) rhetorically asks himself, ``What came first _
music or the misery?'' In other words, does he listen to songs
about heartbreak because he's miserable, or is he miserable because
he's listening to these songs? ``High Fidelity'' is as smart as it
is enjoyable. It's a great date movie about dating. (SM) 1 hour, 54
minutes. A-
</P>
<P>
   ``I Dreamed of Africa'' PG-13 (nudity, sensuality
</P>
<P>
   and some violence)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Kim Basinger
</P>
<P>
   and Vincent Perez.
</P>
<P>
   Cardboard figures have adventures in Africa. Oscar winner Kim
Basinger stars as real-life woman Kuki Gallmann, who up and moves
her family from Italy to the Dark Continent because, as she tells
her son, ``I've stopped growing.'' Directed by one-hit wonder Hugh
Hudson (``Chariots of Fire''), the moviom, made with enough polish
to be a guilty pleasure. Natalie Portman plays the pregnant teen
who heads for California and winds up becoming the Wal-Mart Mom in
Oklahoma. She gets good support from Stockard Channing, Ashley Judd
and Sally Field. (SM) 2 hours. C+
</P>
<P>
   Eleanor Ringel Gillespie, Steve Murray and Bob Longino writes
for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
