<HEADER>
A1766 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-SALTER-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      06-01 0730
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SALTER-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     THE LASTING ART OF DONG KINGMAN 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     Commentary  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By STEPHANIE SALTER  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Because he was 89 years old and had not lived in
the Bay Area for at least a couple of generations, Dong Kingman
died last month with minimal notice in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   As befits an artist, however, his work _ spirited, evocative,
happy watercolors _ ensures that the essence of the man will
command attention for centuries.
</P>
<P>
   Born in Oakland five years after the great earthquake and fire
of 1906, Kingman was a marvelous mix of Asia and America. His
parents were Chinese immigrants who settled in the Bay Area but
moved back to Hong Kong to educate their children.
</P>
<P>
   Until he returned as an adult to the United States during the
Depression, Kingman studied Asian and European painting in China,
as well as calligraphy and architectural drawing.
</P>
<P>
   Each discipline is evident in his many works _ mostly vignettes
of city streets, parks, skylines and water vistas. Also apparent in
his paintings and sketches is nothing less than his outlook on
life.
</P>
<P>
   As the late San Francisco Chronicle columnist Herb Caen once
wrote, ``The wonderful world of Kingman . . . a happy world of
bright scenes and hopeful people.''
</P>
<P>
   Such an attitude, said Caen, was Kingman ``only being true to
himself, for Dong is one of the happiest people I know.''
</P>
<P>
   Friends since Kingman's first one-man show in 1933, Caen and the
artist joined forces in 1967 to produce a beautiful book called
``City on Golden Hills'' (Doubleday). It contains some of the
newspaperman's finest, most poignant love letters to San Francisco
and print after print of Kingman's visual valentines to a city he
never stopped admiring.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is entirely appropriate that Dong Kingman should be my
collaborator on this book,'' wrote Caen, ``for San Francisco _ the
city of his heart and mine _ has been spiced and enriched by the
strong flavor of China ever since it came of age as a world
metropolis.''
</P>
<P>
   As was often Kingman's custom, many of the illustrations in
``City on Golden Hills'' are peeks and glimpses of well-known San
Francisco landmarks from almost secret or insider perspectives:
</P>
<P>
   _ The tip of a tower of the Bay Bridge, tucked behind the heavy
black lattice ironwork of the Third Street truncheon drawbridge.
</P>
<P>
   _ Old St. Mary's Church through the tree branches that line
narrow little Quincy Street off California Street.
</P>
<P>
   _ Coit Tower, tiny and toy-like, from beneath the massive
concrete decks of the (now-demolished) Embarcadero Freeway.
</P>
<P>
   As Caen wrote of Kingman in his afterword to their book:
</P>
<P>
   ``In the 30 years that we have been friends, I have never seen
him without his large notebook and India ink pen . . . he is
constantly sketching, sketching, sketching _ in lightning shorthand
strokes that capture a landscape, a line, a likeness in a flash, a
hidden corner that is suddenly illuminated and captured by the
eternal freshness of his vision.''
</P>
<P>
   According to the New York Times, Kingman's original ambition was
to be a film director. The closest he came was in the early 1960s
when he painted scenes for three Asian-themed American films, ``55
Days at Peking,'' ``The World of Suzie Wong'' and _ perhaps his
loveliest _ ``Flower Drum Song,'' which was set in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Twice a Guggenheim Award winner, Kingman taught art at Columbia
University and Hunter College, among other schools. He traveled the
world, painting its cities and its people.
</P>
<P>
   His works are included in the collections of every major New
York museum as well as the San Francisco Museum of Modern Art and
the de Young Museum.
</P>
<P>
   Although Kingman lived most of his adult years in Manhattan, he
never disconnected from the city of his youth, the city on the
eastern edge of the Pacific Rim.
</P>
<P>
   As Caen told it:
</P>
<P>
   ``Shortly after he moved to New York, I visited him at his
studio, where I found him by a window, painting a row of trees.
Looking out the window and seeing only rooftops, I asked, `Where do
you see those trees?'
</P>
<P>
   ```In Portsmouth Square in San Francisco,' he said, grinning.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stephanie Salter is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. Her electronic mail address
is salter(at)examiner.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-01-00 1229EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
