<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Southern happenings
 &HT;    By Paula Crouch Thrasher
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QR;  Jekyll Island, Ga. _ The 10th annual Country by the Sea Music
Festival on Friday and Saturday welcomes George Jones, Mark Wills
and other artists performing at the South's longest-running
beachside country music festival.
</P>
<P>
   1-877-453-5955, www.jekyllisland.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Pensacola, Fla. _ The 51st annual Fiesta of Five Flags,
Saturday through June 18, features parades, treasure hunts, a
Spanish tall ship, boat parade and children's activities.
850-433-6512, www.fiestafiveflags.org.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Fort Walton Beach, Fla. _ The Billy Bowlegs Pirate Festival,
Sunday through June 11, includes fireworks, parade and treasure
hunts. 850-244-8191.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Miami _ The Bahamas Goombay Festival on Friday through Sunday
transforms Coconut Grove into Nassau's Bay Street. Features arts,
crafts and food. 305-567-1399.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Chattahoochee, Fla. _ The APR Powerboat Superleague presents
the Chattahoochee Challenge: Thunder on the Water powerboat race
Saturday and Sunday. The close-to-shore course will be a one-mile
rectangle formed on the Apalachicola River, where boats moving up
to 100 mph will display turning and cornering maneuvers.
850-627-6558; www.thunderonthewater.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  St. Augustine, Fla. _ Beach Bash 2000 on Saturday features a
scavenger hunt, nature walks and sand castle competition. Anastasia
State Recreation Area. 904-461-2000.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Jacksonville _ Fiesta Playera on Friday through June 17
showcases the traditions of Hispanic Americans. Featuring music and
cuisine from Colombia, Cuba, Jamaica and Puerto Rico.
1-877-423-4378.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Myrtle Beach, S.C. _ The 49th annual Sun Fun Festival _ A
Celebration of Summer is Friday through Monday. Beach games,
sporting events, jazz concerts in the park, parade, air show and
the Miss Bikini Wahine contest. 843-626-7444,
www.myrtlebeachlive.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  New Orleans _ The New Orleans Museum of Art opens ``Half Past
Autumn: The Art of Gordon Parks'' on Saturday. The show is a
retrospective of the American photographer. Through Aug. 27.
504-488-2631.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Roanoke, Va. _ Roanoke Festival in the Park continues through
Sunday. The children's area offers 30 activities, and teens can get
glamour makeovers. Choose from four stages of performing arts,
seven sporting events and car shows. 540-342-2640,
</P>
<P>
   www.rev.net/festival.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Macon, Ga. _ ``Mysteries of Egypt'' continues through July 9
at the Museum of Arts and Sciences with a collection of 300
artifacts. Visitors will learn about King Tutankhamen's tomb, how
the Pyramids were built and view Egyptian mummies. 912-477-3232;
www.masmacon.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Georgiana, Ala. _ Musical festivities Friday and Saturday
honor native son Hank Williams. Also, arts and crafts and food
vendors. 334-376-2396.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Florence, Ala. _ Pope's Tavern hosts the annual Frontier Days,
a lineup of living history displays, crafts and tours of the museum
on Friday and Saturday. 1-888-356-8687.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Chattanooga _ Riverbend Festival 2000, June 9-17, features
Jethro Tull, Chicago and Alabama; river cruises, sporting events,
fireworks, fine arts exhibits. 423-756-2211,
www.riverbendfestival.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Montgomery _ The Montgomery Museum of Fine Arts has two
exhibitions: ``Alabama Art 2000,'' through June 18, featuring the
work of 13 of the state's most accomplished visual artists,
including William Christenberry, Jimmy Lee Sudduth, Mose Tolliver
and Kathryn Tucker Windham; and ``Picasso: 25 Years of Edition
Ceramics From the Edward &AMP; Ann Weston Collection,'' through Aug.
13, featuring 65 ceramic plates, bowls, vases, pitchers and
plaques. 334-244-5700, www.fineartsmuseum.com
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Raleigh _ ``Rodin: Sculpture From the Iris and B. Gerald
Cantor Collection and Additional Works'' is on display at the North
Carolina Museum of Art through Aug. 13. Included among the more
than 120 works in bronze, marble, plaster and terra cotta, are
``The Kiss,'' ``The Thinker'' and ``The Hand of God.'' Tickets:
919-834-4000, www.tickemaster.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Jekyll Island, Ga. _ Jekyll Island Music Theatre Festival,
Friday-July 29, features professional actors and students from
Valdosta State University's theater department performing ``Always
... Patsy Cline,'' ``She Loves Me'' and ``Carousel'' at the Jekyll
Island Amphitheater. 1-877-453-5955, www.jekyllisland.com.
</P>
<P>
   _Paula Crouch Thrasher writes for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
