<SLUG> BC-FBN-STEVE-YOUNG-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     DECISION ON 49ERS QB EXPECTED IN WEEK 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JOHN CRUMPACKER  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA CLARA, Calif. _ San Francisco 49ers coach Steve Mariucci
expects the team's injured quarterback to make a decision on his
playing future by June 10, a decision that would end months of
speculation since a concussion sidelined Steve Young.
</P>
<P>
   Mariucci and Young spoke Tuesday night and the quarterback asked
for a little more time to make his momentous decision. A decision
had been expected this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's going to be out of town and will be back next week,''
Mariucci said Wednesday as the 49ers held a minicamp for rookies
and selected veterans.
</P>
<P>
   ``He would like to get it over with. We all would,'' Mariucci
said.
</P>
<P>
   It has been 249 days since he suffered the concussion that
knocked him out of the final 13 games of the 1999 season and put
his career in peril.
</P>
<P>
   According to Mariucci, the issue with Young now is not medical
or financial. It's strictly football: Does he want to play again?
Young has passed a battery of neurological tests and has
essentially been cleared to play again if he so desires.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has taken various tests and clinically, he's normal,''
Mariucci said. ``If we can consider Steve Young normal, he's
normal. He passed all the tests with flying colors.''
</P>
<P>
   When the coach spoke to his 38-year-old quarterback before he
left on a trip, the two discussed Eric Lindros, the Philadelphia
Flyers' hockey star who returned to the game after a lengthy
concussion-induced layoff only to pick up another concussion on a
jarring hit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, he feels for Eric. We all wish him well,'' Mariucci
said. ``Every situation is independent and different. How that is
related to Steve, no one knows. Steve has to make the decision
based on his own information.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know as much as we can know about the risks and Steve's
willingness to continue to play. It's going to be up to Steve.''
</P>
<P>
   With a new wife who is pregnant, Young may not want to risk his
health by continuing to play. And the 49ers seem ready to move on
without him. Jeff Garcia is the starting quarterback until further
notice and rookies Giovanni Carmazzi and Tim Rattay are getting
practice time behind him as talk of signing career washout Rick
Mirer has cooled.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to revisit that,'' which is Mariucci's way of saying
Mirer will probably not be signed. ``We've been so consumed with
Steve's condition we haven't discussed that. We could make the
decision to go with these three men.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
