u w BC-CONLEY-SPELLING-HNS &LR;      06-01 0457
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONLEY-SPELLING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     SEAN CONLEY CRUISES THROUGH FINAL ROUNDS OF SPELLING BEE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JUDY HOLLAND  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Sean Conley, a slender 12-year-old from Newark,
Calif., confidently cruised through two more rounds of increasingly
tougher words Thursday, the final day of the 73rd National Spelling
Bee. He correctly spelled Mackinaw and ferriferous.
</P>
<P>
   Sean, who is sponsored by the San Francisco Examiner, took
several deep breaths and rocked from side to side before the word
pronouncer issued his first challenge: Mackinaw, which is a short,
belted coat of heavy fabric.
</P>
<P>
   As he did Wednesday when he survived the first three rounds of
the bee, Sean asked that the word be repeated a few times for
alternate pronunciations. Then he asked its origin and its use in a
sentence before acing its spelling. He was among 110 spellers who
remained of the original 248 who competed Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   After the fourth round, the home-schooled seventh grader stepped
down from the stage to stretch his legs during a break and appeared
calm and confident.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fourth round is usually pretty hard, but this was
easier,'' he said, adding that he knew the words his competitors
had been asked earlier in the round _ ``all except for a couple.''
</P>
<P>
   Sean said he kept quizzing the pronouncer about Mackinaw ``to
make sure I'm hearing it right and to give me some time to think
about it.''
</P>
<P>
   The technique worked for him Wednesday when he successfully
knocked off nyctalopia, or the inability to see at twilight;
discomfiture, which means frustration or confusion, and floppety,
which means soft and flexible.
</P>
<P>
   After the fourth round, the number of spellers had dwindled to
64, with the losers being ushered to the so-called ``comfort room''
to regain their composure after hearing the tinny bell that signals
a mistake.
</P>
<P>
   Sean's mother Bry, who teaches him at home, scurried to the
aisle to remind him to tuck his shirt in, gave him the old theater
morale-booster, ``break a leg,'' and then added, ``Or, break a
tongue.''
</P>
<P>
   In the fifth round, Sean tackled ferriferous, which means
containing iron, This time he barely hesitated before nailing that
word too.
</P>
<P>
   Sean's father Mike was sitting in the back row at the crowded
auditorium of the Grand Hyatt Hotel here where the bee was held. He
said he was ``just trying to remain calm.''
</P>
<P>
   The final day is more of a nail-biter, he said, because his son
actually has a chance to better his ninth-place tie in the national
bee last year.
</P>
<P>
   The bee is sponsored by E.W. Scripps Co.
</P>
<P>
   (Judy Holland can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address judy &LR; hearstdc.com).
</P>
</TEXT>
