<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 13:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1792 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r d BC-BOURBON-RULES-HNS &LR;      06-01 0570
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOURBON-RULES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     BOURBON MAKERS GO STRICTLY BY THE BOOK 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JOHN GRIFFIN  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Rules, rules, rules: They are everywhere, even
in the distillery. It may come as a surprise just how strict the
rules governing bourbon are. They date to the 19th century and are
fairly inflexible.
</P>
<P>
   Bourbon must be made from at least 51 percent corn, though most
distillers use more than 65 percent. It cannot be more than 160
proof. It must be aged for at least two years in a new, white oak
barrel that has been charred. (Note the word ``new.'' No barrel can
be used twice.) Nothing can be added at bottling to enhance flavor
or add sweetness or color.
</P>
<P>
   Bourbon, by classification, also must be made in the United
States, in the same way scotch must be distilled in Scotland or
Irish Whisky in Ireland. Almost all bourbons are distilled in
Kentucky (which is where the white oak grows), with Virginia
Gentleman being among the very few exceptions. (Jack Daniel's, a
Tennessee whiskey, is charcoal filtered and, therefore, doesn't
qualify.)
</P>
<P>
   A few of the myths and mandates that go into making Kentucky's
favorite spirit were offered to a rapt crowd of cigar smokers
during the recent Texas Hill Country Wine and Food Festival by
David Pickerell, vice president of production at the venerated
Maker's Mark Distillery.
</P>
<P>
   Over sips of the liquor at various stages of the aging process,
Pickerell told one of the more popular legends surrounding the
birth of bourbon. Some have traced its origins to a Southern
Baptist minister named the Rev. Elijah Craig, who charred out a
white oak barrel as a means of ridding it of a fish odor. True or
not, the irony involved in the story has kept it in circulation for
many years.
</P>
<P>
   Few dispute the origin of the name, which came from Bourbon
County, Ky., where most of the distillation occurred. That can be
traced back further to the Bourbon dynasty in France. (Francophiles
were in abundance in Kentucky's pioneer days, as can be seen in the
names of the cities Louisville and Versailles.)
</P>
<P>
   By 1810, there were 2,000 registered distillers, Pickerell said.
Of that lot, Maker's Mark is the only one still in production. It
survived Prohibition and is going strong today, despite competition
from other premium bourbons such as Booker's and Knob Creek.
</P>
<P>
   ``The demand for Maker's Mark this year is going to be higher
than what we can produce,'' Pickerell said.
</P>
<P>
   The recipe for what is currently distilled, developed by Bill
Samuels, has not been altered since it was introduced in 1958.
Samuels' set of rules insisted on iron-free limestone spring water
as well as red winter wheat instead of rye. The grains are still
crushed with an antique rollermill because it won't scorch the
grain like modern milling machines. To create its velvety taste,
each wooden barrel stave must be air dried outdoors for nine
months.
</P>
<P>
   The early response was a bit different from what bourbon
drinkers think today, Pickerell said, relating a story of how
displeased another famous Kentucky distiller, Jim Beam, was when he
first tried it.
</P>
<P>
   He apparently told Samuels, ``Who wants a sissy whiskey
anyway?''
</P>
<P>
   True or not, it's another choice footnote in bourbon's flavorful
story.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (John Griffin can be reached by e-mail at
jgriffin(at)express-news.net)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
