<HEADER>
A1793 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r d BC-MEAT-GRINDER-HNS &LR;      06-01 0272
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEAT-GRINDER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     TAKE A BREAK FROM THE DAILY GRIND 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By RALPH WININGHAM  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ Having access to an electric meat grinder has
really been a big help in allowing me to try different game recipes
that feature ground meat, stew meat and other creations.
</P>
<P>
   While the hand-cranked grinders like the one passed down by my
wife's grandmother can be used, a three-quarter horse power motor
working for you is a real time saver.
</P>
<P>
   I use the grinder for making sausage, both patties and link, in
addition to grinding all the venison I use for hamburgers, chili
and such. The grinder also comes in handy when meats are on sale,
allowing for inexpensive packages of ground beef or pork.
</P>
<P>
   In the following recipe, I like to grind the onion with the meat
to make a fine meatloaf mixture. No fuss, no muss and no tears.
</P>
<P>
   This makes great sandwiches or can be served as a main dish with
heated tomato sauce on the side.
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   LEAN, MEAN MEATLOAF
</P>
<P>
   2 pounds venison steaks
</P>
<P>
   1 small onion
</P>
<P>
   2 tbsp bacon grease (optional)
</P>
<P>
   2 eggs
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup bread crumbs
</P>
<P>
   2 tbsp Worcestershire sauce
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup catsup
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup Kraft Parm Plus
</P>
<P>
   1/2 tsp garlic salt
</P>
<P>
   salt and black pepper, to taste
</P>
<P>
   Grind steaks and onion together in a meat grinder, using the
fine-grind blade. Place meat in a large bowl and add remaining
ingredients (I add the bacon grease for flavor and because the meat
is very lean). Mix well. Shape into a large loaf, place into a
greased pan and bake at 350 degrees for 1 hour.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-01-00 1318EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000601.0118 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 13:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1794 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-OPERA-GILFREY-LADN &LR;      06-01 0877
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OPERA-GILFREY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SO LONG, `BILLY BUDD`?
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Fact box below; `tonight' refers to Sat., June 3) 
By REED JOHNSON 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
Rodney Gilfry feels downcast whenever he thinks about playing Billy
Budd for the last time.
</P>
<P>
   So do thousands of opera fans from Dallas to Geneva who've seen
the L.A. baritone's virile, magnetic portrayal of the doomed,
heroic young sailor in Benjamin Britten's 1951 work.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hate to say it, but I'm not the spring chicken I was,''
Gilfry, 41, responds when asked if this month's performance for the
Los Angeles Opera might be his final ``Billy Budd.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, within a few seconds, Gilfry has talked himself out of
this apparently unthinkable notion.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a role that I love very much,'' Gilfry says resolutely,
``and I really don't want to give it up. And I don't want to see
any reason that I should.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, why should he? True, Billy Budd, the handsome,
stammering British seaman who runs afoul of the evil master-at-arms
Claggart, is barely into his 20s. As described by Herman Melville
in his 1891 maritime parable, which inspired Britten and his
librettist E.M. Forster, Billy Budd is a true innocent swimming
among sharks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Billy has a kind of outer strength but an inner-childness, and
he's naive,'' Gilfry says. ``He knows no evil. He has a pure
spirituality that's practically untainted.''
</P>
<P>
   The Covina-born Gilfry, on the other hand, is a worldly, savvy
professional and married father of three, a middle-aged,
middle-class suburbanite who now makes his home in Rancho Cucamonga
when he's not jetting off to the world's leading opera houses.
</P>
<P>
   But with his blond California good looks, strong acting skills
and an Olympian's physique that gets mentioned every time he's
interviewed, Gilfry is still strong enough of body and voice to
satisfy most any opera buff's vision of budding Billy.
</P>
<P>
   As proved by his hunky portrayal of Stanley Kowalski in last
September's San Francisco Opera world premiere of Andre Previn's
``A Streetcar Named Desire,'' Gilfry has the physical goods to keep
playing Billy Budd. As Los Angeles Opera founding general director
Peter Hemmings points on, Gilfry certainly wouldn't be the first
baritone to sing the role into his mature years.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is essentially a young man's part, obviously,'' Hemmings
says. ``Rod himself says that he's 41 and the part's a 21-year-old.
But that convention is not unusual in the cinema, is it?''
</P>
<P>
   Director Francesca Zambello's production of ``Billy Budd''
arrives in L.A. after premiering in Geneva in 1994. It was later
staged at Britain's Royal Opera House, Covent Garden. With an
all-male cast that also features bass Jeffrey Wells as Claggart,
and tenor Robert Tear as the wise but wavering Captain Vere, the
production is a scaled-down replica of the Geneva version.
</P>
<P>
   ``This production is a very physical production in the sense
that there's a lot of guys on stage shirtless, there's a lot of
sweat,'' Gilfry says. ``It's not the buttoned-up military type
production where everyone's in authentic-looking 18th-century
military-looking costumes and there's a decorum of dress that's
followed on the set. It's much more impressionistic.''
</P>
<P>
   Gilfry will be playing another character with the initials B.B.
this summer. He'll co-star as Billy Bigelow in a semi-staged
production of Rodgers and Hammerstein's ``Carousel'' at the
Hollywood Bowl on Au. 13.
</P>
<P>
   ``Billy Budd'' will mark the close of Hemmings' 16-year helming
of Los Angeles Opera; he's retiring this summer to return with his
wife to the couple's native England.
</P>
<P>
   Hemmings had been wanting to bring ``Billy Budd'' to Los Angeles
for at least a half-dozen years, but unforeseen events like the
1994 Northridge earthquake intervened.
</P>
<P>
   Having launched his professional career with L.A. Opera _ he had
a one-line role as a herald opposite Placido Domingo in ``Otello''
_ Gilfry is a longtime hometown favorite. Though he has sung 23
different roles in his career, including the title character in
``Don Giovanni,'' Figaro in ``Il barbiere di Siviglia'' and Belcore
in ``L'elisir d'amore,'' Gilfry was glad for the chance to finally
perform his signature part at the Dorothy Chandler.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am home at least half of the year, which has only been made
possible because the Los Angeles Opera is willing to hire me a
couple times a year and leaving me in the very enviable position of
having a thriving international career and still be home,'' he
says. ``As a father, I can tell you it's still too much time
away.''
</P>
<P>
   So, seriously now, how long will he keep playing Billy Budd?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll be very arrogant and presumptuous to the extent that ...
I would want someone who was doing the role to audition for me, so
I could say, `You've got the right idea' or, `You haven't got the
right idea.' I'm so happy to do that, because it's my chance to
save the role once again from being mistreated.''
</P>
<P>
   _____ &QL; 
What:``Billy Budd.'' &QL; 
Where: Los Angeles Opera at the Dorothy Chandler Pavilion,
Performing Arts Center of Los Angeles County, 135 N. Grand Ave. &QL; 
When: 7:30 tonight and June 6, 9, 11, 14; 2 p.m. June 17. &QL; 
Tickets: $27-$146. Call (213) 365-3500. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
