<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 13:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1810 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e BC-TV-SURVIVOR-HNS &LR;      06-01 0745
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SURVIVOR-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     A `MILLIONAIRE' WITH AN ADRENALINE RUSH 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By TIM GOODMAN  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   With one episode of the massively hyped summer series
``Survivor'' in the can, we can safely assume that those who
watched this reality-voyeur series about 16 castaways on an island
off Borneo will be back again and again.
</P>
<P>
   If CBS got any kind of ratings at all Wednesday night for its
``Lord of the Flies'' meets ``The Real World'' epic, then expect a
kind of mini-``Who Wants To Be A Millionaire'' to sweep away the
summer programming doldrums.
</P>
<P>
   This is the right kind of game show. You can still win a million
dollars _ the ultimate prize to the last castaway standing _ but
you have to eat rats and fight snakes to do it, not use a lifeline
to guess if the right color for a pumpkin is orange. Have a seat,
Regis.
</P>
<P>
   ``Survivor'' is an imported idea that feels American, what with
the action, anger and adrenaline. The series runs for 13-episodes
so either somebody dies or more than one gets the boot, or leaves
voluntarily.
</P>
<P>
   The lure of ``Survivor'' is simple: You get to sit on your couch
while a bunch of thrown-together strangers try and get along,
failing miserably and making great TV of it.
</P>
<P>
   The rules are pretty basic. Sixteen people who met for the first
time four hours earlier are put on a boat in the South China Sea,
heading for the tiny jungle island of Pulau Tiga. Well short of the
coast, they are divided into teams of eight and given two minutes
to get as much stuff off the main vessel and onto bamboo rafts as
possible.
</P>
<P>
   One team made it to the island in two hours, the other in three.
After brief hugging and exhausted high-fives, they began getting
snippy with each other. Chemistry is key in a series like this. And
``Survivor'' looks prone to explosions.
</P>
<P>
   The teams are given names that correspond to their beach areas
on the island: The Tagi Tribe and the Pagong Tribe. They will be on
the island for 39 days. They will have to work together, band
together, then work against one another when the voting comes. It
was clear in about two minutes on Wednesday that the Tagi Tribe was
set to re-enact ``Lord of the Flies'' while the Pagong Tribe at
least had a semblance of bonding.
</P>
<P>
   Just like ``Real World,'' viewers may find that opinions about
some castaways change each week, sometimes every few minutes. The
beauty of the show is that Sonja, an elderly woman who was the
first to leave the island, was sweet. You'd much rather have tossed
out Richard, a kind of pouty corporate trainer, or maybe Rudy, the
overzealous 72-year-old former Navy SEAL who still looks like he
can whip your hide.
</P>
<P>
   Each weekly episode encapsulates three days on the island. We
see a lot of foraging, a good bit of lounging around, some
ingenuity (the Pagong Tribe started a fire quickly), a boat load of
jealousy, snappy judgments and, ultimately, the beginning of a
little fear. There are snakes. Spiders. Rats. And not a lot of
food. You can tell that as the weak and the annoying are winnowed
out, it's going to get pretty ugly.
</P>
<P>
   Ah, but that's the beauty of a dumb show like this. We don't
want people sitting around camp fires hugging each other. We want
``Gilligan's Island'' on crack.
</P>
<P>
   ``Survivor'' works brilliantly as drama because the viewer has a
rooting interest in who stays or goes. CBS tosses in games each
episode, pitting the two teams against each other for goods (like
matches, or chocolate) and some coveted immunity (you get to stay
another night on the island).
</P>
<P>
   The setup is kind of hokey, but what do you expect? This is
staged reality. People are interviewed anonymously. The action is
sometimes narrated by the host, Jeff Probst, and some elements are
way over the top (elaborate huts with fire, ominous sayings like
``The tribe has spoken'' and so on).
</P>
<P>
   It will be interesting to see how this plays out with Middle
America. ``Survivor'' could be a huge hit. Remember, most people
don't watch MTV and ``The Real World.'' This reality-voyeur stuff
could prove addictive to them (and there's plenty more coming down
the pipe).
</P>
<P>
   ``Survivor'' certainly makes for better work banter than talking
about ``Friends'' or ``Felicity.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Tim Goodman is the television critic for the San Francisco
Examiner, P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. His electronic
mail address is goodman(at)examiner.com).
</P>
</TEXT>
