<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 13:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1814 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-CHINA-EVICTIONS-$ADV0     06-01 1389
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-EVICTIONS-$ADV04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BEIJING'S OLD CITY RESIDENTS HAVING TO MAKE ROOM FOR NEW
DEVELOPMENT
 &HT;    (1000&AMP;ADDS)
 &HT;    With Photos.
 &HT;    For Use Sun., June 4 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By JULIE CHAO 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ Zhao Zhifeng and her extended family had lived in
their modest one-story house all their lives. In fact, they'd owned
it going back 200 years. But in China, although you can own
buildings, you can never own the land.
</P>
<P>
   So one morning in March, about 30 men showed up with two
bulldozers, she recalls with a mixture of anger and distress, and
turned most of her home to rubble. The land rights had been sold to
developers, and her house was in the way of whatever it is they're
planning _ an office or apartment complex, she still doesn't know.
</P>
<P>
   Now living in the remaining half of the house, Zhao and her
family refuse to go.
</P>
<P>
   All across the city center, re-development has leveled
neighborhoods and destroyed the den of alleys and courtyard houses
that typify old Beijing. In their place have appeared gaudy
shopping malls and undistinguished commercial buildings.
</P>
<P>
   An unusually critical commentary in the Beijing Evening News, a
daily newspaper here, decried the new structures as ``architectural
garbage, the ugliest acne on the face of the ancient capital.''
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, as this city of 14 million tries to remake itself into
a 21st Century metropolis, as bicycles and horse-drawn carts get
squeezed out by the increasingly ubiquitous automobile and
high-rises seem to go up overnight, it's not just regard for
aesthetics that has been lost.
</P>
<P>
   The human cost of ``modernization'' has not come cheap.
Complaints about forced and _ in the case of Zhao _ illegal
demolitions have been soaring as developers race to put up
commercial space and bring in profits.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of letters and lawsuits over the years has culminated
in what may be the largest citizen action in the Communist country
in years: a petition signed by more than 10,000 people was
delivered to the central government in March demanding proper
compensation for being evicted and an investigation into what the
petitioners believe is massive corruption.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the staggering pace of urban renewal is only
accelerating. More than 1 million people, or 220,000 households,
have been displaced since the early 1990s, when Beijing opened up
the real estate market for the first time in 40 years.
</P>
<P>
   About 1.6 square miles of housing was demolished between 1990
and 1998. According to the Beijing Morning Post, this year will
break all records, with another 1 square mile of land to be
re-developed, partly for commercial development, partly for road
expansion to ease the ever-worsening traffic.
</P>
<P>
   The government has made some efforts at preservation. Last year,
it designated 25 historic zones in the city center for protection,
but together they comprise less than two square miles. Many
architects believe that is not enough.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Begin optional trim.)
</P>
<P>
   Some say the architectural splendor of old Beijing started
waning when the Communists came to power in 1949 and declared the
ancient city walls remnants of the feudal society. So they tore
down the walls and old watchtowers to make way for the Second Ring
Road, now a clogged six-lane highway. Beijing natives still recall
the walls fondly as the epitome of the old city.
</P>
<P>
   Over the next several decades, as Beijing industrialized,
housing became congested; buildings crumbled.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: End optional trim.)
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to generate revenue to improve living conditions,
the government opened the real estate market in the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time in communist China, private developers could
get the rights to a piece of land, then profit after resettling
evicted households and building an office tower, hotel or shopping
center. Many residents were happy to be moved out of their old
houses _ most with no heating or indoor toilets _ and be given some
cash and a modern new apartment to rent in the suburbs.
</P>
<P>
   But architects have become alarmed at the thoughtlessness of the
development.
</P>
<P>
   ``To renovate you need investment. With investment you need
returns. So they build bigger and bigger buildings with more and
more volume,'' Jiang Zhongguang, professor at the Beijing Institute
of Civil Engineering and Architecture, said in an interview with
Cox Newspapers. ``From the standpoint of economic efficiency, this
is what is needed. But from a city preservation standpoint, we
can't continue like this.''
</P>
<P>
   More than 10 standing committee members of the National People's
Congress _ China's parliament _ presented a letter last year to
central party leaders appealing for an investigation into
violations of relics laws, not only in Beijing but also in other
cities experiencing a similar scale of demolition.
</P>
<P>
   Zhao's house was no architectural treasure. But it had been in
the family for seven generations. With half of it now in a pile of
concrete, she and her family squeezed into the part of the house
still standing and are refusing to go while all her neighbors have
moved away.
</P>
<P>
   She wrote to numerous government agencies appealing for monetary
damages and the right to hold a march to protest what her lawyer
says was an illegal demolition.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't even begin to talk about human rights,'' said Zhao,
52. ``They violated our right to live. How can we live without a
house?''
</P>
<P>
   She believes corruption of local authorities was behind her
case. She is not alone.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of ordinary citizens have written the central
government alleging collusion between land officials and developers
to pocket part of the resettlement fees. Evicted residents have
also filed hundreds of lawsuits in the last five years demanding
due compensation.
</P>
<P>
   With no response to their letters and no court willing to hear a
case, 10,357 people petitioned Beijing's Number Two Intermediate
People's Court in February to investigate possible corruption and
violations of property rights. They sent the petition to the State
Council, China's Cabinet, and other central government agencies in
March after the court did not respond.
</P>
<P>
   One of the signatories was Zhao Jingxin (no relation to Zhao
Zhifeng). But he is no ordinary Beijing resident.
</P>
<P>
   For two years, the 82-year-old retired professor has resisted
eviction notices, insisting that his beautifully preserved,
17th-Century courtyard house is a city treasure that must be
protected.
</P>
<P>
   His father bought the house in 1950, a year after the communist
revolution, as a show of patriotism and faith in the new
government. But now the land his house sits on is wanted for a
shopping center.
</P>
<P>
   Beijing's top academics and architects have rallied around his
cause. Even U.S. Ambassador Joseph Prueher recently paid a visit to
Zhao's house, taking in the rose bushes and intricate wood
carvings.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Begin optional trim)
</P>
<P>
   Scholars have pointed out the irony of the government spending
millions of dollars to renovate Ping An Avenue a couple of years
ago in Ming and Qing Dynasty styles _ with an outcome that has been
almost universally ridiculed by locals as fake-looking _ while just
a few yards away, an authentic Ming Dynasty house is slated for
demolition.
</P>
<P>
   Zhao's lawyer, Wu Jianzhong, believes that were Beijing to be
awarded the 2008 Olympics, something the government desperately
hopes to win, it could be disastrous for preservation if public
projects are undertaken too hastily.
</P>
<P>
   ``They'll widen the streets and demolish a lot of houses,'' Wu
said. ``With the people all supporting the Olympics, this gives
officials an even bigger excuse to tear everything down.''
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: End optional trim.)
</P>
<P>
   Zhao Jingxin said there is plenty of room outside of Beijing's
old city center for commercial development and other projects.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's only one Beijing in the world,'' Zhao said. ``Fifty
years ago, we tore down the city walls. Now we regret it. If we
continue to demolish the courtyard homes, in 20 or 30 years, it
will be too late. We can't rebuild them.''
</P>
<P>
   (Julie Chao's E-mail address is: juliec(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   For more news from China, go to:
</P>
<P>
   http://headlines.yahoo.com/FullCoverage/World/China/
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
