<SLUG> BC-CAREERS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     E-ETIQUETTE FOR THE WORKPLACE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By DAVE MURPHY  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ One computer program for handling e-mail is
called Eudora. But there really ought to be a program called
Pandora, because the clumsy use of e-mail can open a world of
trouble for workers.
</P>
<P>
   First, consider a few results from a recent nationwide survey of
1,004 employees by Vault.com, an Internet career site:
</P>
<P>
   _ Although 70 percent of employees believe that e-mail improves
communication with their bosses, 51 percent say their tone is
sometimes misinterpreted as angry, abrupt or overly casual.
</P>
<P>
   _ About five out of six respondents regularly delete their
e-mails, and only one out of seven admit to forwarding sexually
explicit or otherwise improper e-mails to friends and co-workers.
</P>
<P>
   _ Although 58 percent said they are not worried about employers
monitoring their e-mail use, 79 percent keep a separate account for
personal e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   _ Eighty percent say that for the majority of their business
correspondence, e-mail has replaced traditional mail, 72 percent
say it has replaced faxing and 45 percent say it has replaced phone
calls.
</P>
<P>
   So what should you do to make better use of your e-mail? Here
are three suggestions (from me, not Vault):
</P>
<P>
   _ Choose your words carefully.
</P>
<P>
   I know this should fit in to the ``duh'' category, but a lot of
smart people make dumb mistakes when it comes to e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   Unless you're sure that it's all right to be informal, you can
come across as a dolt if you misspell words and write the whole
thing as one run-on sentence. If you're joking and it's not obvious
that you're joking, don't joke. The payoff just isn't worth the
risk.
</P>
<P>
   Never say something in an e-mail (or voicemail) that you
wouldn't say to the person's face. E-mail makes it easy for you to
spoil a relationship in a few words. Before you send it, think
about how you would feel if you were the recipient instead of the
sender.
</P>
<P>
   Because busy people get dozens of e-mails a day, make your
subject heading as informative as possible. If you get cute or
vague, the person is liable to think it's junk mail and just trash
it.
</P>
<P>
   &Cx1f; _ Assume that someone is looking over your shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   Even if you have a separate account, don't have anything pop up
on your office computer that you might get you fired.
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't mean you should never use an office computer for
personal use. In these days of 60-hour workweeks, sometimes using
the office computer for a few personal items is only common sense.
If your employer is obnoxious about it, find a different employer.
</P>
<P>
   The same applies to joking back and forth with co-workers via
e-mail. A good boss wouldn't object, as long as you're not
offending anyone or wasting a lot of time. It's all a matter of
being reasonable.
</P>
<P>
   But using the office computer for job hunting is just plain
stupid. Ditto with pornography. You might as well attach a ``kick
me'' sign to your own butt.
</P>
<P>
   _ E-mail is a wonderful tool, if you use it wonderfully.
</P>
<P>
   It can eliminate a lot of meetings and interruptions, letting
people pass along routine information to colleagues and bosses. If
you choose your words carefully, it can also reduce
misunderstandings.
</P>
<P>
   But don't be a slave to your e-mail. Just because someone sends
you something doesn't mean you have to drop everything and read it
instantly. If your company values instant responses, it should have
a separate method for urgent correspondence, either with specially
designated e-mails, pagers or cell phones.
</P>
<P>
   Once you read an e-mail, don't let it linger in your in-box;
soon you'll be scanning through dozens of e-mails to find what you
want. If you need to save it, set up a filing system, just as you
would with paper documents. Have folders for pending items that
need your attention, and other folders for e-mails you just want to
save in case they are ever needed.
</P>
<P>
   If someone sends you an important e-mail, respond to it
promptly, even if it's just a quick note that says, ``Got your
e-mail. I'll look it over as soon as I can.'' That way, people will
know it has been received and not accidentally deleted.
</P>
<P>
   Realize, too, that a lot of e-mails don't disappear just because
you delete them. Companies have backup systems, which is how many
``deleted'' e-mails end up in sexual harassment proceedings and
discrimination lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   Old e-mails never die. They just end up in court.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dave Murphy is the careers editor of the San Francisco
Examiner, P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. His electronic
mail address is murphy(at)examiner.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
