<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-EUROPE-630&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON TELLS BARAK U.S. IS COMMITTED TO MIDDLE EAST PEACE
PROCESS 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: This early version will be updated as needed.) 
 By ELAINE SCIOLINO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LISBON, Portugal _ President Clinton on Thursday called on
Israelis and Palestinians to ``do things that they have not done in
the past'' in an effort to conclude a historic peace agreement
between them. Clinton said the agreement was ``within view now.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking after a meeting with Prime Minister Ehud Barak in this
seaside capital, Clinton also announced that he was sending
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright to the Middle East next week
in an effort to ``work with both leaders on narrowing the gaps''
between them. He said further that he would meet soon with
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   A senior administration official briefing reporters after the
meeting said that Clinton was prepared to convene a three-way Camp
David-style summit meeting in the Washington area with Barak and
Arafat but that much more work has to be done first.
</P>
<P>
   The summit meeting, if held, would be modeled on the 1978
meeting held by President Carter at the Camp David presidential
retreat that pushed Israel and Egypt to conclude their landmark
peace treaty the following year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both leaders know from me and they know from their own
experience,'' Clinton said, ``that they now have to be prepared to
make an intense effort and to do things that they have not done in
the past with real courage and vision if we're actually going to
get a framework that deals with the outstanding issues.''
</P>
<P>
   The president added that he remained convinced that Israel and
the Palestinians would have the ``courage, the vision and the
ability'' to make peace.
</P>
<P>
   ``The United States will do everything we can to help them pass
this milestone,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is tough work,'' he added. ``If it were easy somebody
would have done it a long time ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's remarks underscored his frustration that the two sides
have not made more progress in completing a framework accord to
serve as a blueprint for a final deal in mid-September. The final
agreement will determine the size and shape of a Palestinian
entity, the future of Jerusalem and the fate of about 4 million
Palestinian refugees.
</P>
<P>
   It is clear that Clinton dearly wants to conclude a peace
agreement between Israel and the Palestinians in the last months of
his presidency.
</P>
<P>
   ``The United States will do everything it can to conclude a
historic agreement'' between Israel and the Palestinians, Clinton
said.
</P>
<P>
   Albright will travel to the Middle East directly from Kiev next
Monday, where Clinton will meet Ukrainian leaders before returning
to Washington, the senior administration official said.
</P>
<P>
   The official added that the gaps are still so great that
Albright will probably need to make another trip to the region
before a three-way summit meeting could take place in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The senior administration official confirmed that the United
States has agreed to earmark $50 million of the $1.8 billion of
U.S. military aid budgeted for Israel to shore up Israel's border
with Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   Israel estimates that a new defense line will cost from $300
million to $400 million. The withdrawal last week of Israel's army
from southern Lebanon after 18 years erased a buffer zone that had
shielded northern Israel from attacks by Lebanon across their
common border.
</P>
<P>
   The administration official added that Albright would not stop
in Syria during her visit to the Middle East. Talks between Israel
and Syria collapsed in January and have not resumed despite direct
consultations between Clinton and President Hafez Assad of Syria.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton met with Barak before heading to Germany for the second
leg of a weeklong trip that is scheduled to be his last visit to
Europe as president. He will continue on to Russia and Ukraine
before heading home.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Shortly before Thursday's meeting with Clinton, Barak
underscored the tense atmosphere between the Israelis and
Palestinians. He accused Arafat of stalling in their bilateral
talks, which have been quietly taking place in Stockholm.
</P>
<P>
   ``In recent weeks, we have seen some dragging of feet in regard
to the running of negotiations,'' Barak told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``We are trying to initiate a major move forward.''
That referred both to his talks with Clinton and the meeting
between peace negotiators that is scheduled to resume in Israel and
in Palestinian-run areas on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is very important at this crossroads to move forward with
all force on the framework agreement,'' the Israeli prime minister
said.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Clinton spoke with Arafat by telephone for about
20 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   But Arafat, who recently described the talks with Israel as
deadlocked, was said to be unhappy with ideas proposed by Israel in
Sweden, and he complained of Israeli intransigence.
</P>
<P>
   Nabil Abu Rdaineh, a senior aide to Arafat, told Reuters in
Jerusalem that Arafat had ``informed President Clinton about the
current situation of the peace process, especially the current
stalemate and the deadlock it has reached.''
</P>
</TEXT>
