<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 14:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1828 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-YOUNG-COLUMN02-COX     06-01 0678
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUNG-COLUMN02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Inspired idea for American attractions: ban automobiles
 &HT;    By John Young
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   You could hear the yodeling, as I recall. It wasn't coming from
a mountain top in the Swiss village. It was coming from the radio
in a window.
</P>
<P>
   Had there been yodeling from the mountain that day I visited
Zermatt, I would have heard it, as I could the shuffling of feet,
the wind in trees. What you couldn't hear was automobiles.
</P>
<P>
   The Swiss town at the base of the Matterhorn has no cars, as if
there were any room for them.
</P>
<P>
   You have to park your car down the mountain and take the train.
Electric carts, horse-drawn sleighs and carriages are the only
transport allowed. It makes Zermatt, like Venice, a place where one
wants to be just for the being.
</P>
<P>
   This summer, Zion National Park in Utah takes after Zermatt.
Automobiles are restricted in its most popular section. Park them
at the visitor's center. Take a shuttle. Take a day pack. Enjoy the
ride.
</P>
<P>
   Now the sound of the Virgin River does not compete with
carbon-hoofed horses. Now visitors, 3,000 carloads on a peak day,
do not have to arm-wrestle for the 450 parking spaces at trails and
overlooks.
</P>
<P>
   It was long overdue. Though one of the appealing things about
Zion is the ability to wind down into a steep, red-rock canyon,
there's no reason why visitors should do the driving. The parks
service can do that, freeing other eyes for gawking.
</P>
<P>
   This is a major development that ought to be widespread. Plans
are being formalized to limit access by automobile at Yosemite
National Park and at the south rim of the Grand Canyon.
</P>
<P>
   Good. We've reduced some of our nation's more precious places to
drive-through at the Jack in the Box. All that's missing is the
clown's head.
</P>
<P>
   Putting cars in their place _ namely, in a lot at the visitor's
center _ is the best thing some parks could do. Obviously it's
impossible to ban cars from something as massive as Yellowstone
Park. That means, unfortunately, that despite its grandeur
Yellowstone at times has the feel of a General Motors assembly
line.
</P>
<P>
   With the air pollution problems at the Grand Canyon and in some
of California's scenic gems, reining in automotive traffic makes
more and more sense. But there are many other reasons to take the
Zion route. Chief is that people will enjoy the park more when they
turn off the A/C and the stereo and get out.
</P>
<P>
   They will get smells, sights and sounds they otherwise would
miss.
</P>
<P>
   Pedestrian meccas
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, most of the world's greatest tourist attractions are
those where the car meets its match. Consider New York City. You
bet, people drive in New York, but most quickly find alternatives.
They also quickly find the allure of the sidewalk.
</P>
<P>
   It takes but a day in New York to realize that because so many
are on foot, what you have isn't one massive, suffocating city but
hundreds of little villages in which ``down the block'' is the
chief destination.
</P>
<P>
   By and large the automobile is irrelevant to many New Yorkers.
For one reason, as in Zermatt, as in Zion, where do you park?
</P>
<P>
   There's no reason to carve away at natural treasures to make
room for more cars. We have come to think that whatever is scenic
or historic has to be situated so that we can roll down the window
and touch it. That allows us to speed on to the next scenic
treasure.
</P>
<P>
   That mind-set was evident when Zion began limiting cars in May.
Visitors complained about delays waiting for shuttles. I can think
of few places where I'd rather be delayed than magnificent Zion.
But some people didn't see it as a blessing. They're conditioned to
packing a lifetime of sights into a weekend, leaving time for HBO
at the motel.
</P>
<P>
   If we do it right, people will start changing their notion of
what scenic places are about _ that serenity once again is part of
the beauty.
</P>
<P>
   John Young is the Opinion page editor of the Waco
Tribune-Herald. E-mail: jyoung(at)wacotrib.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
