<SLUG> BC-20MINUTE-MENUS-ADV21-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
$ADV21  
 HEALTHY 20-MINUTE MENUS: BRAISED CHICKEN, FENNEL AND RED PEPPERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDITORS: For use Wednesday, June 21, or thereafter.)  
 ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by 20MINUTE-MENUS clients. Nonsubscribers can
use this article only by special arrangement. For purchase
information, see end of text. 
 By MARIAN BURROS    
 c.2000 Foxcraft Ltd.    
<TEXT>
<P>
   There is one unusual ingredient in today's menu for braised
chicken with a side of green beans and mushrooms, but many
specialty food shops carry olive paste or you can buy it by mail on
the Web from a food dot-com such as www.tavolo.com. Olive paste
comes in green or black and keeps indefinitely in the refrigerator.
Which color you use is really up to you.
</P>
<P>
   If you are lucky enough to shop in a market that stocks the
tiny, thin French version of green beans, you may decide you want
to spend the extra money on haricots verts because they are so much
more tender than conventional green beans. Whatever your
opportunity, whatever your decision, green beans in either form are
a natural for mushrooms, and the touch of olive paste perks up the
otherwise fairly neutral flavors.
</P>
<P>
   Green beans are always better steamed than boiled, which seems
to take the life out of them. Cook them only until they are tender
crisp so that they maintain their texture and color. There is
nothing more depressing than grayish green beans.
</P>
<P>
   The green beans are just a side to the chicken with fennel, the
kind of main dish in which the supporting players _ the fennel,
peppers and onions _ are even more important than the starring
player, the chicken. They are what gives chicken, an otherwise
bland tasting bird, its wonderful flavor. And if you are one those
people who prefer the vegetables to the chicken you can add more of
them and reduce the amount of chicken.
</P>
<P>
   Since this meal offers no serious source of starch, I recommend
some crusty, country bread
</P>
<P>
   BRAISED CHICKEN WITH FENNEL AND RED PEPPERS
</P>
<P>
   12 ounces skinless, boneless chicken breasts
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons flour
</P>
<P>
   Few shakes salt
</P>
<P>
   Freshly ground black pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 tablespoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   6-ounce onion
</P>
<P>
   2 medium bulbs fennel
</P>
<P>
   2 medium roasted red peppers
</P>
<P>
   1 cup dry white wine
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon white wine vinegar
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon chopped fresh thyme
</P>
<P>
   1. Wash and dry the chicken and season the flour with salt and
pepper. Dip the chicken in the flour mixture on both sides and
shake off excess.
</P>
<P>
   2. Heat a nonstick pan large enough to hold all the ingredients
until it is very hot. Reduce heat to medium-high and add the oil.
Saute the chicken in the oil until it is browned on both sides.
</P>
<P>
   3. Meanwhile, coarsely chop the onion. Wash, trim, quarter and
thinly slice the fennel. When the chicken is nicely browned, remove
and set aside. Add the fennel and onion to the pan and cook,
stirring over medium heat, until the vegetables begin to soften.
</P>
<P>
   4. Meanwhile, rinse and cut the roasted peppers into thin
strips. Add to the pan with the chicken. Add the wine and chicken
stock. Reduce heat to low, cover and cook a few more minutes.
</P>
<P>
   5. Meanwhile, wash and chop the thyme and add to the pan.
</P>
<P>
   6. Remove pan from heat and stir in the vinegar and season with
salt and pepper.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 2 servings
</P>
<P>
   GREEN BEANS, MUSHROOMS AND OLIVE PASTE
</P>
<P>
   8 ounces haricots verts or regular green beans
</P>
<P>
   4 ounces assorted sliced mushrooms or 4 ounces white mushrooms
</P>
<P>
   Olive oil pan spray
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon olive paste
</P>
<P>
   Freshly ground black pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   1. Wash and trim the haricots verts or green beans and steam
over water until they are tender; about 7 minutes for the haricots
verts, 10 minutes for the green beans.
</P>
<P>
   2. Wash the mushrooms and dry. If they are whole, trim and
thickly slice. Heat a pan large enough to hold the mushrooms and
spray with olive oil pan spray. Add the mushrooms and saute over
high heat until they release their juices, cooking a few more
minutes until the juices evaporate.
</P>
<P>
   3. Stir in the olive paste; season with pepper and serve.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 2 servings
</P>
<P>
   GAME PLAN
</P>
<P>
   Prepare chicken through step 2
</P>
<P>
   Prepare the green beans through step 1
</P>
<P>
   Continue with chicken through step 3
</P>
<P>
   Continue with green beans through step 2
</P>
<P>
   Finish the chicken
</P>
<P>
   Finish the green beans
</P>
<P>
   YOUR PANTRY
</P>
<P>
   Flour
</P>
<P>
   Salt
</P>
<P>
   Whole black pepper
</P>
<P>
   Olive oil
</P>
<P>
   Onion
</P>
<P>
   Dry white wine
</P>
<P>
   White wine vinegar
</P>
<P>
   Olive oil pan spray
</P>
<P>
   SHOPPING LIST
</P>
<P>
   12 ounces skinless, boneless chicken breasts
</P>
<P>
   2 medium fennel bulbs
</P>
<P>
   2 medium roasted red peppers
</P>
<P>
   8 ounces haricots verts or regular green beans
</P>
<P>
   4 ounces assorted sliced mushrooms or 4 ounces white mushrooms
</P>
<P>
   1 jar olive paste
</P>
<P>
   NUTRITION INFORMATION PER SERVING: 682 calories, 17 grams total
fat, 2.7 grams saturated fat, 104 milligrams cholesterol, 440
milligrams sodium, 70 grams carbohydrate, 11 grams fiber, 52 grams
protein.
</P>
<P>
   Questions may be sent to Marian Burros by electronic mail. Her
address is: marbur(at)nytimes.com. The (at) represents the symbol
on your keyboard. Please include your name and daytime telephone
number. Questions of general interest will be answered in this
column. &QL;
</P>
