<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 14:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1833 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-TAX-CITRUS02-COX     06-01 0591
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAX-CITRUS02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TAX RULING IN TREE CASE COULD HAVE WIDE EFFECT
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;    By JERRY MOSKAL
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ An Okeechobee, Fla., citrus grower has been denied
deductions for tree-planting expenses in a U.S. Tax Court opinion
that the grower's attorney says could affect farmers nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   The decision upheld an Internal Revenue Service denial of $1.4
million in tax deductions for 1992-94 that Palaez and Sons Inc.
claimed for planting and nurturing 39,382 orange, grapefruit and
tangerine trees into producing citrus groves.
</P>
<P>
   Under a 1986 law, Congress denied annual deductions for
production expenses to farmers and certain other businesses that
did not produce a marketable product within two years. Instead,
these producers had to capitalize and depreciate these expenses
over a period of years.
</P>
<P>
   According to Philip A. Diamond, an Orlando tax attorney for the
company, the 1986 law also ordered the IRS to issue regulations on
how these expenses should be claimed over time. he said he was
disappointed that the Tax Court ruling didn't fault the IRS for
failing to do so.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Congress passed the law, (Ronald) Reagan was president
and the Berlin Wall was standing,'' Diamond said in a telephone
interview. ``It's been 14 years, and still the IRS has not issued
any guidance on what the productive period is for crops.''
</P>
<P>
   In his 27-page opinion, Judge Joel Gerber ruled the IRS was
correct in finding that Palaez couldn't use its own experience to
determine that its citrus trees came into production within the
two-year period.
</P>
<P>
   ``Petitioner's argument that the corporation should be allowed
to use its individual experience because (the respondent failed to
issue regulations or guidance as to the national weighted average
preproduction period for citrus trees is without merit,'' Gerber
wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Palaez branched out into citrus production from cattle ranching
in 1989 when it planted 39,382 trees. The firm said that despite a
1989 frost that destroyed half of those trees, the remaining trees
produced a $14,600 net harvest in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   However, Gerber ruled, such modest results failed to prove that
the pre-production period for citrus trees was less than the two
years required to qualify for yearly expense deductions. The
company said it did not claim the expense deductions until the
1992-94 tax years because it was waiting for the IRS to issue crop
growing regulations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going to appeal that's for sure,'' said Christina
Hooker, an officer and tax representative of Palaez. ``It's not
fair. To date, the (U.S.) Treasury still has not come up with
regulations. Right now, I'm in shock.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Diamond was more cautious. ``We're going to review our
options'' to appeal, he said. ``We feel the IRS should have
promulgated weighted averages for citrus growers as Congress
directed. How can a farmer comply with the regulations if they have
not been issued?''
</P>
<P>
   He said Gerber's ruling would have implications not only for
citrus growers, but for apple growers and farmers of other crops
with long pre-production periods.
</P>
<P>
   As a so-called Subchapter S corporation, Palaez's owners pay
taxes on their share of company profits rather than the firm
itself. Subchapter S corporations must have 35 owners or less.
</P>
<P>
   An IRS spokesman said the agency does not comment on pending tax
cases.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
