 AM-NYT-BUDGET  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FOR FRIDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Friday, June 2:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ELIAN GONZALEZ &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   CUBAN-BOY (Miami) _ A federal appeals court on Thursday sided
with the father of Elian Gonzalez, rejecting a request by the Cuban
boy's Miami relatives that he be granted an asylum hearing with
immigration officials. A three-judge panel of the 11th U.S. Circuit
Court of Appeals said the INS decision that only a parent can act
for his 6-year-old child in immigration matters ``comes within the
range of reasonable choices.'' It said that held true even if the
parent was in another country and the child was in the United
States. The ruling requires boy to stay in the United States for at
least 14 days more pending the filing of an appeal. By Rick Bragg.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   CUBAN-BOY-SCENE (Miami) _ Reaction in Miami to the court ruling
in Atlanta. By David Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
   Other sidebars as needed.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-EUROPE (Lisbon) _ President Clinton on Thursday called
on Israelis and Palestinians to ``do things that they have not done
in the past'' in an effort to conclude a historic peace agreement
between them. Clinton said the agreement was ``within view now.''
By Elaine Sciolino.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-NKOREA (Beijing) _ In his first known foreign trip in 17
years, North Korean leader Kim Jong Il hailed China's
capitalist-style reforms, toured Beijing's equivalent of Silicon
Valley and talked to Chinese leaders about his upcoming summit with
South Korea, Chinese officials said Thursday. By Erik Eckholm.
</P>
<P>
   ERITREA-REFUGEES (Asmara) _ A few weeks ago, Abrehet Amdimeskel
was simply a student, who happened to be in English class when the
war with Ethiopia came to her town in southern Eritrea. Now, at 14,
she is the head of her uprooted household, caring for her
grandmother and four younger siblings in a small tent in a huge
refugee camp. The refugee crisis could make the food shortages in
Eritrea far worse. By Ian Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   YUGO-MONTENEGRO (Podgorica, Yugoslavia) _ A Montenegrin official
accused the Yugoslav government of involvement in the killing of
Goran Zugic, the national security adviser of Montenegro. By
Carlotta Gall.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OTHER NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   OBIT-PUENTE (New York) _ Tito Puente, the latin jazz bandleader
and musician, died Wednesday in New York. (Byline to come)
</P>
<P>
   With photos, NYT1.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   PUENTE-MOURNING (New York) _ Mourning Tito Puente at Jimmy's
Bronx Cafe and other hangouts.By Juan Forero.
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-EXECUTE (Denver) _ A look at the decision by Bush on
granting temporary clemency to death row inmate so DNA evidence in
the case can be tested. By Frank Bruni.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICS &LR;  (``p'' code)
</P>
<P>
   GORE-CANCER (Atlanta) _ In a speech laced with memories of a
sister who died of lung cancer 16 years ago, Al Gore promises to
double the amount of fedeeral money spent on cancer research. By
James Dao.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-ENVIRON (Reno, Nev.) _ George W. Bush says the White House
should encourage land conservation with tax credits for private
parties and local governments, instead of simply placing property
off limits by fiat. By Frank Bruni.
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-BRIEFS (Undated) _ News from the hustings.
</P>
