<HEADER>
A1864 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      06-01 1264
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEETING THE URBAN CHALLENGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CAROL STOCKER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMBRIDGE, Mass. _ Urban gardening is always a challenge, thanks
to pollution, tiny lots, and the unyielding shade of surrounding
buildings. But this Sunday, 35 yards here that successfully solve
these problems will be open on a first-time tour to benefit
programs of the Friends of the Cambridge Public Library.
</P>
<P>
   The garden on the tour that I was most curious to visit belongs
to Carol Johnson, the first American woman to head a large
landscape architecture firm and to receive the American Society of
Landscape Architects' ASLA Medal, the field's most prestigious
award.
</P>
<P>
   From the State House to the Lechmere Canal Park, Bostonians are
surrounded by the work of Carol R. Johnson Associates Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Rangy and athletic, Johnson is a quietly intense and firmly
focused woman, attuned to the outdoors. When she was designing the
John Fitzgerald Kennedy Memorial Park next to the Kennedy School of
Government at Harvard, she got the idea for a fountain of water
running over and enlivening the text of JFK's speeches while hiking
in New Hampshire and watching streams coursing over rocks.
</P>
<P>
   The signatures of Johnson's design style include use of
different levels, the massing of plants, and sensitivity to fitting
in with the existing neighborhood. These themes can be found in her
own small Cambridge garden.
</P>
<P>
   But the big surprise is that she has created a wonderful outdoor
space for herself without having any backyard. She has been so
successful at this, in fact, that you can be there a long time
before you notice that her house is right up against the rear
property line, almost in the neighbor's kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   When she bought the 1928 Colonial two decades ago, it sat on
berms that disconnected it from a front yard overgrown with trees
and shrubs.
</P>
<P>
   She gave it a hard look and decided, ``I wanted sunshine and an
experience of different levels, and I wanted to relate the garden
to the house.''
</P>
<P>
   Subtle solutions
</P>
<P>
   Her solutions were low-key, subtle, and brilliant. First, she
boldly cut down the trees and put in a vegetable garden.
</P>
<P>
   Then she built a garage in front of the house to one side, so
the land behind it became a substitute backyard. Though it's really
a side yard, the brick garage, which coordinates with a brick
addition on the house next door, transformed it into a private
enclosure for outdoor dining. Grapevines growing on a tall pergola
over a picnic table provide an outdoor ceiling.
</P>
<P>
   But Johnson's most radical move was extending the berm out from
the house almost to the front sidewalk, essentially elevating the
entire front yard to 4 1/2 feet above street level. This created a
40- by 45-foot ``forecourt'' to the house with a nice lawn edged
with perennial plantings.
</P>
<P>
   So how do you get up to the house now? Johnson moved the
street-level entrance walk to the far side of the lot. You enter
through a gate and follow a walk alongside the base of the berm,
which allows you to admire the May apples and other shade-tolerant
wildflowers enjoying the perfect drainage of their little hillside
site.
</P>
<P>
   Then you climb steps up to the raised forecourt and find
yourself emerging into sunlight. You have also entered a zone of
relative privacy. Even though you are standing in a front yard, its
elevation largely shields you from passersby.
</P>
<P>
   More steps take you to the roof of the garage, which provides a
third level. ``It's a great joy,'' she says of the
furnished-garage-rooftop aerie, ``because I can see down the
street. I sit here and read, and I love looking down at the
gardens. And it's pleasant for guests who gather for drinks before
we eat down below (behind the garage), because the variety of
levels provides different experiences.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet this is a discreet landscape that fits in with the
neighborhood. A picket fence along the street, carefully selected
to coordinate with the neighbors' fences, helps to disguise the
unconventionality of the design.
</P>
<P>
   Remarkably, Johnson grows a lot of food here. She cultivates
``big green leafy things that don't need much sun _ chard, arugula,
rhubarb'' in the vegetable plot, which is encircled by a boxwood
hedge that is not tightly uniform, but casual and lumpy.
</P>
<P>
   The grape arbor yields green grapes for pies. Dwarf fruit trees
in the forecourt produce Bartlet and Asian pears, peaches and
plums. But not for Johnson. Neighborhood raccoons plunder the
produce. ``I'm willing to share. But they're not,'' she complained.
Other wildlife attracted to her Eden includes industrious urban
skunks who have found her small lawn a happy hunting ground for
grubs.
</P>
<P>
   After the spring bulbs and perennials have finished, Johnson
depends on strategically placed urns of impatiens _ the best annual
flower for shade _ to carry color through the summer.
Container-grown plants require daily watering, which is a bother,
so Johnson has hooked each urn to an automatic drip irrigation
system. The little lawn also has an irrigation system, with pop-up
heads ``I'm constantly digging up and breaking.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson would consider her yard a low-maintenance garden _ if
she believed such a thing existed. But working in her yard is one
of her great pleasures and her problem is lack of time, not desire.
``I spend as much time in it as I can.''
</P>
<P>
   No detail too small
</P>
<P>
   Whether designing a major project or her own garden, Johnson
believes she needs ``to have a large vision with an understanding
of detail. There's no detail too small to contribute to the final
vision.''
</P>
<P>
   Many are the details Johnson takes quiet delight in. She points
out the low wall that runs along the top of the forecourt berm like
a crown. ``It's Flemish bond . . . That's a way of laying the brick
to have cross-shaped openings.'' Little mirrors have been set into
these openings along the garage. You'd never notice them now
because they are covered by climbing hydrangea. ``But in the winter
I see it as I'm walking down the street and it makes the garden
look like it goes on forever.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson clearly built this landscape for her own enjoyment, not
to impress others. Its sophisticated use of space contrasts
appealingly with its lack of pretension.
</P>
<P>
   A little ornamental pool by the door used to have a fountain
figure of a toad spitting water, which she cajoled from the late
Jorge Epstein, the prickly salvage king of Blue Hill Avenue. It
finally disintegrated, so she bought a lion's head to replace it
and drilled a hole through its mouth herself. ``But I broke the
lion's tongue. I'm afraid he's going to be spitting water
sideways.'' And where did she get this garden sculpture? She
shrugged. ``It was just one of those concrete things you buy on the
side of the highway.''
</P>
<P>
   The Secret Gardens of Cambridge, An Open Gardens Day this
Sunday, 10 a.m. to 4 p.m., is sponsored by the five-year-old
Friends of the Cambridge Public Library. It will feature gardens
clustered in four neighborhoods _ Central Cambridge, Huron Avenue,
Brattle Street, and Coolidge Hill _ that allow for parking and
walking. The Cambridge Historical Society will serve lemonade at
the Hooper-Lee-Nichols house, 158 Brattle St. The Boudreau Library,
245 Concord Ave., a block past Huron Avenue, will be selling $20
tickets with a handsomely produced booklet of maps and garden
descriptions the day of the event. Cambridge libraries are selling
tickets in advance. Call 349-4032 for more information.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-01-00 1454EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
