<DOCNO> NYT20000601.0147 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 14:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1865 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-HOME-HISTORIC-ART-BOS     06-01 1399
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-HISTORIC-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN OLD HOUSE GET A NEW LEASE ON LIFE 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or
888-603-1036.)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PATTI DOTEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRAMINGHAM, Mass. _ Built by a descendant of a Salem witch trial
victim, passed down from family to family to a wealthy bachelor's
housekeeper, and then abandoned in old age, the once-proud Major
Lawson Nurse house faced its own, 20th-century trial several years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   The sentence? Demolition. It was time for developers to convert
the 46 acres of farmland into house lots. Time to tear down the
late-18th-century Nurse house that sat silently at the property's
edge.
</P>
<P>
   But word of the house's impending doom got townsfolk talking,
especially those interested in preserving New England's
architectural past.
</P>
<P>
   Ann Welles, a self-described ``sucker for old homes,'' was one
of them. Head of the city's historic district commission, landscape
gardener, and mother of two, Welles had driven by the Nurse house
for years. Since it was half-hidden behind a stone wall, she knew
it only as a late-night gathering spot for teenagers.
</P>
<P>
   The challenge
</P>
<P>
   ``It hadn't been lived in for a decade and a half,'' says
Welles, in the renovated kitchen of the Nurse house on Badger
Street. ``The windows were all broken, and the house had been
picked clean except for a few jelly jars. But it had good bones.
And I loved the way the land undulated down to the water.''
</P>
<P>
   She also loved the large, caved-in barn that dominated the
property. But was it salvageable? Yes, said Chris Walsh, an
architect known around town for his interest in historic homes and
an enthusiastic comrade in Welles's rescue effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he knew some sucker would eventually come along and
buy the place,'' says Welles, smiling at Walsh as she serves him a
cup of coffee. ``I was that sucker.''
</P>
<P>
   She'd done cosmetic work on two previous homes but had never
needed a contractor, let alone a contractor who understood
post-and-beam construction. Getting the proper permits was another
hurdle. But after several starts and stops, Welles and her husband
(they have since divorced) were ready to put out bids.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd hold my breath as various contractors walked around and
talked about fixing the old slanting floors and drilling holes in
the chestnut beams for electrical wiring,'' says Welles. ``They
were used to new construction, not an antique with dead possums in
the basement that didn't fit modern building codes.''
</P>
<P>
   And dealing with ghosts was certainly not included in the
contract. Welles tells of stopping by the house one afternoon and
finding the carpenters as ``white as sheets.'' They'd been
hammering away when a couple mysteriously appeared in the driveway
dressed in Colonial garb. They were further unnerved when the
couple asked if Welles was around. Then they disappeared as quickly
as they had come. Welles had to assure the shaken carpenters that
the couple were just friends dressed for a historical society event
_ not former owners returning to haunt workmen driving nails into
their old home.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did this whole thing on a shoestring,'' says Welles, who
credits the success of the three-year project to dedicated workmen
and the passionate and creative input of Walsh. ``To make it work
financially, we had to sell our other house.''
</P>
<P>
   Which meant making the front part of the old house livable for
Welles, her husband, and their two young sons. But first they
cleaned out the barn, tied its corners, and replaced the roof so it
could hold their furniture and all building materials. Then they
started on the house, clearing several raccoon families from the
four, south-facing rooms _ the library, parlor, and two bedrooms
above.
</P>
<P>
   However, to obtain an occupany permit they needed electricity, a
toilet, a sink, and a bathtub. They poured a cement floor in the
basement, and this became the family's ``kitchen.''
</P>
<P>
   Playing Robinson Crusoe soon lost its luster.
</P>
<P>
   ``The boys thought it was fun for about two weeks,'' says
Welles. ``Thank heavens it was summer, because there was no
homework involved and we didn't need heat. But it was dirty down in
that kitchen _ whenever anyone walked overhead or pounded a nail,
dirt filtered down through the floor and onto our pots and plastic
plates. We did a lot of barbecuing that summer.''
</P>
<P>
   A home once more
</P>
<P>
   The result of their disrupted lives _ a handsome home behind an
astonishingly beautiful stone wall _ was worth the discomfort, even
though the marriage did not survive. From the street, the house
looks very much as it must have 200 years ago, the exception being
a small attached barn on the north end that is now a two-car garage
with the master suite overhead. But what brings it into the 21st
century is that the back has been opened up with French doors in
the dining room and an elegant curved staircase encased in a
multiwindowed tower that sprays sunlight on the new open kitchen
and family room.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the beginning, we wanted to retain the front of the house
that looks over the millpond and the side that faces the street,''
says Walsh. ``The window and corner moldings in the front rooms and
the filigree detailing on the front stairs are wonderful. We
stripped the rest of the house back to the frame. From the street,
it still looks like the 1780s house.''
</P>
<P>
   Inside living spaces accommodate a very modern extended family.
The former library is now Welles's office, and the best parlor is
the living room with soft pastels of peach and lime green. The two
bedrooms above are now a bedroom, sitting room, and bath for
Welles's mother, who has recently moved in after putting her
Wellesley home on the market. A large dining room opened up from a
warren of little rooms has a series of French doors along that back
wall that leads to a patio. The large kitchen with fireplace and
family room completes the ground-floor layout.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not, and I repeat, not a restoration,'' says Welles.
``In my previous house, everything was to the period _ 1863. But
this time I wanted black granite counters in the kitchen and a sexy
staircase in the back.''
</P>
<P>
   The boys' bedrooms and bath are above the dining room and
kitchen, and the ``sexy'' staircase leads to the master suite _ a
cozy library, large walk-in closets, and bedroom with high ceiling
and balcony.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we achieved what we wanted in getting the living
pattern right for this family,'' says Walsh. ``It was a challenge
to take an older house with formal rooms and bring it together with
modern spaces. The grandmother has a very private area in the
front, the boys are in the middle, and then Ann has her privacy in
the back. It's a very flexible, flowing space.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I'm glad we didn't lose it to developers,'' continues
Walsh. ``It's a house and a piece of land that shouldn't be lost.
It has it all _ water, historic armature, millpond, barn, house,
and fabulous stone wall.''
</P>
<P>
   That armature went up about a century after the Salem witch
trials, when people began to settle in Framingham. Major Lawson
Nurse, a shoemaker and descendant of Rebecca Nurse, one of the
victims of the witchcraft tragedy, built the house between 1780 and
1810. Unlike other homesteads of that era, it passed down through
several families during the 19th century until it was bought by
John Russell Macomber in 1925. A bachelor, financier, and animal
lover, Macomber put up a large house and stables across the river
from the Nurse house and eventually built a half-mile flat track
and steeplechase that he named Raceland, which attracted some
25,000 visitors annually. He bequeathed the land to his housekeeper
with instructions that it be given to the MSPCA upon her death. The
animal protection group inherited the estate in 1971 and turned it
into the unsuccessful Macomber Center for Humane Education. The
property was sold to developers in the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   It was then that Welles got interested in it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like I belong here,'' says Welles. ``I like waking up
and knowing that other families lived here. I can see their
footprints on the floorboards. Or I'll sit behind the barn and look
out onto the water and think `Oh, this is what it looked like 100
years ago.' ''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
