<SLUG> BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN INCHWORM DAMAGE BEGINS TO ADD UP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER HOTTON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Q. &LR;  Help! My trees are being eaten by cankerworms!
Exterminators said they will treat small trees, but not big ones
like mine, unless there are big bugs. Could I spray soapy water on
my trees to kill the worms? Would that hurt the trees? The worms'
droppings look like poppy seeds, and when they get wet, they are
slippery!
</P>
<P>
   ERIN McQUILLAN, Braintree, Mass. &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A. &LR;  We call them inchworms, from the peculiar gait they use
when walking on leaves that they devour. The gait is primitive, the
critter pushing its body forward, then bringing up the rear in a
looping motion, and continuing by extending the front of the body,
flattening out the loop. They are also called loppers. Their
appetites are huge; they can make lacework of a maple tree in a few
days, even defoliate a large tree.
</P>
<P>
   They have plagued South Shore maples for several years now; this
year does not look too bad, at least in the handyman's experience.
Perhaps the worms are near the end of their cycle, just as the
gypsy moth disappeared after devastating trees for several years.
</P>
<P>
   Spraying the trees with soapy water will not hurt them, but can
do a job on the worms. It is too late now to do that, because they
are pretty well gone. Maybe next year. Right now is cleanup time:
Sweep and hose off the patio, decks, and sidewalks made slippery by
the droppings.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Q. &LR;  My neighbor who has a house in Florida has an interesting
gadget on the phone at his house here that lets him call home to
check if the heat is OK. Are you familiar with such a gadget? I
like the idea.
</P>
<P>
   JOHN PRICE, Peabody, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A. &LR;  The idea is a good one; the handyman is familiar with such
gadgets, and has the following list of providers in his file: Some
systems alert the homeowner to dropping temperature in an empty
house: no answer, temp OK; busy signal, temp too low. Other systems
work differently, usually alerting the neighbors to a dropping
temp.
</P>
<P>
   The companies are: Phone-Stat, 517-372-7426; Freeze-Warn,
203-364-9322 or 800-328-0332; and Control Products, 800-947-9098 or
612-448-2217.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Q. &LR;  Our house was built around 1898, with cement asbestos
shingles applied later. Ivy had covered the front of the house,
much of the sides, and part of the roof and chimney. When we went
to replace the gutters, the gutter companies refused unless the ivy
is removed. We pulled down the ivy and the gutters were replaced,
but the ivy vines have left little black ``stickers'' all over the
white shingles. Is there any way to remove the stickers, short of
removing the intact shingles?
</P>
<P>
   LOUISE HADDEN &AMP; JAMES McINTOSH, Cambridge, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A. &LR;  It would be nice to remove all the asbestos shingles, but
that has to be done professionally at great expense. To get the
stickers off, do not power-wash; this will remove them, but also
could release asbestos fibers _ something you want to avoid.
</P>
<P>
   How to do it safely: Make a strong solution of Spic and Span or
any other strong detergent such as Simple Green, and apply it to
the stickers; let it sit for several minutes; add more if it starts
to evaporate; and scrub lightly with a rough cloth. The idea is to
soften the stickers so they can be rubbed off. Another trick is to
apply a dab of Citristrip to each sticker, wait a few minutes, and
scrub off. This will soften the stickers faster than the detergent,
and is water washable.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Q. &LR;  We had a hardwood floor refinished with Fabulon, then moved
a piano on a dolly that left a big dented scratch in two rooms. The
scratch is shallow, and as wide as my finger is long. I can see it
only if I look it at it from a low angle. My husband suggested
using water to swell the fibers. Would that work? Is there any
other way to reduce that scratch?
</P>
<P>
   DEBORAH LERRA, Westford, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A. &LR;  Like the doctor who told the patient not to move ``that
way'' because it hurt, I suggest you just don't look at the scratch
from a low angle. But seriously, treating with water might work,
although the long, wide scratch is a lot of floor to treat. It also
might be difficult to get to the wood in order to swell the fibers,
and in so doing you could ruin the finish.
</P>
<P>
   I'd live with it until you sand the floors again. Perhaps you
could sand just the scratch, then patch-finish with more Fabulon,
which should patch better than polyurethane varnish. But this might
not work very well because sanding just the scratch will make the
depression wider. So, in the long run, refinishing the entire floor
in each room is the only sure cure.
</P>
<P>
   (Globe Handyman on Call Peter Hotton will answer reader
questions. Write him at the Boston Globe, Boston, Mass., 02107, or
e-mail him at hotton(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
