<SLUG> BC-FAMILY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARTNERS IN FORGETFULNESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LINDA WELTNER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Some might say that my husband and I have fairly typical roles
in our marriage _ ditzy wife, take-charge husband.
</P>
<P>
   If we do, it's not a gender-based division of labor. In
relationships where one member has attention deficit disorder, the
other often takes over the task of putting structure into days that
would otherwise be rendered chaotic by a distractible, disorganized
partner _ of either sex.
</P>
<P>
   Jack's office overlooks our driveway. He checks my calendar
first thing in the morning and makes sure my car isn't home when
I'm supposed to be somewhere else. He keeps track of time for both
of us, leaves me notes reminding me of important events, and holds
on to papers too important to lose, like plane tickets and
passports. It's a typical pattern. I recently met a woman who did
all the driving because her husband was always getting lost.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, I've come to depend on Jack's supervision. The
last trip we took, however, he lost my passport. Luckily, a good
Samaritan found it at Logan Airport and returned it. A month ago,
he went to bed and left the flames on under soup he was making from
turkey bones. He planted six blackberry bushes without untying them
first, crowding them into two unworkable clumps. Too impatient to
wait for me, he packed my things after a weekend at my sister's
house and left behind a gift she'd given me and the $300 mouthguard
I wear at night.
</P>
<P>
   Jack is both bemused and distressed by such incidents, partially
convinced that they're a result of his having felt a bit under the
weather recently, but we're both getting older, and his lapses are
the handwriting on the wall. If he starts doing the things I always
have, I'll have to begin checking up on him.
</P>
<P>
   So far, I've been angelic. It seems only fair that I return the
kindness and tolerance Jack's always shown toward me. Still, he had
only one screw-up to oversee; if this keeps up, I'll have two of us
to keep track of, and so far it's throwing me for a loop. I may be
understanding and good-natured on the surface. Underneath I'm deep
into refusal.
</P>
<P>
   I know that because of a recent dream in which I seemed to have
assumed responsibility for flying a plane from the Middle East to
the United States. I was in a panic. I'm no pilot and the flight
was 18 hours long. The travelers, including Jack, kept milling
around, refusing to get on the plane, and as I unsuccessfully
attempted to corral them, my energy was seeping away. I couldn't
tell which was more terrifying: my uncooperative passengers or the
increasing certainty of a crash. The images were so powerful that I
woke up three times in one night, still having the same dream.
</P>
<P>
   The plane never did get off the ground.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, I'm not prepared to be the one in this partnership who
makes sure our plans don't go awry. If I end up having to take
charge of details, our future is in jeopardy. I have more than
enough trouble with my own forgetfulness. How can I take on Jack's?
</P>
<P>
   I shared my feelings with my best friend, Lynn, deeply
apologetic that I even dared to present Jack's ``senior moments''
to her as a problem. For the past 15 years, Lynn's husband has had
Parkinson's disease, and as Doug has become more and more disabled,
she's had to assume responsibility for everything that goes on in
their separate and shared lives. I was afraid she'd think my fears
were trivial.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't apologize,'' Lynn said. ``It's not the degree of the
problem that's important. It's making the shift in your mind.
That's taken me 10 years, and it's been hard. I didn't want to see
that Doug's abilities were failing, so as I helped him, I was
short-tempered and often angry. I blamed him as if he was
manipulating me. I wanted to run away.
</P>
<P>
   ``The new qualities that came with his illness made him
unrecognizable as the person I had loved and spent my whole life
with. I had to keep reminding myself how important it was to just
observe the changes, to be willing to meet the new person that was
emerging, and not to cling to the idea of the person he had been.
It was even harder for him to make the shift. He was no longer the
person he'd known all his life. As a self-reliant person, he didn't
want to see himself as needing help.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still get very angry, impossibly furious, about this turn
that life has taken for the two of us. My mind shifts back
sometimes and I think about what life was like that glorious year
before he got sick, and briefly think of what it might be like now.
But then I shift back to the way it is.''
</P>
<P>
   Lynn pauses. Her glistening eyes match the catch in my throat.
</P>
<P>
   A hug is a wonderful thing to share.
</P>
<P>
   Linda Weltner's Web site is http://www.shore.net/weltner.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
