<SLUG> BC-IVOR-ISTVAN-SZABOS-SUNSHINE-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN OLD-FASHIONED HOLLYWOOD EPIC ... FROM HUNGARY 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's Hollywood Stars
entertainment column.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to Hollywood Stars, a
weekly entertainment column with color and black-and-white art.)
 Includes black-and-white photos and color slides of Ralph Fiennes
in scenes from ``Sunshine.'' 
 By IVOR DAVIS  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Hungarian director Istvan Szabo is a true legend of
international cinema, but one who remains virtually unknown to
American audiences.
 &HT;    Movies such as ``Mephisto'' (l981) and ``Colonel Redl'' (l984)
occupy spots on many savvy critics' all-time-best lists _ but they
were made in Hungarian and, therefore, available only to small
American audiences in subtitled versions.
 &HT;    That may change on June 9, however, when ``Sunshine'' opens
nationwide. It's a typically big, sweeping Szabo film, but this
time it's in English.
 &HT;    ``Sunshine'' is a novel on screen, a vast, rich,
multigenerational saga, the kind of thing that, if it were between
hard covers, would make the perfect summer read. But the story of
the Sunshine, or Sonnenschein, family is much more. It is nothing
less than a microcosm of the history of middle Europe for the last
150 years.
 &HT;    The film's co-writer, American playwright Israel Horovitz, tells
an old Hungarian joke which sums up the political background
against which the Sunshines live out their lives: An old man is
being interviewed, and he talks about the fact that he was born a
Hungarian, then became Austrian, then German, then Russian.
 &HT;    ``How lucky you are to have traveled so much,'' the interviewer
says.
 &HT;    ``I never left my village,'' the old man replies.
 &HT;    No country was buffeted by the 20th century's winds more than
Hungary, which provides the context for Szabo's fascinating tale.
 &HT;    The film opens with Ivan Sonnenschein, living in the lively,
modern Budapest of today, telling his family's story from the day
when his great-grandfather Emmanuel set out from his village to
make his fortune, clutching the recipe for the family's secret
``sunshine tonic.'' It continues through the lives of Ivan's
grandfather and father, Ignatz and Adam, and their ongoing
struggles against forbidden love and the social and political
consequences of their being Jewish.
 &HT;    To tell such a sprawling story, Szabo and Horovitz had to come
up with a unifying device. They found it in versatile British actor
Ralph Fiennes _ best known for ``Schindler's List'' (l993) and
``The English Patient'' (l996) _ who, with minimal help from the
occasional beard or mustache, plays all three leads: grandfather,
father and son.
 &HT;    ``I needed a face that could carry the whole story,'' Szabo says
by telephone from Vienna, ``and it needed to be a star. My problem,
however, was that great stars are always the same _ that's what
makes them stars. But this man needed to be able to portray three
very different men, who speak differently, behave differently, even
move differently. So he also had to be a great actor. And this was
Ralph Fiennes' talent.''
 &HT;    The story of the Sonnenscheins is also the story of Hungary's
Jews, of their assimilation and betrayal. It is a saga Szabo is
thoroughly familiar with, because it is the story of his own family
and many other Jewish families he knows in Budapest.
 &HT;    ``I was born into a family of medical doctors,'' the director
says, ``and my grandfather and my father told me that every disease
has a long history. A headache is not only a headache _ you have to
find the history behind the headache. And the story of Hungary's
Jews is different from those with other roots.''
 &HT;    American Jews consider themselves part and parcel of the mosaic
of American life, and so it was with families like the
Sonnenscheins. Thus, when Adam Sonnenschein and his new wife change
their name and convert to Catholicism, they do it with a light
heart.
 &HT;    But in doing this, Szabo demonstrates, they lose their roots and
a large chunk of their identities _ which will later come back to
haunt them.
 &HT;    ``There is a scene where they are leaving the building where
they have just changed their name, and they are laughing and
happy,'' Szabo recalls. ``My heart was sad shooting those shots, my
heart was sad editing the scene and my heart is sad every time I
see it, because I know this was the first and the greatest mistake
they made. I want to yell at them, `Why are you so happy? Are you
crazy?'
 &HT;    ``Although, of course, I know they are happy because it's my
film and I asked them to be.''
 &HT;    That mistake, the illusion that all they have to do to ensure
their success is to become indistinguishable from everyone else, is
at the heart of the film.
 &HT;    That message appealed to Horovitz when his London agent asked
him to look at Szabo's 600-page ``Sunshine'' script.
 &HT;    ``Many of my plays deal with the subject of assimilation, of
losing one's identity and trying to gain it back,'' the playwright
says, ``and of course I've always been a sucker for a family saga.
I love to see the history of the world through the eyes of one
family. It never fails to be compelling for me.
 &HT;    ``But Szabo's experience is such a fresh view,'' he adds. ``I
don't know this family until I see this film.''
 &HT;    Both men emphasize that their film is not the story of Szabo's
family or, indeed, of any particular Hungarian family.
 &HT;    ``There were several recipes and there were several families,''
Szabo says. ``Behind every character in the film there are four or
five or six different lives. Every character is a mixture of people
who told me stories, or they are stories I know personally.
 &HT;    ``There were, for example, two fencers with Jewish origins who
were members of that Olympic crew,'' he says. ``Both died during
World War II. One of them was the Olympic champion and one was a
silver medalist.''
 &HT;    To judge by the early critical response to the film, it just
might be the one which wins Szabo the American audience his work
has long deserved. The ``Sunshine'' screenplay won the Writer's
Guild of Canada Award and a similar honor from the European Film
Academy, which also named Fiennes as Best Actor.
 &HT;    Perhaps, in the end, the Sonnenscheins will turn out to be the
world's family.
 c.2000 Ivor Davis  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Ivor Davis is a Hollywood-based reporter and columnist.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``Sunshine,'' consult the
official Web site at www.sunshinemovie.com. And don't forget to
visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for information on Hollywood Stars
and other features. &QL; 
 &UR; (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) &QL; 
 &UR; (She also has information on how to subscribe to Hollywood Stars, a
weekly entertainment column with color and black-and-white art.)
 &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
