<HEADLINE>
COVERAGE OF NEW DRUGS IS QUESTIONED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK JURKOWITZ  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A study published in today's New England Journal of Medicine
states that mainstream media coverage of new medications ``may be
inaccurate and overly enthusiastic,'' blurred by a tendency to
exaggerate benefits and downplay risks and a failure to disclose
financial ties between experts and drug manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
   Given these problems, ``I think that there is a concern that the
public will have an overenthusiastic response about the benefits of
a drug,'' says study coauthor Dr. Stephen Soumerai, of the Harvard
Medical School's and Harvard Pilgrim Health Care's jointly operated
Department of Ambulatory Care and Prevention. Such reporting,
Soumerai adds, has a potential impact on such issues as drug prices
and a patient's willingness to continue taking medication that does
not produce instant results.
</P>
<P>
   The survey, which featured Australian journalist Roy Moynihan as
lead author, analyzed 207 stories (180 newspaper articles and 27
television reports) about three medications: alendronate for the
treatment of osteoporosis; pravastatin, a cholesterol-lowering
drug; and aspirin, which is used to prevent cardiovascular disease.
It concluded that media coverage ``may include inadequate or
incomplete information about the benefits, risks, and costs of the
drugs.''
</P>
<P>
   While more than half the stories failed to note the medications'
potential problems and 70 percent did not discuss
cost-effectiveness, the most eye-opening finding may be the
public's ignorance about the experts who are quoted in these
stories and their connections to the product. The study found that
only 39 percent of the stories that cited an expert with a
financial tie to the drug being evaluated disclosed that
relationship.
</P>
<P>
   ``It simply fails to disclose to the reader the financial ties
of investigators and experts,'' says Soumerai, adding that ``there
has been shown to be some relationships between the level of
(therapeutic) benefits reported and whether or not there was a
financial tie to the (drug) industry.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a very big issue,'' says Tom Rosenstiel, director
of the Project for Excellence in Journalism in Washington. Citing
the explosion of health-related coverage and such disturbing trends
as TV health reports that are sponsored by health-care
organizations, Rosenstiel says the journal study connects to the
``larger problem of oversupply of health news. Rather than
informing the public, we're confusing the public.''
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, the journal survey comes in the wake of published
reports that the Food and Drug Administration was critical of
favorable statements made last year by incoming journal editor Dr.
Jeffrey Drazen about a new asthma drug produced by a company that
employed him as a consultant.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Don't count on a replacement for departed Boston Magazine editor
Craig Unger soon. According to sources, there is no short list,
long list, or in-between list of possible successors and the search
process will start from square one.
</P>
<P>
   And while Boston owner Herb Lipson can switch editors like
George Steinbrenner used to run through Yankees managers, his own
staying power will earn him a lofty honor at this month's City and
Regional Magazine Assocation (CRMA) awards. Lipson will become the
ninth recipient of the CRMA's Lifetime Achievement Award to
``recognize pioneers in the regional and city magazine business,''
says CRMA executive director Jim Dowden. (Think of it as the city
mags' Irving Thalberg Award on Oscar night). Meanwhile, while the
other winners haven't been announced, Boston Magazine reportedly is
a top-three finisher in nine different categories. You can bet
Unger will be putting that on his resume.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Old foes bury the hatchet. April Oliver, the former CNN producer
fired after the ill-fated 1998 Operation Tailwind story alleging
that the US used nerve gas on a mission to kill defectors during
the Vietnam conflict, has settled her suit against the cable
network. Although Oliver attorney Roger Simmons had earlier tossed
out a $5 million figure, terms of the settlement _ reached late
last week _ were not disclosed. Simmons did say that ``April still
stands by her position'' that the Tailwind story was accurate,
adding that ``there's a lot of positive in this from April's
standpoint.'' (Oliver has, however, abandoned her journalism career
for law school.)
</P>
<P>
   One interesting aspect of this deal: Oliver, who in her suit
accused CNN of firing her ``to mollify the military establishment''
will now help CNN defend itself against still pending litigation
resulting from the Tailwind story.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Starting Monday, Robert Bartley, the soft-spoken Iowan who runs
The Wall Street Journal's thunderously conservative opinion pages,
will reprise the weekly ``Thinking Things Over'' column, which
first began in 1936 under Journal editor Thomas Woodlock. While
providing a forum for Bartley's views on the issues, the column
will also be a vehicle for commenting on press performance and
explaining the Journal's editorial commentary.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always been assumed around here that eventually I'd would
write `Thinking Things Over,' '' Bartley said. Asked if this was a
transitional step toward leaving the paper, Bartley _ who has run
the editorial pages since 1972 _ read a segment of his first
column, alerting those who see the move as a ``prelude to early
retirement,'' to the fact that his 92-year-old father still mows
his own lawn.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ten-year-old Emerge magazine, which billed itself as an
``issues-oriented'' publication for ``upscale African-Americans,''
was shut down Wednesday, with its owner announcing plans to
relaunch early next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Emerge represented a hallmark in African-American
publishing,'' says Keith Clinkscales, chairman and CEO of Vanguarde
Media, which publishes the 153,000-circulation magazine. ``However,
a new editorial strategy gives us a unique opportunity to reach a
broader readership and improve our business prospects.'' Vanguarde
indicated that its decision resulted in the elimination of a number
of jobs.
</P>
</TEXT>
