<HEADLINE>
&HT;     STROKE VICTIM STILL HAS FAITH IN CELL TRANSPLANT 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By PAUL GRONDAHL  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARATOGA SPRINGS, N.Y. _ Stroke patient Maribeth Cook seemed to
pass with flying colors an experimental fetal pig brain cell
transplant last September, but she grew worried after receiving
word recently that two other stroke patients in the clinical trial
suffered complications.
</P>
<P>
   A seizure and brain swelling in patients No. 4 and No. 5 in the
unproven animal-to-human cell transplant procedure caused the
biotechnology company conducting the trials to suspend them.
</P>
<P>
   That created anxious moments for Cook, 39, of Saratoga Springs,
who was patient No. 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``At first I was concerned that I might be in danger,'' Cook
said.
</P>
<P>
   But discussions with the coordinator of the clinical trials and
officials with Diacrin Inc., the Charlestown, Mass., biotech
company developing the procedure, called xenotransplantation,
allayed Cook's fears.
</P>
<P>
   Patient No. 4, who suffered a seizure a week after the
transplant, is a diabetic and prone to seizures, according to
Jonathan Dinsmore, Diacrin's senior director of cell
transplantation research.
</P>
<P>
   Patient No. 5 experienced brain swelling several days after the
transplant in a region of the brain that was not involved in the
procedure, Dinsmore said. Both patients had the complications
controlled by medication without serious damage, he added.
</P>
<P>
   The other three patients in the clinical trial suffered no
complications and displayed improvements in stroke deficits with
the injection of fetal pig brain cells, Dinsmore said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Diacrin officials temporarily suspended the clinical
trial pending a review by the U.S. Food and Drug Administration.
</P>
<P>
   ``The FDA is being cautious, which is fine,'' Dinsmore said.
``We're very concerned about safety, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Dinsmore hopes the clinical trial for stroke patients will be
allowed to resume and eventually proceed to the second phase, as
has Diacrin's studies on Parkinson's disease patients. Dinsmore
pointed to Cook's successful transplant as evidence of its safety
and efficacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maribeth is doing very well, a model patient,'' said Loretta
Barron, study coordinator for Cook's clinical trial at Beth Israel
Deaconess Medical Center in the Boston suburb of Brookline.
</P>
<P>
   Barron said Cook has passed batteries of tests in periodic
follow-up visits with her neurologist, Dr. Louis Caplan.
</P>
<P>
   Although magnetic resonance images, or MRIs, have failed to
detect visible new growth and regeneration where 30 million fetal
pig brain cells were injected with a long needle deep into the
stroke-damaged part of Cook's brain, strides have been made during
Cook's thrice weekly therapy sessions in Saratoga Springs.
</P>
<P>
   Cook said she continues to enjoy improvements in the function of
her damaged left side, which was partially paralyzed in a 1994
stroke. She has better range of motion and less rigidity in her
left arm and hand, has been fitted with a smaller and lighter brace
for her left foot and can concentrate better on printed material.
</P>
<P>
   ``The newest improvement is that I'm able to read books again,''
Cook said. ``After the stroke, it was frustrating because I read
the same page over and over again and never finished a book because
I couldn't concentrate long enough.''
</P>
<P>
   She also has been walking more briskly, more often and at
greater distances.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, nine months after the cell transplant procedure, Cook
is scheduled to have another routine checkup in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Even if, as on past visits, an MRI does not indicate new cell
growth in Cook's stroke-damaged brain, Dinsmore said that is not
reason for discouragement.
</P>
<P>
   The amount of fetal pig brain cells a patient gets requires a
delicate balance. Too few cells and the improvements are likely to
be less dramatic and not picked up by an MRI. Too many cells and
there is a risk of overgrowth, like soda foam overflowing a glass,
increasing pressure on the brain.
</P>
<P>
   At 30 million cells, Dinsmore said, optimal growth would have
filled in perhaps 10 percent of Cook's burned-out section of the
brain damaged by her stroke.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't expect the MRI to pick up cells filling in the hole,''
Dinsmore said. ``There's nothing the MRI is telling us that
reflects on whether the graft is surviving or not.''
</P>
<P>
   Dinsmore said one dosage option under review is to give stroke
patients five times the amount of cells Cook received, or 150
million fetal pig brain cells.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, if the FDA allows the clinical trials to resume,
additional stroke patients await the transplant procedure. Nobody
has pulled out as a result of the suspension, Dinsmore said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The complications didn't diminish interest,'' Dinsmore said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Complications can happen with any surgery,'' Barron said.
``There's no clear reason why either patient had complications. A
suspension isn't unusual with a new study like this. I wouldn't be
surprised if the study is continued fairly soon.''
</P>
</TEXT>
