<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHILDCARE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM BOYS TO MEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA F. MELTZ  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Does your 11-year-old son worry he'll never be popular because
he's too thin or too short? Have you found your 13-year-old poring
over a bodybuilding magazine at the grocery store? Has your
14-year-old decided to shave even though you could count the number
of hairs on his chin?
</P>
<P>
   Paying attention to his body's changes, worrying about his
appearance, being pleased he's arrived at masculinity (``Those chin
hairs are sacred!'' says psychologist Michael Thompson) _ these are
rites of passage that are as normal and healthy for boys as similar
ones are for girls.
</P>
<P>
   The thing is, we expect and anticipate this kind of focus on the
physical from our daughters. With sons, it takes us by surprise.
</P>
<P>
   Not only do boys care how they look, researchers say, but they
are just as likely as girls to develop an unrealistic body image
that puts them at risk for several disorders.
</P>
<P>
   The two most widely known eating disorders, anorexia nervosa and
bulimia, are typically associated with adolescent girls. In the
past 10 years, however, more than a million males have been
diagnosed. Disorders that more typically affect boys are ones that
most of us have never heard of: muscle dysmorphia (thinking your
muscles aren't big enough); body dysmorphic disorder, or
dissatisfaction with a body part; and the Adonis complex, a phrase
being made popular by a book of the same name that describes boys
and men who model their bodies on beefed-up images pushed on them
by the culture.
</P>
<P>
   A boy's journey to masculinity begins in the preschool years
when he first forms ideas of what it means to be a man: Is a man
gentle or harsh? Does he change diapers or only tires?
</P>
<P>
   ``The more present a father is, the more a son will model his
image after him,'' says Thompson, a school consultant and co-author
of the best-selling book ``Raising Cain'' (Ballantine). No matter
how involved a father is, however, cultural influences play a
bigger and bigger role as a son grows.
</P>
<P>
   Idealized images
</P>
<P>
   Boys in every generation have had idealized images of maleness
to emulate. Think John Wayne and Johnny Weissmuller. Our sons have
the distinction of being the first boys to grow up being told that
16 1/2-inch biceps aren't big enough, that pecs and delts have to
bulge, that only a six-pack of abdominals will do. Think GI Joe and
WWF.
</P>
<P>
   When GI Joe first appeared in 1964, he had a body an ordinary
boy could aspire to. Today, Joe is so muscular that it would be
hard for any boy to look like him without steroids, says researcher
and psychiatrist Harrison G. Pope Jr. of Harvard Medical School,
co-author of ``The Adonis Complex.'' Ditto the images boys see in
ads and on billboards, TV, and elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Boys take these physical attributes more to heart than we
realize, says psychologist William Pollack of McLean Hospital near
Boston. ``By 8 or 9, they have a clear image of what a male body
should be: big and beefy,'' he says. Pollack is the author of the
best-selling ``Real Boys.'' His newest book is ``Real Boys'
Voices'' (both Random House).
</P>
<P>
   That means that even before his body begins to change, a boy has
a preconceived idea of what he wants it to look like. Anything less
will be disappointing and inadequate. By 14, every boy struggles
with this to some degree as he tries to establish his maleness,
says Thompson. The typical boy worries about:
</P>
<P>
   --Intimidation by other boys: ``Am I big/strong enough?''
</P>
<P>
   --Whether he's attractive to girls: ``Am I too scrawny? Too
short, too fat, too thin?''
</P>
<P>
   --Not being a man in his own eyes: ``Have I achieved my own
definition of masculinity?''
</P>
<P>
   A boy who spends 15 minutes on his hair every morning, thinks
about his clothes, and/or wants to eat healthy or work out with
weights is working on these issues in a healthy developmental way,
says psychiatrist Katharine A. Phillips of Brown University, one of
Pope's coauthors.
</P>
<P>
   But normal can inch toward problematic, partly because we don't
know what our sons are thinking. ``A boy's struggle is most likely
to be entirely internal _ a secret,'' says Pollack. If he does talk
about any aspect of his body, it's often with strong feeling: ``I
hate my hair/ears/nose!''
</P>
<P>
   We typically respond with a comment intended to reassure: ``You
always look fine!'' or ``Why are you worrying so much about the
size of your ears?'' But this tends to push him away, not draw him
near. To him, the first response is dismissive, the second,
shaming. Pollack says it's better to mirror what he said _ ``You're
having a bad hair day, huh?'' _ and acknowledge how important it is
to feel like you look good: ``I hate it when I have a bad hair day;
it makes me grumpy.''
</P>
<P>
   If he changes hairstyle or dress, notice but don't judge: ``I
see you're combing your hair differently'' rather than ``Gee, I
liked the old style. Why'd you change?'' In other words, plant a
seed that there are alternative ways to look _ ``It looks good both
ways'' _ rather than struggle over it.
</P>
<P>
   Weight training
</P>
<P>
   If a boy shows interest in weight training, don't shut him down.
Respond by saying ``Tell me why you want to do this,'' rather than
``That's stupid!'' Even if his reasons surprise you _ ``I hate my
body! I'm scrawny!'' _ be supportive: ``Let's find a trainer who
has experience with boys your age.'' Do some research to find
someone you can trust; if what your son wants to do is
inappropriate, he'll accept it more willingly from the trainer than
from you.
</P>
<P>
   ``With a teenage boy, when you give a flat no rather than `Let's
talk about it,' he feels cut off from you in the struggle,'' says
Pollack. ``So if things get serious, he won't come to you for
help.''
</P>
<P>
   What's most serious is the use of anabolic steroids, or
synthetic testosterone, to enhance musculature. Six to 7 percent of
adolescent boys use them. ``That's one in 15 boys,'' says Phillips.
``Your son probably knows someone who does. Is he susceptible? Do
you even know?''
</P>
<P>
   Because boys' steroid use is typically without medical
supervision (it's illegal without a prescription but widely
available on the black market in gyms), there is frequent abuse.
Boys rarely are aware of the potential side effects:
</P>
<P>
   --Accelerated hardening of the arteries and a higher risk for
early heart disease;
</P>
<P>
   --Severe aggression and irritability, mood swings, and
personality changes that have been linked to violent crime;
</P>
<P>
   --Short-term shrinkage of the testicles and penis;
</P>
<P>
   --Permanent stunting of the body's long bones.
</P>
<P>
   Phillips speculates that one reason there isn't more steroid use
among boys is because it can only be taken by injection. That's
about to change, however. This summer, for the first time,
synthetic testosterone will be sold in gel form, as AndroGel.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the boys who couldn't stomach giving themselves a shot
will be slapping jelly on like crazy,'' says sociologist Michael
Kimmel of the State University of New York at Stony Brook. He is
the author of ``Manhood in America'' (Free Press).
</P>
<P>
   Andostene dione, the adrenal hormone used by home-run king Mark
McGwire, can be purchased legally by any boy at a nutrition store,
says Pope. As many as 15 percent of boys do so, he says, and they
often take 10 times the recommended dose. ``Long-term dangers are
as yet unknown,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Also at the dangerous end of the continuum is body dysmorphic
disorder, when a teen is embarrassed about a part of his body, even
though it looks normal to others. ``It can be any body part, from
thinking your nose is too big to your feet,'' says Phillips, who
specializes in BDD. Muscle dysmorphia causes a boy to be ashamed of
muscles he thinks are too small when, in fact, they're big.
</P>
<P>
   With a mild form of BDD, a boy can function normally, but when
it is severe, he might be too self-conscious and too preoccupied
for any of his usual activities. Many boys with severe BDD drop out
of activities, don't see friends, and spend hours in the bathroom
or holed up in their room.
</P>
<P>
   If this describes your son, seek professional help, says
Phillips. If you fear he's moving in this direction, ask him how
much time he spends each day worrying about his appearance. ``More
than an hour is our cutoff,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Measuring up
</P>
<P>
   What worries Pope is not so much that some boys use steroids but
that all boys are getting warped ideas about their body. ``When
boys feel they can't measure up, they're likely to do bad things to
their body'' and to have poor self-esteem, he says. ``Ten years
ago, only serious jocks used steroids. Now our studies show that
boys who take them do it just to look better, not for any athletic
aspirations.''
</P>
<P>
   The best insurance to keep a boy from moving toward the Adonis
complex is to counteract media images when he's 4 and 5. ``Get them
giggling,'' says Kimmel. ``Get them to see it as silly: `Wouldn't
Daddy look funny if his body was like that!' ''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the ultimate message to send, says Pollack, is this:
``Size and body have nothing to do with masculinity. You're a real
boy or a real man whatever size you are.''
</P>
<P>
   AFTERTHOUGHT _ In most families, life is so hectic and noisy
that children lack experience spending time alone and are
uncomfortable doing so. Sit together for 10 minutes and listen to
the sounds of silence, then talk about what you heard and what the
silence felt like. From ``365 Ways to Raise Great Kids,'' by Sheila
Ellison (Sourcebooks Inc., 1998).
</P>
<P>
   Barbara F. Meltz's is the author of ``Put Yourself in Their
Shoes: Understanding How Your Children See the World'' (Dell).
Write to her at the Globe or via e-mail at meltz(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
