<HEADLINE>
MACLAINE'S SPIRITED NEW OFFERING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE WHITE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you've read any of Shirley MacLaine's previous eight
best-selling books it will probably not surprise you to learn that
in one of her previous lives she was a mistress of the emperor
Charlemagne. Nor will you be stunned to discover that in her
current form she was romantically involved with Charlemagne's
reincarnation, Olaf Palme, the Swedish prime minister who was
assassinated in 1986.
</P>
<P>
   Amazing, no? But pretty much everything about her new book,
``The Camino: A Journey of the Spirit'' is amazing, perhaps
especially the fact that it will be number four on the June 4 New
York Times nonfiction bestseller list. It is engaging, though, in a
way, from the first chapter, where an encounter with a wild-eyed,
barefoot lecher inspires a fervent oath (``I vowed never to be
afraid of going braless again'') to the last, when our heroine
muses, ``Does the role of extraterrestrial input enter into our
evalution of who we are as humans?''
</P>
<P>
   In MacLaine's case, I would say the answer is yes, definitely.
She's endearingly dotty, like a crackpot aunt who pops in from time
to time to tell you about her latest weird enthusiasms. She babbles
on wildly, but she's so earnest, and so unintentionally comic, that
you can't help listening even though you know most of what she says
is utterly preposterous.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Camino'' finds her walking the ancient 500-mile pilgrims'
route across northern Spain to the church of Santiago de
Compostela, said to house the relics of St. James the Apostle. It
seems an odd choice of adventures for MacLaine who, as she writes,
has never been religious, preferring instead to ``seek
spirituality.'' But, as she explains, the Camino has been a source
of ``energy'' since ancient times, running as it does along one of
the earth's ley-lines, ``the essential structure of the earth's
etheric spirit.'' If there's etheric spirit floating around, you
can be sure MacLaine will be in the middle of it.
</P>
<P>
   MacLaine undertook the difficult trek at age 60. She walked at
least 20 miles a day, often alone and in bad weather. She slept in
filthy, rat-infested pilgrims' hostels, fended off a persistent
admirer, became lost more than once, braved vicious dogs, and tried
to elude the news media. On several occasions paparazzi accosted
her in the shower.
</P>
<P>
   Through it all she was protected by two spiritual guides, a
vanilla-scented angel named Ariel, and a 12th-century monk, John
the Scot, an expert in karma and mangoes (``When digested properly,
it stimulates the correct patterns for the projection of
telepathy'') who addressed MacLaine as ``lassie.''
</P>
<P>
   As she walked the Camino in her current life, these two entities
helped her reexperience two of her past lives. In one, she was a
Moorish-Jewish-Christian healer who ``became friendly'' with
Charlemagne and ``spent many hours with him on animal skins in
front of a massive fireplace,'' and bore him three children.
</P>
<P>
   In another incarnation she was an androgynous Lemurian in an
Eden-like Atlantis who underwent sexual division and then lived
happily with the separated half as man and wife until
extraterrestrial input created an imbalance in the collective
consciousness that resulted in a natural disaster that caused
Atlantis to disappear beneath the ocean. Or something like that.
The Atlantis chapters are confusing. However, I got the impression
that MacLaine was drawing a parallel between Lemuria and
present-day America.
</P>
<P>
   ``A person's most profound insights are often regarded as
socially unacceptable and even delusional,'' she writes, near the
end of the book. Now who would that person be? I wonder.
</P>
<P>
   Diane White is a Globe columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
