<HEADLINE>
COURT RULES AGAINST POLITICAL ASYLUM HEARING FOR ELIAN GONZALEZ 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: This early version will be updated as needed.) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 By EDWARD WONG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A federal court in Atlanta announced Thursday morning that it
would not force the U.S. government to grant Elian Gonzalez an
asylum hearing.
</P>
<P>
   The long-awaited ruling by a three-judge panel came as a major
victory for the 6-year-old boy's father, Juan Miguel Gonzalez, who
has insisted on bringing Elian back to Cuba against the wishes of
his relatives in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   But the judges said that Elian could not leave the country for
two weeks to allow his Miami relatives sufficient time to appeal
the decision.
</P>
<P>
   The 33-page written decision by the 11th U.S. Circuit Court of
Appeals came after three weeks of deliberation by Judges J.L.
Edmondson, Joel A. Dubin and Charles R. Wilson. In issuing their
decision, the judges said they were not ruling on whether a boy
should stay with his father but examining ``the separation of
powers under our constitutional system of government.''
</P>
<P>
   In effect, the judges were determining whether the executive
branch of the government _ as represented by the Justice Department
and the Immigration and Naturalization Service _ had the right to
openly interpret legislation that allowed ``any alien'' to apply
for an asylum hearing. And they were looking at whether
intervention by the judicial branch _ as represented by the Atlanta
court _ was warranted.
</P>
<P>
   After the judges weighed whether Elian's Miami relatives could
file an asylum application against the wishes of his father, they
supported the INS' position that the father should speak for his
son.
</P>
<P>
   ``The important legal question in this case, therefore, is not
whether the plaintiff may apply for asylum; that a 6-year-old is
eligible to apply for asylum is clear,'' the court said in its
decision. ``The ultimate inquiry, instead, is whether a 6-year-old
has applied for asylum within the meaning of the statute when he,
or a non-parental relative on his behalf, signs and submits a
purported application against the express wishes of the parent.''
</P>
<P>
   The court said that in refusing to look at the boy's asylum
claim several months ago, the INS had adequately considered whether
Juan Miguel Gonzalez was being unfairly coerced by the Cuban
government. The judges also acknowledged that if Elian returns to
Cuba ``he will be without the degree of liberty that people enjoy
in the United States'' and that ``re-education, communist
indoctrination and political manipulation of plaintiff for
propaganda purposes'' are ``not beyond the realm of possibility.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Nonetheless, we cannot say that the INS' assessment of
plaintiff's asylum claim _ that it probably lacked merit _ was
arbitrary,'' the judges said.
</P>
<P>
   They pointed out that successful asylum seekers must prove to
the INS that they have been persecuted or that they have a
``well-founded fear'' of persecution if they are returned to their
homeland. The INS had made a preliminary determination that there
is no evidence that Elian would meet those standards, the judges
said.
</P>
<P>
   Government officials seemed satisfied with the Atlanta court's
ruling.
</P>
<P>
   ``Under the circumstances, I think that justice has been done,''
Attorney General Janet Reno said at a news conference in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   She stressed that there had been no legal precedent for this
case. ``As the court said, I think our decision was reasoned and
reasonable,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton, who was in Berlin on his last official visit
to Europe, also said that he was ``pleased'' with the court ruling.
</P>
<P>
   But outside the home of the relatives in Miami's Little Havana
neighborhood, where Elian lived for nearly five months, more than
100 protesters who want the boy to stay in this country waved signs
and angrily chanted slogans.
</P>
<P>
   Kendall Coffey, a lawyer for the relatives, said at a Miami news
conference that the Atlanta court acknowledged that the INS had ``a
whole lot of room'' in its discretion to grant or refuse asylum.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a stand-up-and-applause day for the INS,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Coffey said the relatives had made no decision at this time
about whether to seek a new hearing. They were considering whether
to take their appeal to the U.S. Supreme Court, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still believe the legal system may allow this child to have
his day in court'' before Elian is returned to Cuba, Coffey said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   News agencies reported that lawyers for the relatives have
approached Supreme Court Justice Anthony M. Kennedy, asking him to
grant a stay preventing Elian from leaving the United States until
the Supreme Court can consider a formal appeal. There was no
immediate response from Kennedy, who supervises emergency cases
from the appeals court in Atlanta. But he can act on the request
himself or refer it to the full Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for the relatives have 45 days to ask all 12 judges on
the Atlanta court to hear the case. If the court denies that
request, the lawyers have 90 days to appeal to the Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   At the Miami news conference, Elian's cousin, Marisleysis
Gonzalez, complained that her efforts to talk to the boy by
telephone had been rebuffed. She charged that the boy's father and
Cuban officials were afraid to let Elian meet his Miami relatives
again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they should allow us to see the boy,'' she said. ``I
think they should give us the opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   On May 11, lawyers representing both sides of Elian's family
distilled five months of an international struggle to an hour and a
half of legal arguments before the judges. The struggle has
embroiled the governments of Cuba and the United States, thousands
of Cuban-Americans and a family bitterly divided by politics.
</P>
<P>
   Several months ago, the INS returned Elian's asylum application
to his Miami relatives without reading it, saying that only the
boy's father could speak for him.
</P>
<P>
   But on May 11, lawyers for the Miami relatives pointed out
repeatedly that immigration laws do not set a minimum age for an
asylum applicant. They also argued that the Cuban government would
persecute Elian because the boy's mother had fled from the country.
</P>
<P>
   But Gregory Craig, the lawyer for Juan Miguel Gonzalez, said
that the ongoing custody battle was taking a heavy toll on Elian's
family and that the boy's asylum application could not be taken
seriously because a 6-year-old is too young to hold informed
political beliefs. Many child psychologists have agreed on that
point.
</P>
<P>
   The judges had pointed questions that ranged from asking the
lawyers for the Miami relatives whether Elian really understands
the meaning of his asylum application to grilling Craig on whether
Cuba's communist government might compromise the parental abilities
of the boy's father.
</P>
<P>
   Lazaro Gonzalez, Elian's great-uncle, and his daughter,
Marisleysis, have been among the most vocal opponents of returning
the boy to Cuba. Like thousands of Cuban-Americans in this country,
Elian's Miami relatives do not want to see the boy living in a
communist country headed by President Fidel Castro. The relatives
have been supported at every turn by demonstrators waving Cuban and
U.S. flags and placards with slogans like ``Let Elian Have His Day
in Court.''
</P>
<P>
   Elian is staying at the Rosedale Estate in the upscale Cleveland
Park neighborhood of Washington, D.C., with his father and his
father's wife, their 6-month-old son and several schoolmates and a
teacher from Cuba. The group moved there more than a week ago from
the 1,100-acre Wye River conference center in Maryland so they
could be closer to Craig. Before the Cuban entourage moved in, the
grounds of the lush Rosedale Estate were used in part as the
neighborhood dog run.
</P>
<P>
   Elian and his father were re-united on April 22 after Reno
ordered a pre-dawn raid in which federal agents brandished
automatic rifles in front of the boy and his Miami relatives. Elian
was flown to Washington and placed in the care of his father, who
had arrived from Cuba on April 6 to claim his son.
</P>
<P>
   The two had been separated since last November, when Elian's
mother, Elisabet Brotons, took him on an ill-fated attempt to reach
the United States on a smuggling boat. When the vessel capsized,
Brotons and 10 other Cubans drowned. But fishermen discovered Elian
clinging to an inner-tube on Nov. 25 off the Florida coast. Two
other survivors were found in another inner-tube in a Key Biscayne
marina.
</P>
<P>
   The boy was given ``parole'' status by the Immigration and
Naturalization Service and placed in the custody of Lazaro
Gonzalez, in Miami. Until the raid, Lazaro Gonzalez defied
government orders to hand over the boy, hoping to stall federal
officials until the Atlanta court could decide on the asylum
hearing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
