<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 15:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1888 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-COMPUTERS-LAN-ART-BOS     06-01 1598
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTERS-LAN-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 PARTY IS BLOODY, BUT IT'S VIRTUAL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOANNA WEISS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NORTH KINGSTOWN, R.I. _ A rumbling noise is coming from 85 New
Lexington Road.
</P>
<P>
   It's a misty Saturday morning in this neighborhood of closely
mowed lawns and small, tidy homes. Birds chirp. Children ride their
bikes. Number 85, the yellow house on the corner, spits out the
sound of gunfire.
</P>
<P>
   Inside, in a basement lined with wires, 24 home computers are
lined up on tables. Twenty-four people are glued to the screens,
some wedged beside the dryer and the hot water heater. They're
playing video games with 3-D graphics and lots of blood, killing
each other onscreen in disgusting ways. In real life, they're
eating doughnuts, and they're all in a very good mood.
</P>
<P>
   It's 9:30 a.m., and the games will go on for another 18 hours;
LAN parties tend to run long.
</P>
<P>
   LAN stands for Local Area Network, a closed circuit of computers
linked together for maximum speed. A LAN party is a self-contained
video game marathon, a bring-your-own-PC event. Twenty-two people _
21 of them male _ have hauled their computers and monitors to this
little house, which belongs to players Matthew and Sarah Andrade.
The guests come from three states and range in age from 11 to 40.
They call themselves the BadLANs.
</P>
<P>
   The nominal purpose of the affair is to shoot your friends to
smithereens.
</P>
<P>
   But while the BadLANs want to know how real the blood looks when
it splatters _ and their lips curl into wicked smiles as they blow
their friends apart _ in real life, they consider themselves a
nonviolent crowd. A part of the ``gaming community.''
</P>
<P>
   That's the insider's term for the world of bloody virtual
sports, a quiet subculture of growing strength and market clout.
There are scores of Web sites devoted to reviews and news about
computer games. And while it's hard to guess how many people are
playing, some suspect that more than a million Americans go to a
LAN party once or twice a year.
</P>
<P>
   LANgoers are mostly male, mostly young, and mostly urban, said
James Mecham, director of project development at California-based
gamers.com. They are cynical, savvy, and a bit brainy. And they
find satisfaction, even exhilaration, in figuring things out
themselves _ whether it's the fact that Mountain Dew (a favored
beverage in this crowd) has more caffeine than other soft drinks,
or the way to set up a complex computer network.
</P>
<P>
   Many BadLANs players take their home computers apart once a
month, to reconfigure parts and add new features. They talk about
PCs as if they were hot rods. And they chafe at the common
complaint that violent games make a dangerous culture.
</P>
<P>
   The BadLANs say it's the opposite: Gaming gets out their
aggression in a safe and social way. It also puts their computers
to the test.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gaming's the only application that truly challenges a
computer,'' says Dan Ware, 25, of Somerville, Mass., who has a
tattoo on his leg and a geek's dream job: technical director of an
interactive multimedia company.
</P>
<P>
   But even Ware is sometimes trumped by Tyler Whittaker, 15, of
North Kingston, who knows more than anyone around about high-tech
developments. The rule seems to be: The younger you are, the more
time you have to fiddle, the more computer savvy you become. The
more likely you are to some day rule the world.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At the BadLANs, ruling the world is not on the agenda. The
immediate goal is to win the game, whatever it happens to be.
</P>
<P>
   If the game is Quake III, the main idea is death. You're a
virtual person, whose goal is to ``frag'' _ that means kill _ other
players. You run around in a virtual world that could be a medieval
castle or an asteroid. In the foreground of your screen is your
virtual hand, which holds a virtual gun, which you shoot by
clicking your mouse. The experience can be dizzying; one player
took motion sickness medicine before he got to the party.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's StarCraft, where the main idea is . . . death. You
control an alien race, and you try to wipe out other alien races,
by ordering your little aliens to make high-caliber weapons.
</P>
<P>
   You don't need a LAN party to play these games; you can buy
copies in software stores or tap in through the Internet. But once
you've played on a LAN, regulars say, you'll be hooked. For two
reasons: ping and smack.
</P>
<P>
   Ping is the amount of time, measured in milliseconds, that it
takes for a signal to leave your keyboard, travel to the server,
and return to your screen. If you're trying to blow a fast-moving
enemy apart, ping can mean the difference between life and death.
On the Internet, ping can be anywhere from 100 to 500. Here in the
Andrades' basement, the highest ping is 12.
</P>
<P>
   Smack is the cheering and the razzing that players emit at key
moments _ after, for example, a truly epic frag. It's the
computer-game equivalent of the touchdown dance. Smack is what
makes the whole thing social. Typical smack from the BadLANs:
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, in the back, Pappy? That's wrong!''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not wrong. You should have looked behind you and known
I was there!''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to smack, Matthew Andrade is one of the loudest.
When he yells, ``Stop moving! Stand still!'' it resonates off the
pipes. Matt, 32, is a computer operator, studying for a technology
degree. He is the technical director of the BadLANs.
</P>
<P>
   Sarah Andrade, 26, studies psychology and social work. She is
the treasurer and den mother, in charge of getting pizza.
</P>
<P>
   Adam Slesinger, 21, of North Kingston, is the Web master and
co-technical director. He works at a tool company with Matt, and
wants to start a Web design company. He wears a T-shirt that says,
``Reach out and frag someone.'' Adam is the undisputed number-one
player, and, when people frag him, they get excited.
</P>
<P>
   Matt, Sarah, and Adam have been hosting LAN parties for two
years now, ever since the day Matt brought home his first,
primitive networking equipment and announced that he was going to
try to string a few computers together.
</P>
<P>
   They crammed people into a series of small Rhode Island
apartments before Matt and Sarah bought this house in November.
When Matt saw the basement _ and calculated how many computers he
could fit there _ he fell in love.
</P>
<P>
   ``Isn't that sad?'' Sarah says affectionately.
</P>
<P>
   This party is BadLANs XII, their biggest event ever, and with
it, they figure the house has reached its limit. Matt makes liberal
use of extension cords, but tries to plug only two computers into
each wall socket, for practical reasons. At BadLANs XI in March,
Matt and Adam tried to warm up a cup of coffee in the microwave,
and the house went dark.
</P>
<P>
   Still, demand seems to increase every month, and lately _ to
their own surprise _ the group has been getting sponsors. In
exchange for plugs and gratitude and a mention on thebadlans.net,
the group's Web site, gaming sites send free stuff.
</P>
<P>
   Such as the party's sole controlled substance: Bawls, a
super-caffeinated soft drink made from the Amazonian guarana berry.
It has three times the caffeine of a cup of coffee.
</P>
<P>
   By midafternoon, empty bottles of Bawls are everywhere, and
several players have consumed four to five Bawls apiece. They are
getting a little hyper. Tyler Whittaker admits that he has a slight
headache, but says he's ``not really jittery. I'm, like, extremely
awake.''
</P>
<P>
   You have to be alert to focus past the gunfire and the endless
pulsating sound of the electronic background music, to blast away
at the ``skins'' running past your virtual gun.
</P>
<P>
   A skin is a cyberbody, a player's appearance onscreen. A game
like Quake has many skin options. Some look like regular guys in
blue jeans, some like monsters. One looks like a cross between a
chicken and a giant eyeball.
</P>
<P>
   When a skin turns up on somebody else's computer screen, that
player's ``handle'' _ screen name _ shows up above it. At the same
time, running commentary appears in the upper left-hand corner of
the screen:
</P>
<P>
   ``Stryfo was machinegunned by SLaPpy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Xungan blew himself up.''
</P>
<P>
   Adam Slesinger uses the handle ``breadman.'' He's not quite sure
why; could mean food, could mean money. But, he says with more than
a hint of pride, ``People have come to associate `bread' with
`fear.' ''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There might be fear onscreen, but in the real world, relations
are convivial. Players share pointers and fix each other's
computers, and they form a neat line when pizza arrives.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, despite the caffeine and the basement's rising
temperature, real-life conflicts are few. There's a yelp of protest
if someone breaks a rule, and slight outrage about the most basic
gender issue: At one point, Sarah Andrade runs down the stairs,
yelling, ``Who left the toilet seat up?''
</P>
<P>
   Even the male-female distinctions are small, says Sara Domb, 25,
of Medford, Mass. Her one complaint is that she hasn't been beating
the boys. She wants to put herself on a training regimen: an hour
of fragging practice, every day.
</P>
<P>
   Fragging may be a serious pursuit, but Dan Ware sees uses for
gaming that surpass the simple joys of death and dismemberment. The
gaming urge can drive innovations in computer technology, he says.
Eventually, nongamers may benefit, too.
</P>
<P>
   As Ware said, ``But who's to say two companies couldn't hold a
meeting in this environment?''
</P>
<P>
   Presumably, without the blood.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
