<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AFTER 20 YEARS, SPELLING BEE'S PRONOUNCER HAS SEEN IT ALL
 &HT;    600&AMP;add. With SPELLING-BEE.
 &HT;    By BOB DART
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The word that comes to mind is P-A-T-I-E-N-C-E as
yet another speller asks Alex J. Cameron for a definition, and
language of origin, and alternative pronunciations, and use of the
word in a sentence, and then repeats the whole process before
launching the first letter.
</P>
<P>
   ``More and more, they have adults coaching them,'' explains
Cameron, the chairman of the English department at the University
of Dayton who on Thursday completed his 20th year as pronouncer of
the Scripps Howard National Spelling Bee.
</P>
<P>
   The common strategy is for spellers to take their time at the
microphone to avoid mistakes of haste, even on easy words. So every
one seems to ask all the questions allowed in the bee.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somebody has coached them to do it, no matter what,'' said
Cameron. ``It's irritating when it's clear that they know the word
... But from (the coaches') point of view, they're protecting the
speller.''
</P>
<P>
   From its humble beginnings in grammar school classrooms, the
spelling bee has somehow become serious business. For the seventh
year, ESPN broadcast the final rounds Thursday. The show was aired
again Thursday night on ESPN2.
</P>
<P>
   With ESPN reruns throughout the year, Cameron marveled, ``it's
amazing how many people have seen it.''
</P>
<P>
   The winner generally appears on several network television
programs and receives $10,000 in cash from sponsor Scripps Howard,
plus other prizes worth several thousand dollars more. And, of
course, an appearance at the national bee always provides grist for
essays on college applications.
</P>
<P>
   So contestants strive for years to become champion. Preparation
is so intense that competitors often buy a study guide that
includes a CD of Cameron calling out words so they can get
accustomed to his voice while practicing their spelling.
</P>
<P>
   The bee seemed a bit more relaxed when Cameron took over as
pronouncer at the start of the 1980s. He replaced Richard Baker,
another University of Dayton professor who had held the job for the
previous two decades.
</P>
<P>
   Back then, Cameron composed his own definitions and sentences.
But there has been an escalation in the number of contestants, and
in the number of words needed to find the best speller. So a panel
of experts now writes the definitions and sentences, while Cameron
concentrates on the nuances of enunciating the 1,000 or so words
that are readied for spelling _ or misspelling _ in the bee.
</P>
<P>
   The procession of spellers, all below the age of 16 and wearing
identical white polo shirts, can appear endless to spectators. But
Cameron has distinct memories of many competitors.
</P>
<P>
   There was one girl who didn't just cry, but absolutely wailed
after missing her word. Officials were worrying about her welfare,
Cameron recalled, when her brother, about 8 years old, looked out
from behind a curtain and said, ``Oh, she does this all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The next night at the banquet, she was all smiles,'' Cameron
said. ``She was an actress, I guess. You get some theatrics.''
</P>
<P>
   A speller who misses and is eliminated is immediately escorted
off the stage and into a ``comfort room'' where tantrums and
sulking can be conducted in private.
</P>
<P>
   Among his most memorable bees were the 1980 and 1981 contests,
Cameron said. He was assisting his former colleague in 1980 when
Jacques Bailly defeated Paige Pipkin on the word ``elucubrate.''
The following year, though, Paige Pipkin came back and won on the
word ``sarcophagus.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, 20 years later, the guy who came in first during Dick
Baker's last year is my assistant pronouncer and the girl whom he
beat and who came back to be my first winner is running the whole
bee,'' said Cameron.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Bailly, now the associate pronouncer, is an associate professor
of classics at the University of Vermont. The oth(after a mistake)
and convincing them that it's not as big a tragedy'' to lose.
</P>
<P>
   A noticeable change over the years is that the spellers are more
socially mature.
</P>
<P>
   Cameron remembers his predecessor describing how the kids
``played games like musical chairs,'' he said. ``They've gone from
that to holding dances.''
</P>
<P>
   On the Web: www.spellingbee.com
</P>
<P>
   Bob Dart's e-mail address is bobdart(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
