<HEADLINE>
THE BIG DISH ON INTERNET START-UP FAILURES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PATTI HARTIGAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Everybody loves a good failure. Oh c'mon, admit it. There is
nothing like a disaster of epic proportions to make the rest of us
feel less mundane. Nobody cares about the demise of the merely
mediocre; they're forgotten in the time it takes to shrug. But the
belly-flops of the arrogant are relished for all time. Evidence:
``Legs Diamond.'' ``Ishtar.'' ``Waterworld.''
</P>
<P>
   The nascent online entertainment business hasn't even had its
first success yet, but it's beginning to rack up a list of fabulous
flops. In recent weeks, both Pixelon and Digital Entertainment
Network (or simply, the Den) have gone belly up. And oh, what
fiascoes they were. Both ventures aimed to create a new form of
entertainment for the Internet. Pixelon described itself modestly
as an ``industry pioneer''; the Denizens fancied their efforts as
the biggest innovation since the talkies.
</P>
<P>
   Both operations were mired in scandal and mismanagement. Last
month, Pixelon founder Michael Fenne (a.k.a. David Stanley) was
exposed as a convicted swindler and fugitive. Den's cofounder, Marc
Collins-Rector, resigned last fall after he was accused of
molesting a young man. Den launched its site three times; Pixelon's
video player never worked. Den burned through $54 million in the
last year; Pixelon blew $16 million in a single night last fall
with a grandiose bash featuring a reunion of the Who.
</P>
<P>
   Pixelon's leaders seemed to think if they dazzled the world with
a big dot-com party, nobody would notice that their site crashed
every five seconds. Last fall, I told Pixelon's public relations
rep that it was impossible to watch the videos on the site, and he
responded by emphasizing the party lineup: ``We have Kiss! The
Dixie Chicks! The Who!'' Um, does anyone care that the site doesn't
work?
</P>
<P>
   At the very least, the folks at Den were passionate about their
vision _ even if it turned out to be misguided. They wanted to
create interactive video programs for niche audiences, targeting
gay teens, Latino teens, Asian teens, and, yes, even Christian
teens. Each episode has a built-in e-commerce mechanism; for
instance, when a song was part of the plot, the viewer could stop
the show and buy the tune. The idea wasn't half bad. After all, the
successful sites on the Internet cater to narrow, but loyal,
followings. But Den's shows weren't any good: With titles like
``Fear of a Punk Planet'' and ``Frat Ratz,'' they were painful to
watch.
</P>
<P>
   And Den made another major miscalculation. It targeted its
programs for viewers with high-speed Internet access, predicting
that broadband would quickly become mainstream. Wrong. A recent
study by Jupiter Communications showed that only 4.5 percent of all
Internet users have high-speed Internet access; and 52 percent of
all Internet users say they aren't willing to pay more for
high-speed access. That means they're not exactly itching to watch
the latest episode of say, ``Frat Ratz,'' or any of the other
programs being offered by online entertainment companies. BarkTV,
for instance, isn't exactly drawing a huge audience, but neither is
Entertaindom.com, Warner Bros.' overhyped amusement site.
</P>
<P>
   There is, of course, one form of video entertainment succeeding
online. Last week, the Victoria's Secret fashion show attracted 2
million viewers. Why? It sure wasn't the intelligent commentary.
</P>
<P>
   Some day, someone is going to invent a new form of entertainment
for the Internet that doesn't rely on scantily clad models. The
folks at Dreamworks are the next in line to try; the studio's
entertainment site, Pop.com, has been in the ``Coming soon'' stage
for months and months. For now, the fabulous failures of Den and
Pixelon stand out as lessons for the future. There's even a Web
site devoted to such flops: two weeks ago, a failed entrepreneur
launched www.startupfailures.com, a site billed as ``the place for
bouncing back.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   OK, so what have they done to Salon.com? They took away the
clean, spare list of stories and replaced it with a busy design
that looks like all the other news sites and portals online.
Frankly, I don't want to check the weather or chart my stocks or
shop while reading the latest dish (or doorknob-licking scandal) on
Salon. I don't want to listen to ``Salon radio'' while scanning
``stimulating commentary from the Web's most provocative site'' _
their words, not mine. And what's with the small type size and the
links that don't work?
</P>
<P>
   Needless to say, Salon underwent a redesign this week. According
to an editor's note titled ``We Feel Your Pain,'' the site has been
deluged with complaints. Editor David Talbot reminds readers that
they can still access a list of articles organized by date _ that
is, in case they don't really need to see a color glossy of Tom
Cruise over the headline, ``Missing: Intensity.'' File it under
``Missing: Simplicity.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of disappearing acts, somebody walked off with the
Internet's most famous phone booth. That's right, the National Park
Service and Pacific Bell have removed a lone phone booth located in
the middle of the Mojave Desert because it was, well, too popular.
The phone became an Internet sensation when a computer consultant
named Godfrey Daniels became obsessed with it and called its number
every day. He created a shrine of sorts at
www.deuceofclubs.com/moj/mojave.html. Word spread. The mystery
grew. People made pilgrimages to the remote site. They took photos.
They made calls. Apparently, they disturbed the tranquillity of the
area, so officials carted the thing away.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-01-00 1508EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000601.0160 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 15:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1892 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-COMPUTERS-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      06-01 0759
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTERS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TALK IS CHEAP BUT NOT REAL CLEAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I don't phone my mother in Chicago often enough. So she was glad
to hear from me recently, even if I'd only called to experiment on
her.
</P>
<P>
   I was trying out Yap Jack, a $160 device from Net2Phone Inc.
that plugs into a standard telephone and lets you make Internet
phone calls without a computer.
</P>
<P>
   Yap Jack works, and it might even become a hit with expatriates
looking to make cheap phone calls to Bombay or Beijing. But for
calls to less exotic locales, Yap Jack is more trouble than it's
worth.
</P>
<P>
   Yap Jack is about the size of a modem. That figures; it is a
modem, among other things. The device dials into your Internet
provider and logs on. But it also digitizes your voice and routes
it over the Internet to any telephone number in the world.
</P>
<P>
   Setting up the Yap Jack is the hard part. It's not easy to type
your Internet user name and password into the device, using only
the 12 keys of a push-button phone. After all, there's no ``(at)''
or ``/'' symbols on the phone keys.
</P>
<P>
   Yap Jack provides a system for getting around this, including a
British-accented female voice to offer assistance. Still, it took
me about six tries to get everything punched in correctly. People
with no Internet experience would have an even worse time of it.
For one thing, they'd have to sign up with an Internet provider
before they could use Yap Jack.
</P>
<P>
   Using Yap Jack is also a bit more complicated than making a
standard phone call. You pick up the phone, push a button on the
Yap Jack box, and press 1 on the phone keypad. Then you dial the
area code and phone number, and the pound key. And then you hang
up.
</P>
<P>
   Here's what happens next: Yap Jack dials your Internet provider
and logs you in. That takes maybe 20 seconds. Then it sends an
Internet message to Net2Phone's network, telling it what number
you're calling. The message gets routed to the Net2Phone server
computer that's nearest to your call's final destination.
</P>
<P>
   That computer transforms the Internet call into a regular
telephone call, dials the number, and notifies your Yap Jack box
that everything's ready. The box starts beeping, you pick up your
phone, and there's your mom in Chicago, asking why you don't call
more often.
</P>
<P>
   The whole process takes a minute or two. Yes, it's cheaper this
way _ 2.9 cents a minute compared to, say, 7 cents for AT&AMP;T long
distance. But with Yap Jack you pay the usual penalty for Internet
calling: static, disconcerting pauses and beer-barrel acoustics. I
spent most of my chat with Mama asking her to repeat herself. She
didn't mind _ she loves talking to her baby. But I found it a bit
of a drag.
</P>
<P>
   It all comes from moving voice traffic over the public Internet.
Each data packet gets bounced six ways from Sunday through the
Internet ``cloud,'' and some arrive late or out of sequence. That
doesn't matter when you're sending e-mail, but mishandled voice
packets lead to lousy sound quality.
</P>
<P>
   There is a cure for the problem: Internet phone systems that
don't use the Internet. Major companies such as IDT Corp.,
Net2Phone's parent firm, use their own private Internet to carry
phone traffic. Use a Net2Phone calling card to place a call, and
your voice goes over this private network, never touching the
regular Internet. This time, a call to mom sounds just as good as
AT&AMP;T. But you have to dial an extra 14 digits to log onto the IDT
network, merely to save a nickel a minute.
</P>
<P>
   Internet telephone service seemed like a world-changing idea
when it cost 20 cents a minute or more to make a long-distance
call. Today, there's not much point to it for domestic users.
</P>
<P>
   But it could pay off if you place a lot of overseas calls. Yap
Jack users do all right on calls to Bombay _ 34 cents a minute
compared to AT&AMP;T's 55 cents. China costs 19 cents a minute with Yap
Jack, and less for calls to big cities. AT&AMP;T charges 32 cents to
China.
</P>
<P>
   For an hourlong chinwag with a brother in Beijing, there's
something to be said for Yap Jack. Such a caller might tolerate the
lousy sound quality, or the two-minute delay as they wait for Yap
Jack to process the call. I might become a big fan of this product,
if my mother ever moves to China. Till then, I'll stick to a
traditional long distance phone service. And I'll try to call more
often, Mama. Promise.
</P>
<P>
   Hiawatha Bray is a member of the Globe staff. He can be reached
by e-mail at bray(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
