<SLUG> BC-AUTOS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW CHRYSLER CRUISER   BRINGS REPORTS OF GOUGING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (l and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROYAL FORD  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It seemed a simple enough statement: ``If you run into gouging,
let me know.'' I wrote that sentence last week and slipped it deep
into a review of the hot new Chrysler PT Cruiser.
</P>
<P>
   It was in there because I'd heard reports that some dealers were
jacking up the price of the Cruiser by thousands of dollars, and
since I know folks are standing in line out there looking to buy
Cruisers, it seemed like a good idea to ask the readers. Maybe we'd
catch a couple of dealers price gouging.
</P>
<P>
   Well, a funny thing happened on the way to proving a theory.
</P>
<P>
   First of all, there was a flood of e-mail that proves to me
that, no, there aren't a handful of dealers out there ``gouging''
on the price of Cruisers. It is a widespread phenomenon, with
readers reporting jacked-up prices at Chrysler dealers in New
England.
</P>
<P>
   Some people have placed orders based on the manufacturer's
suggested retail price only to find $1,000 to $3,000 added to their
bill later. Take it or leave it, because if you don't, we'll sell
the car to someone else today, some have been told.
</P>
<P>
   Others were coldly informed that everybody's doing it, so if
they want a Cruiser, they'd better be ready to pony up the dough _
often with a hefty down payment and the prospect of months of
waiting for their car to arrive.
</P>
<P>
   One woman, asked to pay $2,000 over sticker, wrote: ``When we
told the salesman we felt like we were being gouged (at a Peabody
dealership) and that we don't even like to pay sticker, he actually
said, `Well, if you're not paying at least sticker, aren't you
gouging the dealer?''' The answer to that is no, but that's a topic
for another column.
</P>
<P>
   From Plymouth came the story of a man who was told, ``I would
have to put down $1,000 and the price would be $2,500 to $3,000
over sticker.''
</P>
<P>
   And in Woburn, another man said he waited an hour before a
Cruiser salesperson could even get to him and was then told ``the
price was $3,000 over list price.''
</P>
<P>
   Many folks wrote to say they simply walked out when they felt
they were being gouged.
</P>
<P>
   But here's the rub: Several writers pointed out that even as
they walked away from deals, there were others lurking in the
showrooms ready to plunk down what the dealers were asking.
</P>
<P>
   And that's when I started to ponder my own theories on gouging.
</P>
<P>
   The last time I raised the topic _ when writing about the Honda
S2000 _ an e-mail came my way from a man asking if, in fact,
letting demand set the price for any automobile is not simply the
fair and free market at work.
</P>
<P>
   I wasn't sure how I felt about that, though I knew he had a
point. It nagged at me months later when I tested the new Toyota
MR2 Spyder, like the S2000, another hot drop-top sportscar.
</P>
<P>
   And then came 10 days in the PT Cruiser, the most gawked-at car
I have ever driven. Park it and people crowd around it. Leave it
alone and unlocked and you might return to find a stranger sitting
in the driver's seat just getting the feel of the car. Demand for
it is so high that Chrysler's initial plans to sell 50,000 Cruisers
are being re-ramped to sell as many as four times that.
</P>
<P>
   So, in fact, while there is genuine and understandable outrage
among some folks over the inflated prices _ flat-out profit-taking
by dealerships _ it is customers who are driving up the price.
</P>
<P>
   And where does that leave us on the issue of ``gouging?''
</P>
<P>
   It leaves me firmly planted on both sides of the fence.
</P>
<P>
   That's because I don't think what has happened with the Honda
and Toyota hot cars is the same as what is happening with the PT
Cruiser.
</P>
<P>
   Why? Because both the MR2 and the S2000 were meant to be
``halo'' cars _ vehicles whose appearance in a manufacturer's fleet
adds an aura that will help dealers across the country sell more of
that manufacturer's other cars. If you can't swing the MR2 or the
S2000, for instance, at least you'll feel better about the Accord
or Celica you do buy.
</P>
<P>
   Further, both of these are cars that the manufacturers have said
flat out were meant for dealers to use _ at very reasonable prices
_ as rewards to their most loyal customers.
</P>
<P>
   As in: ``Hey, Sue, you've bought three Accords here over the
years. How'd you like to get into the hottest car we make at a very
good price?''
</P>
<P>
   Make no mistake. Honda and Toyota let their dealers know they
did not want to see price gouging on the $23,000 MR2 or the $30,000
S2000.
</P>
<P>
   The response of many dealers? Hah! Gouging on the Honda has
reached as high as $10,000 and, on the MR2, the inflated price has
approached $30,000.
</P>
<P>
   This does not make sense to me. Neither car is being produced in
great numbers. For instance, only 5,000 MR2s will be sold in the
United States this year. That means most dealers will get only a
couple of the cars to sell and some may get none.
</P>
<P>
   And those who do get them and who gouge on the price are selling
the potential for great good will for what can only be a few
thousand dollars of profit. A drop of cash, probably, in the annual
bucket of profits.
</P>
<P>
   So, yes, I consider hugely inflated prices on these limited
edition vehicles to be gouging. Dealers are gouging their buyers
and, stupidly, they are gouging themselves by tainting what could
be a well of good will.
</P>
<P>
   The Cruiser, however, seems to me another matter. If, in fact,
its annual sales get into the hundreds of thousands and people are
lined up to buy them at the higher prices, then I guess that is the
free market at work _ fairly. Chrysler is not telling dealers to
back off. Buyers are telling dealers they'll pay the price.
</P>
<P>
   Across a broad range of demographics Americans are saying a fair
price is, indeed, $2,000 and $3,000 above the MSRP. Many of us may
not like it, but the market is setting the price on the PT Cruiser.
</P>
<P>
   Royal Ford's e-mail address is ford(at) globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
