<HEADLINE>
FUND CHIEF'S RARE TRADES PAY OFF IN A BIG WAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sam Isaly isn't going to make any stock trader rich. In the last
year, his mutual fund has bought a total of 12 new stocks and sold
12 stocks.
</P>
<P>
   ``That can be twisted in an amusing thought, that we work one
day a month,'' said Isaly, manager of the Eaton Vance Worldwide
Health Sciences fund.
</P>
<P>
   No one asks a fund manager how much he works. Inquiring minds
want to know how much he earns for his shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   On that score, there are mostly raves about Isaly's performance.
In an investment sector with enviable prospects, thanks to
advancing technology and a graying population, he can claim stellar
records over the recent past and the long haul.
</P>
<P>
   Eaton Vance Worldwide Health Sciences, up 32 percent so far this
year, has been earning nearly double the median returns of health
and biotechnology funds tracked by Lipper Inc. in 2000 and over the
last 12 months.
</P>
<P>
   The $457 million fund's one-year return of 78.4 percent, through
last week, technically ranked it eighth among the 57 sector funds
tracked by Lipper. It earned less than just one fund dedicated
broadly to health care investments. The median health care or
biotech fund earned 30.8 percent over the same period.
</P>
<P>
   Isaly's performance ranks first among that same crowd over five
years (270 percent) and third over the last 10 years (707 percent).
Isaly, 55, who has used a wheelchair since a high school spinal
cord injury, manages the Eaton Vance fund as a subadvisor from New
York, with the help of a dozen other analysts.
</P>
<P>
   Isaly's tendency to buy and hold stocks might lead you to
believe he earned his numbers by investing conservatively and
letting the rising health care tide lift the fund. Wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Eaton Vance Worldwide Health Sciences owns lots of big, global
pharmaceutical stocks, just as every other health care fund does.
But Isaly mixes those holdings with an unusually large count of
what he describes as superaggressive stock picks from around the
world, often focused on biotechnology.
</P>
<P>
   About 15 percent of the fund's assets are usually invested in
what he calls US specialty stocks. Another 5 percent are more
speculative stocks based elsewhere around the world. International
stocks account for about a third of the fund's investments.
</P>
<P>
   That's not an easy strategy to follow when the long-term outlook
for gigantic global health care stocks is so rosy. The first
pressing question: Why rock the boat?
</P>
<P>
   What happens if a fund manager underinvests in giants like
Pfizer and Warner-Lambert Co., which combined make up about 10
percent of the world's biopharmaceutical stock capitalization by
Isley's count, and those stocks roar ahead? Indexes that serve as
the benchmarks for health sector investors move with those big
stocks and will leave more speculative money managers sadly behind.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can compose a portfolio for the top 50 names, and you'll
get an earnings growth rate, we believe, of 12 percent,'' Isaly
said. ``Don't rock the boat; ask me to deliver you 15 percent with
some stock selection, and I probably will do that. But by moving
away from the middle of the road a bit, I'm able to add another 5
percent return.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, he's added a bit more than that. Eaton Vance Worldwide
Health Science has delivered an average of 23.4 percent a year over
the last decade.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, Isaly has lots of money in big names. The Eaton
Vance fund has 7.6 percent of its assets invested in
Warner-Lambert, another 4.9 percent in American Home Products
Corp., and 4.4 percent in Pharmacia AB.
</P>
<P>
   But there are also lots of lesser-known names, like LJL
Biosystems Inc. and Caliper Technologies Corp., two California
companies, and Geltex Pharmaceuticals Inc. of Waltham.
</P>
<P>
   One key calculation for Isaly's more adventuresome picks: He
expects most of those companies will enjoy their most vigorous
stock appreciation in a period starting two years before they first
posts profits and ending two years after the initial earnings.
</P>
<P>
   The best of the small-stock picks: Abgenix Inc., a
biopharmaceutical stock Isaly bought for $3.37 per share in a
private placement three years ago. The stock, now one of his fund's
bigger holdings, traded at $79 per share Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm kind of hapy to have some Warner-Lambert, Novartis, and
Roche, because they're stable growers,'' Isaly said. ``But I know
if I stick only to stable growers, I'm going to get that kind of
return. I need to keep renewing the portfolio with fuel
injection.''
</P>
<P>
   Steven Syre (929-2918) and Charles Stein (929-2922) can also be
reached by e-mail at boscap(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
