<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARS-REVIEW-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 NEW GRAND CHEROKEE IS GRANDER THAN EVER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (l and f coding)  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROYAL FORD  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When I lay hands on an SUV, one of the first things I like to do
is take it where most SUVs never go _ off road.
</P>
<P>
   In my neck of the New Hampshire woods, that means out where the
skidders have been, following the rutted, muddy, stony, log-strewn
paths of departed or ongoing logging operations. It's a good test
for these rigs because skidders do not pause for steep or sloshy,
stone or stump.
</P>
<P>
   So where better to start my week in the 2000 Jeep Grand Cherokee
Limited 4WD? It would be a good test to see if Daimler-Chrysler, in
its 1999 makeover of the Grand Cherokee, had pulled off the
Jekyll-and-Hyde feat of turning this Jeep into a luxurious and
smooth highway performer while at the same time saving its solid
off-road soul.
</P>
<P>
   I took it up steep grades where you could see only the sky
through the windshield. Plunged it through mud, walked it gingerly
over rocks and stumps one wheel at a time, pushed through a
streambed, across a thick scattering of old bark and wood chips,
coaxed it down the same steep grade it had just climbed, this time
with the front bumper seemingly ready to burrow in at any minute.
</P>
<P>
   It remains an off-road beast _ better even than its earlier
incarnation.
</P>
<P>
   Part of that has to do with its new engine, the optional
4.7-liter, 235-horsepower plant that replaces the 5.2 and 5.9
liters of old. This new powerplant has 15 more horsepower than the
old 5.2, only 10 less than the 5.9, and gets better gas mileage
than either (17 miles per gallon in off-road and highway driving).
It's a solid case of overhead cams and new technology knocking
aside the old push-rod engine.
</P>
<P>
   It has power that makes it a stubborn crawler up steep hills,
holds the nearly 2-ton rig back on steep declines, and turns it
into a guttural and strong performer on the highway.
</P>
<P>
   But what is best about this new Jeep is its new all-wheel-drive
system. Called Quadra-Trac, it is a full-time, all-wheel-drive
setup that uses sensors to shift torque front to rear, side to
side, and even to single wheels. This means that, if three wheels
are slipping and only one has the faintest hope of purchase, that
wheel gets the torque to nudge you forward. It's great off-road and
will be wonderful for commuting in the snow.
</P>
<P>
   The Grand Cherokee stands apart in appearance from its more
staid stablemate, the Cherokee, because of a subtle design shift.
They still share the same mouthful-of-Chiclets grille, but on the
Grand Cherokee, that grille is angled back from bumper to hood. The
hood rises in a wedge to a more sloping windshield and a higher
roof line drops off at the rear in a rounded dip. The Cherokee
remains the angular, oblong box it has long been.
</P>
<P>
   The softer lines of the Grand Cherokee hint at the luxury inside
_ an air of comfort meant to please those who won't be chasing
skidders through the woods.
</P>
<P>
   The front leather bucket seats have good support up the sides,
though they could use a bit more firmness at the thigh. The rear
bench, billed as a three-person seat, is comfortable at the doors,
but a strange notch has been cut from the cushion at the center,
leaving a middle passenger with less space on which to sit. Leg
room in the rear is a bit tight, as well.
</P>
<P>
   Ergonomically, all is relatively simple with window, door, and
mirror controls on the driver's side armrest, cruise control on the
steering wheel, light controls on one steering column stem, and
wipers on another. Audio and climate controls are big and easy to
use.
</P>
<P>
   Though many SUVs are built on truck platforms, Jeep has put the
new Grand Cherokee with integrated body and frame rails, making it
stiffer and more stable. As with almost any tall vehicle, you get
some sensation of side-to-side roll when cornering at higher
speeds, though the Grand Cherokee is another example of
manufacturers changing suspension and construction methods to make
them more stable than the tippy boxes of the recent past.
</P>
<P>
   This model came with an ``Upcountry'' suspension system that
included high-pressure gas shocks, special front and rear springs,
and stabilizer bar. Off-road skid plates and shields were included
in this package.
</P>
<P>
   The five-speed transmission did a too-quick, jerky upshift in
lower gears than I would like, but once rolling was smooth in
shifting through higher gears. Disc brakes, assisted by ABS, at all
four wheels brought it to swift, sure stops.
</P>
<P>
   Nice Touch:
</P>
<P>
   --The auxiliary audio control buttons tucked on the backside of
the steering wheel. Felt as if I was playing a video game as I
fooled with volume and stations.
</P>
<P>
   Annoyance:
</P>
<P>
   --The placing of the driver's seat memory buttons on the door
panel above the armrest. My elbow kept hitting them and changing my
seat position.
</P>
<P>
   Royal Ford's e-mail address is ford(at) globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
