r a BC-O'DONOHUE-OBIT-HNS &LR;      06-01 0545
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-O'DONOHUE-OBIT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     JOSEPH O'DONOHUE, ONE-TIME SOCIALITE, DIES AT 88 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By RAY DELGADO  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Joseph J. O'Donohue IV, a former New York
socialite who moved to San Francisco after squandering his fortune,
died Wednesday after a heart attack. He was 88.
</P>
<P>
   O'Donohue, once dubbed ``the most beautiful boy in New York,''
was well known in New York City's social circles, entertaining
celebrities Josephine Baker, Greta Garbo, Marlene Dietrich, Gore
Vidal and assorted royalty. He also traveled frequently to Germany
in the 1930s, where he once dined with Adolf Hitler and expressed
his disapproval of the Fuhrer's anti-Jewish policies.
</P>
<P>
   Excessive spending and bad money management ended the
high-flying lifestyle O'Donohue had become accustomed to and in
1958 he moved to San Francisco, where he led a relatively quiet
life that included friendships with the city's social circle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would love people to remember Joe O'Donohue as a real true
gentleman and one of the last true San Francisco characters,'' said
David Perry, a close friend and a free-lance writer who had been
working with O'Donohue on his memoirs.
</P>
<P>
   O'Donohue was born on Jan. 28, 1912, in New York to a family
that had amassed a considerable fortune, mainly through real estate
holdings and the operation of a ferry service between Manhattan and
Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   Entertaining and being entertained by socialites, actors,
authors and politicians in New York in the 1920s and 1930s,
O'Donohue was also very passionate about ballet, holding a row of
seats at the New York Ballet and hosting lavish parties for dancers
at his Park Avenue apartment.
</P>
<P>
   O'Donohue spent summers in Germany in the 1930s, hobnobbing with
titled nobility and chancellors, culminating in an encounter over
coffee with Hitler, where he complained about the leader's
anti-Jewish policies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things got somewhat tense for a moment,'' O'Donohue recalled
in a 1988 interview with the San Francisco Examiner. ``I don't
think he particularly liked my telling him his idea was wrong, but
I had to in all honesty.''
</P>
<P>
   Mr. O'Donohue walked away from the meeting with an autographed
picture of Hitler.
</P>
<P>
   World War II ended much of the lavishness that O'Donohue had
experienced throughout his life and he had to tap into his share of
the family fortune to pay off debts and cover for bad financial
planning, leaving him strapped for cash.
</P>
<P>
   ``My fortune, I simply did away with it,'' O'Donohue said in the
Examiner article. ``Bad advice, bad lawyers, bad taxes _ it
survived the Depression but it didn't survive me. I've accomplished
so little except passing through life causing no harm _ and totally
demolishing and destroying a fifth-generation estate. With glee!''
</P>
<P>
   In many respects, O'Donohue considered his move to San Francisco
his exile from upper-crust society. He survived on a limited
pension, but he still managed to become close friends with San
Francisco socialites.
</P>
<P>
   O'Donohue is survived by cousins Jack and Claudia Steers of
Connecticut and film director Mel Ferrer of Carpinteria, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   His remains will be cremated and buried in New York at the
family's cemetery plot.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
