<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 15:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1925 &Cx1f; tab-z
r s BC-BUY-NBA-TITLE-SLATE     06-01 1059
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUY-NBA-TITLE-SLATE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAN YOU BUY AN NBA CHAMPIONSHIP? 
</HEADLINE>
  (Slate commentary)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (The following ``separate buy'' article from SLATE, the premier
online magazine of politics and culture, is available from the New
York Times Syndicate. Please contact syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480)
</P>
<P>
   (Malcolm Gladwell is a staff writer at The New Yorker)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BY MALCOLM GLADWELL &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One of the main reasons for last year's NBA lockout was that
owners wanted to impose some sort of fiscal discipline on the game.
They didn't want basketball to turn into the farce that is modern
baseball, where a handful of teams with the deepest pockets
monopolize all the best free agents and, as a result, all the
championships.
</P>
<P>
   To that end, the NBA's new Collective Bargaining Agreement
imposes a salary cap to limit the payrolls of individual teams and
also has a luxury tax _ to begin in the 2001-2002 season _ to
penalize those teams that exceed the cap.
</P>
<P>
   If you look at the current salary structure of the league, it
looks as if that effort at discipline is working. Virtually all of
the most successful teams have payrolls within the fairly narrow
range of $45 million to $50 million.
</P>
<P>
   (One way to look at this is to think in terms of a basketball
price/earnings ratio, where price is the number of millions a team
spends on players' salaries and earnings are wins. Most good teams
have p/e ratios of less than one: Miami [.978], Utah [.984],
Phoenix [.877], Philadelphia [.863] are typical, meaning that in
the NBA right now the consensus is that you have to spend just
under a million dollars to ``buy'' a regular season win.)
</P>
<P>
   The cap is also credited with the emergence of highly
cost-conscious rebuilding strategies in places like Chicago and
Orlando.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, Lakers sources said that owner Jerry Buss
was balking at paying Shaquille O'Neal the full $83.5 million,
three-year contract extension Shaq is due in 2003 because Buss
didn't want to pay the luxury tax. That sounds like fiscal
discipline is working. Right?
</P>
<P>
   Well, actually not. And for proof look no further than this
year's playoffs, where the final four teams also happen to be the
teams with the four highest payrolls. In fact, Portland ($73.9
million) and New York ($71.3 million) are spending almost $20
million more on players than the third highest-spending team and
$30 million more than the average for most competitive franchises.
(The p/e for the Trail Blazers is 1.25 and for the Knicks an
outsize 1.426.)
</P>
<P>
   Portland and New York, quite simply, bought their way into this
year's playoffs, which, under the collective bargaining agreement,
wasn't supposed to happen. What went wrong?
</P>
<P>
   The answer is that the agreement has a crippling loophole. First
of all, the NBA has what is called a ``soft'' cap (unlike the NFL,
which has a ``hard'' cap), in order to promote stability. What that
means is that a team is allowed to exceed the cap in order to
re-sign its own free agents.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, if I'm Orlando and I want to sign Tim Duncan
this off-season, I'm limited by how much room I have under the cap.
If I'm San Antonio, trying to re-sign Duncan, I can pay him
whatever I want. The soft cap explains why Portland has a payroll
of almost $74 million, even though the cap is $34 million: They are
awfully generous when it comes to re-signing players.
</P>
<P>
   To rein in teams that over-exploit the soft cap, the collective
bargaining agreement also includes a luxury tax. According to a
complicated formula, a second cap is created _ significantly higher
than the first _ and for every dollar a team is over the second
cap, they're required to pay a dollar in penalties.
</P>
<P>
   But here's where the loophole comes in. The second cap doesn't
automatically apply to big spenders. It kicks in only when the
total of all players' salaries exceeds 61.1 percent of total
basketball revenues for that year. And that 61.1 percent is a very
generous level. In all, it's never been breached.
</P>
<P>
   Last year _ prorated for a full season _ players' salaries were
about 58 percent of revenue. This year, even after players'
salaries jumped a whopping 18 percent in the off-season, the
National Basketball Players Association estimates they'll reach
only about 59 percent of revenue.
</P>
<P>
   It's possible, for course, that by 2001-2002, when the luxury
tax kicks in for the first time, continued salary inflation will
have pushed us above that mark. But that season, it should be
pointed out, will be the fourth and final year of the NBA's
television deal with NBC. And if, as expected, the next deal is
more lucrative, the share of revenues taken up by salaries is going
to fall again. The luxury tax may well only be a one-year
phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
   The genius _ if you want to call it that _ of the Trail Blazers
and the Knicks, in other words, is that they recognized, in advance
of everyone else, that the luxury tax was essentially toothless. So
long as most NBA teams exercise some restraint _ which most owners
clearly want to do _ the system allows teams like the Knicks and
Trail Blazers to spend all they want.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that the Clippers spend only $22.5 million and the
Bulls spend $27 million means that Portland can get away with
paying Damon Stoudamire $10 million a year and Jermaine O'Neal _
Jermaine O'Neal! _ $5 million a year. It's hard to comprehend just
how idiotic this system is.
</P>
<P>
   The reason we have regulatory or enforcement systems of any sort
_ from the IRS to police departments _ is not because most of us
want to break the law; it's because a tiny minority wants to break
the law. Professional sports are no different. Competitive
inequities are caused by the actions of a small number of owners
like George Steinbrenner or Peter Angelos or Paul Allen who, by
virtue of their temperament or deep pockets, are willing to pay
anything for a winner. A solution that gives the profligate few
carte blanche is not a solution.
</P>
<P>
   We gave up half the season last year for this?
</P>
<P>
   -------
</P>
<P>
   Visit Slate on the Web at: http://www.slate.com
</P>
<P>
   Copyright 2000 Slate
</P>
<P>
   (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-01-00 1523EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000601.0169 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 15:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1929 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u f BC-EXAMINER-SALE-HNS &LR;      06-01 1899
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EXAMINER-SALE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     JUDGE IN S.F. NEWSPAPER CASE PROMISES A PROMPT RULING 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By SETH ROSENFELD  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ U.S. District Judge Vaughn R. Walker, hearing
final arguments in Clint Reilly's antitrust suit to block the
Hearst Corp. from buying the San Francisco Chronicle, pointedly
questioned lawyers about Hearst's plan to give the Fang family a
$66 million subsidy to buy its Examiner.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can't you conclude that the only purpose for which that
subsidy is being paid is to curry favor with the Department of
Justice and local political authorities?'' Walker asked a lawyer
for the Chronicle on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   At another point, the judge sharply questioned the U.S. Justice
Department's assertion that the Fangs would produce an Examiner
that was fully competitive with Hearst's Chronicle, remarking,
``that's certainly not what the evidence suggests is going to
happen here.''
</P>
<P>
   And under questioning by the judge, a Hearst lawyer revealed
that the Justice Department had threatened to sue Hearst for
antitrust violations if it did not sell The Examiner to the Fangs,
who publish the free three-times-a-week San Francisco Independent.
</P>
<P>
   Walker heard more than five hours of arguments from the lawyers
in the unprecedented trial. He homed in on whether Reilly, a real
estate investor and 1999 mayoral candidate, had legal standing to
bring the suit, whether Hearst's sale of The Examiner to the Fangs
was legitimate, and the $66 million subsidy.
</P>
<P>
   The hearing in the overflowing courtroom on the 17th floor of
the Phillip Burton Federal Building ended the nation's first-ever
trial on the dissolution of a joint operating agreement between
newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   The agreements are allowed under an exemption to antitrust laws
that Reilly contends has been misused by publishers around the
country.
</P>
<P>
   Walker said he would attempt to rule promptly. Lawyers in the
case speculated he would decide within a few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The judge's decision could dramatically affect the future of San
Francisco's daily newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   Walker indicated he is considering the legality of the Examiner
and Chronicle sales separately. He could approve or bar both deals,
or approve the Chronicle sale and nix the Examiner sale, lawyers
said.
</P>
<P>
   Hearst's sale of The Examiner to the Fangs is contingent on its
purchase of the Chronicle.
</P>
<P>
   Reilly is asking Walker to permanently bar both newspaper deals
on the ground that they violate antitrust laws and the Newspaper
Preservation Act.
</P>
<P>
   He also wants Walker to nullify two clauses in Hearst's joint
operating agreement with the Chronicle that, he claims, unfairly
exclude other potential buyers for the paper.
</P>
<P>
   Reilly alleges that Hearst's proposed deals would leave Hearst
with the only metropolitan daily newspaper in San Francisco, an
illegal monopoly that would reduce the number of editorial voices
and raise advertising and subscription rates.
</P>
<P>
   He claims Hearst's deal to sell The Examiner to the Fangs _ and
give them a subsidy of up to $66 million over three years _ is a
sham, because the subsidy is insufficient to publish a viable
competitor to the Chronicle.
</P>
<P>
   Hearst, Chronicle Publishing Co. and the Fangs have denied
Reilly's claims and are asking Walker to let the deals proceed.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of hearing neat summations of the two-week trial, which
began May 1 and was put over for final arguments, Walker turned
Wednesday's hearing into an extended colloquy.
</P>
<P>
   Walker by turns questioned and challenged the lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph M. Alioto argued first, presenting Reilly's side for
nearly two hours.
</P>
<P>
   Alioto began by claiming that the newspaper industry in general,
and Hearst and Chronicle in particular, had misused their privilege
under the Newspaper Preservation Act as a ``stepping stone to
monopoly.''
</P>
<P>
   Since 1965, The Examiner and Chronicle have had a joint
operating agreement under which they pool all revenue, use it to
pay their combined costs of printing, circulation and advertising
operations, and split the remainder evenly. Each paper then pays
the costs of its independent editorial staffs.
</P>
<P>
   Such agreements are allowed under the act, an exemption from
antitrust laws meant to keep alive newspapers in danger of failing
due to declining circulation _ in this case The Examiner _ so
communities could benefit from multiple editorial voices.
</P>
<P>
   But now, Alioto argued, Hearst was trying to close or sell The
Examiner on the basis that it was failing and buy the Chronicle. He
claimed that would violate the papers' duty under the act to
maintain the joint operating agreement until it expires in 2005.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the court does not prohibit Hearst from buying the
Chronicle, then it's a road map to monopoly in any city,'' Alioto
said. Newspapers in 13 cities have joint operating agreements.
</P>
<P>
   Walker interrupted to ask Alioto how Hearst's plan to sell The
Examiner to the Fangs fit in with his antitrust claim.
</P>
<P>
   Even it if were a ``pure political ploy on Hearst's part to
curry favor with City Hall and the Department of Justice,'' Walker
asked, how was that an antitrust violation?
</P>
<P>
   Alioto replied that the deal amounted to an illegal combination
between the Fangs and Hearst, saying they never intended to have
truly competing papers.
</P>
<P>
   The Examiner sale to the Fangs, Alioto argued, was a ``down and
dirty bribe.''
</P>
<P>
   He claimed that in return for getting the deal, the Fangs used
their political connections to generate support for Hearst's
purchase of the Chronicle.
</P>
<P>
   The Chronicle deal had been opposed by Mayor Willie Brown and
other local politicians, as well as the U.S. Justice Department,
which had said San Francisco should have competing daily
newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department's antitrust department was investigating
Hearst's plan to buy the Chronicle, as was the San Francisco
district attorney and city attorney.
</P>
<P>
   Alioto argued that Hearst executives agreed to the Fang deal to
placate local politicians.
</P>
<P>
   When Walker questioned whether Reilly had standing to bring the
suit, Alioto said the Clayton Antitrust Act allowed any person to
sue to stop the threatened antitrust activity.
</P>
<P>
   Walker noted that Reilly would still have two newspapers after
the deals go through, ``so he's certainly not injured as a consumer
of newspapers.''
</P>
<P>
   Alioto argued that the Fangs' Examiner would not be a viable
alternative to Hearst's Chronicle, depriving Reilly and other
consumers of comparable alternatives.
</P>
<P>
   Alioto also argued that Walker should void two clauses in the
joint operating agreement that, he says, unfairly prevented other
major media companies from buying the Chronicle and competing with
Hearst.
</P>
<P>
   A ``first right of refusal'' clause gives each partner in the
agreement the chance to outbid any other potential buyer of the
other partner's paper. The other clause bars any firm that owns a
paper within 60 miles of San Francisco from becoming a partner in
the agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Walker said it's easy to see how the clauses might harm the
Chronicle by fending off bidders, but asked how they hurt consumers
like Reilly.
</P>
<P>
   Alioto said the clauses threatened to give Hearst a newspaper
monopoly that would harm consumers by offering fewer newspapers and
higher prices.
</P>
<P>
   When Walker questioned J. Thomas Rosch, a lawyer for Chronicle
Publishing, the judge asked whether economic policy wasn't better
served by simply shutting The Examiner rather than giving the Fangs
$66 million and letting The Examiner suffer a slow death.
</P>
<P>
   Rosch agreed the money would be better spent on making the
Chronicle a stronger competitor against other Bay Area media.
</P>
<P>
   That led Walker to ask, ``Can't you conclude that the only
purpose for which that subsidy is being paid is to curry favor with
the Department of Justice and local political authorities?''
</P>
<P>
   Rosch deferred the matter to the other lawyers, and contended
that Reilly lacked standing to sue because he had failed to show he
would suffer actual harm as a result of the proposed newspaper
deals.
</P>
<P>
   Rosch reaffirmed his view that the two restrictive clauses in
the joint operating agreement are not exempt from antitrust law,
meaning Walker could find them illegal. But Rosch disputed Alioto's
contention that the measures had deterred other bidders for the
Chronicle.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Halling, a Hearst lawyer, also denied Alioto's claim that
Hearst had used the 60-mile restriction and first right of refusal
to get an unfair advantage over other potential bidders for the
Chronicle.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no misuse of the joint operating agreement in any
sense,'' Halling said. ``Hearst had the rights it had and had the
position it had simply as a matter of private contract.''
</P>
<P>
   But Halling, disagreeing with Rosch, said the clauses were
exempt from antitrust law and therefore less likely to be voided.
</P>
<P>
   Halling argued that Hearst had agreed to pay more for the
Chronicle than Knight-Ridder and other bidders because Hearst
already owned half the printing presses it shares with the
Chronicle, and by buying the Chronicle's half would own the whole
printing operation. Other bidders, in contrast, would have to spend
more to get a complete press.
</P>
<P>
   Walker questioned why Hearst agreed to give the Fangs a subsidy
to buy The Examiner instead of simply closing The Examiner as a
failing business.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why wasn't it shut down?'' the judge asked. ``Why didn't
Hearst say to everybody who was trying to influence Hearst to sell
The Examiner, `It's a dead newspaper. It's better buried?' Why
didn't Hearst just stick to its principles in this matter and take
the political risk that attended that?''
</P>
<P>
   Hearst, Halling replied, had a deadline to buy the Chronicle and
feared that the pending investigations could delay the deals.
</P>
<P>
   Hearst's contract to buy the Chronicle expires June 28, after
which the Chronicle Publishing Co. may walk away from the deal,
Hearst's Senior Vice President James M. Asher said in an interview.
Chronicle Publishing could put the paper up for sale anew, keep it,
or exercise a separate right to extend the contract through
October, Asher said.
</P>
<P>
   Walker suggested that Hearst, the Fangs and the Justice
Department all had been misleading in claiming the Fangs would
produce a metropolitan daily newspaper that would fully compete
with Hearst's Chronicle.
</P>
<P>
   Halling denied Hearst had said that.
</P>
<P>
   Walker quoted the Justice Department's press release, which
said, ``For the first time in 35 years San Francisco will have two
independent daily newspapers'' _ which the judge said referred to
1965 when the Chronicle and The Examiner were both metropolitan
morning papers.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's certainly not what the evidence suggests is going to
happen here,'' Walker said.
</P>
<P>
   Gerald Connell, another Hearst lawyer, discounted what he called
Alioto's claim of a ``rather spectacular conspiracy involving the
attorney general of the United States, the mayor of the city, the
Fangs, the Hearsts, and maybe a few others.''
</P>
<P>
   Hearst had told the department that ``there was no life left in
The Examiner,'' Connell said.
</P>
<P>
   But, he added, ``What we were hearing, your honor, was if you
are going to close down The Examiner, we are going to sue you.''
</P>
<P>
   To avoid a suit and to hasten its purchase of the Chronicle,
Hearst agreed to the Fang deal, said Connell.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
