<DOCNO> NYT20000601.0172 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 15:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1944 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-JOURNAL-LEBANON-0602-     06-01 0665
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOURNAL-LEBANON-0602-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    JOURNAL: GRIDLOCK, BUT NO GRID; JACKALS, TANKS IN SOUTH LEBANON
RUSH HOUR
 &HT;    With Photos.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (k) Commentary categories.
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIRUT, Lebanon _ Guerrillas dented our taxi and we had trouble
hearing the sheik over the explosions across the street.
</P>
<P>
   But, at least we missed the jackal.
</P>
<P>
   We're pretty sure that was the large, dog-like, thing that
jogged across the road in front of our car at one point in our
two-day road trip through southern Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   Zipping around south, with its farmlands, mountain villages and
open roads, should be easy. But, we were there as Israel ended its
occupation, hastily pulling out of the mountaintop bunkers it held
for nearly 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   The south is normally home for more than 100,000 Lebanese.
Others, who fled after Israel's invasion in 1982, returned for the
first time after the withdrawal last week(week of May 24).
</P>
<P>
   With Lebanon being smaller than Connecticut, the rest of the
country drove down to check it out, too. They managed to create
gridlock where there isn't even a grid.
</P>
<P>
   Guerrilla groups commandeered abandoned tanks and rumbled down
the narrow roads like impromptu military parades. Soldiers on top
waved flags and fired their assault rifles in the air to the shouts
of bystanders.
</P>
<P>
   And, there were lots of cars. We saw 10 children and adults
packed into a '70s model Toyota. The parents hadn't seen their home
village for 27 years.
</P>
<P>
   Near them, a Shiite Muslim woman in a black head scarf drove a
late model gray Mercedes-Benz with a large yellow Hezbollah _ the
``Party of God'' _ flag propped in the passenger window.
</P>
<P>
   Many people touring the area had not been there for over 20
years and even natives had to stop frequently to ask directions.
</P>
<P>
   Crossroads would jam like downtown intersections. Then, militia
members with assault rifles would emerge to direct traffic. They
weren't Hezbollah, but motley bands that could pose problems later.
Still, they got the traffic moving.
</P>
<P>
   I was with two colleagues and a translator. Our driver, George
Haddad, did not get out of Beirut much and was thrilled at the
adventure.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know my country,'' he chirped in his rudimentary
English as we stopped repeatedly for directions. ``It is my
country, but I do not know it. I live here, but I do not know my
country.''
</P>
<P>
   But this was also a former war zone under a dangerous
transition. There were no police and lots of left over munitions.
</P>
<P>
   One man who gave us directions told us that his cousin, a
15-year-old, had just been killed. The boy had ransacked a post of
the Israeli-backed South Lebanon Army, or SLA, and brought home
what appeared to be a camera. It blew up.
</P>
<P>
   A day before the withdrawal was complete, Israeli or SLA
artillery inexplicably hit a Mercedes-Benz killing a driver for the
British Broadcasting Company.
</P>
<P>
   We were safe and had better luck. It seemed like we found
everything we needed on the road _ government ministers willing to
interview, families reuniting after decades.
</P>
<P>
   We spotted a high-ranking Hezbollah cleric by the road. Sheik
Mohammed Kawtharani, in his turban and robe, was standing next to
his Mercedes and bodyguards. We interviewed him in a house nearby.
</P>
<P>
   It was here that some Lebanese guerrillas, in a rush to remove
an abandoned jeep, whacked our parked taxi, much to our driver's
consternation.
</P>
<P>
   And, the SLA had blown up an munitions dump across the street.
It was on fire now, and the periodic booms sent ordinance and earth
into the air.
</P>
<P>
   By the time Kawtharani's entourage offered us the customary
coffee and cigarettes, the room was filled with smoke anyway _ and
we were headed back into traffic.
</P>
<P>
   (Larry Kaplow is Cox Newspapers Middle East correspondent. His
E-mail address is: larryk(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-01-00 1536EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000601.0173 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 15:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1945 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-JOURNAL-LEBANON-0602-     06-01 0665
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOURNAL-LEBANON-0602-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    JOURNAL: GRIDLOCK, BUT NO GRID; JACKALS, TANKS IN SOUTH LEBANON
RUSH HOUR
 &HT;    With Photos.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (k) Commentary categories.
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
