<SLUG> BC-SHRIMP-SHORTAGE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     TEXAS PROPOSES TOUGHENING RULES FOR SHRIMPERS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By RUSSELL GOLD  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Wary of a declining shrimp population, Texas
Parks and Wildlife officials have released a revised set of
proposed rules to scale back shrimping operations in the state's
bays and offshore waters.
</P>
<P>
   The new rules come a month after an advisory panel of shrimpers
voted down more severe limits.
</P>
<P>
   ``We listened,'' Parks Executive Director Andrew Sansom said. As
a result, parks officials drew up a less sweeping set of
regulations that were released Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Even with revisions, many shrimpers feel the rules will drive
many boats into bankruptcy. The new regulations are likely to be
imposed later in the summer.
</P>
<P>
   Thuy Vu, a shrimper in Palacios and member of the state's Shrimp
Advisory Committee, said there is not enough evidence of an
impending collapse of the shrimp harvest to warrant the new rules.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there is no biological crisis, why do we have to rush into
this?'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The next couple of months are among the busiest in for
shrimpers.
</P>
<P>
   Parks and Wildlife officials have warned that shrimp fishing
could collapse if current depletion trends are not reversed.
</P>
<P>
   Hal Osborn, coastal fisheries director, said an 18-month study
showed adult shrimp were being caught before they reproduced. This
is compounded by a 39-year decline in the shrimp population.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly there is a lot of room for debate about how many
shrimp there are in the world,'' he said, but short of draining the
Gulf of Mexico, an exact count is impossible. The signs, he said,
clearly point in the direction of a pending collapse.
</P>
<P>
   The rules released Wednesday are intended to reverse that trend.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed rules would close an additional 6 percent of bays
and estuaries to trawlers and ban shrimping in state waters, which
extend out to a depth of 60 feet, south of Corpus Christi and
outside the barrier islands.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, shrimpers would have to increase the mesh size of
their nets. The rules also would lop 15 days off the fall season,
but extend the winter season by allowing shrimping at night.
</P>
<P>
   But the rules no longer include provisions such as shortening
the winter and spring seasons by a combined 45 days and requiring
shrimpers in the fall to return to port by 4 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Environmentalists warmly greeted the decision to shut off
shrimping south of Corpus Christi, the home region of the
endangered Kemp's ridley sea turtle.
</P>
<P>
   The Parks and Wildlife Department will hold a series of public
hearings on the proposed rules, including meetings in Rockport on
June 27, Port Isabel on June 29 and Corpus Christi on July 18.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
