r l BC-RELIGION-SCHOOLS-HNS &LR;      06-01 0803
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-SCHOOLS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     HINDU FINDS GRADUATION PRAYER OFFENSIVE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By J. MICHAEL PARKER  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Gracious heavenly Father,'' ``in your name'' and ``amen'' _
expressions taken for granted among Christians at prayer _
sometimes seem grating to non-Christians when uttered at public
events.
</P>
<P>
   Those words angered a group of Hindu families attending a
graduation ceremony at a San Antonio high school last weekend,
although the school's principal is satisfied the prayers fit legal
guidelines.
</P>
<P>
   Sometime this month, the U.S. Supreme Court is expected to
clarify when and how prayer may be included in public school
events, when it announces a decision in a case challenging
student-led prayer at high school football games.
</P>
<P>
   A federal appeals court ruled against such prayers in a case
originating in the Santa Fe School District in Galveston County,
Texas, but differentiated between games and graduation ceremonies.
</P>
<P>
   In San Antonio, Alex Salinas, who attended Madison High School's
commencement last Saturday, said the invocation and benediction
clearly were sectarian and insensitive to non-Christians in the
audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was Christian denominational prayer rather than a generic
prayer,'' said Salinas, a practicing Hindu.
</P>
<P>
   ``About 10-to-12 Hindu families went out to eat at an Indian
restaurant Saturday after the Madison graduation ceremony, and
everybody was talking about it,'' Salinas said.
</P>
<P>
   He said he hadn't thought much about it during the invocation,
but when similar wording was repeated in the benediction at the end
of the ceremony, he found it offensive.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no warning that it was a Christian prayer. We were
all required to stand and participate. It was very offensive,
especially because there have been many Hindu temples burned by
Christians in various parts of the world,'' Salinas said.
</P>
<P>
   He said he believed the offense was unintentional but could
reflect a subtle influence by Christian conservatives on school
officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not looking for blood. I'm just looking for an admission
by school officials that what they did was wrong,'' Salinas said.
</P>
<P>
   Madison Principal Bobby Smith said the prayers were written and
delivered by students. He said he had read both of them and
believed they were appropriate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can appreciate Mr. Salinas' convictions, and I respect them
wholeheartedly. We're not in the business of imposing religion on
anyone,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Smith said he apologized privately to Salinas, but Salinas said
he wanted a public apology.
</P>
<P>
   ``I honestly don't feel like we did anything wrong, but I
apologized to him and his family for any feeling they have that we
offended them,'' Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   However the Supreme Court rules in the Santa Fe case, Smith said
he would abide by it.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A ruling by the high court could help set clearer boundaries for
when prayers are appropriate, if at all.
</P>
<P>
   In a 1992 Texas case, Jones vs. Clear Creek School District, a
federal appeals court found public school graduation prayers
constitutional if they are ``nonsectarian'' and
``nonproselytizing.''
</P>
<P>
   In New Orleans on Tuesday, a panel of the U.S. 5th Circuit Court
of Appeals dismissed a lawsuit against the Aledo (Texas) School
District on allegations it infringed on her right to present a
prayer. Katherine Hackleman Furley sued the district in May after a
school district attorney deleted parts of a prayer she had written
for graduation day.
</P>
<P>
   Rob Boston, assistant director of communications for Americans
United for Separation of Church and State, said he expects the high
court's decision to clear up confusion over prayers at graduation
ceremonies and other school-sponsored gatherings, not just athletic
events.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Clear Creek decision was nonsensical. As a practical
matter, there's no such thing as a nonsectarian prayer. Hinduism is
a polytheistic religion, so to a Hindu, any prayer to one God is
sectarian,'' Boston said.
</P>
<P>
   But Rao Pemmeraju, a former president of the Hindu Temple of San
Antonio, disagreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the Hindu faith, there is only one God, but God can have
many manifestations and many names. We believe we're all children
of God, and we don't believe Hinduism is the only way to salvation.
God is in you and me and everyone,'' Pemmeraju said.
</P>
<P>
   He said most Hindus wouldn't have been offended by the Madison
student's prayer.
</P>
<P>
   Many have tried to water down prayers in an effort to find an
inoffensive compromise, but there is no such thing, Boston said.
</P>
<P>
   His own group has suggested those who want a religious component
to graduation ceremonies could organize a private baccalaureate
ceremony at a church.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
