<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RATINGS SHOULD TELL ALL 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID GRIMES   
 Sarasota (Fla.) Herald-Tribune   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   According to a study in the Journal of the American Medical
Association, there is a surprising amount of violence in G-rated
films.
</P>
<P>
   Films such as ``Snow White and the Seven Dwarfs,'' ``Toy Story''
and ``The Rugrats Movie'' contain numerous scenes of fisticuffs,
sword-fighting, gunplay and other aggressive action.
</P>
<P>
   Although it's unclear whether cartoon violence has an influence
on children's behavior, the researchers recommended that the Motion
Picture Association of America change its rating system to include
more detail on the content of G-rated films.
</P>
<P>
   I think this is a great idea, but like so many great ideas that
were not dreamed up by me personally, it does not go far enough. A
more detailed rating system is also needed for TV shows and for
movies intended for adults.
</P>
<P>
   The TV rating system in place now provides some details about
the shows but much more information is needed. It is not enough to
say that a TV-14 rated show contains intense violence (V), intense
sexual situations (S), strong coarse language (L) or intensely
suggestive dialogue (D). What we need is a system that also warns
viewers of BA (bad acting), OLT (overbearing laugh tracks), UPL
(unimaginative plot lines) and DSB (depressingly scrawny bodies).
</P>
<P>
   A show that is designated TVY7 is intended for children age 7
and older. The only additional warning that might come with a show
of this sort is the letters ``FV,'' which stand for ``fantasy
violence.''
</P>
<P>
   I suggest some additional warnings, including CA (cheap
animation), CL-S (clumsy lip-synching), ABM (annoying background
music) and, of course, NMTPANTBTGBTTC (nothing more than pictures
and noise to bridge the gaps between the toy commercials).
</P>
<P>
   Older TV shows need an upgraded rating system, too, because a
lot of their content can frighten and/or confuse viewers of all
ages. For example, the show ``Leave It To Beaver'' might come with
a MIWPAHHWD warning (mother inexplicably wears pearls and
high-heels while dusting).
</P>
<P>
   TV and movie violence itself is too vaguely described in today's
ratings systems. Words like ``moderate,'' ``intense'' or
``graphic'' are far too general and do not give the prospective
viewer nearly enough information about violent content.
</P>
<P>
   I suggest more specific designations better attuned to today's
ultra-violent action movies, such as D, D &AMP; D (decapitation,
dismemberment and disembowelment), AEMFWHB (alien emerges messily
from within human body), IPMBPDILGJ (intensely private male body
parts displayed in little glass jars) and, of course, AC (airborne
chunks).
</P>
<P>
   The danger of expanding the ratings system is that advocacy
groups of all stripes will want to get into the act. Feminists, for
example, will want to include warnings on movies like ``Snow
White'' and ``Sleeping Beauty'' pointing out SS (submissive
stereotypes) and UMPWCMS (unhealthy my-prince-will-come mindset).
</P>
<P>
   Animal-rights groups will want to warn viewers of WD (whale
demonization) in ``Pinocchio'' and HITAOBA (hippos in tutus and
other blatant anthropomorphizations) in ``Fantasia.''
</P>
<P>
   Alcoholics Anonymous and Mothers Against Drunk Driving might try
to warn viewers about the pink-elephants scene in ``Dumbo'' on the
grounds that it presents an ILHPOHIBWO (inappropriately
lighthearted portrayal of hallucinations induced by whiskey
overdose).
</P>
<P>
   And, of course, Donald Duck could run afoul (afowl?) of
conservative Christian groups on the grounds that his cartoons
contain SL (suspicious lisping) and BDFP (blatant disregard for
pants).
</P>
<P>
   It is entirely possible that by the time you wade through all
the warnings you will have missed most or all of the TV show or
movie, which, come to think of it, might be the best thing for all
concerned.
</P>
<P>
   (David Grimes is a columnist for the Herald-Tribune in Sarasota,
Fla. The Herald-Tribune is a member of the New York Times Regional
Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
