<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOMEVIDEO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOME VIDEO NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
   By PETER M. NICHOLS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   1945 War Story Reborn at Last
</P>
<P>
   During World War II it was possible to play a recorded greeting
from home, but for Sgt. Warnicki (Freddie Steele) in William
Wellman's ``Story of G.I. Joe,'' it necessitates lugging a large
Victrola all over Italy. At each pause in battle he hauls out the
carefully wrapped machine and the record his wife and child have
made for him. Each time the recording plays backward, emitting
unintelligible squawks. By the time it spins properly, he has gone
mad with battle fatigue.
</P>
<P>
   Fans of the film, which opened in 1945 and at the time was
considered one of the most realistic war movies ever, might liken
Warnicki's frustration to their own at its failure to appear on
video. Last week Image Entertainment released the first tape and
DVD editions. ``It has been one of our most requested titles for at
least 15 years,'' said Irv Slifkin of Movies Unlimited, a large
video mail order company in Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   Where has it been? Larry Stern, president of Video-Cinema Films
Inc., a Manhattan distributor and the film's copyright owner,
described a meandering trail that goes back to 1970, when he made a
deal with Lester Cowan, the movie's producer, to place it on
television.
</P>
<P>
   That agreement lasted until 1982, with control resting solely
with the Cowan family. In 1997 the film was again licensed to
Stern, who subsequently made a deal with Image Entertainment to
release it on video. In 1972, he said in an interview, he had two
35-mm prints made. Image did the restoration work, resulting in a
fine disc and tape.
</P>
<P>
   Viewed today, ``The Story of G.I. Joe'' is something of a relic,
though unlike many of today's films it tries to be stirring without
being slathered with sloppy sentimentality. When a soldier dies, a
comrade says he'll never get a letter from Betty. Fine, someone
snarls, she'll never get one from him.
</P>
<P>
   The film is based on the writings of the war correspondent Ernie
Pyle (portrayed by Burgess Meredith), who tags along with the
troops from Tunisia and Sicily to Casino and up the road to Rome.
Pyle, a Scripps-Howard reporter, was a stickler for telling it like
it was for the foot soldier. But the film never loses a certain
gentility. While the fighting is intense, the violence is implied
rather than graphic. Bodies turn up, but there is no actual
bloodshed, and it is startling to hear soldiers yell things like
``Watch it there, fella!'' instead of the threats and obscenities
in today's action films. As muddy as these troops get, they're a
clean bunch.
</P>
<P>
   The film had its beginnings during the war when the Army wanted
to counteract the rising influence of the Air Corps and Navy.
Cowan, then a young producer, was interested in making a movie
about the infantry. He was directed to Pyle, who took a personal
interest, nixing James Cagney, whom he disliked, to play himself.
He did want Arthur Miller to write the screenplay, but Miller
didn't like Cowan and withdrew. Robert Mitchum, never more
droopy-eyed, had his first starring role as Captain Walker. Pyle
was killed in the Pacific in 1944.
</P>
<P>
   NEW RELEASES
</P>
<P>
   Girl, Interrupted
</P>
<P>
   After washing down a bottle of aspirin with a bottle of vodka,
Susanna (Winona Ryder) is sent off to Claymoore psychiatric
hospital. It is the 1960s and Susanna, perhaps a little too smart
for her own good, talks about mystical undertow, but basically her
problems are a neurotic peevishness and a need to grow up. Or, as a
nurse (Whoopi Goldberg) puts it, ``You're a lazy, self-indulgent
little girl who is driving herself crazy.'' At Claymoore, Susanna
falls in with the house insurgent (Angelina Jolie) but then starts
to calm down in, Stephen Holden wrote in The New York Times, ``a
small, intense period piece with a hardheaded tough-love
attitude.''
</P>
<P>
   _ 1999. Columbia/Tri-Star. $107.37; DVD, $24.95. 127 minutes.
Closed captioned. R. Release date: June 6.
</P>
<P>
   Death
</P>
<P>
   In Errol Morris' documentary, subtitled ``The Rise and Fall of
Fred A. Leuchter Jr.,'' a mousy, mild-mannered Boston-born builder
of execution devices gets illusions of omniscience when his
cockeyed notions are adopted by Holocaust deniers. Sent by them to
Auschwitz in 1988, Leuchter furtively chips masonry from rooms once
used as gas chambers at Auschwitz. Finding no residue of cyanide,
he concludes that there were no gas executions at the camp. That
makes him a fixture of the neo-Nazi lecture circuit in Europe, but
here he makes creepy company in ``the best comedy-horror
documentary about the Holocaust ever made'' (Holden).
</P>
<P>
   _ 1999. Universal. $107.37. 91 minutes. PG-13. Release date:
June 6.
</P>
<P>
   The Eel
</P>
<P>
   After murdering his wife and her lover, a seeming model of
Japanese conformity named Yamashita (Koji Yakusho) pedals to the
police station and surrenders. Eight years later he is released in
the custody of a Buddhist priest and begins a new life on a remote
stretch of coast. There he meets Keiko (Misa Shimuzu), who bears an
uncanny resemblance to his wife and awakens all the old issues of
jealousy, rage, remorse and guilt. Directed by Shohei Imamura, ``
Yakusho and Shimizu deliver unerring performances in a splendid
film that harvests hope from a bleak landscape'' (Lawrence Van
Gelder).
</P>
<P>
   _ 1998. New Yorker. $95. 117 minutes. Japanese with English
subtitles. No rating. Release date: June 6.
</P>
<P>
   Next Friday
</P>
<P>
   A loud, low-level sequel to the 1995 comedy ``Friday'' sends
Craig (Ice Cube, who wrote and produced this film) from South Los
Angeles to the suburbs, where he will presumably get a respite from
big-city violence. But out in Rancho Cucamonga all is not bucolic,
what with the gangster Joker boys flashing automatic weapons across
the street, their pit bull, Chico, assaulting the neighbors, and
Craig's cousin Day-Day (Mike Epps) battling his pregnant
girlfriend, D'Wana (Tamala Jones). In other words, don't expect
surprises in a film ``notable chiefly for feeding a stereotype of
blacks as shiftless layabouts interested mainly in recreational
drugs and irresponsible sex'' (Van Gelder).
</P>
<P>
   _ 1999. New Line. $109.37; DVD, $24.98. 100 minutes. Closed
captioned. Release date: June 6.
</P>
<P>
   Other new titles of interest, some of which may have had a
theater release, appeared on television or been on videocassette in
earlier editions.
</P>
<P>
   A SCANDAL IN PARIS. George Sanders is the French thief Francois
Eugene Vido in Douglas Sirk's film, also known as ``Thieves'
Holiday,'' about a young rogue who was born in prison and spends
much of his youth there, takes a phony commission in Napoleon's
army to escape further indictments and eventually becomes the
police chief of Paris. 1946. Kino. VHS, $24.95. 100 minutes.
Release date: June 6.
</P>
<P>
   SEX AND THE CITY. Here is the whole first season of the HBO
series, based on Candace Bushnell's book, starring Sarah Jessica
Parker as a sex columnist who gets much of her material from her
own experiences and those of her friends (Kim Cattrall, Kristin
Davis and Cynthia Nixon). 1999. HBO. VHS, $39.92; DVD, $39.99. 300
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   STELLA, A MATTER OF DIGNITY, ATTILA 74, A GIRL IN BLACK. Four
films by the Greek director Michael Cacoyannis (``Electra,''
``Zorba the Greek'') are on cassette and DVD from Fox Lorber. In
``Stella'' (1955, 92 minutes), a Golden Globe winner, Melina
Mercouri stars as a woman with too many men friends for her own
good. In ``A Matter of Dignity'' (1958, 101 minutes), a
self-centered mother pushes her daughter at a suitor with money and
battles with her impoverished maid. Cacoyannis' only documentary,
``Attila 74'' (1975, 101 minutes), explores the cost of the Turkish
invasion of Cyprus. In ``A Girl in Black'' (1956, 101 minutes), a
young woman fights for her reputation and a solid relationship on a
small Greek island. VHS, $19.98 each; DVD, $29.98 each. Greek with
English subtitles.
</P>
</TEXT>
