<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-CONNELLY-1000(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JENNIFER CONNELLY READY TO PROVE SHE'S MORE THAN JUST A PRETTY
FACE
</HEADLINE>
 
(EDS: Accompanied by CONNELLY-FILMS) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ANDREW MARTON 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Before she gives herself, body and soul, to Antonio Banderas,
Jennifer Connelly registers a series of colliding emotions with the
fluttering delicacy of a hummingbird's wings. In fractions of
seconds, her oval face sorts through feelings of indecision and
self-doubt, guilt and fear, before finally yielding to gnawing,
untrammeled desire.
</P>
<P>
   Too bad Banderas was almost the only one who got to see it.
Indeed, because the film, ``Of Love and Shadows,'' was essentially
a straight-to-video release, few witnessed what was something of an
epiphany in the career of the Brooklyn-raised actress.
</P>
<P>
   By being cast as Irene, a privileged Chilean writer fighting to
save political prisoners from her country's fascist government,
Connelly was finally freed to, well, act. For the 1994 film, she
adopted a Meryl Streep-quality Chilean accent for passionate
debates on the corrosive effects of political repression. The
debates could very well have been a metaphor for her Hollywood
career.
</P>
<P>
   That Connelly so easily traveled through ``Of Love and
Shadows''' maze of character growth was a revelation to those in
the industry who saw it. Given that, for some, she shares with
``actresses'' like Pamela Anderson Lee the voluptuous ability to
make teen-age boys drool and middle-age men gape, few mainstream
casting directors have ever considered her capable of juggling all
the facets of a complex character. But Connelly, a former Stanford
student, has set out to emphatically _ if quietly _ prove those
doubters wrong.
</P>
<P>
   It has been a long, hard road toward respectability. Connelly
started out in the business as an 11-year-old sprite striding
confidently through Sergio Leone's 1984 epic, ``Once Upon a Time in
America.'' Entranced by the performing life, she soon grew into a
series of roles that accentuated her guileless warmth while taking
advantage of her burgeoning physical beauty. By the time she was
20, she seemed primed for stardom, having shown she could be a
resourceful girl-Friday in ``The Rocketeer,'' a Saturday matinee
popcorn flick given big-time hype by Disney.
</P>
<P>
   But that was 10 years ago. Now with the recent release of the
independent film ``Waking the Dead,'' to be followed by two more
higher-profile indie movies later this year (''Requiem for a
Dream'' and ``Pollock''), Jennifer Connelly is engaged in that
toughest of Hollywood challenges. She is looking to overturn an oil
tanker-sized professional and public perception of her.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frankly, I think she is already making much of that transition
to actress from beautiful icon,'' says Keith Gordon, Connelly's
director in ``Waking the Dead.'' ``I know that because people who
ask me about working with her have already changed their
perception.''
</P>
<P>
   But while those in the independent film game are starting to
take her seriously as an artist, the major studios _ and, by
extension, most moviegoers _ are proving more difficult to
persuade. Hollywood has always stubbornly clung to its typecasting.
And the mass popularity of the Internet, with its constantly
circulated glam stills and video clips of Connelly's acting past
(with an emphasis on the few nude scenes she's done), make it even
more difficult for her to erase that old bombshell image.
</P>
<P>
   That her ``image'' _ based squarely on her striking beauty _ is
almost entirely divorced from the actual performances she's given
hardly matters to those afflicted by it. It's a look that has
launched a thousand Web sites, from Portugal to New Jersey, some
carrying such hyperventilating names as the ``Jennifer Connelly
Worship Temple.''
</P>
<P>
   The supreme irony governing Connelly's desire to move her career
to a more ambitious place is that while her looks garnered her so
much early notoriety, they camouflaged her talent. If they were to
re-view her 10 most prominent movies over the past decade, studio
casting agents might just realize that her sensuality, often
dismissed as a Lolita-esque pose, in fact reflects a transparently
warm wellspring of feeling combined with an ineffable sense of
mystery _ the very qualities of the classic film stars of yore like
Katharine Hepburn and Greta Garbo.
</P>
<P>
   ``With Jennifer, the irony is that it is her honesty and
simplicity that achieve her great mystery and depth and that
special ethereal quality,'' says Gordon. ``We just aren't used to
seeing that kind of simplified, open-hearted honesty on screen.
Today it's more about seeing actors put on faces, put on sexiness.
But Jennifer is seductive or mysterious by not putting on seductive
or mysterious airs.''
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
<P>
   That Connelly acts on a tantalizingly elusive level makes it
easy to see why Hollywood has cast her in so many period pieces.
She is a throwback to another time, when Hollywood's biggest female
stars wore black stockings and layers of lipstick, cavorted at
nightspots like ``The South Seas Club'' and rambunctiously lived
life on their own terms. Her restless Eleanor in ``Inventing the
Abbotts'' rebels against the starchy mores of small-town Illinois
in 1957 and revels in her carefree sexuality. Her Jenny Blake in
the Depression-era ``The Rocketeer'' is an aspiring actress with
all the gumption necessary to join the studios' star system. And
her Allison Pond in ``Mulholland Falls'' is the kind of 1940s Los
Angeles femme fatale _ complete with plunging decolletage and spine
of steely conviction _ who can take a slap and return the shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of Jennifer's wonderful sense of mystery, she
definitely feels timeless,'' e-mails Australian director Alex
Proyas, Connelly's director on ``Dark City.'' ``She is a beautiful
enigma and that is why she is cast in so many period or fantasy
films, because she seems unstuck from her era, ethereal and
intangible.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Connelly's ability to haunt a role can enliven the
present day too, as can be vividly evidenced in her most recent
film, ``Waking the Dead.'' As Sarah Williams, she bridges the
vibrant present and the tragic afterlife of her character by
developing her as someone grounded in the daily minutia of life
and, after death, as someone who spectrally visits those she left
behind. It is Connelly's Zen-like perspicacity, communicated with
her signature verbal economy, that allows her to be a persuasive
emissary from the beyond.
</P>
<P>
   Like all the greatest film stars, Connelly best communicates
through her eyes. She's capable of holding a mesmerizing gaze more
meaningfully than many a present-day Oscar winner, allowing viewers
a hospitable window into a raft of roiling emotions. ``She is just
so direct; I mean, she has these green eyes that just look right
through you,'' says actor-director Ed Harris, who cast Connelly in
his upcoming biopic, ``Pollock.'' ``She has this incredibly strong
presence, and she's not afraid of it.''
</P>
<P>
   In a time when Hollywood is enamored with, and amply rewards,
Meg Ryan's pluck and Sandra Bullock's moxie, Jennifer Connelly's
ethereal, haunting presence gets neglected. Two of the actress's
most under-appreciated film qualities are her aura of serenity and
her dreamy equipoise, both endowing her with a labyrinthine
interior life rarely available in most cardboard film characters.
</P>
<P>
   As ``Waking the Dead'' amply illustrates, Connelly's best work
is found in small films that allow unexpected colors to emerge from
her repertory. In ``Far Harbor,'' for example, she wears no makeup,
plays most of her scenes in a formless blue sweater, and can still
command our attention simply by marveling at cloud formations from
a perch on a roof.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jennifer definitely has a certain European, smoldering
complexity in her that is very grown-up and complicated,'' says
Gordon, who recalls a wrenching love scene in ``Waking the Dead''
where Connelly is making love while laughing and crying at the same
time. ``Jennifer invests that kind of sensual moment with such
great complexity that, well, you just don't normally get that in a
typical screen love scene, which is usually just about the
physical.''
</P>
<P>
   When Connelly takes on contemporary roles, she shows an uncommon
bravery in her choices. In director John Singleton's racially
overheated college campus parable, ``Higher Learning,'' Connelly
subsumes her sex appeal behind thick plaid shirts, awkward glasses
and baggy bluejeans. Plus, her social-minded campus organizer is
gay. As she tenderly kisses actress Kristy Swanson, Connelly does
it without a whiff of self-censorship or salaciousness.
</P>
<P>
   Connelly has been attached to two upcoming independent projects
with the kind of disturbing subject matter that will serve further
to remove her from her old beautiful-ornament label. In the
upcoming ``Requiem for a Dream'' she will play a wan heroin addict,
with her normally silken, coffee-brown hair reportedly streaked a
shabby black and blond.
</P>
<P>
   Also expected out in the next six months is ``Pollock,'' with
Connelly playing the role of Ruth Kligman, the last lover of the
painter Jackson Pollock. ``I met a lot of women for this role,''
says Harris, ``Pollock's'' director and star. ``But in Jennifer I
not only found one who had the sexuality the role required but one
who also had a great intelligence and wonderful mystery to her.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a role she hopes wins her respect, even if it doesn't
secure her a higher profile.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very smart on Connelly's part to latch onto independent
roles,'' says Stephen Hunter, film critic for The Washington Post.
``She has discovered it is much better to be the star of an
independent film, where the roles tend to be more challenging
anyway, than to be the babe who dies in the first reel of a big
studio film.''
</P>
<P>
   (Andrew Marton is cultural critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7679, or e-mail:
amarton(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
