</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOHNSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A RECIPE FOR A HEALTHY JUNETEENTH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CECIL JOHNSON 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Some people really know how to take the zing out of a good
thing.
</P>
<P>
   With African-Americans from coast to coast and some places
across the great blue waters getting fired up for
first-of-the-century Juneteenth festivities, along comes the
American Heart Association with a bucket of cold water.
</P>
<P>
   The heart association also is talking emancipation, but not the
kind that African-Americans normally speak of every year on June
19.
</P>
<P>
   In case any of you out there in readerland suffer from the same
knowledge gap about American history that cost a ``Who Wants to be
a Millionaire'' contestant thousands of dollars several weeks ago,
Juneteenth celebrations commemorate the day that word of the
abolition of slavery reached black Texans.
</P>
<P>
   That happened on June 19, 1865, two years after Abraham Lincoln
issued the Emancipation Proclamation. Black Texans for years have
been chided about being the last to get the word about freedom.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't, of course, the fault of the freedmen. It was just
that not much of the Civil War was fought in Texas, and the slaves
were actually freed as the Union forces marched through the
Southern states.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't until the war was over that the northern army occupied
Texas. Then shortly after landing at Galveston, Gen. Gordon Granger
stood on the balcony of Ashton Villa and proclaimed General Order
Number 3:
</P>
<P>
   ``The people of Texas are informed that in accordance with a
Proclamation from the Executive of the United States, all slaves
are free. This involves an absolute equality of rights and rights
of property between former masters and slaves, and the connection
heretofore existing between them becomes that between an employer
and free laborer. The freedmen are advised to remain in their
present homes and work for wages. They are informed that they will
not be allowed to collect at military posts, and that they will not
be supported in idleness, either there or elsewhere.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the main ingredients of Juneteenth festivities has been
food, lots of it. The richest kind. The kind loaded with fat, salt
and sugar. The kind that the heart association wants
African-Americans to emancipate themselves from.
</P>
<P>
   ``This Juneteenth the African-American Outreach Task Force of
the American Heart Association encourages you to: Celebrate
Juneteenth ... Free Your Health. It is time to take our heart and
our health into our own hands,'' says a letter by the association's
Texas affiliate.
</P>
<P>
   A brochure attached to the letter calls upon African-Americans
to ``Eat for Life,'' meaning primarily that they should reduce
their intake of saturated fat and sodium and eat more fruits and
vegetables _ foods that are higher in vitamins, minerals and fiber.
</P>
<P>
   The association also recommends against smoking and heavy
drinking, while emphasizing exercise and the need for blood
pressure and diabetes checks.
</P>
<P>
   So what, you say. It points out that stroke and heart disease
are leading causes of death among African-American men and women.
In the same vein, here's some more bad news:
</P>
<P>
   _One hundred-thousand African-Americans die of cardiovascular
disease each year. The coronary heart disease death rate for
African-American women is almost 72 percent higher than for white
women.
</P>
<P>
   _The same stroke death rate comparison exists between
African-American women and white women, while the stroke death rate
for African-American men in 94 percent higher than it is for white
men.
</P>
<P>
   _High blood pressure kills African-American men at 350 times the
rate it kills white and African-American women at 315 times the
rate it takes the lives of white women.
</P>
<P>
   The heart association goes on to give information on how to
sense a heart attack or a stroke coming on and what to do. The keys
to preventing them, the association says, is to reduce, recognize
and respond.
</P>
<P>
   No one can really quarrel with the soundness of the
association's advice. But Juneteenth is one heck of time to give
it. On the other hand, what better time than Emancipation Day could
one choose to emancipate oneself from slavish eating habits that
could doom one to a premature death?
</P>
<P>
   (Cecil Johnson is a columnist and editorial writer for the Fort
Worth Star-Telegram. You can reach him at
cecil(at)star-telegram.com or (817) 390-7663. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
