<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GREENWICH-CARS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A FIAT WILL PLAINLY REIGN AT GREENWICH CONCOURS 
</HEADLINE>
   By KEITH MARTIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREENWICH, Conn. _ The star of the show at the fifth annual
Greenwich Concours d'Elegance this weekend isn't an aristocratic
Bentley or a pristine Bugatti. It's a much-traveled 1927 Fiat 509
that once hauled fish to market. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Greenwich concours has a tradition of being more than just a
beauty show for cars. Each year, its founders, Bruce and Genia
Wennerstrom, look for cars that have an unusual story behind them.
He has also continued to expand the scope of the event, this year
adding classic motorboats, motorcycles and even a vintage
airplane. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The old Fiat had been owned by Ignazio Franciamore in his home
province, Agrigento, in Sicily; he used it as a taxi afterWorld War
II, then sold it in the 1950s to a man who used it for fish
deliveries. In 1987, an American collector bought the car and
brought it to Scranton, Pa. But it was shipped without antifreeze
in the motor and the engine block cracked in the Northeast winter,
rendering the car unusable.
</P>
<P>
   Franciamore's son, who shares his father's first name and
nickname (Iggy), operates a BMW dealership, F&AMP;S Motors, in the
Bronx. He heard about the old Fiat parked, fittingly, behind a
pizza restaurant in Scranton and went to look at it. Upon examining
the car's papers, he found his father's name listed as a previous
owner.
</P>
<P>
   He bought the car, restored it, and in 1998 drove it in the
Columbus Day parade in Manhattan. Both Iggy Franciamores, the
87-year-old father and his 60-year-old son, are expected to be on
hand with the car in Greenwich. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   More than 280 automobiles are expected at the two-day event,
with different cars displayed each day. The theme for the Greenwich
Concours d'Elegance on Saturday is cars from the late 1870s to the
late 1970s, with both domestic and European cars in the pre-World
War II field and American cars only in the postwar section. On
Sunday, the Greenwich Concours Europa comprises postwar European
sports, touring and competition cars. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Among the featured cars will be a Ford GT40 Mk IV that was part
of the Ford team that defeated Ferrari at Le Mans in 1967, a 1940
Cadillac four-door convertible sedan with side-mounted spare tires,
a 1950 Buick Super wood-paneled wagon, a 1953 Ferrari 342 America,
one of only three built, and a 1929 Stutz Blackhawk boat-tailed
speedster.
</P>
<P>
   The event is open from 10 to 5 both days, with presentation of
awards beginning each day at 3 p.m. Admission is $12, with children
12 and under free if accompanied by an adult; proceeds benefit the
Americares charity. The concours takes place at Roger Sherman
Baldwin Park, 100 Arch St., in Greenwich, Conn. For further
information, call (203) 618-0460. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
