<SLUG> BC-ERNESTMURRAY-COLUMN0602-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Courts have a duty to use scientific data wisely
 &HT;    By Ernest Murray
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LUFKIN, Texas _ Right here in Texas we have two cases in the
news where DNA testing could prove beyond a shadow of a doubt guilt
or innocence.
</P>
<P>
   DNA, the building blocks of life that give every living creature
a distinct imprint, has moved from the realm of science fiction to
real life applications.
</P>
<P>
   In one case, DNA testing will hopefully close the books on the
final resting place of outlaw Jesse James. While history records
that James was shot and killed in 1882 in St. Joseph, Mo.,
residents of Granbury claim the real Jesse James faked his death,
moved to north Texas, changed his name to J. Frank Dalton and died
in 1951 at the ripe old age of 104. The DNA sample from the exhumed
body will be compared with DNA from a known James' descendant
living in Oklahoma.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that the body buried under James' name in 1882 also
was exhumed, in 1995. Scientists who examined those remains said
the body was most likely that of James.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, while the courts are eager to confirm the rather
insignificant identity of man long dead, the Texas Court of
Criminal Appeals is denying DNA testing that might prevent the
execution of a man convicted of capital murder.
</P>
<P>
   Ricky Nolen McGinn, scheduled to be executed for the 1993 rape
and killing of his 12-year-old stepdaughter, Stephanie Rae Flanary,
could have his death sentence commuted to life in prison if DNA
evidence proves the semen and hair samples from the murdered girl
do not match McGinn's.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George W. Bush, who advocates DNA testing to ``erase any
doubts'' from some death penalty cases, has indicated he was
leaning toward delaying the execution for 30 days while testing
could be done.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of Jesse James, aka J. Frank Dalton, DNA testing
will only prove who's buried in that grave in Texas, but for Ricky
Nolen McGinn, a life hangs in the balance.
</P>
<P>
   If DNA can show by a reasonable doubt that McGinn is not guilty
of capital murder, then by all means take him off death row. If on
the other hand, the tests confirm the jury's sentence, he should be
put to death.
</P>
<P>
   As science unlocks more of the mysteries of DNA, it is certain
to raise ethical, moral and legal questions that were unheard of a
decade earlier.
</P>
<P>
   The cases of Jesse James and Ricky Nolen McGinn illustrate two
very different ways DNA testing can be utilized. It is hoped that
courts will concentrate on using this new technology to confirm
guilt or innocence rather than resolve bragging rights.
</P>
<P>
   Ernest Murray is managing editor of The Lufkin Daily News.
E-mail: emurray(at)coxnews.com. Website:
www.coxnews.com/newsservice.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
