<SLUG> BC-MOMMA-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`BIG MOMMA'S HOUSE': MOMMA, WHO WOULD HAVE THOUGHT? 
</HEADLINE>
  (Production notes at end) 
 By ELVIS MITCHELL    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The fitfully amusing ``Big Momma's House,'' starring the comic
whirligig Martin Lawrence, could best be described as ``Stakeout''
goes ghetto, with a touch of ``Tootsie'' for flava _ er, flavor.
Lawrence plays Malcolm, an FBI agent with a penchant for doing
undercover work in full body makeup, apparently to use some of the
disguises he didn't get around to in ``Blue Streak,'' his last
``Where's Martin?'' picture.
</P>
<P>
   Any fan of Lawrence's sitcom ``Martin'' knows about his skill in
using transformative appliances to convert himself into another
person with even fewer inhibitions than he displays as himself.
When he threw on padding to play Sheneneh, a homegirl-next-door
with press-on nail talons and enough hair extensions to tie a
four-mast sailboat to a dock, his immersion into this
tough-as-nails character who is all Id was shocking and funny. Here
he gets to do the same thing when he goes undercover as Big Momma,
a stubborn old Southern woman who throws elbows and knees to the
groin like a club fighter.
</P>
<P>
   Why? Big Momma's granddaughter, Sherry (Nia Long), is on the run
because her ex-boyfriend, Lester (Terrence Howard), a murderous
bank-robber, has escaped from prison and is after her. Desperate,
Sherry calls Big Momma to seek refuge and rekindle their cold
relationship. Malcolm and his partner (Paul Giamatti) believe they
can use Sherry to get to Lester. Since the real Big Momma (Ella
Mitchell) is conveniently out of town (and stays away so long you
wonder if she is ever coming back), Malcolm seizes the opportunity
to take her place. When Lawrence conceals himself under a cubic ton
of Max Factor, you wonder where he hides his ears, which stick out
like handles on a water pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   This isn't much of a movie; it looks like a series of baseball
card shots and may have the worst rhythms ever in a film directed
by a former editor, in this case Raja Gosnell. When ``Momma'' does
come to life, it does so because of bits like a small turn by the
wide-body jet comedian Cedric ``the Entertainer,'' who plays a
raise-the-roof preacher who knows just how to awaken the inner Holy
Ghost in his parishioners. In his first appearance, Cedric sports a
high-gloss California curl and the camera seems to linger on his
coiffed head in disbelief. Later, he has sprouted an Afro with a
streak of magenta.
</P>
<P>
   In his Big Momma cover-up, which must contain enough plastic to
wrap an entire herd of beef, Lawrence brings to mind Foghorn
Leghorn in disguise; he's a bigger-than-life cartoon. In taking on
some of Big Momma's duties, like midwife _ in a tired childbirth
scene, all the onscreen characters say ``Awww'' when the baby
arrives, a grim pander to the audience _ Lawrence uses his eyes to
offer knowing complicity.
</P>
<P>
   And that's the last thing this movie needs: a wink to let the
audience know it's all make-believe. Lawrence showed more devotion
to craft in his television series. And Eddie Murphy, who has done
much the same thing in films like ``The Nutty Professor,''
certainly goes deeper into character when he puts on makeup.
Lawrence gets laughs when, as Big Momma, he leads the church in a
rendition of ``Oh Happy Day'' and jumps into dances like the Robot
and the Smurf, but if he hasn't done this stuff before, then it
certainly feels as if he has. When he is just talking to Sherry's
son, the effect is less worried and naturally funny.
</P>
<P>
   A restless actor, Lawrence is better when forced to react to his
co-stars, particularly taller ones, as he did with Tim Robbins in
``Nothing to Lose'' or Will Smith in ``Bad Boys.'' In such
situations, he can make use of his ability to parody vanity. The
able Giamatti isn't a co-star here, and his exasperation seems to
come from the fact that he is relegated to pratfalls. The alluring
Long has shown great progress as an actress this year; her work in
the feature ``Boiler Room'' and in a segment of ``If These Walls
Could Talk 2'' on HBO shows she is ready for bigger things, so
coasting on her beauty here must have been like a paid vacation.
Flittering on the periphery is Howard, who acts as if he is in a
real movie, which makes a difference. With his movie-star
concentration, in his few scenes he gives ``Big Momma's House''
weight.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `BIG MOMMA'S HOUSE'
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Raja Gosnell; written by Darryl Quarles and Don
Rhymer, based on a story by Quarles; director of photography,
Michael D. O'Shea; edited by Bruce Green and Kent Beyda; music by
Richard Gibbs; production designer, Craig Stearns; produced by
David T. Friendly and Michael Green; released by 20th Century Fox.
</P>
<P>
   Cast: Martin Lawrence (Malcolm), Nia Long (Sherry), Paul
Giamatti (John), Jascha Washington (Trent), Terrence Howard
(Lester), Cedric ``The Entertainer'' (Reverend), Anthony Anderson
(Nolan) and Ella Mitchell (Big Momma).
</P>
<P>
   Running time: 97 minutes. Rating: ``Big Momma's House'' is rated
PG-13 (Parents strongly cautioned). It includes loud toilet humor,
a childbirth scene and reams of shameless comic violence, innuendo
and strong language.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-01-00 1620EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000601.0194 </DOCNO>
