<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 16:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2011 &Cx1f; tth-z
r e BC-STEELY-DAN-SPI &LR;      06-01 0813
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STEELY-DAN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STEELY DAN TAKES NEW ALBUM ON A SUMMER TOUR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GENE STOUT  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The title of Steely Dan's new album, ``Two Against
Nature,'' began as an inside joke between cofounders Donald Fagan
and Walter Becker.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the idea of the two of us against encroaching
decrepitude,'' Fagan, 52, said with a smirk.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really two against human nature, in the sense that your
body is telling you to slow down to a certain extent and maybe you
don't have as many ideas as you used to. Maybe you feel that you're
kind of in a kid's game and it's weird to still be doing this.''
</P>
<P>
   Formed in Los Angeles in 1972, Steely Dan has been reeling
through the years with a breezy, jazz-influenced pop sound
instantly recognizable to two generations of fans. ``Reelin'
Through the Years,'' ``Rikki Don't Lose That Number,'' ``Deacon
Blues,'' ``Peg,'' ``Hey Nineteen'' and other songs are classics.
</P>
<P>
   Fagan, Becker and an entourage of singers and musicians
including guitarist John Harrington are back on the road for a
summer tour supporting the new album, the duo's first studio effort
since 1980's ``Gaucho.
</P>
<P>
   With a set list featuring such new songs as ``What a Shame About
Me,'' ``Cousin Dupree'' and ``West of Hollywood,'' Steely Dan's
signature sound remains comfortably intact.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people think `Two Against Nature' sounds like it could
have been done a couple of years after we stopped recording in the
late '70s,'' Fagan said in a phone interview.
</P>
<P>
   ``Walter and I discussed using different recording methods and
maybe some new technology. But once we had the songs written, we
naturally defaulted to our usual way of doing things. There are
differences, but I think they're subtle.''
</P>
<P>
   Once celebrated as brilliant musical geeks, Fagan and Becker
listened to old records by Duke Ellington, Charlie ``Bird'' Parker
and other jazz legends while growing up in the 1950s and early
'60s.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think by the time we were 12, we knew what kind of music we
liked,'' Fagan said. ``And I've never really heard anything better
than that music.''
</P>
<P>
   Living in New York, Fagan often listened to all-night jazz
stations.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just happened that my junior high school years coincided
with the very best period for jazz of a certain kind.
</P>
<P>
   ``Walter and I were kind of the last jazz fans of that era in
that we both started listening to jazz when we were maybe 10 or 11
years old, when not many people were interested in it anymore, at
least not on a popular level like in the '40s.''
</P>
<P>
   Named for a sex toy in William Burroughs' cult novel ``The Naked
Lunch,'' Steely Dan released its first album, the Latin-tinged
``Can't Buy a Thrill,'' to glowing reviews in 1973. The song
``Reelin' in the Years,'' featuring Elliot Randal's sizzling lead
guitar, was an immediate hit.
</P>
<P>
   Picking up in the recording studio where they left off with
``Gaucho,'' Fagan and Becker resisted the temptation to reinvent
themselves musically.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like some of the things I've heard lately. But I know that
if we went in and remixed `Two Against Nature,' people would
complain that we were trying to be trendy, just by changing the
echo on the snare drum or something,'' Fagan said.
</P>
<P>
   The duo also has resisted working with younger artists, a la
Carlos Santana on his blockbuster Grammy-winning album
``Supernatural,'' in order to reach younger listeners.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd love to collaborate with youth, but we're not very good
at it,'' Fagan said. ``We tend to run them over with a steamroller.
They don't really appreciate it.''
</P>
<P>
   Santana's recent success may have given Steely Dan's new album a
little boost.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been told that it may have helped us, in the sense that
you don't have to be 16 and have a lot of tattoos to get on the
radio,'' Fagan said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I don't really know. We've never really thought that much
about radio.''
</P>
<P>
   Fagan and Becker worked together on songs, coming up with
wonderfully impressionistic lyrics. On ``Almost Gothic,'' Fagan
sings, ``She's pure science with a splash of black cat/ She's
almost gothic and I like it like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Twenty years ago, fans snickered over ``Hey Nineteen,'' about a
romance between a young woman and an older man. On ``Two Against
Nature,'' the duo updates the theme with ``Janie Runaway,'' in
which an older male dreams of a girl ``who makes me feel like
painting again'':
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's plan a weekend alone together/ Drive out to Binky's
place/ The Sugar Shack in Pennsylvania/ Or would that be a federal
case?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think as you get older, you find yourself getting into a
routine,'' Fagan said. ``But I don't see why you have to stop
appreciating beauty. I see a lot of guys who are sort of afraid to
look at girls now that they're in their 40s and 50s. To me it's the
most fun.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-01-00 1628EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000601.0195 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 16:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2012 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-AT-THE-MOVIES-NYT &LR;      06-01 1008
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AT-THE-MOVIES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWS OF THE SILVER SCREEN 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVE KEHR    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Art of Cool in a Hot Spot
</P>
<P>
   It was a very warm day in Brooklyn, and an even warmer day
inside the house where the director Bob Gosse was shooting ``Julie
Johnson,'' an independent feature that stars Lili Taylor, Courtney
Love and Spalding Gray.
</P>
<P>
   With the windows shrouded with heavy black cloth to simulate
night, and about 20 crew members and a dozen extras crammed into a
hallway, a kitchen and a dining room, the temperature had soared
well beyond sauna standards.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Gosse, a founding partner of the Shooting Gallery, a
production company, and the director of the 1997 film ``Niagara,
Niagara,'' was keeping amazingly cool behind the camera. The
objective was a complicated tracking shot that followed Donna
Hanover, playing the dutiful academic wife to Gray's physics
professor, as she opened the door for Taylor and Love, and ushered
them into a cocktail party.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do it again, but better'' was Gosse's half-joking direction as
take followed take, each one spoiled by a missed cue or an
overstepped mark. But neither Gosse nor his performers betrayed the
slightest hint of discomfort. Sometimes acting is knowing how not
to sweat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Julie Johnson,'' adapted from a play by Wendy Hammond, is the
story of a Hoboken housewife, played by Taylor, whose life changes
radically when she decides to enroll in a night school class,
``Introduction to Computers.'' ``When Lili's character announces,
`I don't want to be stupid no more,' it kicks off an unraveling
that becomes the narrative arc of the picture,'' Gosse said. Not
only does Julie discover that she has a genius for advanced
mathematics, but also that she's been living a lie. She kicks out
her domineering husband and takes up instead with her best friend,
Claire ( Love).
</P>
<P>
   ``I grew up on the West Coast with hippies,'' Love said, ``where
if people were gay, they were gay. No big deal. But then a couple
of years ago, when I started getting projected more into the
mainstream and having to deal with mainstream American values and
not really understanding it, I started to meet people who weren't
out, who weren't resolved with it, and that's the majority of
people who live in this country. And I started to have a lot more
compassion for the fact that they can't come out, because it's not
that easy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I went to a Wynona Judd show,'' added Love, best known as the
leader of the rock band Hole. ``And she's like married, not a gay
person at all. But I went to the show, and there were so many women
there I just thought, OK, this is like the big gay fest for women.
I felt this vibe of not-straightness in the room, and yet everybody
seemed to have wedding rings and children. Right after that, I read
this script.''
</P>
<P>
   ``She's whip smart,'' said Gosse of Love, ``and she's brought an
intelligence to Claire that wasn't apparent in the screenplay. It
would be easy to read this script and see Claire in a condescending
way, but I didn't want to condescend to either of these women.''
</P>
<P>
   For Taylor, too, it was important to avoid the big-hair,
pink-sweater, rhinestone-glasses cliches that define New Jersey in
so many movies and television shows. ``I see Julie as basically
asleep, and then the tension builds and she breaks. This story
reminds me of the fairy tale called `The Handless Maiden,' and for
a while I imagined her without hands, as someone incomplete.''
</P>
<P>
   When she approaches a role, Taylor said, ``I try to be as blank
as possible, and then by reading the script over and over, by the
sixth time through things start seeping in, maybe by osmosis. First
I have to know what's going on inside the character. I'm more of an
inside-out than an outside-in. Some actors work great outside-in,
but I feel like I'm wearing a suit and it doesn't quite fit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I find with a good script that I can break the character down
into four or five general phases. I usually name each phase, and I
write out all the beats in between on a chart. It's especially
useful on independents, when it's all over the place and you're
moving so quick. Let's say I have seven scenes in one day and I've
got to go from phase to phase, so I just look at my little chart
and I'm right there.''
</P>
<P>
   Love has her own approach. ``I've been working with the clothes,
trying to get it right but totally getting it wrong. I was in the
lobby of my hotel and I saw Sofia Coppola and Spike Jonze, and it
was the day before the shooting started. I sat down with them and I
had a coffee and they both were like, a hundred bucks you can't get
through this movie without wearing something cool. I came to work
the first day, and I said I'm not wearing one cool thing. Nothing
cool is coming out of me! I'm really finding her that way. It's
good to strip down and not be cool. And I'm gonna win that hundred
dollars.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The March of Verite
</P>
<P>
   With ``Cinema Verite: Defining the Moment,'' the Canadian
filmmaker Peter Wintonick has created the ``That's Entertainment''
of documentaries _ an all-star tribute, generously illustrated with
clips and interviews, to the 1960s movement that changed the face
of nonfiction filmmaking.
</P>
<P>
   Armed with the lightweight cameras and sound-recording equipment
developed in the '50s, directors like Richard Leacock and Robert
Drew (``Primary''), Albert and David Maysles (``Salesman''), D.A.
Pennebaker (``Don't Look Back''), Michel Brault (``Les Ordres'')
and Frederick Wiseman (``Titicut Follies'') discarded the studied
compositions and rhetorical flourishes of the dominant ``March of
Time'' style in favor of a more casual, more intimate, less overtly
manipulated manner that created a powerful impression of reality.
</P>
<P>
   ``That style is still being used in its purest form by many
practitioners,'' Wintonick said, ``but it's also influenced a lot
of audio-visual language, from the Danish Dogma movement to music
videos. It's a technique that has great resonance still because it
has direct human, dramatic content.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-01-00 1628EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000601.0196 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 16:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2016 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-CONNELLY-FILMS-TEX     06-01 0434
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONNELLY-FILMS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHO'S JENNIFER CONNELLY?
</HEADLINE>
 
(EDS: Accompanies FILM-CONNELLY) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Who's Jennifer Connelly?'' you ask. Rent the following movies
and not only will you know who she is, you'll be petitioning Oscar
voters on her behalf _ or at the least downloading her picture from
the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``Labyrinth'' (1986) _ Here, Connelly is barely into her teens
yet already her mystical, otherworldly quality begins to establish
itself. Watch her hold her own opposite glam-rocker David Bowie.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``The Hot Spot'' (1990) _ A Dennis Hopper-directed film noir
where Connelly forms a triangle of intrigue with Don Johnson and
Virginia Madsen. Notable for Connelly's sweet portrayal of a chaste
yet yearningly romantic accountant torn by a terrible secret.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``Of Love and Shadows'' (1994) _ Perhaps her most complete role,
Connelly wears a Spanish-inflected accent very comfortably as a
Chilean writer willing to risk her life to expose a repressive
government.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``Mulholland Falls'' (1996) _ Connelly isn't around for long in
this Los Angeles-based potboiler but she is at her high gloss best
as a tall drink of pulchritude in heels and a black dress with
plunging neckline who drives Nick Nolte to adultery and murder.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``Inventing the Abbotts'' _ (1997) One of the last of Connelly's
``bad girl'' films. Her Eleanor Abbott wants to escape the yoke of
her domineering father, and she does it through a steamy
relationship with someone from the wrong end of the social
register. That someone is Billy Crudup's Jacey, and he is a good
match for the sexually adventuresome Eleanor.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``Dark City'' _ (1998) Somehow Connelly manages to register
great range in this sci-fi, ``end of days'' phantasmagoria. At
first, she's a heavy-lidded torch singer cut from the Jessica
Rabbit mold. Later, she's a guilt-ridden wife coping with a
dizzying series of surreal events. Finally, she is a welcome ray of
sunshine on a once-bleak urbanscape.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``Waking the Dead'' _ (1999) Connelly has distilled all the
political activist residue from the late '60s and poured it into a
more cynical early 1970s landscape. She is warm, passionate,
forthright, righteous, romantic _ in short an adorable and,
sometimes, exasperating spitfire. She also is a blithe otherworldy
spirit, literally haunting her boyfriend, Billy Crudup, in his
second successful pairing with Connelly.
</P>
<P>
   _ Andrew Marton
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-01-00 1636EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
