 AM-PAGE1-CONSIDER-NYT 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are considering for
the Page 1 of Friday, June 2. The N.Y. Times News Service night
supervisor is Pat Ryan; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
patryan(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-EUROPE (Lisbon, Portugal) _ President Clinton called on
Israelis and Palestinians on Thursday to conclude a historic peace
that he said is ``within view now.'' And to help narrow their final
differences, he announced that he will send Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright to the Middle East next week to work with both
sides. In remarks after a 90-minute meeting with Prime Minister
Ehud Barak in this seaside capital, Clinton also announced that he
would meet soon with the Palestinians' leader, Yasser Arafat, in
Washington. By Elaine Sciolino.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL GENERAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   CUBAN-BOY (Undated) _ A federal appeals court in Atlanta sided
with Elian Gonzalez's father on Thursday in the 6-month-old
international custody battle, ruling that immigration officials
were entitled to deny an asylum hearing for the Cuban boy. Under
the ruling, Elian must remain in the United States for 14 days to
give his Miami relatives a chance to appeal. (Summary from wires)
By Rick Bragg.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``p'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   GORE-CANCER (Atlanta) _ Invoking World War II and the race to
the moon, Vice President Al Gore pledged Thursday to double federal
spending on cancer research and to make ``a flood'' of new cancer
treatments and tests available to all Americans who need them. In a
speech brimming with soaring oratory and buoyant optimism, Gore
described the nation as standing on the brink of medical
breakthroughs fueled by genetic research, and called on the federal
government to use its resources to turn those discoveries into
preventing and curing the most fatal cancers. By James Dao.
</P>
<P>
   FINANCIAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``f'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-ANTITRUST (Washington) _ The federal judge trying the
Microsoft antitrust case agreed Thursday to delay his final ruling
for about a week, giving the Justice Department time to reply to
Microsoft's proposal to revise the government's breakup plan. Judge
Thomas Penfield Jackson had planned to issue his final ruling,
widely expected to call for a breakup of the company, Thursday or
Friday. But the Justice Department asked him Thursday for an
opportunity to reply to Microsoft's comments on the government's
remedy proposal, which were filed with the court on Wednesday. By
Joel Brinkley.
</P>
<P>
   INVESTMENT-FRAUD (Undated) _ The federal Securities and Exchange
Commission and 38 state attorneys general announced Thursday a
combined fight against an increasingly growing type of white collar
crime that bilks thousands of Americans, particularly older
investors, out of hundreds of millions of dollars each year. The
schemes involve fraudulent promissory notes, which are investments
that typically involve a loan to a company made by an investor in
exchange for a fixed amount of returns. The officials estimated
that more than 3,000 American investors were victims of promissory
note schemes last year alone.
</P>
<P>
   SCIENCE
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-STROKE-RECOVER (Undated) _ Using a new kind of stroke
rehabilitation therapy, scientists have shown for the first time
that the brain can be coaxed into reorganizing its circuitry so
that people regain nearly full use of their partially paralyzed
limbs in just two to three weeks, even if the stroke happened years
ago. The rehabilitation, called constraint induced movement
therapy, involves immobilizing a good arm or leg so that the
patient is forced to use his bad arm or leg for familiar tasks.
With intensive practice in using the paralyzed limb, people can
literally rewire parts of their brains, researchers said, and
overcome a kind of learned helplessness that prevented their limbs
from moving. Moreover, the technique works for patients who had
their strokes decades ago and have had limited use of their limbs
ever since. By Sandra Blakeslee.
</P>
<P>
   CULTURE
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``e'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   OBIT-PUENTE (New York) _ Bandleader and percussionist Tito
Puente, who rode to fame on the heels of the 1950s mambo craze and
for the next five decades helped define Latin jazz, has died. He
was 77. (Summary from wires) By Joyce Wadler.
</P>
