<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 16:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2021 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-MOVIES-BEEFCAKE02-COX     06-01 0444
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-BEEFCAKE02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A titillating look at gay life in '50s
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   An awkward mix of gee-whiz nostalgia and full-frontal
titillation, ``Beefcake'' attempts to be several movies at once. It
may have plenty of nudity, but dramatically speaking, there are
more condiments here than beef.
</P>
<P>
   Writer-director Thom Fitzgerald (``The Hanging Garden'') takes
us to the hep-talkin', big-daddio world of 1950s Hollywood. It's a
candy-colored place where handsome, wide-eyed wannabes could find
themselves ushered into a poolside wonderland of well-muscled men
wearing nothing but teeny-tiny posing pouches. And, sometimes, not
even that.
</P>
<P>
   The newest arrival as ``Beefcake'' begins is played by Josh
Peace, whose character's name, in a nod to ``Valley of the Dolls,''
sets the tone: Neil O'Hara. He's welcomed into the circle of Bob
Mizer (Daniel MacIvor), a shutterbug whose Athletic Model Guild is
responsible for turning out ``physical culture'' books and films.
His oeuvre consists of oiled, half-naked fellows frolicking with a
mock innocence that only underscores their tableaux's blatant
homoeroticism. ``So who watches these films, anyway?'' asks Neil,
oblivious to the fact that, in the closeted world of the '50s, this
is pre-Stonewall pornography for gay men.
</P>
<P>
   ``Beefcake's'' faux-naif tone switches bluntly when it
re-creates the court trial of Mizer, charged with running a male
prostitution ring. In case we miss the point, Fitzgerald shoots
these scenes in black and white. The movie is also peppered with
interviews from actual models or leaders of the big-beauty-boy
culture, including Jack LaLanne and Joe D'Allesandro (the
model-actor who went on to let it all hang out in several Andy
Warhol flicks).
</P>
<P>
   The movie's blend of camp, talking heads and nudie naughtiness
is always engaging, but it never adds up to a coherent whole. By
the final (and amusing) credits, you'll appreciate the wiggy,
make-believe world that Mizer and his ilk created to circumvent the
moral codes of the time. And you can understand why Fitzgerald
wanted to explore the territory. But you might be justified in
feeling that ``Beefcake'' is sometimes just as cheerfully
exploitative as the Mizer movies of yore.
</P>
<P>
   ``Beefcake''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C+
</P>
<P>
   Starring Daniel MacIvor and Josh Peace. Unrated, but contains
simulated sex and lots of nudity.1 hour, 36 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: A cheerful , campy but empty-headed look at
homoeroticism, 1950s-style.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Murray writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-01-00 1646EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000601.0201 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 16:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2023 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-MOVIES-FILTH02-COX     06-01 0862
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-FILTH02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sex Pistols: Vicious, rotten punks revisited
 &HT;    By Eleanor Ringel Gillespie
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Their season of discontent was absurdly brief _ 26 months. Yet
they resonated throughout the world in a way that few bands ever
have, before or since.
</P>
<P>
   ``They'' are the 1970s British punk rockers the Sex Pistols
(Johnny Rotten, Sid Vicious, Paul Cook and Steve Jones), who
managed to turn out one album and survive (barely) one U.S. tour
before imploding. But their impact, as the sensational documentary
``The Filth and the Fury'' points out, was such that they
``achieved notoriety in 19 languages.''
</P>
<P>
   Filmmaker Julien Temple examines this notoriety with an ardent,
cutting-edge artfulness that expertly captures The Way It Was when
four young men with nasty attitudes could knock a nation on its
ear. Temple, whose style is a shrewd mixture of MTV fast cuts and
mid-'70s outrageousness, knows the Pistols made a lot of music
(some of it pretty bad) and made a lot of headlines. Most of all,
however, they made a commotion. They shook people up. As Rotten,
aka John Lydon, says, ``This band wasn't about making people happy.
It was about attack. Attack, attack, attack.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes the public attacked back. Rotten literally feared for
his life when he went out. (Rightly so; he was once slashed on the
streets by a razor-wielding nonfan.) So did the music industry.
When the Pistols' ``God Save the Queen'' made it to the top of the
Billboard chart, the line on that chart was left blank.
</P>
<P>
   Temple first profiled the Pistols in a 1980 documentary called
``The Great Rock 'n' Roll Swindle,'' which told their story mostly
from the point of view of their dandyish manager, Malcolm McLaren.
He insisted that the Pistols were his creation, sort of his
personal performance-art project. The new film lets the band
members have their say, in which they often contradict McLaren and
sometimes one another. In a gesture that verges on gallantry,
however, Temple keeps them shrouded in shadows. We never see Johnny
Rotten at fortysomething. He remains frozen in the '70s, a raging,
charismatic punk Peter Pan.
</P>
<P>
   Sid Vicious, aka John Ritchie, remains frozen in the '70s as
well. That's because, after allegedly stabbing his junkie
girlfriend, Nancy Spungen, to death in the Chelsea Hotel, he died
of a heroin overdose. Still, thanks to the earlier film and some
recently discovered early footage, Vicious appears _ in interviews,
in performance and, finally, in the sad final phase of his
self-destructive addiction, nodding off on camera or stumbling
around the stage like the walking dead.
</P>
<P>
   The walking dead is pretty much how Rotten saw _ and still sees
_England circa 1976, when the Pistols were born. Temple underscores
this view with a crafty use of clips, ranging from Laurence Olivier
as ``Richard III'' (his refrain, ``deformed, unfinished,'' was one
of Rotten's influences) and bits by ghastly/jolly English comics of
the era to shots of riots in the street while the posh set go on
with their tea and crumpets as if the Empire still stood.
</P>
<P>
   The picture's title is taken from a tabloid headline after a
particularly rowdy appearance on the BBC. The band is stoned; but
then, so is their host. In fact, that's one of the fascinations of
this film. Twenty-five years later, the Pistols, with their torn
shirts and safety-pin accessories, look more ``normal'' than the
absurd wide-tied, blow-dried TV pundits who interview them. The
idea that they were competing on the charts with the likes of the
Bee Gees or Kansas or, heaven help us, leftover David Cassidy, is
an astonishing juxtaposition.
</P>
<P>
   The film has a few problems. First, it's a bit like a typical
Rotten song: repetitive. We get the point; we get the point; we get
...
</P>
<P>
   Second, unless you are exceptionally well-versed in the punk
scene chronology, you may have some trouble telling what happened
when. That Vicious started out as a fan and was a late addition to
the group comes as a real surprise to some of us. Temple never
quite lets us know when the transition was made.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, unless you've a very good ear for voices, you may not
know who's saying what. Still, it's generally clear when the
endlessly quotable Rotten is speaking. He says the band was ``a bit
like a Harold Pinter play _ it shouldn't work but it does.'' And
pondering the Vicious-Spungen tragedy, he notes, ``I could take on
England, but I couldn't take on one heroin addict.''
</P>
<P>
   Ah, but take on England they did. The Sex Pistols may not have
been the best band ever, but as a cultural phenomenon they were,
well, phenomenal. This movie reminds us what a short, strange trip
it's been, taking us through a spit-smeared looking glass to a time
so close and yet so very far away.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Filth and the Fury''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A-
</P>
<P>
   A documentary. Rated R for profanity, sexual content and drug
use. 1 hour,
</P>
<P>
   45 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: The Sex Pistols rampage again! Nostalgia with an
attitude.
</P>
<P>
   Eleanor Ringel Gillespie writes for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
