<HEADER>
A2024 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-MOVIES-MOMMA02-COX     06-01 0475
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-MOMMA02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Martin Lawrence large and in charge as `Big Momma'
 &HT;    By Bob Longino
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Big Momma's House'' is one super-sized Martin Lawrence.
</P>
<P>
   As an FBI agent on a neighborhood stakeout to capture a vicious
bank robber, Lawrence dons layer upon layer of prosthetics to
impersonate a 325-pound, small-town granny in Cartersville (the
movie, however, was filmed in Los Angeles). The results may be
predictable, but with Lawrence's manic comedic timing they are also
occasionally quite funny.
</P>
<P>
   Part ``Witness,'' part ``Mrs. Doubtfire,'' ``Big Momma'' is
mostly a series of sight gags (Big Momma in a tent dress pouring on
the grease in a cast-iron skillet to cook up burned pork chops,
squeezed into tights to join a kung fu class, meshed with a triple
X-sized jersey to help a little boy on an outdoor basketball court
and prove to a couple of young bullies that granny's got game).
</P>
<P>
   At its most inspired, ``Big Momma'' goes to church with Lawrence
donning leopard-spotted gloves, an enormous white suit, heels and
hat to witness to a receptive congregation (Oscar winner Greg
Cannom did the star's makeup). ``I have lusted in my heart,''
Lawrence's granny meekly says, ``in my living room, in a hot tub
and in the back of an El Camino.''
</P>
<P>
   Somewhere in all of this is a story. It involves an on-the-lam
Sherry (Nia Long), suspected of helping the bank robber. She's fled
the big city with her young son to take refuge at Big Momma's
house. Big Momma is the grandmother she hasn't seen in years and,
naturally, Lawrence falls hard for her.
</P>
<P>
   While much of the plot is your standard-issue drag show plus
one, big, inexplicable out-of-nowhere boo scare, ``Big Momma'' does
briefly reach for something more. At least twice, Lawrence's macho
agent morphs into a more fully realized woman (in one instance,
lecturing an aging _ and overly aggressive _ suitor in how to woo a
woman and loudly proclaiming, ``I am not street booty''). It hints
at the kind of moments that made Dustin Hoffman's ``Tootsie'' and
Jack Lemmon's ``Some Like It Hot'' truly remarkable movies.
</P>
<P>
   And ``Big Momma'' is indeed Lawrence's gig. Most of the
supporting cast simply hover on screen. As the bank robber Lester,
the able actor Terrence Howard (``The Best Man'') has virtually
nothing to do but look sinister.
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence's ``Big Momma,'' however, lives large. It's a small
film with one hefty impersonation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Big Momma's House''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B-
</P>
<P>
   Starring Martin Lawrence and Nia Long. Rated PG-13 for crude
humor including sexual innuendo and for profanity and violence. 1
hour, 39 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: Predictable plot but plenty of laughs.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Longino writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
