<SLUG> BC-HAMLET-ALMEREYDA-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALMEREYDA TURNED TO OLIVIER TO GUIDE HIM THROUGH `HAMLET' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SEAN AXMAKER  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Director Michael Almereyda's big business ``Hamlet'' is firmly
set in the high tech world of modern New York but for inspiration
he looked back.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Olivier was a great guide,'' says Almereyda, referring
to Sir Laurence Olivier's 1948 British production, still considered
by many as the finest screen adaptation of the play. ``Olivier
slashed it. He's held up as the one to beat but he cut out
Rosencrantz and Guildenstern, he cut out Fortenbras.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He cut out `Oh what a rogue,' '' chimes in Ethan Hawke,
Almereyda's young Hamlet.
</P>
<P>
   ``He allowed the text to breathe,'' continues Almereyda,
``partly by cutting it and partly by introducing interludes where
the camera just prowls around the castle. He focused very sharply
on things he had absolute conviction in. Instead being intimidated
by Olivier's or anyone else's version, we just wanted to do the
best we could on our own terms.''
</P>
<P>
   Almereyda and Hawke use the possessive ``we'' to include the
collaboration of their rich cast, which includes veteran performers
(Sam Shepard and Kyle Maclachlan), young stars (Julie Styles and
Steve Zahn), funnyman Bill Murray in a serious role (``He had never
died in a movie before,'' notes Almereyda, who can now lay claim as
the man who first killed Bill Murray), and two performers who have
portrayed the melancholy Dane themselves on stage _ Liev Schreiber
and Diane Venora.
</P>
<P>
   ``One way of showing that you love something is to be able to
include a sense of play,'' the director says. ``Everyone involved
in the project was there because they wanted to work with
Shakespeare, they wanted to say those words. It's like wanting to
sing a song, but we wanted to do it our own way and make it as
immediate and urgent and true to ourselves as we could make it and
hope that other people would share those feelings.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Hamlet'' is in many ways the ultimate role for an actor, which
may explain why so many cinematic incarnations have been, shall we
say, a little more mature than the written role suggests _ he is,
after all, a student returning from college (``the perpetual grad
student,'' quips Almereyda). Hawke is the youngest actor to tackle
the role in a feature film.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always felt when I read it that it was a young man's
part, that it was the emotional life of a young man,'' Hawke
confesses. ``There's this great Holden Caulfield line (from
``Catcher in the Rye'') about seeing Laurence Olivier play Hamlet,
which is that he wasn't as phony as all the rest of the actors but
he still played Hamlet more like a general than the pathetic guy he
had imagined him to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Their ``Hamlet'' may take place in the skyscrapers and city
streets of a steel and glass New York City, but the words are
distinctly Shakespeare's.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a conceit, of course. All the way through, they're
speaking heightened language, but I wanted it to be more felt, to
seem more internal and not blustery,'' says Almereyda.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shakespeare was an actor and very aware on a fundamental level
that civilization is made up of people acting all the time, acting
as fathers, acting as lovers. We're playing roles all the time, and
in `Hamlet' almost every character has a role to play and they have
a mask that they very consciously wear.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
