<HEADER>
A2028 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-BLOOM-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT     06-01 1074
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLOOM-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`HOW TO READ AND WHY': LITERATURE'S GREATEST HITS _ INSTRUCTIONS
FOR USERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Editors: publication notes at end of review)  
 By MICHIKO KAKUTANI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Not so long ago, it would have seemed preposterous for a serious
scholar to bother writing a book titled ``How to Read and Why,''
but in our digital, image-driven age, the eminent teacher and
critic Harold Bloom apparently feels it is necessary to reiterate
the reasons why we read. The resulting book, like so many of the
author's recent works, is a hodgepodge of erudite analysis,
familiar arguments, pompous grandstanding and lengthy digressions;
it might well have been subtitled ``My Favorite Books and Why I
Like Them.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the reasons Bloom gives for reading will be obvious to
anyone who loves books: that we read to ``enlarge life,'' to enter
an ``alternate reality,'' to be ``liberated into perspectives not
previously available'' to us. We read for knowledge _ of the world,
of others and of ourselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why read?'' Bloom asks. ``Because you can know, intimately,
only a very few people, and perhaps you never know them at all.
After reading `The Magic Mountain' you know Hans Castorp
thoroughly, and he is greatly worth knowing.''
</P>
<P>
   Other reasons that Bloom offers for reading are less persuasive,
couched, as they are, in the utilitarian _ and for this author
unlikely _ language of a self-help manual. We read, he writes, ``to
strengthen the self, and to learn its authentic interests.'' Poems,
he contends, ``can help us to speak to ourselves more clearly and
more fully, and to overhear that speaking,'' while novels can treat
the ``dark inertia, the sickness-unto-death'' we experience in
daily life. ``Our despair requires consolation,'' he adds, ``and
the medicine of a profound narration.''
</P>
<P>
   Though such observations on the how and whys of reading are
supposedly this book's raison d'etre, they actually feel like
afterthoughts, grafted onto a meandering discussion of works of
literature Bloom admires. Among others, he talks about short
stories by Turgenev, Chekhov, Hemingway and Calvino; poems by
Tennyson, Dickinson, Wordsworth and Keats; novels by Austen,
Dickens, Proust and Mann; and plays by Shakespeare, Ibsen and
Wilde. Bloom, who is Sterling Professor of Humanities at Yale
University and Berg Professor of English at New York University,
explicates such authors' works as if he were lecturing to a class,
setting forth his prodigiously learned but often arbitrary
judgments with sweeping grandiosity.
</P>
<P>
   As he did in his 1994 magnum opus, ``The Western Canon,'' Bloom
demonstrates his taste in these pages for categorizing literary
works and ranking them in strict hierarchies. He declares that
modern short stories are either Chekhovian or Borgesian, the first
gratifying ``our hunger for reality,'' the second teaching us ``how
ravenous we still are for what is beyond supposed reality.'' He
asserts that ``Don Quixote'' is the best of all novels, and that
Cormac McCarthy's ``Blood Meridian'' is ``the strongest imaginative
work by any living American writer.''
</P>
<P>
   As for human nature, he suggests that all people _ not to
mention all literary characters _ can be divided into four types:
Hamlets, Falstaffs, Don Quixotes or Sancho Panzas.
</P>
<P>
   The author of ``The Anxiety of Influence'' (1973), Bloom is
perhaps best known for his Freudian theory of poetic influence,
which suggests that writers are shaped by their Oedipal struggle to
free themselves from the legacy of their literary forefathers, and
this volume underscores what a fierce hold this theory still exerts
over his critical imagination.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, ``How to Read and Why'' often reads like a complicated
genealogical chart, with virtually every writer eventually tracing
his lineage back to Shakespeare, Bloom's all-time hero and the
subject of his last book, ``Shakespeare: The Invention of the
Human.''
</P>
<P>
   Apparently it's not only Dostoyevsky who took character-writing
lessons from Shakespeare, but Chekhov, too; and Chekhov, in turn,
Bloom argues, was ``the major influence upon all story writers
after him.'' Novelists who write about characters who change _ that
is, characters who evolve in the course of the story _ also owe a
debt to Shakespeare, Bloom contends; included in this group, he
says, are writers like Austen, Goethe, Stendhal, Philip Roth and
Cormac McCarthy.
</P>
<P>
   In another chapter, Bloom points out Melville's considerable
debts to Shakespeare, comparing Ahab to the likes of King Lear and
Macbeth, and he goes on to argue that writers as disparate as
Faulkner, Nathanael West, Thomas Pynchon, Ralph Ellison and Toni
Morrison ``are Melville's children.''
</P>
<P>
   Though this sort of genealogical analysis can illuminate certain
writers' evolution, it can also obscure genuine differences in
their voices and their visions, and the ways they have been shaped
by the cultural zeitgeist of their day.
</P>
<P>
   In this volume, Bloom is so obsessive on the subject that he
sees influence everywhere he looks _ never mind whether that
influence is so vague as to seem illusory, or whether it actually
sheds light on a writer's work.
</P>
<P>
   He contends that Hemingway ``is most Shakespearean'' when he
``is most ambitious in his stories,'' as in the case of the
quasi-autobiographical ``Snows of Kilimanjaro.'' He insists that
``Turgenev is one of the most Shakespearean of writers in that he
too refrains from moral judgments.''
</P>
<P>
   And he argues that Coleridge's ``Rime of the Ancient Mariner''
is ``Shakespearean in its detachment of tone.''
</P>
<P>
   There are other problems with this book as well. Many of Bloom's
assessments of individual writers and larger cultural developments
are debatable at best.
</P>
<P>
   He highhandedly declares that ``literary parody expired'' with
Nathanael West. And he contends that contemporary culture suffers
from a ``loss of irony,'' rather than a surfeit.
</P>
<P>
   More alarmingly, he repeatedly asserts that writers like Milton
and Wallace Stevens ``require mediation'' if the lay reader is to
understand them. There is the suggestion in such remarks that there
is only one way to read such writers, and that most people need
someone like Harold Bloom to tell them how to do it. Such an
outlook manages to be patronizing and self-congratulatory all at
the same time. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `HOW TO READ AND WHY'
</P>
<P>
   By Harold Bloom
</P>
<P>
   283 pages. Scribner. $25.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-01-00 1649EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000601.0206 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 16:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2029 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-THEATER-NOTES-NYT     06-01 0993
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THEATER-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWS OF THE GREAT WHITE WAY 
</HEADLINE>
  By JESSE McKINLEY    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Big Women and `Little Women'
</P>
<P>
   Even as Sunday's Tony Awards signal the end of one season,
another slate of shows is wheeling into sight, whether you're ready
or not.
</P>
<P>
   First comes news of the return of a celebrated one-woman play
whose star has been absent from the Broadway stage for nearly 15
years.
</P>
<P>
   It is Jane Wagner's ``Search for Signs of Intelligent Life in
the Universe,'' a panoramic look at a group of radicals, corporate
tools and homeless visionaries, all inhabiting the body and mind of
Lily Tomlin.
</P>
<P>
   The show was a critical and popular hit in 1985 and subsequently
toured extensively. Tomlin won a Tony for her performance and soon
became a film star.
</P>
<P>
   Now she is returning to Broadway, having dusted off the piece
last summer during a long American tour. ``Search'' is to open on
Nov. 16 after playing at the Seattle Repertory Theater and the
McCarter Theater in Princeton, N.J. The plan is for a 10-week run
at a Shubert theater, possibly the Booth.
</P>
<P>
   Tomlin said the impetus came after she and Wagner showed a short
portion of ``Search'' to students in a workshop at the University
of Southern California. ``The kids had never seen it,'' Tomlin said
in a telephone interview from Los Angeles. ``And they just
responded.''
</P>
<P>
   The opening date, however, may sound awfully familiar to the
producers of ``Little Women,'' the musical adaptation of the Louisa
May Alcott novel. The piece, being produced by Randall L. Wreghitt
(``The Beauty Queen of Leenane'') and Dani Davis, had a reading in
April. That was followed in short order by the dismissal of the
original songwriting team.
</P>
<P>
   In their place are Mindi Dickstein, a lyricist whose most recent
stage credits include versions of the children's stories ``Black
Beauty'' and ``Little Red Riding Hood,'' and the composer Jason
Howland, a protege of Frank Wildhorn. Howland had been a producer
on it.
</P>
<P>
   That hiccup aside, ``Little Women'' still plans a Sept. 27
opening in Boston and a Nov. 16 opening at the Ambassador Theater
on Broadway.
</P>
<P>
   Spokesmen for both shows said they were confident that their
dates were solid, but someone will probably make way because
producers are loathe to share their big night. Luckily for them,
they have six months _ and the entire Tony telecast _ to sort
things out.
</P>
<P>
   Return of Vidal
</P>
<P>
   It's been more than two months since producers began to talk
about a revival of ``The Best Man,'' Gore Vidal's 1960 satire set
in the hothouse environs of a presidential campaign. But now the
project appears to be moving ahead with a surprising cast.
</P>
<P>
   No contracts have been signed, but Jeffrey Richards, one of its
producers, says that Spalding Gray, the acclaimed monologuist, has
agreed to appear, alongside Charles Durning and Elizabeth Ashley.
Gray would play William Russell, an upstanding presidential
candidate with a secret or three, while Durning would be the ailing
President Hockstader. Ashley would play Gammage, the coy national
committee chairwoman.
</P>
<P>
   An agent privy to the negotiations said Kyle MacLachlan had also
been approached, but Richards would not confirm that. Ethan
McSweeney (``Never the Sinner'') will direct.
</P>
<P>
   Vidal, never shy to opine, said he was extremely pleased with
the casting if not with the process.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was no problem casting 40 years ago unless you wanted
Marilyn Monroe,'' he said, speaking from Ravello, Italy, where he
lives. ``Today, the actors might still be available, but these
agents in Hollywood would rather have their client play a small
role in a western to be shot on speculation in Tucson rather than
put him in `Hamlet' on Broadway.''
</P>
<P>
   If all goes ahead, Vidal would come back to the States to see
his opening. The show is expected to arrive on Broadway in
September and run through the general election, probably closing
right before the inauguration in January. That timing would also be
felicitous for Vidal; his latest history, ``The Golden Age,'' about
World War II, is to be published by Doubleday in September. And on
Oct. 4 he turns 75.
</P>
<P>
   How does he feel his examination of 1950s politics fares in the
current political climate?
</P>
<P>
   ``The first thing that you or anyone would notice is there's no
mention of money,'' Vidal said. ``No hard money or soft money.
Nobody talks about it.''
</P>
<P>
   He doesn't plan to update it to fit today's cash-dominated
scene. ``The audience is going to be transported to the days of
Dick Nixon and Jack Kennedy,'' he said. ``You're going to see what
we took for granted.''
</P>
<P>
   Eviction of a Legend
</P>
<P>
   Think of Stella Adler, and one almost instantly imagines the
fervent early years of American theater, when Stanislavsky was
king, matinee tickets were $1 and theaters were grand. But now the
acting school that bears that legendary actress' name is in danger
of becoming homeless.
</P>
<P>
   The Stella Adler Conservatory, which Adler founded in 1949 and
taught at until her death in 1992, has been at 419 Lafayette St. in
the East Village for a decade, just down the block from the Public
Theater. But this year the conservatory was told it would be
evicted when its lease expires next summer.
</P>
<P>
   While that is over a year away, the school needs to raise $1.5
million to guarantee a new home. Tom Oppenheim, the conservatory's
artistic director and Adler's grandson, said the timing _ during an
inflated real estate market _ could not be worse.
</P>
<P>
   ``I looked at a space at 26th Street and 11th Avenue last year,
which was $15 per square foot,'' Oppenheim said. ``Now its $40 per
square foot.''
</P>
<P>
   To raise the money, Oppenheim has turned to foundations and past
students. The school lists luminaries like Marlon Brando, Warren
Beatty and Harvey Keitel as alumni.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there is a positive aspect to all of this,'' Oppenheim
said, ``it's that it connects us to alumni and the theater
community.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-01-00 1652EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
