<DOCNO> NYT20000601.0208 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 16:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2033 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-POL-TICKER0602-COX     06-01 1950
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POL-TICKER0602-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    POLITICAL TICKER: Purported gore plan in secret memo
 &HT;    (EDs: A brief roundup of the day's campaign events, pulled from
Cox staff and wire reports.)
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Justice Department investigators have uncovered a memo
describing a proposed strategy for Al Gore to help a longtime
friend and Democratic fund-raiser obtain a $400 million federal
contract. The document's origin is unknown, and Gore says he knows
nothing about it and never intervened. The undated three-paragraph
memo _ unaddressed and unsigned _ suggests that ``Gore has called
or is ready to call'' then-General Services Administration chief
Roger Johnson in an attempt to help developer Franklin Haney lease
a planned office building, the Portals, to the Federal
Communications Commission.
</P>
<P>
   AND MAY IT GO BETTER THAN SOME OF THOSE OTHER `WARS'
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore, speaking at Emory University Medical Center in Atlanta
today, promised to lead ``a war'' on cancer and offered a proposal
to speed Medicare coverage for preventive screenings that the human
genome research project promises. He also called for measures to
keep medical records private and to ban employment and health
insurance discrimination against workers who find through genetic
testing that they are predisposed to disease.
</P>
<P>
   COOPERATION OVER CONFLICT
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush proposed tax incentives for private conservation
efforts and more money for federal programs to promote preservation
instead of simply placing land off-limits by federal order.
Standing on the shores of Lake Tahoe in Nevada, Bush criticized the
Clinton-Gore administration, which he said has steadily increased
the government's grasp on forests, monument properties and
seashores. Saying ``this Washington-centered mindset'' breeds
resentment and conflict, Bush said it's time to build conservation
partnerships among the federal and state governments, local
communities and private landowners.
</P>
<P>
   HOLDING HIS FEET TO THE CAMPFIRE
</P>
<P>
   In a close presidential race, Al Gore can't afford to lose any
traditionally Democratic voting sector. However, on securing the
votes of environmentalists, Gore has been paddling in rough waters.
Over the years, he's worked hard on his environmental resume,
written a book ``Earth in the Balance,'' drawn attention to global
warming and been pictured hiking and canoeing in the wilderness.
But some enviros are bitterly disappointed in his record under
President Clinton, and Gore's environmental allies worry that Green
Party candidate Ralph Nader will siphon off votes.
</P>
<P>
   BLOWING SMOKE ON JOB LOSSES?
</P>
<P>
   Confronted by a handful of angry tobacco workers in Macon, Ga.,
who said they feel the federal government is trying to eliminate
their jobs, Al Gore said he doesn't want to make cigarettes illegal
and would do what he could to protect tobacco-industry jobs _ so
long as it doesn't undercut efforts to keep kids from smoking. ``I
am happy to do anything I can to help you preserve your livelihood,
but I am not going to say or do anything that in any way undermines
or weakens the toughest possible measures to prevent children from
ever getting into the habit of smoking. Now if that costs me votes,
I'm willing to pay that price,''
</P>
<P>
   KEYES `FINE' _ AS A NO. 2
</P>
<P>
   Constitution Party candidate Howard Phillips told reporters that
he thinks Alan Keyes ``would be a fine running mate''for his party
if Keyes left the Republican Party. Phillips: ``I have invited
(Keyes) to join our ticket, although it is my intention to remain
as presidential candidate.''
</P>
<P>
   THE HILLARY AMBITION TOUR? . . .
</P>
<P>
   Rick Lazio launched one of his most stinging attacks yet against
Hillary Clinton, asking whether his Senate rival's campaign is
``about ambition, or is this about public service?'' Lazio said New
Yorkers should ask candidates: ``What have you done for us for the
last eight years? Have you been in our corner, or are you just a
Johnny-come-lately who is aspiring to a position?'' He also told
reporters: ``This is a struggle between somebody on the far left
and somebody in the center.'' What makes Clinton a far-leftist? Her
unsuccessful attempt to overhaul the nation's health care system,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   . . . OR THE NEW YORK STATE OF MIND
</P>
<P>
   Hillary Clinton took an aggressively combative tone against her
new Senate opponent, criticizing Rick Lazio for operating what she
said was a campaign based on insults and asserting that her
positions better reflected the views of mainstream New Yorkers.
``While my opponent tells you where he's from, I'm going to tell
you what I'm for,'' Clinton said at the lower Manhattan
headquarters of the carpenters union. ``This is not about who's
from New York; this is about who will fight the right fights for
all New Yorkers.''
</P>
<P>
   HOME LOAN BEEF TOSSED OUT
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Election Commission dismissed a complaint against
Hillary Clinton over an arrangement for a home loan. The
Conservative Campaign Fund alleged in September that the first lady
and Terry McAuliffe, a friend and one of President Clinton's chief
fund-raisers, violated federal election law when McAuliffe agreed
to co-sign for the Clintons' $1.7 million home in Westchester
County _ in effect, providing a huge campaign contribution.
Criticism of the arrangement led the Clintons to finance the
five-bedroom house themselves.
</P>
<P>
   THE VICTIM TRAP
</P>
<P>
   Rick Lazio has a good chance to defeat Hillary Clinton ``if he
doesn't treat her as a victim,'' said George W. Bush. His comment
was picked up by an open mike during a break while taping a Chris
Matthews ``Hardball'' show on MSNBC. Bush to Matthews: ``I think he
is going to win if he doesn't make a mistake, if he doesn't treat
her as a victim.'' Clinton's popularity soared in public opinion
polls as a result of her husband's impeachment battle with
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   THIS IS YOUR LIFE
</P>
<P>
   Besides trying to spotlight Al Gore's personal side by mixing
slices of his biography into policy addresses, the Democratic
National Commitee plans to spend at least $20 million for ads
focusing on Gore's life. In a first step toward launching the ad
campaign in the next couple of weeks, party officials have asked
about the availability of TV time in at least a dozen states.
Officials in both parties say the states include Michigan,
Pennsylvania, Ohio, New Mexico, Iowa, West Virginia and Gore's
homestate of Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   GOING WITH THE MAN IN MISSOURI
</P>
<P>
   Eyeing an open seat in the House, top Republicans are wading
forcefully into a contested primary as the party picks a candidate
to replace retiring Democratic Rep. Pat Danner of Missouri. Speaker
Dennis Hastert reportedly intends to campaign for state Sen. Sam
Graves. That will come as a disappointment to Kansas City Council
member Teresa Loar. ``I haven't heard from (party leaders), but
I've heard from a number of sources that they prefer a white
conservative male to a moderate female,'' she told the Associated
Press. Danner is undergoing treatment for breast cancer.
</P>
<P>
   THE VEEP GLASS CEILING
</P>
<P>
   The cheering, foot-stamping and tears lasted for eight minutes
after Geraldine Ferraro accepted the Democratic nomination for vice
president in 1988, the first woman to be nominated by a major
party.
</P>
<P>
   Sixteen years later, both major party candidates say they are
considering women for the No. 2 spot. But despite gains made by
women elsewhere in politics, most observers figure the chances for
a female veep this year are slim. ``It's ironic that women voters
are such a key target group and yet there is so little talk about a
woman for V.P.,'' said Celinda Lake, a Democratic pollster.
</P>
<P>
   SURPRISE _ MONEY'S THE ISSUE
</P>
<P>
   At the beginning of the New Jersey race for Democratic Senate
nomination, the issues largely were the tax increases that cost Jim
Florio re-election as governor in 1993, Social Security and health
insurance. But now, with only days to go before the primary, Jon
Corzine's record-shattering $33 million campaign spending spree is
the biggest issue, transforming the ex-Wall Street investment
banker from unknown to favorite in a matter of months. Florio has
spent only $2 million on his own campaign.
</P>
<P>
   TOTAL ACCESS _ AT A PRICE
</P>
<P>
   An association of county governments, partially funded by local
taxpayer dollars, contributed $20,000 each to the Democratic and
Republican parties to help get the ears of elected officials in
Washington. The five-figure ``soft money'' donations allow
officials of the National Association of Counties to attend
contributor-only luncheons, briefings and other congressional
events. ``Participating in these two groups gives us access to
leadership on both sides ... additional access that we may not
have,'' said association spokesman Tom Goodman.
</P>
<P>
   E-MAIL WARS OF ENDLESS WORDS
</P>
<P>
   Presidential campaigns have always whispered nasty little
nothings about the opposition into reporters' ears. But just as
e-mail has ushered in a new era of communication ease and
connectedness for the world at large, it also has created a
hyper-efficient form of press release, a paperless document that
not only links the political world to the nation's assignment
editors, columnists and news anchors in seconds, but also allows
the campaigns to fire at each other at will, all day long. As a
result, a presidential campaign is no longer so much a series of
stops as an endless wave.
</P>
<P>
   DRUG PUNISHMENT GOING TO A VOTE
</P>
<P>
   A measure that would send nonviolent drug offenders for drug
treatment instead of to jail has qualified for California's
November ballot. The measure would require those convicted of
possession to receive treatment and probation. Anyone convicted of
selling or making drugs would be excluded, as would those with a
record of violent crimes. Passage is estimated to save taxpayers up
to $150 million in annual prison operation costs and up to $575
million in prison construction costs. The ballot initiative was
backed by billionaire George Soros. It is opposed by police and
prison guards.
</P>
<P>
   SO GET TOGETHER, TALK ABOUT IT
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-two Senate Democrats jumped into the debate over Social
Security, writing to George W. Bush for more details on his
proposal to create individual investment accounts ``so that the
American public, elected officials and other policy-makers can
evaluate your proposal. ... The public needs the full details of
any proposals,'' the Democrats wrote. Bush spokesman Ari Fleischer
said Bush welcomed bipartisan input and supported a proposal by a
bipartisan group of senators to have a commission study changes to
the retirement system.
</P>
<P>
   17 DOWN, 33 TO GO
</P>
<P>
   Ralph Nader is now on the ballot in 17 states, according to CNN.
``We expect to be on 40 states by the end of June, and we're going
for all 50 by the end of summer,'' Nader said in an interview. The
Christian Science Monitor said Nader's bid ``is attracting enough
liberal support in key states to make life difficult for Al Gore
this fall.''
</P>
<P>
   AS CLOSE TO A PHOTO OP AS HE'LL GET
</P>
<P>
   Ralph Nader, with head down and shoulders stooped and clutching
his trademark stuffed brown folder, appeared oblivious to the crowd
calling to him on his way to a recent campaign appearance in New
Haven, Conn. ``Nader, remarkably devoid of charisma despite nearly
40 years in the public eye, wasn't interested in introducing
himself to the others,'' the Boston Globe said.
</P>
<P>
   _Compiled by Ernie Freda from staff and news reports.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
