<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 16:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2034 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-TV-WEEKEND-NYT &LR;      06-01 0984
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-WEEKEND-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`HARLAN COUNTY WAR' AND `SEX IN THE CITY' 
</HEADLINE>
  (Production notes at end of review) 
 By RON WERTHEIMER    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sure, Holly Hunter is a remarkable actor, but who would have
guessed she could do a dead-on impersonation of Jimmy Stewart?
Well, she can. It comes in a pivotal scene in ``Harlan County
War,'' when Hunter's character, Ruby Kincaid, whose husband and
father are striking coal miners, tries to persuade a group of women
to join their men on the picket line. She has Stewart nailed, right
down to those tongue-tied pauses.
</P>
<P>
   ``I watched scabs take my men's jobs,'' she says. ``They'd ah,
dah dah, they've been treating us like this since I's a little
girl. Yub yub yub, I'm gettin' sick to death of bein' pushed
around.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Ruby succeeds in convincing the other women. And yes, the
downtrodden miners ultimately succeed in their bitter fight with
the mine owners. But Hunter, luminous as she is, cannot succeed in
fleshing out this cardboard morality tale.
</P>
<P>
   The film, which Showtime is offering on Sunday night, is fiction
set inside the wrenching 13-month miners' strike in Kentucky that
was the subject of the Oscar-winning 1976 documentary ``Harlan
County, U.S.A.''
</P>
<P>
   As soon as you meet Ruby, you know she is one of nature's
noblewomen. She lives in a sad little company-owned shack with her
working-stiff husband, Silas (Ted Levine); her widowed daddy, Tug
Jones (Wayne Robson), a victim of black lung; and two angelic
children. She cooks, she sews, she hauls water (no indoor
plumbing), and she says, ``Nothin' ever bothers me.''
</P>
<P>
   Conditions in the mine are hellish, but when a union organizer,
Warren Jakopovich (Stellan Skarsgard) shows up, Ruby isn't
impressed. She tells him, ``You cain't ever change the way things
is done here.''
</P>
<P>
   Warren, a former miner born in Poland (as good a cover as any
for Skarsgard's Swedish accent), proves to be noble, too. Under his
guidance the miners call a strike, and a long standoff follows.
</P>
<P>
   Ruby begins to warm to the idea of the union, especially after
her daddy gives her one of the film's too many too-pat speeches:
``We been coal miners in this family since way back yonder. Pretty
good life. Get a contract, it'll be better.''
</P>
<P>
   She volunteers her pluck for the cause, becoming Warren's ally
and even accompanying him to New York to confront the president of
the mine's parent company at a shareholders' meeting, where she
delivers another Stewartesque oration. Scenes like this are meant
to tug at your heart, as the bluegrass-tinged score makes clear.
The banjo signals happy turns; the fiddle, sad ones.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the best efforts of the other actors, Hunter may as well
be in a one-women show here. There is no sexual tension, or human
engagement of any kind, between Warren and Ruby. Her moments with
Silas, even an explicit lovemaking scene, have no heat. Their
marriage is tested a bit by the strike and Ruby's newfound
independence, but matters are neatly resolved.
</P>
<P>
   Ruby's most fully realized encounter is with the fancy bathtub
in her New York hotel room. Her unvarnished wonder at the luxurious
plumbing is memorable, but the moment feels like an exercise from
acting class.
</P>
<P>
   Hunter looks wonderful in her simple cotton dresses, even if her
upper arms seem to have been sculptured by lifting weights, not
tubs of laundry. But strong as she is, she cannot lift this film,
written by Peter Silverman and directed by Tony Bill as more civics
lesson than drama. Nor can she breathe life into the down-home
dialogue.
</P>
<P>
   When Ruby tells a slimy mine executive why her husband chose to
strike, she says: ``That's why God give us tongues. If it don't
taste right, spit it out.''
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe change the channel.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `HARLAN COUNTY WAR'
</P>
<P>
   Showtime, Sunday night at 8
</P>
<P>
   Written by Peter Silverman; directed by Tony Bill. Robert W.
Cort, David Madden, Mimi Rogers and Chris Ciaffa, executive
producers; Keri Selig, co-producer; Flavio Labiano, director of
photography. Music by Van Dyke Parks.
</P>
<P>
   Cast: Holly Hunter (Ruby Kincaid); Stellan Skarsgard (Warren
Jakopovich), Ted Levine (Silas Kincaid), Wayne Robson (Tug Jones),
Alex House (Buddy Kincaid), Charlotte Arnold (Lucinda Kincaid), Ker
Wells (Little Lee) and Jennifer Irwin (Mary Ball).
</P>
<P>
   Comb your hair, Junior. Those four randy bachelorettes are back,
looking for love in all the wrong places. As ``Sex and the City''
begins its third season on HBO, Sunday night at 9, fragile Carrie
(Sarah Jessica Parker) is still trying to get over her breakup with
Big. Uncertain Miranda (Cynthia Nixon) is still on again, off again
with dogged Steve (David Eigenberg). Perky Charlotte (Kristin
Davis) still can't get her hands on the man of her dreams while
insatiable Samantha (Kim Cattrall) can't keep her hands off one
nightmare guy after another.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's episode opens with the four women standing, ``Titanic''
style, on the prow of a Staten Island ferry. Carrie is on her way
to judge a firefighters' beefcake contest and her friends are along
to ogle. Samantha finds a fireman to smolder with while Carrie
fends off the advances of a politician, Bill Kelly (John Slattery).
``He's way too I'm-the-guy,'' Carrie says. But before long she's
thinking about playing I'm-the-girl with him. Bill will be back in
the next episode, when Carrie hits the campaign trail and wonders
if there can be sex without politics.
</P>
<P>
   This series earns the adjective adult, both for its frank
presentation of its subject matter and its sophisticated look at
the childishness of grown-ups. Its four stars continue to work
together seamlessly. They keep their characters just this side of
caricature and they keep their viewers wondering how a half-hour
can zip by so quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Do women this adorable really travel in hungry packs around New
York?
</P>
<P>
   Dream on, Junior.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
