<HEADLINE>
`LEXX' EXPLORES SCI-FI'S LUSTIER SIDE 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of a scene from ``Lexx.'') 
 By CHRISTOPHER BLAND  
 c.2000 TV Guide Canada  
 Not to be published in Canada before June 11. 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features.)  
 &HT;    It has been called ``Star Trek's'' evil twin.
 &HT;    In the sci-fi series ``Lexx,'' there are no final frontiersmen
selflessly rescuing alien kittens from trees. Along the darkly
humorous edge of ``Lexx,'' lust bubbles and life is cheap.
 &HT;    As science fiction, it's something different. As television,
``Lexx'' is downright bizarre. ``Lexx'' is a siren of distinction
for its black comedy, skewed take on the human condition and open
sexuality, qualities that act as counterpoints to contemporary
sci-fi sensibilities, according to Lex Gigeroff, co-writer of the
show, along with Jeffrey Hirschfield _ who also voices the show's
lust-struck robot, 790 _ and executive producer Paul Donovan.
 &HT;    Perhaps some of its unique style comes from the fact that the
series is filmed in a remote area of Canada _ Halifax, Nova Scotia.
And the people behind the show are all dedicated to taking a
low-key, unassuming approach to the genre.
 &HT;    ``Science fiction has a tendency sometimes to be very pompous
about itself,'' Gigeroff says, speaking from the Halifax office of
Salter Street Films, which co-produces ``Lexx'' with Germany's Time
Film und TV Produktion.
 &HT;    ``We're really dealing with weighty issues here,'' he adds,
``but there's all sorts of ways of doing that. You can do that in a
heavy-handed way or in a bit more of an ironic or off-center way,
and I think that's the trick, trying to find the outside edge of
science fiction.''
 &HT;    Gigeroff realizes that ``Lexx'' is not the first show to walk
sci-fi's fringes, beginning with the landmark ``The Prisoner''
(1967), which starred Patrick McGoohan.
 &HT;    ``There were things like `The Prisoner,' which was certainly
dark at times,'' he says, ``and also things like `Dark Star,' John
Carpenter's dark 1974 space comedy.''
 &HT;    ``Lexx'' debuted in 1996 as four made-for-television movies
called ``Lexx: The Dark Zone Stories,'' now called season one. The
movies came two years after Paul Donovan's 1994 movie ``Paint
Cans,'' which featured Gigeroff and Canadian actor Michael McManus,
who plays ``Lexx's'' undead assassin, Kai.
 &HT;    Two years later, ``Lexx'' returned as a 13-part series, then
returned again this spring with 13 new segments. ``Lexx'' is most
popular in the United States, Canada, Britain, France and Germany.
Yet fans exist even farther abroad: Linked to ``Lexx's'' Web site
(www.Lexx.com) are a few sites in Russia.
 &HT;    On the simplest level, ``Lexx'' is the story of three space
outcasts _ Kai, Stanley Tweedle (Brian Downey) and Xev (Xenia
Seeburg) _ wandering space in a cybernetically enhanced insect
spacecraft, the Lexx.
 &HT;    ``It's a show that's not really connected to Earth in any way,''
Gigeroff says. ``They are not colonists from Earth ... So it kind
of gives you a lot of freedom, a really tremendous latitude to go
for it.''
 &HT;    That latitude resulted in a change to this season's story
structure. While season two was a series of stand-alone episodes,
this year is a narrative centered around an interplanetary war.
 &HT;    ``Paul really liked the idea of being able to take a bit more
time with some stories,'' Gigeroff says.
 &HT;    ``It's sometimes a challenge to create a wholly self-contained
little universe each week,'' he adds. ``You can take a bit of time
with some characters, which is what we tried to do with Nigel,''
meaning Nigel Bennett, the Emmy Award-winning Canadian actor cast
as season three's recurring character, Prince.
 &HT;    Another change involved Seeburg. Introduced during season two as
a replacement for German actress Eva Haberman, who played Xev's
progenitor, Zev, in the ``Lexx'' movies, Seeburg first appeared as
a savvy, red-haired love slave. The change to Seeburg's natural
blond tresses resulted during production this season, once Seeburg
was sure that fans had accepted her as Haberman's replacement.
 &HT;    ``People would see me like I look in real life, even the people
that I worked with, and they would always go, `Oh, Xenia, it's so
good to see you without that horrible red wig,''' Seeburg says from
her home in Dusseldorf, Germany. ``So finally it was like an
all-around agreement.''
 &HT;    A constant of the show has been its stunning digital effects,
created by Filmeffekte GMBH in Germany and CAGE Digital in Halifax.
Yet the effects, too, have evolved: This season was shot using
high-definition technology that was blended with digital imagery,
then treated on video for a film effect.
 &HT;    Perhaps the only thing that hasn't changed is the knack of the
cowardly captain, Stanley Tweedle, for routinely finding himself in
life-and-death situations.
 &HT;    ``We really think it's one of our missions in life to put Brian
Downey in as many uncomfortable shooting positions as possible,
just because he's such a great guy,'' Gigeroff jokes. ``Paul and I
will be talking about what we're doing, and Brian will come by and
ask, `What are you going to put me in next week?' And he does it
cheerfully.''
 &HT;    He's pleased that ``Lexx'' has won a fan base, but Gigeroff says
the producers never aimed for mass appeal.
 &HT;    ``We've always kind of wanted to try and get a little cult
show,'' he says. ``This is never going to be a show which everybody
is going to like. It was never meant to be.''
 &HT;    Some of the show's guest stars have been cult icons in their own
rights. Malcolm McDowell, who played an ultraviolent ``droogie'' in
``A Clockwork Orange'' (1971), has appeared. So have Rutger Hauer,
who was the tragic antagonist Roy Batty in ``Blade Runner'' (1982),
and Tim Curry, still best known as just a sweet transvestite in
``The Rocky Horror Picture Show'' (1975).
 &HT;    As for the future, Gigeroff refuses to speculate. Given the
precarious nature of television, he says, he's content for the
moment with what he calls ``an incredible rocket ride so far.''
 &HT;    (Christopher Bland is a staff writer for TV Guide Canada, based
in North York, Ontario.)
 c.2000 TV Guide Canada  
<TEXT>
 &UR; Distributed by New York Times Special Features. &QL;
<P>
   (EDITOR: For further information on ``Lexx,'' consult the
official Web site at www.lexx.com. Or visit the Sci-Fi Channel Web
site at www.scifi.com. And check out The New York Times Syndicate
Web site at http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for information on
StarBeat and other features.) &QL; 
