<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 16:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2042 &Cx1f; tab-z
w e BC-DON-BLUTH-TITAN-AE-ST     06-01 1282
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DON-BLUTH-TITAN-AE-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DON BLUTH, ON `TITAN A.E.,' IS AS ANIMATED AS EVER 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a photo of Don Bluth, co-director of ``Titan A.E.'') 
 By IAN SPELLING  
 c.2000 Ian Spelling  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features.)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Though warm as a campfire and always soft-spoken, animator Don
Bluth, the man behind such features as ``The Secret of NIMH''
(1982), ``An American Tail'' (1986), ``All Dogs Go To Heaven''
(1989) and ``Anastasia'' (1998), calls a spade a spade,
consequences be damned.
</P>
<P>
   There's a no-nonsense tone in his voice, an edge that just might
benefit his latest animated epic, ``Titan A.E.''
</P>
<P>
   Co-directed by Bluth and his longtime partner, Gary Goldman,
``Titan, A.E.'' unfolds in 3028, as aliens called the Drej destroy
the Earth, leaving a million survivors stranded in assorted drifter
colonies. One survivor, the cynical 20-year-old Cale (voiced by
Matt Damon), learns that he is genetically coded to be a map that
will lead to the Titan, a ship with the power to create a new
Earth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the earlier films I've done in my career are pretty
much in the area of Disney wannabes,'' Bluth says by telephone from
a Phoenix screening room, where he's racing to finish the film in
time for its June 16 release. ``They would have a terminal disease,
a terminal disease that I call cute.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything is very soft and round and cute and harmless,'' he
explains. ``That's what Disney is. We tried to shift over to an
edgier picture with `Titan A.E.,' one that's not a wannabe. We were
hunting for something that had a little more quills on it, that was
more prickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of digs in the dialogue, a lot of sarcasm,''
the director says. ``It's faster-paced than most of my films. I
don't think people can look at it and say it's in the Don Bluth
style.''
</P>
<P>
   Bluth laughs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if that's a good thing or a bad thing,'' he adds.
``I have no objectivity about this film. All I know is that it's
very different from anything I've done before.''
</P>
<P>
   Bluth and Goldman weren't supposed to make ``Titan A.E.'' They'd
crafted ``Anastasia'' at Fox's fledgling animation facility in
Arizona, followed that with a direct-to-video sequel, ``Bartok the
Magnificent'' (2000), and then sat empty-handed.
</P>
<P>
   Fox president Bill Mechanic then phoned Bluth and Goldman. The
two directors assigned to ``Titan A.E.'' _ then called ``Planet
Ice'' _ were off the project. Mechanic asked Bluth and Goldman to
pick up the baton, warning that time was of the essence.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had fewer months than we'd ever had before,'' Bluth
recalls, ``but we said, `If there's nothing else ready, we don't
have much choice, do we?' So we grabbed it.
</P>
<P>
   ``And, like any good soldier, I surrounded myself with sci-fi
brains who seemed to know all the genre movies that had ever been
made,'' he says. ``I said, `Tell me why some sci-fi movies are
really, really exciting, why some of them work so well.'''
</P>
<P>
   According to Bluth, his predecessors had sunk $30 million into
artwork and scripting before he ever put ink to acetate. Damon,
Drew Barrymore, Bill Pullman, Nathan Lane and Janeane Garofalo had
already recorded dialogue.
</P>
<P>
   Starting over, however, was out of the question.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `We're going to take this artwork and reorganize it,
so it's something we can use,''' Bluth says. ``I had a really good
art director and production designer. We shuffled through all of
this stuff and said, `OK, here's what we're going to do.' That
seemed to work out really well.
</P>
<P>
   ``Also, when I got into the picture, it seemed to me that the
entire focus was on the hardware,'' he recalls. ``I thought, `Who
wants to look at just hardware?' I was reminded that a lot of
people do.
</P>
<P>
   ``But a movie to me is about character, about how personalities
come together, how they relate to each other and what the
ramifications of that are,'' Bluth says. ``We went back, crammed in
more of the character material, re-recorded some of the dialogue,
and now character drives the story. We were on this film for many
months, and even in the last week new lines were being written.''
</P>
<P>
   Now that the film is about to be released, Bluth must face his
greatest nemesis: the Mouse House. As it has for ages, Walt Disney
Pictures will pit one of its own animated features directly against
Bluth's. ``Fantasia 2000'' will open nationwide on the same day
``Titan A.E.'' hits the screens.
</P>
<P>
   One might think there's enough room in the world for multiple
animated success stories. Bluth, however, doubts that Disney feels
that way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would often get angry,'' says Bluth, who toiled for Disney
as an animator on such films as ``Robin Hood'' (1973) and ``Pete's
Dragon'' (1978). ``I used to think, `How could they be so
uncharitable?' But business is business. I think that's the way
they look at it, that all is fair in business and they don't mind
who they kill.
</P>
<P>
   ``Disney is the giant,'' he says. ``Even though I'm working with
Fox, I still think of myself as the David. Disney has a lot of
muscle, and I don't suppose anybody really knows how much muscle
they do have. They can block and can do anything they have to do to
make sure they win.
</P>
<P>
   ``And it's all done with a very beautiful veneer, so no one ever
suspects there's anything sinister underneath it.''
</P>
<P>
   Complicating matters further, there's more at stake with ``Titan
A.E.'' than meets the eye. It's conceivable that Fox might give up
on animation entirely if ``Titan A.E.'' tanks. Dreamworks _ whose
animation division is helmed by another Disney refugee, Steve
Katzenberg _ will release ``Chicken Run'' this summer, but surely
can't abide too many disappointments along the lines of its most
recent effort, ``The Road to El Dorado'' (2000).
</P>
<P>
   ``Anastasia is in the black at this point, but it didn't really
go out there and change the world one bit,'' Bluth says. ``So we
went in for a second one, and I believe everyone is saying, `Well,
if this one doesn't work, then what?'
</P>
<P>
   ``In tandem with what we've been doing is Katzenberg. `Prince of
Egypt' (1998) was going to blow the world away and it didn't _ it's
not in the black yet. Right after that they did `Road to El
Dorado.' It was a little disappointing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unless somebody steps up, throws a spear and hits the coconut,
I think we're sort of pronouncing our own doom,'' Bluth says.
``It's no secret that Fox has laid off a lot of our staff. A lot.
There were 360 and it's down to 60. So there's a lot at stake.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Ian Spelling is a New York-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``Titan A.E.,'' consult the Fox
Web site at www.foxmovies.com. And check out The New York Times
Syndicate Web site at http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for
information on StarBeat and other features. &QL; 
