<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROCK-STAR-DON-HENLEY-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EAGLE ON HIS OWN: DON HENLEY SINGS FOR HIMSELF AND HIS FAMILY 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of rock star Don Henley.) 
 By GARY GRAFF  
 c.2000 Gary Graff  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features.)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Back in 1984, Don Henley _ the once and future singer/drummer
for the Eagles _ lamented in song that there was ``Not Enough Love
in the World.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, on his first solo album of all-new material in 11 years,
Henley informs us that ``I'm very, very happy/And I know that's not
what you'd expect from me at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Henley isn't kidding. He's been married since 1995 to Sharon
Summerall, a fellow Texan with whom he moved from California to a
home outside Dallas, where they're raising three children. He has
found a life's calling outside music in the Walden Woods Project,
an environmental-preservation organization. And this year he and
his Eagles partner Glenn Frey are being inducted into the
Songwriter's Hall of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, the spirit of bonhomie saturates Henley's new
album, ``Inside Job.'' There are still plenty of pointed social and
political commentaries amid the 13 tracks, but they're balanced by
songs that celebrate the happy state of his home life, including
``Nobody Else in the World But You,'' ``Taking You Home,''
``Everything is Different Now,'' ``My Thanksgiving'' and
``Annabel,'' a lullaby for his oldest daughter.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has certainly had an inspirational effect,'' the
52-year-old Henley says. ``At the risk of sounding like I've been
in some sort of self-help program _ which I haven't _ I've
rediscovered my better self. I feel in my mind and in my heart like
I did when I was in my early 20s, when I was in college _ and I'm
not drunk or high!''
</P>
<P>
   Henley is quick to add that he's always considered himself an
optimist, and he felt that as a songwriter his mission was to point
out that things could be better. But he also acknowledges that the
sweet tenor of ``Inside Job'' will catch off-guard those who are
used to the sharp tone of past hits such as ``Dirty Laundry,''
``Sunset Grill,'' ``All She Wants to Do is Dance'' and the
Grammy-winning ``The End of the Innocence.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It has crossed my mind that it might not be very well received
or it might even be ridiculed in some quarters,'' says Henley, who
moved to Los Angeles in 1970 with his band, Shiloh, before joining
Linda Ronstadt's band and subsequently forming the Eagles in 1971.
``But you know, I don't (care) anymore. This woman and these
children have helped me to rediscover myself, and I don't mind
putting that out there.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has been a very liberating thing for me,'' he adds. ``I've
gotten so much strength and courage from my family that I can
afford to be totally open and honest about how I feel. If people
like it, great. And if they don't, that's great, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Henley has not run out of dragons to slay, however. ``Workin'
It,'' the first single from ``Inside Job,'' offers Henley's take on
the current state of American society. ``They're Not Here, They're
Not Coming'' pokes fun at UFO disciples, while ``Damn It, Rose''
was inspired by a friend's suicide and deals with what Henley calls
``empty rebellion.''
</P>
<P>
   But while that kind of song used to dominate his albums and seep
into his other material, Henley feels that the fire doesn't burn
within him in quite the same way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can always go home to the children and to the wife, and the
world goes away for a little while,'' Henley says. ``That gives me
the strength and the serenity to live with those things. But, yes,
it has heightened my awareness and, yes, it has made me more angry.
But I think that's balanced, because my life is more balanced.''
</P>
<P>
   Henley _ who left his former label, Geffen, to move to Warner
Bros. Records for ``Inside Job'' _ does have a new battle to wage.
He and some other artists, including his former backup singer
Sheryl Crow, Billy Joel, Bonnie Raitt and Hole's Courtney Love,
have joined forces to fight the music industry and Congress over
what the musicians feel are actions that are being taken to strip
them of their rights to their own work.
</P>
<P>
   Henley explains that the 1976 Copyright Act provided for the
full return of an artist's work to that artist after 35 years. But
the Recording Industry Association of America, which represents the
record companies, has quietly inserted an amendment _ tagged onto
an unrelated bill _ that reclassified recordings as work for hire,
which allows the labels to own them forever.
</P>
<P>
   This is part of the ``greedfest'' that has followed the recent
spate of entertainment-industry mergers, Henley says, and he feels
that ``it's just the first shot across the bow from the record
company. I think they're going to keep on trying to ... cheat
artists out of the rights to their work.''
</P>
<P>
   Henley expects the amendment to be passed into law, and is
frustrated at what he sees as other artists' lack of willingness to
lend their voices to the protest.
</P>
<P>
   ``Artists have managed to get organized for all other causes _
for the rain forest, for the environment in general, for
anti-nukes, for cures for cancer, for the homeless, for hunger ...
all manner of charity work we've done,'' Henley says. ``But we've
never been able to get our s--t together for ourselves. And we're
getting reamed in Washington by the record companies, by the
Internet companies, by big business in general.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we're not careful, we're going to sleep through it and have
all our rights taken from us.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really want this younger generation of rock 'n' roll
artists,'' he says. ``I know they resent a lot of us '70s artists _
I know Billy Corgan doesn't think very highly of people like me.
But whether they like me or my generation or not, there's work to
be done in the artistic community and in the world community.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope they all develop a social conscience at some point,''
Henley adds. ``They probably have one, but there's a lot of ways
you can waste your time thinking you're doing good things. There's
a lot of causes out there, but some are more important than
others.''
</P>
<P>
   Any conversation with Henley, of course, ends up involving the
Eagles, the iconic Rock and Roll Hall of Fame group whose 1976
collection ``Their Greatest Hits 1971-1975'' has been the
biggest-selling album in U.S. history.
</P>
<P>
   The group dissolved amid much acrimony during the early 1980s,
but came back together in 1994 for a successful reunion tour that
spanned two years.
</P>
<P>
   The band started work on a new studio album last year, but
Henley says a combination of factors conspired to put the Eagles on
the back burner.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was really at a point in my album where I thought I could
divide my time and my attention and my creativity between my
project and that project,'' Henley says, ``and I found I couldn't
do it. My album had to take priority.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anyway, frankly, I don't think it was going very well,'' he
admits. ``We were definitely headed down the track towards making a
very mediocre record, and I think we needed some distance from
it.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Gary Graff is a Beverly Hills, Mich.-based free-lance
writer.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on Don Henley, consult the Warner
Bros. Records Web site at www.wbr.com/donhenley. And check out The
New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for information on StarBeat and
other features. &QL; 
