<SLUG> BC-FREE-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`RUNNING FREE': ON FREEDOM TRAIL WITH A TALKING HORSE 
</HEADLINE>
  (Production notes at end of review) 
 By A.O. SCOTT    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Horses are noble, spirited creatures, but what do they think
about? If they were granted the power of speech, what would they
say? The old television series `` Ed'' presented one version of
equine consciousness, but you won't hear any stable-door wisecracks
in ``Running Free,'' Sergei Bodrov's earnest, music-drenched story
of a plucky young colt's adventures in the deserts of southern
Africa. It turns out that horses _ or Lucky, at least, who narrates
the film in the pleasant adolescent tenor of Lukas Haas _ are
masters of the obvious who think and speak entirely in movie
cliches.
</P>
<P>
   Lucky is born in the midst of an ocean voyage from Germany to
Africa, where his mother is being shipped to work in the copper
mines. ``Africa was far away,'' he notes perceptively. At first the
white human characters speak German until, for the convenience of
the audience, they switch to Afrikaans _ and British-accented
English. Meanwhile Lucky channels horse language for us. When an
imperious stallion named Caesar whinnies and snorts, Lucky explains
that he is ``furious that a lowly workhorse had dared to enter his
domain.'' And when Caesar's spunky daughter Beauty shakes her mane
around to announce her presence as Lucky's love interest, her beau
remarks that she's ``funny and full of life.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps she could have shared some of her jokes with the
filmmakers, who mistake muzzy, mystical sentimentality for
childlike wonder. This is somewhat surprising, in view of the
accomplishments of Bodrov, best known in this country for his
Oscar-nominated ``Prisoner of the Mountains,'' and the screenwriter
Jeanne Rosenberg, who collaborated on the script of Carol Ballard's
``Black Stallion,'' a horsy flick of unusually broad and durable
appeal. But then again, Rosenberg shares a story credit with
Jean-Jacques Annaud, the film's producer and the perpetrator of
such acts of high-concept cinematic paganism as ``Quest for Fire''
and ``The Bear.''
</P>
<P>
   Like those films. ``Running Free'' can be very beautiful to look
at. Shot on location in Namibia, it includes some gorgeous aerial
shots of the vast orange emptiness in which Lucky longs to run
free. But the equine action sequences are poorly edited, and the
voice-over and the sugary Windham Hill-inspired world music score
combine to mar the glories of nature, one of which, after all, is
silence.
</P>
<P>
   The plot blends a bit of ``Bambi'' with a dollop of ``Lassie,''
as the film's treatment of animals vacillates between cutesy
Disney-style anthropomorphism and ``Born Free'' exoticism. Lucky
befriends an orphaned stable boy named Richard (Chase Moore), who
works for the grouchy Boss Man (Jan Decleir), owner of Caesar, and
the two of them, on a desert ramble, befriend a young African girl
named Nyka (Maria Geelbooi), who stars in the film's most
emblematically ridiculous scene. As boy, girl and horse sit around
a campfire, Richard pulls out his harmonica, plays a few bars and
then hands it to Nyka, who faultlessly reels off the movie's love
theme, which obligingly swells to its full orchestration as the
camera lifts into the desert night. But why didn't Lucky get a
turn?
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `RUNNING FREE'
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Sergei Bodrov; written by Jeanne Rosenberg, based on
a story by Jean-Jacques Annaud and Rosenberg; director of
photography, Dan Laustsen; edited by Ray Lovejoy; music by Nicola
Piovani; production designer, Wolf Kroeger; animal handlers, Sled
Reynolds, Bobby Lovgren and Heath Harris; produced by Annaud;
released by Columbia Pictures.
</P>
<P>
   Cast: Lukas Haas (Narrator), Chase Moore (Young Richard), Jan
Decleir (Boss Man), Arie Verveen (Adult Richard) and Maria Geelbooi
(Nyka).
</P>
<P>
   Running time: 82 minutes. This film is rated G. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
