<HEADER>
A2049 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-ART-NOTES-NYT &LR;      06-01 0998
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ART-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ART WORLD NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 By CAROL VOGEL    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Daughters' Gift to the Modern
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Ian Woodner, the Manhattan real estate developer who
died in 1990, was one of the greatest collectors in the United
States. Besides an extraordinary group of drawings, some of which
were acquired by the National Gallery of Art in Washington in 1991,
he amassed a large group of Cycladic works of art.
</P>
<P>
   He also had passion for paintings, drawings and prints by the
19th-century French artist Odilon Redon. He put together the
largest group of Redons in the world.
</P>
<P>
   Woodner's two daughters, Dian and Andrea, oversee the Ian
Woodner Family Collection, a foundation that Woodner established
before his death. They have given the Museum of Modern Art nearly
100 paintings, pastels, watercolors, drawings, prints and
illustrated books by Redon.
</P>
<P>
   ``My father was a painter, too, and he would paint in the style
of Redon,'' said Dian Woodner.
</P>
<P>
   The works the foundation is giving the Modern represent only
about half of Woodner's collection of Redons. Some still belong to
his daughters, said Joshua Rubenstein, Dian Woodner's lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   Woodner said she and her sister wanted to develop a relationship
with an institution in their hometown, which is one reason they
chose to give the Redons to the Modern. The other, she added, was
that ``Redon is one of the first modern painters, and I think his
work will shine at the Modern.''
</P>
<P>
   Glenn Lowry, the Modern's director, called the gift ``one that
came from heaven.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Redon was an artist we never had great strength in,'' he
added. ``Now, in one shot, we have a collection that puts us second
only to the Musee d'Orsay in both range and quality.''
</P>
<P>
   The gift includes early studies from nature, still lifes and
mythological images.
</P>
<P>
   While individual works from the Woodner collection will be on
view from time to time, Lowry said the museum was planning an
exhibition devoted to the entire collection once its major
expansion is completed in four to five years.
</P>
<P>
   Biennial Buys
</P>
<P>
   The Whitney Museum of American Art has made a tradition of
buying a selection of works it features in its Biennials. Curators
compile lists of works they would like the museum to buy and then
make proposals to the appropriate committees, made up of trustees
and others who help raise the money and make the final decisions.
</P>
<P>
   This year the museum has bought works by 20 Biennial artists.
``It's a varied list,'' said Lawrence Rinder, the new curator of
contemporary art. ``Half are by artists who have not been
represented in the Whitney's collection before.'' Rinder stressed
the importance of adding Biennial artists to the museum's
collection. ``Great works by key American artists are an important
legacy to continue,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Among the artists entering the museum's collection for the first
time are Dara Friedman, whose ``Bim Bam'' consists of two films,
one shown directly above the other, projecting sideways images of a
woman repeatedly opening and closing a door; Doug Aitken, whose
``Electric Earth,'' a video piece installed in a maze of rooms, won
a prize at last summer's Venice Bienniale; Silvia Kolbowski, whose
``Inadequate History of Conceptual Art'' is a video and sound
installation; Inigo Manglano-Ovalle's video installation ``The
Kiss,'' which shows the artist washing a glass wall of Mies van der
Rohe's Farnsworth House; and E.V. Day's exploded evening dress,
``Bombshell.''
</P>
<P>
   The museum also decided to add works of artists already in its
collection, but not necessarily with purchases from the Biennial.
It is continuing to build a collection of works by Robert Gober,
but rather than buy his sculpture of a sink with human legs that is
in the Biennial, the museum has bought three more of his color
lithographs.
</P>
<P>
   Dia's Museum
</P>
<P>
   Fourteen months after the Dia Center for the Arts announced that
it would open a $20 million museum in an abandoned paperboard
factory in Beacon, N.Y., a depressed Hudson River town, this
contemporary arts institution is holding something of a
groundbreaking ceremony Friday, with Gov. George Pataki presiding.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've finished the environmental cleanup and major
construction is about to begin,'' said Michael Govan, director of
Dia.
</P>
<P>
   Dia officials have drawn up plans for the building's renovations
with Open Office, a Chelsea architectural firm. The scheme has also
had advice from several living artists represented in Dia's
collection, including Walter de Maria, Richard Serra, Michael
Heizer and John Chamberlain, who have been involved in designing
galleries devoted to their works.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Irwin, the California artist who designed the central
garden for the J. Paul Getty Museum in Los Angeles, has created a
grid of flowering trees that form a canopy over the parking lot
opening onto a piazza, which serves as the museum entrance. Irwin
has also been involved in plans for the entire complex. ``He has
orchestrated natural light throughout the building so there will
never have to be lights on during daylight hours,'' Govan said.
</P>
<P>
   An Appointment
</P>
<P>
   Laurie Beckelman has been appointed to the new position of
deputy director of special projects at the Solomon R. Guggenheim
Museum. Beckelman is vice president of the World Monuments Fund and
was previously executive director of the Joseph Papp Public Theater
and chairwoman of the New York City Landmarks Preservation
Commission.
</P>
<P>
   By special projects, the museum means the creation of the new
museum, designed by the Los Angeles architect Frank Gehry, that it
hopes to build overlooking the East River at the foot of Wall
Street.
</P>
<P>
   ``Laurie will be working on the progress of how to make it
happen,'' said Judith Cox, a deputy director of the Guggenheim.
``She will help push that process along. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-01-00 1702EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
