<HEADER>
A2056 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-ANTIQUES-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      06-01 1179
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANTIQUES-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REMEMBERING (AND EDITING) THINGS PAST
</HEADLINE>
  By WENDY MOONAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ If the ultimate beach book is a really long novel,
then Proust's seven-volume ``A la Recherche du Temps Perdu'' should
top the summer reading list. ``Remembrance of Things Past,'' now
being called ``In Search of Lost Time,'' has never gone out of
print and is considered the greatest French novel of the 20th
century.
</P>
<P>
   With summer upon us, it seems fitting that Christie's is selling
the first part of the novel _ ``Swann's Way'' _ in galley proofs
riddled with Proust's own corrections and jottings. This long-lost
set of galleys has drawn a great deal of attention since it was put
on view in March at the inauguration of Christie's opulent new
Paris headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   Legislation permitting Christie's to conduct auctions in France
has not yet been passed. So on Wednesday, Christie's will auction
the lost Proust galleys in London, and the sale is expected to be
the highlight of Book Week there.
</P>
<P>
   Christie's Proust sale includes the complete text, in annotated
galley proofs, of ``Combray,'' the earliest section of ``A la
Recherche du Temps Perdu,'' as well as the text of all but the
final page of ``Un Amour de Swann'' (``Swann in Love''). These two
parts make up most of ``Du Cote de Chez Swann'' (``Swann's Way''),
the first of the seven parts of Proust's magnum opus. The set of
galleys is expected to sell for $960,000 to $1.4 million.
</P>
<P>
   According to Verene de Soultrait, a specialist in the book
department at Christie's Paris, the proofs represent the most
important literary autograph manuscript of Proust left in private
hands. These are not simply galley proofs but proofs so extensively
marked up in Proust's own hand that they look like concrete poetry,
with a visual appeal as well as literary significance.
</P>
<P>
   Bart Auerbach, a literary appraiser in New York, explained that
Proust's novels ``are virtually rewritten on the galleys.''
</P>
<P>
   Proust was well aware of how obsessive he was in his rewriting,
adding and canceling lines until the last possible moment before
his works went into print.
</P>
<P>
   As the Christie's catalog points out, in 1913 he wrote a letter
to a J.L. Vaudoyer about ``Combray,'' admitting: ``I am busy
correcting my first proofs. New galleys arrive every day, but I
have not returned a single one yet . . . My corrections so far (I
hope that this will not go on) are more than just that. Not one
line in 20 remains of the original text (already rewritten as it
was). It is crossed out, corrected wherever I can find a blank
space, and I paste on pieces of paper at the top, bottom, left,
right, etc. . . .''
</P>
<P>
   This lost text remains unpublished to this day. ``It's a
literary event in a sense, because no one knew it was available,''
Auerbach said of the sale.
</P>
<P>
   Christie's will not reveal the name, vocation or country of the
consignor.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Reese, a rare book dealer in New Haven, Conn., said the
galleys were important because they ``address the issue of
authorial intention.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The set of galleys raises the question of what is the proper
text,'' he continued. ``You see the levels of his intentions as he
goes along with his endless tinkering and reworking of the past.
The galleys are another layer in the story, a whole new set of
information on one of the great novels of the 20th century. It is a
truly important literary event.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of Proust's manuscripts are in the collection of the
National Library of France. The library bought most of its Proust
archive from Marcel Proust's niece, who inherited it from her
father, his brother. Scholars there have published two other sets
of galley proofs for ``Swann's Way.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They realized, however,'' de Soultrait writes in the catalog,
concerning the lost proofs in the sale, ``that a third set must
have existed, consolidating all the revisions and adding numbers of
others, which Proust returned to the printer for subsequent page
proofs. No future critical edition of the novel may omit close
study of the extensive autograph revisions.''
</P>
<P>
   Felix de Marez Oyens, senior director of Christie's
International Department of Printed Books and Manuscripts, in
London, said: ``A lot of Proust's text is not represented in either
the second proofs or in the published edition, because he did so
much rewriting that he then crossed out. The reworkings are part of
the creative process. This is the objective expression of it, the
physical expression of his changes of mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Auerbach added, ``There was always a possibility that something
like this would turn up, but it was remote. If you are a Proust
collector, this sale could be your last chance to get something.
Another opportunity might not ever come up.''
</P>
<P>
   Proust, of course, is more popular that ever. There is, for
example, the Proust Society of America, based in New York; the
aptly named NAPS, or North American Proust Society, headed up by
the New York novelist Eric Kraft; and a Proust Support Group in San
Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Yale University Press recently published William C. Carter's
946-page ``Marcel Proust: A Life.'' Last year, Editions du
Patrimoine in France published ``Le Monde de Proust Vu par Paul
Nadar,'' a book of historic Nadar portraits of Proust and his
circle.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, Vintage published Alain De Botton's popular ``How
Proust Can Change Your Life: Not a Novel,'' a biographical portrait
with lessons on Proustian self-improvement, like ``How to Express
Your Emotions'' and ``How to Suffer Successfully.''
</P>
<P>
   The appeal of Proust runs deep. ``Camus, Sartre and Gide have
faded,'' Auerbach said. ``Proust has lasted. I have a theory that
Proust, like all great writers, created an alternative universe
that we can live in. It's the same for Trollope and Joyce. You
become part of the Proust world and it's endlessly absorbing. It's
the lost childhood in all of us. It's the detail, the beauty of the
style, the absorption. You just want to stay in it.''
</P>
<P>
   He recalled that E.M. Forster called ``Recherche'' a ``cathedral
of a novel.''
</P>
<P>
   In his biography, Carter notes that Proust lived through three
turbulent eras: the fin de siecle, the Belle Epoque and World War
I. He writes, ``His novel bears witness to the rich, complex
workings of the mind and heart _ memory, love, passion, both sacred
and profane _ and to the oceanic transformations that changed the
horse-and-buggy world to one of aviation, Cubism, mode in fashion,
comfort and hygiene.''
</P>
<P>
   David Rea, a retired lawyer in Sag Harbor, N.Y. who is a
longtime Proust enthusiast, put it differently. ``Proust composed
with intensity and intelligence,'' he said. ``He may have been the
first to articulate the idea of involuntary memory; how certain
sounds, smells and touches take you out of the present. Trivial
things assume the role of great things. The book touches you at a
number of levels, and when it's over, you're sorry and wish it were
longer. It's like the Odyssey. Miracles are happening all the time
despite the terrible dailiness of life.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
