<HEADER>
A2058 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-MOVIES-IN-BRIEF-2TAKE     06-01 1307
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-IN-BRIEF-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT'S ON VIEW IN THE THEATERS 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here is a selective listing by critics of The New York Times of
new or noteworthy movies. Ratings and running times are in
parentheses.
</P>
<P>
   ``BATTLEFIELD EARTH,'' starring John Travolta and Barry Pepper.
Directed by Roger Christian (PG-13, 117 minutes). In the year 3000
beings from the planet Psychlo conquer Earth in only nine minutes
and reduce all humans to grunting illiterates. The chief nasty,
Terl ( Travolta), devises a scheme to put the man-animals to work
in the gold mines for him. He sees potential in one cave dweller (
Pepper) and straps him to a machine that beams the wisdom of the
ages into his head. Little does Terl realize that by educating a
human, he is sowing the seeds of his own destruction. Sitting
through this film with its stock villains is like watching the most
expensively mounted high school play of all time. It may be a bit
early to make such judgments, but ``Battlefield Earth'' may well
turn out to be the worst movie of this century (Elvis Mitchell).
</P>
<P>
   ``CENTER STAGE,'' starring Ethan Stiefel, Sascha Radetsky,
Amanda Schull, Peter Gallagher and Donna Murphy. Directed by
Nicholas Hytner (PG-13, 113 minutes). Hytner's film tracks the
professional and romantic travails of a group of young dancers at
the fictitious American Ballet Academy in New York. The script is a
patchwork of show biz movie and romantic comedy cliches and the
acting rarely rises above daytime soap-opera obviousness, but who
ever went to a dance movie to see good writing or realistic acting?
The movie is loaded with lively dance sequences, and Hytner films
them beautifully, especially the showstopping finale, choreographed
by Susan Stroman and spiritedly danced by Stiefel, Radetsky and the
lovely Schull, who carries the movie with her energy and grace
(A.O. Scott).
</P>
<P>
   ``DINOSAUR,'' with the voices of D.B. Sweeney, Alfre Woodard and
Ossie Davis. Directed by Ralph Zondag and Eric Leighton (PG, 90
minutes). Reputedly the most expensive animated feature ever made,
Disney's showcase of computer animation technology begins with a
breathtaking sequence, a visual and sonic extravaganza that the
rest of the movie never quite lives up to. The story, of a young
dinosaur raised by lemurs who must lead a herd of his fellow
reptiles to safety after an asteroid strikes the earth, is cobbled
together from other Disney plots. But the effects _ the dinosaur's
movements and their nearly seamless insertion into real locations _
will impress skeptical grown-ups (the movie reportedly cost about
$200 million). More important, the film, in spite of some
potentially upsetting scenes of carnivorous mayhem, will delight
children and whet their desire for the inevitable tie-in
merchandise (Scott).
</P>
<P>
   ``EAST-WEST,'' starring Sandrine Bonnaire, Oleg Menchikov and
Catherine Deneuve. Directed by Regis Wargnier (PG-13, 115 minutes).
After World War II the Soviet government undertook a propaganda
campaign to entice Russians living in the West to return home.
Aleksei Golovine ( Menchikov) and his French wife, Marie (
Bonnaire), the couple at the heart of Wargnier's sumptuous, moving
historical melodrama, are luckier than most of their fellow
returnees, who are killed or imprisoned on arrival. ``East-West''
chronicles Aleksei's ambivalence about their new life in a drab,
depressing communal apartment and Marie's desperate attempts to
escape it. The film may be faulted for dissolving the horrors of
history in Hollywood-style catharsis, but it also uses the
resources of old-fashioned emotionally emphatic filmmaking to shed
light on forgotten history. ``East-West'' is a grand costume
pageant, full of grandeur and period detail, but it is also the
portrait of a marriage under extreme external and internal pressure
as well as a showcase for two great film actresses: Bonnaire and
Deneuve, playing an actress who becomes aware of Marie's plight
during a tour of the Soviet Union (Scott).
</P>
<P>
   ``FREQUENCY,'' starring Dennis Quaid and Jim Caviezel. Directed
by Gregory Hoblit (PG-13, 100 minutes). ``Back to the Future''
meets ``Field of Dreams'' meets ``It's a Wonderful Life'' meets
``The Sixth Sense'' in this entertaining but shamelessly
sentimental supernatural soap opera with a macho heart. Caviezel is
a morose young policeman who contacts his dead father, a heroic
firefighter, on a ham radio and contrives to save him from the
accident that cost him his life during the 1969 World Series. From
here, the two collaborate on changing other aspects of the past and
on catching a serial killer. There are enough testosterone tears to
soak Shea Stadium (Stephen Holden).
</P>
<P>
   ``GLADIATOR,'' starring Russell Crowe, Joaquin Phoenix, Connie
Nielsen, Richard Harris and Oliver Reed. Directed by Ridley Scott
(R, 150 minutes). This movie is the answer to a question no one
bothered to ask: what would happen if someone decided to film the
imminent extreme football league as if it were a Chanel commercial?
Scott subjects action-packed bouts of mayhem and decapitation in
the Roman Colosseum to his glossy, inhuman directing style; it is
admirable but repellent. Crowe is the noble Roman general who ends
up fighting for his life. Crowe gives a performance with
ball-of-fire intensity, suffused with a movie star's impatience. He
holds the movie together, such as it is (Mitchell).
</P>
<P>
   ``HAMLET,'' starring Ethan Hawke and Liev Schreiber. Directed by
Michael Almereyda (R, 112 minutes). Almereyda has rooted his
voluptuous and rewarding new adaptation of Shakespeare's play in
today's Manhattan. The city's contradictions of beauty and squalor
give the movie a sense of place, and New York becomes a complex
character in this vital and sharply intelligent film. Often shaded
in lush, soothing hues of blue, ``Hamlet'' exudes an intoxicating
masochism in which half the cast is battling despondency and the
other half has the glint of imminent insanity. Here the melancholy
of Hamlet ( Hawke) over the death of his father is almost a state
of grace: it gives him a sense of purpose that the other characters
lack. The director's rigorous trimming has a boldness and vivacity
that make this version exhilarating while leaving Shakespeare's
language and intent intact (Mitchell).
</P>
<P>
   ``LOVE AND BASKETBALL,'' starring Sanaa Lathan and Omar Epps.
Directed by Gina Prince-Bythewood (PG-13, 118 minutes). The
writer-director Gina Prince-Bythewood's feature-film debut, about
the romantic and competitive bond between the basketball players
Monica ( Lathan) and Quincy ( Epps), has an enchanting, lived-in
homeyness. Prince-Bythewood does a wonderful job of creating an
atmosphere for her characters _ particularly for the superb Lathan
_ but the movie fails to fashion a consistent narrative. It doesn't
seem to be about anything. But it is a promising first movie from a
filmmaker with a lot to offer. Who knew anyone could get a drama
out of Title IX, the federal law ensuring that girls get a chance
to compete in high school sports? (Mitchell).
</P>
<P>
   ``M:I-2,'' starring Tom Cruise, Thandie Newton and Sir Anthony
Hopkins. Directed by John Woo (PG-13, 120 minutes). Cruise returns
as the daredevil secret agent Ethan Hunt in Woo's loud, flashy,
incoherent new blockbuster. The film is jampacked with movie
references _ to Hitchcock, to the first ``Mission: Impossible''
movie, and to Woo's earlier, and superior, Hong Kong action films _
but it's at once overheated and flat. The plot, involving killer
viruses, is baffling rather than twisty. The introduction of a love
interest ( Newton) who also happens to be the bad guy's
ex-girlfriend adds an element of melodrama that's more annoying
than affecting. Some good car chases and explosions, though
(Scott).
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   ``ROAD TRIP,'' starring Breckin Meyer, Seann William Scott, Amy
Smart, DJ Qualls and Tom Green. Directed by Todd Phillips (R, 91
minutes). ``National Lampoon's Animal House'' meets ``There's
Something About Mary'' in the gross-out farce of the late spring.
Four college boys led by Josh ( Meyer) embark on a desperate
1,800-mile journey from upstate New York to Texas to intercept an
X-rated dorm room video mistakenly sent to Josh's loyal girlfriend
in Austin. The fun is all in the gags, among them the notorious
French toast sequence, the envelope-pushing sperm bank scene, and
the hilarious car-jumped-over-the-bridge demolition derby. You'll
laugh despite yourself (Holden). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``SHANGHAI NOON,'' starring Jackie Chan and Owen Wilson.
Directed by Tom Dey (PG-13, 110 minutes). Chan is one of the great
physical comedians, and this martial arts western spoof is a
high-spirited, marvelously silly showcase for his talents. Chan
plays Chon Wang, an Imperial Guard dispatched from Beijing to the
Old West to rescue a princess played by Lucy Liu. But the heart of
the movie is the interplay between Chan and Wilson, who depicts his
inept outlaw sidekick with goofy, spacey charm. After the glum
bullying of ``Gladiator'' and the noisy bombast of ``M:I-2,'' it's
refreshing to see a movie so good-natured, so confident in its
ability to provoke not queasy awe or numb exhaustion, but pure
delight (Scott).
</P>
<P>
   ``SMALL TIME CROOKS,'' starring Woody Allen and Tracey Ullman.
Directed and written by Allen (PG, 95 minutes). The sweet, funny
wisp of a movie starts out as a parody of ``Big Deal on Madonna
Street,'' then turns into a child's-eye ``Bonfire of the
Vanities,'' before returning to its original mode as a caper
comedy. Allen and Ullman are Ray and Frenchy Winkler, an inept
thief and ex-con and his upwardly mobile wife whose cookie business
takes off and allows her to indulge her dream of being a Park
Avenue hostess. If the movie suffers severely from attention
deficit disorder, the jokes are funny (but mild), the screwball
comic tone impeccably sustained and Ullman (putting on her Fern
Rosenthal voice) and Elaine May (as Frenchy's dimwitted cousin)
delightfully goofy (Holden). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``TIME CODE,'' starring Jeanne Tripplehorn, Saffron Burrows,
Holly Hunter and Stellan Skarsgard. Directed by Mike Figgis (R, 93
minutes). Figgis' astonishing new film, shot in a single day with
hand-held digital video cameras, tells four stories simultaneously,
in real time. ``Time Code'' is at once a mordant satire of the
hypocrisy and self-delusion of the film industry and an earnest
declaration of faith in the medium itself. In addition to its
technical innovations, which test the limits of the human eye, ear
and mind, the film boasts some brilliant improvisational acting
from its enormous cast. Especially fine are Tripplehorn and
Skarsgard, whose strongly emotional performances add a measure of
pathos. Whether ``Time Code'' will ultimately be seen as a bold
prophecy of the dawning visual age or as a passionate, gimmicky
curio is for the future to decide. At present, though, it is hard
to think of a more exciting demonstration of the inexhaustible
possibilities of film (Scott).
</P>
<P>
   ``U-571,'' starring Matthew McConaughey, Bill Paxton, Jon Bon
Jovi, David Keith and Harvey Keitel. Directed by Jonathan Mostow
(PG-13, 120 minutes). Mostow, whose previous film, ``Breakdown,''
was a marvel of B-picture minimalism, shifts from the wide-open
spaces to the cramped interior of a World War II submarine movie.
McConaughey, whose knotted-with-unease face makes it look as if he
were cramming for finals, is part of a secret mission to capture a
Nazi code-encryption machine and get it back to the Allies. He and
his crew have to do so on a Nazi U-boat they have hijacked. Mostow
does a fine job of building tension, given that he is working in a
minor genre whose climactic notes you will know if you have ever
seen a movie set on a sub (Mitchell).
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-01-00 1713EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
