<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    JACKSON KEEPS REMEDY RECORD OPEN IN MICROSOFT TRIAL
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington (f) financial categories.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The judge in the Microsoft antitrust case on
Thursday gave the software giant and the government six more days
to further hone their arguments before he closes the trial's record
for good.
</P>
<P>
   The unexpected order delays a final decision over what remedies
to impose on Microsoft, which has already been found to have
violated antitrust laws, for at least a week.
</P>
<P>
   It also sends a signal that U.S. District Judge Thomas Penfield
Jackson could need even more time to devise a solution of his own
choosing rather than relying entirely on a government draft that
has been bitterly assailed by Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   The order gives the Justice Department and 17 states until
Monday morning to respond to Microsoft's latest attack on their
plan to break the company into two parts.
</P>
<P>
   A 34-page defense filing, issued late Wednesday, blasted the
government's proposed decree as ``defective in numerous respects,
making the document vague and ambiguous.''
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft will then have until Wednesday morning to respond to
the government's Monday rebuttal ``if it so chooses.'' Given the
blizzard of briefs that the company's lawyers have already filed
with Jackson in their bid to derail the government plan, it seems
unlikely that yet another such opportunity would be missed.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft spokesman Jim Cullinan said the prosecutors, in a
conference call with Jackson, had asked for a chance to file
another brief in the landmark case. ``This new delay should raise
some serious questions about the government's plan and the entire
process employed in this case,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Cullinan said David Boies, the government's lead trial attorney,
had acknowledged during the exchange that Microsoft had raised ``a
number of valid points'' about the proposed decree in its current
form.
</P>
<P>
   Several government lawyers are also known to be concerned about
the impact of the breakup on the company's foreign markets, which
for the most part are subject to external sets of antitrust laws.
The company does business in more than 110 countries.
</P>
<P>
   In the aftermath of the most recent Microsoft filing, Gina
Talamona, a Justice Department spokesperson, had characterized
Microsoft's complaints as ``another effort to posture for appeal.''
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Microsoft, the most actively traded U.S. stock, rose
$2 to $64.56 after Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co. analyst Rick Sherlund said
the stock ``might be able to recover some lost ground'' following
Jackson's remedy ruling.
</P>
<P>
   Significant portions of that ruling are likely to be stayed,
pending an appeal which almost surely will be heard, sooner or
later, by the U.S. Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   On the Web: www.dcd.uscourts.gov/
</P>
<P>
   Andrew J. Glass's e-mail address is andyg(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
