<SLUG> BC-INDIGO-GIRLS02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Still the Girls, but these are women with a history
 &HT;    By Shane Harrison
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Like the oppressive summer heat and the brilliant white dogwoods
of spring, it's hard to imagine Atlanta without Amy Ray and Emily
Saliers, aka the Indigo Girls.
</P>
<P>
   The socially conscious singer-songwriters have been an integral
part of Atlanta's music scene for nearly 15 years. Though they've
been a nationally successful act since the late 1980s, Saliers and
Ray have remained in the Atlanta area, where they enjoy a loyal and
supportive fan base.
</P>
<P>
   ``They keep us going,'' says Saliers, 37, even if airplay is
scarce these days. Modern rock radio, she says, is too homogenized.
``It's all guy bands. They play No Doubt and that's it. I like to
hear diversity.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the lack of radio support, Saliers professes to be happy
with the level of success she and Ray have achieved. ``I get to
play music for a living and then I get to come home to Atlanta, my
beautiful city. I'd rather do this than anything else.''
</P>
<P>
   When not performing, they lend their celebrity to many causes.
Among the groups that Saliers and Ray support are Honor the Earth
Campaign, which raises funds and awareness of environmental issues,
and Youth Pride, an Atlanta-based support organization for gay and
lesbian youth.
</P>
<P>
   INDIGO GIRLS TIME LINE
</P>
<P>
   After nearly two decades together, the pair has achieved a
number of milestones. Here are some highlights:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  1963: Emily Saliers born July 22.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  1964: Amy Ray born April 12.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Circa 1973: Saliers and Ray meet while attending Laurel Ridge
Elementary School. ( Saliers: ``We met in elementary school when we
were 9 or 10 years old. We started playing while we were in high
school. I've known Amy for almost 30 years now.'')
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  1981: Saliers and Ray play for their first audience _ their
high school English class. (Saliers: ``We were real excited about
it. It was great to have an audience.'')
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  1981: Indigo Girls are the unofficial house band at the Little
Five Points Pub.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  1984: The pair, who had been playing under the names Saliers
and Ray and the B Band, take the name Indigo Girls.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  1985: The ``Crazy Game'' 7'' single, the duo's first official
recording, is released. (Saliers: ``We made copies of that and sold
it on the Emory campus. We just set up a table and sold them.'')
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  1986: The independent ``Indigo Girls'' EP is released.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  1988: They are signed to Epic Records, which has released all
the duo's subsequent albums.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  1989: A three-week stint opening for R.E.M., including two
nights at the Omni hotel in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  February 1989: ``Indigo Girls,'' their major-label debut, is
released.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  October 1989: ``Strange Fire'' is released.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  1990: ``Indigo Girls'' wins the Grammy Award for best
contemporary folk recording. The pair was up for best new artist
but lost. That year's best new artist race would become infamous.
(Saliers: ``(Winning the Grammy) was really exciting. It felt good.
We were actually up for best new artist, too, and Milli Vanilli
won.'')
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  1990: Daemon Records, Ray's nonprofit independent label, is
established.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  September 1990: ``Nomads Indians Saints'' is released.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  June 1991: ``Back on the Bus, Y'all'' is released.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  May 1992: ``Rites of Passage'' released.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  May 1994: ``Swamp Ophelia'' released.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  October 1995: The live set ``1200 Curfews'' is released.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  April 1997: ``Shaming of the Sun'' is released.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  1998: The principal of Irmo High School near Columbia, S.C.,
cancels a scheduled performance by Indigo Girls, citing parental
complaints about the singers' lesbianism. The show was rescheduled
the next week at Columbia's Township Auditorium, with help from
members of Hootie &AMP; the Blowfish, whose Mark Bryan called the
principal's decision ``naive and wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  October 1998: Saliers and her partners open Watershed, a
restaurant in Decatur. (Saliers: ``It's a lot of work. I've got
three partners who do most of the work, though. I'm sort of the PR
person for it now.'')
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  September 1999: ``Come on Now Social'' is released.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  February 2000: Ray has an emergency appendectomy. Doctors
discover and remove an ovarian cyst at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Tonight: The Summer Shed Tour kicks off at Chastain Park
Amphitheatre.
</P>
<P>
   Indigo Girls
</P>
<P>
   7:30 tonight-Saturday. $26.50-$28.50 at Ticketmaster. Chastain
Park Amphitheatre, 4469 Stella Drive N.W. 404-888-9961 or
404-249-6400.
</P>
<P>
   Shane Harrison writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
