<HEADLINE>
CHINA CONFIRMS VISIT OF NORTH KOREAN LEADER 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: This early version will be updated as needed.) 
 By ERIK ECKHOLM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ China and North Korea confirmed Thursday that North
Korea's leader, Kim Jong Il, was in Beijing earlier this week for
three days of secret meetings.
</P>
<P>
   The trip was the reclusive Kim's first journey abroad since he
succeeded his father as leader in 1994 and his first visit to China
since 1983.
</P>
<P>
   The 58-year-old Great Leader, as he is called at home, took
advantage of the rare venture outside his cloistered country to
visit China's leading computer manufacturer, the Legend Group, as
well as the imposing imperial gate at Tiananmen Square, Chinese
officials reported.
</P>
<P>
   Coming just two weeks before Kim's scheduled summit meeting with
South Korean President Kim Dae Jung, the surprise trip appeared to
be aimed at shoring up North Korea's ties with China _ the
economically stricken country's only important ally.
</P>
<P>
   China is anxious to avoid serious instability in the region or a
total collapse of the North Korean government that might draw South
Korean involvement, or perhaps even U.S. troops, to its border. It
has encouraged the North to engage in peace talks and to open its
economy to foreign trade and investment.
</P>
<P>
   China fought alongside North Korea against the United States and
South Korea during the 1950-53 Korean War and was long an ally in
communism. But relations became strained in 1992, when Beijing
extended diplomatic recognition to economically thriving South
Korea, and have only slowly recovered.
</P>
<P>
   During Kim's visit, from Monday to Wednesday, he was the guest
of honor at a banquet given by President Jiang Zemin and met
separately with other leaders including Prime Minister Zhu Rongji,
Vice President Hu Jintao and Li Peng, the former prime minister who
now heads the national legislature. Kim was accompanied by several
top military and political officials.
</P>
<P>
   The two sides reached an ``important consensus'' on bilateral
and regional issues of common concern, said a Foreign Ministry
spokeswoman, Zhang Qiyue, Thursday evening, declining to be more
specific. ``Bilateral relations were raised to a new level.''
</P>
<P>
   China also made new promises of food and other aid to ailing
North Korea, Zhang said at a special briefing.
</P>
<P>
   A short announcement Thursday from the official North Korean
news agency _ as in the case of China's issued only after Kim had
completed his overnight train journey and was safely back home _
described an ``unshakeable will'' to develop friendship with China
and also said that ``consensus was reached on all matters
discussed.''
</P>
<P>
   North Korea's government has recently tried to break out of its
longstanding diplomatic isolation, opening relations with Italy and
Australia and holding talks with Japan and the United States.
</P>
<P>
   In footage of their meeting shown on Chinese television Thursday
night, Kim wore a gray Mao-style jacket while Jiang wore a
Western-style suit and tie.
</P>
<P>
   The Chinese spokeswoman declined to explain the extreme secrecy
surrounding the trip, saying, ``We think this is a normal visit.''
</P>
<P>
   But other Chinese officials said privately that the North
Koreans had insisted that the visit be kept secret until Kim's
return to Pyongyang, and they suggested that he was concerned about
his security or the possibility of a coup attempt.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an indication of possible instability,'' one Chinese
official said, although Kim's activities have long been shrouded in
secrecy.
</P>
<P>
   In public, the Chinese were all smiles, stressing that the
long-standing friendship between the two countries had been
strengthened.
</P>
<P>
   Jiang told his guest that China welcomes the talks between the
North and South Korean leaders scheduled from June 12 to 14 in
Pyongyang, and ``hopes the two sides improve their relationship,''
the New China News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
   Chinese officials have said in private that they find the North
Koreans unpredictable and frustrating, and too proud to openly
accept Chinese coaching on economics or foreign policy.
</P>
<P>
   The official accounts Thursday from China seemed intended to
help the North Koreans save face, avoiding any mention of issues
that have strained relations.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Jiang was quoted as praising North Korea's economic
achievements, even though the country has suffered a severe
economic decline and food shortages that have sent hundreds of
thousands of refugees fleeing into China.
</P>
<P>
   China was angered last year when North Korea tested a long-range
missile, frightening Japan and spurring stronger efforts by Japan
and the United States to develop anti-missile defenses, which China
strongly opposes.
</P>
<P>
   Zhang, the Foreign Ministry spokeswoman, would not say if the
issue had been discussed but restated China's hope of avoiding any
arms race in the region or any proliferation of weapons of mass
destruction.
</P>
<P>
   China has for years encouraged North Korea to begin opening its
tightly controlled economy, which collapsed after subsidies from
the former Soviet Union ended nearly a decade ago. Officials
refused to say whether Kim made any commitments in that regard,
but, according to official Chinese accounts, Kim praised the
success of economic reforms in China.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
