<SLUG> BC-CONSTANTINE-ULSTER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     FORMER DEA CHIEF BEGINS WORK ON OVERHAULING ULSTER POLICE
FORCE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARV CERMAK   
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y.  &Cx1f; _ Former U.S. drug enforcement chief Thomas
Constantine says the key to peace in Northern Ireland will be the
development of a police service ``everyone is comfortable with.''
</P>
<P>
   Constantine, ``an Irish-American Catholic,'' is in the province
to oversee implementation of peace reforms, including the
transition of the Royal Ulster Constabulary (RUC) to the new police
force.
</P>
<P>
   Roman Catholics are demanding as much change as possible in the
RUC, a predominantly Protestant force hardened by three decades of
strife and terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we can put together a police service that everyone is
comfortable with, maybe there will be an end to the violence,''
said Constantine, reached by telephone in Belfast Wednesday night
after the announcement of his appointment as oversight commissioner
by Britain's Northern Ireland Office.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although there has been a cease-fire for two years, there have
been two murders just this week,'' he added. ``The situation is
very contentious. Some neighborhoods are fenced off, opposition
flags fly on street poles and various groups don't even talk to
each other.''
</P>
<P>
   Constantine, 60, is a former New York State Police
superintendent who last spring retired as head of the U.S. Drug
Enforcement Administration. He said he would ``monitor and
referee'' the implementation of 175 recommendations resulting from
a two-year independent study of police reform by Chris Patten, the
last colonial governor of Hong Kong and now a European Union
commissioner.
</P>
<P>
   The recommendations cover assorted police issues, including
hiring, training, communications, finance, human rights,
construction of police academies and information systems.
</P>
<P>
   ``The report called for an independent from outside England and
Ireland to serve as oversight commissioner,'' Constantine said.
``Conditions here are very sensitive because four or five parties
have different ideas. I won't become involved in politics or the
running of police operations,'' Constantine said.
</P>
<P>
   Constantine, who is from Schenectady, N.Y., was asked to serve
for five years, but he agreed to a three-year commitment. ``I
accepted three years, and then we'll see what develops,'' he said.
He will travel to Ireland four or five times a year, staying on the
job for two weeks at a time.
</P>
<P>
   Constantine is expected to discuss the pace of police reform
with senior Northern Ireland officials and issue public reports,
starting in October.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being Irish was certainly a part of my decision to take the
assignment, but more importantly family members urged me on,
insisting that I could not turn down people who were calling me.''
</P>
<P>
   Constantine said police reform, if successful, can be a
significant contribution to problem solving. He called the
undertaking a one-time opportunity to resolve a very difficult
situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very familiar with all aspects of police work, but this is
a very challenging assignment. I'll be putting in 15 or 16 hours a
day because I have a lot to learn,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has been an incredible 30-year period of violence,
during which the people have suffered greatly. People have been
courageous and they are making strides, but it's too early to say
if this new program will be successful,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   As oversight commissioner Constantine will also be required to
hold periodic public hearings to evaluate the implementation
progress and report findings to the British Parliament and the
Northern Ireland secretary of state.
</P>
<P>
   Constantine was appointed a professor at the State University of
New York at Albany and has been operating a private law enforcement
consulting firm since his retirement from the DEA a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A native of Buffalo, he moved to Schenectady in 1970. He and his
wife, Ruth Ann, have six children, including Lt. Thomas Constantine
of the Niskayuna (N.Y.) Police Department and Kevin Constantine, an
FBI agent in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   He was DEA director for five years. Prior to that he was a
member of the Erie County Sheriff's Department for two years and
put in 30 years with the State Police. He rose through the ranks
from uniformed trooper to superintendent, a position he held for
eight years.
</P>
</TEXT>
