<HEADER>
A2072 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-TONY-AWARDS-ART-2TAKE     06-01 1118
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TONY-AWARDS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TONY FORECAST: DRAMATIC RACES, MUSICAL CHAIRS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 By JESSE McKINLEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Unless there are some major surprises _ and there
always are _ on Sunday night, Tony voters will declare that
Broadway's best musical is ``Contact,'' which many people say is
not a musical, and that its best play is ``Copenhagen,'' which many
people say they simply don't understand.
</P>
<P>
   Confused? You should be.
</P>
<P>
   It has been that kind of year on Broadway, an odd mishmash of
daring new work and lukewarm fare that has left theater
professionals searching for a cohesive theme.
</P>
<P>
   All that confusion should end on Sunday, however, with the
broadcast of the Tony Awards, Broadway's annual rite of
self-congratulation, self-flagellation and, occasionally, even
real, genuine drama. The awards, overseen by the American Theater
Wing and the American League of Theaters and Producers, represent
the single occasion during the year when the theater's reach
extends past the footlights and across the nation, creating a
window of televised visibility when all the winners are superstars
for as long as it takes to thank their parents and their pets.
</P>
<P>
   In the ceremony at Radio City Music Hall, 21 awards will be
handed out: 12 during the high-profile CBS broadcast starting at 9
p.m., and nine others during an earlier portion that will be
broadcast on PBS. CBS will handle the big awards, like best musical
and best play, as well as those for revivals and all eight acting
categories. PBS will televise the design, direction and special
awards.
</P>
<P>
   Rosie O'Donnell is back as host and an executive producer of the
show, bringing with her the hope that the telecast will rebound
from last year's dismal ratings. Her presence may provide a spark
of life in a show whose 1999 incarnation could have been titled
``Night of 1,000 Unhappy Stars.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps most important, Tony officials are promising that
production numbers from all the nominated musicals will make it on
the air. Last year the show ran long, and a number from ``It Ain't
Nothin' but the Blues'' was canceled at the last minute.
</P>
<P>
   ``My absolute prediction?'' said Jed Bernstein, president of the
league. ``The show will end at 11 o'clock on the dot, and every
nominated musical will have been on the air.''
</P>
<P>
   But beyond a few major categories, any solid predictions may be
foolhardy.
</P>
<P>
   While the season's creative ups and downs may have caused
concern about Broadway's future _ new plays, anyone? _ the lack of
a single blockbuster is creating some highly competitive Tony
races, in categories from best revival of a play, in which Tom
Stoppard's ``Real Thing'' is head to head with Eugene O'Neill's
``Moon for the Misbegotten''; to best actress, in which the
downtown newcomer Claudia Shear (``Dirty Blonde'') may just snag an
award over several of her more Broadway-tested colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   And while the theater aficionado will certainly pay closer
attention than the layman, even a casual viewer can see the
potential drama in races that pit mother against daughter (Rosemary
Harris of ``Waiting in the Wings'' and Jennifer Ehle of ``The Real
Thing'' for best actress in a play), ``brother'' versus ``brother''
(Philip Seymour Hoffman and John C. Reilly of ``True West'' for
best actor in a play) and Susan Stroman against herself in two
categories (best choreography and best direction of a musical, for
``Contact'' and ``The Music Man'').
</P>
<P>
   HEAVY FAVORITES
</P>
<P>
   In an informal poll of 20 producers, press agents, nominees and
other Broadway eggheads, only a few sure things seem to emerge.
</P>
<P>
   One of those locks seems to be on the evening's big prize, best
musical.
</P>
<P>
   Despite protests from Local 802, the Broadway musicians' union,
that ``Contact'' does not adhere to the standards of a traditional
musical because it has no orchestra or original score, the show
remains an overwhelming favorite to win, in the minds of those
polled. The producers of ``The Wild Party,'' ``Swing!'' and ``James
Joyce's `The Dead''' may not have to worry about drafting
acceptance speeches; not one of the 20 voters thought any of these
shows would win.
</P>
<P>
   The same story for the award for best play. ``Copenhagen,''
Michael Frayn's heady exploration of a critical moment in the lives
of two famous physicists, is a near-unanimous choice, even though
few of those asked could give a full explanation of what the drama
was all about. ``Dirty Blonde,'' Shear's affectionate look at Mae
West, is a long shot, some said, but lacks what one voter called
``the snob factor.''
</P>
<P>
   `` `Copenhagen' makes you feel smarter for having seen it,''
said one producer, who, like all of the prognosticators, spoke on
condition of anonymity. ``Even if you don't really understand it.''
</P>
<P>
   The producers of ``Kiss Me, Kate,'' which leads all shows, with
12 nominations, can probably breathe a little easier. The show,
which had late competition from ``The Music Man'' for the award for
best revival of a musical, was an overwhelming favorite of those
polled. ``Kate'' also looks strong in the design categories,
meaning it may lead all shows in total Tonys.
</P>
<P>
   LEADING LIGHTS
</P>
<P>
   In the individual acting categories, too, a couple of performers
appear ready to be anointed.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Stokes Mitchell, who received terrific reviews for his
work in ``Kate,'' is considered a near-certain winner as best
leading actor in a musical. This is in part because of his work in
that show. But it also reflects many voters' opinion that Mitchell
could easily have won in 1998 for ``Ragtime'' but was surprised by
the late-season entry of Alan Cumming, who won for ``Cabaret.''
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell's only real competition would seem to be Craig Bierko
(``The Music Man''), but few think his turn as a charming con man
has a real chance.
</P>
<P>
   In the category for leading ladies in musicals, Heather Headley
looks to be headed for her first Tony as well, for the title role
in ``Aida,'' though Marin Mazzie (``Kate'') seems to be gaining
support among those in the Broadway industry who feel bad that she
has yet to win a Tony despite previous nominations for ``Passion''
in 1994 and ``Ragtime.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the category which breaks your heart the most,'' said
a producer who is friendly with Mazzie but voting for Headley.
``But Heather is the title character of an enormous show and the
only thing that's great in it.''
</P>
<P>
   Beyond that, however, the landscape gets murkier, with several
categories that have no clear winner and several nominees in the
hunt.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   TIME FOR REDEMPTION
</P>
<P>
   The early awards on PBS, the favorite portion for many industry
types, promise to be heavy on redemption and heartfelt recognition.
</P>
<P>
   The only bet-the-kid's-college-fund lock here is that Stroman
will win for best choreography for ``Contact,'' besting her own
effort on ``Music Man'' and those of Kathleen Marshall (``Kate'')
and Lynne Taylor-Corbett (``Swing!''). In addition to being
mightily talented, Stroman is also extremely well liked in the
business, and this looks to be her night.
</P>
<P>
   She is also favored to win for best direction of a musical. She
is nominated for ``Contact'' and ``Music Man,'' though Michael
Blakemore (``Kate'') may make a run for it. Blakemore, mind you,
will probably have already won one award by this point; he is the
favorite to win best direction of a play, for ``Copenhagen.''
</P>
<P>
   For best score, there are two favorites. The first is ``Aida,''
by Elton John and Tim Rice, which has been shut out of the best
musical category but is nonetheless a commercial hit. The logic for
a win here is that it would allow voters who like the show _
especially those voters from out of town who would like to see it
tour _ to express their support.
</P>
<P>
   The other option seems to be ``The Wild Party,'' by Michael John
LaChuisa, which probably won't win best musical but is more
aesthetically ambitious than the sugar-pop score for ``Aida.''
</P>
<P>
   For best book, opinion seemed to be coalescing around the script
for ``James Joyce's `The Dead,''' adapted by Richard Nelson, which
would once again prove the value of choosing the right source
material. ``Contact,'' with a book by John Weidman, is also a
contender, with a few voters favoring ``Wild Party.''
</P>
<P>
   But the real races will begin with the national broadcast on
CBS.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most contested categories will probably be best
revival of a play, in which voters were evenly split between ``A
Moon for the Misbegotten'' and ``The Real Thing.'' (The other two
nominees, ``Amadeus,'' and ``The Price,'' registered nary a vote.)
</P>
<P>
   Here the voters are divided by a certain mild jingoism _
``Moon'' is an American production, while ``Real Thing'' is a
British import _ and a sense that a revival should involve
something, well, dead.
</P>
<P>
   `` `The Real Thing' is only 15 years old,'' said one agent,
noting that he had a client in the 1984 Broadway production.
``O'Neill has that certain back-from-the-grave gravitas.''
</P>
<P>
   Another voter added, `` `Moon' seems the kind of thing Broadway
should be doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, several voters thought ``Real Thing'' might have a slight
edge by dint of an even more powerful phenomenon: O'Neill fatigue.
In particular people mentioned last year's acclaimed four-hour
production of ``The Iceman Cometh.''
</P>
<P>
   ``People still remember `Iceman,' and they remember it was
loooong,'' a nonprofit producer said. `` `The Real Thing' is
contemporary and easier to sit through.''
</P>
<P>
   Likewise the leading men in both of those productions, Gabriel
Byrne in ``Moon'' and Stephen Dillane in ``Real Thing,'' look to be
neck and neck for the best actor.
</P>
<P>
   The dark horse in the race is Philip Seymour Hoffman, the rising
film actor whose well-received turn in ``True West'' has only
gilded his reputation. The other two nominees are John C. Reilly,
another hot movie talent who alternates roles with Hoffman in
``West,'' and David Suchet, who played the gloomy Salieri in the
closed revival of ``Amadeus.''
</P>
<P>
   Who will win? Pushed to answer, a majority said Dillane would
carry the day, despite Byrne's name recognition from films.
</P>
<P>
   `IT'S WIDE OPEN'
</P>
<P>
   Leading actress in a play is an even tighter category, with five
talented performers in the mix: Ehle, Harris, Shear (``Dirty
Blonde''), Cherry Jones (``Moon'') and Jayne Atkinson (``The
Rainmaker'').
</P>
<P>
   ``I have heard every option,'' one producer said. ``It's wide
open.''
</P>
<P>
   Handicapping this race is a process of elimination, voters say.
Atkinson's show is long closed, so scratch her. Ehle is young;
she'll have her day. (Just not this Sunday.)
</P>
<P>
   That leaves her mother, Harris, the older, sentimental choice;
Jones, the Broadway insider choice; and Shear, the populist choice.
</P>
<P>
   While Jones has an edge in the informal tally, the race seems
primed for an upset from Shear.
</P>
<P>
   A chatty, amiable sort, she has been active in interviews and
pre-Tony promotional events. Voters also say that a nod for Shear
here may be a way of acknowledging her other work on ``Dirty
Blonde,'' which she also wrote; conceived with the show's director,
James Lapine; and practically dragged to Broadway from a run
downtown.
</P>
<P>
   ``It won't win best play,'' one voter said, ``but she could be
given a nod here to say, `Good work, come again.'''
</P>
<P>
   She also has a potential block of votes behind her from the
Shubert Organization, Broadway's largest theater owner and a
principal producer of ``Dirty Blonde.''
</P>
<P>
   CLASH OF CHARACTERS
</P>
<P>
   One of Shear's co-stars, Kevin Chamberlin, who plays a
cross-dressing Mae West fan, is in the running for best featured
actor. His principal competition is the respected English actor Roy
Dotrice, who plays the crotchety father in ``A Moon for the
Misbegotten.''
</P>
<P>
   As is often the case, the winner will be determined by how
voters choose between two of Broadway's favorite gestures: the
crowning of a new star (i.e., Chamberlin) or the recognition of a
veteran talent (the 77-year-old Dotrice).
</P>
<P>
   The straw poll suggests Dotrice has a slight edge, but one press
agent not connected to the show insisted that Chamberlin had the
race in the bag.
</P>
<P>
   Why? The costume.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you want to win and you're a man,'' said the press agent,
``put on a dress.'' As evidence, he cited Harvey Fierstein, a
winner for ``Torch Song Trilogy,'' in 1983, and George Hearn,
victorious in drag in ``La Cage aux Folles'' in 1984.
</P>
<P>
   Other supporting categories have strong favorites. Blair Brown
is widely expected to be named best featured actress in a play
(``Copenhagen''), though the award would also seem to reflect her
earlier _ and unnominated _ work in ``The Dead.''
</P>
<P>
   ANOTHER GOLDEN RULE
</P>
<P>
   For featured actor and actress in a musical, most voters liked
Boyd Gaines and Deborah Yates (the Girl in the Yellow Dress) in
``Contact.'' But Yates can expect some strong competition from her
co-star Karen Ziemba and Eartha Kitt, generally considered one of
the few stand-out elements about the Public Theater's ``Wild
Party.'' One theory holds that Ziemba and Yates will split the
``Contact'' coalition, allowing Kitt to take the prize.
</P>
<P>
   But if Gaines wins and Ziemba or Yates carries the day, it could
be the perfect overture to a probable win for ``Contact'' as best
musical. Such a victory would probably cause ever more hand
wringing by theater people but would also adhere to one of
Broadway's golden rules.
</P>
<P>
   As one producer put it: ``Whatever leaves them clapping and
coming back for more, that's the best musical on Broadway.''
</P>
<P>
   YOUR BOX SEAT
</P>
<P>
   The Tony Awards ceremony at Radio City Music Hall will be
broadcast live on Sunday night. The first hour, from 8 to 9 p.m.,
will be broadcast by PBS (Channel 13 in New York). From 9 to 11
p.m. the program will be seen on CBS (Channel 2 in New York).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
