u f BC-CARS-GASKETS-FORD-NYT     06-01 0781
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARS-GASKETS-FORD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORD ADDS TO WARRANTY ON ENGINE GASKET FLAW 
</HEADLINE>
   By CHERYL JENSEN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a move that consumer advocates say could benefit owners of
all brands of vehicles, Ford Motor Co. has agreed to cover
head-gasket repairs for some rear-wheel-drive cars with the
3.8-liter V-6 engine. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ford had announced in February that it would pay for repairs on
about 718,000 front-drive automobiles with that engine: the 1994-95
Ford Taurus and Mercury Sable, the 1994 Lincoln Continental and the
1995 Ford Windstar. But the rear-drive cars _ Cougars, Mustangs and
Thunderbirds from the 1994-95 model years _ were excluded. Some
consumers were stuck with bills ranging from $1,600 for gasket
repairs to $4,000 for destroyed engines.
</P>
<P>
   Ford changed its mind this spring, saying it now realizes that
owners of those cars were also having problems. It is extending the
head-gasket warranty on about 294,000 rear-drive cars and
reimbursing owners who already paid for repairs.
</P>
<P>
   A head gasket is a thin seal between the engine block and the
cylinder head; if it fails, coolant can leak out or seep into
mechanical components, potentially causing total engine failure.
</P>
<P>
   Phil Edmonston, author of the annual ``Lemon-Aid Car Guide,''
said Ford's action was important to owners of other makes because
it reinforced the idea that engines should not suffer major defects
for at least seven years or 100,000 miles. General Motors and
Toyota have offered similar special policies to cover head-gasket
defects.
</P>
<P>
   Edmonston, who also has a Web site, www.lemonaidcars.com, said
that having such a ``durability parameter'' would give consumers
who have problems with other cars ammunition to use in small-claims
court or in negotiations with car companies. In addition, Ford's
action puts pressure on other automakers to follow suit. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One company that could feel such pressure is DaimlerChrysler.
Some of its 2-liter, 4-cylinder engines have also had head-gasket
problems, which the company is covering on a case-by-case basis.
</P>
<P>
   Under its new policy, Ford will extend to seven years or 100,000
miles, whichever comes first, the warranty on the head gaskets on
the 3.8-liter V-6 in '94-'95 models. The normal warranty is 3 years
or 36,000 miles. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The automaker will also reimburse consumers who had those
repairs done, even if the work was not done by a Ford dealer, a
company spokesman, Mike Vaughn, said. There is no limit on the
repair cost, and Ford will pay if a new engine was required. The
policy also covers owners of used cars.
</P>
<P>
   The letter being sent to consumers will tell those who already
paid for repairs how they can apply for a refund. Those who
purchased the vehicles used and do not receive a letter should
contact a Ford dealer.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Ford is taking a Band-Aid approach to it,'' said Clarence M.
Ditlow of the Center for Auto Safety. ``They put on one Band-Aid to
see if it would stop the bleeding. It didn't. Now they put on
another one, a bigger Band-Aid. But what they need to do is have a
comprehensive program.''
</P>
<P>
   He said Ford should have extended the warranty to 120,000 miles,
``which is the average useful life of a vehicle today,'' and should
have covered models predating 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Ditlow and Edmonston want Ford to include '93 cars; Ditlow said
he thought the problem dated as far back as '88 models. Vaughn said
records showed there was no problem with earlier vehicles. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Although he urged Ford to cover '93 models, Edmonston said the
company was responding in a generous, timely manner. He said
DaimlerChrysler should do the same on 2-liter engines in the
1995-99 Neon, Dodge Stratus, Plymouth Breeze, Dodge Avenger and
Chrysler Sebring. The problems are being dealt with on a
case-by-case basis; the company has not extended the warranty.
</P>
<P>
   A DaimlerChrysler spokesman, Mike Aberlich, said all owners were
not being notified because ``it does not appear to be a universal
problem.'' He added: ``That's not to say that we might not decide
to do something in the future. We are still watching and analyzing
it.''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Aberlich said DaimlerChrysler was reimbursing consumers for
out-of-warranty repairs on a case-by-case basis when they called
the company's toll-free assistance number _ (800) 992-1997 or went
to dealerships. He said the dealers would consider factors
including whether there was any evidence that the vehicle was
abused. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One problem with DaimlerChrysler's policy is that owners who
figure their warranty no longer applies and go to an independent
repair shop instead of to a dealer might lose a chance for eventual
reimbursement. ``They are penalized,'' Edmonston said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
