<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 17:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2079 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-MEDICAL-INSURANCE-NYT     06-01 0845
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDICAL-INSURANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATIENT: KNOW THY RIGHTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, June 4) 
 By JENNIFER STEINHAUER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In recent years, Congress has passed several laws designed to
help people remain insured when they change jobs, and to obtain
coverage for life-altering medical situations that insurers often
shunned.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is, most people pay little attention to what their
rights are in such situations until they need them, and then may be
unaware of the new laws' existence.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   Do you know many 25-year-old single men who are deeply obsessed
with the Newborns' and Mothers' Health Protection Act of 1996? (It
was designed to eliminate what came to be called drive-by births by
mandating that insurers cover minimum hospital stays following
childbirth.)
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   Employers offering health insurance are required by law to keep
their workers abreast of the latest changes in health care law. But
they often go about it in ways that are sure to escape notice.
</P>
<P>
   Annual notices to employees are required for some laws, but a
lot of other important information about health care rights is
buried in what are called summary plan descriptions of benefits
packages, mounds of legalese about as readable as the package
inserts in a Tylenol box. Smaller companies often count on health
maintenance organizations to inform their employees, and HMOs have
been known to fall down on the job.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Taylor, a principal of the Teare Group, a health care and
human resources consultancy, said the first problem involved in
keeping employees informed is that employers often do not
understand what they have to provide in writing. ``The second is
that the employee may not read it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Small wonder that the Department of Labor, which has
jurisdiction over many of the laws, fields 1,700 calls a week on
health care questions alone. The department has begun to audit
companies to make sure they are giving their workers the necessary
information, especially on the Health Insurance Portability and
Accountability Act, or HIPAA.
</P>
<P>
   Among other provisions, the 1996 law expanded protections for
people with serious medical conditions who change jobs, and it has
helped millions of people, but millions more do not know a thing
about it.
</P>
<P>
   Under the law, as long as there has not been a break in health
care coverage of 63 days or more, the waiting periods commonly
imposed before a new employer's health insurance plan will cover
pre-existing conditions can be reduced or eliminated entirely.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, say you have a chronic heart problem and were
treated for it under your former employer's health plan, but your
new employer's plan does not cover pre-existing conditions for the
first year of employment.
</P>
<P>
   The amount of time your condition was covered by your former
employer's plan counts against that waiting period _ if it was at
least a year, coverage under your new plan begins immediately.
(Your former employer is required to give you a certificate proving
prior coverage.) A similar provision applies to new employees'
children with pre-existing conditions.
</P>
<P>
   Under the law, employers cannot discriminate against workers
because of chronic conditions. For example, ``under HIPAA, you
cannot charge an individual a higher premium just because they have
diabetes,'' said Leslie Kramerich, acting assistant secretary of
the Labor Department unit that oversees pensions and benefits.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some employers used to say, `We will let you in, but because
you have diabetes, you have to pay a 40 percent higher premium,' or
they would keep you out, period.''
</P>
<P>
   The law also requires that employees who give birth be permitted
to enroll the baby for coverage immediately, and not have to wait
for the next open enrollment period.
</P>
<P>
   ``My instinct is that people don't realize how important HIPAA
is,'' said James P. McElligott Jr., a lawyer in Richmond, Va., who
specializes in health care law. ``Today, as a result of HIPAA, if a
child is born to a couple or adopted, that child can have
cradle-to-grave health care coverage no matter what its medical
condition is. That is an enormous change from the way things used
to be.''
</P>
<P>
   If you think your employer has failed to comply with the law, or
you are leaving a job, or you want to understand the basics and the
many exceptions and nuances of HIPAA and other health care laws,
the Department of Labor offers an easy-to-navigate Web site,
www.dol.gov/dol/pwba, with plenty of information. Too much, in
fact: unless you are a policy wonk, I do not recommend clicking and
wading through, say, ``Health Insurance Portability for Group
Health Plans; Interim Rules and Proposed Rule (04/08/1997).''
</P>
<P>
   But documents explaining every twist and turn in health care law
in exhaustive detail are there. Georgetown University also
maintains a Web site for consumers with specifics about the laws
and state-by-state guidelines in modern standard English:
data.georgetown.edu/research/ihcrp/hipaa/.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-01-00 1736EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000601.0243 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 17:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2080 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN04-CO     06-01 0730
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 1STLEDE &HT;    1STLEDE
 &HT;    Eds: Changes throughout
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Funeral for a mistress; black tie optional
 &HT;    For release June 4, 2000.
 &HT;    By Howard Kleinberg
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ The lady wrote in earnest. She had been to the funeral
of her husband's longtime _ and ``very public'' _ mistress after
debating (a) whether or not to go and (b) what to wear. In
retrospect now, she wondered in writing not about her presence at
the funeral but of her attire.
</P>
<P>
   In her query to the Miss Manners-type columnist for The Weekend
Times of London, Mrs. Name and Address Withheld asked if her choice
of navy blue was appropriate inasmuch as it wasn't mourning black
or celebratory white.
</P>
<P>
   The response was more astonishing than the request; it, too, was
sincere: a delicate grey would have been the ideal shade, wrote the
man from the Weekend Times. There also was the mild, almost
obligatory, admonishment: ``How brave, if inappropriate, of you:
good manners quite excuse a wife's attendance at such events.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Name and Address, of course, was breaking no new ground in
attending the a tryst-tainted farewell. Did not the widow of French
President Francois Mitterand acquiesce to a graveside appearance by
her late husband's mistress as well?
</P>
<P>
   The table had been set for such attendances, what we were
dealing with in this most recent event was attire. Despite her
choice of navy blue, the letter writer complained, ``all eyes
present still switched from the deceased to me,'' thus prompting
her letter to the newspaper as to whether she had the appropriate
wardrobe.
</P>
<P>
   I would have considered that a triumph, not an embarrassment. To
have the old mistress not be the center of the show at her own
funeral should have been celebrated as retribution. I'd have worn a
Hawaiian shirt and white shorts!
</P>
<P>
   Oh, how the world is turning. It is almost acceptable on the
European side of the Atlantic that mistresses are a tolerable part
of daily life. Yes, there is some grousing but reality is reality
to Europeans.
</P>
<P>
   Now, on the U.S. side, mistresses and other things naughty,
while still raising some apoplectic reaction, are becoming more
common. (We give Europe Starbucks Coffee and McDonald's and they
give us mistress tolerance.)
</P>
<P>
   Rudy Guliani's withdrawal from the U.S. Senate race in New York
was accepted more to be based on his prostate cancer rather than
his fooling around. The tearful discourse by wounded wife Donna
Hanover played a secondary role _ and allowed Rudy to retreat
almost protectively into the empathetic arms of his mistress.
(Mistress number 2, that is.)
</P>
<P>
   Also note how quietly Newt Gingrich recently married the woman
with whom he had an affair to break up his second marriage. We're
sort of getting attuned to these things; certainly not at the
Southern Baptist Conventions but elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Just look at what has filled our plates in recent years: The
chronic Bill Clinton and retrospective revelations about JFK, FDR,
LBJ and Ike as well as the fully-named Henry Hyde, Dan Burton and
Helen Chenoweth. Throw in a male general hitting on a female
general, a school teacher having her student's babies, and a female
Air Force pilot having a verboten penchant for enlisted men, and
we're a nation in transition.
</P>
<P>
   Is there nothing in our lives that does not have a sexual tone
to it? Do we titter or grumble when we read that liver-lipped movie
actress Angelina Jolie calls out for more sex: ``Before I die, I
wanna taste everyone in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   I wonder what those dozens of betrayed wives will wear when
Angelina is ready to be buried.
</P>
<P>
   Sex sells. It sells in stores, at movie theaters, in books, in
newspapers, on TV, just about anywhere. Some think Americans are
too puritanical. We're not. We just haven't been as public about
it, for fear of what our neighbor will think.
</P>
<P>
   Led by European example, some of those barriers are beginning to
crumble _ not so much by choice but by the simple fact that
everyone now knows everyone else's private business.
</P>
<P>
   And that which we don't know, we always can ask by writing to a
Miss Manners.
</P>
<P>
   Howard Kleinberg, a former editor of the Miami News, is a
columnist for Cox Newspapers. His e-mail address is
hkmiami(at)aol.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
