<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 17:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2087 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-BAUHAUS-TEXTILES-2TAK     06-01 1125
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BAUHAUS-TEXTILES-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ART REVIEW: EVEN THE EGALITARIAN BAUHAUS HAD A HAUSFRAU TENDENCY 
</HEADLINE>
  (Exhibition notes are at end of review.) 
 By ROBERTA SMITH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It's always startling to be reminded that the
Bauhaus, that font of modernist invention, did not allow women to
participate in its architecture, wall-painting and furniture
workshops because they were considered too physically demanding.
Such genteel, if chauvinistic, concern seems out of character at a
place where aesthetic equality _ the elevation of craft and design
to fine-art status _ was a founding principle. But no, at the
Bauhaus, women had only gentler options: ceramics, metalwork and
especially the ancient, implicitly female craft of weaving.
</P>
<P>
   Such policies must have saved a lot of breath. After all, the
elevation of craft, or anything else, requires bodies: dedicated
souls willing to learn the basics, bend the rules and inspire
disciples. Surely it was easier to guide women toward the loom en
masse than to convince individual men and women that weaving could
be as expressive and important as any other art, fine or applied.
</P>
<P>
   One wonders if the school's founding fathers fully appreciated
the extent to which the women of the Weaving Workshop proved them
right. Theirs was the only workshop that spanned all of the
Bauhaus' stormy 14-year history, an existence characterized by
financial difficulties, internal discord, physical relocation (from
Weimar to Dessau to Berlin) and an increasingly unsympathetic
political climate. Despite everything, the workshop established the
fundamentals of contemporary textile design and created one of the
most important, if least studied, aspects of the Bauhaus legacy.
</P>
<P>
   This confluence of opposed and dovetailing agendas comes to mind
in the Jewish Museum's illuminating, densely packed survey of the
life and art of Anni Albers, perhaps the most significant member of
the Bauhaus Weaving Workshop. Organized by the Albers Foundation
and the Peggy Guggenheim Museum in Venice, ``Anni Albers'' is part
art exhibition, part weaving seminar, part biography and altogether
fascinating.
</P>
<P>
   It is not without flaws, most notably cramped space compounded
by intrusive display tables that cornily resemble looms. These last
are the salient characteristic of Gae Aulenti's exhibition design;
but while they obstruct the viewing of Albers' handloomed wall
hangings, they efficiently display nearly 100 examples of the
textile samples she designed for possible commercial production.
</P>
<P>
   The show brings together work done over five decades on two
continents in several media. In addition to a broad range of
textiles, it includes gouache and watercolor textile studies,
jewelry and examples of the lithographs to which Albers turned in
the 1960s, somewhat relieved to give up the physical complexities
of the loom. Its driving force is Albers' thorough exploration of
weaving as both a fine and an applied art, her appreciation of the
structural and imagistic possibilities of its basic grid structure
and her sensitivity to the subtleties of texture and color possible
on the loom.
</P>
<P>
   Annelise Fleischmann, born in Berlin in 1900, arrived at the
Bauhaus in 1922. By 1925, she had completed its famous foundation
course, which included color instruction from the mystical Johannes
Itten, and overcome her initial suspicion that weaving was
``sissy.'' She had also married the painter and color theorist
Josef Albers, who was 13 years her senior and the first Bauhaus
student to become a master (as they called teachers). They were
perhaps an unlikely pair: She was the cosseted but artistically
inclined daughter of a Jewish furniture manufacturer in Berlin; he
was from the coal-mining city of Bottrop in the Ruhr, a Catholic
and the son of a skilled laborer who taught him to take pride in
working by hand.
</P>
<P>
   In 1933, just after the Nazis closed the Bauhaus for good, the
Alberses were invited by Philip Johnson and Edward M.M. Warburg to
emigrate to the United States, where they continued to spread the
Bauhaus gospel. They spent their first 16 years teaching at Black
Mountain College, the experimental art school in Asheville, N.C. In
1950, they moved to Connecticut, where Josef taught at Yale until
his retirement in 1958. (He died in 1976 at 88, she in 1994 at 94.)
</P>
<P>
   Photographs of the Alberses at home indicate their faithfulness
to Bauhaus simplicity and spareness, even in a small house in
Connecticut. These pictures are part of a personal-history gallery
that includes letters, memorabilia, a selection of the
pre-Columbian textiles that Albers collected (and learned from),
and examples of the Chanel-inspired jackets she made for herself,
as well as curiosities like little squares of corrugated cardboard,
gouged and colored to resemble rough-textured weaving samples, that
she used as teaching aids to sharpen what she called ``tactile
awareness.''
</P>
<P>
   Albers could be as less-is-more and as true to materials as the
next Bauhauslern, as is evinced by the textile samples _ drapery,
upholstery fabric, wall coverings _ that she designed both at the
Bauhaus and in the United States, mostly for Knoll and Sunar. (Some
are still available.) These fabrics give pre-eminence to structure
and materials. Their weaves are often as open and simple as a basic
dishcloth, but Albers also understood the cumulative effect of
little changes, like knots or twists, or irregularities on an
expanse of fabric. Over the years, she experimented with a range of
materials now taken for granted in fabric design _ raffia,
fiberglass, jute, horse hair, harnessmaker's thread, metal thread
and foil, Lurex and plastic. (Their variety would have impressed
Donald Judd, who deeply admired her husband's paintings.)
</P>
<P>
   Following the lead of Gunta Stoelzl, her colleague and teacher
at the Bauhaus, Albers began working with cellophane as early as
1929, producing a design for a wall covering for a school
auditorium in Bernau that both absorbed sound and reflected light,
and also earned her her Bauhaus diploma. (A swatch of this material
is in this show and also in ``Making Choices'' at the Museum of
Modern Art, which includes a small but impressive selection of
Albers' work, as well as a handsome wall hanging by Stoelzl.)
</P>
<P>
   It is significant that one of Albers' favorite teachers at the
Bauhaus was Paul Klee. Klee taught a course for weavers only, and
works like Albers' ``Red and Blue Layers'' (1954), which is
actually mostly orange and pink, echo the influence of his vibrant
palette. More important, Klee encouraged his students both to
attend to and take expressive liberties with the implicitly modern
structure of weaving: the grid.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Especially after Albers came to the United States and became
more familiar with pre-Columbian textiles, she introduced
suggestions of landscapes (``Monte Alban,'' 1936) and cityscapes
into her weaving. In some of her most successful pieces, like
``From the East'' and ``Under Way,'' she allowed rogue threads to
wander in a kind of abstract script across the face of a weaving.
In the boldly scaled ``Red Meander,'' this wandering determines the
labyrinthine pattern of the entire weaving.
</P>
<P>
   In 1949, Albers became the first textile artist to be given a
solo show at the Museum of Modern Art; both her work and her
writings made her revered within the textile field. Today, her work
commands a broader stage. It benefits from heightened attention to
the histories of design and the crafts, including the Weaving
Workshop; increased consciousness of the role of women in the
formation of modernism; and the frequency with which contemporary
art employs fabric, weaving and other kinds of ``women's work.''
</P>
<P>
   This exhibition confirms that Albers is equal in importance to
her husband, both for her work and as a link between European and
American modernisms. It also reveals how perfectly weaving met the
basic conflict, never really resolved, at the heart of the Bauhaus:
between the artist as creative autodidact pursuing personal
expression and the artist as versatile master craftsman, figuring
out ways to use technology to make beautiful everyday objects
available to all. This conflict was never a problem for the
weavers, who pushed their medium toward decoration, abstraction and
function as the situation demanded. No one did this as effortlessly
as Anni Albers. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   EXHIBITION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   ``Anni Albers'' remains at the Jewish Museum, 1109 Fifth Ave.,
at 92nd St., Manhattan, (212) 423-3200, through Aug. 20. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
