<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 17:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2092 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-SCIENCE-ON-BROADWAY-A     06-01 0843
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCIENCE-ON-BROADWAY-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRITIC'S NOTEBOOK: SCIENCE IS FINDING A HOME ONSTAGE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 By BRUCE WEBER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ During previews for ``Copenhagen,'' the playwright
Michael Frayn received a letter from a woman who had just seen it.
``She said that neither she nor anyone she was with liked all the
science in the show,'' Frayn recalled in a recent interview, ``and
that unless I took it out it wasn't going to last long on
Broadway.''
</P>
<P>
   There is, of course, a great deal of science not to like in
``Copenhagen,'' if that's your inclination, and indeed, anyone
paying attention to word of mouth about the play is sure to hear
complaints that its erudition is off-putting. It is a play, after
all, about nuclear fission, the making of the atomic bomb and the
esoteric concepts _ known as the uncertainty principle and
complementarity _ that are the fundamentals of quantum physics. But
it is also a play about friendship, personal loss, patriotism and
the gravest of moral responsibilities. And, being performed nightly
to full or nearly full houses, it is the favorite to win the Tony
Award for best new play on Sunday. So some people like the science,
or are at least willing to accept it in the service of drama.
</P>
<P>
   Presenting difficult concepts is always risky for a playwright,
but it is particularly so in an era when audiences have been
conditioned by lowbrow entertainment to have their senses tickled
but not to have their brains massaged. As it happens, though,
Werner Heisenberg and Niels Bohr, the two great physicists that
Frayn resurrects (literally) in ``Copenhagen,'' are not alone in
their challenging speeches or the connections they make between the
mysteries of the universe and the mysteries of the human
experience. Science and scientists have been onstage all over the
place this season.
</P>
<P>
   Off-Broadway, Tina Landau's ``Space,'' which appeared at the
Public Theater last fall, presented astronomers on the lookout for
communication from the far reaches of the galaxy, and last week
``Proof,'' David Auburn's fine new play about the world of higher
mathematics, opened at the Manhattan Theater Club.
</P>
<P>
   Off-off-Broadway, Target Margin Theater presented ``The Five
Hysterical Girls Theorem'' by Rinne Groff, another play trafficking
in the lyrical perplexities of number theory; the Ensemble Studio
Theater staged ``Moving Bodies'' by Arthur Giron, a biography of
the physicist Richard Feynman; and playing now at SoHo Rep is
``Hypatia,'' Mac Wellman's willfully muddling theater tapestry
based on the life and death of the title character, a fifth-century
mathematician and philosopher.
</P>
<P>
   In the wings is a new musical by Joshua Rosenblum and Joanne
Sydney Lessner, also called ``Proof'' _ I saw a staged reading by
the York Theater Company last month _ which is about Andrew Wiles,
the Princeton professor who explained one of mathematics' most
famously lingering enigmas, Fermat's Last Theorem. (It declares
that for integer values of n greater than 2, no whole number
solution exists for xn plus yn equals zn. Can you whistle that
tune?)
</P>
<P>
   And at the Ivanhoe Theater in Chicago, Penny Penniston's ``Now
Then Again,'' a charming if unheralded play about young physicists
in love _ ``Copenhagen'' is not the only show of the season to use
Heisenberg's uncertainty principle metaphorically _ closed on
Sunday after an extended run. Its ingenious structure _ the first
half moves forward to a point in time; the second act moves
backward from the same point, but the events that preceded it have
altered _ is intended to illustrate Heisenberg's declaration that
observable phenomena are not necessarily as they appear.
</P>
<P>
   The works achieve a range of success, and they wander to varying
degrees into the explication of the science. ``Copenhagen'' does
the most with the most; even if you can't reiterate Heisenberg's
theories after you leave the theater, you feel as if you understand
them while you're in it. (For the record, Heisenberg stated that it
is impossible to know both an atomic particle's position and its
momentum exactly; to observe a particle, he argued, you have to hit
it with a photon of light, and such a collision will affect the
particle's course. Full disclosure: I looked it up and also
discussed it with Frayn.)
</P>
<P>
   But in all of these works, the pursuit of scientific knowledge
looms as a search for beauty and truth, which a number of these
plays argue is precisely what playwrights and other artists do. (To
this end, Groff's ``Five Hysterical Girls'' concludes with a play
within the play.) Several _ ``Now Then Again'' and Auburn's
``Proof,'' for example _ equate the difficult search for scientific
truth with the search for human connection and love. And all make
the case that science, like art or love, is a deeply human
endeavor, all but doomed, pardon the expression, to uncertainty.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   This flowering use of science as narrative material and
scientific concepts as metaphors for the stage is worth remarking
on for several reasons. For one thing, it provides evidence that
science is re-entering the realm of popular culture, not just in
imaginative, futuristic fiction but also in other mainstream and
alternative forms: from historical reconstruction and theoretical
abstraction to fluffy romance and contemporary realism.
</P>
<P>
   Why this is so is a matter for speculation. ``One explanation is
that it's completely random,'' Auburn said in an interview, a sly
invocation of a mathematical concept in itself. But the revolution
in technology is surely a factor. The World Wide Web, e-mail, cell
phones (particular favorites of theatergoers, it seems) have all
been around long enough to have saturated public consciousness yet
are still new enough to feel like magic; you don't have to be able
to explain them to use them or be impressed by their prevalence.
And it's clear that scientific discoveries, or at least their
manifestations, have entered public discourse and the acquisitive,
boom-time culture with the force of fashion. The high-minded
mysteries of science suddenly seem, um, hip.
</P>
<P>
   Tapping into a societal mood has always been the theater's stock
in trade, and the emergence of science on stage is a sign of this,
just as a stream of plays about gender politics, sexual identity
and AIDS have been over the last two decades, or as plays dealing
with poverty- and squalor-driven violence emerged as the gap
between the affluent and deprived strata of society widened. Not to
say that the theater is undergoing a sea change, but writers do
seem to be taking note of a new country to explore.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a technological age we're living in,'' said Auburn,
whose background in mathematics peaked, he said, with a B-minus in
college calculus, ``and technology is a field that produces a lot
of drama. Maybe the divide between the two cultures'' _ that is,
the one that separates scientists from nonscientists _ ``is
breaking down a little bit.''
</P>
<P>
   For playwrights this territory is full of challenges, the main
one being the issue of how much to explain about concepts that few
if any audience members are familiar with. In ``Copenhagen,'' Frayn
used the character of Bohr's wife, Margrethe, a highly intelligent
woman but not a world-class physicist, as an intermediary between
her husband and Heisenberg and in some ways as a stand-in for the
audience. To include her in their conversations, they have to
explain things they would silently assume with each other.
</P>
<P>
   Auburn purposely shied away from equation-solving in his play _
the proof of the title has to do with prime numbers, but what it
proves is never made explicit _ but in the opening act one
character believes that another is not mathematically savvy, and as
he condescends to her he's also helping the audience. And Auburn
did have his play vetted by members of the math department at New
York University, who also visited rehearsals.
</P>
<P>
   ``What the cast got from them,'' Auburn said, ``more than any
specific math information, was a feel for what the discourse is
like. It isn't dry or analytical; they were having fun,
argumentative discussions about their field, really scrapping with
each other. It was surprising to the performers, I think.'' In any
case, he said, the focus of his play is less on math than it is on
relationships.
</P>
<P>
   Frayn, on the other hand, went the opposite way.
</P>
<P>
   ``There probably is too much explication,'' he said. ``But I
wouldn't have done it if it didn't seem essential to the story.
It's difficult to understand why everyone felt they were absolutely
safe, as far as the usage of atomic bombs is concerned, unless you
explain about the two uranium isotopes and fast neutrons. And you
can't make clear why the balance of probability began to change
unless you explain the change of uranium into plutonium in a
reactor. You simply cannot tell the story without explaining those
things. It's not to everyone's taste.''
</P>
<P>
   Making the science comprehensible, said Frayn, whose academic
background is in philosophy, was, indeed, difficult.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a lot of writing and rewriting, to make it clear to
myself,'' he said. ``I did find that difficult, but if I could make
it clear to myself, I thought other people could follow.''
</P>
<P>
   Potential perplexities aside, the new science plays add welcome
elements to the theatrical landscape. There's a whole new
vernacular afoot, a scientific argot whose music is just beginning
to be parsed. Terms like lepton, composite number, photon and
isotope haven't exactly been part of the stage's working vocabulary
until now, and watching playwrights work with them and struggle to
make them useful as communicative, sonorous tools can be a nifty
pleasure for theatergoers. And if the grand concepts of science
they connote can be lassoed by playwrights well enough to make them
a little more accessible and applicable to you and me, that's a
service.
</P>
<P>
   One thing I particularly like is the spate of unusual new
characters that science brings to the stage. These include people
like Heisenberg and Bohr (played with great verbal elan by Michael
Cumpsty and Philip Bosco), whose high-minded retrospective debate
(they are brought back from the dead for the purpose) makes
excruciatingly clear the application of intellectual abstraction to
concrete events. But there is also a whole collection of younger
people with young people's immediate concerns.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Proof'' and in ``Now Then Again'' the main characters, all
in their 20s, find the pursuit of difficult knowledge no less
enlivening and nervous-making than things like their careers, their
families, their social graces, their hormones and their heartaches.
I can't recall having seen similar types on the stage before this,
and the two pairs of actors involved _ Mary-Louise Parker and Ben
Shenkman in ``Proof,'' Joseph Wycoff and Katie McLean in ``Now Then
Again'' _ make their characters revelatory. All four performances
were thoroughly rounded and persuasive, illuminating an obviously
extant kind of life experience I'd never before considered but was
delighted to discover. Intelligence and Emotion
</P>
<P>
   Not least among the satisfactions of these plays is that they
add ammunition to the combat against American culture's troubling
anti-intellectualism. Whatever the artistic achievement of these
works, what each of them accomplishes is the lesson that
intelligence is not a quality that exists as an antithesis to _ or
even apart from _ conscience, emotional capability or common sense.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's fun to write about smart people,'' Auburn said. ``You're
not condescending to your own characters when you write about them.
You're looking up to them and trying to do them justice.''
</P>
<P>
   May there be more of them.
</P>
<P>
   WHERE THEY PLAY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the current Manhattan plays mentioned in the Critic's
Notebook article on science and the theater:
</P>
<P>
   `COPENHAGEN,' Royale, 242 W. 45th St., (212) 239-6200. Tuesdays,
Thursdays and Fridays at 8 p.m.; Wednesdays and Saturdays at 2 and
8 p.m.; Sundays at 3 p.m. Tickets: $40 to $65; $25 student rush
tickets at the box office on the day of performance.
</P>
<P>
   `HYPATIA,' SoHo Rep, 46 Walker St., (212) 334-0962. Through
Friday, Saturday and Sunday night at 7:30. Tickets: $12 and $15.
</P>
<P>
   `PROOF,' City Center Stage I, 131 W. 55th St., (212) 581-1212.
Tuesdays through Fridays at 8 p.m.; Saturdays at 2:30 and 8 p.m.;
Sundays at 2:30 and 7 p.m. Tickets: $50.
</P>
