<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-$ADV04-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     IRONY OF U.S.-CHINA RELATIONS: OLE FOES CAN BECOME NEW
FRIENDS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 &HT;     (For release Sunday, June 4) &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 &HT;     By ROBERT E. THOMPSON  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ When the president of China phones the president of
the United States to thank him for his efforts in winning House
passage of a trade bill, that is not just news. It is a step toward
improved relations between two of the mightiest powers on earth.
</P>
<P>
   The call, which came on May 28, took White House staffers by
surprise. None of them could remember President Jiang Zemin having
previously initiated a telephone call to Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   For about 40 minutes, the two presidents reportedly talked about
issues including nuclear non-proliferation, the relationship
between China and Taiwan, possible U.S. construction of a missile
defense system, and, of course, trade.
</P>
<P>
   In tandem with House Republican leaders, Clinton worked
diligently to win House approval of legislation to grant China
normal trade status on a permanent basis rather than on the
year-to-year arrangement that has been in effect for two decades.
</P>
<P>
   In doing so, Clinton was at odds with his Democratic leaders in
the House _ Richard Gephardt of Missouri and David Bonior of
Michigan _ and with one of the party's staunchest political allies,
organized labor.
</P>
<P>
   But the House voted, 237 to 197, for the trade bill. It provided
an excellent example of the claim that politics breeds strange
bedfellows. Leading the pro-vote were two normally bitter foes:
Clinton and House GOP Whip Tom DeLay of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   House passage of the measure, followed by the trans-Pacific
phone call, should place relations with China on a more even and
productive course than they often have been in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   The next hurdle is to win Senate approval, which is expected to
be achieved more easily than in the House.
</P>
<P>
   One major obstruction to Senate approval could be Sen. Jesse
Helms, R-N.C., who heads the Foreign Relations Committee and is
against doing anything to improve Clinton's legacy during the last
months of his presidency.
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton, who has persevered in his effort to cultivate
Jiang, is not about to cave in before a Helms onslaught.
</P>
<P>
   The current situation points up the irony that has characterized
the U.S.-Chinese relationship over many years.
</P>
<P>
   During World War II, China, like England and the Soviet Union,
was a staunch ally of the United States. Although that war ended in
1945 for America, Britain and the Soviet Union, another one erupted
anew in China where the nationalists under Chiang Kai-shek and the
communists led by Mao Zedong continued to fight a civil war.
</P>
<P>
   Despite aid from America, the nationalists lost and left the
mainland for the island of Taiwan (then known as Formosa) in 1949.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1950s, Americans found themselves in bloody warfare
against China, their one-time ally, in the frozen hills of North
Korea.
</P>
<P>
   Here at home, with McCarthyism in full rampage, Republicans _
including Richard Nixon _ accused leaders of the Truman
administration of being ``soft on communism'' and of ``losing''
China. They also asserted that Truman had dispatched warships to
the Formosa Strait, which separates mainland China from Taiwan, to
prevent the nationalists from launching an invasion of the
mainland.
</P>
<P>
   That, of course, was pure poppycock. When Dwight D. Eisenhower
became president in 1953, he withdrew the ships from the Formosa
Strait, and some newspaper headlines proclaimed ``Ike Unleashes
Chiang.''
</P>
<P>
   But nothing happened. Of his own volition, Chiang remained
leashed. He could not wage warfare against Mao's forces without
U.S. help, and Ike was not about to commit American military might
to the China battle.
</P>
<P>
   The United States and China remained enemies throughout the
1950s and 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   Then another irony occurred. Nixon, who had built his early
career on opposition to all things communist, had become president
and in 1972 accepted an invitation to visit China. Thus he opened a
door that had been tightly closed to Americans for nearly a quarter
century.
</P>
<P>
   What he saw when he got there was a stultified society. Grand
buildings constructed long ago by English imperialists were in
decay. Farmers were tilling the soil with ancient instruments. Many
women slaved at home without modern conveniences.
</P>
<P>
   In what was the singular highlight of his presidency, Nixon had
an enjoyable and worthwhile visit in China. But he did not formally
extend diplomatic recognition to Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   That task fell to Jimmy Carter, who made the announcement to
coincide with a visit to the United States by Chinese leader Deng
Xiaoping. Deng arrived on Dec. 29, 1979, and diplomatic recognition
became effective on January 1, 1980.
</P>
<P>
   In his diary, Carter wrote: `I was favorably impressed with
Deng. He's small, tough, intelligent, frank, courageous,
personable, self-assured, friendly, and it's a pleasure to
negotiate with him.''
</P>
<P>
   Carter's successor, Ronald Reagan, who like Nixon had been a
strong opponent of communist China, visited that country in 1984,
continuing policies that Nixon and Carter had originated.
</P>
<P>
   Reagan's vice president, George Bush, had been U.S. envoy to
China during Gerald Ford's presidency and was highly respected by
the Chinese. As vice president and then as president, he returned
to China as a friend.
</P>
<P>
   So it goes. Old foes become new friends. That is the story and
the irony of American-Chinese relations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
