<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 18:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2100 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-TEN-FRENCH-OPEN-NYT &LR;      06-01 1068
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-FRENCH-OPEN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AGASSI KNOCKED OUT OF FRENCH OPEN BY KUCERA 
</HEADLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER CLAREY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ On tour, they call Karol Kucera ``Little Cat,'' and down
the stretch on Thursday at the French Open, Andre Agassi looked as
defenseless as a goldfish in a bowl.
</P>
<P>
   For Agassi, there will be no repeat of last year's emotional
journey at Roland Garros. No theatrical bows and blown kisses to
all corners of the court. No hands clutching the head in stunned
delight. No communion with the Parisian public.
</P>
<P>
   Agassi turned escape into an art form here on his way to the
1999 title, but this year it was Kucera's turn to twist free of the
ropes, winning 2-6, 7-5, 6-1, 6-0 in the second round and sending a
shock wave through the refurbished center court where Agassi and
Steffi Graf became champions last year, before they became an item.
</P>
<P>
   It has been a disastrous first week for U.S. tennis stars: The
No. 2 men's seed Pete Sampras and the No. 2 women's seed Lindsay
Davenport were both beaten in the first round. The top-seeded
Agassi, winner of three of the last four Grand Slam events, made it
only one round further, and like Davenport, part of the explanation
was a physical problem. In Davenport's case, it was a wrenched
back; in Agassi's case a blister on his right foot.
</P>
<P>
   Agassi served for a two-set lead at 5-4 in the second set, but
at 15-15, he dumped an ill-advised and poorly struck drop shot into
the net. He then got the worst of a cross-court forehand exchange
with Kucera and then, on the next point, missed a backhand passing
shot to lose his serve and his edge. Kucera soon broke his serve
again _ with Agassi making unforced errors on the final two points
_ to even the match at one-set apiece. ``That gave me a lot of
confidence,'' Kucera said. ``He had the whole match in his hands
and suddenly it's one-set all.''
</P>
<P>
   After Kucera jumped out to a 4-1 lead in the third set, Agassi
returned to his chair, pulled off his right shoe and sock and
summoned trainer Per Bastholt. Agassi explained that a blister had
started bothering him late in the second set.
</P>
<P>
   Bastholt wrapped Agassi's big toe and treated the sole of his
foot, where a new blister was developing. But while Agassi returned
to the court, he would not win another game, losing 11 in a row in
total, as Kucera confidently smacked ground strokes to the corners
and Agassi proved incapable of keeping up with his rhythm. Agassi
then proved incapable of bringing himself to answer questions from
the media, fleeing Roland Garros and risking a $10,000 fine.
</P>
<P>
   That would be a mere slap on the wristband for a tennis player
of Agassi's means, but there is no question that Thursday's loss
will hurt a great deal more despite the fact that it did have a
precedent. Kucera, a fluid 26-year-old counterpuncher from Slovakia
with a great running forehand, had a 2-2 record against Agassi
coming into the match and beat him in a testy fourth-round match at
the U.S. Open in 1997, in which Agassi mocked Kucera's habit of
catching his service toss and began hitting moonballs in
frustration. Kucera and his coach Miloslav Mecir took Agassi's
behavior as a compliment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some players just have a good game for certain other players,
and Karol has a good game for playing Andre,'' Mecir said. ``He
doesn't get bothered by power. He can find answers to hard shots,
and he can run very, very well.''
</P>
<P>
   Kucera was ranked eighth in the world at the end of the 1998
season, and he might have finished in the top 10 again last year if
not for a sore right wrist that kept him from playing for six weeks
in the summer. According to Mecir, the former U.S. Open finalist
whose nickname ``The Big Cat'' inspired Kucera's, his pupil decided
to change the type of string in his racquet at the end of last
season in an attempt to alleviate the chronic pain in his arm.
</P>
<P>
   ``He thought it would be gentler on the arm, but the problem was
that he lost confidence and control of the ball,'' Mecir said.
</P>
<P>
   After struggling early in the season, losing in the first round
of the Australia Open and in the year's first two Masters Series
events in Indian Wells and Key Biscayne, Kucera resumed using his
former strings and made life difficult for the opposition, beating
Gustavo Kuerten on clay in Monte Carlo and winning all four of his
matches easily at the World Team Cup last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew I had some chances today,'' Kucera said. ``I feel that
my game is coming back.''
</P>
<P>
   With Agassi out, Michael Chang is the only U.S. man to reach the
third round. Anna Kournikova, the No. 14 women's seed, was
eliminated, if not necessarily upset, by Sylvia Plischke of
Austria, 6-2, 4-6, 6-3. No player has ever attracted so much
attention without ever winning a tournament, and Kournikova's
losing streak will not end in Paris, but her inconsistency against
Plischke was certainly due, in part, to the torn ankle ligament she
suffered three weeks ago and which curtailed her preparation for
Roland Garros.
</P>
<P>
   More surprising was Argentine qualifier Agustin Calleri's
four-set victory over Kucera's Slovakian Davis Cup teammate Dominik
Hrbaty, the No. 14 seed and one of the world's most dangerous
clay-court players.
</P>
<P>
   Marat Safin, the 20-year-old Russian survived his grueling
encounter with flashy Australian Andrew Ilie after Ilie retired
because of cramps in his legs and right arm while trailing 0-5 in
the final set. Stefan Koubek of Austria was unable to finish his
match for a different reason. While trailing Attila Savolt of
Hungary by the score of 3-6, 7-5, 6-0, 5-2, he was defaulted after
throwing his racquet in anger at a line call and hitting a ballboy.
Koubek said he never intended to strike the youth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm angry with myself that it went this far, but it happened
and now I can't change anything,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Neither can Agassi, and it will be intriguing to see whether
Thursday's defeat is merely a bump in his road or the beginning of
another detour for a man whose career has been defined by peaks and
valleys. As for Kucera, he must be wary of a letdown. And if he has
any doubt about the danger, he should bear in mind what happened to
Dominique Van Roost one day after her tear-filled victory over
Davenport. Facing Spaniard Marta Marrero and leading 6-0, 4-1, she
ran out of energy and accuracy on Thursday and ended up losing in
three sets.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
