<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 18:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2101 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-SENIORS-COLUMN-DOLE-$     06-01 1019
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SENIORS-COLUMN-DOLE-$ADV04-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRIT AND HUMOR MAKE DOLE A HERO TO MANY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, June 4) 
 By FRED BROCK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In some ways, Bob Dole is an unlikely spokesman for older
Americans.
</P>
<P>
   After all, the former Kansas senator was one of 68 Republicans
in the House who voted against the creation of Medicare in 1965,
although he has since supported it. He loathes the idea of retiring
and, at 76, doesn't consider himself old. His most cynical
detractors say he is cashing in on his celebrity status by
accepting money from Pfizer for appearing in ads urging men with
erectile dysfunction to have checkups and, presumably,
prescriptions for Viagra, which Pfizer makes. The ads made him
late-night fodder for Leno and Letterman for months.
</P>
<P>
   But despite all that, and in the wake of his unsuccessful run
for the presidency in 1996, Dole has emerged as a hero to many
older people, regardless of their politics. For them, he has
displayed a rare combination of determination, courage and humor in
the face of severe battlefield wounds suffered in World War II that
left him with a withered right arm. He also has struggled with
serious illnesses, including prostate cancer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I'm a pretty good role model for seniors,'' he said
during a recent interview in his office at Verner, Liipfert,
Berhnard, McPherson &AMP; Hand, the Washington law firm where he is a
special counselor. ``I've had problems and worked through all of
those. I'm getting older, but I've survived. Maybe by speaking out
I can help people.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Mike Mcgee, Pfizer's senior medical adviser, who also sat in
on the interview, said: ``Everyone expected Senator Dole to
disappear after he lost the 1996 election. But what does he do? He
goes public, and with humor and a real smart and engaging
personality.''
</P>
<P>
   Mcgee was referring to Dole's 1998 appearance on CNN's ``Larry
King Live,'' when he disclosed that he had taken part in clinical
trials for Viagra and that it had halted his impotency resulting
from the removal of his cancerous prostate in 1991. Overnight, a
medical condition that had received little attention exploded into
the public's awareness.
</P>
<P>
   ``My wife was a little startled,'' Dole said. ``She didn't know
I was going to say it.''
</P>
<P>
   At first he was a bit testy over the Viagra jokes, but has since
mellowed and concedes that, ``Actually, some of them were pretty
funny.'' Doles revelation on television led to his relationship
with Pfizer. In addition to Viagra-related ads, he also helps the
drug giant with a broader campaign to inform older Americans about
the value of early detection and treatment of diseases.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not so much Viagra,'' Dole said. ``It's the underlying
cause of E.D.''
</P>
<P>
   Early detection usually means drug therapy, which is good for
companies like Pfizer. ``There is a vested interest for Pfizer or
any of the pharmaceutical companies,'' Mcgee said. ``They are very
prejudiced toward prevention.''
</P>
<P>
   In the two years that Pfizer has run its Viagra ads, 7 million
men have received the drug. For every million who asked for Viagra,
it was also discovered that an estimated 30,000 had untreated
diabetes, 140,000 had untreated high blood pressure and 50,000 had
untreated heart disease.
</P>
<P>
   Dole says the fact he is on Pfizer's payroll has not affected
his opinions on issues, including those related to health care.
``I'm still a free citizen; I've never been told I shouldn't
express some opinion,'' he said. ``I don't have any inhibitions.''
</P>
<P>
   He favors a federal program to help low-income people pay for
drugs, but does not think the government should get involved for
people who can afford them on their own.
</P>
<P>
   He thinks the proposal by Gov. George W. Bush of Texas to partly
privatize Social Security by allowing people to invest a portion of
their contributions in the stock market is fine in concept. But he
worries that ``the devil is in the details.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to protect the people who aren't good at investing,''
he said. ``Maybe put the money in savings accounts or CDs or
something.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's proposal ``is not a radical plan,'' he said. ``It's bold,
because for the first time you would change Social Security. It
puts it on the table. People can shoot at it. It's going to be a
big issue.''
</P>
<P>
   He said his proudest accomplishment in the Senate came in 1983,
when he and Daniel Patrick Moynihan, the New York Democrat, helped
lead bipartisan efforts to rescue Social Security. Dole suggested
that he and Moynihan could chair a commission Bush plans to appoint
to work on his Social Security proposal.
</P>
<P>
   He stresses the importance of preventive care and of remaining
engaged. ``I sort of got into a slump in my 50s,'' he said. ``Then
I started to realize how important it is to take care of yourself.
Now I work out on a treadmill. I can't do much with my arms, but I
figured I'd keep my legs strong. I want to be mobile. I've seen
people I thought were old at 50. They don't take care of
themselves. It's so important to stay connected and exercise your
mind and body.''
</P>
<P>
   Dole, tan and trim after losing 12 pounds on the Atkins diet,
hates the idea of retiring. ``Suddenly you wake up and you're
70-some years old,'' he said. ``But I've never thought of myself as
old. To me, old is when you can't function. I go down to Florida.
We stay about three days. I like to get a little sun and then I
want to come home. Some people stay three months, six months. What
do they do?''
</P>
<P>
   Dole says his age _ 73 at the time _ cost him some votes when he
ran for the White House. ``But I've demonstrated I would have lived
out my first term, anyway,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He said everyone had to make his or her own judgment about when
to retire, but he thinks some people overreact to growing old.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess if you really get paranoid you don't buy any new
shirts or shoes,'' he said. ``You think, `Well, I'll never wear
these out.' I guess when you get to be Strom's age, you worry about
room service _ `How long will it be? Thirty minutes?''' He was
referring to Sen. Strom Thurmond of South Carolina, 97.
</P>
</TEXT>
