<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Friday, June 2, 2000, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST
</P>
<P>
   Summery heat will envelop most of the East Coast states Friday,
but a cold front moving east from the Ohio Valley will ensure a
return to seasonable temperatures in the Northeast this weekend.
Afternoon readings will peak in the upper 90s over parts of the
Middle Atlantic states and interior Southeast. The heat and high
humidity will set the stage for a broken band of strong
thunderstorms to form in the midday and afternoon as a cold front
sweeps east. In the wake of the front, northwesterly breezes will
deliver much cooler air to the Middle West.
</P>
<P>
   Thunderstorms with heavy rain will occur from northwestern Texas
to western Oklahoma as moisture-laden air is lifted near a wavering
front. Weak high-level winds will foster slow-moving storms which
will raise the risk of local flooding. Meanwhile, most of the
Southwest will be hot and dry.
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: HURRICANE SEASON
</P>
<P>
   The six-month Atlantic hurricane season began Thursday, but the
most active time in the season is still a few months away. Although
tropical oceans have warmed above the 80 degree temperature
threshold for hurricane development, vigorous winds near 50,000
feet will rip apart most seedling clusters of thunderstorms roaming
the Atlantic. These winds will relax as the summer progresses, with
the heart of hurricane season arriving in the middle of September.
A typical season produces 10 tropical storms, six of which reach
hurricane status with winds of at least 65 knots. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
