<HEADER>
A2113 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      06-01 0844
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     WHOSE RIGHTS RULE IN ADOPTIONS? 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     Commentary  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARIANNE MEANS  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Supreme Court this week declined to block an
Oregon law allowing adult adoptees access to their birth records
without the prior consent of their biological parents.
</P>
<P>
   This may not be the high court's last word on this emotional
issue. But the action freed Oregon to go ahead with an experiment
that a group of biological mothers had tried to legally stop. And
it could eventually eliminate the secrecy that has traditionally
protected the privacy of adoptions throughout this country.
</P>
<P>
   This is a classic case of a clash of individual rights. Whose
are more important?
</P>
<P>
   Adults who have been adopted but have no idea of their ancestry
are understandably curious about their biological roots. And
knowledge about their birth parents can be useful in assessing
hereditary behavioral and disease traits.
</P>
<P>
   But the Oregon law is wickedly unfair to mothers who give up
their babies for adoption. They generally do so for sad and
humiliating but compelling reasons. The babies may be illegitimate,
the result of horrific rape, or simply a financial and emotional
burden that a poor family or teen-age mother cannot assume.
</P>
<P>
   The parents have counted on the presumption _ usually based on a
specific promise from state officials _ that the stigma of an
unwanted pregnancy would not be revived years later by a forced
confrontation with accusatory offspring. Illegitimacy may no longer
be the devastating scandal it used to be, but the decision to make
it public should be the mother's alone.
</P>
<P>
   Some adoptive parents may not object to their adoptee's
fascination with biological roots but some may feel bumped to
second place, with all their years of nurturing reduced to
something unimportant.
</P>
<P>
   Now Oregon is about to plunge into that emotional thicket while
the world watches. The experiment will also challenge the sincerity
of Texas Gov. George W. Bush and other conservatives opposed to
abortion who have been crusading for adoption as an alternative to
ending a pregnancy. If unwed, poor or mentally troubled mothers
carry the fetus to term, what consequences await them later?
</P>
<P>
   Will Bush and company protect their privacy? Who will adopt such
children if they know they may later be forced to deal with
potentially irresponsible birth parents?
</P>
<P>
   Four other states allow adults who have been adopted
unconditional access to their original birth certificates so they
can find their biological parents whether the parents want to meet
them or not. They are Kansas, Tennessee and Alaska; Alabama
approved an unconditional access law last month.
</P>
<P>
   Similar bills are also under consideration in other states,
although across most of the country original birth certificates are
sealed and can be opened only by court order.
</P>
<P>
   Limited access is allowed in 19 states if the birth parents
consent, which seems like a sensible compromise that hurts no one
and can be useful to both parties.
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 6 million Americans are adopted, and there is no
way to know how many adult adoptees have been told about the
circumstances which led to their arrival at their new family. It is
an individual parental decision, and a very private one.
</P>
<P>
   A few years ago open-records advocacy groups began publicly
pressing for access to adoptees' pasts, claiming the right to know
everything trumped the right to privacy. They have a legal and
political advantage over a group of birth mothers who have been
fighting them; the adoptees speak openly before the media while the
mothers have of necessity remained anonymous.
</P>
<P>
   The conflict is explosive on many levels. In some cases, there
may be a happy reunion. Web sites and other commercial registries
try to arrange such reunions.
</P>
<P>
   But anecdotal evidence indicates that often opening old records
meant to be closed creates trouble and turmoil. The mother may have
a cherished civic reputation and a new family that does not know of
her youthful indiscretion. There is unlikely to be any emotional or
cultural bond between mother and child after all those years. In
one notorious case, a black man who was the child of a rape knocked
on the door of his middle-aged white birth mother and sent her into
terrified shock.
</P>
<P>
   Many adoptees say they simply wish to have more information and
are not out to embarrass their birth mothers. But with open records
they can do both.
</P>
<P>
   A Portland lawyer, Franklin Hunsaker, who represented six
biological mothers who fought the Oregon law, said that his clients
were ``scared and even angry that their rights have been ignored.''
</P>
<P>
   If enough women are scared about what is happening, more and
more will choose abortion over adoption. The open-records movement
is so young we don't have proof yet that it encourages abortion.
But common sense says it will.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Marianne Means can be reached at the e-mail address means(at)
hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-01-00 1811EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000601.0262 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 18:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2123 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-MOTHER-JAIL-HNS &LR;      06-01 0765
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOTHER-JAIL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     BOY ABDUCTED BY MOTHER REUNITED WITH HIS FATHER 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By DEMIAN BULWA  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A 10-year-old California boy has been reunited
with his father after an eight-year ordeal that began when the
man's wife allegedly poisoned him with an insecticide-laced
milkshake and fled to Mexico with their son.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest break in the bizarre case _ which has been featured
more than 20 times on the television program ``Unsolved Mysteries''
_ didn't arrive until March 15 when the wife, San Francisco native
Elizabeth Fuentes-Ortiz, was arrested near Guadalajara. She was
brought back to the United States to face charges.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, FBI agents have been working on locating and
bringing back her son, Jonathan.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the police have kept a close eye on Fuentes-Ortiz,
who is at the women's jail in Redwood City.
</P>
<P>
   And Tuesday night, they said, it paid off when San Mateo County
sheriff's deputies at the jail became suspicious when two adults
and a boy arrived and requested an 8 p.m. jailhouse visit.
</P>
<P>
   After the visit, the trio _ Jonathan, his maternal grandmother
and another relative _ were stopped by the Redwood City police. The
grandmother admitted the boy was Jonathan and said he had been
staying at her home in Alameda County for the past week, said
Redwood City Sgt. Kathryn Anderson.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday morning, Gilbert Ortiz, 31, greeted a son who has
become a stranger _ and who may have been told any number of
stories about his father, said Anderson.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson declined to say where Ortiz lived.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I can tell you is that I talked to Gilbert's sister, and
she said the meeting was very nice, but that there were a lot of
emotions involved,'' said Anderson, who has investigated the case
from the start. ``Pretty cool, huh? Certainly this has hugely
affected many lives. And, at this point, it was so important for
the father to see the son. We're just hoping for the best.''
</P>
<P>
   Fuentes-Ortiz, who police said was going by the name Rosa Isela
Negrete, was arrested by the FBI on a federal Unlawful Flight to
Avoid Prosecution warrant signed in 1992. She is charged with
attempting to murder her husband and also will face parental
abduction charges, Anderson said. She is being held in lieu of $1
million bond.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The police say the saga began March 11, 1992, when Fuentes-Ortiz
took lunch _ a McDonald's hamburger and a milkshake _ to her
husband while he was working at Toys R Us in Redwood City. She
allegedly told him the shake was filled with amino acids to help
him build muscles and that it might taste funny.
</P>
<P>
   The shake was spiked with a common insecticide and Ortiz went
into convulsions 10 seconds later in the store's break room,
Anderson said. His heart stopped, and his liver failed, and, before
he lapsed into a coma, he was able to tell the police only that a
friend had provided the concoction.
</P>
<P>
   When he emerged from the coma 11 days later, he filled in the
rest of the story, and the police went to his house to serve a
search warrant and arrest Fuentes-Ortiz. But she had left with
Jonathan, without a trace.
</P>
<P>
   The police still do not have a clear motive in the alleged
poisoning, Anderson said, and Fuentes-Ortiz has declined to give a
statement. Ortiz told detectives in 1992 that his marriage was a
happy one.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson said Ortiz had permanent nerve damage in his feet and
toes and got muscle spasms in his calves that caused him to
stumble. He has little sensitivity in his fingertips and may have
suffered permanent liver and kidney damage.
</P>
<P>
   The police and the FBI tried to track down Jonathan and
Fuentes-Ortiz in the years after the alleged abduction, focusing on
Mexico because of tips from informants and family members, and
chasing down dozens of leads that followed appearances on
``Unsolved Mysteries.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the FBI's Fugitive Task Force in San Francisco
assigned an agent to the case. After a confirmed sighting of
Fuentes-Ortiz, she was arrested at her home in La Barca, Jalisco
state, with the cooperation of local officials. Anderson then asked
the National Center for Missing and Exploited to make a
computer-enhanced photo of what Jonathan would look like at 10
years old, and gave it to deputies at the Women's Correctional
Center, asking them to call her at home if they received a visit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being a mother, I took a leap of faith and figured she would
want to see her child,'' Anderson said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
