<DOCNO> NYT20000601.0263 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 18:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2128 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-GREAT-RACE-COX     06-01 1391
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GREAT-RACE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Forsyth Central students heading west in '39 Ford
 &HT;    By Sandy Amann John
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   An opportunity of a lifetime'' is surely an overused phrase, but
when Forsyth Central High School sophomore Steven Dockery uses it
to describe his plans for the summer, it's hard to accuse him of
exaggerating.
</P>
<P>
   Dockery, three classmates and their teacher, Bill Hembree, will
put 4,000 miles on a 1939 Ford convertible and see the back roads
of America as they become Georgia's first entry in the high school
division of the History Channel's Great Race in June.
</P>
<P>
   Sophomores Matthew Williams and Nick Martin and freshman Travis
O'Dell will share navigation duties with Dockery.
</P>
<P>
   Hembree's interest in the race was fueled last year when the
event _ really a cross-country road rally for vintage cars _
started on the Marietta Square.
</P>
<P>
   The auto service instructor learned the race has a high school
division, the X Cup, to encourage young people to become interested
in vintage cars. He turned to his friends in the Early Ford V-8
Club for help, and member Mike Coggins donated the '39 Ford.
</P>
<P>
   Coggins, a local car collector who owns three of the rare '39
ragtops, shared Hembree's enthusiasm about the Great Race and
decided to lend the car in an effort to ``get kids involved in
older cars,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In return for his generosity, Coggins will share driving duties
with Hembree during the race. Fixing up the convertible and raising
the money needed to cover costs during the rally has been a class
and school project since December.
</P>
<P>
   The Ford _ painted ``coach maroon'' with leather upholstery,
wood-grain dash and a rumble seat _ was in good shape cosmetically,
but it needed a lot of mechanical work.
</P>
<P>
   ``We rebuilt it mechanically so it won't break down,'' Williams
said.
</P>
<P>
   The students pulled the engine and took it apart; it was rebuilt
by a member of the Early Ford V-8 Club. Students redid the
60-year-old wiring from bumper to bumper and worked on the
transmission and brakes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We also had to modify the cooling system so it will run
cooler,'' said O'Dell, pointing out the car will be driven over the
Rockies and through the desert during the 15-day race.
</P>
<P>
   They also fixed up the interior, adding insulation and modern
equipment such as seat belts and turn signals, as required by the
race and state laws along the way.
</P>
<P>
   The owner paid for the parts, Hembree said, and Forsyth Central
students supplied the labor of restoring the convertible. Many
students came to the school's auto shop on holidays or stayed late
to work on the project.
</P>
<P>
   The car is powered by a V-8 ``flathead'' engine, which
originally put out about 85 horsepower, but it ``has been
extensively modified'' to about 125 hp, he said. It's also been
modified to use unleaded fuel; it requires premium unleaded and
gets about 20 mpg.
</P>
<P>
   Along with fixing up the car, Forsyth Central students have had
to raise money to pay for the race. While the History Channel
waives the customary $10,000 entry fee for X Cup contestants, there
are plenty of other costs. Motel rooms, meals and spare parts add
up; Hembree estimates the total at $12,000 to $14,000.
</P>
<P>
   The school raised a few thousand dollars at a car show in
Cumming in May, and students approached friends, family and local
businesses to raise more.
</P>
<P>
   The Great Race moves from town to town on back roads, avoiding
interstates except to enter and leave major cities. The vintage
cars never go more than 55 mph.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll be fording creeks, driving on unimproved roads,''
Hembree said. ``We'll drive through everything: rain, snow. We've
got a convertible, but no air conditioning. It's got a heater, but
we don't know how well it's working.''
</P>
<P>
   Other systems can fail easily, too, so the team will travel with
enough spare parts to fix most emergencies. They'll take an extra
generator, distributor, water and fuel pumps, and parts for the
engine and carburetor, Martin said.
</P>
<P>
   Spare tires are another consideration. Race rules require cars
to use tires from their original era _ no radials. Last year, one
race entry suffered 12 flats.
</P>
<P>
   And the convertible needs an oil change every 1,000 miles
because there's no oil filter.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to practice repairing by the side of the road,''
Martin added. A ``sweep truck'' follows entrants on each leg of the
race and can haul a broken-down car to the next stop, so
participants won't be stranded, but the team is responsible for
repairs.
</P>
<P>
   Two members of the Early Ford V-8 Club will travel along as a
support team. If necessary, they and the three students who don't
have navigation duty the next morning will work through the night
to make repairs and get the convertible on the road again.
</P>
<P>
   There's plenty at stake for doing well in the race. The X Cup
offers $25,000 in scholarship money, which will be divided among
the eight youth teams based on their showing in the race.
</P>
<P>
   The Great Race is a point-to-point rally with teams relying on
an analog speedometer and clock as their only navigation tools.
Hembree's students have met with race veterans and watched an
instructional video on navigation techniques, which they then put
to practice in weekend on-the-road sessions.
</P>
<P>
   To start the race, the students will fly to Boston after
finishing final exams. The Ford will be carted there in a covered
trailer supplied by the Early Ford V-8 Club. During the race, the
car will be garaged in the trailer each night to protect it ``from
the weather and sabotage,'' Dockery said.
</P>
<P>
   While the driver and navigator complete the three or four legs
of the race each day, the other team members will head to the next
town in a Chevrolet Suburban. The teenagers are expected to help
Great Race workers with jobs such as setting up banners and parking
cars as the vintage vehicles take part in festivities in each host
town.
</P>
<P>
   This year, 100 pre-1951 vehicles are competing, the largest
field in the 18-year history of the race, according to Debra Fazio,
a spokeswoman for the History Channel.
</P>
<P>
   The X Cup division is in its fourth year. After crossing the
finish line in Sacramento, Calif., Hembree and his students will
rent a car and head home, stopping at the Grand Canyon, the Alamo,
New Orleans and whatever else interests them.
</P>
<P>
   Between taking the northern route out west and the southern
route back to Georgia, they expect to drive through 23 states.
</P>
<P>
   The '39 Ford will be pulled home in the trailer; the car and
team are scheduled to ride in Cumming's Fourth of July parade.
</P>
<P>
   Plenty of Forsyth Central students were interested in joining
the X Cup team. Hembree settled on four based on criteria including
``discipline, grade-point average and lack of a serious dating
relationship, since we'll be gone for a month.''
</P>
<P>
   Those who make the trip will get an educational experience that
crosses many disciplines, Hembree said, from math skills required
to navigate to history lessons from seeing the country.
</P>
<P>
   They'll improve their social skills as they meet people from all
around the country, and they'll practice writing, because he's
requiring each student to keep a journal.
</P>
<P>
   And being in a race where thousands of people line the streets
to cheer you on is great for building self-esteem, he added.
``Everybody ought to be cheered by thousands at least once in their
life.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Hembree is so sold on the X Cup, he plans to enter
another team from Forsyth Central in 2001, when the race takes off
from Centennial Olympic Park in Atlanta. The final destination has
not been determined, Fazio said.
</P>
<P>
   And next year's students will start from scratch with a
different vintage car, because the team earns points for restoring
a vehicle as well as racing it.
</P>
<P>
   Coggins said he'll probably supply a car again next year.
</P>
<P>
   All four of the students on the team say they've ``grown up
around cars,'' and three of them own vehicles that are older than
they are.
</P>
<P>
   Dockery is restoring a 1966 Chevy Caprice, and O'Dell is working
on a '67 Chevy pickup. Williams drives his red 1970 Ford pickup to
school and is building a motor for a '62 Ford. Martin currently has
a mid-'90s-model vehicle, but he plans to get an old one when he
can afford it.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
