<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AFC-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AFC Enterprises makes organizational changes
 &HT;    By Shelia M. Poole
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AFC Enterprises said Thursday it has merged its international
operations and sales development teams into the domestic operating
companies for its top brands.
</P>
<P>
   International and domestic operations had been separate for
AFC's Church's Chicken, Popeyes Chicken &AMP; Biscuits and Cinnabon
divisions.
</P>
<P>
   As the company expands globally, it makes sense to ``have the
president of the operating company strategically lead the worldwide
operations of their companies,'' said AFC President and Chief
Operating Officer Dick Holbrook. ``The international teams are very
excited about being part of the overall brand team. We think this
will help us accelerate growth and provide better support for our
partners internationally.''
</P>
<P>
   AFC has aggressively mined international markets since 1992. The
company has 605 units overseas and expects to open another 200 by
the end of the year. Top markets include Asia, Central America and
Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Holbrook said the company is still considering going public but
declined to specify a date.
</P>
<P>
   He did not rule out an IPO this year. ``I think the market will
dictate that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Systemwide sales at AFC's 3,400 restaurants, bakeries and cafes
and its wholesale and manufacturing operations increased 10.9
percent in the first quarter to $696.5 million. In addition to the
top three brands, AFC owns Seattle's Best Coffee, Torrefazione
Italia Coffee and Ultrafryer Systems.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
