<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 18:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2133 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-MILLER-SPELLING-HNS &LR;      06-01 0716
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILLER-SPELLING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     LOCAL TEEN WIN THIRD PLACE IN NATIONAL SPELLING BEE  
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By AUSTIN ZALKIN  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Alison Miller, 14, of Niskayuna, N.Y., took third
place in the National Spelling Bee Thursday. Alison, who was
sponsored by the Albany Times-Union, became a crowd favorite with
her spritely and confident spellings.
</P>
<P>
   She received a standing ovation when she bowed out of the
competition in the 12th round.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess I'm just pretty good at (looking) confident,'' Alison
said after the bee. ``I wasn't exactly confident'' inside, she
admitted.
</P>
<P>
   The winner was George Abraham Thampy, 12, a home-school student
from Maryland Heights, Mo., who was competing in his third straight
National Spelling Bee. He correctly spelled ``propaedeutic'' and
``demarche'' for the championship.
</P>
<P>
   George received $10,000 in cash from E.W. Scripps Co., sponsor
of the bee, now in its 73rd year. A week ago, George placed second
in the National Geography Bee in Washington, sponsored by the
National Geographic.
</P>
<P>
   Second place in the Spelling Bee went to Sean Conley, 13, a
home-schooler from San Francisco, who finished ninth in last year's
bee.
</P>
<P>
   Alison is also a home-schooled student.
</P>
<P>
   Her mother and teacher, Mary O'Keefe, said she thought
home-schooled students have an advantage in bees because they have
more time to read and tend to watch less television.
</P>
<P>
   Alison said she watches no more than two hours of television a
month. Her extra study time may have helped her to finish 12th in
the nation in May in the national Mathcounts competition and to
finish among the top 30 in the USA Math Olympiad for high school
students.
</P>
<P>
   Alison's father, Ross Miller, called her ``a remarkable kid.''
</P>
<P>
   She and 109 other spellers had advanced past the first three
rounds on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The rules allow spellers to ask the pronouncer for the language
of origin, the word's definitions, alternate pronunciations and its
use in a sentence in order to help them decipher the word.
</P>
<P>
   Alison _ in a rare display of initiative among spellers _ often
engaged the pronouncer in a dialog, suggesting definitions and word
origins and winning his assent to her versions, before going on to
spell the words correctly.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Alison easily disposed of her first word of the
day, ``quomodo,'' in the fourth round.
</P>
<P>
   She later said she'd seen quomodo in a book of old words.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very excited'' to know the word, she said. ``I'd been
pretty nervous.''
</P>
<P>
   She told the pronouncer she thought quomodo came from a Latin
root, and he said she was correct. Her spelling was flawless.
</P>
<P>
   Alison also knew that her next word, ``parapraxia,'' came from
Greek. Asked to spell ``escritoire'' in the ninth round, she asked
the pronouncer, ``Does that mean a writing desk?''
</P>
<P>
   Answer: Yes.
</P>
<P>
   She then spelled it correctly.
</P>
<P>
   Alison correctly suggested that her 10th round word,
``rouleau,'' was French in origin and that her 12th word,
``venire,'' came from Latin.
</P>
<P>
   But she then misspelled the word as ``veniery'' despite
identifying the root word, and was eliminated from the contest.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I may have seen it before,'' Alison said of venire,
which means a group of people from whom a jury is selected. ``The
pronunciation really didn't register with me.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, Alison moved ahead by correctly spelling ``dengue,''
``mulct,'' ``cloze'' and ``sphingine.''
</P>
<P>
   After asking for the definition of sphingine and being told that
it was defined as resembling a sphinx, Alison let out a knowing
``ahhh'' that led to laughter in the crowd. She quickly spelled the
word and marched happily back to her seat.
</P>
<P>
   She earned $3,000 for winning third place.
</P>
<P>
   Alison, who made it to the third round of the bee in 1998, was
competing in the bee for the last time. Next year she will be
equivalent to a ninth grade student, and will be ineligible.
</P>
<P>
   Alison said she would no longer spend half an hour a night
studying words.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to continue studying spelling,'' she said. ``But
I'm going to continue loving words.''
</P>
<P>
   Alison said she plans to be a writer.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Austin Zalkin can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at
dart(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
