<SLUG> BC-BKC-FLA-COACH-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNIVERSITY OF FLORIDA COACH GIVEN $6 MILLION CONTRACT 
</HEADLINE>
   By ROBBIE ANDREU   
 Gainesville (Fla.) Sun   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DESTIN, Fla. _ The University of Florida reaffirmed its
commitment to basketball and Billy Donovan this week, giving
Donovan a new five-year, $6 million contract that will make him one
of the highest-paid coaches in college basketball.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to build something special with basketball here,
something that will last forever, and obviously we think Billy is
the key to that happening,'' said Jeremy Foley, the University of
Florida athletic director who began negotiating a new deal with
Donovan shortly after the Gators' appearance in the NCAA final in
April.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's important everyone understands this guy is going
to be our basketball coach for a very long time. I think it's
important from a recruiting perspective and a commitment
perspective,'' Foley said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   In only four seasons, Donovan has elevated the Florida program
to an elite level. He led the Gators to the Sweet 16 in 1999, and
this year the team played in the national title game for the first
time in school history.
</P>
<P>
   The new contract will pay Donovan an average of $1.2 million
annually over the next five years, tying him with Kentucky's Tubby
Smith as the highest-paid basketball coach in the Southeastern
Conference.
</P>
<P>
   Donovan becomes the school's second millionaire coach, joining
football coach Steve Spurrier, whose annual salary is close to $2
million, making him one of the highest-paid coaches in all of
football.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most valuable asset in your athletic program are your
coaches,'' Foley said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, I'm thrilled,'' Donovan, 35, said. ``I'm very
fortunate and blessed to be working for an administration and
athletic director like I am here.''
</P>
<P>
   This is the third time in three years Donovan's contract has
been restructured. His salary this past season was about $750,000,
up $300,000 from his salary two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Donovan's assistants also have been given raises.
</P>
<P>
   Donovan said several prominent schools have approached him in
the past couple of years about job opportunities. He said no NBA
teams have contacted him, though.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm committed to the University of Florida,'' he said. ``I'm
driven by the challenge to get back to the national championship
game and driven to try and maintain the program, keep it going the
way it's going right now.''
</P>
<P>
   (The Sun in Gainesville, Fla., is part of the New York Times
Regional Newspaper Group.)  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
