<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 18:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2137 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-BIG-MOMMA-REVIEW-LADN     06-01 0677
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIG-MOMMA-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COPYCAT FILM STILL GARNERS LAUGHS
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Fact box below) 
Our rating: 2 1/2 stars 
By BOB STRAUSS 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Big Momma's House'' has most of what you'd expect from a
summer movie. In fact, you have or soon will see most of what it's
got in other summer movies.
</P>
<P>
   Martin Lawrence stars as a government agent who is a master of
disguise and therefore always yanking amazingly deceptive (to
everyone but the audience) masks off his head just like Tom Cruise
in ``Mission: Impossible.'' He winds up in drag and fat suits, as
Eddie Murphy soon will in the ``Nutty Professor'' sequel.
</P>
<P>
   There's some ultra-gross bathroom humor, a la every other youth
comedy in our boldly advancing new century. Perhaps even more
sickening, Hollywood's latest, sheeplike trend in repulsive
laugh-getting, sloppy tongue kissing, is well-represented here.
</P>
<P>
   All sounds soullessly surefire, doesn't it? Well, it is and it
isn't, but Lawrence's exuberant lead performance and occasional
contributions from a game supporting cast do make for some hearty
howls here and there _ a few of which even rise above the generic
pandering.
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence, who it can be happily reported appears none the worse
for wear after his near-fatal heat stroke last summer, is FBI
specialist Malcolm Turner. With his schleppy partner John
(``Private Parts'' victim Paul Giamatti), Malcolm is assigned to
the case of a vicious escaped bank robber, Terrence Howard's
Lester. Convinced that the killer crook's never-recovered haul is
in the possession of his former girlfriend Sherry (Nia Long),
Malcolm and John stake out the title Georgia home, owned by the
fleeing young woman's cranky, jumbo-size grandmother (stage actress
Ella Mitchell, an extremely good sport by any reckoning).
</P>
<P>
   Sure enough, the feds intercept a phone call indicating that
Sherry and her young son, Trent (Jascha Washington), will soon be
arriving at BMH. Problem is, Big Momma has already taken off for an
indefinite period to help a friend in need. So Malcolm breaks out
the fat suit, hoping to trick the long-estranged granddaughter into
giving up the loot and, hopefully, Lester. Of course, Malcolm
doesn't figure that Sherry might be an innocent dupe _ or that
he'll fall hard for her.
</P>
<P>
   You can imagine some of the jokes: masks peeling at inopportune
moments, gargantuan simulations of feminine anatomy with travel
agendas all their own, smitten Malcolm trying to control himself
under all that latex while Sherry blithely makes herself intimately
at home.
</P>
<P>
   But in the film's wilder moments, when Malcolm is expected to
behave like Big Momma without a clue as to what the situation calls
for, Lawrence's vibrant comedic energy blows the roof off the
house. Guess what? Big Momma's a midwife, and the time comes, as it
inevitably will, to deliver. He/she's picked upon to give the
Sunday service witness, and you just know Malcolm hasn't been
inside a church since childhood. He does know, however, exactly
what to do with a bullying self-defense instructor who revels in
brutalizing his elderly students.
</P>
<P>
   The director is Raja Gosnell, a former film editor who last
helmed the astonishingly synthetic Drew Barrymore comedy ``Never
Been Kissed.'' ``Big Momma's'' is certainly more contrived than
that one, and its by-the-book heartwarming moments _ Lawrence, in
more than one false persona, naturally bonds like crazy with the
fatherless Trent _ are just as hokey.
</P>
<P>
   But despite that and its incessant raiding of the summer comedy
gag shelf, this undeniably is also a ``House'' of some genuine,
enjoyable mirth. &QL; 
____ &QL; 
The film: ``Big Momma's House'' (PG-13; language, violence,
nudity). &QL; 
The stars: Martin Lawrence, Nia Long, Paul Giamatti, Jascha
Washington, Terrence Howard, Ella Mitchell. &QL; 
Behind the scenes: Directed by Raja Gosnell. Written by Darryl
Quarles and Don Rhymer. Produced by David T. Friendly and Michael
Green. Released by 20th Century Fox. &QL; 
Running time: One hour, 47 minutes. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
