<HEADER>
A2145 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-CLINTON-0602-COX     06-01 1128
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-0602-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLINTON WARNED BY GERMAN LEADER ON BUILDING MISSILE DEFENSE
SYSTEM
 &HT;    (800&AMP;ADD)
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (w) Washington categories.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN _ President Clinton got a blunt reminder here Thursday of
European unease over a proposed U.S. missile defense system, when
German Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder warned publicly that such
weaponry might prompt Russia to boost its nuclear arsenal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to be very careful that any such project does not
re-trigger the process of a renewed arms race,'' Schroeder told
reporters through a translator, with Clinton standing at his side.
</P>
<P>
   Schroeder made his remarks following a meeting with Clinton that
focused largely on Russia and the proposed national missile defense
(NMD) system, which, if deployed, would be designed to protect the
United States from an incoming ballistic missile attack.
</P>
<P>
   White House officials have cast the system as protection against
attack by a rogue state, such as North Korea, or even a
sophisticated terrorist group.
</P>
<P>
   Officials in Moscow have expressed concern, however, that such a
system could upset the balance of strategic power between the
United States and Russia, which together possess more than 80
percent of the world's nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Those fears have been echoed this week in France and elsewhere
across Europe, which suffered two major wars in the last century
and sat on the fault line of a half-century of Cold War tension.
</P>
<P>
   Schroeder said he expressed his ``concerns'' about that directly
to Clinton, who arrived here late Thursday on the second leg of a
week-long swing through Europe, Russia and Ukraine.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton travels Friday to the German town of Aachen, a
crossroads of European culture for 12 centuries. There, Clinton
will become the first American president to receive the prestigious
Charlemagne Award, a tribute to his efforts to end fighting in the
Balkans, scene of Europe's bloodiest conflict since World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is weighing whether to build a limited NMD system that,
proponents claim, would be able to intercept and destroy one or a
few ballistic missiles fired at the United States from across the
Pacific Ocean.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon plans to test the system in July then advise
Clinton on its projected cost and effectiveness. It would take four
or five years to put into place.
</P>
<P>
   A decision from Clinton isn't expected until the fall. The issue
is front-and-center on the agenda for talks in Moscow this weekend,
however, between Clinton and Russian President Vladimir Putin, who
opposes the system.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton did not respond to Schroeder's remarks in public. During
his meeting, however, Clinton sought to assure the German leader
that the ballistic shield under consideration in Washington would
pose no strategic threat to Russia.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a system that is not directed against Russia,''
Clinton's national security adviser, Samuel Berger, told reporters
here. ``This is a system that is directed at Saddam Hussein or
North Korea or others who may acquire, or who are acquiring,
long-range missiles.''
</P>
<P>
   Further, said Berger, the administration wants to integrate any
NMD into the existing global arms control regime, specifically
through amendments to the Anti Ballistic Missile (ABM) treaty inked
between Russia and the United States in 1972. That treaty restricts
missile shields such as the one that Clinton is considering, on the
grounds that such defenses have the potential to fuel arms
competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is our very strong preference to proceed, if the president
so decides, in the context of the arms control regime,'' said
Berger, adding that Clinton had stressed that point during his
90-minute meeting with Schroeder. ``We are proceeding with care,
and with deliberation to all the dimensions of this.''
</P>
<P>
   Berger said Clinton would stress similar points to Putin when
the president visits Moscow Saturday night (Moscow time) through
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important that President Putin hear from President
Clinton how we see the threat, how we see this system, how we don't
see it as a threat against Russia.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Thursday, Clinton wrapped up a three-day visit to Lisbon
by meeting with Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton emerged from the meeting saying that Barak and
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat must ``do things that they have
not done in the past,'' if they are to meet a Sept. 13 target for
completing negotiations aimed at ending 50 years of war and enmity
between Arabs and Jews.
</P>
<P>
   With time slipping away on his hopes for brokering a
comprehensive Middle East peace accord, Clinton stressed that both
Barak and Arafat must seize ``the real urgency of this moment to
actually get back on the timetable and complete the work that has
to be done.''
</P>
<P>
   Hoping to lay the groundwork for a Camp David-style peace
summit, Clinton ordered Secretary of State Madeleine Albright to
travel to the region and meet separately with both leaders next
week.
</P>
<P>
   And, said Clinton, he would meet in Washington with Arafat ``as
quickly as I can.''
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Despite the tough going, Clinton said he remained hopeful that
Israelis and Palestinians could meet the Sept. 13 target.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still convinced that they have the courage and the vision
and the ability to do this,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton reiterated his earlier belief that momentum for peace is
building, aided, if also complicated, by Israel's surprise
withdrawal last week from southern Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   Despite accusations from both sides Thursday of foot-dragging in
negotiations, Clinton hopes to pull Arafat and Barak together for a
face-to-face summit well before that to nail down a so-called
framework agreement, or road map toward an overarching peace
accord.
</P>
<P>
   Compromise is needed from both leaders, though, even to set the
stage for a summit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both leaders know, from me and they know from their own
experience, that they now have to be prepared to make an intense
effort,'' Clinton said, ``and to do things that they have not done
in the past, with real courage and vision, if we're going to
actually get a framework agreement that deals with the outstanding
issues.''
</P>
<P>
   After decades of conflict and years of off and on peace talks,
Israel and its Palestinian foes are down to the most difficult
issues dividing them, including the question of Palestinian
statehood, the future of Jerusalem _ claimed by both sides _ and
the right of Palestinian refugees to return to Israeli-controlled
lands.
</P>
<P>
   (Bob Deans' E-mail address is: bobdeans(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
