<P>
   LEBANON-REFUGEES (Doheria) _ With the Israeli pullback from
south Lebanon, hope for Palestinian refugees to return to their
ancestral homeland has been rekindled. By Charles Sennott. 1,300
words.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-WALL (Jerusalem) _ Ultra-Orthodox parliamentarians win
initial support for a bill setting a seven-year jail term for women
who wear prayer shawls and read from Torah scrolls at the Western
Wall, Judaism's holiest site. By Aliza Marus. 700 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICS (p) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   LAZIO-CAMPAIGN (Binghamton, N.Y.) _ Listen to Rick Lazio laying
out his beliefs before several hundred supporters in this upstate
town, and if you didn't know better, you might think he was the
Democratic candidate for U.S. Senate instead of the Republican one.
By Fred Kaplan. 800 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL (a) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ELIAN-COURT (Atlanta _ A federal appeals court denies an asylum
hearing for Elian Gonzalez, a ruling that could send the 6-year-old
boy back to Cuba with his father within weeks. By Bob Hohler. 1,000
words.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-DEATH-DNA (Undated) -- Governor George W. Bush's expected
decision to grant a stay of execution to a convicted child rapist
and murderer would be the most striking proof yet of how advances
in DNA technology are shaking the longstanding national consensus
on crime and punishment and the death penalty. By John Aloysius
Farrell. 1,100 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL (f) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BOSTON-AIRLINES (Boston) _ The city's lucrative mix of business
and leisure passengers, combined with a healthy population and
robust economy, have the airlines battling to become the dominant
carrier here. By Matthew Brelis. 1,400 words.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-FUTURE (Cambridge, Mass.) _ Urban-planning experts at a
Harvard University Conference on the Internet and Society say that
the move of businesses away from cities _ a move the Internet helps
make possible _ will put more stress on natural resources in
suburbs and rural areas. By Peter Howe.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SPORTS (s) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TEN-FRENCH (Paris) _ Top seed and defending champion Andre
Agassi, hobbled by a blister, loses to Karol Kucera at the French
Open. By Bud Collins.
</P>
<P>
   BKN-LAKERS (Portland) _ The All-NBA teams came out this week,
sending this whacky Western Conference Final back here for a sixth
game Friday night. By Peter May.
</P>
<P>
   FBN-PATRIOTS (Foxborough, Mass.) -- Though preferring to sign a
new deal with the Patriots, wide receiver Terry Glenn says he won't
be a holdout. By Nick Cafardo.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The Boston Globe &LR;  &QC;
