<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 18:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2151 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a BC-ISRAEL-ILLUSIONS-OPED     06-01 0956
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-ILLUSIONS-OPED-IHT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISRAEL'S WITHDRAWAL FROM LEBANON: THE END OF ILLUSIONS  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Commentary)   (This 700-word ``separate-buy'' commentary is from the
International Herald Tribune.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: To broaden your newspaper's borders _ and readers'
horizons _ the New York Times Syndicate is pleased to offer you the
following article from the renowned International Herald
Tribune.)  
 &HT;    
 (The highly respected IHT delivers a distinctly international
perspective on the news (six times weekly) from the heart of
Europe, Paris.)  
 &HT;    
 (To publish this IHT article, it must be purchased from the New
York Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If you prefer, her e-mail
address is weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert,
please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This op-ed has been transmitted twice _ into the
``k'' commentary news and ``a'' general news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By ABRAHAM RABINOVICH  
 c.2000 International Herald Tribune  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ In its hasty withdrawal from Lebanon last week,
Israel may have left behind a major casualty _ its deterrent image.
</P>
<P>
   It was as if a grinning gunslinger in a Clint Eastwood film
confronts the hero and spits in his face. Without so much as a
``make my day,'' Eastwood draws _ his handkerchief and dabs his
cheek. He then walks away, wordlessly acknowledging that he had
trespassed on the gunslinger's turf.
</P>
<P>
   It is not an ending Eastwood fans would find satisfactory, and
Israelis don't like it either. But they are willing to live with it
as long as quiet prevails along their northern border.
</P>
<P>
   The critical question is whether Israel's enemies will regard
its withdrawal from occupied land as a step towards regional peace
or an indication that Israel is no longer invincible.
</P>
<P>
   Acknowledgement of Israel's military power is at the base of the
Middle East peace process. Although continuing to regard the Jewish
state as a foreign element and a usurper of Arab land, the Arab
world decided after several wars that Israel could not be defeated
and that they would have to come to terms with it.
</P>
<P>
   Second thoughts induced by Hezbollah's success could lead to
dangerous confrontations. In the past week, large sections of the
Arab media have begun to portray Israel as a paper tiger, and
Hezbollah has pointedly called on the Palestinians to follow in its
path.
</P>
<P>
   It is a reasonable assumption that Palestinian militants _ and
others in the Arab world _ are right now absorbing the implications
of what they perceive as the routing of Israel's vaunted army by a
determined force of guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
   A leading Jordanian journalist told an Israeli colleague several
years ago that what had finally convinced him that the Arabs would
have to recognize the Jewish state was Israel's siege of Beirut in
1982.
</P>
<P>
   For three months, Israel pounded the city with aircraft and
artillery in an effort to pry the PLO from there. Sometimes an
entire apartment building would be leveled with a ``smart'' bomb in
an effort to get at Yasser Arafat.
</P>
<P>
   The remorselessness of the Israeli attack in the face of world
condemnation had convinced him, said the journalist, that Israel
would do whatever it thought it had to do in order to survive.
</P>
<P>
   Given that determination and Israel's proven military prowess,
the journalist concluded that the best option available to the
Arabs was to make a reasonable peace.
</P>
<P>
   However, it was war weariness, not determination, that Israel
has projected in recent years over Lebanon. A peace movement, led
by mothers of army-age sons, gave increasing currency to the idea
of pulling out.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Ehud Barak made it a central part of his election
platform last year. Israel was no longer willing to accept an
average of 25 deaths a year to sustain its defense buffer in South
Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   In the euphoria induced by Hezbollah's impressive performance,
however, there has been a distortion of perspective.
</P>
<P>
   The loss of Israel's will to fight in Lebanon was due not just
to the casualties it suffered but to a belief by most Israelis that
they were indeed an occupying power and had no business remaining
in Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   The entire fighting arm of Hezbollah is believed by Israeli
experts to number only around 500. In the 1973 Yom Kippur War,
Israel was caught flat-footed by a surprise attack launched by
Egypt and Syria, whose armies numbered in the hundreds of
thousands.
</P>
<P>
   In a stunning battlefield recovery, Israel defeated both armies
as well as other Arab forces that joined them and showed itself
willing to take the casualties necessary for victory.
</P>
<P>
   The 2,500 fatalities it suffered in less than three weeks were
proportionally several times higher than the price paid by the
United States in Vietnam in a decade.
</P>
<P>
   If threatened on its home ground, Israel will do what it has to
do to survive. Along with other strategic considerations, the
humiliating haste of the Lebanese pullout will likely encourage it
to factor in its deterrent image the next time it is challenged to
a shoot-out. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITOR'S NOTE: Abraham Rabinovich is a Jerusalem-based
journalist.) &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this 700-word op-ed from the International Herald
Tribune, it must be purchased from the New York Times Syndicate's
sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or fax her at
732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is: weyded(at)nytimes.com. If
unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at
816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
