A2154 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a BC-NASTY-AIR-PLANES-IHT-     06-01 0832
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NASTY-AIR-PLANES-IHT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN AIR OF DANGER LURKS AT 36,000 FEET: INFLIGHT GERMS  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Travel, Health Editors)   (This 600-word ``separate-buy'' article is from the International
Herald Tribune.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: To broaden your newspaper's borders _ and readers'
horizons _ the New York Times Syndicate is pleased to offer you the
following article from the renowned International Herald
Tribune.)  
 &HT;    
 (The highly respected IHT delivers a distinctly international
perspective on the news (six times weekly) from the heart of
Europe, Paris.)  
 &HT;    
 (To publish this IHT article, it must be purchased from the New
York Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If you prefer, her e-mail
address is weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert,
please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``t'' travel news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By ROGER COLLIS  
 c.2000 International Herald Tribune  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   A question from Shirley Gur in Shpinoza, Israel: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   QUESTION: A while ago, much was being discussed about the risk
of picking up bugs or viruses on flights. I even read somewhere
that air-conditioning systems are not good for passengers and that
airlines shut them down to save fuel and to sedate passengers to
relax them during the flight.
</P>
<P>
   Within hours of returning from London, I came down with a bad
throat infection. One friend arrived back from Barbados with a
raging stomach upset, while others have had respiratory problems.
</P>
<P>
   Has the subject been put to sleep, so to speak, for lack of
evidence?
</P>
<P>
   ANSWER: No. Health in the air is of growing concern to
travelers, pilots, cabin crews and regulatory authorities.
</P>
<P>
   At 30,000 feet (9,150 meters) the air in a plane has to be
artificially created. At that altitude, the cabin is pressurized to
8,000 feet, the equivalent of sitting on top of a mountain.
(Outside air is too cold and thin for us to breathe.)
</P>
<P>
   Low air pressure makes your heart and lungs work harder. Low air
pressure can be dangerous for people prone to strokes or heart
disease.
</P>
<P>
   John Peppin, a reader in Torquay, England, reports having
``succumbed to unstable angina eight days after a flight of four
and a half hours'' and cites rumors that airlines reduce cabin
pressure to 10,000 to 12,000 feet, an assertion that he says is
vigorously denied by the British Airline Pilots Association.
</P>
<P>
   Modern aircraft supply a mix of fresh and recirculated air in
the cabin, with the change rate as low as one every 10 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Airlines can save up to 2 percent of fuel costs, representing
millions of dollars for a large carrier, by cutting in half the
quantity of air they bring into the cabin _ thereby recirculating
50 percent of cabin air. Turning off an air-conditioning pack not
only saves fuel but reduces noise in the cabin.
</P>
<P>
   Airlines routinely instruct pilots to do this. None of the
airlines provide data on how much air is recirculated. There are no
international standards on contaminants or air quality except for
levels of carbon monoxide, ozone and carbon dioxide.
</P>
<P>
   Quality of air in the cabin also depends on the efficiency of
catalytic air filters or how often they are changed. The new
generation of filters are said to remove at least 99.7 percent of
air particles 0.3 microns in size, which includes large bacteria
but excludes viruses.
</P>
<P>
   Worries are being expressed about the risk of catching serious
airborne diseases, such as influenza, bronchitis and tuberculosis.
</P>
<P>
   But evidence tends to be circumstantial due to lack of research
and the difficulty of tracking passengers after the flight and an
incubation period of three to four days: Passengers don't always
link their illness with a particular trip.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Dawood, a London physician and the editor of
``Travelers' Health,'' says that while viruses and other airborne
diseases can be spread in any confined space, what makes it worse
in the air is the tendency of nasal passages to dry out in the
environment of the aircraft cabin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Normally, the first line of defense in airborne disease is the
thin film of moisture that coats the nasal passages in which there
are enzymes and layers of hairy `cilia' that protect you.
</P>
<P>
   ``My tip is to remain well hydrated and to use a nasal saline
spray. Squirt it into your nostrils and inhale to keep things
moist.'' &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this 600-word article from the International Herald
Tribune, it must be purchased from the New York Times Syndicate's
sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or fax her at
732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is: weyded(at)nytimes.com. If
unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at
816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
