   &UR; AN AIR OF DANGER LURKS AT 36,000 FEET: INFLIGHT GERMS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NASTY-AIR-PLANES-IHT &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (UNDATED)_ Have you recently traveled somewhere and returned
with an unwelcome souvenir: a virus or ``bug?'' Well, you're not
alone. Travelers increasingly complain about getting sick from air
travel. Although the airlines deny it, they are cutting back on the
amount of recirculated air in the planes' cabins to save on fuel
costs and to sedate passengers....By Roger Collis, International
Herald Tribune. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Travel, Health Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (600 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ISRAEL'S WITHDRAWAL FROM LEBANON: THE END OF ILLUSIONS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ISRAEL-ILLUSIONS-OPED-IHT &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ In its hasty withdrawal from southern Lebanon last
week, Israel may have left behind a major casualty _ its deterrent
image. The critical question is whether Israel's enemies will
regard its withdrawal from occupied land as a step towards regional
peace or an indication that Israel is no longer invincible. Much
rests on the distinction...By Abraham Rabinovich, International
Herald Tribune &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Commentary) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (700 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ARAFAT FIGHTS `LOSER' IMAGE AFTER HEZBOLLAH'S VICTORY &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ARAFAT-EMBARRASSED-INDEPENDENT &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ A week after Israel's troops beat a hasty retreat
from Lebanon, Yasser Arafat has publicly acknowledged that he faces
growing political pressure to emulate the success of Hezbollah's
guerrilla forces. ``Hezbollah are being portrayed as heroes in the
Arab world, while the Palestinians look like losers,'' he
reportedly told an Israeli minister at a meeting in the West Bank.
``My situation is not simple,'' Arafat added. ``The pressure being
applied on me is coming from every direction.''...By Phil Reeves,
The Independent of London &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (750 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HEZBOLLAH BRINGS REVENGE ON `COLLABORATORS' &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; `FINKS'-HEZBOLLAH-INDEPENDENT-FISK &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TAIBE, SOUTHERN LEBANON _ In the government hospital in Nabatea,
Abbas Koussan's battered face and body are a mark of shame on his
country; on the Hezbollah's militia who liberated his village of
Taibe, on the U.N. troops who failed to protect him, on the
government security men who refused him permission to tell his
story even in his hospital bed, on the Israelis who tried to
blackmail him into collaboration. And on his neighbors in the
pretty little Shiite Muslim hamlet, some of whom _ convinced that
he was a collaborator _ beat Abbas Koussan insensible after looting
his little shop. Why could Hezbollah not stop such acts of anarchy
in a village which they controlled?...By Robert Fisk, The
Independent of London &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (875 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LAS VEGAS PROVIDES REFUGE FOR DISSIDENT WRITERS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ASYLUM-VEGAS-INDEPENDENT &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Las Vegas has a colorful history of offering
refuge _ to scam artists, mobsters, racketeers and the criminally
insane, for a start. Perhaps that explains why the city has been so
ready to offer a helping hand to an altogether different category
of fugitive: writers under threat from oppressive foreign
governments. Las Vegas has just been named North America's first
``City of Asylum'' _ the political sort of asylum, that is _ under
a program run by the International Parliament of Writers...By
Andrew Gumbel, The Independent of London &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (425 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A LAPTOP YOU CAN WEAR? &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WEARABLE-LAPTOP-INDEPENDENT &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ You've heard of a laptop keyboard but how about
making your lap into a keyboard? Wait a year or so:
Electrotextiles, a British company, has developed a way of
including conductive fibers in cloth to produce a keyboard that can
be rolled up or even knitted into clothes, with the bonus of ties
that can act as a mouse...By Charles Arthur, The Independent of
London &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (375 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; U.N. FORCES SHOULD BE GIVEN TOOLS TO DO THE JOB &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; KOFI-WAKES-UP-OPED-INDEPENDENT &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ He is right, of course. It is just a shame that it
took so long for the obvious to be said out loud. In an exclusive
interview with The Independent, Kofi Annan, the United Nations'
secretary general, pointed to the undeniable fact that, too often,
U.N. troops need a tougher mandate and better hardware...By The
Editorial Board of The Independent &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (EDITORIAL) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (450 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MOST OF WORLD'S LANGUAGES `WILL VANISH BY 2100' &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DYING-LANGUAGES-INDEPENDENT &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ Most of the world's 6,000-plus languages will have
died out by the end of the century, experts predicted Monday.
Linguists issued fresh warnings about the perilous position of the
thousands of languages spoken mainly by adults but increasingly
rarely by their children and grandchildren. They said the
continuing drive for the young to communicate in one of the three
most popular tongues _ English, Spanish or Mandarin _ threatens to
destroy a key ingredient of humanity's cultural heritage...By Steve
Connor, The Independent of London &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (625 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SPERM BECOME CASUALTIES OF THE ROAD &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SPERM-DRIVERS-INDEPENDENT &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ Driving for long periods can cause more than frayed
nerves. Scientists have discovered sitting behind the wheel can
also result in falling sperm counts. The testicles of male drivers
heat up enough to have a direct impact on sperm production, and
researchers believe the findings explain why the wives of taxi and
truck drivers often find it more difficult to conceive than the
partners of casual drivers...By Steve Connor, The Independent of
London &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (300 words) &QL;   &LR;  &QL; 
