<SLUG> BC-AZR-BUDGET-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 
The Arizona Republic plans to move the following stories for use by
clients of the NYTimes News Service for FRIDAY, JUNE 2. If you have
any questions, please call the Republic News Desk at (602)
444-8286.
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
SWAYZE (Undated) - Actor Patrick Swayze was uninjured after he was
forced to make an emergency landing Thursday on a dirt road near
Prescott Valley when his twin-engine Cessna had mechanical
problems. By REPUBLIC STAFF. Story will move in the `A` and `E`
categories. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
UNIVERSITY (Phoenix) - A group of religious men who already operate
seven universities are looking to build Arizona's first four-year
Catholic University. The state has no parochial college now despite
750,000 Catholics in the area. `Phoenix is far and away the largest
city in the country without a Catholic university, ` said Msgr.
Edward Ryle, director of the Arizona Catholic Conference. If
officials find the interest and funding, the college could open its
doors in fall 2002. By KELLY PEARCE. Story will move in the `A`
category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
GARFIELD (Phoenix) - For years, officials have poured money into
Phoenix's Garfield neighborhood in a continuing effort to rid it of
crime and blight. What's happened? Do these `weed and seed`
programs work? By BILL HERMANN. Story will move in the `A`
category. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
