<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 19:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2165 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-CONLEY-SPELLING-3RDLD     06-01 0809
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONLEY-SPELLING-3RDLD-WRITETHRU-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     SEAN CONLEY PLACES SECOND IN NATIONAL SPELLING BEE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (EDS: New throughout.)  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JUDY HOLLAND  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Sean Conley, a methodical and calm seventh-grader
from Newark, Calif., seized second place in the 73rd National
Spelling Bee Thursday, losing in the 14th round to another contest
veteran whom he identified from the start as his toughest
competition.
</P>
<P>
   The winner's trophy went to George Abraham Thampy of Maryland
Heights, Mo., who correctly spelled demarche _ a step or maneuver _
to win the 2000 Scripps Howard National Spelling Bee.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, there was barely a whisper in the crowded ballroom
of the Grand Hyatt Hotel when it came down to a duel between Sean
and George. Both were 12 years old, schooled at home and recognized
each other from last year when Sean tied for 9th place at the
national bee and George tied for 3rd.
</P>
<P>
   The San Francisco Examiner sponsored Sean.
</P>
<P>
   The two-speller duel lasted only one round until Sean stumbled
on ``apotropaic'' _ safeguarding against evil.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd fell silent as he repeated it several times. He asked
about the word's origins. There was a long pause.
</P>
<P>
   Using his index finger, he traced out the letters on the back of
the yellow cardboard No. 20 tag around his neck. (No pens or
pencils are allowed.)
</P>
<P>
   Finally, he uttered: A-P-O-T-R-Y-P-A-I-C. The dreaded bell
clanged, sounding a mistake.
</P>
<P>
   His rival George then had to spell ``propaedeutic,'' which means
preparatory study or instruction. George nailed it to move ahead of
Sean.
</P>
<P>
   To clinch victory, George then had to spell another word
correctly _ and ``demarche'' gave him the first place prize.
</P>
<P>
   Holding the winner's trophy under the bright lights of cameras,
George said he would share the $10,000 prize with his parents and
said he hopes to study medicine. He said he prayed for help at the
end and that God came through.
</P>
<P>
   Sean put the best spin on his second place showing, claiming
that he was relieved that, as runner-up, he would avoid scores of
interviews on talk shows that tend to make him nervous.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not that disappointed,'' Sean said. ``I've still got
$5,000.''
</P>
<P>
   Sean said he knew all along that George ``was the competition.''
</P>
<P>
   The 248 spellers that began on Wednesday were winnowed down to
only Sean and George on the stage. At that point, Sean said later,
``I was pretty sure I would lose because George was so good.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He just knew every single word. He must have studied pretty
much all his spare time.''
</P>
<P>
   Mike Conley, Sean's father, said he and his wife knew ``from the
moment we walked into this place that George was the man to beat.
He's a machine. He's very cool.''
</P>
<P>
   Sean said once the tougher words started, he began tracing out
the letters on his number tag because ``I wanted to see what looked
best.''
</P>
<P>
   Before stumbling on ``apotropaic,'' he correctly spelled
``Mackinaw,'' ``ferriferous,'' ``luftmensch,'' ``vivace,''
``ramage,'' ``morceau,'' ``gourami,'' ``nonpareil,'' ``lucifugous''
and ``phrontistery.''
</P>
<P>
   His mother Bry Conley said Sean had his share of luck, including
getting the word ``luftmensch,'' a German word that means dreamer
and that he knew because she majored in the language at the
University of New Mexico and has tutored him in German.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Conley also said he had no trouble with ``vivace,'' which
means in a brisk manner, because Sean has seen it on sheet music
when playing the piano. ``It makes all those grumblings worth it,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   She said she also ``had a pretty good feeling it would come down
to him and George.''
</P>
<P>
   Sean, who hopes to start college at 16, ``has always loved
numbers and letters,'' said his mother.
</P>
<P>
   The family belongs to Tri-City Homeschoolers, where she says
Sean ``is pretty much working independently.'' She said they
decided to teach Sean at home ``because he was very advanced
academically and was shy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We were afraid he would be bored and teased,'' she said.
``This has allowed him the freedom in planning his schedule.''
</P>
<P>
   Alex J. Cameron, the word pronouncer for the bee for 20 years
who is also chairman of the English department at the University of
Dayton in Ohio, said the best spellers share a character trait.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can stand on stage with the lights on and the microphone
on and remember,'' Cameron said.
</P>
<P>
   Cameron added he has seen wild tears of losers followed by wild
laughter.
</P>
<P>
   ``For kids this bright to fail in public, it's something that
doesn't happen very often,'' he said. ``It's good for them to see
that when they make a mistake, the world goes on and their parents
still love them.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL; (Judy Holland can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address judy &LR; hearstdc.com).
</P>
</TEXT>
