</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-GOLF-750&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROMOTERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 JAPAN'S GOLF BOOM OF THE '80s ENDING IN DISASTER FOR BANKS AND By HOWARD W. FRENCH    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ During the economic boom in the 1980s, few things
reflected this country's exploding wealth better than its sudden
madness for golf.
</P>
<P>
   In a nation of badly overcrowded cities and itsy-bitsy homes,
wide, lush fairways were constructed at such a clip that by the end
of the decade there were 2,400 courses, covering an area roughly
triple the size of Tokyo itself. Lavish clubhouses included
expensive artwork from masters like Chagall and Monet and solid
gold fixtures. Bankers and promoters were financing memberships _
for up to $200,000 each _ as investments that they predicted would
take off like a well-hit tee shot.
</P>
<P>
   But the golf club investment craze here ran into trouble when
Japan's economic bubble burst 10 years ago. Personal bankruptcies
rose, the value of club memberships fell and many courses were
immediately in a financial hole.
</P>
<P>
   Now, at least 1,700 of the country's golf courses are either
bankrupt or in financial trouble, according to industry estimates.
And the bankers and other lenders who financed the courses and the
individual memberships are desperately trying to contain one of the
the economy's biggest problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is very difficult to exactly calculate the extent of the
bad loan problem in this country,'' said Takehito Sasaki, managing
director at PricewaterhouseCoopers, Japan. ``Some people estimate
it at $1.2 trillion. Maybe 20 percent of that is related to the
golf course crisis.''
</P>
<P>
   Included in that is an estimated $95 billion in
non-interest-bearing security deposits on club memberships that are
tied up in distressed clubs _ more than the gross domestic product
of Ireland or Singapore or New Zealand.
</P>
<P>
   Large numbers of club memberships are now maturing for the first
time, meaning that subscribers may demand reimbursement from the
clubs, and many Japanese are realizing for the first time the
extent of their losses. In short, the clubs have little or nothing
to pay them.
</P>
<P>
   The crisis over golf course debt comes at a time when Japan is
having some success in whittling down other types of unconventional
debt, like loans to so-called love hotels, and to Pachinko parlors,
both of which were linked to the country's speculative boom in the
1980s. Debt in both industries has been sold recently at steep
discounts to investment banks in the United States and elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Japan's golf crisis is coming to a head right now for reasons
that have to do with the Ponzi scheme nature of the business, and
the almost lemming-like zeal with which ordinary Japanese ponied up
to become players. With the eager encouragement of banks that were
lending both to golfers and developers, memberships were sold as
investments with the promise that they could be cashed in after 10
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our orders were to market financial products, and to find as
many customers as possible,'' said one former bank employee, who
insisted on anonymity. ``We were not encouraged to ask many
questions.''
</P>
<P>
   The slick young agents who were peddling these ``investments,''
were quick to add that it would be foolish to cash in, because the
memberships could always be sold to others at a rich profit.
</P>
<P>
   With Japan's economy looking as if it were enjoying an endless
ascent, middle-class people took out loans to ``invest'' in club
memberships, which sold anywhere from $50,000 to $200,000,
convinced that their memberships would double or triple in value _
as they did for a time _ every two or three years. Typically, the
same banks that were lending to golf course developers were
promoting loans linked to their clubs, without the slightest
disclosure of conflict of interest.
</P>
<P>
   ``Banks were lending as much as 20 million yen to their
customers to get them to become members of golf courses,'' said
Seijiro Takayama, a lawyer who has represented many people who have
lost their fortunes in memberships that have turned worthless, but
with little success. ``The banks were not reporting to the
investors about the state of the clubs, nor were they inspecting
these individuals' finances either.''
</P>
<P>
   Shuichi Yamashita, an official of the Golf Management Research
Institute, a consulting company. said: ``There were cases where
really bad people deliberately swindled people. But that is only
part of it. This is the failure of people who turned the golf
business into a money making machine. There are many companies who
saw that this area is very profitable, and advanced into it even
though they knew little about this field. There were all kind of
consultants urging people into the business as a source of easy
profits.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
