<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000601.0290 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 19:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2167 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-JAPAN-GOLF-2NDTAKE-NY     06-01 0438
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-GOLF-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 TOKYO: easy profits.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   This kind of misfortune has led to a new boom in at least two
sectors: loan collecting, and the protection racket. Takayama said
that Japanese yakuza, or organized crime groups, were offering
their services to golf club members who had lost their personal
savings in the debacle. Playing the other side of the street too,
sometimes simultaneously, the gangsters have also been employed by
golf clubs' management to scare members out of filing lawsuits to
recover their investments.
</P>
<P>
   For Michiko Fujii, a 64-year-old deputy director of a golf
school, who saw club memberships investments as the perfect adjunct
to her work, news of the collapse of the Omon Golf Club, in Tochigi
prefecture north of Tokyo, one of her five memberships, came in the
form of a simple postcard.
</P>
<P>
   ``I bought it in January 1989, and for two years heard nothing
from them,'' Fujii said. ``Then I received a postcard saying that
they wanted to explain the condition of the club. Shortly
afterward, we learned that the club had already been seized by a
financial company in Osaka, and the caddies and instructors had
already all been fired.''
</P>
<P>
   Other clubs have collapsed but have been forced by the courts to
allow their members to continue playing until they are ultimately
liquidated. And some clubs continue to function more or less
normally, with their memberships traded actively, almost like
futures, but at steep discounts
</P>
<P>
   Fujii paid 9.8 million yen, or $90,740 at current exchange
rates, for a membership in the Nishikata Golf Club, a decade ago.
And as an early entry into the membership pool, she once thought
she had gotten a terrific deal. Others eventually paid three times
as much.
</P>
<P>
   Today, a membership in that club can be picked up for less than
$300. And still there are few takers. What is worse, many of the
golf courses that remain open are so hard up for money that they
gladly accept flat, cheap day rates for nonmembers, destroying the
last shred of exclusivity that had surrounded the clubs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the banks were the most guilty party, an angry Fujii
said. There was always some credit company ready to lend money for
memberships. They were allied with the golf courses, telling
people, anyone can get a loan like this, and if you buy the
membership, the price will steadily rise. And many people were
tricked.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I also feel responsibility. I listened to the promoters
who told me that if you buy something in Japan that is tied to the
price of land, it's value will never go down. I listened to these
people and my judgment failed.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
