<HEADER>
A2168 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r l BC-DRS-PENMANSHIP-LADN &LR;      06-01 0937
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DRS-PENMANSHIP-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN THE PEN IS DEADLIER THAN THE SWORD
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ANGELA LEMIRE 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In his spare time, Cedars-Sinai Medical Center's Chief of Staff
Dr. Paul Hackmeyer is refining his looping technique.
</P>
<P>
   No, he's not honing his suture skills, nor is he simulating
precise hand maneuvers for delicate open-heart surgeries.
</P>
<P>
   Hackmeyer is learning penmanship all over again, hoping to
eliminate those cursive writing pitfalls that _ whether fairly or
unfairly _ have earned doctors a bad rap among professionals as
chicken-scratching scribes.
</P>
<P>
   Along with some 75 other Cedars-Sinai colleagues last month, he
took a voluntary class to improve handwriting, part of the
hospital's mission this year to emphasize patient safety.
</P>
<P>
   Since a national study last year by the Institute of Medicine
found that about 50 percent of medication errors in hospitals stem
from the prescription ordering process, improving the legibility of
doctors' handwritten prescriptions seemed a vital piece of the
patient safety puzzle, he explained.
</P>
<P>
   In worst-case scenarios, simple errors could turn deadly.
</P>
<P>
   Take, for example, the widely publicized 1999 Texas case in
which a widow won a $450,000 settlement after her husband died from
taking the wrong medication he received from a pharmacist who
misread a doctor's poor penmanship.
</P>
<P>
   ``This tragic situation certainly is a cautionary tale for
everyone in the medical profession,'' said Hackmeyer, who also
cited staff surveys that found handwritten correspondence between
physicians and nurses often required time-consuming clarification
and upset staff relations.
</P>
<P>
   Cedars-Sinai enticed doctors to class with a contest that asked
them to decode handwritten reports of two of the more
handwriting-challenged doctors.
</P>
<P>
   The grand prize was a Sunday brunch for two at the Four Seasons
Hotel in Beverly Hills.
</P>
<P>
   Hackmeyer is still surprised so many doctors lined up to change
their scribbling ways.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we all took it in spirit,'' recalled Dr. Andrew
Wachtel, a pulmonary medicine specialist whose only failing grades
in elementary school were for penmanship.
</P>
<P>
   Admittedly, his handwriting in his adult life is at its worst
when he's hurried, or standing up to fill out bedside charts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not just doctors who have bad handwriting, but with
doctors, it shows more to other people and it can be the difference
between life and death,'' said Barbara Getty, one of two nationally
renowned handwriting experts from Portland, Ore., who coached
Cedars-Sinai's staff.
</P>
<P>
   Getty and Inga Dubay, both former teachers at the elementary and
college level, co-authored the handwriting reform manual ``Write
Now'' (Portland State University, Continuing Education Press,
1991).
</P>
<P>
   Their book and seminars teach adults and children an easy
flowing italic style for both printed and cursive forms.
</P>
<P>
   ``Think of the difference between the two as joined printing,''
explained Getty. ``It's less awkward to make the transition between
the two.''
</P>
<P>
   And the italic style has fewer pen strokes and ``looping,'' the
main feature of traditional cursive writing that tends to tangle,
run astray or leave letters incomplete.
</P>
<P>
   One misstroke can contort an ``A'' into a ``U,'' or add letters
that weren't intended.
</P>
<P>
   Italics enable doctors to write speedily, Getty said, but added,
``the bottom line is legibility. People have to read what you
write.''
</P>
<P>
   Pharmacist Nick Movsessian, who works at Costco Wholesale stores
throughout the San Fernando Valley, agreed.
</P>
<P>
   Besides patient safety, he worries he will be held liable for
such a mistake, regardless of whether the doctor's handwritten
prescription was legible.
</P>
<P>
   As a precaution, Movsessian and co-workers double-check every
technician's computer-generated prescription label against the
doctor's original handwritten prescription before filling
prescription bottles.
</P>
<P>
   If there's any doubt, they call the doctor _ a process that
sometimes delays patient orders one working day.
</P>
<P>
   And since hundreds of medications are similarly spelled, he says
that's common.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always a big concern,'' said Movsessian. ``And these
types of problems are more prevalent than people care to think.''
</P>
<P>
   A scribbled order for the antidepressant ``Prozac'' easily can
resemble the ulcer drug ``Prilosec'' he noted as an example.
</P>
<P>
   And to add more confusion, both drugs come in dosages of 10, 20
and 40 milligrams.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question, if doctors slow down and print, it would
solve a lot of problems,'' said Movsessian.
</P>
<P>
   More high-tech solutions also are on the horizon.
</P>
<P>
   Wachtel currently sits on a Cedars-Sinai committee hoping to
incorporate within two to five years a digital-entry prescription
ordering system to replace the handwritten method, as the hospital
did three years ago with patient charts and physician reports.
</P>
<P>
   But as a precaution until then, most doctors at the hospital are
telephoning pharmacies to verify prescriptions, while others are
practicing penmanship.
</P>
<P>
   Realistically, big strides in penmanship won't happen overnight,
so Getty and Dubay tell doctors to at least make the extra effort
with prescriptions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Myself, I loop too much. And in looping, it goes too much into
the next letter,'' said Hackmeyer. ``But I'm going to slow down and
take the time to use these techniques.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Wachtel, ``It's a humbling experience. But I'm willing to
keep practicing and trying at it. Everybody wants to take better
care of the patients. That's what we're all about.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-01-00 1903EDT &QL; 
