<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YUGO-MONTENEGRO-630&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLITICAL MOTIVE SUSPECTED IN KILLING OF MONTENEGRIN AIDE 
</HEADLINE>
   By CARLOTTA GALL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PODGORICA, Yugoslavia _ The shooting death Wednesday night of a
top aide to the president of Montenegro is being widely interpreted
here as a political attack on the West-leaning government.
</P>
<P>
   Goran Zugic, 39, the security adviser to Montenegro's president,
Milo Djukanovic, was gunned down as he arrived home shortly after
11 p.m. outside the modest apartment block where he lived with his
wife and two young children. His murder follows several
high-profile killings in recent months in Serbia, but is the first
such death in Montenegro, Serbia's smaller partner in the Yugoslav
federation.
</P>
<P>
   As such, it has shocked the population here and has shaken the
government, which has been trying to steer a peaceful course away
from Belgrade's control and the isolationist policies of President
Slobodan Milosevic of Yugoslavia. The timing, just a week ahead of
local elections in which pro-Milosevic parties are pitched against
the Montenegrin government and its allies, raised speculation that
the killing was an attempt by Belgrade to destabilize the political
process.
</P>
<P>
   Looking stern and upset as he spoke at a memorial service for
his adviser, Djukanovic said, ``It looks like a terrorist act
against democracy and against the security of the people.''
</P>
<P>
   Zugic, a trained lawyer who had made his career in the security
service and became security adviser to the president two years ago,
had worked for peace and democracy, the president said. ``After all
the efforts to keep the peace and take care of the people, and in
the end this happens,'' Djukanovic said. ``We are not used to such
aggression. We usually try to make friends out of our enemies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing will discourage us from working for democracy. The
whole of Montenegro is with you,'' he told a packed hall of
government officials and Zugic's wife and family.
</P>
<P>
   He described the murder as political, as did other government
officials and politicians, and said it had all the hallmarks of
recent assassinations in Serbia. But he vowed that unlike those
murders, he would not leave it unsolved.
</P>
<P>
   Serbia has witnessed the slaying of four prominent political and
business figures in as many months, among other gangland style
killings. The notorious paramilitary leader, Zeljko Raznatovic,
better known as Arkan, and Milosevic's defense minister, Pavle
Bulatovic, were both shot dead by gunmen earlier this year. A few
weeks later the head of Yugoslav Airlines was shot outside his
apartment, and then a representative of Milosevic's Serbian
Socialist Party, Bosko Perosevic, was killed last month in
apparently unrelated incidents.
</P>
<P>
   The people of Podgorica, which remains an easy-going provincial
town where both the president and prime minister frequent cafes and
restaurants with only minimum security, spoke of shock at the fact
that the gun violence of Belgrade has come to their town.
</P>
<P>
   Montenegro's leading independent newspaper, Vijesti, which
reported the killing in its last edition, was sold out unusually
early, by 10.30 a.m. ``It is a very big story, we are all in a
state of shock that what has been happening in Belgrade should
happen in Podgorica,'' a reporter said.
</P>
<P>
   The Montenegrin justice minister, Dragan Soc, told reporters
that the killing looked like a political assassination and
expressed hope that it would not trigger a wave of unresolved
crimes in Montenegro.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are dealing with a murder like those we have seen outside
Montenegro, and that is disturbing,'' he said, declining to
speculate on motives. ``We are shocked but not surprised,'' said
Miroslav Vickovic, a parliamentarian and opposition leader. ``It
shows the line between the political and the criminal is
disappearing.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Police acted quickly after the murder, sealing exits form the
city and stopping and searching every car on the streets. Witnesses
reported that they heard two bursts of automatic gunfire and saw a
lone gunman flee on foot, the Reuters news agency reported. The
city was calm Thursday with no visible extra security. Guric will
be buried Friday at 2 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Belgrade made little comment about the killing, and Nikola
Sainovic, a senior official in Milosevic's governing party, said it
should not be linked to the murders in Serbia. ``I wouldn't draw
any parallel,'' he told a press conference.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic had been scheduled to visit Montenegro on June 8 for a
political rally of his supporters ahead of the municipal elections.
On Thursday Momir Bulatovic, the Yugoslav prime minister and the
leader of the pro-Milosevic Socialist People's Party in Montenegro,
denied that Milosevic was concerned about security but said that
the party would decide in coming days whether the president would
attend the rally.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
