<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 19:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2171 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-RUNNING-FREE-REVIEW-L     06-01 0479
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUNNING-FREE-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOTE TO EQUUS: BE QUIET AND ACT LIKE A HORSE
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Fact box below) 
Our rating: 2 stars 
By GLENN WHIPP 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The prehistoric creatures in Disney's ``Dinosaur'' were
originally going to communicate through voiceover narration until
the filmmakers decided that having them talk would be a better
call. Judging from the film's first six minutes, silence would have
been the best option of all. But even the dinosaurs' most infantile
musings are preferable to the interminable and mundane ruminations
of the mixed-up horse in ``Running Free.''
</P>
<P>
   This exquisitely shot kids movie suffers from the fatal decision
to have a human voice (Lukas Haas, the Amish boy in ``Witness'')
narrate every thought, feeling and reflection of the
ever-so-sensitive orphaned horse, Lucky. That means when Lucky has
lost his mother, we can't just watch him scan the distance with a
forlorn look in those big, brown eyes. Instead, we hear him whine:
``I had to find my mother. Why didn't they understand I needed to
be with my mother?''
</P>
<P>
   Lucky's long-winded bleatings don't end there. Lucky on
ambition: ``I had to find my place in the world. It was time for me
to set out into an unknown world, where I would be as wild and free
as in my dreams.'' Lucky on the need for companionship: ``I started
to feel lonely. I had nobody.'' Lucky on freedom: ``I would rather
die than bow to Caesar.''
</P>
<P>
   Caesar, you see, is the bad horsie who rules the ranch at the
South African mining town where Lucky finds himself. Lucky, his mom
and other (less talkative) horses were sent to this godforsaken
place from Germany. Lucky, just a colt, finds a friend in a fellow
orphan, a stable boy, Richard (Chase Moore). Lucky's mom isn't so,
well, lucky, running afoul of the villainous Caesar, which sets up
an eventual corral showdown that is anything but OK.
</P>
<P>
   Russian director Sergei Bodrov, making his English-language
feature debut, captures the bare beauty of the Namibian desert and
comes away with some fine footage of his equine actors. It's too
bad he couldn't trust his images to convey the essence of the
story, which, for the most part, they do.
</P>
<P>
   Failing that, ``Running Free'' could have used some clever,
intelligent writing on the order of the 1994 ``Black Beauty''
remake which had Alan Cumming providing the horse's voice to fine
effect. There's nothing remotely like that here for narrator Haas,
rendering Lucky a nag in a thoroughbred arena. Place your bet on
another movie. &QL; 
____ &QL; 
The film: ``Running Free'' (G; for all audiences). &QL; 
The stars: Chase Moore. &QL; 
Behind the scenes: Directed by Sergei Bodrov. Screenplay by Jeanne
Rosenberg. Based on a story by Rosenberg and Jean-Jacques Annaud.
Released by Columbia Pictures. &QL; 
Running time: One hour, 22 minutes. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
