u f BC-BANKRUPTCY-NORRIS-COL     06-01 0629
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BANKRUPTCY-NORRIS-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE NEW BANKRUPTCY REFORM: MAKE THE RICH PLAN AHEAD
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla., Texas, S.D., Iowa, Kan.)  By FLOYD NORRIS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The market for million-dollar homes in Florida and Texas has
long been stimulated by the fact that such houses appeal to one
particular class of wealthy people _ those who are about to file
for bankruptcy. Now Congress is about to increase the appeal of
such homes to rich people who may not face imminent bankruptcy, but
see it as a possibility if they lose a big lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   The unlimited homestead exemption in those two states _ as well
as in South Dakota, Iowa and Kansas, although relocating deadbeats
tend to prefer Boca Raton winters to those of Sioux Falls _ has
long been the most obvious way that people with a lot of assets can
abuse the bankruptcy code.
</P>
<P>
   Go broke owning a $10 million mortgage-free house in Houston,
and you can stiff your creditors while you keep the house. Once you
emerge from bankruptcy, you can sell the house and use the cash to
maintain the lifestyle you think you deserve. So high-livers tend
to move from New York, where the homestead exemption is $10,000, to
Florida or Texas before they file for bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
   The bankruptcy bill passed by the House did nothing to deal with
that abuse, but after a bruising floor fight, the Senate voted to
cap the homestead exemption at $100,000.
</P>
<P>
   Now, meeting behind closed doors, a compromise has been reached,
and the senators fighting that abuse have tentatively signed off on
it. It will be pitched as a meaningful reform, one that will reduce
the abuse. But the reduction is likely to be minimal.
</P>
<P>
   Under the proposal, the unlimited Florida and Texas exemptions
will be available only to those who have lived in the states for at
least two years before they file for bankruptcy. And even for them,
the exemption will be limited to the amount of equity that the
person had in the home two years before filing, plus $100,000.
Somebody who moves to Florida just before filing will be out of
luck. If fraud can be proved, something that is never easy, money
put into a house up to seven years before filing may be vulnerable.
</P>
<P>
   The catch is that many once-rich people can plan for going
broke, stalling off creditors and appealing judgments while the
two-year clock is ticking. ``It just says, be sure not to wait too
long to get your house in Texas or Florida,'' says Elizabeth
Warren, a Harvard law professor.
</P>
<P>
   The bill also will put a limit of $1 million on the amount a
person can squirrel away in an individual retirement account immune
from creditors. But it won't do anything about a myriad of other
ways, often involving trusts, that money can be protected from
creditors. Congress decided not to put a cap on such maneuvers.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the once-wealthy who take the trouble to plan will
still be able to hold on to assets while creditors suffer, the bill
that emerges from Congress is sure to make life harder on most of
those who file for bankruptcy _ usually after a divorce, job loss
or severe illness. The credit card companies will collect more of
what they are owed.
</P>
<P>
   The supposed urgency of bankruptcy legislation came from a rapid
rise in the number of bankruptcy filings. That surge has ended, and
the number of new cases is falling. But this is a bill with
momentum, and final passage is likely if a few disputes _ including
one related to judgments against abortion protesters _ can be
settled. The new law will do a lot to cut out abuses by people who
were just scraping by before they went broke, but much less to
eliminate abuses by people who were rich before a judge ordered
them to repay people they had defrauded.
</P>
<P>
   They will call that reform.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
