r e BC-CLINT-BLACK-LADN &LR;      06-01 0800
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINT-BLACK-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLACK TO BASICS
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Fact box below) 
By FRED SHUSTER 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   At a recent awards show, country superstar Clint Black ignored
his just-won silver-plated trophy _ and reached for another sort of
reward: wife Lisa Hartman Black.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody seemed surprised. A country traditionalist from the Texas
heartland, Black was one of the first artists to kick-start
country's mass popularity in the '90s. And he did it by sticking
true to country's ideals _ heart, home and healthy respect for the
fans.
</P>
<P>
   A soft-spoken, humorous guy, Black was in town recently to pick
up a statuette from the Academy of Country Music for his
chart-topping hit, ``When I Said I Do,'' a touching duet with his
wife affirming the importance of a loving marriage. Black wrote and
produced the song, as well as producing and directing the video.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I Said I Do'' was the first single from Black's ninth and
current album, ``D'lectrified.'' The exclusively acoustic disc
features a rich spectrum of sound and draws on a number of country
styles while cameos come from such diverse names as comedians Eric
Idle and Kevin Nealon, country stars Waylon Jennings, Steve Wariner
and Marty Stuart, and rockers Bruce Hornsby and Edgar Winter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd wanted to do an `unplugged' album for a while,'' Black,
37, said backstage at the 35th annual Academy of Country Music
Awards at Universal Amphitheatre. ``There was no reason not to do
one. It looked like it would be an easy process. Then I started
thinking about it, and I felt I wasn't throwing myself enough curve
balls. It just didn't seem challenging enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Black appears Aug. 27 at the Greek Theatre. At 8 p.m. Tuesday,
the A&AMP;E Network will debut a ``Biography'' on the singer covering
his roots in Katy, Texas, and beyond.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's definitely a core artist for this station and the entire
country format,'' said R.J. Curtis, operations manager at local
country station KZLA-FM (93.9). ``If you do any kind of music
research and artist testing, his name comes up often as a huge
favorite of listeners.''
</P>
<P>
   Curtis said the duet, ``When I Said I Do,'' had received more
than 1,000 spins at KZLA in heavy rotation since its release in
October.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gets played several times a day,'' he said. ``People are
very passionate about it.''
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Black said he always knew he'd eventually record a
duet with Lisa Hartman Black when the right song came along.
</P>
<P>
   ``I took that for granted,'' he explained as he motioned to the
country academy trophy for top vocal event of the year. ``I knew
the right tune would make it happen. You should have seen her face
when they called our name.''
</P>
<P>
   Black joked that since he got married, the most frequently asked
questions have been when are he and his wife going to make a
record, a movie and a baby.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got two of the three down,'' Black said, clearing his
throat. ``We're practicing on the third.''
</P>
<P>
   Like other popular country acts, Black is equally inspired by
pop and country. It's been said that without Black paving the way,
there wouldn't be a Garth Brooks.
</P>
<P>
   Born in New Jersey, but raised in a Houston, Texas, suburb,
Black didn't take up guitar until the age of 13 when he started
playing harmonica. Two years later, he began writing songs,
eventually landing gigs in local coffeehouses, bars and clubs.
</P>
<P>
   In 1987, Black met singer-songwriter Hayden Nicholas, and the
two began collaborating and recording demos. A tape of their songs
made its way to ZZ Top manager Bill Ham, who quickly signed Black
and got him a deal with RCA Nashville by the end of 1988.
</P>
<P>
   Black's first single, ``A Better Man,'' went to No. 1, and a
star was born. For Black, awards season had begun in earnest.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice to win these things, but you have to keep in mind
they are the result of your fan base,'' Black said. ``That's what
you have to keep being thankful for. That people out there buy your
records and come to your shows. That's the biggest reward of all.''
</P>
<P>
   Black said he himself remains a fan, especially of Loggins, who
appears on ``D'lectrified.''
</P>
<P>
   Loggins, Black says, is ``the singer I aspire to be as good as.
He had all the range, emotion and soul I wanted when I was a kid.
Here he was in my studio.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Black said he had to stop twiddling the dials long
enough to give thanks for a long career.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was more than I expected,'' he said. ``I never expected
much more than, `get a record deal and get on stage.' I had to stop
for a minute or two and just take it all in.'' &QL; 
--- &QL; 
Who: Clint Black. &QL; 
Where: Greek Theatre, 2700 N. Vermont Ave., Los Angeles. &QL; 
When: 7:30 p.m. Aug. 27. &QL; 
Tickets: $25 to $57.50. &QL; 
Information: (213) 480-3232. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-01-00 1918EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
