<DOCNO> NYT20000601.0297 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 19:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2183 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-BEAU-TRAVAIL-REVIEW-L     06-01 0474
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEAU-TRAVAIL-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SLEEPY `TRAVAIL'
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Fact box below) 
Our rating: 2 1/2 stars 
By BOB STRAUSS 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sensuous well past the point of delirium, Claire Denis' ``Beau
Travail'' is an insistently poetic ode to, well, guys with their
shirts off. Loosely based on Melville's ``Billy Budd,'' transposed
to a 20th-century Foreign Legion outpost in the barren African
enclave of Djibouti and with the homoerotic implications amped up a
couple of megatons, this French production, while unfailingly
beautiful, seems always, oppressively on the verge of an incoherent
swoon.
</P>
<P>
   With minimal dialogue and an editing strategy that's less
concerned with narrative flow than artistically juxtaposing
textures of desert, water and flesh, ``Beau Travail's'' primary
concern (after muscles) is ritualism. Most of the screen time is
devoted to detailing the Legion's young recruits at their
exercises, maneuvers, chores and what even appears to be downtime
organized for maximum group bonding impact. For most, this will
have the movie equivalent effect of nodding off in church.
</P>
<P>
   In an isolated culture like the Legion's, it's little wonder
that Sgt. Galoup (Denis Lavant, the ``Lovers on the Bridge'' actor
with the evocatively ravaged face), who's thoughts we hear
regularly on the soundtrack, has a borderline psychotic need to
preserve his idea of corps propriety. He mentions something about
``rumors'' once spread regarding the veteran commander (Michel
Subor) to whom Galoup is devoted, and determines to destroy a
popular new arrival, Legionnaire Sentain (Gregorie Colin), before
he does harm to the executive officer's reputation _ or so he keeps
telling himself, and us, though his true, unexamined motivation.
</P>
<P>
   Director Denis, who grew up in Africa, has a marvelous eye for
the continent's natural and human wonders. That was evident in her
first feature, ``Chocolat,'' 11 years ago, and is made only more
intensely apparent in ``Beau Travail'' by the tactile camerawork of
Agnes Godard, who shot last year's stirring ``Dreamlife of Angels''
and is clearly in the top rank of France's young cinematographers.
</P>
<P>
   But ``Chocolat,'' which was presumed to be
semi-autobiographical, had an emotional immediacy and tragic
inevitability that the new movie, with its sculpted aesthetic
agenda, never approximates. Denis and company do, however, give
Michelangelo a run for his money. &QL; 
_____ &QL; 
The film: ``Beau Travail'' (NR; nudity, language, drug use,
violence). &QL; 
The stars: Denis Lavant, Gregorie Colin, Michel Subor. &QL; 
Behind the scenes: Directed by Claire Denis. Written by Jean-Pol
Fargeau and Denis. Based on Herman Melville's ``Billy Budd.''
Produced by Jerome Minet. Released by New Yorker Films. &QL; 
Running time: One hour, 30 minutes. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-01-00 1919EDT &QL; 
