<P>
   INVEST-CASTRO (Undated) _ Investing with Oscar Castro of the
Montgomery Global Communications Fund. By Joanne Legomsky.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SENIORS-COLUMN-DOLE (Undated) _ Bob Dole is an unlikely
spokesman for older Americans. After all, the former Kansas senator
voted against the creation of Medicare in 1965, although he has
since supported it. He loathes the idea of retiring and, at 76,
doesn't consider himself old. But he has become a hero to senior
citizens for surviving prostate cancer, for speaking out about
using Viagra, the impotency drug, and for his sense of humor.
Actually, he says, some of the Viagra jokes made at his expense
were pretty funny. By Fred Brock. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ECONOMY-CRYSTALBALL (Washington) _ The writer looks into a
crystal ball and foresees: two interest rate increases by the
Federal Reserve this summer; a larger than expected federal
surplus; and, the new economy emerging as a campaign issue. The
crystal ball is a prototype without a warranty. Check back in a few
months to determine its accuracy. By Richard W. Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   FREEDOM-COLUMN (Undated) _ Daniel Akst suggests forfeiting the
professional quality stove or the new sports utility vehicle and
saving up for a really nifty commodity _ freedom. Ditch that
lucrative but unworthy gig you've been slaving at all these years
and do something you believe in _ teach school, start a business,
move to the country, join the Elks, read a book, for Pete's sake.
Unfortunately, the author concludes, freedom has a marketing
problem.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PERSONAL FINANCE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CAR-REFINANCE (Undated) _ The latest wrinkle in consumer
lending: refinancing &QL; 
your car loan. Does it make any sense, especially now? By Stacy
Kravetz. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With photo. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MEDICAL-INSURANCE (Undated) _ In the Money &AMP; Medicine column,
Jennifer Steinhauer writes about the Health Insurance Portability
and Accountability Act, or HIPAA. This little-known law enables
employees changing jobs to qualify for medical coverage of
pre-existing conditions if the condition was covered under the
insurance at their previous job. It also requires enrollment of
children immediately after birth instead of waiting until the next
enrollment period and prohibits employers from charging higher
premiums for employees with chronic conditions.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   GUATEMALA-PHILANTHROPY (San Pedro La Laguna, Guatemala) _ An
eBay executive brings computers to the shores of Lake Atitlan,
Guatemala. One longterm goal is to enable villagers to sell their
handicrafts on eBay. By Abbie Ellin. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; AUTOS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   HONDA-HYBRID (Undated) _ With gasoline prices pushing toward $2
a gallon in some parts of the country, Honda could not have picked
a better time to bring out the Honda Insight, a car that gets 70
miles to the gallon on the highway. Honda has sold more than 400 of
the futuristic looking hybrid _ part gas, part electric _ cars
since it went on sale in December. That's double the number of
purely electric cars sold by all manufacturers combined in the last
few years. By Andrew Pollack. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   HYBRID-CARS (Washington) _ Gasoline-electric cars can be clean
and extremely fuel-efficient, but when it comes to pollution,
engineers are learning that hybrids cannot accomplish everything
that environmentalists want. That point was demonstrated at the
American Tour de Sol race here on May 18. The alternative-vehicle
race showed that hybrids did better on fuel economy than some of
the electrics, but caused more emissions of gases that are thought
to cause climate change. By Matthew L. Wald. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
