<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 19:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2188 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-DIGITAL-COLUMN-LADN &LR;      06-01 0764
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIGITAL-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WARDING OFF COMPUTER COOTIES
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: A copy of this is also being transmitted to lifestyle wire) 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVID BLOOM 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The recent pair of computer virus scares sparked a few thoughts,
particularly as I plowed into the massive paperback version of
``Cryptonomicon,'' sci-fi hotshot Neal Stephenson's latest
crackerjack read.
</P>
<P>
   It was Stephenson's ``Snow Crash'' that envisioned a
three-dimensional cyberworld where human-looking online avatars
exchange virtual documents by literally handing them to one
another. One lethal troublemaker hands out virtual notes laced with
viruses capable of wiping clean the recipient's brain functions,
literally leaving only TV-like ``snow'' on the mind's screen.
</P>
<P>
   We're a long way from viruses that actually directly affect
human health (unless you count the alleged addictive nature of
online conversation for some users). But the I Love You virus'
quick propagation across the planet showed how widespread our
connections with each other already are, and how vulnerable we can
be to electronic disruption on a wide scale.
</P>
<P>
   I received eight of the corrupted I Love You e-mails (and five
warnings not to open them), but given the current state of my
romantic endeavors, felt pretty sure none of my correspondents
could claim any such warm, much less identical, sentiments toward
me. So I didn't open any of them.
</P>
<P>
   That saved me some grief, because the problems started when
people opened the attachments. Lesson 1: Know who's sending you
something, and why, before you open any attachments.
</P>
<P>
   Lesson 2: There aren't many attachments you should ever open,
especially those with more unusual suffixes like .exe (for an
``executable'' file that can automatically run a mini-program when
opened) or .vbs (again, for a program written in the Visual Basic
language).
</P>
<P>
   Of course, that means you'll miss some of the little pieces of
goofball comedy that float around the Net.
</P>
<P>
   But here's Lesson 3: If your friends truly love you, they'll
save everyone some time, bandwidth and headaches by sending you a
link to a site where such goofball stuff resides, instead of a big
fat attachment. Then you can decide whether to download and run the
piece more easily.
</P>
<P>
   Plus, you'll help the site build up traffic, so it can get more
advertisers and outlast the little drabs of investment capital
financing its operations.
</P>
<P>
   Lesson 4 is that anti-virus programs can work, but are pretty
worthless in the first assault of a new virtual beast. The programs
have to be updated to spot the virus (which the big anti-virus
makers quickly did), or they can't catch it coming in.
</P>
<P>
   Lesson 5: Always backup the stuff you care about. What would be
a huge pain to replace if your computer's hard drive was wiped
clean by a virus? For me, it's the contact information and calendar
that run my life, and a few digital photos of my children.
Regularly drag copies of that information to a floppy disk or
online storage site (your Internet service provider probably gives
you a few megabytes of space, and companies such as X:drive
(www.xdrive.com) and i-drive (www.idrive.com) provide much more for
free.
</P>
<P>
   Lesson 6 might be the subtlest, but most important of all. Some
online commentators pointed out, and National Public Radio satirist
Harry Shearer picked up on, how infrequently most news reports
mentioned that the virus only attacked users of a specific
operating system, Windows, and e-mail program, Outlook Express,
from a single company, Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   If you use a Macintosh or a mainframe, you were safe. If you use
Eudora or Netscape Communicator, you were safe.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't just a ``computer virus'' that caused the mess, which
is how most news reports termed the problems. It was a Microsoft
Windows and Outlook Express virus that caused the mess.
</P>
<P>
   And because so many of us use those programs, the virus could
spread rapidly. To make a biological metaphor, the Internet is
suffering from a lack of diversity in its ecosphere. Just as any
species in the wild with a lack of genetic diversity can be wiped
out by a virus-borne disease, so, too, the Net was vulnerable
because too many people use the same programs.
</P>
<P>
   So ponder how much you want to be like everyone else the next
time you choose a computer, or operating system, or e-mail client.
Standards have their place, goodness knows, in this fractured
computing world. But there's a lesson here for the virtual world:
diversify or (watch your hard drive) die. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-01-00 1925EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
