<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 19:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2192 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-ERITREA-REFUGEES-420&AMP;     06-01 0919
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ERITREA-REFUGEES-420&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INCREASE IN REFUGEES COULD WORSEN FOOD CRISIS IN ERITREA 
</HEADLINE>
   By IAN FISHER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ASMARA, Eritrea _ A few weeks ago, Abrehet Amdimeskel was simply
a student, who happened to be in English class when the war with
Ethiopia came to her town in southern Eritrea. Now, at 14, she is
the head of her uprooted household, caring for her grandmother and
four younger siblings in a small tent in a huge refugee camp.
</P>
<P>
   As towns like hers emptied out, she lost track of her parents
and two other siblings, and can only hope they found their way to
some other camp.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want peace,'' she said in a camp of about 37,000 refugees
in the town of Dadu, 30 miles northwest of the capital, Asmara.
``We want this to stop. We don't know anything about this war.''
She started to cry but would not let herself.
</P>
<P>
   In the last few days Ethiopia and Eritrea seem finally to have
made progress toward ending their two-year war. But relief
officials say it is far from certain that the hundreds of thousands
of people displaced in the last three weeks of intense fighting
will go home anytime soon. Ethiopia on Wednesday declared the war
over, but there is no cease-fire yet and many people, relief
officials say, will simply be too afraid to return. Complicating
the problem is the worry that this refugee crisis could make the
food shortages in Eritrea, which are already bad, far worse. Most
of the refugees are from the southwest, the Gash Barka region,
which produces two-thirds of the nation's grain, according to the
U.N. World Food Program.
</P>
<P>
   The seasonal rains _ and thus the main planting season _ are
expected to start in the next two weeks. If the displaced cannot
get home to plant, said Bruce Orina, a spokesman here for the
International Committee of the Red Cross, ``We are talking about
potentially a grim situation as food security is concerned.''
</P>
<P>
   Already, war and drought have reduced the Gash Barka region's
harvest by 90 percent, the World Food Program estimates, and
770,000 people faced food shortages even before this latest round
of fighting.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no other area in Eritrea that can fill that gap,''
said Lindsey Davies, a spokeswoman for the agency here in Asmara.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the United Nations began airlifting tons of food for
the short-term, and other relief groups are scrambling to provide
essentials like blankets, tents, cooking pots and clean water. All
are in short supply, relief officials say, though it is possible
the needs will evaporate if peace talks in Algeria produce a final
cease-fire and everyone goes home.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   What has become clearer in the last few days, though, is just
how many people were uprooted from their homes after Ethiopia
launched a major offensive on May 12, pushing through the trenches
along the nations' disputed border and into the places where people
actually live.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last week, thousands of Eritreans have been moving
along the roads, particularly along the border areas south of
Asmara, flowing north to escape fierce fighting with almost nothing
in their hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``The enemy was shelling with heavy artillery,'' said Negisti
Tesfu, 35, a mother of six who fled from her home near Adi Quala
five days before to a camp in Dbarwa, some 12 miles south of
Asmara. ``There were air bombardments. So I was forced to leave.''
She said at least one child was killed, a 5-year-old boy, along
with six cows and two donkeys. She said her home was demolished.
</P>
<P>
   Early on, the Eritrean government estimated that about 550,000
people were displaced _ a number that Ethiopia said was propaganda
aimed at building sympathy abroad. That would have meant that more
than 1 in 10 people were displaced in a nation of 3.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   But Davies of the World Food Program said that her agency now
believed that the estimate was probably correct, based on checking
the population figures and a rough count of a dozen or so informal
encampments stretching from the Sudanese border east to the city of
Keren.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're saying it's plausible but it could go up or down''
depending on the fighting, she said. ``We have to constantly assess
and verify the numbers.''
</P>
<P>
   The estimates include an unknown number of the 330,000 Eritreans
already displaced by the war in the last two years. That in an odd
way has been fortunate, because the World Food Program already had
20,000 tons of wheat in the country that is now feeding a much
larger number of people.
</P>
<P>
   Relief officials say the suffering has also been lessened by the
extraordinary organization of the Eritrean government in getting
people out of the war zones quickly. Tens of thousands of people
were moved by government buses and trucks into camps. Entire
villages have been relocated to the camps, complete with their
local administrators and, sometimes, their shops.
</P>
<P>
   But life is still very hard. Thousands of people who settled
along the Gash River in the west have to contend with infestations
of scorpions and snakes. Hospitals in the evacuated regions are
closed, so there is a shortage of medical care. Relief officials
worry that if people do not leave before the rains, the camps will
be flooded and it will difficult to transport supplies over muddy
and waterlogged roads.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course I would like to live in my house,'' said Habte
Tefere, 80, from a village that was shelled near the Adi Quala.
``But I couldn't. So I had to come here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
