<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FINFRONTS-NYT </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOR SATURDAY AMs
</P>
<P>
   Business Day Front Page (coded ``f'' unless otherwise noted):
</P>
<P>
   (Top lede)
</P>
<P>
   INVESTMENT-FRAUD (Undated) _ Federal and state authorities
announced a combined fight Thursday against a fraudulent fixed-rate
investment that they say bilks thousands of Americans, particularly
older people, out of hundreds of millions of dollars a year. The
scheme involves promissory notes, which are investments that
typically involve a loan to a company in exchange for a fixed
return. Officials estimated that more than 3,000 American investors
were victims of promissory note fraud last year alone. By Jayson
Blair.
</P>
<P>
   (Scheduled to move by 8 p.m. ET.)
</P>
<P>
   (Display)
</P>
<P>
   TV-SURVIVORS (Undated) _ Last summer, ABC's ``Who Wants to Be A
Millionaire'' turned the television world on its head by defying
every expectation and seizing huge audiences, eventually
catapulting ABC to overall network ratings leadership. Now a new
CBS series, about a group of people forced to live together in
primitive circumstances on an island off Borneo, has had a
similarly stunning start, and television executives are already
wondering whether it can do for CBS what ``Millionaire'' did for
ABC. By Bill Carter.
</P>
<P>
   (With graphic.)
</P>
