<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SITE-OF-WEEK-LADN </SLUG>
  
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Fact box) 
By DAVID BLOOM 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Veterans.com: A just-launched site, in this Memorial Day week,
dedicated to the men and women who have served in our Armed
Forces. &QL; 
Where: www.veterans.com &QL; 
What's cool: The eyewitness accounts by vets of their experiences
in war and peace are often fascinating. And, unlike listening to
war stories, you can read as much or as little as you like before
clicking onto something else. &QL; 
Features: It's sponsored by the History Channel, a cable TV outlet
that sprinkles in links to its own programming (which is, perhaps
unsurprisingly, heavily oriented toward coverage of great
conflagrations of the past). There's a lot of interesting stuff,
like a veterans' locator service, links to unit reunions around the
country, a resource list, online store, ``Dirty Little Secrets of
the Vietnam War,'' and ``Veteran of the Month.'' The site is less
than a week old, and will need to fill in more to be truly great,
but holds promise as more veterans connect with it and each other. &QL; 
You'll like this if: you've already heard all the old war stories
down at the VFW Hall 3,000 times. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Think your Web fave is good enough for Site of the Week? Send your
suggestions to davidbloomearthlink.net. &QL;
</P>
