<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: A MONTH TO REMEMBER 
</HEADLINE>
   By GAIL COLLINS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ I tell you, it's good to have May over with.
</P>
<P>
   There was something apocalyptic going on in May, a
post-millennial twitch. The pope spilled the third secret of
Fatima. The National Rifle Association (led by Charlton Heston, the
star of many, many movies about dyspeptic males fending off the end
of the world) announced plans to open a theme restaurant on Times
Square. And that enormous forest fire in New Mexico _ all right, we
have enormous forest fires all the time, but very few set
deliberately by the national government for our own good. (How far,
by the way, is Los Alamos from Roswell?)
</P>
<P>
   Here in New York, Rudy Giuliani mutated into a variation on
Barney the Dinosaur, a fluffy critter who prefers dinner with his
new squeeze to a press conference announcing a big police bust.
We've been a little edgy around him ever since, wondering if he's
actually the same person. ``Invasion of the Body Snatchers'' pods
may be at work here, or one of those ``X-Files'' aliens who looks
like your best friend, but spouts green acid when he's poked. The
city is disoriented. New York has had fighting mayors and crooked
mayors, and the one before this one was extremely polite. But Love
Mayor sounds so '90s, so _ Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Rick Lazio became the new, post-Giuliani Republican Senate
candidate. Lazio, a Republican congressman from Long Island,
appeared to have popped out of the ground from nowhere, but
actually he's been dying for the nomination all along, and spent
most of the spring desperately waving his arms in crowd scenes,
looking available. The split lip he collected when he took a header
during a Memorial Day parade worked well for him, being as close as
a young 21st-century politician can come to a war wound. Besides,
it gave the Republican convention this week something to talk about
besides Lazio's two great thundering qualifications:
</P>
<P>
   A) From here.
</P>
<P>
   B) Not unhinged.
</P>
<P>
   The only drawback is Lazio's strong resemblance to those unnamed
``Star Trek'' crewmen who get included on every expedition so the
mutants will have somebody to incinerate. And there was something a
little eerie, not to say unappetizing, about his promise to the
people of Buffalo that he would ``be here so often I'm going to be
sweating Buffalo wings.''
</P>
<P>
   But for those of us who spent our formative years in pre-Vatican
II parochial schools, the story of the month was still the Lady of
Fatima letter. For kids who went to school on split shifts in
trailers, we spent a lot of valuable class time speculating about
the exact nature of the secret the Blessed Virgin was supposed to
have passed on to the pope via a trio of Portuguese shepherd
children in 1917. Most people believed it simply revealed the date
of the end of the world. In my particular neighborhood, the word
was out that Pope Pius XII had opened the letter, burst into tears
and cried ``Oh Canada, poor Canada.'' We found this somewhat
comforting, since we were in Ohio at the time.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, it was hard to escape the evidence that the final
days were upon us, what with the air raid drills, the bomb shelters
and a set of nuns who could always come up with a prophecy that
made it seem extremely unlikely that anybody was going to be around
for summer vacation. Our parents had moved to the suburbs so we
could grow up in perfect safety, then sent us off to schools where
the faculty assured us we were doomed. It was a rich culture,
actually, and we probably have it to thank for the fact that these
days, on television and in the movies, any character who moves into
a gated community with a good security system is guaranteed to get
eaten by werewolves.
</P>
<P>
   The actual secret of Fatima had to be a letdown for those who
were expecting a timetable for Armageddon. The Vatican says the
letter revealed the assassination attempt on the pope in 1981,
although it seems to be couched in that really flexible,
one-size-fits-all prose used by all truly successful
future-forecasters. We appear to have gone through a lot of angst
for nothing but the fun of it.
</P>
<P>
   Personally, I'm ready for a stretch of utter predictability.
That's why it was so reassuring on Wednesday night when the only
woman over 35 on the ``Survivor'' series was the first person to
get thrown off the island.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
