<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HARLAN-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAT, PREDICTABLE `HARLAN'
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Fact box below; `tonight' refers to Sun., June 4) 
Our rating: 2 stars. 
By DAVID KRONKE 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Harlan County War'' is an earnest civics lesson with a moment
or two of drama. Holly Hunter stars as Ruby, the wife of an
impoverished Kentucky mineworker (the film is set in the '70s) who
becomes an impassioned voice for a beleaguered union trying to get
a toehold against the monolithic company that exploits its ravaged
employees.
</P>
<P>
   While Warren (Stellan Skarsgard), the putative union
representative, broods and smokes, Ruby comes up with all the ideas
most effective in battling the mine operators. Warren doesn't even
cogently explain to the cracker mineworkers why the schemes will
sway public empathy, which forces Ruby's husband, Silas (Ted
Levine), into unmotivated bouts of moodiness in which he turns
against his forward-thinking wife.
</P>
<P>
   Hunter nails the regional accent to such an extent that you
might be hard-pressed to understand what she's saying a lot of the
time. Her stature as an Oscar-winning leading lady works against
her here, as her turn becomes all about her accent and mannerisms
and looking just a smidgen more glamorous than the hardscrabble
folks surrounding her _ it's not quite as bad as Jodie Foster in
``Nell,'' but it's close.
</P>
<P>
   Such black-and-white issue development (owners &QC;
</P>
<P>
   bad; workers &QC;
</P>
<P>
   good) may in fact be historically accurate, but it doesn't help
the movie's dramatic thrust. When gunplay finally figures in, it
feels like a bald attempt to rouse viewers from their stupor.
Documentarian Barbara Koppel's Oscar winner ``Harlan County,
U.S.A.,'' which inspired this telefilm, essayed this struggle far
more compellingly and convincingly. &QL; 
--- &QL; 
The show: ``Harlan County War.'' &QL; 
What: Drama about the unionization of a Kentucky coal mine. &QL; 
The stars: Holly Hunter, Stellan Skarsgard, Ted Levine. &QL; 
Where: Showtime. &QL; 
When: 8 tonight; also June 14 and 20. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-01-00 1948EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
