<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 19:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2215 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-ECON-ART-2TAKE     06-01 1205
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-ECON-ART-2TAKES-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SMALL INDUSTRY SHINES IN THE SILVER LINING OF RUSSIA'S 1998
ECONOMIC CRASH 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By MICHAEL WINES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   VOLOGDA, Russia _ Don't look now, says Viktor Petukhov, but that
Russian economy the world wrote off as a basket case two years ago
is roaring back to life.
</P>
<P>
   He is certainly right about the roaring part.
</P>
<P>
   Inside a peeling salmon-colored stucco building near the center
of this otherwise quiet town, Petukhov, the director of the Vologda
Textile Enterprise, stood one recent day and surveyed the
ear-splitting success he has wrought. Around him, 100 mechanical
looms clack-clacked in deafening unison, spitting miles of linen
onto spools as big as car axles.
</P>
<P>
   Overhead, hissing water jets spewed a dust-eating mist that hung
through the vast room like cigar smoke in a bar.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything has to be clean! There are cleaning ladies all
around!'' Petukhov shouted. ``If there is any dirt, it will affect
the quality of the product!''
</P>
<P>
   Later, over Turkish coffee in his office, he said linen sales
leapt by 50 percent last year and would grow another third or so
this year. And this from a firm that was bankrupt and rudderless
just four years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's growth everywhere,'' he said. ``All we need now is
stability and some government understanding of the problems.''
</P>
<P>
   This is Russia's not-quite-open secret: the crash of 1998, the
meltdown that wiped out Russia's middle class and turned the
Kremlin into a global deadbeat, is over.
</P>
<P>
   Its devastating aftereffects _ a sharply devalued ruble; the
disappearance of imported goods; a government cut off from
addictive foreign loans _ turned out to be fuel for an economy that
had simply run out of gas. A landscape littered with bankruptcies
two years ago now sprouts hundreds of Vologda Textiles.
</P>
<P>
   The question is whether that comeback is real and gaining
strength, or will run out of steam.
</P>
<P>
   The Kremlin casts it as real, if shaky, and the numbers look
promising. Industrial production through April was 10.3 percent
greater than in the same period of 1999. Russian exports jumped 50
percent. The average worker's salary _ a meager $73 per month _
nevertheless was up 7 percent in March over a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Companies and the government have begun to pay workers the
months and even years of back wages they are owed. Inflation this
year is expected to be a third of the 1999 rate. Investment in new
equipment and buildings is rising for the first time in a decade.
</P>
<P>
   Most promising, Russia's budget now runs a primary surplus _
that is, it has money left after domestic spending to pay some of
its foreign debt. In Washington in May, President Vladimir Putin's
chief economic adviser told President Clinton that the Kremlin no
longer needs to secure new foreign loans just to pay its old ones.
</P>
<P>
   Putin now announces the good news personally, as in April when
he disclosed a higher-than-expected increase in economic growth in
the first quarter. ``By our Russian standards of recent times,'' he
boasted, ``this is not just stable and good. This is enormous
growth.''
</P>
<P>
   He cautions, and experts agree, that it cannot last absent basic
economic reforms. He already has proposed wholesale changes in
taxes, including a flat income tax and corporate tax cuts. He
promises to announce equally sweeping changes in June. If they
become law, his advisers say, Russia's economy should grow by
roughly 5 percent a year _ and inflation should fall steadily _ as
far as the eye can see.
</P>
<P>
   But other top government forecasters are less cocksure. They
agree that Russia's economy is reaping the economic windfall of the
1998 crisis. The problem, they say, is that the windfall has now
been more or less exploited _ and there is little to take its
place.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the second part of this year, the positive influences will
mostly be over,'' said Alexander Frenkel, the chief macroeconomics
forecaster at the Russian Academy of Sciences' Economics Institute.
``And the influence of negative factors _ low investment; a foreign
payments crisis; a low standard of living _ may significantly
influence economic growth.''
</P>
<P>
   Eduard F. Baranov, the first deputy chief of the government's
Economic Research Center, says Russia's boomlet has been confined
mostly to raw-materials exports and light industries like
food-processing and textiles. Major industries have mostly been
left behind.
</P>
<P>
   The nation's Vologda Textiles, he said, ``are like little plants
that give us hope. The more we have, the better our chances.'' But
they are not the architects of basic reform that the economy needs.
``We still have the mentality of the old Soviet plan, when we
didn't have to think about sales or quality or lowering expenses,''
he said. ``We have to rebuild our organization at the molecular
level. And it's going to take a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the bears say, the glowing statistics look a lot
different when Russia's performance is compared to the months
before the August 1998 crash instead of the depressed months after
it. Investment so far this year is surely greater than last, they
allow. But it still is only 92 percent of what was registered
during the earlier part of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Workers' real income is substantially higher than a year ago.
But it remains barely 77 percent of what it was in 1998, and that
translates into a lower standard of living.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wages haven't returned yet to their pre-crisis level,''
Baranov said. ``And while salaries have increased, they have risen
at a lower rate than prices.''
</P>
<P>
   A Russia that poor is hard put to generate enough domestic
demand to make the economy grow. The statistics bear that out,
Frenkel says: exports are driving the recovery, accounting for more
than $8 of every $10 of growth in the gross domestic product.
</P>
<P>
   Russian exports have boomed because the fallen ruble has made
them exceptionally cheap. But most are raw materials like timber,
chemicals and especially high-priced oil that are going to a world
whose appetite for commodities is increasingly sated.
</P>
<P>
   Exporting consumer goods is a non-starter; most remain too
shoddy or poorly marketed to sell abroad. Some of those same goods
have prospered at home because of another crisis-borne opportunity:
the chance to fill the gaps created on store shelves after the
ruble's crash made foreign products too expensive for most people.
</P>
<P>
   But those gaps have been largely closed. To keep growing,
companies now must attract new buyers _ no easy task in a nation
whose products are not ready for export and whose citizens are too
poor to buy anyway. In fact, exports have slowed this year, and
industrial output fell in April. So did the measure of business
managers' confidence in the future.
</P>
<P>
   All that seems at odds with the brimming orders at Vologda
Textile and its kin. But in more than a few ways, Vologda Textile
epitomizes the economy's two-steps-forward, one-back quality. Like
the rest of Russia, this place has come a long way in the last few
years, yet it still has miles to go.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
