<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 19:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2219 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-ECON-ART-2NDTA     06-01 1138
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-ECON-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 VOLOGDA, Russia: to go.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   For 38 years after its founding in 1953, Vologda Textile was a
worry-free place. Its 5,000 workers had state-guaranteed jobs. The
bottom line was no concern: the state bought the output, too. In
its heyday, the factory churned out 22 million square meters of
linen _ 8.5 square miles _ a year.
</P>
<P>
   But when communism ended in 1991, Vologda Textile followed the
rest of Russian industry into a black hole. The government hastily
privatized the company. Among the harebrained schemes its new
managers chased was a switch from making textiles to making jeeps.
By the mid-'90s, the company was bankrupt.
</P>
<P>
   Vologda's regional government finally intervened, and in 1998 it
dispatched Petukhov, a dour furniture-factory manager with an
all-business attitude, to clean up the mess. A mess it was, too.
Workers had gone unpaid for three years. With a crippled factory as
the buyer for their product, farmers had stopped growing flax, and
cultivation had plummeted from 200,000 acres in the early '90s to a
paltry 6,000 acres in 1998. Exports were a fantasy: the ancient
looms produced linen that was only 100-centimeters wide for a world
market that only bought cloth 150 centimeters wide.
</P>
<P>
   That said, Vologda Textile had some advantages. For one, Russia
was posed to prosper in the world textile business, if it could
only control costs.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Europe, the textile industry is shutting down,'' Petukhov
said. ``Labor costs are very expensive in Europe, and fabrics
produced in Europe are very expensive. Since we're all in a single
economy now, the centers of textile production have been moving
east to Russia, Ukraine and other places.''
</P>
<P>
   Also, the region's government was already pushing the sorts of
economic reforms that Putin is pressing on the federal parliament.
The region's new governor, Vyacheslav Y. Pozgalev, exempted
businesses from all taxes provided that they poured the savings
back into their companies. He loaned money to flax farmers and
equipment to see them through the fiscal dry spell between planting
and harvest. And he gave Vologda Textile a break on electricity
prices and a hefty order of linen to get it back on its feet.
</P>
<P>
   It also helped that clothing is one of life's essentials. ``When
people's income fell after the crash, lots of them became poor,''
Frankel observed. ``And when you're poor, all you can afford is
food and clothes.'' The crash of '98 solved Vologda Textile's
competitiveness woes: almost overnight, the ruble's plunge made its
linen four times cheaper to foreign buyers. Ordinary Russians
bought, too, because they had to. Nationally, textile production
shot up 20 percent in 1999, even as other industries struggled
after the fiscal collapse.
</P>
<P>
   But none of that might have helped had the factory not
bootstrapped itself into profitability. The management slashed the
workforce to 1,300, ending the featherbedding that was a staple of
Soviet factory life. The government shut the monolithic trade
agency that marketed textiles abroad, so Petukhov began hawking his
wares, and building relationships, at trade shows in Milan, Paris
and New York.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   As in most Russian industry, new equipment was too expensive. So
over a year, workers rebuilt 400 looms to produce 150-centimeter
fabric and fired up a foundry to make hard-to-get spare parts.
</P>
<P>
   Linen-making is bewilderingly complex, entailing 80 operations
from flax to cloth, and plates on the big looms and thread-making
machines reveal service dates stretching back as far as the 1970s.
That is consistent with the rest of Russia, where machinery is on
the average over 16 years old, twice what it was in 1970.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   As the result of all the changes Vologda Textile will sell 6
million meters of linen this year _ well below historic totals, but
enough to make a profit. Next year, the goal is 8 million meters.
</P>
<P>
   Exports have rocketed to 80 percent of sales, with Italy and the
United States the primary customers. Petukhov also has paid off
back wages. That helped workers, who make between 31 cents and 46
cents an hour, or $50 to $70 a month, for mind-numbing and
unhealthy work. ``American workers would never work for such
wages,'' Petukhov grumbled.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   On the assembly line, 37-year-old Tatyana Naidyonova, an apron
covering her Harley-Davidson tee-shirt, paused from cleaning a
machine with kerosene and agreed. ``It's not much money,'' she
said. ``But where else can you get any more?'' Raises will have to
wait until the plant can sell more and better linen.
</P>
<P>
   For that, Petukhov is eyeing a new production line for batik,
and a bleaching line that will accept 150-centimeter linen without
bunching it up and causing streaks.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Pozgalev, the governor, says private investors, this time with
experience, could buy the factory by year's end. His eventual goal,
and Petukhov's, is to move from a supplier of basic cloth to a
producer of more profitable dyed and refined fabrics _ and
eventually to make and export clothes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have only to solve the problem of the quality of our
material and little by little increase the volume,'' Petukhov said.
``What's needed is that in Russia we produce as much as possible,
and buy as little as possible abroad.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   That is a long way away. The factory still faces basic problems
and Soviet mindsets at every turn. One example: linen production is
severely crimped by the supply of local flax, which is in turn
limited by the state's utter failure to replace Soviet-style
collective farming and put in place sound management. So Vologda
Textile has been forced to buy higher-priced flax from Belgium,
France and the Netherlands, which is slapped with a 15 percent
customs duty. That raises Vologda Textile's costs, and lowers
sales.
</P>
<P>
   The factory also has to navigate the Gordian customs office,
which inexplicably follows the factory's processing of imported
flax into cloth even after the duty is paid and the reedy plant is
made into thread.
</P>
<P>
   The factory is peppered with tags on various machines reserving
them exclusively for imported flax under customs supervision. Asked
why, Petukhov said dryly: ``We have a bureaucracy in this country.
You probably have one in America, too.''
</P>
<P>
   The problem of using imported flax may be solved soon; local
flax production should jump by two-thirds, to 25,000 acres, next
year.
</P>
<P>
   For now, though, Vologda Textile must import some 40 percent of
its raw material from Europe. That lifts costs. But Petukhov savors
the irony. ``For once,'' he says, ``we're importing our raw
materials from the West, instead of the other way around.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
