<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CNN-AOL0602-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AOL's Case looks forward to merger
 &HT;    By Russell Grantham
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ America Online Chairman Steve Case said a recently
announced management shuffle following AOL's pending merger with
Time Warner will allow him to work with one of his ``heroes,'' Ted
Turner, to map the media giant's future.
</P>
<P>
   Both Case and Turner, Time Warner's vice chairman and currently
head of its Turner cable TV empire, took pains Thursday to counter
news reports that Turner was unhappy with the reorganization.
</P>
<P>
   Case said he and Turner will be ``joined at the hip'' and will
be responsible for exploring future technological and business
opportunities after the merger, which will combine businesses
ranging from the Atlanta Hawks to CNN to Time magazine to AOL's
Internet service.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ted and I will be freed to think strategically about where the
next opportunities will be,'' he said Thursday at the a luncheon
speech before hundreds of CNN correspondents and other guests at
its annual CNN World Report Conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``For many years, Ted has been one of my heroes,'' he said,
adding that he was ``enthralled'' when he heard Turner speak in the
late 1970s. He said Turner's tenacity in launching the
around-the-clock CNN news channel inspired him during his own
efforts to keep AOL going.
</P>
<P>
   But recent news reports have said Turner complained about a
reorganization plan announced last month in which Turner will no
longer head the Time Warner division that includes CNN and other
units he brought into the company in a 1995 merger.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, Time Warner Chairman Gerald Levin and AOL
President Robert Pittman said Turner, who will remain vice
chairman, will have a bigger role in the company.
</P>
<P>
   The merger goes to a shareholder vote of both companies on June
23, but must also win approval from government regulators.
</P>
<P>
   Turner told journalists after the luncheon that he was ``happy
as a clam.''
</P>
<P>
   He batted aside questions about his role in the company and his
plans after the merger.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't even merged yet. It's business as usual. But
obviously, I'm happy. I'm happy as a clam,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He said his daily routine won't change much. ``I'm going to have
my bowl of Wheaties every morning,'' he joked before ducking into a
men's room, with several journalists following.
</P>
<P>
   ``And guess what?'' he added a few minutes later. ``I'm even
happier now.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
