<P>
   GERMANY-MAGAZINE (Frankfurt) _ Suddeutsche Zeitung, one of
Germany's most respected newspapers, has apologized to its readers
and fired the two top editors of its magazine supplement over
apparently phony interviews with American celebrities written by
Tom Kummer, regarded as one of the hottest young journalists in
Germany. By Edmund L. Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-POLITICS (Queretaro, Mexico) _ The presidential campaign
has opened a vast demographic divide between the old and new
Mexicos, a political fault line that runs smack through the
Martinez household, tucked along a tidy suburban street here. By
Sam Dillon.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-GOLF (Tokyo) _ During the 1980s, few things reflected
Japan's exploding wealth better than its sudden madness for golf.
By the end of the decade there were 2,400 courses, covering an area
roughly triple the size of Tokyo itself. Lavish clubhouses included
expensive artwork from masters like Chagall and Monet and solid
gold fixtures. Bankers and promoters were financing memberships _
for up to $200,000 each _ as investments that they predicted would
take off like a well-hit tee shot. But the golf club investment
craze ran into trouble when Japan's economic bubble burst 10 years
ago. Now, at least 1,700 of the country's golf courses are bankrupt
or in financial trouble. And the lenders who financed the courses
and the individual memberships are desperately trying to contain
one of the the economy's biggest problems. By Howard W. French.
</P>
<P>
   (MOVED)
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in the ``w'' news file.)
