r e BC-TV-WEEKEND02-COX     06-01 0676
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-WEEKEND02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Roundup of TV hightlights for the week
 &HT;    By Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News ServiceFriday
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QR;  New York Yankees at Atlanta Braves (7:35 p.m. on TBS) _ The
first of a three-game interleague series is a rematch of last
October's World Series.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Twenty Years of Stories: This is CNN'' (9 p.m. on CNN) _
Larry King hosts part two of the news network's retrospective,
which covers the second decade. Of course, with the Yankees-Braves
game airing opposite, this isn't exactly going to bang the Nielsen
gong here in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Saved By the Bell'' (10 a.m. on NBC) _ I believe it was
Homer Simpson who once said, ``Oh, that Screech! He cracks me up!''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Passport to Paris'' (8 p.m. on the Family Channel) _
Whatever happened to the Olsen twins, Mary-Kate and Ashley,
formerly of ``Full House''? They're on the Family Channel in a new
movie, headed to Paris, and getting boyfriends. Obviously, the
apocalypse draws nigh.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Harlan County War'' (8 p.m. on Showtime) _ Conyers' own
Holly Hunter stars in this new movie, based on the same true events
covered in the 1976 documentary ``Harlan County U.S.A.'' With a
rural Kentucky accent that's almost impenetrable at times, Hunter
plays the wife of a coal miner who gets involved in unionizing the
mines.
</P>
<P>
   Movies
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Singin' in the Rain' (10 p.m. Friday on Turner Classic
Movies) _ Movie about one actress (Debbie Reynolds) who dubs her
voice for another (Jean Hagen). And of course, there's Gene Kelly.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``My Fair Lady'' (Noon Sunday on American Movie Classics) _
Movie in which one singer (Marni Nixon) dubbed her voice for
another (Audrey Hepburn). And of course, there's Rex Harrison.
</P>
<P>
   Best Bet
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``The Tony Awards'' (9 p.m. Sunday on CBS)
</P>
<P>
   Of the traditional big four TV awards shows (Oscar, Emmy,
Grammy, Tony), the Tonys generally have the best production
numbers, and why shouldn't they? While the others usually throw
together kitsch and rehearse a couple of times, the Tonys, honoring
Broadway theater, use the best production numbers from the best
shows, performed by the pros who do it eight times a week.
</P>
<P>
   Tonight, as usual, the hot competition is in the musical revival
category, where ``The Music Man'' (represented by ``76
Trombones''), ``Kiss Me Kate'' (``Too Darn Hot'') and ``Jesus
Christ Superstar'' (``Superstar,'' ``Gethsemane'') are competing.
</P>
<P>
   Rosie O'Donnell returns as host, and presenters (all of whom
have done at least some theater work in their careers) include
Kathie Lee Gifford, Kelsey Grammer, Bernadette Peters, Carol
Burnett, Nathan Lane and Susan Lucci.
</P>
<P>
   And if you want a total Tony wallow, WGTV airs an hour of lesser
awards from 8-9 p.m. before CBS takes over.
</P>
<P>
   Second-Best Bet
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Sex and the City'' (9 p.m. Sunday on HBO)
</P>
<P>
   The four single women whose lives are chronicled in HBO's series
``Sex and the City'' are as shallow as a stack of Waffle House hash
browns. And yet they remain perversely fascinating (as well as
fascinatingly perverse).
</P>
<P>
   It could be the great clothes they're always wearing. It could
be the great bedroom romps they're always having. But mostly, it's
the writing. Without writers providing them with bons mots (i.e.,
if they were real), these gals would hardly be worth the bother of
ignoring.
</P>
<P>
   Back for a third season of 18 episodes starting Sunday, ``S&AMP;C''
stars Sarah Jessica Parker as sex columnist Carrie Bradshaw, and
her three friends: sleep-around Samantha (Kim Cattrall), cynic
Miranda (Cynthia Nixon) and idealist Charlotte (Kristin Davis).
</P>
<P>
   In the first two episodes, Carrie is wooed and won by an older
politican who turns out to have a very kinky fantasy that'll make
you go ``Eeeeewww.'' Typical ``S&AMP;C'' fare, but there's some
substance as well, as the women ponder the power of old fairy tales
and wonder whether they just want a strong man to rescue them.
</P>
<P>
   Phil Kloer writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
