<HEADER>
A2229 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-BOOK-NOTES01-COX     06-01 0576
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-NOTES01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ex-publicist is living other side of the story
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   For years, Jane Heller was a New York publicist who promoted
such authors as Stephen King and Mary Higgins Clark on their way to
the top.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never once said, `I wish I could do what you're doing,'''
Heller said in a telephone interview this week. ``Then I got
promoted to vice president and the job wasn't as much fun. So I
quit.''
</P>
<P>
   She free-lanced for a while for Waldenbooks and then she got an
idea for a humorous novel about the stock market. Published in
1994, ``Cha Cha Cha'' was bought by the Literary Guild and optioned
for a television movie. Suddenly the woman who had helped publicize
other authors had her own publicist.
</P>
<P>
   Six years and six novels later, the 50-year-old Stuart, Fla.,
author has become a sort of queen of beach books. Julia Roberts'
movie company, Shoelace Productions, has bought the rights to her
sixth novel, ``Sis Boom Bah,'' and USA Today touted Heller's
latest, ``Name Dropping'' (St. Martin's, $24.95), as a great summer
read.
</P>
<P>
   Set in New York, ``Name Dropping'' is the comic tale of a
preschool teacher whose life is turned upside down when a glamorous
celebrity magazine writer with the same name moves into her
apartment building. Suddenly the teacher begins getting flowers and
invitations to gala parties.
</P>
<P>
   ``In all my books, I write about ordinary women who get
themselves into and out of trouble and discover a new
self-confidence. They're all my alter egos.''
</P>
<P>
   As for being labeled a beach book author, Heller considers it a
compliment. ``I read serious fiction that tackles serious themes,
but I think there's also a place for old-fashioned, escapist
fiction. People need to laugh and people need to relax. If I can do
that for people, I feel pretty good.''
</P>
<P>
   Heller will sign books at 7 p.m. Monday at Chapter 11 bookstore
at Northlake (2100 Henderson Mill Road, 770-414-9288).
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Quick reads: Book lovers looking for an out-of-print or
hard-to-find title may have an easier search now. Lightning Source
(www.lightningsource.com) has teamed up with Amazon.com to offer
more than 9,000 titles for printing-on-demand. The books, which are
stored electronically in a digital library, can be printed
immediately and sent to Amazon.com for shipment. The books can be
delivered in a traditional printed format or as eBooks.
</P>
<P>
   Lightning Source president Ed Marino says the list of titles in
the digital library is growing at an average of 250 per week. ``As
Lightning Source's selection continues to grow,'' he said,
``Amazon.com will be able to offer additional hard-to-find titles
to its customers.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  New deals: Michael Jordan is collaborating with Washington
Post sports columnist Michael Wilbon on a sequel, ``A Whole New
Ballgame: Michael Jordan Comes to Washington.'' The book, which
will examine Jordan's new career with the Washington Wizards, will
be published in fall 2001 by Random House. ... Doubleday has bought
paperback rights to J. Michael Veron's surprise golf best seller,
``The Greatest Player Who Never Lived.'' Veron's sequel about a
hidden golf course near Augusta National, ``The Greatest Course
That Never Was,'' will be published next spring.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  E-mail: dobriant(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Don O'Briant writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
