<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 20:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2231 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-ROMANCE-NOVELS02-COX     06-01 1439
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROMANCE-NOVELS02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The latest generation of romance novels goes beyond the
bodice-ripper formula, reflecting real life
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Barbara Cartland died recently, it marked the end of an era
of ``no sex, please'' romance novels.
</P>
<P>
   But the romance genre had been in the midst of a revolution long
before the British author's demise.
</P>
<P>
   Remember Fabio? The blond-tressed hunk whose bare chest was
featured on the covers of hundreds of bodice-ripper novels several
years ago now makes his living pushing margarine.
</P>
<P>
   Today's romance readers _ an impressive group that buys 54
percent of the paperback fiction published _ have changed with the
times. Yes, some covers still show partially clad dashing rogues,
but most are more tasteful, with sweeping, floral illustrations.
And the swashbuckling pirates are just as likely to be found in the
nursery changing diapers.
</P>
<P>
   These are not your mother's romance novels.
</P>
<P>
   Plots that once focused on trembling virgins waiting to be
rescued by Prince Charming now feature strong, independent women
dealing with corporate infighting, office romances, adoption,
single motherhood and family life.
</P>
<P>
   Today's heroines are about as helpless as Scarlett O'Hara, says
Nora Roberts, who has penned 134 novels since 1981, racking up
sales of more than 106 million copies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to write about someone who is sitting around
mooning at the window saying, `Someday my prince will come.' That's
not what the American woman believes or wants to read,'' she says.
``This is the woman who has her own life and is fulfilled within
herself, but who wants to find a man who is right for her.''
</P>
<P>
   The basic story line is the same, though. Girl meets boy,
conflict keeps them apart, and in the end they all live happily
ever after.
</P>
<P>
   ``In today's romances,'' Roberts adds, ``the reader will see
more of the hero's point of view, his internal thoughts, than they
did in the '70s and early '80s. Back then, it was written all from
the heroine's point of view. Now it's 50-50, or even more from the
male point of view.''
</P>
<P>
   Roberts, who cut her teeth on romance novels, has added suspense
to her plots and become a best-selling hardback novelist. Others,
including Georgia writer Deborah Smith, have followed the same
path.
</P>
<P>
   ``These bigger books tend to mix romance, family drama and maybe
a dash of suspense or mystery,'' says Smith, the author of ``Blue
Willow'' and ``A Place to Call Home.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Home, family, middle-class values, love and commitment have
always formed the core of the romance novel,'' Smith says.
``Despite shifts in styles and attitudes, tweaking the details,
updating the approach, at heart the books remain a celebration of
those ideals and society's attitude toward them at the moment.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the formula, apparently it's exactly what women want. A
1999 study commissioned by the Romance Writers of America showed
that 37.9 million women had read at least one romance novel in the
previous year.
</P>
<P>
   Romance novels began as cheap paperbacks after World War II,
featuring heroines who were nurses, secretaries or teachers.
</P>
<P>
   ``They fell in love with their bosses or other powerful male
figures,'' says Marietta writer Sandra Chastain. ``Women were still
seen as figures who remained in the home throughout the '50s and
'60s. The success of the romance novel may have come about because
the readers longed to escape, longed for excitement and adventure.
The romances during that time featured women who were pretty
passive.''
</P>
<P>
   The women's movement of the '60s and '70s brought more sex to
the novels, along with plots that had the heroine being swept away
by the hero. By the '80s, the women characters played a more active
role and lived more adventurous lives.
</P>
<P>
   In the past decade, Chastain says, women have traveled the
world, become corporate directors who are wealthy and in a position
to choose their lifestyles.
</P>
<P>
   Now there's another change taking place. Author Jennifer Blake
sees a new generation of readers ``who have seen liberation,
enjoyed it, but find it commonplace.'' These women now want home
and family and traditional values of the kind their grandmothers
knew back in the 1940s and '50s.
</P>
<P>
   ``That accounts for the abundance of books with marriage, babies
and cowboys on the covers and as subjects,'' says Chastain, one of
the founders of the Georgia Romance Writers group. ``We're back to
John Wayne, Mom and apple pie. Women go `home' again, searching for
their roots and looking for the boy next door.''
</P>
<P>
   That, incidentally, is the plot for Roberts' recent best seller
``Carolina Moon.'' The heroine returns to her hometown in South
Carolina to open a shop and try to solve the murder of a childhood
friend. Of course, in the process she falls in love with her dead
friend's brother.
</P>
<P>
   Other changes are affecting romance novels as well: among them,
the disappearance of publishers and the emergence of e-books.
Subgenres have sprung up as well. BET Arabesque and Genesis are
publishing African-American romances; Steeple Hill, Multnomah and
Barbour are focusing on inspirational novels; and Kensington has
just released a line of Latin American romances written in Spanish
and English in the same volume.
</P>
<P>
   ``The changes have been positive for women of color,'' says
Carmen Green (``Endless Love,'' ``Sister, Sister''). ``In 1994,
Kensington started the Arabesque line of books written by and
targeted to the African-American female audience. What they
discovered is that women between the ages of 18 and 80 loved these
stories.''
</P>
<P>
   Although predominantly read by black women, the stories are
inclusive of every race. The types of plots that are hot right now,
Green says, are stories that depict families.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did a series starting with `Silken Love' and `Keeping
Secrets,' featuring the Crawford family. I never planned a third
story, but because of the positive response, I've written `Endless
Love,' the final story about the family.''
</P>
<P>
   African-American relationships are essentially no different from
white relationships, she adds. The characters typically have to
overcome some type of obstacle to achieve their goal. There are a
few subtle differences, though, she adds.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can identify with common situations like
blue-light-in-the-basement parties, barbecue in the yard on the
Fourth of July, banding together, breaking apart or remembering the
deep emotions at Grandma's funeral.''
</P>
<P>
   And then there's the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before the online bookstores emerged,'' says author Stephanie
Bond, ``readers were at the mercy of shrinking shelf space
dominated by a handful of best-selling authors. ... But now romance
readers, who are notoriously voracious, go online to find more of
what they like, to make new discoveries and to share their likes
and dislikes in chat forums. Since many romance authors have their
own Web sites, the reader feels more connected to the writer and
the book.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith, meanwhile, has been signed as one of the first authors to
be published in Time Warner's eBook program through its iPublish
division. The 50,000-word book ``Alice at Heart'' will be produced
solely in digital format. No publishing date has been set, but the
story revolves around a young woman who learns she has an island
legacy including three aging half-sisters who claim to be mermaids.
</P>
<P>
   Harlequin Books, the world's largest publisher of women's
fiction, has turned to the Internet (www.eHarlequin.com) to foster
more interest in the genre. The Web site offers information about
all things romantic, including a book that is serialized each week.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, MightyWords (www.mightywords.com) launched two new
e-romance series, ``The Lipstick Chronicles'' and ``Seven Deadly
Sins'' ($2.50 per installment).
</P>
<P>
   ``The Lipstick Chronicles'' _ described as a cross between
``Ally McBeal'' and ``Sex and the City'' _ is the story of five
feisty women who run Allheart.com, an online greeting card company
in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seven Deadly Sins'' features 28 installments of four short
romances dealing, of course, with each sin. Romance writers
contributing are Mary Jo Putney, Jennifer Blake, Stella Cameron and
Justine Dare.
</P>
<P>
   No matter what format is used to tell the stories, however, one
thing remains the same, Chastain says.
</P>
<P>
   ``In pure romance, the one requirement for women who read and
write romance is that there has to be an uplifting or happy
ending.''
</P>
<P>
   Don O'Briant writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
