u s BC-CAR-BRISTOL-DIRT-COX     06-01 0521
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-BRISTOL-DIRT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Dirt racing to hit Bristol
 &HT;    By Rick Minter
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dirt-track stock-car racing is set to run what is expected to be
its breakthrough event this weekend at Bristol Motor Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   The concrete surface used during Winston Cup and Busch Grand
National series races has been covered with 18 inches of clay, and
the Woodstock-based Hav-A-Tampa Dirt Racing Series is set to run
races tonight and Saturday. The World of Outlaws sprint car series
will be at Bristol on June 9-10.
</P>
<P>
   Wayne Estes, who is promoting the races at Bristol, grew up
watching stock cars at the now-defunct Peach Bowl in Atlanta and at
Dixie Speedway in Woodstock, where stock cars still race on dirt
every Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   The HAT series race at Bristol is much like the first NASCAR
Winston Cup race at Indianapolis Motor Speedway, Estes said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a breakthrough event,'' he said. ``There are drivers who
have always dreamed of running at Bristol, but their career paths
took them somewhere other than the Winston Cup circuit.''
</P>
<P>
   More than 100 drivers already have told series officials that
they are planning to try to earn one of the 30 starting positions.
</P>
<P>
   The races also will be a chance for dirt-racing fans to
experience the amenities of a first-class speedway. And a chance
for people who normally watch NASCAR races from air-conditioned
suites to see a dirt race.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be 5,000 people in the suites this weekend, and
many of them have never seen a dirt race,'' Estes said.
</P>
<P>
   Speedway officials are expecting as many as 30,000 spectators.
However, the number won't approach a sellout, because Bristol can
accommodate more than 150,000 people.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the response has been more than Estes and others
expected.
</P>
<P>
   ``We way underestimated the potential of these dirt races,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Last weekend, The Dirt Track at Lowe's Motor Speedway, a
half-mile dirt oval adjacent to the superspeedway, opened to a
capacity crowd for its first race, a World of Outlaws sprint-car
race.
</P>
<P>
   More than 12,000 people attended a preliminary feature Thursday,
and more than 19,000 packed in to see Friday's main event.
</P>
<P>
   Estes said the HAT series and the World of Outlaws are drawing
well because they put on a good show. And their top drivers, such
as Scott Bloomquist and Sammy Swindell, have name recognition among
race fans in general.
</P>
<P>
   ``They run side by side, they do a lot of passing, and they
don't mind bumping into each other,'' Estes said. ``And for a $35
ticket, fans can see preliminary races, six heats, a last-chance
race and the feature race.''
</P>
<P>
   Swindell tested at Bristol last week and ran a lap at 141.088
mph in his sprint car, and Bloomquist's Late Model went 121.443
mph. Winston Cup driver Steve Park holds the record for stock cars
at 126.370 mph.
</P>
<P>
   Bloomquist, a veteran driver and the all-time HAT win leader,
was in awe of the track after his test run.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a fast, demanding race track,'' he said, ``for both
man and machine.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
