u i BC-ELIAN-MIAMI-COX     06-01 0792
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELIAN-MIAMI-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `What injustice! What injustice!'
 &HT;    By Mark Bixler
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ The news hit hard in Little Havana.
</P>
<P>
   It came to Northwest Second Street from a yellow-and-black radio
tuned to WAQI-AM (710), a Cuban station called Radio Mambi. Dozens
of people were huddled around the radio in front of the house where
Elian Gonzalez lived for six months when the announcer delivered
the blow from Atlanta at 11:03 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a decision against the lawyers of the family of Elian
Gonzalez. . . `` he said in Spanish.
</P>
<P>
   A young man cursed. Lips quivered. You could hear gasps from the
crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Fishermen found Elian on an inner tube off Fort Lauderdale last
Thanksgiving. His mother drowned trying to bring him here from
Cuba. Elian's Miami relatives want the government to give him
political asylum, but his father wants to take him to Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   When three judges of the 11th Circuit U.S. Court of Appeals in
Atlanta announced their decision Thursday that Elian, 6, is too
young to apply for asylum, it unleashed emotions here.
</P>
<P>
   ``What injustice! What injustice!'' cried Norma Bayez, a
58-year-old Cuban-American.
</P>
<P>
   She was one of about 100 people in the street in front of the
house where Elian used to live, there to protest the government's
handling of the case. At least one woman at the house Thursday was
overcome by heat and emotion_or perhaps a combination of the two.
An ambulance took her away.
</P>
<P>
   Police reported no arrests or violence in the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Lazaro Astengo, an unemployed security guard who came here from
Cuba in 1979, shouted and cut the air with his hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't trust no more in the government because they're a
bunch of traitors! Now we don't trust the justice system of this
country!'' he said. ``I lost my hope about this country. I thought
this was the best country in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Leaders of Miami's powerful Cuban community urged calm.
</P>
<P>
   Ramon Saul Sanchez, leader of the Democracia Movement, said he
expected demonstrations beyond the shouting and sign-waving that
defined Northwest Second Street immediately before and after word
spread of the decision in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very disappointed,'' he said. ``There are cases in which
the voice of a child should be heard.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he and other Cuban-American leaders were talking about a
flotilla that would sail toward Cuba, stopping just short of its
territorial waters, as a symbolic escort for Elian should the
courts determine that his father can take him back to the island.
</P>
<P>
   ``America is about freedom and about giving people the
opportunity to live in freedom, and we haven't done that with Elian
Gonzalez,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Lt. Bill Schwartz, spokesman for the Miami Police Department,
said officers planned to keep a low profile but were ready for any
unrest that might erupt. He said no cops were working overtime
Thursday, but some plainclothes officers were keeping riot gear
within reach, just in case.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our intelligence tells us we won't need them,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Jose Basulto, founder of the anti-Castro group Brothers to the
Rescue, spent several hours answering reporters' questions. He was
walking towards a radio reporter in the shade when Astengo, the
27-year-old former security guard, raced up and draped his right
arm on Basulto's shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   ``Senor Basulto! Tenemos que hacer algo!'' he said. ``Mr.
Basulto! We have to do something!''
</P>
<P>
   Just what could be done, though, was not clear. Basulto said the
lawyers would make the next move, perhaps an appeal to the U.S.
Supreme Court. The demonstrators, meanwhile, tried to comfort each
other as they lingered for hours in front of the house. Elian's
relatives no longer live there, but it has become a shrine.
</P>
<P>
   About 35 signs hang from a chain-link fence out front. One shows
Elian nailed to a cross and asks the world not to crucify him.
Several demonstrators wore T-shirts that each showed the photo of a
federal agent forcibly retrieving Elian during an April 22 raid in
the house. The red block letters above and below the picture varied
from shirt to shirt, from ``Federal Child Abuse'' to ``The First
Infamous Crime of the New Millenium'' to ``Elian_Miami is With
You.''
</P>
<P>
   People in the protest shirts tried to encourage each other all
afternoon. Many see it as far more than a custody fight. They see
it instead as a struggle against the communist system that Fidel
Castro imposed on Cuba in 1959.
</P>
<P>
   One woman reproached another who could not seem to stop crying.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what Fidel wants _ to see us crying,'' she implored.
``We need to be strong and show him that we're better than he is.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
