<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEN-MEDIA-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN NO NEWS IS GOOD NEWS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOM HOFFARTH  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Say goodbye to the Sports Illustrated cover jinx.
</P>
<P>
   It's been replaced by Anna Kournikova, the new SI cover minx.
</P>
<P>
   Subscribers to the magazine who opened their mailboxes this week
might have thought there was a sequel to the swimsuit edition.
Nope. Just Anna, showing us what the phrase ``bedroom eyes'' means
as she clutches a pillow in a shoulderless blouse framed by her
ravishing mane of blonde hair on the June 5 issue.
</P>
<P>
   Breathtaking.
</P>
<P>
   If the tennis tart made the magazine's cover every week, who'd
complain?
</P>
<P>
   You'd be surprised.
</P>
<P>
   ``We get second-guessed on our covers 45 out of 52 weeks,
especially when there's a feature cover,'' SI managing editor Bill
Colson said Thursday morning as the issue began to make local
newsstand vendors reconsider whether ID checks were needed to sell
this one.
</P>
<P>
   ``Someone always thinks there's a news event more important than
whatever feature we have,'' Colson added.
</P>
<P>
   Such as this week, with the NBA conference finals, the NHL
Stanley Cup Finals and the Indianapolis 500 all colliding over
Memorial Day weekend.
</P>
<P>
   But there's also the French Open, which Kournikova was competing
in. Until Thursday, when she lost her second-round match.
</P>
<P>
   Not that SI expected her to win. That's the point of the story.
</P>
<P>
   And that's what intrigued preeminent sports journalist Frank
Deford to pitch the piece to Colson.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Jezebel of Sweat,'' Deford calls her in the story. ``At a
time when we are all supposed to be so gender-enlightened, when
pretty isn't supposed to matter anymore in the workplace,
especially in such a meritocratic domain as sports . . . here is
what Kournikova proves about Homo sapiens, male division, circa
2000: Skin-deep still counts.''
</P>
<P>
   How true.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a bona fide story, so why not put it on the cover when
there's a little lull (in the sports world)?'' asked Colson. ``We
obviously wanted to do it in a tasteful way, in a fun, journalistic
way. Why now? The playoffs in basketball and hockey go on for
months. We could put them on the cover every week. We had a
basketball cover last week and will probably have one next week.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is just different. We hardly ever do a cover like this.''
</P>
<P>
   Except every February when some women in (name an exotic locale)
do work on their Victoria's Secret resume.
</P>
<P>
   Which gave Colson a thought about Kournikova.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe she'll do the swimsuit issue next year,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Hopefully.
</P>
<P>
   __ More titillation: Under the headline ``Sweetness: Fox Media
Star Lisa Guerrero has the Hottest Moves in the Business'' is Sport
magazine's idea of a feature on the L.A. TV journalist in its June
issue.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, and by the way, there's a picture of Sweet Lisa with her
hair pulled up, laying out on a blue leather couch in some kind of
black get-up that has the author of the story, Darryl Howerton,
tripping all over his media credential.
</P>
<P>
   ``During the interview, it wasn't like his tongue was hanging
out,'' said Guerrero, in Detroit this week working on FX's
``Toughman'' competition show. ``I thought the story and picture
was very nice and flattering. That's who I am. I don't get hung up
on it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe I should care more about (my image in that light), but
it's just fun and sports. It's not as if I'm some hardcore news
journalist.''
</P>
<P>
   As she was trying to be with Hugh Downs for Fox's live tomb
excavation special from Egypt two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very fine line,'' continued Guerrero, who next week
will shoot a magazine cover for Women's World Weekly (a fitness
publication) and Oye (an Hispanic men's publication). ``From a
programming and magazine standpoint, you need someone attractive to
sell. Hopefully, I'm not crossing that line.''
</P>
<P>
   __ A classy 20 years: As Cable News Network celebrates two
decades of operation this week _ it went on the air June 1, 1980 _
``Sports Tonight,'' which started with Fred Hickman and Nick
Charles, deserves recognition for its commitment to journalism in a
cable sports field fighting for viewer attention.
</P>
<P>
   CNN's sports division, which has produced such talent as Keith
Olbermann, Dan Patrick, Hannah Storm, Dan Hicks and Van Earl
Wright, finds itself under the watch of Jim Walton. He began at CNN
as a news journalist in '81, switched to sports as a tape editor in
'83 and vaulted to executive producer in '85 after his work for the
network on coverage of the '84 Los Angeles Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   ``The early days of CNN were a time when there was not enough
resources to do what we wanted to do,'' Walton said. ``It was
nonunion, so we all did everything. And we learned from a great
person in Bill MacPhail (hired by Ted Turner to run the operation
after his days at CBS Sports).''
</P>
<P>
   As ESPN and Fox have developed their own wacky ways of
presenting sports, CNN remains a reliable alternative, available in
many forms. Aside from the 24-hour CNN-SI channel, the ``Sports
Tonight'' hosted by Hickman and Vince Cellini is the news show's
main sports element. Then there's the 20- and 50-minute updates on
CNN Headline News and an affiliate feed service that provides many
local TV stations (including all in L.A.) video highlight packages.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot depends on what you want,'' admits Walton. ``Some go
after the laugh or the fancy graphics, and some go after substance.
That's just society. Different people like different things.''
</P>
<P>
   WHAT SMOKES &QL;
</P>
<P>
   __ Joe McDonnell's year-and-a-half disappearance from regular
sports talk ends Sunday night with a KABC-AM (790) show from 9 p.m.
to 1 a.m. _ the same time slot he used to have great success with
years ago on KFI-AM (640). ``That's what's so appealing _ it'll be
just like the old days,'' said McDonnell, who'll continue doing
sports updates for all-news KFWB-AM (980) during weekday afternoon
drive-time. Another old twist to this gig: Columnist Doug
Krikorian, who worked with McDonnell at the old KMPC when it was an
all-sports station on 710-AM a few years back, rejoins his
partner. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   __ CBS NFL analyst Sam Wyche, who was supposed to do work on The
Nashville Network's coverage of Arena Football League games this
season, will have surgery next month to have vocal cords repaired.
They were mistakenly severed during an operation in March when
noncancerous lymph nodes were removed from his lungs. ``It's been a
nightmare,'' Wyche told the Cincinnati Post. ``My one-word opinion
of it is, it's been a nightmare. But it's all done now.'' &QL; 
WHAT CHOKES &QL;
</P>
<P>
   __ Zero tolerance for any more Bobby Knight media interviews.
Outside of Roy Firestone actually admitting during Tuesday's ESPN
egg-toss that he never saw the original CNN-SI video of The General
choking former player Neil Reed, of Knight hand-picking seven
reporters to talk to before the TV show (henceforth known as the
``Sympathetic Seven''), and then seeing the picture over the wire
services of Knight thanking ESPN stage manager Gail Green during a
break . . . sure, it was a fine piece of video journalism. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   __ The fifth season of HBO's ``Arli$$'' somehow begins Sunday.
By episode two, you'll probably be hoping that the cast of ``The
Sopranos'' rubs out Robert Wuhl. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   __ Why stop at allowing ABC Sports chief Howard Katz to waive
the green flag and officially start the Indianapolis 500? That
wasn't a ceremonial gesture _ it was the real deal. He screws up
and there's the chance of a 33-car pileup. You gotta believe NBC
Sports czar Dick Ebersol would love to toss up the opening tip for
the NBA Finals next week. But he can't. He shouldn't. Neither
should Katz, nor ABC, take advantage of their rights-fee clout by
becoming more than innocent bystanders.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
