<SLUG> BC-CONFERENCE-USA-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOMETIMES, CHANGE CAN BE GOOD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WENDELL BARNHOUSE 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ When companies _ or conferences _ redesign
their logos, it's similar to rearranging the deck chairs on the
Titanic. If the symbol that has made you famous needs changing,
then maybe you're not ... famous.
</P>
<P>
   Well, TCU's future league home has redesigned its logo.
Conference USA recently unveiled a new look. But before Frog fans
start panicking and thinking that they're joining a conference
headed down Failure Freeway, know this: C-USA's new brand is an
improvement over the original and indicates that the league is
moving forward aggressively.
</P>
<P>
   Still in its infancy, what C-USA lacks is the instant
identification that leagues such as the SEC, ACC, Big 10 and Big 12
have. From its inception five years ago, Conference USA has been,
well, a bit bulky. What the league is trying to move toward is the
kind of ``Oh, yeah'' recognition that other leagues have.
</P>
<P>
   ``In some ways, we want this logo to become our `Swoosh,' ''
C-USA commissioner Mike Slive said.
</P>
<P>
   Swoosh as in Nike's swoosh brand, the second-most recognizable
symbol in sports, right behind the dollar sign. Money, income,
brand recognition, a corporate ``mark,'' marketing,
cross-licensing. Those are all terms associated with big-time
college sports.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly, we have become a more concentrated corporate
partnership program,'' Slive said. ``This gave us a linchpin to
move in a lot of different directions. We're moving into the second
phase of the conference's life. One of our strategic goals was to
enhance the name, reputation and recognition of the league. This
gives it a kick start.''
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, C-USA presidents ordered a new logo be developed.
Conference officials won't say how much the project cost, but it
was not a shoestring operation. SME Power Branding of New York
helped design and develop the new logo.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to show the conference was progressive and unified;
we think the new logo shows that,'' said John McNamara, C-USA
associate commissioner for marketing and corporate development.
``With the expansion, adding TCU and East Carolina, the timing was
perfect to do something new. The original logo was fine, but it was
outdated.''
</P>
<P>
   What's unusual about C-USA's new logo is that it's the Swiss
Army knife of collegiate brands. It has three levels _ a formal
logo that includes the name Conference USA, a more informal one
with C-USA (which will be used on uniforms, courts and fields) and
a third logo that can be used with member school's logos and with
corporate partners. No other conference has one that is as
versatile.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the original logo featured 12 stars, one for each of the
original members. The new one has one star.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's some symbolism there,'' Slive said. ``That reinforces
the strength of the conference and the unity of our member
schools.''  &LR; subheds:Briefly C-USA's athletic directors have agreed
to basketball divisional setups to accommodate new members TCU and
East Carolina in 2001-2002. East Carolina probably would be added
to the American Division, with TCU being placed in the National
(which currently includes South Florida, Alabama-Birmingham,
Memphis, Houston, Southern Miss and Tulane). The league's
presidents are expected to vote on the AD's recommendations this
month or in August.
</P>
<P>
   ESPN's Roy Firestone, the main interviewer of Indiana coach Bob
Knight during his invitation-only media spin session this week,
didn't do much to change Knight's less-than-respectful view of
journalists. The key piece of evidence against Knight has been the
videotape of Knight with his hand on Neil Reed's neck. Firestone
admitted he had not seen the 2.3 seconds of video. With that
admission, there was no credibility to the one-hour interview.
</P>
<P>
   Virginia Tech nearly won the national championship in football
last season and is now reaping the benefits. A record 23,000 season
tickets have been sold and a $22 million, 12,000-seat expansion of
Lane Stadium is being planned. And CBS has picked the Hokies for
four national telecasts, the maximum number under its contract with
the Big East Conference.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-01-00 2017EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000601.0335 </DOCNO>
