<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 20:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2244 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-BBC-LONGHORNS-TEX     06-01 0735
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBC-LONGHORNS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS COUNTING ON TALENTED PITCHING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WHIT CANNING 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Penn State catcher Joe Puliafico took some pains this week to
assure everyone that, while the Nittany Lions may be from a faraway
land, they have dutifully kept abreast of developments.
</P>
<P>
   ``What do we know about Texas' pitching?'' he said. ``Well,
let's be honest _ we know a lot. Those guys are all over /Baseball
America''. We've read about them, and they're very impressive.''
</P>
<P>
   /Baseball America'' thanks you for the plug, Joe. And while
you're admiring the literary profiles of D.J. Jones, Beau Hale and
Charlie Thames, here's a name you haven't seen for a few months:
</P>
<P>
   Phil Seibel.
</P>
<P>
   Around the environs of Disch-Falk Field, where Texas (44-19)
will host Penn State (45-17) at 7 p.m. tonight in the opener of
abest-of-three Super Regional, Seibel's timely return has been
tantamount to a knock on the door from the prodigal son. And he
could be the final piece of the puzzle that sends the Longhorns to
the College World Series for the first time since 1993.
</P>
<P>
   He was there at the beginning of the season, when Texas pitching
seemed truly brilliant and the Longhorns rose to a No. 2 national
ranking. Having handed his 1999 closer role over to Thames, Seibel
had a 4-1 record and a 1.99 earned-run average as the Sunday
starter.
</P>
<P>
   Then on March 5, he threw a pitch against Missouri and strained
a ligament in his elbow. Rehabilitation took 2 1/2 months.
</P>
<P>
   He next pitched in the Big 12 Tournament, drawing an
experimental start and throwing 60 pitches in a game Texas
eventually lost. Then, with the Longhorns facing elimination at the
regional Sunday in Tempe, Ariz., Seibel took the mound against
Arizona State.
</P>
<P>
   This time, he stuck around for a while.
</P>
<P>
   In 6 1/3 innings, he allowed five hits, three runs _ one earned
_ walked two and struck out six. With relief help from Thames, he
picked up the victory, lowered his ERA, and vaulted the Longhorns
into a championship game against the Sun Devils, which Texas won,
9-7.
</P>
<P>
   A powerful left-hander who normally throws in the 90s, Seibel
said he ``probably isn't 100 percent yet, but this is close enough;
I'll take it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I threw everything ... fastball, slider, changeup ... and they
all worked and there was no pain. Actually, my elbow feels fine, I
just don't feel totally right with some other stuff. I feel I'm
still missing a little zip from the layoff, and I think I was in
the upper 80s. But I had good stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   During the latter part of the season, life without Seibel took a
toll on the Longhorns, who developed a debilitating habit of losing
the Sunday game in every key series. With Seibel rejoining the
rotation, coach Augie Garrido will be back in the position of
putting a strong arm on the mound in every situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Tempe, the whole pitching staff was awesome, and Phil's
return just highlighted it,'' Garrido said. ``D.J. got us off to a
good start, and the best-pitched game of the tournament may have
been the one Beau Hale lost. Plus we got a complete-game win from
Ray Clark, the first of his career.
</P>
<P>
   ``Phil gives us that extra option we haven't had for two months.
In fact, the guy who seems to be struggling right now is Charlie.
I'm thinking about maybe giving him a start, just to change the
pattern, because he's putting a lot of pressure on himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we seem to have also gotten our offense back, and we're
even hitting home runs. I think there's a little extra bounce in
our step right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Seibel, a junior from Cypress, Calif., was also putting pressure
on himself, and he figures that was a big part of the rehab
problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the reason it took so long,'' he said, ``is because
for about the first month, I kept trying to work in the bullpen and
force the injury to go away. I kept thinking maybe I could start a
game and pitch out of it. But it just kept getting worse.''
</P>
<P>
   He had his arm examined at the Jobe Clinic in California and
they prescribed a completely different rehab plan: total rest. For
the next month, he didn't pick up a baseball until throwing against
Sam Houston State two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``This may sound funny, but I think I got well when I stopped
caring about it so much. In Tempe, I had fun. I was relaxed and
just throwing the ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I'll stick with that.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
