<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-CANCER-650&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE PLEDGES TO INCREASE FEDERAL SPENDING FOR CANCER RESEARCH 
</HEADLINE>
   By JAMES DAO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA, Ga. _ Invoking World War II and the race to the moon,
Vice President Al Gore pledged on Thursday to double federal
spending on cancer research and to make ``a flood'' of new cancer
treatments and tests available to all Americans who need them.
</P>
<P>
   In a speech brimming with soaring oratory and buoyant optimism,
Gore described the nation as standing on the brink of medical
breakthroughs fueled by genetic research, and called on the federal
government to use its resources to turn those discoveries into
preventing and curing the most fatal cancers.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I am entrusted with the presidency, I will work with you to
put the same energy and priority into fighting cancer that we would
put into preventing a war that could take 500,000 American lives
every year,'' Gore, the likely Democratic nominee, told more than
600 people at Emory University Medical School. ``The stakes are
that great. We can win this war.''
</P>
<P>
   The speech offered a vivid example of the recent tactical shift
by Gore away from attacking his likely Republican rival, Gov.
George W. Bush, and toward outlining his own vision in strikingly
upbeat terms.
</P>
<P>
   All this week, Gore, who has been criticized by some Democrats
as appearing overly harsh on the campaign trail, has brought a
softer, more personal, even intimate touch to his events.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Gore and an Army friend described their experiences
in Vietnam. On Tuesday, he and his wife, Tipper, who has been
treated for depression, appeared together at a mental health forum.
And on Thursday, Gore referred to the death of his sister, Nancy,
from lung cancer and brought along her husband, Frank Hunger, to
talk to reporters.
</P>
<P>
   At Emory on Thursday, Gore outlined a multi-point plan for
battling cancer, portions of which he had discussed before. He
called for doubling, to $9 billion, the amount the federal
government will spend over the next five years on cancer research.
He advocated legislation to make clinical trials available to more
adults and to require Medicare to pay for more cancer-screening
tests. And he vowed to make changes to the Food and Drug
Administration that would speed the approval of new cancer drugs.
</P>
<P>
   The address was short on policy details but long on sweeping
phrases and historical analogies meant to inspire his audience. For
example, Gore cited President John F. Kennedy's vow to put a man on
the moon 40 years ago as a precedent for his own ambitious goal: to
end all deaths from colon, breast and prostate cancer by the year
2010.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some say it is impossible to find the answer to many forms of
cancer,'' Gore said. ``I don't agree. One hundred years ago they
said the same thing about smallpox. And 60 years ago they said the
same thing about polio. They were wrong then. The pioneers and
activists such as all of you convince me that the naysayers are
wrong again now.''
</P>
<P>
   He also likened the mapping of the human genome, the template
for genetic traits, to the Allies' breaking Nazi Germany's military
code in World War II. The genome map, which is nearing completion,
is widely expected to hasten the development of new drugs and
screening tests for serious diseases.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are on the verge of cracking another enemy secret code,''
Gore said. ``This enemy kills more Americans every single year than
all the Americans who died throughout the entirety of World War II.
When we intercept the messages that cancer sends secretly coded
from cell to cell, we are going to turn the tide. We will gain the
ability to decisively win the war against cancer.''
</P>
<P>
   The vice president reiterated his support for having the Food
and Drug Administration regulate tobacco to prevent cigarette
companies from selling ``deadly products'' to adolescents. Teen
smoking, he said, was ``the number one preventable form of death
and disease in America today.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   During the 1996 Democratic National Convention, Gore gave a now
famous speech in which he described with searing detail the death
of his older sister, Nancy, from lung cancer in 1984. The address,
meant to highlight the Clinton administration's war on smoking,
brought tears to some convention-goers eyes. But it also prompted
critics to suggest that Gore had exploited a painful family chapter
for political gain.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Gore obliquely referred to his sister's death
without mentioning her. But he tried to show that her illness had
changed him, giving him an emotional bond with cancer victims and
infusing him with a passion to see the disease cured.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know from my own family's experience what cancer can do to a
family,'' he said. ``Many of us here have made sense of a loss by
rededicating ourselves to the hope of a cure for other's loved
ones.''
</P>
<P>
   The event also started on an tearful note as the man who
introduced Gore, Patrick Kardian, repeatedly choked up as he
described his own battle with Hodgkins Disease. At one point, Gore
wrapped an arm around Kardian and whispered in his ear, ``You're
doing great.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the proposals outlined by Mr. Gore were the following:
</P>
<P>
   _ Speeding up the process for having Medicare, the government
health care program for the elderly and disabled, pay for new
diagnostic tests for cancer. Under Gore's plan, a panel of medical
experts would make recommendations on new tests worthy of Medicare
coverage. If Congress did not act on a recommendation within 60
days, Medicare would automatically begin paying for it.
</P>
<P>
   _ Increasing by fivefold the number of patients participating in
cancer clinical trials sponsored by the National Cancer Institute.
Gore asserts that survival rates for children with cancer have
risen sharply because most of those children participate in
clinical tests. But less than 3 percent of adults with cancer
participate in clinical tests, he said.
</P>
<P>
   _ Passing legislation that would prohibit discrimination based
on a person's genetic makeup. Gore argued that few people would
undergo genetic tests that could pinpoint the potential for cancer
if they feared losing their jobs or health insurance.
</P>
<P>
   _ Extending Medicaid coverage to people who are diagnosed with
certain cancers, including breast and cervical, through federal
screening programs, but lack health insurance.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
