<P>
   Off-lead story:
</P>
<P>
   EBAY-BIDS (Undated) _ When eBay, the Internet auction company,
suspended the seller and voided the sale of a vivid abstract
painting whose price shot from $.25 to $135,805 last month, his
offense had nothing to do with the authenticity of the painting.
Rather, Kenneth Walton had entered a bid of $4,500 on his own
offering _ a practice known as shill bidding that violates eBay's
rules _ on the second day of a 10-day auction, long before
speculation that the painting might be by the renowned painter
Richard Diebenkorn sent the price soaring. But an analysis of that
and other eBay art auctions reveals that the flourishing
cyberauction world faces a deeper problem: rings of shill-bidders
that may include self-bidding. By Judith H. Dobrzynski. (Scheduled
to move by 8:45 p.m. ET in ``a'' news file.) 2,800 words.
</P>
