<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-WALL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BILL TO BAN WOMEN FROM PRAYING AT WESTERN WALL IS BACKED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALIZA MARCUS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ In a move that shows the strains between religious
and secular Jews in Israel, ultra-Orthodox parliamentarians have
won initial support for a bill setting a seven-year jail term for
women who wear prayer shawls and read from Torah scrolls at the
Western Wall, Judaism's holiest site.
</P>
<P>
   The vote, the first of three, sparked outrage Thursday from
women's rights activists and liberal parliamentarians, who warned
that such a bill undermines Israel's democracy and undercuts
women's rights. While unlikely to become law, the bill puts further
strain on Prime Minister Ehud Barak's unwieldy governing coalition.
</P>
<P>
   ``This bill is fundamentalist in its essence and truly
frightening,'' said Naomi Chazan, a parliamentarian from the
liberal Meretz party, which is part of the governing coalition.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will do everything to prevent Israel from turning into an
Afghanistan or Iran,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The bill, supported by the three religious parties in Barak's
governing coalition, was introduced Wednesday in response to last
week's Supreme Court decision giving a women's prayer group the
right to pray at the Western Wall in Jerusalem's Old City. It
passed 32-26 in the 120-member Knesset.
</P>
<P>
   The court decision had been condemned by Israeli Orthodox
rabbis, most of whom do not believe that Jewish religious law
allows women to do certain things normally reserved for men, such
as donning a prayer shawl while praying or reading aloud from Torah
scrolls.
</P>
<P>
   The bill seeks to block the Supreme Court's ruling by banning
women from holding religious ceremonies near the Wall, which is
already split into men's and women's sections.
</P>
<P>
   The bill states, ``No religious ceremony will be held in the
women's section of the Wall, which includes reading from Torah
scrolls, Shofar blowing, wearing prayer shawls or tefillin.''
</P>
<P>
   But the lawyer for the Women of the Wall, which filed its first
court petition 11 years ago, said that for now, the bill pending in
parliament did not free the government from following the ruling of
the Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   The three judges gave the government six months to come up with
a way to allow the Women of the Wall, which is composed of
Orthodox, Conservative, and Reform Jews, to pray at the Western
Wall. ``That decision is binding, there is no court order
suspending the enforcement of that decision, therefore the
government must comply with it,'' said lawyer Jonathan Misheiker.
</P>
<P>
   The view of what women can and cannot do in religious services
is one that differs among Orthodox, Conservative, and Reform Jews.
</P>
<P>
   In Israel, where state and religion are not separate, all Jews
fall under the purview of the Orthodox rabbis, who control
marriage, divorce, and conversion.
</P>
<P>
   But over the past few years, non-Orthodox Jews have struggled to
break the Orthodox religious monopoly, setting off bitter political
and court battles over whether Orthodox rabbis should be allowed to
define Judaism for all Jews.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-01-00 2026EDT &QL; 
