as donning a prayer shawl while praying or reading aloud from Torah
scrolls.
</P>
<P>
   The bill seeks to block the Supreme Court's ruling by banning
women from holding religious ceremonies near the Wall, which is
already split into men's and women's sections.
</P>
<P>
   The bill states, ``No religious ceremony will be held in the
women's section of the Wall, which includes reading from Torah
scrolls, Shofar blowing, wearing prayer shawls or tefillin.''
</P>
<P>
   But the lawyer for the Women of the Wall, which filed its first
court petition 11 years ago, said that for now, the bill pending in
parliament did not free the government from following the ruling of
the Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   The three judges gave the government six months to come up with
