A2258 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-SEC-NOTES-COX     06-01 0685
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEC-NOTES-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   SEC to give Atlanta two more championship games
</P>
<P>
   By Tony Barnhart
</P>
<P>
   C.2000, Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   DESTIN, Fla. _ Trying to shore up its position in the Atlanta
market, the Southeastern Conference will award the 2004 and 2005
men's basketball tournaments to the Georgia Dome today.
</P>
<P>
   The 2001SEC basketball tournament will be in Nashville, with the
2002 event back in Atlanta, which also will host the Final Four
that season. The 2003 tournament will be at the Super Dome in New
Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   The SEC presidents will make the decision official with their
vote today, when the conference's annual spring meetings close.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlantic Coast Conference has shown signs that it wants its
tournament to have a stronger presence in the Atlanta market. In
March the ACC tournament will return to Atlanta for the first time
since 1989. The ACC is expected to award another tournament to the
Georgia Dome, for either 2009 or 2010.
</P>
<P>
   Donovan's new deal
</P>
<P>
   Florida basketball coach Billy Donovan, who led the Gators to
the Final Four in only his fourth season, has been rewarded with a
five-year, $6 million contract.
</P>
<P>
   Donovan's annual salary of $1.2 million ties him with Kentucky's
Tubby Smith as the highest-paid basketball coach in the SEC.
</P>
<P>
   Florida's Steve Spurrier is college football's highest-paid
coach at $2 million per season.
</P>
<P>
   Six-hour rule
</P>
<P>
   The SEC is contemplating a rule that would require football
players to pass a minimum of six hours in the fall quarter in order
to be eligible for a bowl game. The rule would apply to all sports,
but the focus is on football.
</P>
<P>
   Some senior football players who think they are going to be high
draft choices quit going to class in their final season. Then they
leave school to prepare for a professional career.
</P>
<P>
   The state of Florida already has a rule that applies to all
schools in the state.
</P>
<P>
   Some athletics directors agree with the idea in principle but
are concerned the rule might put the SEC at a disadvantage in bowl
games against teams that don't have to adhere to such a rule. They
think the rule should be passed at the NCAA level.
</P>
<P>
   Deuce loose in Costa Rica
</P>
<P>
   Mississippi running back Deuce McAllister, a Heisman Trophy
candidate, has spent the past three weeks in Costa Rica picking up
some extra credits in Spanish. McAllister is living with a local
family, going to class in the morning, and working out in the
afternoon. He will pick up six hours of Spanish, which will put him
closer to his goal of graduating in December.
</P>
<P>
   Coach David Cutcliffe says he is trying to stay calm.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, I was worried, because they've had some problems over
there,'' Cutcliffe said.
</P>
<P>
   Two American students were killed in Costa Rica earlier this
year.
</P>
<P>
   McAllister told Cutcliffe to look on the bright side.
</P>
<P>
   ``At least, he thought it would get me away from agents,''
McAllister told the Memphis Commercial Appeal.
</P>
<P>
   McAllister is scheduled to return to Oxford, Miss., today.
</P>
<P>
   Worth noting
</P>
<P>
   The SEC is expected to announce today that its members will
share a record $73 million in revenues from televised football and
basketball. Last year, the 12 schools shared $68.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   The SEC championship football game, Dec. 2 at the Georgia Dome,
already is a sellout. The only tickets now available are the 15,900
that will go to each of the two participating teams.
</P>
<P>
   The SEC presidents will discuss a change in the transfer rule.
Only football and basketball players who transfer from SEC schools
have to sit out a year. The new rule would make athletes in all
sports sit out a year.
</P>
<P>
   Alabama's football opener at UCLA will be televised on ABC, with
a kickoff of 3:30 p.m. It will be Alabama's first game in
Pasadena's Rose Bowl since Jan. 1, 1946, when the Crimson Tide beat
Southern California.
</P>
<P>
   Negotiations have started for the television rights to the SEC
football championship game. ABC has held the rights since the game
started in 1992. The contract ends this year.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
