<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 20:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2263 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-BOSTON-AIRLINES-BOS &LR;      06-01 1380
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOSTON-AIRLINES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CARRIERS BATTLE TO CORNER BOSTON BUSINESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW BRELIS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Hub airports _ where one airline dominates and flies
nonstop to dozens, if not hundreds, of cities _ are common.
</P>
<P>
   But Boston, the so-called Hub of the Universe, is reaping the
benefits of not being the hub for any airline.
</P>
<P>
   The city's lucrative mix of business and leisure passengers,
combined with a significant population base and robust economy,
have the airlines battling in a high-stakes game to become the
dominant carrier in a place where location _ the Northeast corner
of the country _ makes it impossible to have traditional
hub-and-spoke operations.
</P>
<P>
   For passengers, the fierce competition is bringing cutting-edge
services, new terminal facilities, and fare wars as airlines pour
money into Logan International Airport.
</P>
<P>
   Logan, John F. Kennedy International Airport in New York, and
Los Angeles International Airport are the only large US airports
where four airlines have at least 10 percent of the market. Nowhere
is the market as fragmented as in Boston, where 11 percentage
points separates number one from number four.
</P>
<P>
   While paid-in-advance fares out of Providence are lower than in
Boston _ because of the presence of no-frills Southwest Airlines _
fares from Logan are still more competitive than they would be in a
city where one airline dominates, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the corporations we deal with benefit'' from the
competition, said Jim Carter, regional director of sales for
American Airlines. ``They are seeing very aggressive program
proposals.''
</P>
<P>
   Boston's demographics _ its size and the mix of business and
leisure travelers _ make it too attractive for airlines to ignore
or to let their competitors walk away with the market.
</P>
<P>
   About nine out of every 10 passengers at Logan use Boston as
their origin or destination, a staggering figure in the airline
industry.
</P>
<P>
   In that regard, Logan ranks second only to Orlando, which has 94
percent of its passengers starting or ending their journeys in that
Florida vacation destination.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boston is one of the few major markets in the US today that
does not have clear carrier leadership,'' said Doug Blisset, vice
president of network analysis for Delta Air Lines.
</P>
<P>
   ``Essentially, you have four carriers with equal revenue in
Boston. The size of the market is so significant that if you can
build a `top of the mind' or `carrier of choice' presence, the
benefits are significant _ and the profit base is potentially very
strong.''
</P>
<P>
   If the proposed merger of United Airlines and US Airways shrinks
that number to three, the competition will still be fierce. And
what would become the number two and number three carriers _ Delta
and American, respectively _ are not about to give up the quest for
dominance.
</P>
<P>
   Both have announced major terminal projects worth more than $600
million combined. Delta alone plans to spend about $350 million in
private funds to build a new Terminal A, which will make it the
only airline in Boston with its own terminal.
</P>
<P>
   And long before Terminal A is complete, Delta passengers will be
able to check in at the central parking garage and obtain boarding
passes there. Airline officials say it is all part of an effort to
make the Atlanta-based carrier foremost in the minds of New
Englanders.
</P>
<P>
   Leo F. Mullin, Delta's president, chairman, and chief executive,
has made ``winning in the Northeast and the North Atlantic'' major
priorities.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at the Northeast, the cornerstones are New York
and Boston,'' Mullin said in an interview shortly before the recent
United-US Airways merger announcement.
</P>
<P>
   ``In both of those cities, we have 22 or 23 percent of the
market share. We have weaponry in Boston: the main line, the
shuttle, Delta Express and Comair, and our international alliance
with Air France. With our Terminal A expansion, we have the
intention of service to London, Paris, Rome, Dublin, and
Manchester.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boston is a crucial element in terms of winning in the
Northeast.''
</P>
<P>
   Delta also plans to woo customers with upgraded service. It is
wiring Terminal A for a local area network that will extend to the
parking garage, allowing for remote check-in for passengers who
want to avoid lines inside the terminal.
</P>
<P>
   Officials are reluctant to say much about the plan, which is at
least a year away from being put into service. But Rick Danner,
Delta's regional director of customer service, said:
</P>
<P>
   ``When you are leaving Boston, we want you to think of driving
to the (parking garage's) fourth floor to check in with Delta. Once
you are there, it will be the start of a whole new experience for
airline check-in.''
</P>
<P>
   Delta is also continuing to expand its schedule in Boston and
will begin twice-daily nonstop service to Los Angeles on July 1.
</P>
<P>
   United recently increased the number of nonstops to LAX to five
daily. American also offers frequent nonstop service to Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think three strong carriers in that market is a good
thing,'' said American's Carter. ``Competing against United and
Delta helps us be that much better when you are competing against
world class airlines.''
</P>
<P>
   More competition also means lower fares.
</P>
<P>
   Delta has announced an introductory round-trip fare to Los
Angeles of about $350, less than half the cost of the lowest fare
avialable for the last weekend in June. All the airlines matched
Delta's fare, beginning in July.
</P>
<P>
   If the merger with US Airways goes through without major impact
on the route structure in Boston, United will be the largest
airline at Logan, with more than 30 percent of the market. But the
airline will have logistical issues as it consolidates operations,
because United is expanding in Terminal C, while US Airways has
more gates in Terminal B, where it is also expanding.
</P>
<P>
   United's city manager, Diane Bergan, said the airline's
long-term strategy is to grow internationally and domestically from
Boston, no matter which terminal it operates from.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just completed one year of service to London with a perfect
reliability record,'' she said. ``The strong competition in Boston
provides significant choices for consumers and makes Boston very
attractive.''
</P>
<P>
   United also is slated to bring its Chariots _ mobile check-in
stations that can be moved to where there are long lines _ to
Boston. They're due by the end of this year or early in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   And American Airlines this year announced a major expansion of
its facilities in Terminal B. The carrier will add about 300,000
square feet of terminal space, letting it bring the Boeing 777
jumbo jet to Boston without having to shut down an adjacent gate
because of the plane's wingspan.
</P>
<P>
   An American spokeswoman vowed that ``we will be competitive'' in
Boston. ``It is a very important city to us, by virtue of our $270
million expansion effort.''
</P>
<P>
   There are also significant benefits to the Massachusetts Port
Authoirty, which owns and operates Logan.
</P>
<P>
   ``The airlines recognize that they need to spend money to
attract passengers, and you would not have that if we were
dominated by one airline,'' said Virginia Buckingham, the
authority's executive director and CEO. ``It makes it easier for
Massport to leverage private investment.''
</P>
<P>
   Buckingham said Massport may be able to use the United-US
Airways deal to free up terminal space for other airlines. ``Right
now, we have no place to put them,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, high demand for space and limited supply have let
Massport begin innovative lease arrangements, whereby the authority
can demand that an airline turn over its gates if they are not used
frequently enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have the option of stepping in and pulling some gates back
to get them up to the average,'' said Thomas J. Kinton Jr.,
Massport's aviation director. ``Over time, we expect the average
usage to go up, which will keep pressure on airlines to fly out of
Boston.''
</P>
<P>
   Massport can also order an airline to sublease a gate to a
competitor, which prevents airlines from being locked out of
Boston, Kinton said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because we are not dominated by one airline, we can stay in
the driver's seat,'' Buckingham said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
