<HEADER>
A2266 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-TEN-FRENCH-BOS &LR;      06-01 0869
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-FRENCH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANDRE AGASSI OUSTED FROM FRENCH OPEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BUD COLLINS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ In an earlier time, a king of France named Louis XVI was
rather harshly removed from his title _ with a guillotine at the
Place de la Concorde. That was 1793.
</P>
<P>
   The blow was a little softer _ but maybe as painful _ for King
Andre I of the House of Agassi on Thursday. It was delivered by a
Slovak commoner called Kucera, who separated Andre from his French
crown with a gut-strung blade, a tennis racket wielded with utmost
sharpness and severity as the assembled public gasped.
</P>
<P>
   Andre would have been better off at the Place de la Concorde, a
broad plaza of merriment from which the guillotine has been removed
and handsome fountains now play while a gigantic Ferris wheel
spins. But surely the suddenly ex-ruler of these red courts felt
soaked, his head spinning, as he trudged away from Stade Roland
Garros, beaten by strapping 6-foot-2-inch Karol Kucera, 2-6, 7-5,
6-1, 6-0, in the second round.
</P>
<P>
   The second round? Pretty early for a major tournament to fall
apart. But late in the afternoon, as the sun finally made other
than a fleeting appearance at this French Open, this day was marked
as Black Thursday. Both the king and queen of tennis, in the pop
view anyway _ Agassi and Anna Kournikova _ were gone. Dispatched
from the scene as certainly as Louis XVI and his roommate, Marie
Antoinette.
</P>
<P>
   Thud. Thud. What a devastating pair of falls.
</P>
<P>
   You see, preceding Andre to the scrap heap was Anna, the goddess
of camera pointers and marketers, the resident of such diverse
magazine covers as Forbes and currently Sports Illustrated. It was
downhill from the start as No. 35 Sylvia Plischke, from a skiing
mecca, Innsbruck, Austria, schussed past her, 6-2, 4-6, 6-3.
</P>
<P>
   Kournikova, the Russian who turns 19 in five days, may win ogles
and endorsement contracts _ never titles. Agassi, having sprung
from the same Nick Bollettieri nursery in Bradenton, Fla., is quite
a different character, a champion of all-time quality _ although he
can show a similar prima dona temperament. Unlike Louis XVI, Andre
I could run away and hide as he did Thursday, unwilling to discuss
his debacle. He thus incurred a $10,000 fine, the sort of chump
change he hands out to footmen.
</P>
<P>
   As Kucera said, ``Andre's got the match in his hands in the
second set, but I was lucky to get back. Then I got into it, and
the match was open. I got confident, started to hit. But my name is
still a little bit small.''
</P>
<P>
   Not altogether. A dangerous guy though ranked No. 60, Kucera two
years ago beat Pete Sampras in the quarters at the Australian and
Agassi in the fourth round at the US Open. He incurred an
astounding loss to Paradorn Srichaphan, the pride of Thailand, at
the Australian in January, but has been slowly pulling himself
together since.
</P>
<P>
   Did it all turn on the big name's big toe? Andre and his
entourage of girlfriend Steffi Graf, coach Brad Gilbert, and
trainer Gil Reyes, rearranged their lengthening faces and vanished
so fast that the unanswered question will soon become stale.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, it was all Andre up to 6-2, 5-4, as he went to the
baseline to serve for a two-set lead. He had also been up a break
earlier in the set, but seemed a touch complacent _ cavalier and
overly sure?
</P>
<P>
   He didn't press hard enough to nail down a two-set lead _ and
the unraveling began, during which he won one _ that's one _ more
game, and lost the last 11, from 1-1 in the third.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, yes, the saga of the big toe. At 1-4 to the rear in the
third set, Agassi called an injury timeout. Trainer Per Bastholt
appeared to treat a blister on the lead piggie of the king's right
foot and shave a callous that was pressuring the blister. Andre
made grim faces, but returned to battle, seeming unimpaired. But
something was missing.
</P>
<P>
   Kucera could smell it, and let loose with self-assured, booming
groundies. Clearly Andre was no longer the champ, and it was only a
matter of minutes, and the 12 points he could scrape together,
before it became official.
</P>
<P>
   The king was dead, and 15,166 unbelieving subjects groaned, then
applauded as he waved goodbye. Two other defending champs had been
cut off in the second round (Andres Gimeno by Guillermo Vilas in
1973; Guga Kuerten by Marat Safin in 1998), but none was marched
off shackled in a bagel.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things happen out there that you need to get by,'' Andre had
mused as the tourney began. They happened; he didn't.
</P>
<P>
   The last time he graced Court Central was the occasion of
Andre's 1999 coronation. The throng hailed him boisterously for his
revival from two sets deep, behind Andrei Medvedev, to ascend the
throne and become merely the fifth in history to have worn all four
major crowns.
</P>
<P>
   Sampras was evicted in the first round along with Todd Martin,
Andre in the second. Jim Courier and MaliVai Washington are looking
for rest homes. The male American Iron Age is rusting, with only
the little king of 1989, Michael Chang, still standing here, if
unsteadily.
</P>
<P>
   Kings can hurt, too, but, all in all, Andre I's treatment in
Paris was somewhat better than Louis XVI's.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
