<HEADLINE>
NASDAQ SURGES TO 5.3 PERCENT GAIN 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By ROBERT D. HERSHEY Jr.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Technology stocks roared ahead Thursday, propelling
the Nasdaq composite index to its seventh-best gain in percentage
terms, up 5.3 percent. That performance followed Tuesday's record
7.9 percent rise.
</P>
<P>
   The index surged 181.59 points, to 3,582.50, and cut the
Nasdaq's losses on the year to nearly 12 percent.
</P>
<P>
   After Wednesday's downturn, investors became re-enthused
Thursday as the economic news of the day suggested that the economy
was slowing markedly from the breakneck pace that had led the
Federal Reserve to raise interest rates six times since last June.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're beginning to see the impact'' of the slow-acting but
powerful antiinflation medicine being used by Alan Greenspan, the
Fed's chairman, said Frank Cappiello of McCullough, Andrews &AMP;
Cappiello in Baltimore. ``We sense that he's gotten near the end of
raising rates. And if that's the case, then these tech stocks are
woefully underpriced.''
</P>
<P>
   The Standard &AMP; Poor 500 stocks also posted a gain, up 28.21
points, or 2 percent, to 1,448.81, while the Dow Jones industrial
average climbed 129.97 points, or 1.2 percent, to 10,652.20.
</P>
<P>
   News of slackened industrial costs and construction spending
still left many analysts unpersuaded that rate increases are near
an end and that this spring's stock slide is over.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm skeptical,'' said Byron R. Wien, chief U.S. strategist at
Morgan Stanley Dean Witter. He said the economic slowing was from a
``very feverish'' pace, suggesting that more Fed tightening might
be needed, and that in any event corporate earnings growth was
probably on the wane. ``I would certainly have a defensive
position'' toward stocks, Wien advised.
</P>
<P>
   In Atlanta, Robert M. Balentine, chief executive of the
investment counselors Balentine &AMP; Co., took a similar view. ``We're
simply seeing some bounce off the lows,'' he said. ``We would use
the rally to raise cash for better buying opportunities ahead
rather than think the worst is behind us.''
</P>
<P>
   And while the skeptics cited continued subdued trading volume as
evidence that the rally lacked enthusiasm, there had been a clear
improvement lately in the proportion of stocks moving higher.
Thursday, 2,061 New York Stock Exchange issues advanced while 927
declined, and new 52-week highs nearly doubled new lows, 68 to 35.
</P>
<P>
   The ratio was even better for the S&AMP;P 500, where 353 stocks rose
while 131 declined and 16 were unchanged.
</P>
<P>
   Several Nasdaq issues posted double-digit gains, with the
heavily weighted Cisco Systems, up 4, to 60 15/16, having the
biggest impact.
</P>
<P>
   Hewlett-Packard, up 14 1/16, to 134\, after a meeting that
impressed security analysts, accounted for nearly two-thirds of the
Dow's rise. Intel climbed 5, to 129 11/16.
</P>
<P>
   Although the market for initial public offerings has been
severely chilled of late, ONI Systems, a fiber optics company,
attracted huge demand for 8 million shares it offered late Tuesday
at 25. The stock started trading Thursday at 75, climbed as high as
86 and finished at 82 9/16.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
