<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATROITS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GLENN HOPEFUL ON CONTRACT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MASHPEE, Mass. _ On a blissful spring day at Willowbend Country
Club, Terry Glenn, playing the part of celebrity golfer _clad in
yellow-striped polo shirt and straw hat _ said his contract
situation will not get the best of him or his teammates.
</P>
<P>
   Though preferring to sign a new deal, Glenn, who has two years
remaining on a six-year pact, said he won't be a holdout.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could hold out, but I feel I would be doing my teammates a
bad deal,'' Glenn said. ``They want to win as much as I want to
win. I feel Drew (Bledsoe) basically came in with me because when I
came in we clicked and we started winning. So he's on the same
wavelength. I'd be doing them an injustice to hold out.''
</P>
<P>
   Glenn watched as Marvin Harrison (4 years, $24 million) and
Keyshawn Johnson (8 years, $56 million) signed huge deals with
Indianapolis and Tampa Bay, respectively. Both are Pro Bowlers, a
select club that Glenn joined last season, but when Glenn asked for
a new deal after the season, the Patriots told him to wait.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn will earn $2.4 million this year and about the same next
year, but compared with the $6 million-plus Harrison and Johnson
will earn, Glenn, who is not even the highest-paid receiver on his
own team, appears well behind his 1996 first-round classmates.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I have no choice, then I have no choice,'' said Glenn. ``If
I have a choice, then I wouldn't want to wait.''
</P>
<P>
   Glenn has been a part of most of the offseason conditioning
program, but recently returned to his home in Columbus to work out
at Ohio State with his former strength coach, Dave Kennedy. He has
spent time working directly with Bledsoe and remains excited about
the prospects of the new offense under offensive coodinator Charlie
Weis, who has gone back to the system (with a few new wrinkles) in
which Glenn thrived (90 receptions in 1996).
</P>
<P>
   ``No doubt ever since I heard (Bill) Belichick and Weis got the
job, I gave my friends a high-five because it's what I wanted,''
said Glenn. ``We went to a Super Bowl with that offense. There are
a couple of other things we need to put into the offense, but we're
looking good.''
</P>
<P>
   With Ben Coates gone, it appears Glenn will have to carry even
more of the burden, which he embraces.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm excited every year as far as getting ready with my
teammates,'' he said. ``I would love to go back to the Pro Bowl,
but I'm going to set my sights on more team goals. I'd rather go to
the Super Bowl than the Pro Bowl.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Thomas doesn't volunteer
</P>
<P>
   Henry Thomas surfaced at Thursday's tournament after skipping
the team's ``voluntary'' minicamp Tuesday and Wednesday. He was the
only veteran not in attendance.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas said he didn't attend because ``it's voluntary.'' Thomas
thinks after 13 years he should be cut some slack, and that may be
the case. The Patriots need Thomas's leadership, not to mention his
ability as a defensive lineman.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas spent the offseason working out in Houston. He will take
part in Friday's mandatory minicamp, which runs through the
weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Asked why he didn't call Belichick, Thomas said: ``Why should I?
So it's disrespectful not to call? I didn't mean it to be
disrespectful. I wanted to be home with my family in Houston
because that's where I live.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
