<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-BLAZERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLAZERS HAVE TALENT IN RESERVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORTLAND, Ore. _ The All-NBA teams came out this week. The
Lakers had a first-team selection (Shaquille O'Neal) and a
second-teamer (Kobe Bryant). The Blazers, who were the second-best
team in the NBA this season, have one of the 50 greatest players of
all time in Scottie Pippen, more than a few All-Star Game
performers, and yet placed no one in the top 25.
</P>
<P>
   All season long, the Blazers have touted their depth more than
their individual stars. It helped them win games, if not accolades
for their players. And it helped send this whacky Western
Conference final series back here for a sixth game Friday night
against the Lakers at the Rose Garden.
</P>
<P>
   In the first five games, the vaunted Portland bench was getting
outplayed by such luminaries as Rick Fox, Derek Fisher, and Robert
Horry. The Lakers grabbed a 3-1 lead with two insulting wins here
in Games 3 and 4. It got so bad in Game 4 that Trail Blazers coach
Mike Dunleavy kept Detlef Schrempf on the pine for the full 48 and
used backup point guard Greg Anthony for just four minutes.
</P>
<P>
   But the Blazers' dense pack was back in business for Game 5
Tuesday at the Staples Center. Schrempf was exhumed and played 27
valuable minutes, collecting a game-high six assists. Brian Grant,
who has been sacrificing his body to play out of position as a
backup center most of this series, was heroic in 23 minutes. No one
moped about not playing (Schrempf, Anthony) or having to play out
of position against a behemoth (Grant).
</P>
<P>
   ``It's called professionalism,'' Dunleavy said. ``When you put
the time in and prepare yourself and when you're called and you
step up and do the job. We're fortunate to have guys who do that.''
</P>
<P>
   That's Blazer Ball, as it was conceived by general manager Bob
Whitsitt (with a big assist from owner Paul Allen's bankroll)
before the season started and was developed as the season
progressed. To an already imposing mix, Whitsitt added Schrempf,
Pippen, and Steve Smith and Portland chased the Lakers for the
first four months of the season before falling off. They're still
chasing them, but they also are still alive, to the surprise of
many after the Memorial Day weekend performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were in a situation where we had the veteran guys who were
focused on winning a championship, so we knew we could cut their
minutes and develop the young guys along the way,'' Whitsitt said
Thursday. ``We thought we'd have a real professional team and have
great chemistry, which we've had. But this is a tough league. You
really don't know what you get until you get there.''
</P>
<P>
   Grant has been the embodiment of team sacrifice, especially in
this series. With the arrival of Pippen, he quickly went from
starter to reserve. That was an adjustment.
</P>
<P>
   And with Portland's still mind-boggling decision not to activate
Joe Kleine (in favor of the never-used and never-will-be-used Gary
Grant), that has meant the undersized Brian Grant has had to go
eye-to-sternum with O'Neal when Arvydas Sabonis gets into foul
trouble, which is always.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to take a page from Charlie Ward's book and Detlef
Schrempf's book. I'm a bench player this year,'' Grant said. ``I've
had to get used to being a bench player. Here, towards the end, you
just realize that you have to be ready, no matter when you go in.
It would have been very easy for me to get upset that I didn't go
in the whole first quarter and for half the second. But I just
stayed positive, went out there, and was able to hit some big shots
and give the team a lift.''
</P>
<P>
   So many times, it's the ``other guys'' who help determine the
outcome of a series. The Blazers are more than willing to let Ron
Harper, A.C. Green, or the aforementioned reserves beat them. They
even gave the usually reliable Glen Rice some easy looks in Game 5
and lived to tell about it.
</P>
<P>
   Pippen led the charge in Game 5 and hopes to do the same Friday
night. Bryant, who missed practice Thursday because of a sprained
right foot, is hoping to bounce back from a disastrous performance
and already is feeling the heat of Phil Jackson's deftly probing
needle. Bryant usually bounces back.
</P>
<P>
   The Blazers will again rely on their reserves to tip the
balance. That's the way it has been and that's the way it will
continue to be.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
