<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 20:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2271 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-TV-SURVIVORS-ART-2TAK     06-01 1199
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SURVIVORS-ART-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SURVIVOR' RATINGS GIVE ANOTHER BOOST TO VOYEURISTIC TELEVISION 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Ratings graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By BILL CARTER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Last summer, ABC's ``Who Wants to Be a Millionaire'' turned the
television world on its head by defying every expectation and
seizing huge audiences, eventually catapulting ABC to overall
network ratings leadership.
</P>
<P>
   Now a new summer series, about a group of people forced to live
together in primitive circumstances on an island off Borneo, has
gotten off to a similarly stunning start, and television executives
are already wondering whether it can do the same thing for CBS.
</P>
<P>
   ``Survivor,'' CBS's experiment in mixing ``Lord of the Flies,''
with ``Gilligan's Island'' and ``Treasure Island,'' came out of the
gate roaring Wednesday night, pulling in 15.5 million viewers, a
figure that dwarfed any show CBS has used on a Wednesday night in
two years _ during the regular TV season, never mind the summer. In
a reverse for CBS, the network with the oldest audience, the show
drew a surprising number of young viewers, providing a glimpse of
the marketing clout of a combined CBS and Viacom Inc., with its
youth oriented radio and cable stations, like MTV and VH-1.
</P>
<P>
   The early success could be due to that promotional push. Even
CBS executives will not predict how well the ratings will hold up.
But the initial success is likely to intensify the market for
programs that record real people doing real-life things. Indeed,
networks were said to be lining up Thursday to acquire the rights
to similar televoyeur shows, including one set on a bus, one set in
a futuristic house supposedly on another planet, and one in which
an actor tries to sabotage his teammates in a series of contests.
</P>
<P>
   CBS itself is set to capitalize immediately with the debut next
month of ``Big Brother,'' possibly the most elaborate effort in the
movement toward voyeuristic shows, in which 10 people spend three
months together in a house, with their every movement recorded live
on camera.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The initial ratings for ``Survivor,'' huge by summer standards,
can only feed the trend. The show proved to be more than
competitive with ``Who Wants to Be a Millionaire,'' which ABC
scheduled at the last minute to try to hold down the audience for
``Survivor.''
</P>
<P>
   ABC did edge `'Survivor'' in one respect; it attracted more
overall, viewers, 16.8 million viewers. But ``Survivor's'' most
noticeable feat was the number of young viewers it brought in to
CBS. ``Survivor'' not only beat ``Millionaire'' in every category
of young viewers, from teen-agers through adults between the ages
of 18 and 49, and 25 and 54; it also managed to triple CBS's
average prime-time audience among viewers between the ages of 18
and 34.
</P>
<P>
   That achievement shocked a number of CBS's competitors. An
executive with one competing network said, ``Those are simply
incredible numbers for CBS.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Leslie Moonves, the president of CBS Television, called the
ratings ``a great corporate victory,'' saying ``We had people doing
interviews everywhere, on radio on VH-1 on MTV,''
</P>
<P>
   The show stirred so much interest that Moonves decided to
schedule a repeat broadcast of the first episode, Saturday night at
10.
</P>
<P>
   In the first of the 13 scheduled ``Survivor'' episodes, two
teams of eight people each, carefully cast to include a wide range
of ages, ethnic groups and personalities, were thrown together on
the island of Pulau Tiga, where they had to do everything from
build latrines to forage for food to create a fire.
</P>
<P>
   They were also bitten by bugs, harassed by rats (which viewers
have been promised they will later see these folks eat for dinner),
and challenged by a raft-racing task with the reward of some
waterproof matches. The losing team had to vote one person off the
island. (Each show ends with someone's ignominious departure.)
</P>
<P>
   Because she fell and cost her team a victory in the raft race, a
62-year-old woman named Sonja was the first victim of the show's
Darwinian ethos.
</P>
<P>
   Still, ``Survivor's'' instant ascent to event status provided
some solace for Sonja, who was interviewed all over television
Thursday, from CBS's own ``Early Show'' (which, every Thursday for
the next 13 weeks, has first claim on everyone bounced from the
island), to MSNBC, Fox News, and even ``The Daily Show'' on Comedy
Central.
</P>
<P>
   Almost as busy as Sonja Thursday was Ben Silverman, an agent
with the William Morris Agency, who spent four years in Europe, and
was an early advocate of the European reality shows, whose formats
are now making their way into the United States. Silverman had a
hand in bringing ``Millionaire'' to ABC and was involved in the
heated negotiations for ``Big Brother,'' in which CBS outbid ABC by
putting up a reported $20 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ratings for `Survivor' have put the networks into
overdrive for other formats,'' Silverman said. ``Right now CBS and
ABC are the most involved.'' He said he expected several shows he
represents to be sold shortly.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   These include ``The Bus,'' which examines ordinary people on a
bus tour and ``The Mole,'' the one in which an actor
surreptitiously plays havoc with contestants in a series of scenic
challenges like bungee jumps.
</P>
<P>
   Another show sets up a house as though it in on some outer-space
colony in a distant future. Silverman said he also represents
several other shows in the genre that he could not yet reveal.
</P>
<P>
   What all the shows have in common, beyond their initial success
in European countries, from Great Britain to Holland to Belgium, is
their use of real people interacting on camera. Most of the shows
also have extensive Internet components, where fans can follow the
progress of the contestants even when the show is not on the air.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   How real these ``reality shows'' actually are has been
questioned, but Mark Burnett the executive producer of
``Survivor,'' said Thursday: ``It is exactly real. I refuse for any
reason to manipulate what really happens. These people are on
camera, and they say what they say, but I'm not going to manipulate
them.''
</P>
<P>
   The rats, he said, are real and ever present on the island. The
snakes, he said, are real and truly dangerous, enough so that he
made sure that anyone bitten could be evacuated by helicopter to a
hospital within 30 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Burnett argued that the events are in no way staged or re-edited
to build drama. Each show represents three days of taping on the
island. Each ends with one member voted out until a winner is
selected, and takes home the $1 million prize.
</P>
<P>
   But Burnett said he does edit the show to set up future plot
lines, as he did in the first episode, which showed a brief shot of
one contestant reading his Bible. ``We are setting that up, because
clearly religion does become a factor. Some people don't like being
preached to, particularly on an island where you can't get off.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Moonves said he was being cautious about the show's initial
ratings success. ``I don't want to declare victory after one
episode.'' But he acknowledged that ``the show has tremendous
economic upside.'' That upside cannot be exploited in the current
slate of shows, no matter how big the ratings get, because all of
them were sold out to eight full sponsors, which include Reebok,
Bud Lite beer and the U.S Army.
</P>
<P>
   But Moonves said, ``The advertisers saw those ratings and and
got phenomenally jacked.'' This was especially because of those
exceptional numbers among younger viewers.
</P>
<P>
   If that keeps up, CBS can expect to sell its commercials in
``Big Brother'' for even higher prices, as well as those for future
editions of ``Survivor.''
</P>
<P>
   And there will almost certainly be future editions. Moonves said
he was not yet ready to start up the process of picking another
group of people to be isolated in another exotic locale, though the
mechanism is already in place to do so.
</P>
<P>
   Burnett said ``I don't think we'll go back to an island, but we
may go some place like Africa or the Andes or the Australian
outback.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The decision to order another ``Survivor'' adventure series may
not take much longer. ``We could have another `Survivor' ready by
January,'' Moonves said.
</P>
<P>
   That would again parallel ``Millionaire,'' which ABC brought
back quickly after its summer success, installing it first as a two
week event in November, a rating sweep month.
</P>
<P>
   January is not a sweep month, but February is _ and the
``Survivor'' format calls for 13 weeks of shows. ``If it works well
in January, it will work well in February,'' Moonves said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
