u i BC-MIAMI-REAX-COX     06-01 0576
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIAMI-REAX-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Miami reaction muted
 &HT;    By Alexandra Navarro Clifton and Bill Douthat
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _Reaction to Thursday's federal apeals court ruling in the
Elian Gonzalez case spurred a small but vocal demonstration in
Miami's Little Havana neighborhood outside the small house where
Elian had stayed with his Miami relatives.
</P>
<P>
   About 50 people gathered outside the house to express their
anguish _ some falling to the ground sobbing.
</P>
<P>
   The fence around the house is still adorned with home-made
posters showing Elian with his mother, written diatribes against
Bill Clinton and Janet Reno, prayers and American and Cuban flags.
Small groups stood around portable radios listening to Cuban
commentators.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never thought this could happen in this country,'' said Ana
Alfonso. ``Give the child an opportunity to speak. Children running
away from communism have always been welcomed here.''
</P>
<P>
   Miami police also gathered, waiting and watching at both ends of
the street.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't expect any trouble,'' Lt. Bill Schwartz said. ``We
are prepared to deal with any violence or unrest.''
</P>
<P>
   Cuban activist Ramon Saul Sanchez said his group plans a
Flotilla to Communist Island in about three weeks. He said the
group would leave from Miami Marine Stadium and stop in
international waters 12 miles off the coast of Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to bring awareness to the American people and the
international community that Cuba has been a divided country for
the last 40 years because of one man _ Fidel Castro,'' Saul Sanchez
said. ``We need to bring down those barriers.''
</P>
<P>
   Ana Bonnin was adjusting the yellow ribbons and flowers
supporters of the family have left on the fence in front of the
house. She has been outside the small home since January.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel very betrayed,'' Bonnin said. ``Where are the rights of
the mother who died for that child to be free?''
</P>
<P>
   The crowd _ small compared to the one that swelled to hundreds
the day federal marshals snatched the boy from the home April 22 _
directed their anger alternately to Clinton, Reno and the media.
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't a family issue, it is a humanitarian issue'' said
Everalso Buznejo, a Hialeah man who said his daughter drowned in
1992 trying to get to the United States in a homemade raft. ``This
child isn't being sent back to his father, he's being sent back to
the Cuban government.''
</P>
<P>
   A small number promised violence if the 6-year-old boy is sent
back to the communist nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``To hell with being peaceful _ we have been peaceful long
enough,'' said Daniel Jimenez, a 23-year-old unemployed dishwasher.
</P>
<P>
   Cuban-Americans in West Palm Beach, who protested in large
numbers when Elian was seized by federal agents, took the latest
setback quietly.
</P>
<P>
   ``To some extent, the ruling was expected,'' said Jorge
Avellana, who helped organize past protests. ``It's not the end.
Now we will wait to see what the Supreme Court has to say.''
</P>
<P>
   Cristobal Oviedo, an activist in the Cuban-American community in
West Palm Beach, said he's disappointed the Clinton administration
has not allowed the Miami relatives to visit Elian.
</P>
<P>
   ``The court doesn't play games and I'll accept whatever the
court decides,'' he said. ``But Clinton is on the side of the
father and Castro.''
</P>
<P>
   alexclifton(at)pbpost.com
</P>
<P>
   billdouthat(at)pbpost.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
