u a BC-PUENTE-DISCOGRAPHY-NY     06-01 0282
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PUENTE-DISCOGRAPHY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE RECORDINGS OF TITO PUENTE 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also OBIT-PUENTE, PUENTE-MOURNING) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tito Puente recorded some 120 albums over more than 50 years.
Here is a selection of some of his best work, including his vital
dance music.
</P>
<P>
   CUBAN CARNIVAL (RCA). A cross between Ellingtonian orchestration
and Latin percussion. Considered one of Puente's masterpieces.
Recorded in 1955 and 1956.
</P>
<P>
   DANCE MANIA, Vol. 1 and 2 (RCA). From 1958, orchestral dance
music at the highest possible level, with Santitos Colon singing.
</P>
<P>
   TOP PERCUSSION (RCA). A trip into Afro-Cuban religious and
secular music, using mostly percussion.
</P>
<P>
   MAMBORAMA (Tico). An instrumental album of mambos from 1959,
with Puente playing vibraphone and showing off some of his more
modern jazz arrangements.
</P>
<P>
   VAYA PUENTE (Tico). Tough dance music from 1962.
</P>
<P>
   TITO PUENTE SINGS THE EXCITING LA LUPE SWINGS (Tico). Rocking
early salsa with one of the better singers of the time.
</P>
<P>
   HOMENAJE A BENY (Tico). A three-CD set recorded in the late
1970s, featuring a series of salsa's best singers, including Celia
Cruz, Hector Lavoe and Adalberto Santiago performing the music of
Beny More.
</P>
<P>
   THE LEGEND (Tico). An example of the modern orchestral dance
music Puente was working on in the late 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   ROYAL T (Concord). A late classic of relaxed Latin jazz, from
1993.
</P>
<P>
   TITO'S IDEA (RMM/TropiJazz). A jazz orchestral album from the
mid-1990s that features tunes like ``Woody 'n' You'' and ``Nica's
Tempo.''
</P>
<P>
   TITO PUENTE LIVE AT BIRDLAND DANCEMANIA '99 (RMM). A hard-core
dance album that reflects Puente's band-leading precision; it won a
Grammy.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
