A2275 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LAD     06-01 0770
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIME TO SILENCE JEALOUS PORTLAND FANS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; PORTLAND, Ore.  &UR; _ &LR;  To the team with the most composure will go
the Western Conference Finals crown. And if the Los AngelesLakers
can dispose of the Portland Trail Blazers tonight in six games,
well, so much the better.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, we can hear the reddish-black jackals now, howling about how
the Lakers were the ones whose stiff upper lip went slack Tuesday.
Staring at a gilded invitation to close out Portland on their home
court, the Lakers did blink, we'll (Gary) grant the Trail Blazers
that.
</P>
<P>
   Losing one's repose in a hail of turnovers and 3-pointers is one
thing. That's easily remedied. As Kobe Bryant commented in the wake
of the Lakers' 96-88 loss in Game 5: ``You just throw it out and
you just move on.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers had a wide-open shot at the NBA Finals and clanked it
off the rim. Hey, even a pure shooter such as Glen Rice misses an
uncontested jumper every now and then.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers didn't lose their nerve, just their instinct. Instead
of acting reflexively, they found themselves ``just thinking about
the chance to go the finals after beating a good team,'' reserve
guard Derek Fisher said.
</P>
<P>
   Next thing the Lakers knew, their muscles were tighter than the
Laker Girls' second skins.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was some extra anxiety,'' Fisher conceded, ``some extra
tension that really hadn't been there in this series.''
</P>
<P>
   Five minutes in the lotus position, a few big Brahma breaths and
the Lakers will be fine. There's nothing wrong with them that a
couple of relaxation exercises can't fix.
</P>
<P>
   The Trail Blazers flexed their resilience, coming back from a
15-point loss in the series opener to win Game 2 and staving off
elimination in Game 5. In this case, the power to snap back is not
to be confused with strength of character.
</P>
<P>
   Lakers coach Phil Jackson was being kind when he called the
Trail Blazers jackals after they woofed at the Lakers in the waning
moments of their 106-77 Game 2 win.
</P>
<P>
   If we were a jackal, we'd be indignant. Jackals, because they
feast on decaying flesh, have a bad smell. That much at least is
consistent with the whiff we've gotten from the Trail Blazers.
</P>
<P>
   The Portland players reek of crassness. They're not just fouling
Shaquille O'Neal on every possession, they're fouling the whole
competitive arena.
</P>
<P>
   It's not a killer instinct they've bared in this series. No,
what has been on display is the death of decency.
</P>
<P>
   With less than three minutes remaining in the second quarter of
Game 3 in Portland and the Trail Blazers ahead by nine points,
forward Rasheed Wallace blocked a shot by Ron Harper and started
taunting the Lakers' 14-year veteran. No surprise there; in
Wallace's world, the bait-and-switch is a basketball play, not a
sales technique.
</P>
<P>
   The shocker was Wallace chose to taunt Harper, a recovering
stutterer, about his speech impediment. That kind of meanness most
of us outgrow along with our Superheroes underwear.
</P>
<P>
   Wallace, 25, is old enough to know the difference between
trash-talking and talking trashy.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, the bench is where the Trail Blazers are deep.
Nobody ever said anything about their emotional balance.
</P>
<P>
   In the final minute of Game 4, Scottie Pippen, who's supposed to
be blazing the trail for Portland, planted his elbow in the back of
John Salley's head. Pippen didn't draw a foul for his
unsportsmanlike act, though he later was fined $10,000 by the
league.
</P>
<P>
   Pippen ought to have been suspended for Game 5; instead, he
emerged as its star, getting 22 points, seven rebounds, six steals,
four blocked shots and three assists.
</P>
<P>
   Injustice won that game, but we're counting on justness
prevailing in the best-of-seven series. It'd be agreeably apropos
if the Lakers were to extinguish the Trail Blazers' season tonight
at the Rose Garden given that the fans here tend not to act any
more civilized than their favorite Portland players.
</P>
<P>
   They acknowledged the presence at the games last weekend of
actress-slash-director-slash Lakers fan Penny Marshall by booing
her lustily. They jeered a Jack Nicholson look-alike, then cheered
when he was made over to resemble a rabid Portland fan.
</P>
<P>
   The Portland fans really need to get over their Tinseltown envy.
It's not at all becoming.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers might have lost a little composure in Game 5, but
that's easily found. Somewhere along the way, the city of Portland
and its basketball stars seem to have replaced something that's
irretrievable: their class.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
