<HEADER>
A2282 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKN-BERKOW-COLUMN-NYT     06-01 0774
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-BERKOW-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: SEEING RED 
</HEADLINE>
   By IRA BERKOW    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. DOES a bull get mad when he sees red?
</P>
<P>
   A. No. A cow gets mad when she sees red. A bull gets mad when
people mistake him for a cow.
</P>
<P>
   Old joke. But it brings to mind a reverse thought off what is
becoming a commonplace theme: the Knicks are better without Patrick
Ewing. In fact, what might be the case is, the Pacers are better
without Rik Smits.
</P>
<P>
   Critics have grown louder about Ewing since the Knicks have won
their only two playoff games against the Pacers this series without
their longtime center, who was hobbled by injury in those two
games.
</P>
<P>
   Ah, but consider Smits, his counterpart center. When the Pacers
made their great run to overcome the Knicks' 18-point lead
Wednesday in Game 5 of the Eastern Conference finals, Smits, for
much of that time, had been replaced by Dale Davis. And Smits was
scoreless in the game, 0 for 6 from the floor. He had 4 rebounds,
compared with the substitute forward Derrick McKey, who gathered in
9. And in the final quarter, with the Pacers holding off the
Knicks, to take the three-games-to-two lead in the series, Smits
was a sedentary spectator.
</P>
<P>
   So, if Smits is in the game when Ewing is in the game _ and the
Pacer strategy is obviously to insert Smits when Ewing is at his
post _ then perhaps the Knicks are actually better with Ewing in
the game because that means that Smits is in the game.
</P>
<P>
   Food for thought, no?
</P>
<P>
   Remember Game 3, when Smits scored 21 points in the first half?
The Pacers could manage only a 1-point lead at the half. And they
eventually lost, with Smits scoring just 4 points in the second
half. Of course, both Smits and Ewing have had their superb moments
recently, but those sweet minutes are becoming more rare. Ewing was
superb, to be sure, in the first quarter of Game 5, scoring 9 of
his 13 points, including one dazzling spin layup. He even made a
pretty pass, for his lone assist in the game. And the glorious
effort, it seemed, wore the warrior out.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Smits had come out with some remarks the other day that
he'd rather play against Ewing than the spryer Knickerbockers. This
particularly riled Knick Coach Jeff Van Gundy. ``How,'' asked Van
Gundy, in effect, ``does Smits have the nerve to diss my future
Hall of Famer?''
</P>
<P>
   Smits, as it were, was simply being honest. He loves it when
Ewing is reluctant to challenge him when he's ogling the hoop to
launch a 3-pointer. And Smits, like Ewing, aging belligerents both,
are so battered from metatarsal to patella to pectoralis major,
that at times it seems the only way they can drive to the basket is
nurse-aided.
</P>
<P>
   After the Knicks' practice Thursday at SUNY-Purchase College and
prior to Game 6 Friday night in Madison Square Garden, Ewing was
given, as the pols say, equal time. Did he believe the Pacers were
better without Smits?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't care about that stuff,'' he said. ``I have nothing to
say about it. My foot is a little sore and I'm going to ice it.
I'll be ready for tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   And Van Gundy on Ewing's value in this year's playoffs: ``We
beat Miami with Patrick on the floor.'' And the Smits factor? ``No,
the Pacers aren't better without Smits. What matters is how a group
on the floor is playing. There's no set, predictable group at any
time. It's all a human factor, how players are playing. It varies
from game to game.''
</P>
<P>
   So Van Gundy, to avoid elimination Friday night, has to be
concerned not only with Smits versus Ewing, but also with Travis
Best, the Pacer point guard, who, Van Gundy says, gets better every
game, from no points in Game 1 to 24 points in Game 5. And he must
be concerned with Jalen Rose, who is a terror when he's not in a
stupor. And Mark Jackson, who does everything to the smaller Knick
guards but bully them for pocket change.
</P>
<P>
   And, of course, there is still Reggie Miller, who has been
relatively quiet in this series _ after two spectacular series
against Milwaukee and Philadelphia leading into this one. The
impression here is that Miller, invariably a menace to the Knicks,
is just hiding behind a door waiting to jump out and shout,
``Boo!''
</P>
<P>
   Not only do moves on the court separate one player from the
other, but also which players are put on the court and when
separates one coach from another. That's why some players are
better than others, and some coaches are better than others. Ewing
and Smits both, if used wisely, can contribute handsomely. Both,
however, have a tendency to slow their teams down.
</P>
<P>
   Enter Larry Bird, Pacer coach. Enter Van Gundy. Let the
profundity begin. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-01-00 2056EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
