r s BC-BKN-LAKENOT-LADN-(SLA     06-01 0466
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKENOT-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRYANT WILL PLAY _ MOST LIKELY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORTLAND, Ore. _ If it's true the Los Angeles Lakers need a
little adversity to sharpen their focus, then the mere thought of
losing their All-Star guard should be enough to snap them to
attention for tonight's Game 6 of the Western Conference Finals.
</P>
<P>
   Kobe Bryant's sprained right foot kept him off the court for a
second straight practice Thursday, and although officially he's
listed as probable, coach Phil Jackson couldn't say for certain
that he'll play.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll know game time,'' Jackson said. ``He's not ready to
practice yet. We'd like to have him out there, but it's just not
comfortable enough for him now.''
</P>
<P>
   Bryant, who injured the foot in the first quarter Tuesday night,
received treatment Thursday and left without speaking to reporters.
But his teammates are confident he'll be on the floor _ if not
necessarily 100 percent _ tonight.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know he'll be out there,'' Robert Horry said. ``It's the
most important game of his career so far, so he'll be out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Bryant hasn't missed a game since returning from a broken hand
Dec. 1, and has since played through a variety of sprains, pulls
and bruises. So the Lakers find it difficult to believe he won't
play tonight, with a finals berth at stake.
</P>
<P>
   ``That hasn't even crossed my mind,'' Glen Rice said.
</P>
<P>
   Bryant wanted to shoot Wednesday, but Jackson pulled him off the
court.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he understood that as much as there's a need to be out
there on the floor and get a rhythm, there's also a need to
preserve himself for an opportunity if he has it (Friday),''
Jackson said.
</P>
<P>
   If Bryant does play, there's no telling how much the injury
might slow him.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, it might be a blessing in disguise,'' Horry said.
``That way he doesn't have to be running around so much, putting a
lot of pressure on himself to try to carry us, and just hit his
open J's, because he can do that so well also.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Derek Fisher, ``We feel like with Kobe we can go in there
and win. Without him, it definitely makes it a lot harder. But I
think we still feel confident enough in the other members of this
team that we can figure out a way to go up there and win.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Extended: Chris Bodaken, the team's director of video
services and part-time scout, has signed a new multiyear contract,
the team announced.
</P>
<P>
   Bodaken, a Stevenson Ranch resident and former assistant coach
at St. Francis, has worked on the Lakers' staff since 1993. He
joined the organization as a ball boy in 1986.
</P>
<P>
   __ Ouch report: Little-used rookie swingman Devean George, out
for the last week with a badly sprained left ankle, is out
indefinitely.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
