<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 21:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2285 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-PUENTE-MOURNING-NYT &LR;      06-01 0783
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PUENTE-MOURNING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK'S HISPANIC COMMUNITY MOURNS FOR TITO PUENTE, ITS MAMBO
KING 
</HEADLINE>
  (With OBIT-PUENTE) 
 By JUAN FORERO    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The cars, some with Puerto Rican flags fluttering
from windows, slowed to a crawl Thursday as they passed Tito
Puente's, the restaurant on City Island in the Bronx co-owned by
the mambo king himself.
</P>
<P>
   Most simply rolled past, the drivers and occupants looking sadly
at the name Tito Puente on the large neon sign and the
green-and-white awning. Others went inside, glancing at countless
pictures of the famous band leader and percussionist. A few left
roses and carnations at the bar, with one follower leaving a
handwritten note, ``Tito, you will be missed.''
</P>
<P>
   While the man known as El Rey, or the King, had millions of fans
the world over, across the Bronx and the rest of New York City,
where the musical legend was first and foremost known as Tito, he
was also seen a much more: A hero for the Puerto Rican community,
and a role model for the young. A man who, despite his great
success, had never forgotten his roots.
</P>
<P>
   ''He was a superstar, but he was part of the community,'' said
Bob Gotay, 48, who spent three hours Thursday afternoon outside
Tito Puente's, reminiscing about a man whose music had attracted
him since his childhood. ``You knew that every time you saw him,
that for one more day the culture was safe and in good hands.''
</P>
<P>
   Gotay said he and other Bronx residents of Puerto Rican descent
who had long followed Puente's career felt the need to be at the
restaurant, an establishment where the orchestra leader often dined
on filet of sole in plum tomato sauce, gave interviews to reporters
and, on occasion, played his music to a rapt crowd.
</P>
<P>
   ''We just wanted to take a look and say goodbye in our own way,
take a glance at the sign and maybe connect with him,'' said Gotay,
a Con Edison customer service representative who grew up in the
Soundview section of the Bronx. ``It was just a nostalgic thing,
come out here, sit a couple of hours and pay homage to a guy who
touched my life.''
</P>
<P>
   Although born in East Harlem, where he began his career playing
in neighborhood haunts, Puente would later leave an indelible mark
in several clubs in Midtown Manhattan, like the Palladium and La
Casa Del Mambo, as well as many clubs the Bronx, said friends and
fellow musicians. Through the late 1960s and into the early 1980s,
he played at clubs like the Hippo Campo on Jerome Avenue, Colgate
Gardens in the South Bronx and the Hunts Point Palace. Those who
played with him or saw him perform can never forget the flamboyance
and energy that went into every song.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a tremendous influence, not only for the up-and-coming
bands, but also for the people who came out dancing, who wanted to
have contact,'' said Ramon Rodriguez, director of the Harbor
Conservatory for the Performing Arts in East Harlem, a musical
school that Puente often visited. ``This was the only music where
people could get close to their superstars, unlike in the American
market where superstars are untouchable.''
</P>
<P>
   Nicky Marrero, 50, a percussionist and Bronx resident who often
performed with Puente, said that the master showman became a
``heartthrob for the salseros here,'' speaking of the die-hard
dancers who lived for the nights when they could dance to Puente's
music.
</P>
<P>
   ''In the Bronx, wow, you breathe the name Tito Puente and it's
like breathing oxygen,'' he said. ``He was like oxygen to us. And
he made a lot of people happy.''
</P>
<P>
   Louis Bauzo, a teacher at the Harbor Conservatory who also
played with Puente, said that the Puente built a following not just
with his music, but by making friends and remembering names. ``He
was always very accessible to the public,'' recalled Bauzo, 52.
``You couldn't just walk down the street with him. You'd have to
leave an hour early because he would be stopped constantly.''
</P>
<P>
   While his popularity would often take him around the world, he
often returned to such places as Jimmy's Bronx Cafi on Fordham Road
in the Bronx, a famed restaurant and night club, and Willie's Steak
House on Westchester Avenue. Year after year, he also played at
local venues to raise money for Tito Puente Scholarship Fund, which
gave needy teen-agers a shot at college.
</P>
<P>
   Sherley Ghappour, a waitress for three years at Tito Puente's,
said that she was always impressed by how Puente would make small
talk with her, treating her the same as he treated other famous
musicians and politicians. ``Forget it, he was a beautiful
person,'' she said. ``If I ran in, he'd be, like, `Hi how are you.'
He would kiss me. He was always such a happy person.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
