<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 21:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2286 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-CLINTON-EUROPE-1STLD-     06-01 0978
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-EUROPE-1STLD-WRITETHRU-900(2TAKES)-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON TELLS BARAK U.S. IS COMMITTED TO MIDDLE EAST PEACE
PROCESS 
</HEADLINE>
  (SUBS for complete rewrite to restructure and add background.) 
 By ELAINE SCIOLINO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LISBON, Portugal _ President Clinton said Thursday that a
historic peace agreement between the Israelis and Palestinians was
``within view now,'' and he urged both sides to make whatever
compromises were needed to reach an agreement.
</P>
<P>
   In remarks after a 90-minute meeting with Israel's prime
minister, Ehud Barak, in this seaside capital, Clinton also
announced that he was sending Secretary of State Madeleine Albright
to the Middle East next week in an effort to ``work with both
leaders on narrowing the gaps'' between them. And he said that he
would meet soon with the Palestinians' leader, Yasser Arafat, in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is also prepared to convene a three-way Camp David-style
summit meeting in Washington with Barak and Arafat, said a senior
administration official who briefed reporters. But the official
added that before that could happen, both sides would have to make
substantial progress, and that because the differences are so
great, Albright would need to make a second trip to the Middle
East.
</P>
<P>
   The summit meeting would be modeled on the one that President
Jimmy Carter held at the Camp David presidential retreat in 1978
that pushed Israel and Egypt to make peace.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both leaders know from me and they know from their own
experience,'' Clinton said, ``that they now have to be prepared to
make an intense effort and to do things that they have not done in
the past with real courage and vision if we're actually going to
get a framework that deals with the outstanding issues.'' Clinton
met with Barak before heading to Berlin for the second leg of a
weeklong trip that is to be his last visit to Europe as president.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's remarks underscored his frustration that the Israelis
and Palestinians have not made more progress toward completing a
final peace accord by their self-imposed deadline of Sept. 13.
Negotiations in Stockholm aimed at drafting an outline for a final
settlement were suspended last week after violent protests in Gaza
and the West Bank. The agreement is supposed to settle issues that
have been unresolvable for decades: the size and shape of a
Palestinian entity, the future of Jerusalem and the fate of
Palestinian refugees.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Before Thursday's meeting, Barak emphasized the tense atmosphere
between the Israelis and Palestinians when he accused Arafat of
stalling during the talks.
</P>
<P>
   ``In recent weeks, we have seen some dragging of feet in regard
to the running of negotiations,'' Barak told reporters. ``We are
trying to initiate a major move forward,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat responded by saying that Israel was stalling the talks,
not the Palestinians. ``They are the side that is wasting time and
not moving toward peace,'' Arafat said Thursday in Gaza.
</P>
<P>
   The strong language was a significant change in tone for Barak,
who almost never engages in public criticism of his adversaries,
even his political opponents at home. His comments Thursday could
have simply reflected that he is actually upset with the
Palestinians and the lack of progress. Or his statement could have
been part of the routine back-and-forth of public diplomacy that
Barak is known to loathe and seldom use.
</P>
<P>
   But his uncharacteristically strong words may have been timed to
appear resolute before the Israelis just as he is apparently ready,
according to leaks in the press, to make long-delayed concessions
in the negotiations. The talks are expected to resume this weekend
or sooner, though it is not yet clear where.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   It has been evident from Clinton's tone during this trip just
how much he wants to conclude a peace agreement between Israel and
the Palestinians in the last months of his presidency, and that he
is prepared to invest the time it would take to do so.
</P>
<P>
   On some issues, like Kosovo, European security and trade,
Clinton has sounded at times as if business is over. For instance,
his discussion of a proposal on a limited missile defense system
lacks the passion that he brings to his discussion of peace between
Israelis and Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   ``The United States will do everything we can to help them pass
this milestone,'' he said Thursday in remarks made to the staff at
the U.S. Embassy in Lisbon. ``This is tough work. If it were easy
somebody would have done it a long time ago. But actually, it is
within view now.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and his top aides on the Middle East believe that
Israel's withdrawal from Lebanon a week ago has transformed the
political landscape in the region and created a new opening for a
breakthrough.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Several times in briefing reporters, the senior administration
official referred to ``the new reality'' on the ground and the
``moment'' that will not last forever.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton made that clear at a news conference on Wednesday when
he called the Israeli withdrawal from Lebanon ``daring'' and added
that it ``imposes a much greater sense of urgency'' on all the
parties to make peace.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The flurry of activity by Clinton as his presidency nears its
end is reminiscent of the push for an Arab-Israeli peace by the
Reagan administration in 1988. Then, the ``moment'' to be seized
was the Palestinian uprising known as the intifadeh, which prompted
a new peace initiative by then Secretary of State George Shultz.
</P>
<P>
   Both Barak and Arafat have said their goal is to reach agreement
by mid-September. If they do not, Arafat has threatened to
unilaterally declare a Palestinian state.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   But ``moments'' and deadlines for Middle East peace agreements
come and go. After two days of meetings with Barak and Arafat in
Norway last November, for example, Clinton said he was beginning a
``last sprint'' for a peace settlement. At the time, the goal was
to forge a framework agreement by February 2000 that would serve as
a blueprint for a final peace accord.
</P>
<P>
   Then the deadline slipped to May. But the two sides were too far
apart to meet even that deadline, and now the focus has shifted to
the September date.
</P>
<P>
   As usual, administration officials were unwilling to discuss the
details of the meeting between Clinton and Barak, but one senior
administration official said that Clinton tried to draw out Barak
on each of the outstanding issues: borders, refugees, Jerusalem and
security arrangements.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Israel has handed over 42.9 percent of the disputed West
Bank to the Palestinians. And it has agreed to turn over to the
Palestinian Authority three Arab villages near Jerusalem. The most
difficult issues continue to be worked out through several secret
channels between the Israelis and Palestinians, with only
unsubstantiated details coming through leaks to the press. For
instance, one report by a Barak critic said that for a final deal
to be reached, Israel will have to give up 95 percent of the West
Bank, not 60 percent to 75 percent, which has always been the
working assumption. But none of the actual details of the
negotiations have been released.
</P>
<P>
   Albright on Monday will travel to the Middle East directly from
Kiev, where Clinton will meet Ukrainian leaders on the final stop
of his trip, the senior administration official said.
</P>
<P>
   The challenges facing Albright are not new, nor has she had a
particularly successful record on her trips to the Mideast. In
September, on her first trip there since Barak came to power,
Albright encountered a typical snag when the Israelis and the
Palestinians failed to deliver an agreement for a signing ceremony
in Egypt that she had hoped to preside over. And in 1997, just two
weeks after her first official visit to the Middle East, in which
she urged the Israelis to take time out from expanding settlements
on the West Bank, former Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu
announced plans to build more housing there.
</P>
<P>
   Albright will not stop in Syria during her visit to the Middle
East, the official said. Talks between Israel and Syria collapsed
in January and have not resumed despite direct consultations
between Clinton and President Hafez Assad of Syria.
</P>
<P>
   The senior administration official who briefed reporters on
Thursday also confirmed that the United States has agreed to
earmark $50 million of the $1.8 billion of U.S. military aid
budgeted for Israel to shore up Israel's border with Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   Israel estimates that a new defense line will cost from $300
million to $400 million. The withdrawal of Israel's army from
southern Lebanon last week after 18 years erased a buffer zone that
had shielded northern Israel from attacks from Lebanese territory.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Clinton spoke by telephone with Arafat, who
recently described the talks with Israel as deadlocked and was said
to be unhappy with ideas proposed by Israel in Sweden.
</P>
<P>
   Nabil Abu Rdaineh, a senior aide to Arafat, told Reuters in
Jerusalem that Arafat had ``informed President Clinton about the
current situation of the peace process, especially the current
stalemate and the deadlock it has reached.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
