<HEADER>
A2288 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BBO-BRAVES-YANKEES060     06-01 0633
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-BRAVES-YANKEES0602-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Looking for a spark
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ If there is solace in the Bronx, it is because the
New York Yankees are performing exactly as they did at this time
last year.
</P>
<P>
   The 1999 Yankees swerved all over the first two months of their
season, too.
</P>
<P>
   The first weekend of interleague play finds the defending world
champions still awaiting the jolt of inspiration that drove them
from a 24-19 start last spring to another romp through October.
</P>
<P>
   For whatever reasons, it hasn't happened. The Yankees just went
through a 13-13 May, the club's first non-winning month since
August of 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you can just sort of knit one and pearl two, you keep it
where it is and sort of tread water until you hit that seven or
eight in a row,'' manager Joe Torre said. ``Then all of sudden,
it's different.'' Shortstop Derek Jeter said, ``You don't want to
say it's like a switch that you can turn on and off, but we're
waiting for that point when everyone is running at the same time.''
</P>
<P>
   Since an eight-game winning streak that ended April 19, the
Yankees have gone 17-18. Held as the standard for situational
hitting the past two seasons, these Yanks have been out-hit 24
times in their first 49 games. They have been sustained by
excellent pitching, but David Cone and Roger Clemens are a combined
5-10.
</P>
<P>
   Tellingly, when the World Series rings were handed out earlier
this week, Clemens found his bearing the No. 33. That was the
departed David Wells' number. Clemens was wearing No. 22 the night
he beat John Smoltz in Game 4 of the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   Was it so long ago?
</P>
<P>
   ``Wearing the crown is a very delicate thing,'' Torre said.
``You have to remember that it doesn't give you any free ticket
anywhere. It's not something to be stuck in anybody's face like,
'We're the world champs. We don't have to work as hard as you.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The 1999 Yankees carried a heavier burden. They dealt with the
manager's cancer case, Darryl Strawberry's suspension and what
Torre calls ``the albatross of the 125 wins'' from the historic
1998 campaign.
</P>
<P>
   That team stood 29-20 after 49 games and was 1 1/2 games behind
Boston in the AL East. These Yankees come to Atlanta 28-21 and 1
1/2 games behind Boston. The 1999 club emerged from its black cloud
to play .611 baseball, 77-49, and go 11-1 through the postseason.
</P>
<P>
   This team has encountered none of the emotional trauma, just a
steady drizzle of injuries that has put the projected Opening Day
lineup on the field 11 times in the first 49 games.
</P>
<P>
   Third baseman Scott Brosius missed the first 18 games with a
rib-cage pull. Left-hander Andy Pettitte missed three starts with a
strained back. Jeter missed two weeks with an abdominal strain,
during which time New York lost eight times in 12 games. His return
is hoped to be an omen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Derek makes us better just by being on the field,'' Brosius
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Yanks can get better in plenty of places. The 1999 champions
batted .282 and averaged 5.6 runs a game. This year, the Yankees
are hitting .269, 12th in the league, and scoring 4.8 runs. Last
year's team walked 4.4 times a game, third in the league; this
year's walks are 3.4, 13th in the league. This team also is on pace
to commit 11 more errors.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves series should sound a bell. Starting this weekend,
the Yankees play 17 games against first-place teams _ the Braves,
Boston and the Chicago White Sox _ during the next 24 days, plus
three more against the rival Mets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our bullpen has been the only thing that's been consistent,''
Jeter said. ``We're still waiting for that point for everything
else to pick up. We hope it's coming soon.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
