<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Judge in Microsoft Trial Delays Ruling for U.S. Reply
</P>
<P>
   The federal judge in the Microsoft antitrust case unexpectedly
agreed to delay his final ruling for about a week, giving the
Justice Department time to reply to Microsoft's proposal to water
down the government's breakup plan. Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson
had planned to issue his final ruling, widely expected to call for
a breakup of the company, by today. But Justice Department
officials asked whether they could reply to Microsoft's comments on
the government's remedy proposal, which were filed on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Big Nasdaq Gain Leads Broad Rally
</P>
<P>
   Technology stocks soared, lifting the Nasdaq composite index
181.59 points, or 5.3 percent, to 3,582.50. It was the index's
seventh-best gain in percentage terms. The Standard &AMP; Poor's
500-stock index also rose sharply, up 28.21 points, or nearly 2
percent, to 1,448.81, while the Dow Jones industrial average
climbed 129.97 points, or 1.2 percent, to 10,652.20.
</P>
<P>
   Retail Sales Increased 4.3 Percent in May
</P>
<P>
   Retail sales climbed 4.3 percent in May with consumers buying
housewares, appliances and summer fashions, even as higher interest
rates and gasoline prices threatened to crimp spending. Several
department store companies met or topped forecasts. Sears, Roebuck
said sales jumped 3.5 percent. Expectations ranged from 1 percent
to 3 percent. Its shares rose 50 cents, to $37.4375. Sales at J.C.
Penney stores rose 1.1 percent, beating projections for unchanged
sales.
</P>
<P>
   In Online Auctions, Rings of Bidders
</P>
<P>
   A close analysis of eBay art auctions reveals that the
flourishing cyberauction world faces a deeper and more intransigent
problem than people who bid on their own items to drive up the
price: the prospect of rings of shill bidders, acting as partners.
</P>
<P>
   Fashionmall.com to Buy Boo.com
</P>
<P>
   The remnants of Boo.com, the Web retailer that sought bankruptcy
last week when investors refused to give it more cash, were
acquired by Fashionmall.com, a New York Internet company, for an
undisclosed price.
</P>
<P>
   Alcan Wins Algroup With Higher Bid
</P>
<P>
   Alcan Aluminium of Canada agreed to buy Algroup of Switzerland
after an influential Swiss shareholder group threw its support
behind a sweetened deal worth $4.7 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Advertising That's All About Luck
</P>
<P>
   Advertisers and media magnates are celebrating the concept of
good fortune with a lengthening list of products, publications and
pitches centered on the word ``lucky,'' including a magazine named
Lucky, a character called Mr. Lucky who promotes the Excite Web
site and the venerable Lucky Strike cigarette brand, which is being
reintroduced with a big advertising push that plays up the name.
</P>
<P>
   Prudential to Buy Stake in Kyoei Life
</P>
<P>
   Prudential Insurance Co. of America, the largest life insurer in
the United States, has tentatively agreed to take a stake in the
Kyoei Life Insurance, one of Japan's many faltering life insurers.
</P>
<P>
   Manufacturing Index Edges Lower
</P>
<P>
   The National Association of Purchasing Management reported that
its overall index of economic activity in the manufacturing economy
fell 1.7 points, to 53.2 in May, the lowest reading since February
1999. A separate report showed that spending on construction
projects fell 0.6 percent in April.
</P>
</TEXT>
