<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 21:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2291 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f BC-AUTO-FUEL-ECONOMY-ART     06-01 0975
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTO-FUEL-ECONOMY-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
USING A LOOPHOLE, CARMAKERS CLAIM FUEL ECONOMY GAIN 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By KEITH BRADSHER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ A soon-to-be released government report calculates
that the average fuel economy of new family vehicles has improved
slightly in the 2000 model year, but the numbers would look much
worse if automakers had not begun producing huge numbers of
vehicles that can run on either gasoline or ethanol.
</P>
<P>
   Consumers almost never fuel them with ethanol, which is sold by
only 108 of the nation's 178,000 service stations. Nonetheless,
General Motors, Ford Motor and DaimlerChrysler are producing
roughly 750,000 dual-fuel minivans, small pickup trucks and cars
this year at an extra cost of up to $300 each. These vehicles are
counted by the government as getting roughly triple the gas mileage
that they actually achieve, allowing manufacturers to sell more
full-sized sport utilities and pickups while still meeting federal
standards for average fuel economy.
</P>
<P>
   The government report, produced by the National Highway Traffic
Safety Administration, calculated that the average fuel economy for
all new family vehicles sold in the 2000 model year would be 24.7
miles per gallon, after including the special treatment of
dual-fuel vehicles. That is up slightly from 24.5 in the 1999 model
year and the same as in the 1998 model year, but still well below a
peak of 26.2 miles per gallon in the 1987 model year.
</P>
<P>
   Without the benefit from the special treatment of ethanol, the
overall number would be up very slightly from 1999, when many
dual-fuel vehicles were also sold, and down from 1998, when
automakers were just starting to build the dual-fuel vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   The growing popularity of large sport utility vehicles and
pickup trucks that are far less fuel-efficient than cars has
lowered the average fuel economy of the nation's vehicles in recent
years. Automakers have made the big vehicles a bit more
fuel-efficient for this model year. But there are so many of them
being sold that they have dragged down the average.
</P>
<P>
   Fuel economy has become a political issue again this year
because of rising gasoline prices, the possibility of shortages of
certain types of gasoline in the Midwest this summer and growing
criticisms of large family vehicles by environmentalists and safety
advocates.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John McCain, the Arizona Republican who unsuccessfully
sought his party's presidential nomination earlier this year, has
used his position as chairman of the Senate Commerce Committee to
order Congress' General Accounting Office to perform a broad review
of American fuel-economy policies.
</P>
<P>
   At McCain's request, the review is focused on the safety,
environmental and energy conservation issues raised by the
fuel-economy standards for sport utilities and other so-called
light trucks, which are more lenient than the standards applied to
cars. Pia Pialorsi, a spokeswoman for the Commerce Committee, said
on Thursday that the report should be finished by August.
</P>
<P>
   The 12-year-old law that gives special treatment to automobiles
that can burn ethanol or gasoline also requires the National
Highway Traffic Safety Administration to prepare an extensive
report of the legislation's effectiveness by the end of the
government's current fiscal year, on Sept. 30. The law will make
the fuel-economy calculations for dual-fuel vehicles less favorable
for automakers in 2004, and manufacturers have already begun
lobbying for an extension of that deadline.
</P>
<P>
   An auto executive who insisted on anonymity said that the
industry was counting on support for an extension of the law from
the farm lobby and from politicians who might want to impress
voters in Iowa, which holds the first presidential caucuses.
</P>
<P>
   Samuel Leonard, General Motors' policy director for fuel economy
and air pollution, said the fuel-economy credits for dual-fuel
vehicles were needed as an incentive for automakers to build
vehicles that could burn ethanol, a type of alcohol made from corn,
sugar cane or even waste paper. For many years, automakers refused
to build vehicles for which alternative fuels were not available
while the oil industry refused to distribute fuels that few
vehicles could burn. The fuel-economy credits could break the
standoff, Leonard said.
</P>
<P>
   Environmentalists have long been skeptical of ethanol, mainly
because there have been conflicting studies on whether it takes
more fossil fuels to grow corn and turn it into ethanol than would
be burned by gasoline-powered vehicles. Oil companies do not like
to sell ethanol because it is so corrosive that it cannot be
shipped in steel pipelines, requiring costly trucks, barges, and
rail cars instead, said John Felmy, the director of policy and
statistics at the American Petroleum Institute in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   There have also been predictions of a coming ethanol shortage.
The Environmental Protection Agency has proposed the elimination of
a popular gasoline additive, MTBE, which accounts for almost 3
percent of the volume of gasoline, and the use of ethanol instead.
The ethanol industry says it can increase production.
</P>
<P>
   The average fuel economy of new cars has inched up to 28.4 miles
per gallon from 28.3 in the 1999 model year, the report said. But
the average for light trucks _ sport utilities, pickup trucks and
vans _ jumped to 21.2 miles per gallon from 20.7 a year earlier.
Almost all of the automobiles being produced with the capacity to
burn ethanol are minivans and small pickup trucks, like Ford
Rangers with 3-liter engines and Dodge and Chrysler minivans with
3.3-liter engines, as automakers have struggled to comply with
federal standards.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Safety agency officials estimated that labeling vehicles as
capable of burning ethanol or gasoline had allowed Ford and
DaimlerChrysler to increase the calculated average fuel economy of
their sport utility vehicles and other so-called light trucks by
about eight-tenths of a mile per gallon in the 2000 model year. The
benefit for GM is four-tenths of a mile per gallon in the current
model year. GM has indicated that it plans to step up production.
</P>
<P>
   The government's rules require each automaker to produce cars
with a so-called corporate average fuel economy of at least 27.5
miles per gallon and light trucks with an average fuel economy of
at least 20.7 miles per gallon. Gasoline prices have recently
increased but over the last decade, adjusted for inflation, they
have been among the lowest ever, and this has helped create demand
for light trucks with poor gas mileage.
</P>
<P>
   Auto executives have called repeatedly for Congress to repeal
the corporate average fuel economy rules (known as CAFE) and
replace them with higher gasoline taxes, but there has been no
enthusiasm in Washington for such a move. ``A philosophy of CAFE
that doesn't have a corollary of fuel policy doesn't work,'' said
James Holden, the president of DaimlerChrysler's Chrysler unit, in
an interview earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   The giant Ford Excursion sport utility vehicle and a growing
number of full-size pickup trucks are not included in the
fuel-economy averages at all, because they exceed the maximum
weight that regulators set in the 1970s for consideration as a
family vehicle. GM and Ford told regulators at the time that they
could not envision selling family vehicles weighing as much as
their current models do.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's review and the safety agency's report on dual-fuel
vehicles in September are unlikely to result in legislative action
this year. The Republican majority in the House approved a
transportation budget two weeks ago that, for the sixth year in a
row, bans the spending of federal money to revise federal
fuel-economy rules.
</P>
<P>
   House Democrats organized an effort to remove the ban but then
backed away from introducing the necessary amendment, fearing an
election-year split between environmentalists, who favor stricter
standards, and labor unions, which worry that American automakers
depend on big gas guzzlers for their profits.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate is tentatively scheduled to vote in two weeks on a
nonbinding resolution calling for an end to the ban. Sen. Slade
Gorton, R-Wash., a state with no auto assembly plants and high
gasoline prices, said that he hoped to do better than last year,
when the Senate defeated a similar resolution, 55 to 40.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm convinced we'll get more votes than last year, and we've
got a 50-50 chance of winning it,'' Gorton said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
