<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-GERMANY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON FINDS GERMANS CRITICAL OF U.S. MISSILE DEFENSE PLAN 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also CLINTON-EUROPE) 
 By ELAINE SCIOLINO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN _ President Clinton arrived in Germany for a three-day
visit Thursday and faced immediate criticism of his
administration's plans to build a limited missile defense system.
</P>
<P>
   In a 90-minute meeting with Clinton in the official Chancellery,
Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder added his voice to the chorus of
European allies criticizing the administration's plan, telling
Clinton that it could touch off a new arms race.
</P>
<P>
   Standing beside Clinton following their meeting, Schroeder told
reporters that the American president presented his views on his
administration's position ``in a very frank way.'' Schroeder added,
``I then went on and stated my concerns, concerns that we have to
be very careful that any project does not re-trigger the process of
a renewed arms race.''
</P>
<P>
   In an interview that will appear in Friday's editions of
Berliner Zeitung, Schroeder was even more forceful, saying,
``Neither economically nor politically can we afford a new round of
the arms race. No one can dispute the Americans' right to develop
what they believe is right for national defense. On the other hand,
we are partners in a common alliance.''
</P>
<P>
   Other German officials have warned that the missile defense
would weaken military ties between the United States and its
European allies. And they have accused the United States of
overstating the threat.
</P>
<P>
   In his own remarks to reporters, Clinton did not respond to
Schroeder's assertions. But in briefing reporters later, the
national security adviser, Sandy Berger, acknowledged the
criticism.
</P>
<P>
   ``He expressed his concern that we proceed with due
consideration for the impact on others, including Europe,'' Berger
said in summing up Schroeder's remarks.
</P>
<P>
   A number of European leaders are concerned that a missile
defense system could upset existing disarmament accords,
particularly the 1972 Antiballistic Missile Treaty with Russia,
which must be amended to allow for the missile defense plan.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Clinton nor any of his aides have made the point _ at
least not publicly _ that the administration's plan is far less
ambitious than one proposed by George W. Bush, the presumptive
Republican nominee for president, who is ready to abandon the ABM
treaty as a relic of the past.
</P>
<P>
   But Berger stressed that the discord was ``not at all sharp,''
adding, ``It was a very intelligent discussion of a very
complicated issue.''
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Clinton laid out the American conviction that it
must find ways to counter dangerous emerging nuclear threats like
North Korea.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm concerned about how we proceed with Europe and their sense
of comfort level with this,'' Berger paraphrased Clinton as telling
Schroeder. ``But ultimately, I've got to make a decision in terms
of national security.''
</P>
<P>
   Schroeder's criticism slightly tarnished the opening of
Clinton's visit to Berlin, the first by an American president since
it became the capital of a united Germany following the end of the
Cold War. On Friday Clinton travels to Aachen, the ancient capital
of Charlemagne, to receive the Charlemagne Prize, awarded annually
to a person who has worked toward European unity and prosperity.
</P>
<P>
   On another area of contention between the United States and
Germany, Clinton expressed American concern over Germany's handling
of child custody cases involving American parents.
</P>
<P>
   According to the State Department, Germany favors German parents
in custody cases and prevents American parents from gaining access
to children living in Germany.
</P>
<P>
   Two high-profile cases involve Lady Catherine Meyer, the wife of
the British ambassador in Washington, and Joseph Cooke, a New
Yorker. Meyer's two sons from a previous marriage were abducted by
their German father; she has been allowed to see them for a total
of 24 hours in the past six years.
</P>
<P>
   Cooke has been fighting to regain custody of his two children,
who were handed over to foster parents in Germany seven years ago
after his wife, a German, fled there with them and declared she was
mentally ill.
</P>
<P>
   Schroeder announced Thursday that Germany would set up a working
group of experts with the United States to investigate custody
disputes involving American parents, but warned he could not
interfere directly in the court system.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has recently come under pressure from an organized lobby
of American parents who complain that Germany has violated
conventions guaranteeing the return of kidnapped children.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the House of Representatives endorsed the effort in a
resolution, voting 416-0.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
