<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBC-UCLA-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRUINS WILL FEEL THE HEAT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LEE BARNATHAN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; LOS ANGELES _ A movie poster proclaims the road trip is ``the
greatest college tradition of all.''
</P>
<P>
   In baseball parlance, the road trip could refer to Louisiana
State's Alex Box Stadium. Only for UCLA's baseball team, it's not
considered great.
</P>
<P>
   Daunting is a better word, for this is UCLA's challenge: winning
a Super Regional series at a place that has 8,000 fans screaming
and stomping on metal bleachers close to the field.
</P>
<P>
   In heat and humidity considered extreme by California standards.
</P>
<P>
   Against a team ranked second nationally that has won 84 percent
of its home games since 1984.
</P>
<P>
   Put another way: When UCLA coach Gary Adams scouted LSU, a
fellow coach who had a football player on his team said playing at
LSU was louder than a goal-line stand at Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   Adams said the closest Pac-10 stadium is at Arizona State, but
you'd have to ``multiply ASU by 10,000 times'' to equate it with
LSU.
</P>
<P>
   In last week's regional at Oklahoma City, UCLA played in some
humidity and suffered a bit. It's worse in Baton Rouge.
</P>
<P>
   To get to the College World Series, the Bruins (38-24) have to
beat the Tigers (46-17) in a three-game series that starts today.
</P>
<P>
   ``How we handle the crowd will be a factor,'' Adams said. ``I've
been told that's the toughest element. Well, that's tied with the
heat and humidity.''
</P>
<P>
   If UCLA were a bunch of eager-eyed freshmen, Adams would be more
concerned. But since this is a junior-laden team that went 18-14 on
the road this season, Adams is less concerned.
</P>
<P>
   Both teams have offensive firepower. UCLA has outfielder and
Alemany High graduate Bill Scott (.430, 21 HR, 75 RBI), first
baseman Chase Utley (.389, 21 HR, 67 RBI) and catcher Forest
Johnson (.356, 22 HR, 76 RBI).
</P>
<P>
   LSU, which outscored its regional opponents 45-4 last week, has
catcher Brad Cresse (.399, 29 HR, 100 RBI), the son of former
Dodgers coach Mark Cresse, and first baseman Brad Hawpe (.366, 9
HR, 72 RBI). The Tigers also have won seven straight and 12 of 15.
</P>
<P>
   Both teams also have some pitching, but the offenses often
overshadow them. The Bruins likely will start Rob Henkel (6-3, 5.59
ERA), then come back Saturday with Josh Karp (10-1, 4.72 ERA),
leaving either John Brandt (7-5, 4.02 ERA) or Bobby Roe (7-5, 5.36
ERA) to start Sunday's if-necessary game.
</P>
<P>
   Sometime this weekend, LSU will throw Brian Tallet, a 6-foot-7
left-hander who's 13-3 with a 3.20 ERA and 121 strikeouts in 123
innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their talent matches up with ours,'' Adams said. ``They aren't
the No. 2 team in the nation for nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   UCLA is making its 11th postseason appearance and fourth in the
last five years. Perhaps unfortunately, UCLA's region (at Oklahoma
City last week) was rated 15th of the 16 regions, and LSU's was
second. Had LSU not won its region, UCLA would have hosted today's
Super Regional.
</P>
<P>
   Things didn't work out that way, so the Bruins have their noisy,
sticky and sweaty challenges ahead.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
