<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-ENVIRONMENT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH ANNOUNCES PROPOSALS ON CONSERVATION OF SCENIC AREAS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CLAY ROBISON 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAND HARBOR STATE PARK, Nev. _ With Houston's pollution problems
seemingly light years away, George W. Bush on Thursday stood on the
shore of a sparkling Lake Tahoe to announce proposals to boost
conservation of scenic areas and other natural resources.
</P>
<P>
   Key to Bush's plan are tax incentives to help spare pristine
land from development and giving local governments and private
landowners a greater voice in conservation decisions.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas governor and likely Republican presidential nominee,
under fire from environmentalists over air pollution problems in
Houston and other Texas cities, chose one of the nation's most
scenic areas to encourage preservation of what he called ``the
living presence of the great almighty.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to preserve places like this in America,'' he said.
``It is our duty to use the lands wisely _ and sometimes not use
them at all.''
</P>
<P>
   But the governor quickly drew fire from the campaign of Vice
President Al Gore, his likely Democratic opponent and a politician
long associated with environmental issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``Trusting George W. Bush to protect our land, air and water is
putting the fox in charge of the henhouse,'' a Gore spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats also pointed out that Texas is 49th among the states
in per capita spending on parks and recreation.
</P>
<P>
   The key points of Bush's conservation plan include:
</P>
<P>
   --Fully funding the federal Land and Water Conservation Fund at
$900 million a year and using half of the money to provide funding
for state and local conservation efforts. The fund, established 35
years ago, has never been fully funded, according to the Bush
campaign. Federal funds come primarily from revenues from offshore
oil and gas drilling.
</P>
<P>
   --Exempting 50 percent of the profit from land sales for
conservation purposes from the capital gains tax. Bush said this
tax break was necessary to encourage people who couldn't afford to
give their land away to sell it to protect wildlife or plant
habitat or for other conservation purposes.
</P>
<P>
   --Matching grants for states to establish incentive programs to
help private landowners protect rare species while engaging in
traditional land management practices.
</P>
<P>
   --Eliminating the estate tax. This proposal, which Bush has
repeatedly advocated, would cost $55 billion over five years, his
campaign said, but would protect ``cash-poor'' farmers and ranchers
from having to sell part of their land to developers to pay
inheritance taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said it was wrong for Washington to unilaterally restrict
uses of federal lands.
</P>
<P>
   ``The federal government and the states, local communities and
private landowners must respect and work with one another to
preserve our natural heritage,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said a private lands enhancement program in Texas has
worked well. It allows state experts to provide technical
assistance to private landowners who want to protect wildlife or
preserve natural habitat. Bush said nearly 10 million acres in
Texas are under wildlife management plans.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush campaign said the Texas Legislature authorized $60
million in bonds for parks in 1997 under Bush's administration.
</P>
<P>
   An environmentalist active in an effort to preserve Lake Tahoe,
which straddles the Nevada-California state line, gave Bush's
proposals a mixed review.
</P>
<P>
   Rochelle Nason of South Lake Tahoe, Calif., executive director
of the League to Save Lake Tahoe, said tax credits were a
``positive thing'' for conservation but weren't enough.
</P>
<P>
   Nason said it wouldn't always be in the public interest to turn
over control of federal lands solely to local communities. ``The
needs of the American people as a whole have to be considered when
you're looking at the management of federal lands,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Nason said Gore also has been supportive of conservation
partnerships.
</P>
<P>
   While in Nevada on Thursday, Bush also attended private
fund-raisers for his campaign and for the Republican National
Committee's presidential trust, which will assist his presidential
effort. They were among a series of fund-raisers that Bush has
attended in several western states this week.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet news service Salon reported Thursday that Nevada
donors included casino owners.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the GOP's religious conservatives have moral objections
to gambling, and disapprove of accepting donations from members of
the gambling industry. Bush spokeswoman Karen Hughes said Bush
doesn't accept money for his presidential campaign from gambling
political action committees, but doesn't try to screen the business
interests of individual donors.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
