<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORLD-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN: LONDON BOMB BLAST
</P>
<P>
   A small bomb blew up under the Hammersmith Bridge over the
Thames in London, causing structural damage and traffic chaos but
no injuries. No one claimed responsibility for the blast, but
authorities speculated it was timed by dissident Irish republicans
to disrupt the power-sharing Northern Ireland government. The
bridge has been the target of two previous Irish republican bombs.
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN: DUNKIRK REVISITED
</P>
<P>
   Sixty years after the ragtag flotilla that Churchill called
Britain's ``great tide of small vessels'' helped rescue 340,000
soldiers from the beaches of Dunkirk, some 60 boats will cross the
English Channel from Dover on Friday in commemoration. In 1940
hundreds of fishing boats, pleasure craft and tugs braved German
fire for 10 days to ferry soldiers pinned down by the Nazi advance
to navy ships in deeper waters.
</P>
<P>
   INDIA: NEPAL FLIGHTS RESUME
</P>
<P>
   Indian Airlines has resumed flights to Nepal five months after
Islamic militants hijacked one of its planes from Katmandu. The
national carrier suspended flights because of what India saw as
security lapses. The shutdown cost Nepal millions of dollars in
lost tourism revenues.
</P>
<P>
   MIDDLE EAST
</P>
<P>
   EGYPT: NO E-MAIL DIVORCE
</P>
<P>
   A Muslim can divorce his wife by uttering the words ``I divorce
you'' three times, but he cannot end a marriage by pronouncing his
decision in an e-mail message, a court in Alexandria has ruled. The
court said Islam, which is the basis of family law in Egypt, does
not accept electronic documents as evidence. The issue arose in the
case of a woman who remarried after receiving an e-mail divorce
message from her first husband, who later changed his mind and
demanded she come back to him.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL: GOLAN BUILDING
</P>
<P>
   The Israel Lands Authority issued tenders for the marketing of
86 housing units in the Golan Heights settlement of Katzrin.
Leftist lawmakers criticized the move, saying that if peace talks
with Syria resume, the new construction will be ``like a bone stuck
in Israel's throat,'' as Mossi Raz, a legislator, put it.
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA
</P>
<P>
   MOZAMBIQUE: FLOOD VICTIMS RESETTLED
</P>
<P>
   Seventy percent of the people displaced by this year's
devastating floods have been resettled or returned home, the
government reported. Of the more than 490,300 people displaced,
about 4,500 were still living in resettlement camps last month. All
told, about 700 people died in the floods that ravaged this country
in February and March.
</P>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   ECUADOR: COUP PLOTTER PARDONED
</P>
<P>
   Congress has pardoned the former armed forces chief of staff,
Gen. Carlos Mendoza, and 116 other military officers involved in
the January coup in which President Jamil Mahuad was overthrown and
replaced by Vice President Gustavo Noboa. The amnesty, suggested by
Noboa, eliminates the need for what was expected to be a
politically divisive trial of General Mendoza, above, who has said
other senior military commanders were involved in the plot but
refused to identify them.
</P>
<P>
   CANADA: ENVOY BACKS GORE
</P>
<P>
   Canada's ambassador to the United States has effectively
endorsed Al Gore over George W. Bush in the presidential race. ``We
know Vice President Gore, he knows us; he's a friend of Canada,''
Raymond Chretien said in a speech to Canadian officials. The
ambassador, a nephew of Prime Minister Jean Chretien, said,
``Governor Bush, on the other hand, doesn't know us as much,''
adding, ``When he thinks of borders, he thinks of Mexico, not of
Canada.''
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO: CARDENAS PARTY FINED
</P>
<P>
   The party of the leftist presidential candidate Cuauhtemoc
Cardenas was hit with fines of $253,082 by the federal elections
agency for filing incomplete accounts of its spending last year,
the highest of the sanctions levied against 11 political
organizations. The governing Institutional Revolutionary Party was
fined only $6,571.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
