<HEADER>
A2301 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-CAR-IRWIN-LADN-(SLANG     06-01 0513
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-IRWIN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COUTURE ENJOYS FIRST HOME ADVANTAGE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEITH LAIR  
 c.2000 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRWINDALE, Calif. _ Saturday night's Star Formula Mazda race at
Irwindale Speedway might be the biggest in Larry Couture's racing
career.
</P>
<P>
   Couture, the vice president of technical development and
transfer at City of Hope National Medical Center, has had a lot of
victories and top finishes. But when he takes to Irwindale's
half-mile oval, it will be his first race in front of the hometown
fans. He contributes half his winnings to the Duarte-based research
medical facility.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people at the City of Hope know I race and they're
making this a big deal,'' he said. ``A lot of people will be coming
out and that's pretty exciting. It's unusual for a vice president
of an institution like this to race. Most people don't know someone
personally who races, so this is as cool as it gets.''
</P>
<P>
   Also racing will be the NASCAR Late Model series in twin 40-lap
races, Super Stocks and Grand American Modifieds. Qualifying for
those classes starts at 5 p.m., with racing beginning at 7 p.m. The
Star Mazda series qualifies today, but the grandstands will not be
open.
</P>
<P>
   Couture admits that, amid all the hoopla, Saturday's event will
be quite challenging. The 43-year-old Claremont resident has raced
on only one oval course, earlier this year. He and his crew-chief
wife, Jill Mathison, who is also employed at the City of Hope, are
rookies in the pro series and their team is one of only three in
the series that is not part of a factory team. The series is
considered a steppingstone to the larger open-wheel road racing
series.
</P>
<P>
   He got his start racing in the Formula Ford series and in the
Vintage Auto Racing Association series the past four years, getting
several victories and top-five finishes. He opted for the Star
Mazda series because of the cost considerations, the
competitiveness of the younger drivers and the chance to race on
ovals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was usually near the front of the pack and felt it wasn't
very competitive,'' he said of his previous racing. ``In this
series, there are 20 very talented drivers in virtually identical
cars. This is taken all very seriously.''
</P>
<P>
   Couture is in 14th place in the Western Division standings after
four races. He was 19th in his first Formula Mazda race on the mile
oval at Phoenix International Raceway, 14th at Buttonwillow and
26th and 17th in a two-day, two-race event at Thunderhill.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm beginning to fit in,'' he said. ``I'm in the middle and
lower end of the pack. I'm pleased to be in 14th. I feared I'd be
worse and I hoped for better.''
</P>
<P>
   Racing in Formula Fords gave him plenty of road-racing exposure.
One reason he chose the Star Mazda series was the chance to race
ovals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Phoenix was exhilarating,'' said Couture, who thinks _ with
the right sponsorship package _ that he could be racing in the
Indianapolis 500 in three or four years. ``It's very intimidating
and nothing like road racing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-01-00 2126EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
