<DOCNO> NYT20000601.0378 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 21:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2302 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-CUBAN-BOY-1STLD-WRITE     06-01 1155
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUBAN-BOY-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-1000(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
APPEALS COURT RULES IN FAVOR OF INS IN ELIAN CASE 
</HEADLINE>
   (SUBS for complete rewrite. Contains more quotes, reaction and
analysis. Note new byline.)  
(See also CUBAN-BOY-POLITICS and CUBAN-BOY-ASSESS) 
(ART ADV: Photos NYT15, 16, 18, 19 are being sent to NYT photo
clients. Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By RICK BRAGG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ A federal appellate panel Thursday upheld the right of
immigration officials to let Elian Gonzalez's father take the boy
back to Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   A three-judge panel of the 11th U.S. Court of Appeals, in
Atlanta, ruled unanimously that the Immigration and Naturalization
Service had the power to decide that only a parent can act for such
a young child in immigration proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   The decision let Juan Miguel Gonzalez take a step closer to
bringing his son home, though the panel barred Elian from leaving
the United States for at least 21 days to give his Miami relatives,
who have fought to keep him from returning to Cuba, time to appeal
the decision.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling is seen as a solid defeat for the relatives who took
him in after his mother and 10 others drowned in a failed crossing
from Cuba. The boy was found floating on an inner tube off the
Florida coast on Thanksgiving Day.
</P>
<P>
   The judges said that the law gave wide discretion to the INS in
such cases and that the powers of the executive branch should be
respected.
</P>
<P>
   ``This case, at first sight, seems to be about little more than
a child and his father,'' the panel wrote in their decision. ``But,
for this court, the case is mainly about the separation of powers
under our constitutional system of government.''
</P>
<P>
   That plain language, said some legal experts, will make a
successful appeal difficult.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very important step in achieving the goal we have
sought from the very beginning, to give Juan Miguel and his family
the opportunity to return to a life together,'' said Attorney
General Janet Reno.
</P>
<P>
   But the Elian case has involved more than a family. It has drawn
international attention _ not all of it good _ to Miami and its
powerful Cuban-American community, stirring resentment among the
city's other ethnic groups and leading to turmoil in city hall.
</P>
<P>
   The 33-page ruling upheld a decision by a U.S. district judge in
March that Elian was too young to comprehend a complicated asylum
application, and that his father's rights to bring him home
outweighed the desires of the boy's Miami relatives to keep him in
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The decision was written by Judge J. L. Edmondson, who was
appointed by President Ronald Reagan, and was joined by Judge Joel
F. Dubina, an appointee of President George Bush, and Judge Charles
R. Wilson, an appointee of President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The three-judge panel, in Atlanta, found that the INS was
``within the outside border of reasonable choices'' in denying the
child's asylum application, which he had signed in a childlike
scrawl, ``ELIAN.''
</P>
<P>
   David Abraham, a professor of immigration law at the University
of Miami, said the panel merely recognized ``the conservative
traditions of respecting the separation of powers and recognizing
that Congress has delegated the authority to make the calls in
tough cases'' to the INS..
</P>
<P>
   ``The court found that INS was not arbitrary in what it did,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Miami relatives were, as of Thursday evening, still weighing
their options in appealing the decision. They can either ask for a
re-hearing of the case by the same three-judge panel, or appeal the
decision to the full 11-judge 11th Circuit Court of Appeals, or
appeal to the Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have not concluded; we're going to keep fighting for
Elian's freedom,'' said Lazaro Gonzalez, Elian's great uncle and
the man who defied federal orders to give up the boy.
</P>
<P>
   His defiance led to a raid on April 22 in which federal agents
took the boy from his home and brought him to Maryland, where he
was reunited with his father. Father and son are now staying in
Washington in a home owned by an international youth organization.
</P>
<P>
   As for whether there is solid grounds for an appeal, Kendall
Coffey, one of the Miami family's many lawyers, said the ruling
``did not constitute a resounding endorsement of the way INS
handled this matter.''
</P>
<P>
   The appellate panel did, in fact, write that ``the court neither
approves nor disapproves the INS decision to reject the asylum
application filed on plaintiff's behalf.'' But, the judges wrote in
their ruling, the INS did not contradict federal law.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to thank the American people,'' Juan Miguel Gonzalez
said in Washington, D.C. ``I hope we can finally go home.''
</P>
<P>
   His lawyer, Gregory B. Craig, said it is time for the Miami
relatives to give up their battle to keep Elian. ``It is now time
to end this chapter of Elian's life and to let this family go in
peace,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the little house in Little Havana where Elian lived for
almost five months, news of the ruling drove several women to their
knees on the narrow asphalt street.
</P>
<P>
   Men wept outside the house, a shrine of sorts here in Cuban
Miami, even though Elian's Miami relatives are no longer staying
there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm hurt,'' said Bienvenido Comas, 27, a city of Miami
engineer. ``I cried today. But I have no more tears.''
</P>
<P>
   There were no violent outbreaks in the city, even in the heart
of Little Havana, where protesters had burned dumpsters and tires
and clashed with police after the raid. Police made more than 300
arrests then.
</P>
<P>
   This time, there was only sadness and disillusionment outside
the tiny walk-up cafes that usually buzz with political talk and
gossip.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today's a gloomy day,'' said Jose Portonado, an artist who
lives in Little Havana. ``But I knew it was gonna happen. I just
knew it. In the back of my mind I was hoping there would be some
master plan we did not know about. This was our last hope.''
</P>
<P>
   But the return of Elian to Cuba is still, more than likely, at
least a few weeks away.
</P>
<P>
   The appeals panel said a previous injunction they issued to keep
Elian in this country during appeals remains in force until the
panel issues a mandate to enforce Thursday's ruling.
</P>
<P>
   But such a mandate would not be issued until seven days after
the case is effectively closed under federal appellate rules. The
panel shortened the usual 45-day period to formally close the case
to 14 days.
</P>
<P>
   That means the Miami relatives have just 14 days to appeal the
case.
</P>
<P>
   If they want to appeal the case directly to the Supreme Court,
their lawyers must seek a separate order staying Elian's departure
from a Supreme Court justice or the entire court.
</P>
<P>
   If they do not appeal, which is unlikely, the mandate to enforce
the order would be filed in 21 days.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In Miami, political and legal experts said the saga will not do
Miami any good if it is prolonged even more.
</P>
<P>
   ``The case demonstrated that the overwhelming majority of
Americans were not prepared to have distant relatives kidnap a
child from his relatives as a way of continuing a 40-year-old
struggle,'' said Abraham.
</P>
<P>
   But here, where hatred of Fidel Castro is still fresh, many
Cuban-Americans cannot stand the thought of returning the child to
a Communist country.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a time of desperation,'' said Comas.
</P>
<P>
   In Germany, President Bill Clinton said he was pleased with the
court's decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``As I have said before, this is a case about the importance of
family and the bond between a father and son,'' Clinton said in a
written statement from Berlin, the second stop on the president's
European tour. ``I have supported the justice Department's
conclusion that Elian's father, Juan Miguel Gonzalez, is the one
best suited to speak for his child.''
</P>
<P>
   And in Atlanta, Vice President Al Gore said he continued to
believe that a family court should decide Elian's case. George W.
Bush, campaigning in Nevada, said Gore should urge Clinton to allow
such a family court hearing.
</P>
<P>
   The boy's great uncle, Lazaro Gonzalez, said the family has no
choice but to keep fighting any way it can. ``We are going to keep
searching for the laws that Elian is entitled to,'' he said. ``So
that Elian Gonzalez remains in a free country, as his mom wished.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
