<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-HEALTH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE EXPANDS ON PLAN FOR CANCER TREATMENT 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By PATTY REINERT 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Vice President Al Gore announced Thursday a new plan
to pay for early cancer screenings, give patients faster access to
cutting-edge treatments and outlaw discrimination by insurers and
employers based on genetic test results.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I'm entrusted with the presidency, I will work with you to
put the same energy and priority into fighting cancer that we would
put into preventing a war that would take 500,000 American lives
every year. The stakes are that great,'' Gore told cancer
researchers at Emory University Medical Center.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, who lost sister Nancy Gore Hunger to lung cancer,
announced last year that if elected president, he would double the
amount of federal money spent on cancer research to total $9
billion over the next five years.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, after visiting young cancer patients, he expanded
on that plan, telling researchers at Emory that he would propose a
``fast-track'' for approving preventive benefits for Medicare
patients to pay for cancer screenings. He also would do away with
deductibles and co-payments for Medicare recipients seeking
mammograms and testing for colorectal cancer.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president's plan also would expand Medicaid coverage to
cover colorectal cancer. Legislation currently before Congress
would provide that coverage for breast and cervical cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Citing President Kennedy's speech promising to put a man on the
moon, Gore promised to make it a national priority to ensure early
detection and treatment of colon cancer. When detected early, there
is a 96 percent survival rate for colon cancer, he said, yet today
only 61 percent of those diagnosed survive because their cancer is
too far along before it is diagnosed.
</P>
<P>
   Within the next decade, he said, ``no one in America should have
to die from colon cancer, breast cancer or prostate cancer.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We may not get there, and certain forms of these diseases may
be beyond our reach,'' he said. ``But of this much we can be
certain: If we don't set the goal, we will never get there.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore, who was accompanied by his brother-in-law, Frank Hunger,
said that when he hears the word cancer, ``I see the faces of
friends and neighbors who have been stricken.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see the people I have met across this country who have
battled back with unyielding courage and determination,'' he said.
``I know from my own experience what cancer can do to a family.''
</P>
<P>
   But Gore stopped short of telling his sister's story, which made
headlines during the 1996 Democratic National Convention when he
was forced to acknowledge that he continued to receive money from
his family's tobacco farm for several years after her death.
</P>
<P>
   Gore Hunger, who began smoking as a teen-ager, died in 1984. She
was 45.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday night, during a town hall meeting with undecided
voters in Macon, Gore was challenged by two tobacco company
employees who said they fear the federal government's anti-smoking
campaign would cost them their jobs. Gore said he sympathized, and
would work to preserve jobs, but he said he would not yield on his
top priority of preventing companies from targeting children in
their advertising campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen someone die from lung cancer,'' he said. ``I am just
not going to compromise on this. I am not.''
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, he reiterated that pledge, saying, ``We need to
stop them from marketing a deadly product to children.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore also vowed to make sure the benefits of cancer research and
treatment are accessible to all Americans, regardless of race or
economic status. ``Right now African-Americans are one-third more
likely to die of cancer than white Americans,'' he said. ``We
simply need to change that.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
<P>
