<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 21:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2309 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-BUSH-EXECUTION-DNA-BO     06-01 1254
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-EXECUTION-DNA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPRIEVE BY BUSH REFLECTS NEW ROLE OF DNA   TESTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN ALOYSIUS FARRELL  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Texas Governor George W. Bush's decision Thursday
to grant a stay of execution to Ricky McGinn, a convicted child
rapist and murderer, is striking evidence of how advances in DNA
technology are shaking a longstanding national consensus on crime,
punishment and the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   As DNA tests have freed thousands of suspected and convicted
inmates _ including eight men condemned to death _ new doubts have
been raised about the reliability of the criminal justice system.
Unquestioned support for capital punishment is no longer perceived
as a political slam-dunk.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is an evolving consciousness among everyone: the public
and the politicians,'' said Richard Dieter, executive director of
the Death Penalty Information Center, an anti-death penalty group
here. ``Now Governor Bush has recognized the importance of DNA
evidence _ and that doubts can well arise in capital cases, despite
unanimous juries and the appellate process.''
</P>
<P>
   For the first time in two terms as governor, during which 131
men and women have been executed in Texas, Bush granted a 30-day
reprieve Thursday, just half an hour before McGinn was scheduled to
die. It was a startling turnaround for a politician who has
steadfastly defended capital punishment and who, like his famous
father, has used his willingness to impose the death penalty to
appeal for votes.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's decision was surprising as well in light of the facts in
the McGinn case. McGinn, 43, was convicted of raping his
12-year-old stepdaughter and then hacking her to death with an ax
in 1993. Her blood, and the bloody ax, were found in his car. A
pubic hair and semen found on the victim were tied to McGinn by
traditional forensic lab tests.
</P>
<P>
   McGinn will now have the opportunity to have DNA tests run on
the hair and semen. If the evidence is shown to be from someone
else, McGinn's attorneys will argue that he should be exonerated of
rape. Because Texas law requires that a death row inmate be
convicted of a serious felony in addition to murder, he could then
escape execution.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is overwhelming evidence that McGinn is guilty of the
murder. So what they are saying is, `Yes, he may have hacked her to
death, but you can't prove he raped her first.' It is a strange
case to choose as an example,'' said Joshua Marquis, an Oregon
prosecutor who serves on the board of directors of the National
Association of Defense Attorneys.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout his years as governor, Bush has consistently listed
the question of guilt or innocence as his primary concern when
allowing executions to proceed in Texas. But political and legal
experts said Thursday that in the current climate it is problematic
for any presidential candidate _ even a law-and-order governor like
Bush _ to turn down a condemned inmate's request for a DNA test.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously Governor Bush is in a very awkward position running
for president: the opponents of the death penalty have been trying
to make Texas the poster child of capital punishment,'' said
Marquis.
</P>
<P>
   Marquis is one of many law enforcement officials who are worried
about the amount of attention given to DNA testing. Though only one
in 10 condemned inmates maintains a claim of innocence to death,
and one in 100 has proven his innocence, the publicity given to DNA
cases makes it seem that hundreds of innocent men and women linger
on death row, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if they have changed the climate,'' Marquis said
of death penalty foes, ``but they have certainly distorted the
debate.''
</P>
<P>
   The political climate has been undeniably altered since the 1988
and 1992 presidential campaigns, when Presidents Bush and Clinton
employed their support for capital punishment to help propel them
to the White House. And it was just four years ago that Clinton
signed legislation passed by a Republican Congress that
dramatically curtailed the rights of condemned prisoners to appeal.
At the time, four of every five Americans supported capital
punishment, and worried that executions were being needlessly
delayed.
</P>
<P>
   But even as the ink from Clinton's signature dried on the
Antiterrorism and Effective Death Penalty Act of 1996, a trickle of
news reports about the results of DNA testing began to transform
public opinion. The trickle turned into a torrent as the news media
reported on hundreds of cases where accused or convicted prisoners
were set free by virtue of a DNA test. Other condemned prisoners
were released from death row when news organizations, defense teams
_ and in one some celebrated instances a Northwestern University
journalism class _ exposed flaws in the prosecution's case without
using DNA testing.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department, in a 1996 report titled ``Convicted by
Juries, Exonerated by Science,'' concluded that DNA testing exposed
disturbing flaws in the US judicial system. Post-conviction DNA
tests, the department said, revealed the limitations of such
traditional law enforcement tools as police and eyewitness
testimony, the use of jailhouse informants, and blood type and hair
tests.
</P>
<P>
   Another Justice Department study, released last September,
concluded that ``the strong presumption that verdicts are correct .
. .has been weakened by the growing number of convictions that have
been vacated because of exclusionary DNA results.''
</P>
<P>
   The FBI, whose labs handle DNA testing for local law enforcement
officials from around the nation, reported that of 10,000 sexual
assault cases from 1989 to 1995, DNA tests revealed that 20 percent
of the men identified as the primary suspects by eyewitnesses or
the police were, in fact, innocent.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are just seeing case after case where it sure looked like
somebody was guilty and it turns out the eyewitness was wrong or
the police withheld evidence or the DNA found that a blood test was
less than accurate,'' said Dieter, of the Death Penalty Information
Center.
</P>
<P>
   Conservatives such as columnist George F. Will and preacher Pat
Robertson have joined New York lawyer Barry Scheck, who served on
the O.J. Simpson defense team, in endorsing the burgeoning
``innocence'' movement. Lawmakers like Senator Patrick Leahy of
Vermont and Representative William Delahunt of Quincy, both former
prosecutors, have introduced legislation in Congress to give
inmates a right to DNA testing.
</P>
<P>
   Support for the death penalty in the Gallup Poll has dropped
from 80 to 66 percent. In Illinois, Governor George Ryan has
declared a moratorium on executions after 13 death row inmates
there were exonerated. The New Hampshire legislature recently voted
to repeal that state's death penalty _ though capital punishment
was preserved by Governor Jeanne Shaheen's veto.
</P>
<P>
   The impact of DNA testing is such that foes of the death penalty
worry that a double standard may emerge between cases where
testable physical evidence like blood and semen or hair is
recovered, and those where it is not.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people see DNA as a magic thing, which will solve all
our problems and help us sort the guilty from the innocent. But
whether we are fortunate enough to have DNA to test is an accident,
a stroke of good luck,'' said Austin attorney Raoul Schonemann, one
of a small corps of lawyers who defend death row inmates in Texas.
``It is not enough if we are really committed as a society to not
executing innocent people.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
