<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 21:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2310 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-LEWIS-TRIAL0602-COX     06-01 0681
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEWIS-TRIAL0602-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Defense teams beginning to challenge one another
 &HT;    By Bill Torpy and Bill Rankin
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The murder trial against NFL star Ray Lewis and two
co-defendants created an odd alliance Thursday, pitting flamboyant
defense attorney Bruce Harvey and Fulton County District Attorney
Paul Howard against Lewis' own high-powered legal team.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis' team, as it has often in the trial, won that encounter.
</P>
<P>
   But the incident, and one earlier in the day, were the first
glimpses of cracks in the united front that the three murder
defendants and their seven attorneys have erected against the
prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   Sherman Street, a friend of co-defendant Reginald Oakley, was
flown in from Baltimore to testify Thursday he was with Oakley the
day before he surrendered on murder charges. Street was set to
testify he warned his friend that he'd ``be the fall guy because
Ray Lewis had a lot of money and resources.'' Oakley agreed with
that statement, according to Street.
</P>
<P>
   Harvey wanted the statement introduced, saying that it reflected
on Oakley's ``state of mind'' shortly before he took a bus from
Baltimore to Atlanta to surrender. Harvey wants to show his client
as an underdog.
</P>
<P>
   The jury never heard the statement.
</P>
<P>
   Don Samuel, one of Lewis' lawyers, objected, saying testimony
can't come from one co-defendant against another in a joint trial.
The problem, Samuel said, was Lewis could not cross-examine Oakley,
the other defendant.
</P>
<P>
   Fulton County Superior Court Judge Alice D. Bonner agreed,
basically gutting Street's testimony.
</P>
<P>
   The legal confrontation came on the heels of a similar issue
when Atlanta police Lt. Mike Smith quoted Lewis as saying he was
with ``the wrong people'' when Jacinth Baker, 21 and Richard
Lollar, 24, were stabbed to death Jan. 31.
</P>
<P>
   Harvey and Steve Sadow, attorney for co-defendant Joseph
Sweeting, objected vigorously, saying their clients were harmed by
the statement. They wanted their cases severed, which Bonner
denied.
</P>
<P>
   When arguing to get the ``fall guy'' statement into evidence,
Harvey, in a reference to Lewis' team, said, ``The shoe's on the
other foot.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith, who commands the homicide division, admitted on
cross-examination Thursday afternoon that he told a witness ``all
African-Americans have nicknames'' out of frustration because he
was getting no real names of the occupants of Ray Lewis' limousine.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had no place to go that day. We were stuck on nicknames,''
Smith testified. ``We had `Shorty,' `Derby,' `Fedora,' `AJ,' and I
was trying to link the nicknames with real names; there was tension
there.
</P>
<P>
   ``To have that misconstrued and if it offends anyone, I
sincerely apologize,'' he said. ``But we wanted the two people or
three people, whoever were responsible for the deaths.''
</P>
<P>
   The jury is composed of 10 blacks and two whites. All the
defendants and the victims are black.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, Bonner said she has issued a subpoena for limo driver
Duane Fassett to be recalled Fassett, the state's key witness, did
not testify, as expected, that he had seen Lewis punch a victim or
heard the co-defendants admit to the stabbings.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors need to confront Fassett on discrepancies in his
accounts before they can admit into evidence his prior statements.
</P>
<P>
   Fassett is resisting the subpoena in a Maryland court.
</P>
<P>
   Also, Ed Garland, Lewis' lead attorney, read the jury a
stipulation rebutting the testimony of Chester Anderson, the
admitted con man who is the only state witness who said he saw
Lewis kicking a victim. Anderson testified that a man with him also
saw Lewis attacking the man.
</P>
<P>
   However, that man, John DiSiena, told prosecutors he was drunk
and did not see that. Bonner ordered both sides to draw up a
statement saying this.
</P>
<P>
   ``John DiSiena would testify that he did not see Ray Lewis kick
anyone and he did not tell Chester Anderson he saw Ray Lewis
kicking anyone,'' said Garland, standing before the jury box.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
