<DOCNO> NYT20000601.0387 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 21:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2311 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-LEWIS-COVERUP0602-COX     06-01 0586
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEWIS-COVERUP0602-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Prosecutors say Lewis directed cover-up
 &HT;    By Bill Rankin and Bill Torpy
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Moments after his stretch limo sped away from where
two young men who lay mortally wounded on a Buckhead street,
prosecutors say, Ray Lewis began a concerted cover-up to escape
blame.
</P>
<P>
   Immediately, he ordered members of his party to keep their
mouths shut. Later, he had evidence destroyed and lied to police,
prosecutors contend.
</P>
<P>
   While prosecutors have elicited scant evidence that Lewis
actually assaulted anyone, they are trying to convince jurors that
the star NFL linebacker had a guilty state of mind in the hours
after the killings.
</P>
<P>
   But Lewis' attorneys contend there are other reasons behind his
incriminating behavior. And, in this case, Lewis cannot be
convicted of lying to police or obstructing justice because he is
charged only with the more serious crimes of murder, felony murder
and aggravated assault.
</P>
<P>
   ``The evidence does tend to lend itself to an argument of a
consciousness of guilt, that is, Mr. Lewis engaged in the cover-up
because he was involved to some degree,'' former federal prosecutor
Buddy Parker said. ``It would be very important evidence if there
was an additional charge it could apply to, but they don't have
that in this case.''
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, District Attorney Paul Howard presented Lewis'
statement to police the morning after the stabbings, during which
he lied by saying he couldn't identify most of the limo passengers.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis' lead defense attorney, Ed Garland, has conceded that his
client was ``not truthful'' to police. But Garland contends Lewis
was not concealing his guilt. Instead, Lewis ``panicked,'' fearing
the damaging publicity could jeopardize his NFL career, Garland
said.
</P>
<P>
   According to testimony, Lewis did more than lie to police:
</P>
<P>
   As his limo left the crime scene, Lewis turned to his companions
and commanded, ``Keep your mouth shut and don't say nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   After he was seen huddling with his girlfriend Jessica Robertson
in his Georgian Terrace hotel room later thatmorning, Robertson
drove away and stopped behind a fast food restaurant where a fellow
limo passenger dumped a white hotel laundry bag into a Dumpster.
Prosecutors say the bag contained Lewis' bloodstained suit.
</P>
<P>
   A photo of Lewis' entourage, which would have helped police
identify the limo passengers, was destroyed. Limo passenger Evelyn
Sparks said the photo was taken from her purse by Robertson. ``She
said she burned it,'' Sparks testified.
</P>
<P>
   Co-defendant Reginald Oakley was seen wearing an oversize
sweatsuit hours after the slayings, not the outfit he wore Super
Bowl night. Prosecutors will say he got the sweatsuit from Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta lawyer Jack Martin said the jury will have to sort out
which argument _ the prosecution's or the defense _ is more
believable.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem for Lewis is, this type of evidence puts pressure
on him to take the stand to explain his actions,'' Martin said.
``This may be the prosecution's strategy, because their only hope
for conviction may be that the jury doesn't believe Mr. Lewis.''
</P>
<P>
   If Lewis is acquitted, Fulton prosecutors may not be able, under
the law, to indict him for a cover-up. ``You get only one bite at
charging somebody in a case like this,'' said DeKalb District
Attorney J. Tom Morgan. ``They needed to put all their eggs in one
basket.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
