<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 21:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2315 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-ELIAN-COURT-BOS &LR;      06-01 1058
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELIAN-COURT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
APPEALS PANEL DENIES ASYLUM HEARING FOR ELIAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Moving Elian Gonzalez a giant step toward returning
to Cuba, a federal appeals court Thursday ruled that US immigration
officials acted legally in rejecting the 6-year-old refugee's
request for an asylum hearing.
</P>
<P>
   Elian's Miami relatives, who helped turned the boy into an
international symbol of the anti-Castro movement, said they may
appeal to the US Supreme Court in a last-ditch effort to block his
repatriation to Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   But Thursday's unanimous ruling by a three-judge panel of the
11th US Circuit Court of Appeals in Atlanta appears to clear the
way for Elian and his father, Juan Miguel Gonzalez, to return to
their communist homeland if their Miami relatives do not succeed in
further court challenges within 14 days.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's what I've always felt from the deepest part of my
heart,'' Juan Miguel Gonzalez, outside his lawyer's office in
Washington, said of the ruling. ``A child always should be with his
parents, and I should be speaking on behalf of my son.''
</P>
<P>
   His lawyer, Gregory Craig, said, ``It is now time to end this
chapter of Elian's life and let this family go in peace.''
</P>
<P>
   The decision, hailed by President Clinton and denounced by
Cuban-American exile leaders, marked a major milestone in the
extraordinary saga of a child who effectively became a pawn in an
international custody battle after he was rescued at sea last
November off the Florida coast.
</P>
<P>
   Elian's mother, Elisabeth, and 10 others who had fled with him
from Cuba died when their small boat capsized before fishermen
found the boy clinging to an inner tube in the Atlantic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm heartbroken,'' one of his rescuers, Donato Dalrymple, said
of the court ruling. Dalrymple, who lifted Elian from the inner
tube, was clutching the boy in April when federal agents seized the
child at gunpoint from the home of his Miami relatives.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to keep fighting for the liberty of Elian,'' said
the boy's great-uncle, Lazaro Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
   While Elian lived with his relatives in Miami's Little Havana,
court papers were filed to make him the youngest refugee to seek an
asylum hearing in the United States without a parent's consent. The
Immigration and Naturalization Service denied the request, and the
appeals court upheld the decision, despite concerns about returning
Elian to ``a country with little respect for human rights and basic
freedoms.''
</P>
<P>
   Though the INS based its decision on an ``imperfect'' policy,
the decision fell ``within the outside border of reasonable
choices,'' the appeals panel wrote in a 33-page decision.
</P>
<P>
   The panel said ``reasonable people can disagree'' about the INS
decisions, which Clinton and Attorney General Janet Reno refused to
reverse.
</P>
<P>
   ``Still, the choices were not unreasonable, not capricious and
not arbitrary, but were reasoned and reasonable,'' the judges
wrote. ``The INS's considerable discretion was not abused.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, traveling in Europe, said the court ruling affirmed his
position that the case is ``about the importance of family and the
bond between a father and son.''
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, Reno told reporters, ``We have said all along
that Elian belongs with his father, Juan Miguel Gonzalez. Today's
ruling affirms that view.''
</P>
<P>
   The decision also reverberated in the 2000 presidential
campaign, as Vice President Al Gore, stumping in Atlanta,
reiterated that he wants a family court to decide the case. His
position, favored by Elian's Miami relatives, is at odds with the
Clinton administration's.
</P>
<P>
   Campaigning in Nevada, Texas Governor George W. Bush called on
Gore to press Clinton for a family court hearing.
</P>
<P>
   In Miami, where the case stirred emotions for months and the
community is still struggling to deal with the ethnic rifts it
created, reaction to the ruling was muted.
</P>
<P>
   A small crowd gathered at the home where Elian had lived in
Little Havana, even though his relatives have already moved to
another neighborhood. Spanish-language talk radio dissected the
court decision in regularly scheduled programs, but shows on health
and lawn care went on uninterrupted, unlike the saturation coverage
of earlier developments in the case.
</P>
<P>
   Clergy scheduled special Masses for Thursday night and called
for prayer. Otherwise, there was disappointment, but no recurrence
of the scattered violence that erupted after the predawn raid in
which Elian was seized.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a case that has been defined by miracles as well as
heartbreak, this is a painful moment,'' said Kendall Coffey, a
former US attorney who is part of the legal team for Elian's Miami
relatives. ``While we may disagree with the ruling, it feels very
good to be in the court system of this country rather than in what
passes for justice 90 miles from our shores.''
</P>
<P>
   In a minor victory for the Miami relatives, the court denied a
motion by Elian's father to replace Lazaro as the child's
representative in the asylum case. Giving Juan Miguel such status
would have allowed the father to withdraw the asylum request and
immediately return to Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   ``Notwithstanding that much has happened since Lazaro brought
this suit,'' the judges concluded, ``we see no powerful reason to
make a change at this point.''
</P>
<P>
   Lazaro and his daughter, Marisleysis Gonzalez, said they will
continue to try to see Elian, who is staying with his father at a
home in Washington that is protected around the clock by federal
agents.
</P>
<P>
   Marisleysis, who became Elian's primary caregiver in the United
States before the INS raid, said she had called to talk to Elian
this week, but the mother of the boy's schoolmate who answered the
phone refused to let her talk to him.
</P>
<P>
   Marisleysis, whose emotional reaction to the INS raid was
televised worldwide, Thursday was calm and dry-eyed at a news
conference held near Miami.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still have faith,'' she said. ``I will keep my faith and I
think the battle isn't over yet. He's still here. He's still in
this great country.''
</P>
<P>
   But Elian's father longs for his stay to end quickly. ``I love
him very much,'' Juan Miguel said, ``and I would hope that this
would come to an end and I can finally go back home together with
my son and my whole family.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
