<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 21:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2320 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-TEXAS-EXECUTE-1070(2T     06-01 1111
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-EXECUTE-1070(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH DELAYS AN EXECUTION FOR THE 1ST TIME IN 5 YEARS
</HEADLINE>
  By FRANK BRUNI with RICHARD A. OPPEL Jr.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO, Calif. _ In a step he had never taken over the
course of 131 executions in five years, Gov. George W. Bush
Thursday night agreed to a 30-day reprieve for a death-row inmate
in Texas, citing concerns that adequate tests on DNA evidence in
the case had not been performed.
</P>
<P>
   Bush made his decision, which he had telegraphed well in
advance, after both the 5th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals, and the
U.S. Supreme Court late Thursday rejected final-hour pleas by
lawyers for the inmate, Ricky Nolen McGinn, who had been scheduled
for execution by lethal injection at 6 p.m. Central time.
</P>
<P>
   McGinn was convicted of raping and killing his 12-year-old
stepdaughter in 1993, but Bush acknowledged over recent days that
the DNA evidence connecting McGinn to the rape was inconclusive and
might be clarified by modern tests. It was the rape, layered on top
of the murder, that qualified McGinn for a death sentence.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who had just arrived at the state capitol building here
for a conference of governors, announced the stay only about 15
minutes before the originally scheduled time for McGinn's
execution. Bush noted that the actual reprieve would be granted by
Texas state Sen. Rodney Ellis, a Houston Democrat who was
technically acting as governor while Bush and the lieutenant
governor were both out of the state.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have recommended and Senator Ellis has accepted my
recommendation to grant a 30-day reprieve in the case of Mr.
McGinn,'' Bush told a group of reporters who huddled around him in
a corridor of the state capitol building here.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anytime DNA evidence can be used in its context and be
relevant as to the guilt or innocence of a person on death row, we
need to use it,'' Bush explained, in a straightforward, unemotional
voice. ``We're doing so in the state of Texas. I expect the courts
and all relevant parties to act expeditiously to review the
evidence and to finally determine his innocence or guilt as to the
charge of rape in the case of Ricky McGinn.''
</P>
<P>
   Because Bush is now the presumptive Republican nominee for
president, his actions as governor are under more intense scrutiny
_ none more so than his vigorous enforcement of the death penalty.
Texas easily leads the nation in executions.
</P>
<P>
   Although his Democratic opponent, Vice President Al Gore, also
supports capital punishment, some of his allies would like to use
the issue to cast doubt on Bush's efforts to portray himself as a
``compassionate conservative.''
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, Bush's unusual action in the case of McGinn
underscored the way in which modern DNA testing and technology have
begun to affect the debate over capital punishment by casting doubt
on convictions once considered solid and just.
</P>
<P>
   In recent months, even some staunch conservatives have begun to
acknowledge qualms about capital punishment, in light of a number
of death sentences that have been overturned recently after DNA
testing exonerated the inmates. How these developments will
ultimately affect public support for the death penalty, which has
been broad and strong and often independent of political party
affiliation, remains unclear.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's aides said that his action was not even remotely
influenced by politics and noted that he had made many tough and
unpopular decisions about the death penalty in the past, including
several since he declared his candidacy for the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   As governor, Bush's only independent authority is to grant a
30-day reprieve of an execution. He cannot pardon someone or
commute a death sentence without the prior recommendation of the
Texas Board of Pardons and Paroles and, under those circumstances,
has commuted only one death sentence over the last year, sparing
the life of Henry Lee Lucas, a confessed serial killer.
</P>
<P>
   In that case, as in this one, the argument against the death
penalty was not a sentimental but an evidentiary one, with
questions emerging about some of the testimony and material
marshaled to establish the defendants' guilt and seal the
particular conviction for which he received his death sentence.
</P>
<P>
   But this was the first time that Bush agreed to a reprieve for a
death-row inmate, and he did it against the wishes of the pardons
board, which had voted 11-7 not to stay McGinn's execution. For the
moment, Bush's action merely delays McGinn's execution, although
his lawyers hope that they can now perform new DNA tests that will
shed new doubt on McGinn's guilt.
</P>
<P>
   What Bush did Thursday, and the way in which he presaged it with
a series of remarks on Wednesday, suggested that he was at least
somewhat sensitive to his image as an especially fervent advocate
of capital punishment and pleased to happen upon a case that
allowed him to temper it.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, Bush had almost always waited for courts to
complete their reviews of death-row inmates' appeals before he
signaled his own intentions or thinking on the matter.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush broke from that pattern this time around, gladly
telling reporters on Wednesday that he was likely to grant McGinn a
30-day reprieve. At the time, the 5th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals
had yet to rule on the issue, and McGinn's lawyers had not turned
to the U.S. Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   Several Republican political strategists around the country said
that they doubted Bush was simply trying to soften his image by
showing a capacity for clemency. They noted that public support for
capital punishment still runs high and that Bush three years ago
declined to grant a reprieve in a much showier, more widely covered
case: that of a woman named Karla Faye Tucker.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think that this is political,'' said Mike Murphy, who
was the principal strategist for Sen. John McCain's presidential
campaign. But, Murphy added, ``The truth is that the explosion in
DNA technology has really changed the death penalty dynamic, and
perhaps he's taking that reality into account a little bit.''
</P>
<P>
   Karen P. Hughes, a spokesman for Bush, said Thursday afternoon
that McGinn's case was the first one Bush has faced as governor in
which the possibility of further DNA testing was so central to the
question of innocence or guilt.
</P>
<P>
   ``The DNA testing at the trial level was inconclusive and
there's an opportunity to get more information now from that test,
so he feels it's the right thing to do,'' Hughes said. ``These are
life and death decisions, and Governor Bush makes them based on
principle.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The fate of McGinn from this point on remains unclear, because
his lawyers are in waters largely uncharted in Texas. They must
obtain the evidence they want tested, including clothing from the
victim that contained a semen stain and a pubic hair found on the
victim's body, and then analyze the DNA. But they said Thursday
that they are not certain whether they have just 30 days to
complete this, or whether the case now returns to a state district
judge to set a new execution date, which would give the defense
team at least 60 days.
</P>
<P>
   If DNA tests show that the hair and semen were not from McGinn,
``obviously he's not guilty of rape and he can't be executed,''
said Barry Scheck, a DNA expert who joined McGinn's defense team
last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the other hand,'' Scheck said, ``the DNA testing might link
him to other crimes. These are all things to find out.''
</P>
<P>
   But no matter how the tests turn out, prosecutors say they
expect the murder conviction to stand because of other evidence
that tied McGinn to the girl's killing.
</P>
<P>
   In Texas, murder is punishable by death only if the killing
occurred under certain specified circumstances, including the
murder of a police officer or fireman in the line of duty;
committing murder during a kidnapping, burglary, robbery, rape,
arson, or prison escape; murdering for money, or paying someone
else to do so; and murdering a child under the age of six.
</P>
<P>
   In this case, the death penalty threshold was achieved when the
jury found McGinn had also raped his stepdaughter.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
