<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 21:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2322 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-ELIAN-RULING0602-COX     06-01 1305
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELIAN-RULING0602-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Court rejects hearing for Elian
 &HT;    By Rhonda Cook
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Elian Gonzalez will remain in this country for at
least three more weeks while attorneys for his Miami relatives
decide whether they want to continue the international custody
struggle in an Atlanta federal appeals court or the U.S. Supreme
Court.
</P>
<P>
   The Cuban-American relatives lost another round Thursday, when
the 11th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals ruled here that the
Immigration and Naturalization Service was within its legal rights
to deny Elian an asylum hearing.
</P>
<P>
   The 6-year-old shipwreck survivor's great-uncle had filed the
hearing petition against the wishes of the boy's father, his sole
surviving parent.
</P>
<P>
   Within minutes of the ruling, attorneys for Elian's Miami
relatives asked the Supreme Court for an emergency temporary
injunction ``to assure that Elian will remain in the United
States'' while they prepare a petition asking the court for a
hearing. But they withdrew the request late Thursday afternoon when
they realized Elian's father, Juan Miguel Gonzalez, cannot take the
boy back to Cuba for at least 21 days.
</P>
<P>
   The Miami relatives have two weeks to file an appeal and then
another week before the appellate court's ruling will be finalized,
U.S. Attorney General Janet Reno said. Kendall Coffey, attorney for
the Miami family, said he hadn't decided on a course of action, but
Elian's relatives vowed not to give up.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going to keep fighting for Elian's freedom,'' said the
boy's great-uncle, Lazaro Gonzalez, with whom Elian lived for five
months after being rescued off the Florida coast.
</P>
<P>
   The youngster's mother and 10 others drowned when their boat
capsized after they fled Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   Juan Miguel Gonzalez, who has had his son with him in the
Washington, D.C., area since federal agents forcibly reunited them
in late April, pleaded with the Miami family to stop the legal
fight so he can take his family back to Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's what I have always felt most profoundly in my heart _ a
child simply should always be with his father,'' Gonzalez said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish this would end once and for all _ to be able to leave,
return to my home with my son and my entire family and that this
delay will not continue unnecessarily,'' he said through an
interpreter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Make no mistake about what happened today,'' said the father's
lawyer, Gregory Craig. ``This case has been decided, and in our
view there is no longer any doubt about the ultimate outcome.''
</P>
<P>
   The court decided that because no federal law addresses whether
a child as young as Elian can seek asylum against the wishes of his
parents, the Immigration and Naturalization Service was required to
devise a policy dealing with the case's ``extraordinary
circumstances.''
</P>
<P>
   The judges acknowledged Cuba violates human rights, but said the
INS, not the courts, should determine immigration policy.
</P>
<P>
   The court denied a request by Elian's father to replace Lazaro
Gonzalez as the boy's representative in the court proceedings, a
move that would have allowed Juan Miguel Gonzalez to drop the
asylum request and take his son back to Cuba immediately.
</P>
<P>
   The 11th Circuit appeals court was the third court to reject the
Miami relatives' legal arguments. A three-judge panel on the court
unanimously affirmed a ruling by a federal judge in Miami, who had
concluded that federal immigration officials acted within their
broad legal powers when they decided that only Elian's father could
speak for him on the issue of asylum. A family court judge in Miami
also dismissed a custody petition filed by Elian's great-uncle.
</P>
<P>
   Elian, who was rescued on Thanksgiving Day while clinging to an
inner tube off the coast of Fort Lauderdale, lived with his Miami
relatives until federal agents removed him in a predawn raid April
22. He was whisked that morning to Washington, where his father,
stepmother and baby brother had been waiting for two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The custody battle took on international ramifications when
Cuban President Fidel Castro demanded Elian's return and marshaled
support from tens of thousands of angry Cubans. In Miami,
Cuban-Americans were equally adamant that Elian not be returned to
the Communist nation.
</P>
<P>
   Lazaro Gonzalez filed the asylum petition, arguing Elian would
become traumatized if returned to Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   But on Thursday, the 11th Circuit panel of judges _ J.L.
Edmondson of Atlanta, Joel Dubina of Montgomery, Ala., and Charles
Wilson of Tampa _ ruled the INS acted legally in refusing an asylum
hearing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The INS's considerable discretion was not abused,'' Edmondson
wrote for the panel.
</P>
<P>
   The 33-page ruling did not focus on custody matters, but on the
narrower question of ``the separation of powers under our
constitutional system of government.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It is the duty of the Congress and the executive branch to
exercise political will,'' the ruling said. ``Although courts
should not be unquestioning, we should respect the other branch's
policymaking powers. The judicial power is a limited power. It is
the duty of the judicial branch not to exercise political will, but
only to render judicial judgment under the law.''
</P>
<P>
   Elian's Miami relatives have three options within the next two
weeks: Ask the three-judge panel to reconsider, request a hearing
before all 12 judges on the appeals court or turn to the U.S.
Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   Experts say it's unlikely the Supreme Court would give them the
solution they want.
</P>
<P>
   ``My gut instinct is it's unlikely there will be a stay or a
(hearing) in this case,'' said University of Georgia law professor
Dan Coenen, who was a clerk for the late Justice Harry Blackmun in
1979 and 1980. ``These are highly discretionary matters and my gut
instinct may be wrong but my instinct is this is not likely to (be
heard by the Supreme Court).''
</P>
<P>
   Randy Beck, who was a law clerk for Justice Anthony M. Kennedy
in 1990 and now teaches constitutional law at the University of
Georgia, said he doubted the Supreme Court would take the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``They often say their job is not to correct errors in
individual cases,'' Beck said.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General Reno hailed the appeals court's decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very important step in achieving the goal we have
sought from the very beginning _ to give Juan Miguel and his family
the opportunity to return to a life together,'' Reno said. ``I am
hopeful that this matter will soon reach a final resolution so that
Elian, his father and the family may resume their lives away from
the scrutiny of the media and the uncertainty that the legal battle
has caused for his entire family.'' In Miami the ruling was met
with screams and cries of disappointment from protesters outside
the Little Havana home where Elian had lived.
</P>
<P>
   Sandra Linar, a 40-year-old homemaker, held a sign with a photo
of Elian and his mother. ``It is not over yet,'' Linar said. ``God
is with us.''
</P>
<P>
   But unlike the civil unrest that followed the April 22 raid,
Miami's streets were quiet Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is very hard and difficult, but at least if people see this
was a legal process, it makes it somewhat different than April
22,'' Miami Mayor Joe Carollo said from City Hall. ``Everything's
quiet. I want to make sure the city remains peaceful.''
</P>
<P>
   The relatives held out some hope that Elian's father still would
be stopped from taking him back to Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope the laws of this country favor him and give him the
opportunity to seek asylum,'' said Marisleysis Gonzalez, Elian's
cousin, who has described herself as a surrogate mother.
</P>
<P>
   She said she hopes the courts will force Elian's father to allow
her family to visit the boy, whom they have not seen since the
April 22 raid.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
