<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-MIDEAST-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON SAYS MIDEAST PEACE AGREEMENT `WITHIN VIEW NOW' 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CRAGG HINES 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LISBON, Portugal _ President Clinton, diving back personally
into the Middle East peace negotiations, expressed confidence
Thursday that Israeli and Palestinian leaders can reach a final
agreement by their September deadline.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is tough work,'' Clinton said after a 90-minute meeting
here with Prime Minister Ehud Barak of Israel. ``But, actually, it
is within view now.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said he remained ``convinced'' that Barak and
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat ``have the courage, the vision and
the ability to do this, and the United States will do everything we
can to help them pass this milestone.''
</P>
<P>
   The White House again held out the prospect of a Middle East
summit in the United States when the two sides were closer to a
comprehensive settlement, if such a meeting could help get them
reach a final agreement.
</P>
<P>
   The stir in the peace process was occasioned by Israel's
withdrawal from Lebanon, but a senior administration official
cautioned that ``moments don't last forever.''
</P>
<P>
   Barak complained to Clinton and to reporters that Arafat has
been stalling the talks. ``In recent weeks, we have seen some
dragging of feet in regard to the running of negotiations,'' he
said. But Arafat charged that the delays were the fault of the
Israelis
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said he would meet soon with Arafat in Washington. That
session is probably at least a week away. Clinton arrives home from
his European journey late Monday and leaves Tuesday for a quick
trip to Japan for a memorial service for the late Prime Minister
Keizo Obuchi.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton announced that Secretary of State Madeleine Albright
will travel to the Middle East next week ``to work with Barak and
Arafat ``on narrowing the gaps that still remain between them.''
</P>
<P>
   A senior administration official said Albright is likely to make
at least one more trip to the region before a U.S.-sponsored summit
was seriously considered. Such a session would likely be styled
after the Camp David sessions in the late 1970s that resulted in
the breakthrough peace deal between Israel and Egypt.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and the official left little doubt that they believe a
Middle East endgame is again at hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are dealing with the most fateful issues there are between
Israelis and Palestinians,'' the U.S. official said. ``The issues
of permanent status, borders, settlements, refugees, Jerusalem,
security agreements. All of these issues go to the heart of
identity, existence and security, and these are very tough
negotiations, to be sure, given how profound the issues are.''
</P>
<P>
   The official refused to offer details on any of the negotiating
points, including reports that Israel was prepared to consider
handing over up to 90 percent of the West Bank to Arafat's
Palestinians, up from the earlier 60 percent thought to be on the
table.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would say that both sides have signaled to each other and to
us that they're prepared to try to take into account the needs of
the other, as well as meeting their own needs,'' the senior
official said. ``If you're going to reach a deal, you're going to
have to make some painful decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said Barak ``reaffirmed his intense commitment'' to
reach a complete agreement with the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   Barak and Clinton met for about 90 minutes in the president's
hotel in the Portuguese capital before Clinton flew on to Berlin on
the second leg of his week-long European trip.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, who spoke by telephone with Arafat on Wednesday after
announcing the Barak session, said the Palestinian leader ``shares
this commitment and ... recognizes the real urgency of this moment
to actually get back on the timetable and complete the work that
has to be done.''
</P>
<P>
   Barak and Arafat have set a deadline of Sept. 13 for having a
final agreement, although negotiations in much of the last six
months have been slow-going. Nonetheless, the president believes
the deadline can be met, the senior official said.
</P>
<P>
   White House officials conceded that any progress in the
Israeli-Palestinian negotiations is not matched on the separate
Israeli-Syrian track.
</P>
<P>
   But aides traveling in Europe with Clinton refused to rule out
anything, in light of Israel's withdrawal of its military units
from Lebanon after 18 years of occupation.
</P>
<P>
   ``No matter how you slice it, in the Middle East there is a new
reality,'' said a senior administration official, who spoke on
condition of anonymity. ``Israel is out of Lebanon.'' The act not
only fulfills the demands of a U.N. resolution but also ``shows
that something like this, which many thought couldn't happen, can
happen.''
</P>
<P>
   The official confirmed that the United States had approved use
of $50 million in funding to allow Israel to shore up its northern
border with Lebanon, a historic flash point in the region. The
approval comes with an allowance for Israel to use domestic
contractors rather than the usual process of employing U.S. firms.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
