<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 21:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2329 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-TEACHER-SHOOT0602-COX     06-01 0864
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEACHER-SHOOT0602-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Father believes shooting was accidental
 &HT;    By Scott McCabe
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAKE WORTH, Fla. _ Police are backing away from charging a
75-year-old man with failing to properly lock up the pistol they
say Nathaniel Brazill used to kill his popular seventh-grade
teacher last week.
</P>
<P>
   Lake Worth police had said Tuesday they planned to ask
prosecutors to charge Elmore ``Granny'' McCray, the father of the
godmother of the 13-year-old Brazill, with the misdemeanor of
failing to safely store a firearm.
</P>
<P>
   But rather than recommend charges, investigators Thursday simply
asked the State Attorney's Office to review their findings.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's out of our hands,'' Lake Worth police Detective Lt. Paul
Patti said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile Thursday, Brazill's father, Nathaniel Brazill Sr. of
Orlando, said on ``Good Morning America,'' that he believes his son
accidentally shot and killed Lake Worth Middle School teacher Barry
Grunow with the gun.
</P>
<P>
   ``To us, we just don't believe that Nate pulled the trigger. The
gun came out and accidentally went off,'' the father said.
</P>
<P>
   But police Lt. Raychel Houston said Thursday that Brazill
``racked a round'' into the semi-automatic gun's chamber while he
was talking to Grunow and before he fired the gun.
</P>
<P>
   ``They wouldn't have charged him with first-degree homicide if
they thought it was an accident,'' she said of the department's
request for that charge to the state attorney's office. She said
they made the decision based on a security-camera tape of the
shooting, witnesses' statements and the rounds from the gun _ one
live and one spent _ found near Grunow's body.
</P>
<P>
   State Attorney spokesman Mike Edmondson declined comment
Thursday about McCray's case.
</P>
<P>
   Any criminal charge against McCray hinges on proving the gun was
loaded at the time Brazill took it.
</P>
<P>
   Brazill told police he loaded the .25-caliber Raven pistol
himself after finding it in a tin box in a dresser drawer at
McCray's home. Brazill found bullets in the dresser drawer as well,
Houston said. McCray also told police the gun was not loaded.
</P>
<P>
   The misdemeanor law also says a gun owner must keep the weapon
secure if he or she ``knows or reasonably should know that a minor
is likely to gain access to the firearm.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the week, police thought Brazill regularly stayed
with McCray and that McCray should have known Brazill might find
it. But they recently learned Brazill didn't often stay there,
although he did stay there just two days before the shooting. His
mother, Polly Powell, said Thursday that Brazill returned to her
home May 24 after staying there about five days while she was in
South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   Lake Worth police also said Thursday they have obtained three
warrants in the last two days, including one to search Brazill's
home again. The second search is not because of any new
developments but just to make sure they didn't miss anything,
Houston said. On Sunday, Brazill's mother, had allowed police to
take Brazill's computer and reams of web page printouts, many that
dealt with military weaponry, helicopters and handwritten notes.
</P>
<P>
   With the second of the three warrants, the FBI Thursday began
examining data from Brazill's Gateway computer and CD-ROM games.
The third was to obtain records from Brazill's Internet service
provider.
</P>
<P>
   Police found war games, but none, so far, of the gruesome,
first-person based video games like ``Doom'' and ``Quake,'' Patti
said.
</P>
<P>
   State Attorney Barry Krischer has moved to seal the warrants and
information about any items seized by police.
</P>
<P>
   Law enforcement officials are still working overtime to present
a murder case against Brazill to the grand jury by June 15. Grunow
was killed Friday at Lake Worth Middle School.
</P>
<P>
   Krischer has said he hopes to convince the grand jury to charge
Brazill as an adult. The county's state attorney said on
``Nightline'' Wednesday night that if Brazill was tried as a
juvenile he could only serve 18 to 36 months in a lockdown
facility, and would probably get out early because he is an honor
student. ``So within two years he'd be home, out on the street,
merely under the supervision of the Department of Juvenile Justice.
And that is not justice for the family of Barry Grunow,'' Krischer
said.
</P>
<P>
   Jason Ziedenberg, senior policy analyst for the Justice Policy
Institution in Washington D.C., which advocates alternatives to
imprisoning juveniles, said Krischer is wrong. He said that under
Florida law a juvenile judge can keep a child in custody until 21.
On his tour through South Florida Thursday, Gov. Jeb Bush said he
offered condolences to Barry Grunow's wife, Pam, earlier in the
week and has written a $100 personal check to the fund set up for
the family.
</P>
<P>
   But he said he remains opposed to mandatory trigger locks.
``People who are concerned about gun safety are going to put gun
locks on their guns.''
</P>
<P>
   He also said that despite the shooting, ``schools are safer
today they they were 2 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure you legislate against tragic events like this.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
