u i BC-LEBANON-REFUGEES-BOS &LR;      06-01 1351
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEBANON-REFUGEES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOPES RISE FOR PALESTINIANS CAUGHT IN BORDER LIMBO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES M. SENNOTT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DOHEIRA, Lebanon _ At the fence that marks the border with
Israel, two Palestinian sisters reached hands leathered by age
through coils of barbed wire and across decades of war and exile to
touch each other for the first time in 52 years.
</P>
<P>
   One sister was among thousands of Palestinian refugees in
Lebanon who crowded the border this week to see the land and the
families she left behind after Israel's triumph in the 1948 war.
Until Israel abruptly withdrew its troops and ended its occupation
in south Lebanon 10 days ago, the sisters had been unable to get
even this close for two decades.
</P>
<P>
   By the United Nations' count, there are 360,000 Palestinians in
Lebanon, and most still live in the squalor of refugee camps. For
more than a half century, they have been caught between Lebanon,
which does not want them, and Israel, which refuses to allow their
return.
</P>
<P>
   With the dramatic Israeli pullback from south Lebanon, hope for
Palestinian refugees to return to their ancestral homeland has been
rekindled. But so have fears that Palestinian frustrations will
reignite in the refugee camps and result in the kind of
Syrian-backed, cross-border attacks that first prompted the Jewish
state to invade Lebanon in 1978.
</P>
<P>
   Up a steep cliff along the border fence, Miriam Mousa, 65, stood
on a narrow gravel strip Tuesday and came agonizingly close to her
sister, Dania, and other family members torn from her after she
fled her Palestinian village at the age of 13 during the 1948 war.
She ended up in Lebanon, but the rest of her family remained in the
former Palestine, most of which became the state of Israel.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was alone here for all this time. All my family was in
Palestine. Look. Look at them. This is my sister, this is my
brother,'' she said, wiping away tears. ``My God, I have been
praying to see them for so long.''
</P>
<P>
   She was among roughly 100 Palestinian refugees standing on the
Lebanon side of the fence while her family and about 100 other
Palestinians who live in what is now Israel gathered on the Israeli
side. All were shouting and some wept as they tried to find
relatives and friends separated during the war.
</P>
<P>
   The men shook hands and the women embraced through the
barbed-wire fence. Israeli soldiers eventually began separating
them, uncoiling a new roll of barbed wire to secure the border. But
the families continued shouting messages even as they were pushed
back from the fence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am Itaf, the daughter of Rigan,'' an elderly woman yelled
from the Israeli side. ``Who are you? Do you know me?''
</P>
<P>
   Immediately, there came a scream from the other side. It was a
cousin whom she had not seen since they were children.
</P>
<P>
   ``How did this happen to us?'' the elderly woman cried out.
</P>
<P>
   She turned away, crying and repeating the phrase: ``How did this
happen to us?''
</P>
<P>
   Israel's 22 years of occupation in south Lebanon kept the pair
from reuniting at the border. And for the 30 years before that,
Lebanon's restrictions on Palestinian refugees kept most
Palestinians from being able to travel to the fence.
</P>
<P>
   Now with the border area open to them, the older Palestinians
stand heartbreakingly close to the land where they were born. And
for the younger generation, it is a first chance to see the land of
family lore.
</P>
<P>
   The mix of anger and yearning is powerfully felt in Ain el
Hilwe, the largest of 12 Palestinian refugee camps in Lebanon. The
refugees in the teeming UN camp direct their anger not only at
Israel, but also at Palestinian President Yasser Arafat, who they
say has not applied enough pressure on the issue of ``right of
return'' for refugees in the final phase of a six-year peace
process.
</P>
<P>
   There are an estimated 3.5 million Palestinians registered as
refugees by the UN Relief and Works Agency. Most live along
Israel's borders in Lebanon, Syria, Jordan, and in the West Bank
and Gaza Strip. One-third, or about 1.2 million, still live in a
string of 59 ramshackle refugee camps in the region.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our own leaders have forgotten us,'' said Abed Makdah, 56, who
said he was 4 years old when his family fled the village of El
Ghabbisiya near the coastal town of Akko and came to Lebanon, where
he lives in Ain el Hilwe.
</P>
<P>
   Makdah, secretary general of the camp's Popular Committee, a
form of self-rule, adds, ``They speak only of the refugees' right
of return in words, not deeds. Where do they think we are supposed
to go at the end of the peace process? Do they think we can just
disappear?''
</P>
<P>
   The heavily armed Palestinian factions in the refugee camps see
the Shiite Muslim militia's guerrilla war against Israeli
occupation as proof that military resistance is the only way to
achieve their goals. At a massive rally celebrating Israel's
pullout, Hassan Nasrallah, leader of the Islamic Hezbollah
organization that fought the guerrilla war against Israeli troops,
encouraged the Palestinians to model fighting units on Hezbollah.
</P>
<P>
   Such calls to arms by dozens of factions and splinter groups in
camps like Ain el Hilwe deeply trouble analysts here, who fear that
neighboring Syria, with 30,000 troops stationed in Lebanon, could
help arm the guerrillas in order to put pressure on Israel to
return the Golan Heights. Israel's negotiations with Syria broke
down six months ago, and Israel's proposals to withdraw from Golan,
which it captured from Syria in 1967, are considered to have been
shelved for the forseeable future.
</P>
<P>
   Rearming the Palestinian militias is also a scenario that
troubles the Lebanese, many of whom believe that the Palestinian
fighters dragged their country into a 15-year civil war that killed
70,000 people by the time it ended in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Palestinians have no civil rights in Lebanon. They live in the
camps, where unemployment soars up to 70 percent. Young people,
some of whom are fourth-generation refugees, know nothing but
despair and dislocation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lebanon cannot keep the refugees for a set of reasons that are
both political and economic,'' said Simon Karam, Lebanon's
ambassador to Washington in the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   ``Politically, keeping the refugees is impossible because
naturalizing them would do great harm to the demographic balance of
Muslims and Christians in Lebanon,'' he said. ``And economically,
it can't afford to shut down these refugee camps. Where would these
people be housed, where would they work? It is an untenable
situation.''
</P>
<P>
   At the entrance to the teeming city of about 65,000 refugees who
live in the Ain el Heliwe refugee camp, a Palestinian teenager with
a machine gun was waiting to take a reporter to the ``colonel,'' a
longtime Palestinian resistance fighter named Mounir Moqdah.
</P>
<P>
   Deep in the maze of litter-strewn alleys of the camp, the young
man ducked into a small metal door that led to a courtyard where
Moqdah, a fugitive from Lebanese and Israeli intelligence agencies,
has his headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   The bearded, 40-year-old, self-proclaimed ``colonel'' of Fatah,
the largest political faction within the Palestine Liberation
Organization, was dressed in a camouflage uniform and leather
sandals, lounging on a couch. A rocket-propelled antitank grenade
launcher rested against a wall mural of the Jerusalem skyline and
the Muslim shrine of the Dome of the Rock mosque.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Israelis only understand force,'' he said, blowing smoke
from a Rothman cigarette. ``We will have to force them to comply
with UN Resolution 194, just as they were forced to comply with
425.''
</P>
<P>
   UN Resolution 194 granted the right of return and compensation
to Palestinian refugees who fled or were forced to flee during the
1948 war. UN Resolution 425, passed in 1978, demanded that the
Israeli military completely withdraw from Lebanon. The UN is
expected this week to make its determination that Israel has
complied with the resolution.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hezbollah's victory has shown us that these long, drawn-out
negotiations are not what works,'' Moqdah said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
