<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 22:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2333 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BOX-HOLYFIELD0602-1ST     06-01 0535
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-HOLYFIELD0602-1STLEDE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDS: This version omits sentence in next to last graf on Ruiz
turning down a bout with Lewis.
 &HT;    Holyfield's plans put on hold
 &HT;    By Mike Tierney
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The injured Evander Holyfield likely must wait at
least two months before facing John Ruiz, a two-month delay in his
grand plan to regather the three major heavyweight titles.
</P>
<P>
   Their June 10 date was postponed because of Holyfield's torn
muscle below the ribs on his left side, and promoter Don King said
Thursday in Las Vegas that the makeup would be rescheduled in
August.
</P>
<P>
   Caesar's Palace remains the probable site, King added. The
Showtime cable network will carry the bout for the vacant WBA
crown.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Christopher Vaughns, Holyfield's physician in Atlanta, and
Dr. Flip Homansky, ringside physician for the Nevada State Athletic
Commission, estimated that Holyfield would require about four weeks
to heal. He would then need a few more weeks to train, though he
can continue aerobic work.
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield said he was hurt in a sparring session on May 21 on a
blow to the small of his back on the right side. The left side
began to tense up later.
</P>
<P>
   He visited a doctor in Houston, where he trains, three times
within five days, then phoned his attorney in Atlanta, Jim Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each time he sparred, it got a little worse,'' Thomas said. He
returned to Atlanta on Wednesday for an MRI, which revealed the
torn muscle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's a serious injury,'' Homansky said, ``but
it's incapacitating when he throws a punch. He can take a punch.''
</P>
<P>
   As Holyfield put it, ``It only hurts if I hit the opponent. I
hurt myself to hit him.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas insisted the injury is unrelated to Holyfield's advanced
boxing age (37) and lengthy fight resume (41, including four losses
and a draw).
</P>
<P>
   ``Absolutely not,'' Thomas said. ``It's a simple athletic
injury. It has nothing to do with age or deterioration. This could
happen to an 18-year-old.''
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield has never before pulled out of a fight, though Thomas
says he twice regrets not doing so.
</P>
<P>
   He entered the ring with Michael Moorer in 1994 with a sore
shoulder. ``And it cost him,'' Thomas said, recalling the loss by
decision. ``The shoulder pretty much tore out in the second
round.''
</P>
<P>
   The next year, in a rubber match with Riddick Bowe, Holyfield
took ill leading up to fight night and absorbed a technical
knockout in the eighth round.
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield also mentioned that he was sick last year against in
his first meeting with Lennox Lewis, which was controversially
scored a draw. ``He kept those (ailments) to himself,'' Thomas
said. ``He wants to be 100 percent for this fight. ``
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield said, ``I'm cheating myself by not going in at 100
percent. Two or three times before, I should have said I'm not
going out there. I'm a lot smarter than I was then.''
</P>
<P>
   Norman Stone, Ruiz's trainer/manager, described his fighter as
devastated by the development. And he noted that Ruiz has recovered
from hand surgery a month ago, caused by a broken cereal bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's ready to go,'' Stone said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
