<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 22:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2347 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-MEXICO-POLITICS-ART-N     06-01 1224
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-POLITICS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEXICO'S DOT-COM GENERATION IS VOTING FOR CHANGE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By SAM DILLON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   QUERETARO, Mexico _ The presidential campaign has opened a vast
demographic divide between the old and new Mexicos, a political
fault line that runs smack through the Martinez household, tucked
along a tidy suburban street in central Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Eduardo Martinez is a 29-year-old accountant. His wife, Karina,
once worked at a Ford dealership, but now does aerobics at a gym
and tends their children. Mention the party that has run Mexico
since the 1920s and they respond with contemptuous talk about its
legacy of graft and fraud. Like most young urban Mexicans, they
intend to vote for Vicente Fox, the first opposition candidate with
a shot at victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``The country needs a change and Fox can bring it,'' Martinez
said, strapping her two toddlers into car seats for a shopping
trip.
</P>
<P>
   But their maid, Lucia Hernandez, a gray-haired woman of 53 who
commutes from her tin-roofed home outside this state capital, still
praises the governing party, known as the PRI, for building a
school in her rural village 20 years ago. Like millions of older,
semiliterate, rural voters, she plans to vote for its candidate,
Francisco Labastida.
</P>
<P>
   The Martinezes and their maid reflect the dramatic voter
polarization recorded all across Mexico in polls before the
country's presidential election on July 2. Although the leading
candidates appear virtually tied, they draw their support from
radically contrasting constituencies. The traditional Mexico of
aging peasants, hardscrabble farms and corn subsidies supports
Labastida. The new Mexico, where millions of young college
graduates are modernizing an economy already bubbling with scores
of new dot-com startups, backs Fox.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is quite a political cleavage,'' said Alejandro Moreno,
the chief pollster at the Mexico City newspaper Reforma. ``In no
previous election have we seen such sharp differences between
voters supporting the PRI and younger voters looking for change.''
</P>
<P>
   A nationwide survey conducted for the Reuters news agency by
Zogby International in early May found the same split that Moreno
has measured in several Reforma soundings.
</P>
<P>
   Older, semiliterate voters in farm areas were supporting
Labastida. ``But less than a third of Mexicans under 29 years old
said the PRI deserves to be elected again,'' said Andrew Hurst,
Reuters' Mexico bureau chief.
</P>
<P>
   The country's divided electorate has grown by 12 million voters
since 1994, when Ernesto Zedillo won election comfortably as the
country's 13th consecutive PRI president. The trends make it all
but certain the party will eventually lose the presidency, since
the rural vote that for decades has provided its bedrock support is
disappearing as farmlands give way to industrial parks all across
this nation of 100 million people.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, 30 percent of Mexico's election precincts were
classified as rural. Today, only 20 percent of the precincts, home
to 12 million of Mexico's 59 million registered voters, are rural.
Ten percent of the voters live in ``mixed'' precincts, part rural,
part urban, said Eduardo Badillo, the federal official who directed
the three-year effort to compile the voter list for this year's
balloting. In contrast, Mexico's youth vote has become dominant,
with half the electorate under 35 years old, he said in an
interview.
</P>
<P>
   Karina de Martinez, 26, is one of an estimated six million young
Mexicans expected to vote this year for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never saw any reason to vote before, because I knew the PRI
would win and it'd just be more of the same,'' she said. Her
husband, who manages a federal toll highway running through
Queretaro, says he does not like Fox's brash style, but will vote
for him anyway to bring change. ``Being in the government, you see
all the corruption that exists,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   One day in early May, Lucia Hernandez, the maid, paused as she
loaded clothes into the washing machine to ask Martinez whom she
planned to vote for.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said Fox,'' Martinez said. ``Lucia said she was going to
vote for Labastida. And to tell you the truth, it made me angry!
This is why the PRI could still win, because of people like our
maid. I asked myself, `How can that be?'''
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez, who has 14 children, lives in Chichimiquillas, a
gritty village where the business district consists of a tiny store
stocked with crackers and Coca-Cola, a tire repair shop and a
sherbet stand. To arrive at the Martinez home, she rides a bus for
an hour through bone-dry hills.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody votes for the PRI there,'' she said in a
conversation with a visitor in the Martinez living room, even
though many of her neighbors lost their life savings in Mexico's
1994 peso devaluation. Hundreds of straw-hatted villagers flocked
to a recent rally in the Chichimiquillas square, she said, at which
PRI officials alternately praised Labastida as a patriot and
raffled off refrigerators and washing machines.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't win anything,'' she said wistfully of the rally.
``Still, we have a lot of confidence in the PRI. Whenever I've
needed a hand they've always helped me. Why not say so?''
</P>
<P>
   A searing incident a decade ago appears to have sealed her PRI
loyalties forever. Hernandez took a neighbor's young daughter,
suffering from dysentery, on a bus to a county hospital, she said.
The child died in the hospital, and her parents did not have enough
money to pay for a coffin and retrieve her body. Hat in hand,
Hernandez went to the local PRI political boss to ask for help. He
gave her $50 to pay for a funeral, she recalled.
</P>
<P>
   ``When somebody helps me like that, I don't forget it,''
Hernandez said.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, the PRI often seems forgotten in this state
capital, even though until just three years ago the state had never
had an opposition governor. Today both the state governor and the
mayor of the state capital are from Fox's center-right National
Action Party. The city's prosperous economy is based on dozens of
factories that turn out everything from tractors to cornflakes. As
in many Mexican cities, National Action has grown so rapidly in
Queretaro that Labastida advisers say his campaign has virtually
written it off as a lost cause.
</P>
<P>
   One young voter who helped vote National Action into power in
Queretaro is Rodrigo Marvan Cuevas, 26, who is just embarking on an
architectural career. His father, a well-known architect, has built
office buildings for PRI governments for several decades, but
Rodrigo considers the party's long monopoly on politics an
embarrassing anachronism.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our political system is still in diapers!'' he mused during a
conversation at his studio in a leafy Queretaro neighborhood. ``How
can it be that only recently the vote in Mexico has begun to
count?'' Marvan intends to vote for Fox.
</P>
<P>
   ``No private business ever does well without competition, and
it's the same thing in politics,'' he said, adjusting the volume on
a recording by Duke Ellington as he talked.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have a single PRI friend,'' he said. ``In my
generation and at my educational and professional level, there just
are no PRI members.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
