<HEADER>
A2350 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-GORE-CANCER0602-COX     06-01 0635
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-CANCER0602-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gore pledges fight to the finish
 &HT;    By Diane Lore
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Vice President Al Gore vowed in Atlanta on Thursday to
lead the war on cancer, doubling federal funding for research
within the next five years. He also pledged to increase fivefold
the number of clinical trials for new treatments and set a goal of
eliminating deaths from colon, breast and prostate cancer within
the decade.
</P>
<P>
   ``I pledge this from my heart: If I am entrusted with the
presidency, I will work with you to put the same energy and
priority into fighting cancer that we would put into preventing a
war that could take 500,000 American lives every year,'' said Gore,
who brought his presidential campaign to Emory University's health
sciences campus and Children's Healthcare of Atlanta at Egleston.
</P>
<P>
   Likening the effort to John F. Kennedy's mission to put an
American on the moon, Gore said wiping out cancer is a
``reasonable'' and ``attainable'' goal, similar to eradicating
smallpox from the world and polio from the United States.
</P>
<P>
   He said the timing was right for such a venture since America
recently has seen historic drops in the incidence of cancer and in
death rates, as well as the creation of new therapies to fight the
disease. Gore's cancer-fighting initiatives would build upon
efforts by President Clinton, who has pushed since 1998 for an
increase in spending on cancer research _ with a goal of a 65
percent increase within five years.
</P>
<P>
   Gore outlined a plan to combat cancer that would include:
</P>
<P>
   Revising Medicare so that elderly people can get cancer
screenings, such as mammograms and colorectal screenings, without
having to pay deductibles or co-payments.
</P>
<P>
   Urging employers to let workers get cancer screenings on paid
time, similar to a program started by Boston's city government.
</P>
<P>
   Developing uniform ``best practice standards'' for physicians.
Such standards would help more patients benefit from advancements
in detection, diagnosis and treatment of cancer. Now, Gore said,
standards of care vary widely.
</P>
<P>
   Gore said he would mandate that private insurers routinely cover
the medical bills of patients enrolled in clinical trials.
</P>
<P>
   And he wants to strengthen the fight against children's smoking,
through beefed-up advertising campaigns and tougher penalties
against companies that pander to kids.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's plan was a hit with the friendly crowd, who rewarded him
with two standing ovations and cheers at several points. The plan
also drew support from former President Carter.
</P>
<P>
   ``My father, mother and all my siblings were addicted to
cigarettes, and all died with cancer,'' Carter said in a
</P>
<P>
   statement issued Thursday. ``This is why I applaud the
development of an aggressive and comprehensive cancer-fighting
agenda, as Al Gore has proposed.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore specified funding for three areas: $300 million toward the
creation of a university-based ``Centers for Excellence'' that
would work with the National Institutes of Health on cancer
research, $200 million for anti-smoking advertising and $25 million
for school-based nutrition programs.
</P>
<P>
   The American Cancer Society declined comment on the vice
president's proposals. The nonprofit organization has been working
with all candidates to develop such goals, said spokesman Roger
Salazar. Other groups, such as the National Breast Cancer
Coalition, reported they had not studied the plan in enough detail
to comment.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Johns, Emory Healthcare's chief executive officer, said
he believed Gore's plan ``was on target'' _ focusing on prevention
and patients' access to care. ``I think it's a wonderful thing for
someone to set bars and challenges,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
