<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 22:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2352 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BBN-BIGRED-MACHINE060     06-01 0822
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BIGRED-MACHINE0602-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A big red reunion
 &HT;    By Hal McCoy
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CINCINNATI _ Immediately after the 1976 Cincinnati Reds, a.k.a.,
The Big Red Machine, completed a four-game sweep of the New York
Yankees, club president/general manager Bob Howsam, the
construction engineer of The BRM, accepted the trophy and uttered
some prophetic words.
</P>
<P>
   ``Baseball fans everywhere better enjoy what they have just
seen, because it will never happen again,'' he said. ``Never again
will a baseball team without use of free agents dominate the
game.''
</P>
<P>
   He was right. Free agency changed the way teams built winners.
The legacy of Howsam and The BRM was that the team was a dominant
winner from 1970 to 1976, then faded into near-oblivion.
</P>
<P>
   The Big Red Machine re-surfaces Saturday at Cinergy Field as
part of a 1975 team reunion celebration, some with expanded
waist-lines, some with graying hair, but still young in spirit and
each stuffed with memories from better times.
</P>
<P>
   The Machine was built from within, either with players nurtured
and cultivated in the Reds system or through trades by using
players from the system.
</P>
<P>
   Nine home-grown players were featured: catcher Johnny Bench,
first baseman Tony Perez, shortstop Davey Concepcion, third baseman
Pete Rose, right fielder Ken Griffey Sr., starting pitchers Don
Gullett and Gary Nolan, relief pitchers Will McEnaney and Rawlins
Jackson Eastwick III.
</P>
<P>
   Five players were acquired through two trades: second baseman
Joe Morgan, left fielder George Foster, center fielder Cesar
Geronimo and starting pitchers Jack Billingham and Freddie Norman.
</P>
<P>
   Not one player was brought in through free agency because Howsam
refused to cave in to the hire-for-pay mercenary system that was
engulfing the game. The first Cincinnati free-agent signing was
outfielder Paul Blair in 1979, after Howsam was out of the game.
</P>
<P>
   The team's manager, George ``Sparky'' Anderson, has been elected
to the baseball Hall of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   Bench, Morgan and Perez are in the Hall of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   Rose would have been were it not for his gambling tendencies.
And Rose isn't part of Saturday night's re-union, banished from the
game and from being with his former teammates by commissioner Bud
Selig.
</P>
<P>
   Concepcion's numbers are better than five of the 10 shortstops
in Cooperstown, including Phil Rizzuto and PeeWee Reese.
</P>
<P>
   Gullett was on his way to Hall of Fame numbers when a shoulder
injury ended his career at age 27, after he had posted a 109-50
major-league record with 44 complete games and a 3.63 career earned
run average.
</P>
<P>
   Griffey finished with a .296 career average and is overlooked
because he wasn't a power hitter, accumulating only 152 home runs
in his 18-year career.
</P>
<P>
   Geronimo was one of the finest defensive players ever to roam
center field.
</P>
<P>
   In 1977, Foster hit 52 home runs, drove in 149 and had 388 total
bases, all still club records.
</P>
<P>
   The Big Red Machine players left some on-the-field legacies,
too.
</P>
<P>
   Bench invented the hinged catcher's mitt, enabling him to be the
first catcher to snag balls with one hand, like a first baseman,
and he was the first to wear a batting helmet when he caught.
</P>
<P>
   Concepcion discovered that throwing the ball to first base on
one hop on AstroTurf got the ball to first base quicker, a method
used by many shortstops to this day, including his successor in
Cincinnati, Barry Larkin.
</P>
<P>
   After winning seven straight post-season games in 1976, sweeping
three in the National League playoffs from the Philadelphia
Phillies when a best-of-five format was used, the Reds swept four
from the Yankees. Teams in the second half of the 20th century,
from 1950 on, were measured by the standards set by the Big Red
Machine and the BRM was compared favorably to the 1927 New York
Yankees, generally accepted as the best team of the 20th century.
</P>
<P>
   The pitching staff was not solid through and through and more
often than not, except when Gullett pitched, the Reds clubbed
opponents into submission, prompting Billingham to come up with
some very bad verse any time he pitched.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of how many runs he needed to win, Billingham said,
``Seven is heaven, eight we skate, nine is divine and 10 we'll
surely win.'' OK, so Henry Wadsworth Longfellow he wasn't, but he
was right.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson's legacy was a hands-off, let-em-play policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a guy who barely had a cup of coffee in the major
leagues, a guy who couldn't hit,'' Anderson said. ``What was I
going to tell Johnny Bench and Tony Perez and Joe Morgan and Pete
Rose. I'll never forget right after I took over the team, Bench
tapped me on the shoulder in the dugout one day, when I was
standing in front of him, and said, 'Sparky, let me give you some
advice. Just stay out of our way and we'll carry you to the top.'''
And he was right.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
