<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 22:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2354 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKN-PACERS-MULLIN-HNS     06-01 1057
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-PACERS-MULLIN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MURPHY  
 c. 2000, Houston Chronicle  
NEW YORK _ Deception is reality.
<TEXT>
<P>
   That, perhaps more than anything else, sums up the life and
times of Indiana Pacers guard Chris Mullin.
</P>
<P>
   That phrase describes not only Mullin's textbook-pure game but
his appearance as well, where he seems to have gone out of his way
to cultivate the central-casting version of the perfect Hoosier
native.
</P>
<P>
   With his crew-cut blond hair (so short his scalp shines on the
sides), his pale blue eyes and paler white skin, Mullin is such a
ringer for one of those Hoosier high school phenoms of the past
that you half-expect him to have one of those hyphenated names like
Jimmy-Dan or Bobby-Dean.
</P>
<P>
   That's the deception.
</P>
<P>
   Reality hits you the moment Mullin opens his mouth and the
Brooklynese starts spilling out. While not quite as over the top as
the ``yooze guyz'' of Goodfellas or The Sopranos, Mullin quite
obviously is New York City-born and -bred.
</P>
<P>
   And he's now back in the city _ his city _ as the Pacers prepare
for tonight's Game 6 of the Eastern Conference finals. But Mullin
has yet to play a single second against the Knicks, which has to
cut him deeply, especially with his family and friends sitting in
the stands and watching on TV.
</P>
<P>
   Even Indiana coach Larry Bird gives Mullin a wide berth,
especially when the Pacers are in the Big Apple.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't say much to Chris, because I know he's dying inside,''
Bird said. ``I don't like to see Chris sitting over there not
playing. It's killing him. It's got to be killing him.''
</P>
<P>
   Bird insists defensive matchups, putting the 36-year-old Mullin
up against the likes of Latrell Sprewell and Allan Houston, are why
Mullin isn't playing.
</P>
<P>
   But like his jumper, Mullin's attitude is pure textbook (just
look under the chapter, ``Boat; Not Rocking'').
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, while his voice may fill the room, his ego does not.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, (not playing against New York) doesn't bother me at all,''
said Mullin, perhaps pulling another deceptive maneuver. ``It seems
to tweak a lot of people besides me. I get asked a lot about it,
but it really doesn't bother me. I didn't play a lot this season,
so it's not like I was playing 30 minutes (a game) all season and
then when the playoffs came I stopped playing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Come playoff time, it's all about matchups. I think the one
thing is that I can be consistent with the things I can control. So
20 hours of the day are mine _ I can work out, feel good and have
good energy. Or I could be obsessing about the two hours that I
think they should have done for me.''
</P>
<P>
   The odd thing is that Mullin actually brought this upon himself.
</P>
<P>
   With the Pacers looking to revamp the lineup, Mullin approached
Bird about surrendering his starting role so sixth man Jalen Rose
could get more minutes and more looks in the offense.
</P>
<P>
   Things worked out well for Rose, who was named the NBA's Most
Improved Player. But Mullin saw his average of 23 minutes a game
last season plunge to just over 12 this year _ and that doesn't
count the 24 games Mullin sat out because Bird didn't play him.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he went to the coaches to kind of step down as a starter,
I don't think he envisioned this,'' said teammate Austin Croshere,
who considers Mullin a mentor. ``I haven't spoken to him about (not
playing vs. the Knicks), but I can only imagine that it's very
difficult for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's never said anything, and he's never complained about it,
but that's a tribute to the type of person he is. He wants to do
anything for the team, so he's not going to rock the boat. Anybody
on this team knows that if you put him in a 3-point contest you're
going to lose. Even if you want to play one-on-one or two-on-two
with him. There's a lot of game left in him.''
</P>
<P>
   Teammate and fellow New York native Mark Jackson, who also
played with Mullin at St. John's, couldn't agree more.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a scientist to the game of basketball,'' Jackson said.
``He hasn't changed a bit since the first time I met him in New
York. He's usually the first one in the gym and the last one out.
He's a worker and a great friend, an example of what type of role
model an NBA player should be.''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't too long ago, though, that Mullin was one of the top
stars in the league, on a par _ scoring-wise, anyway _ with the
likes of Michael Jordan, Dominique Wilkins, Karl Malone, Alex
English and Clyde Drexler.
</P>
<P>
   It was Mullin's penchant for deception _ the on-court kind _
that made him so effective. While he lacked quickness, Mullin
developed a quick first step and an even quicker release on his
lefty jumper. Between the 1988-89 and 1992-93 seasons, Mullin
averaged 27.8 points, scoring almost 10,000 points in that span.
</P>
<P>
   And while most basketball fans can easily tick off most of the
names from the original Dream Team _ Magic Johnson, Jordan, Patrick
Ewing, David Robinson, John Stockton, Malone and Bird (some can
even get Christian Laettner, the token college player) _ many seem
to forget about Mullin.
</P>
<P>
   But his Dream Team gold medal from the 1992 Olympics sits right
next to the one he won at the 1984 Olympics, another reminder of
the Chris Mullin that once was.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't forget about it,'' said Bird of Mullin's place in NBA
history. ``I know what he means to the game. It's just that right
now in this series it's not a good matchup. So far, anyway. But
Chris usually plays well against the Knicks, so you never know. He
might get in there.''
</P>
<P>
   Considering his resume, it would be easy for Mullin to be
bitter. But he continues to watch, not letting a single complaint
pass from his lips as the Pacers attempt to land the franchise's
first berth in the Finals.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not enjoyable not playing, but your job becomes something
else, which is to be a professional and be ready,'' Mullin said.
``It's been an adjustment. Three or four years ago, it would have
been hard to do this. But there are a lot more important things. My
friends and family have a lot harder time with it than I do.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't feel like anything is slipping away. I don't feel like
I have to prove myself. I'm every bit the player I was last year;
it's just not my time right now, but that doesn't mean somewhere
down the line it's not going to be, and I want to be ready.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
