<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELIAN-ATL0602-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Immigrants campaign for change, awareness
 &HT;    By Kelly Simmons
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Miriam Bley was 20 when she tried to leave Cuba for
the United States the first time in 1969.
</P>
<P>
   At the Havana airport, military security officers rifled through
her bags and patted down her clothing, she recalled Thursday. When
her mother handed her three pesos she had saved for the trip, Bley
panicked, afraid that the guards would suspect she was smuggling
money out of the country. She went into the bathroom and flushed it
down the toilet.
</P>
<P>
   When she came out, the guards were waiting for her. ``They told
me I had done something unforgivable, disrespectful,'' Bley said.
``They said I could face a trial or go to jail. Or I could not ever
be allowed to leave the country. When I heard the noise of the
airplane leaving, my heart was breaking.''
</P>
<P>
   It took a year _ and some influence from a high-level Cuban
immigration official, Bley said _ before she was allowed to leave.
</P>
<P>
   Those memories of the Communist regime in Cuba are what brought
Bley to the the Cuban Club in Doraville Thursday to decry the 11th
U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals ruling that immigration officials had
acted appropriately in denying the 6-year-old Elian Gonzalez an
asylum hearing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's preposterous to think that Elian would be able to live a
sane and humane life (in Cuba),'' said Rafael Andino. ``We're
extremely saddened and outraged by the decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Elian's Miami residents have two weeks to appeal the
decision, the Cuban-Americans gathered Thursday sensed that the
battle was nearly over.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know at this point that we can do much more than
pray,'' Frank Fernandez said.'' Pray for this boy, who will
essentially spend his life in slavery.''
</P>
<P>
   Andino and Fernandez, Cuban descendants who met while classmates
at Georgia Tech, formed the group Concerned Americans of Cuban
Heritage soon after Elian was taken from the home of his Miami
relatives by federal officials. The purpose of the group was to
start a dialogue in Atlanta about human rights violations that
continue in Cuba, Fernandez said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's our main concern,'' said Andino, an engineer for a
pharmaceutical company who left Cuba in 1968 at the age of 3.
``It's not an issue of a father's right at all. The issue is that
under Cuban law, it's not possible for Elian's father to speak
freely for his son and it's not possible for Elian to speak freely.
That's what we want people to know.''
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, the group said it planned to reach out to members of
Congress to try to change immigration policies.
</P>
<P>
   ``It won't be in time to help Elian,'' Fernandez said. ``In the
future, other Elians might not have to face this scenario.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
