A2373 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-MEXICO-ZEDILLO-0602-C     06-01 0711
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-ZEDILLO-0602-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MEXICAN PRESIDENT SAID HE PREDICTED HIS PARTY WOULD FACE TIGHT
RACE IN 2000
 &HT;    (450&AMP;ADD)
 &HT;    By SUSAN FERRISS 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ In an interview with visiting U.S. newspaper
editors Thursday, Mexican President Ernesto Zedillo said he warned
his 71-year-old ruling party long ago it would face a stiff battle
to hold onto power in this year's presidential election.
</P>
<P>
   ``Almost six years ago when I became president-elect I went to
my party and said, 'OK, we have won this election. This has been
clean, transparent and legal election,''' Zedillo told members of
the American Society of Newspaper Editors. ``But we must not be
satisfied either with the state of democracy in our country or . .
. the capacity of our party to compete in a full democracy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I mentioned to my people in our party that I anticipated . . .
that this race in the year 2000 would be a highly competed and
close race,'' Zedillo said. ``A little bit more than a year ago . .
. I repeated the same. I said, 'OK, we have to get ready for a
close race.'''
</P>
<P>
   Zedillo met with the editors just a month before Mexico's July 2
election, which is indeed expected to be the closest presidential
race in this country's modern history.
</P>
<P>
   Top opposition candidate Vicente Fox Quesada, is neck-in-neck
with Francisco Labastida Ochoa, the candidate of Zedillo's party.
</P>
<P>
   That party, the Institutional Revolutionary Party, or PRI, has
controlled Mexico's presidency since 1929. Fox has mounted a
vigorous campaign that calls for change, and blames the PRI for
corruption and for leaving half the country impoverished.
</P>
<P>
   Zedillo said electoral reforms during his administration and
before have paved the way for more political competition in Mexico,
which has suffered from a reputation for electoral fraud and
vote-buying on behalf of the PRI.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the reason is very simple,'' Zedillo said when asked
why he thought his party was fighting so hard in this year's
election. ``The others have learned very well to compete with the
new rules.''
</P>
<P>
   The presidential campaign is being financed largely by public
funds this year. The candidates have equal access to buy time for
commercials in the media.
</P>
<P>
   The opposition has noted improvements in coverage by a media
once completely under the PRI's thumb. But election officials are
still criticizing coverage in some media as biased toward the PRI,
especially in Mexico's provinces.
</P>
<P>
   The opposition has also complained that some federal social
service programs might be used in rural areas to induce votes for
the ruling party.
</P>
<P>
   Zedillo has denied any political manipulation of programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are in the middle of a very intense, highly competed
election,'' he said. ``But for me, the most important aspect of
that election is that it is being conducted with the rules and
institutions that fully guarantee citizens that their votes will be
counted . . . and will be respected.''
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional ad follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Zedillo also talked to the editors about the investigation into
the December 1998 killing of Philip True, a Mexico-based reporter
for the San Antonio (Texas) Express-News newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   Two suspects are in jail awaiting trial in Jalisco state, where
True was killed while on a trip to write about Huichol Indians.
</P>
<P>
   American Society of Newspaper Editors president Richard Oppel _
the editor of the Austin American-Statesman _ traveled to Jalisco
with other editors to meet with the state attorney general. They
were told a trial would probably start in three to five weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it was very sad,'' Zedillo said of True's killing.
``But I think that his case should not be interpreted as meaning
that journalists are not safe because they are journalists in this
country. Unfortunately, we have a security problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Zedillo said, ``Mr. True went into this place, these rather
primitive communities with a very particular culture,'' and may not
have been aware of the dangers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope that full justice is made in this process,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   (Susan Ferriss' E-mail address is: susanf(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
