r s BC-BBO-MODESTI-COLUMN-LA     06-01 1101
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-MODESTI-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTERLEAGUE PLAY NEEDS TINKERING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR;  ``Interleague play'' is such a bloodless phrase, conveying
none of the clashing emotions the concept inspires even now, three
years after it became reality. So let's call it what it is.
</P>
<P>
   It's Jesse Ventura in spikes.
</P>
<P>
   It's a bulging, bellowing bull in baseball's china shop. It's an
irritant to the purists, a salve to the populists. It's the answer
to the simplistic cry for something _ anything! _ different. It's a
development that wouldn't have been necessary in the first place if
the establishment hadn't been screwing up.
</P>
<P>
   It was a shock to the senses back then but feels strangely
natural now, leaving some of the purists to wonder what they were
so worried about.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before it began, because I'm basically a traditionalist, I
wasn't sure we should change everything,'' said Dodgers CEO Bob
Daly, who was no more than a well-connected fan when games between
National and American League teams were first blended into the
baseball schedule in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Three years seem to have changed Daly's mind. Maybe the Dodgers'
25-19 record in interleague games has something to do with it.
Maybe not.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do like the interleague play,'' he said this week. ``I liked
being able to watch Ken Griffey (Jr.) when he was in Seattle. It's
a chance to see those great ballplayers (in the other league).''
</P>
<P>
   But if Daly's change of heart is typical of how baseball people
have come to feel about the trashing of a near-century of
tradition, so is his belief that we haven't seen the best that
interleague play has to offer.
</P>
<P>
   Daly would like to see interleague play broadened by rotating
the divisional matchups _ so the Dodgers, for example, wouldn't
face the teams from the American League West year after year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd love to see the Yankees, Boston, Cleveland, some of the
other teams come in here,'' he said at Dodger Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Daly's opinion, changing with the seasons, does indeed reflect
the ambivalence many properly feel toward interleague play in its
present format.
</P>
<P>
   As interleague play gets under way for the fourth time, with the
Dodgers and Angels meeting in Anaheim at 7 p.m. and 26 other teams
taking part today, it remains either too much of a bad thing or too
little of a good thing.
</P>
<P>
   Or both. The issue, like that leather-jacketed governor, doesn't
seem to be going away.
</P>
<P>
   Interleague play was a product of the owners-players dispute
that wiped out the 1995 World Series and left baseball officials
desperate to do something (anything!) fan-friendly.
</P>
<P>
   Having stolen a page from the NBA and tried to market individual
players and their personalities, baseball figured the least it
could do was give fans a chance to see all of those players. So
teams were scheduled to play 15 to 18 of their 162 regular-season
games against teams from the other league.
</P>
<P>
   The original concept would have had a star like Mark McGwire, of
the St. Louis Cardinals (of the National League's Central
Division), showing up in Seattle (of the American League West) once
every three years.
</P>
<P>
   As long as you're giving fans expansion, more playoff teams and
all the home runs they can eat, why make them wait for the World
Series to see that dream matchup of the Yankees and Braves?
</P>
<P>
   As well, baseball trumpeted interleague play for fulfilling
latent regional rivalries _ Dodgers-Angels, Cubs-White Sox,
Mets-Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   Has the gimmick worked? Attendance figures say it has been, on
balance, popular. An average of 33,482 fans (up 16.8 percent from
intraleague games) can't be wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Or can they? Interleague play cannot yet be called an artistic
success, or said to have made baseball better competition.
</P>
<P>
   __ The revamped schedule has added interleague games at the
expense of the extra games teams used to play against teams from
their own divisions, diluting the drama of pennant races and
subtracting showdowns between existing rivals.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers will face the San Francisco Giants only 12 times in
2000, down from 18 in 1992, before realignment and the advent of
interleague play. This promotes rivalries?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a proponent of more intradivisional play,'' said Dodgers
manager Davey Johnson. ``You can put me down as a traditionalist, a
bona fide traditionalist.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Having different teams playing different opponents can
unfairly tilt the races for wild-card playoff spots.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, when the Cubs, Giants and Mets battled for the NL wild
card, Chicago had the advantage of playing its interleague games
against the AL Central (a collective 57 games below .500) while San
Francisco faced the AL West (one game under) and New York faced the
AL East (62 games over). The Cubs forced the Giants to a one-game
playoff at Wrigley Field and won it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like the fact that ERA and home run titles are being
decided among guys who didn't play in the same ballparks,'' Dodgers
pitcher Orel Hershiser said, looking at the schedule imbalance as
an individual.
</P>
<P>
   __ For every Dodgers-Angels matchup that might stir some
curiosity _ Edison Field's only three 39,000-plus crowds after
April last season came for the Dodgers in July _ there are a couple
of disasters pitting losers with no historical or geographical
connection against one another.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City plays at Pittsburgh tonight. Let's not all jump on a
plane at once.
</P>
<P>
   __ Until the leagues agree on the designated hitter, AL teams
will always be fish out of water having to bench their DHs while
playing in NL parks. That helps to explain NL teams' 362-327
advantage in interleague victories.
</P>
<P>
   __ The curiosity is in danger of fading as teams play the same
teams for the fourth year in a row. Until it gives us
Dodgers-Yankees, interleague play is just calisthenics.
</P>
<P>
   The chances for improvement depend on how baseball resolves its
looming argument over league and division realignment. The owners'
meeting scheduled for June has been postponed indefinitely. If they
can't even schedule a meeting, how can they schedule interleague
play?
</P>
<P>
   The idea's initial popularity at the turnstiles gives it a
chance to work. But it will feel like a novelty until baseball
figures out how to make it fit into and not detract from the
pennant races that historically define the sport's drama.
</P>
<P>
   Until then, interleague play is the grappler in the oak-paneled
office. It hasn't ruined everything and it just might be a good
idea, but you hope it doesn't get any ideas about the crystal
vase. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-01-00 2233EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
