<SLUG> BC-CAR-MOTORS-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KANKE KNOWS WINS WILL COME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TIM HADDOCK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; MK Kanke has been racing on the NASCAR Featherlite Southwest
Series off and on for the better part of the last 13 years. Seldom
has he been this close to a points title.
</P>
<P>
   Only don't ask the Kennedy High graduate to talk about series
championships. He's been close before and fallen short every time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I worry about points at the last race,'' Kanke said.
</P>
<P>
   Entering Saturday's Food 4 Less 100 at El Cajon Speedway in
eastern San Diego County, the sixth race on the 19-race schedule,
the 38-year-old Frazier Park resident is four points out of first
and going to a track that has treated him well over the years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got my first win on the series there,'' Kanke said. ``We
should do well. I'm looking forward to a top-five finish.''
</P>
<P>
   That first win came in 1993, his sixth year on the series. In
1997, he also finished second at El Cajon, where he has seven
top-five finishes over his career.
</P>
<P>
   And even though Kanke is the among the series leaders, he has
yet to win a race this year. He has two top-fives, including a
second-place finish at Irwindale Speedway where he missed the
checkered flag by half a second behind Greg Pursley of Newhall.
</P>
<P>
   But the series veteran knows the wins will come.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one of those deals where if you run in the top fives,
you'll win some races,'' Kanke said. ``I really thought we had a
shot at Irwindale. But it was my first time at Irwindale. I pretty
much gave (Pursley) everything I had.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Record tests for Hornaday: Ron Hornaday Jr. of Palmdale has
plenty of reasons to be excited about Saturday's NASCAR Busch Grand
National Division race at Dover Downs International Speedway in
Delaware.
</P>
<P>
   For one, Hornaday enters the MBNA Platinum 200 in fourth place
in the series standings, one place higher than last week.
</P>
<P>
   For another, Hornaday has been running practice laps at the
``Monster Mile'' in 23 seconds flat, nearly .2 seconds faster than
the track record set by Winston Cup driver Matt Kenseth last year.
</P>
<P>
   After three years on the NASCAR Craftsman Truck Series and this
year on the Busch circuit, Hornaday has yet to race at Dover.
Still, the few laps Hornaday has turned have been to his liking.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dover is just like a big Bristol to me, and I like it,''
Hornaday said. ``This is the type of track I love. It has big
banking, and a driver makes a huge difference here. It is
definitely a track that you have to respect, but you can't be
timid. If you get timid here, you either get wrecked or lapped in a
hurry.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Chasing Voigt at Irwindale Speedway: Ben Walker of Canyon
Country took the second of two NASCAR Super Late Model Food 4 Less
Twin 50 races Saturday night at Irwindale Speedway. But a pair of
top fives from series leader Greg Voigt of Goleta secured a safe
lead in the standings.
</P>
<P>
   Walker, who also finished third in the first Twin 50 feature of
the night, is 80 points behind Voigt, who finished fourth in the
first feature and was runner-up in the second.
</P>
<P>
   In other action at Irwindale Speedway, T.K. Karvasek of North
Hills won the NASCAR Super Stock main and Ross Uppman of Hawaiian
Gardens won the NASCAR Mini Stock main.
</P>
<P>
   __ Baja 500 kicks off with local flavor: A handful of local
drivers will be taking part in the 32nd running of the Tecate/SCORE
Baja 500 this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the team of John Clark Gable and Dodd Darin of
Malibu in the top-class Trophy Truck division, George Seeley of
Glendale will run in the Class 5 division, Bill Markel of Lancaster
in Class 8, Dennis Nuckles of Leona Valley and Ty Godde of
Lancaster in SCORE Lites, Kevin Ward of North Hollywood in
motorcycle Class 30 for riders over 30 years old and Richard
Jackson of Acton in motorcycle Class 50 for riders over 50 years
old.
</P>
<P>
   The desert race, round three of the SCORE Desert Series, covers
441.6 miles of desert terrain through Baja California, starting and
finishing in Ensenada.
</P>
<P>
   The race starts at 6 a.m. Saturday for motorcycles and ATVs;
7:30 a.m. for the rest of the classes. The race ends 18 hours later
Sunday night.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
