u l BC-CNN-PARTY0602-COX     06-01 0516
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CNN-PARTY0602-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CNN celebrates 20 years
 &HT;    By Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Ted Turner stood on the stage of Philips Arena
Thursday night and surveyed the 15,000 or so people in the stands
who had just finished giving him a standing ovation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have this many people for basketball games,'' he
joked.
</P>
<P>
   The night was no game, though it was frequently fun, as CNN
capped off a day-long celebration of its 20th anniversary with a
tribute to itself and a concert by Diana Ross and the Supremes, who
stepped in at the last minute for an ailing Rod Stewart.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've done extremely well,`` Turner continued in a relaxed
mood. ``But I risked everything at every turn in the road, so I
deserve it all.''
</P>
<P>
   CNN filled the arena with loyal supporters _ old hands who
helped launch the network and have since departed, like Ed Turner,
Earl Casey and first president Reese Schonfeld; cable operators and
advertisers who supported CNN when it was widely seen as a
pipsqueak operation doomed to failure; and nearly all of its
current on-air talent.
</P>
<P>
   ``For so long people thought this wouldn't work,'' analyst Jeff
Greenfield said backstage before the party started. ``To celebrate
20 years with this kind of blow-out is a way of saying, 'Hey, we
made it.' ''
</P>
<P>
   About two dozen CNN anchors milled around the ``green room''
backstage before going on to pay tribute to the CNN world empire.
Meteorologist Flip Spiceland and Headline News anchor Lynne Russell
debated whether it was the original Supremes backing Ross (it
wasn't), and anchor Joie Chen, just back from maternity leave,
chatted with Leon Harris.
</P>
<P>
   After a 15-minute video timeline of CNN moments and fireworks,
the party's organizer, CNN-U.S. President Richard Kaplan aired a
compilation of other celebrities trying to say James Earl Jones'
signature line, ``This is CNN.'' Among those trying, but failing,
to equal Jones were Ellen DeGeneres, Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright, America Online Chairman Steve Case and Bugs Bunny.
</P>
<P>
   Anchor Bernard Shaw introduced Turner, saying he joined CNN in
1980 because, ``I saw it as the last frontier of television news.
But the pioneer was not just one network, it was one person.''
</P>
<P>
   After his brief remarks, Turner lamented that he had to leave
soon to go back to CNN Center and be interviewed by Larry King for
Thursday's two-hour retrospective. He not only missed most of
Ross's concert (which included all of her hits and four costume
changes), but the moment when she walked down to the front row of
the audience.
</P>
<P>
   There the video cameras caught AOL's Case in a Hawaiian shirt,
Time Warner Chairman Gerald Levin dancing with his wife, and CNN's
Kaplan. Ross stuck her microphone into the executives' faces,
urging them to sing along to ``Stop! In the Name of Love.''
</P>
<P>
   Kaplan was game, singing a few bars.
</P>
<P>
   That may explain why, although CNN televises almost everything,
it decided in advance not to televise its own birthday party.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
