u f BC-MICROSOFT-ANTITRUST-1     06-01 0893
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-ANTITRUST-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICROSOFT JUDGE POSTPONES FINAL RULING FOR ABOUT A WEEK 
</HEADLINE>
   (SUBS to rewrite and expand by 600 words.)  
 By JOEL BRINKLEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The federal judge trying the Microsoft antitrust
case unexpectedly agreed to delay his final ruling for about a week
Thursday, giving the Justice Department time to reply to
Microsoft's proposal to water down the government's breakup plan.
</P>
<P>
   The judge, Thomas Penfield Jackson, had planned to issue his
final ruling, widely expected to call for a breakup of the company,
Thursday or Friday. But Justice Department officials called him
Thursday morning to ask if they could reply to Microsoft's comments
on the government's remedy proposal; the comments were filed with
the court on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The comments were supposed to be the final filing in the case,
the last step before Jackson's ruling. But in a conference call
Thursday morning with Microsoft and the government, Jackson gave
the Justice Department until Monday to respond, and Microsoft until
Wednesday to file a counterresponse. His ruling will probably come
almost immediately after that.
</P>
<P>
   During the remedy hearing in Jackson's courtroom on May 24, the
judge asked the federal and state governments that are partners in
the suit to file a final ``clean'' version of their remedy proposal
by May 26. The plaintiffs agreed, but a Microsoft lawyer, John
Warden, then said the company wanted an opportunity to ``comment on
the form of the proposed decree prior to its entry.''
</P>
<P>
   Another Microsoft lawyer, Steven Holley, said outside the
courthouse later that ``comment on the form'' meant looking for
typographical errors and ``internal inconsistencies'' in the
government plan.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Microsoft's response heavily revised the government
proposal _ gutting it, in the view of some government officials.
Some proposals the government viewed as important were deleted,
others were eviscerated, and the timetables for carrying them out
were lengthened _ doubled in some cases.
</P>
<P>
   The government plan would create two new companies; one would
hold the Windows operating systems, the other everything else,
including the Office suite of programs like Word for word
processing and Excel for spreadsheet calculations. It would also
impose restrictions on the company's conduct that would remain in
place while the breakup was being carried out.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft's brief explained that the changes were necessary
because the government proposal ``is vague and ambiguous in
numerous respects,'' littered with ``many flaws.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Were the court to accept all of Microsoft's proposed
changes,'' the brief continued, ``the government's proposed final
judgment would be improved, but much of the vagueness and ambiguity
would remain because it is inherent in the structure of document.''
</P>
<P>
   A Microsoft spokesman, Mark Murray, said, ``We view our
revisions as putting lipstick on a pig.''
</P>
<P>
   Vivek Varma, another Microsoft spokesman representing the legal
department, said Warden ``had not misspoken'' in court. But ``we
had every intention of showing the inadequacies, including
substantively, in the government's proposed order,'' particularly
since Jackson rejected Microsoft's request for remedy hearings.
</P>
<P>
   During the conference call Thursday morning, David Boies, the
government's lead trial lawyer in the case, told the judge that the
Justice Department had found at least a few useful comments among
the dozens of proposed revisions in the Microsoft brief.
</P>
<P>
   Later, Murray leapt on that, saying, ``They told the court that
there wasn't any need for additional remedies hearings, and now it
turns out that there were defects and problems with their
proposal.''
</P>
<P>
   One participant in the call said Jackson was irritated by the
request for further delay; he has repeatedly said he wants to
conclude the case quickly and allow it go forward on appeal. But in
the end, he acceded to the request, after winning assurance from
both sides that this would be the final delay.
</P>
<P>
   Gina Talamona, a spokesman for the Justice Department, said,
``We believed that it was appropriate to request a short
opportunity to comment on Microsoft's specific changes, both to
determine whether there are a few that we can accept without
undermining our remedy proposal, while also offering our reasoning
for urging rejection by the court of the others.''
</P>
<P>
   In its filing on Monday, the Justice Department is certain to
oppose most of the substantive changes, like Microsoft's proposal
to delete the prohibition on continuing to offer special marketing
deals to certain computer manufacturers. In his ruling, Jackson
found that Microsoft had used the special deals to reward
cooperative companies and punish others that did not follow
Microsoft's directions on issues of importance to the company.
</P>
<P>
   But the department may choose to take into account Microsoft's
concerns about the timetable for the breakup plan. Microsoft noted
that the company would have to win approval for elements of the
plan from several federal agencies, including the Securities and
Exchange Commission and the IRS, as well as governments of
countries where the company has subsidiary offices.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obtaining such approvals,'' the Microsoft brief said, ``would
be a time-consuming process.''
</P>
</TEXT>
