<SLUG> BC-EDIT-CUBAN-BOY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: SPEEDING THE ELIAN CASE 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Friday, June 2:
</P>
<P>
   A three-judge panel of the Court of Appeals for the 11th Circuit
has issued a sound ruling that takes an important step toward
bringing the Elian Gonzalez case to a proper and just conclusion.
The court ruled that the Immigration and Naturalization Service was
within its legal authority when it said that the young boy rescued
off the Florida coast last November cannot seek asylum on his own,
and that only his father, Juan Miguel Gonzalez, can speak for him.
Gonzalez has said he wants to take his child home to Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   Given the appeals court decision, the boy's Miami relatives, who
have been fighting to keep Elian in the United States, should
accept the reality that he belongs with his father. The relatives
are entitled to ask for a re-hearing, but otherwise there is very
little legal basis for dragging out this bitter and destructive
case further. The case has already done damage to the image of the
Cuban-American community in Miami and subjected a young child to a
long sojourn away from home after the death of his mother at sea.
Elian has now spent more than a month living with his father,
stepmother and half-brother in the Washington area while awaiting
the appellate court decision.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's decision affirms the judgment that was issued in
March by Federal District Court Judge K. Michael Moore, and upholds
the decisions of Attorney General Janet Reno and the INS
commissioner in affirming the father's parental rights. Although
this page condemned the pre-dawn raid on the Miami relatives'
residence on April 22 as a matter of law enforcement tactics, the
relatives cannot now argue that they have not had their day in
court.
</P>
<P>
   The appellate court found that the INS' decision that a
6-year-old child must be represented by an adult in asylum
proceedings, and that only a parent may speak for the child, absent
evidence of a clear conflict between the parent and the child, was
``reasoned and reasonable.'' Moreover, the court found that
Congress left the details of the asylum process to the discretion
of the executive branch, and that the authority of the executive
branch to fill in the policy details is especially great in the
immigration area.
</P>
<P>
   The court has given Elian's Miami relatives 14 days to request
that the case be reheard by all 12 judges of the appeals court. It
appears that Elian will be required to remain in the country for at
least that period. Lawyers for the relatives are also seeking
intervention by the Supreme Court to ensure that Elian will remain
in the United States until that court can consider an appeal.
</P>
<P>
   But the Miami relatives should recognize that even if Elian were
allowed to apply for asylum on his own, it is highly unlikely that
his claim would be granted. Indeed, the INS has already made a
preliminary assessment that his claim would probably lack merit
because he would have to show a ``well-founded fear of
persecution'' in his home country, a difficult standard to meet.
</P>
<P>
   The courts should wrap up any remaining appeals requests as
quickly as possible. It is time for the federal authorities to
begin preparations to allow Elian and his family to go home.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
