<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-DNA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH'S FIRST REPRIEVE BLOCKS EXECUTION OF CONVICTED KILLER 
 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN W. GONZALEZ 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Gov. George W. Bush signed off on his first
reprieve for a convicted killer Thursday, minutes before the man's
execution.
</P>
<P>
   The 30-day delay will allow Ricky Nolen McGinn time for DNA
retesting of crucial evidence in his 1993 capital murder case.
McGinn's execution was postponed so that the most advanced DNA
testing techniques could be used on evidence in the rape that
preceded the murder of his 12-year-old stepdaughter, Stephanie Rae
Flanary of Brownwood.
</P>
<P>
   ``I expect for the courts and all relevant parties to act
expeditiously to review the evidence and to finally determine his
innocence or guilt as to the charge of rape,'' Bush said while
campaigning in California.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anytime DNA evidence can be used in its context and be
relevant as to the guilt or innocence of a person on death row, we
need to use it,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   If exonerated of the sexual assault, McGinn could have his death
penalty sentence reduced to life in prison or a lesser term.
</P>
<P>
   McGinn's reprieve, which expires at the end of June, was the
first granted for DNA retesting purposes since Bush took office in
1995. Bush has allowed a total of 131 executions, including 20 this
year, but in recent days he said he supports retesting if it could
exonerate a condemned inmate.
</P>
<P>
   Although the execution delay was recommended by Bush, the relief
was granted by the acting governor, state Sen. Rodney Ellis,
D-Houston, president pro tempore of the Texas Senate. The
politically charged decision fell on Ellis because both Bush and
Lt. Gov. Rick Perry were out of state.
</P>
<P>
   ``While I am reluctant to second guess the verdict of a Texas
jury and our courts, we must be willing to take every step possible
to ensure that justice is done,'' Ellis said.
</P>
<P>
   Ellis disputed assertions that Bush recommended the reprieve to
promote his ``compassionate conservative'' bid for the GOP
presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas Court of Criminal Appeals, the 5th U.S. Circuit Court
of Appeals and the U.S. Supreme Court each turned down McGinn's
appeals this week, leaving a one-time-only reprieve of 30 days as
his only available relief. The trial court has the authority to
further postpone the execution date if the sophisticated DNA
testing isn't completed. Ellis said there is some doubt whether it
can be done in 30 days.
</P>
<P>
   McGinn learned of his fate in Huntsville, where he was awaiting
lethal injection after 6 p.m. as ordered by his trial court in
Brownwood. Under what prosecutors called a ``tremendous'' amount of
incriminating evidence, the 42-year-old mechanic and carpenter was
convicted in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   The girl, who was in McGinn's sole care while her mother was out
of town, was found bludgeoned to death about three miles from
McGinn's home on May 22, 1993.
</P>
<P>
   An older type of DNA testing on McGinn's ax detected the girl's
blood and excluded 99.9999999 percent of possible donors, experts
said. His lawyers contend that retesting of a pubic hair found on
the girl's body and a semen stain on her clothing could exonerate
him of the sexual assault.
</P>
<P>
   But Dianne Clements, president of the Houston-based Justice for
All, a crime victims' advocacy group, predicted the testing will
not change McGinn's fate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I absolutely believe that it will be his DNA. ... Nothing will
prove that McGinn did not rape and murder Stephanie Flanary,''
Clements said.
</P>
<P>
   She asserted that McGinn's plea for DNA retesting was an abuse
of the appeals process _ the same conclusion reached earlier this
week by the Texas Court of Criminal Appeals.
</P>
<P>
   ``We cannot as a society throw out traditional evidence ... and
rely on DNA because DNA does not tell the whole story _ his prior
sexual assaultive history; his molestation of another stepdaughter;
her blood on his clothing, his shoes, his pants, his car,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Clements said the reprieve is ``devastating for the victim's
family. Once again, that defendant, that convicted killer, is in
control of their lives when they thought that would be
eliminated.''
</P>
<P>
   For Austin attorney Rob Owen, McGinn's reprieve was bittersweet.
While relieved for McGinn, Owen couldn't help but think of his
client, Jerry Lee Hogue, who was executed two years ago after Bush
declined a similar DNA-based reprieve request. Hogue, proclaiming
his innocence, was executed in 1998 for the 1979 rape and murder of
Jayne Markham in Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   ``We certainly begged the governor to give us the same 30 days
he's now giving Mr. McGinn,'' Owen said. ``If Jerry had had the
good fortune to hang around for two more years until the governor
was running for president, he might have gotten more serious
attention.''
</P>
<P>
   Owen believes there aren't many death row inmates who would
benefit from a new round of DNA tests and doubts there will be any
surge in reprieves requested or granted.
</P>
<P>
   ``In any case where there is any plausible claim that DNA
testing can make us more confident in the result, then we ought to
do it. But I think it is probably an exaggeration to say there are
going to be hundreds of cases. That's probably not going to
happen,'' the lawyer said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
