<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOFA-BIDDING-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 CITY OF S.F. SEEKS COMPETITIVE BIDS FOR BANK BUSINESS  &HT;     By SAM ZUCKERMAN 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The city of San Francisco announced Thursday
that it is putting its banking business out for bid, a move that
jeopardizes an exclusive relationship with Bank of America that
goes back about 75 years.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco Treasurer Susan Leal said her office is requesting
competitive bids for seven pieces of banking business, from
processing paychecks to handling credit card receipts for city
services. Bids will be due in July, and contracts should be awarded
in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   Wells Fargo and Union Bank of California said they will try to
win the business, setting up what may be a three-way contest to be
San Francisco's banker.
</P>
<P>
   Securing the city's banking contracts would hand the winners
big-league bragging rights. For BofA, which won the franchise when
founder A.P. Giannini headed a bank that was still called by its
original name, Bank of Italy, handling the city's business
symbolized the bank's status as the region's leading financial
institution.
</P>
<P>
   That is a position that Wells Fargo, now the biggest bank
headquartered in the West, would love to wrest from BofA. And San
Francisco's Union Bank, the perennial No. 3 in California, could
burnish its reputation by taking some of the city's business.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a trophy,'' said Fred Martin, BofA's former director
of government relations.
</P>
<P>
   Big-Time BofA
</P>
<P>
   Until now, BofA has managed San Francisco's primary bank
accounts and most of the rest of the city's banking operations on a
noncompetitive basis. Wells Fargo and Union currently sell
relatively minor banking services to the city.
</P>
<P>
   About $20 billion passes through San Francisco's various
accounts annually, and BofA collects fees totaling about $1
million, Leal estimated. By contrast, Wells Fargo and Union receive
about $60,000 and $12,000 a year, respectively, for the banking
services they provide to San Francisco, the treasurer's office
said.
</P>
<P>
   Leal's decision to request bids for banking services was not a
surprise, because the treasurer has previously disclosed that she
was weighing such action. In an interview yesterday, she explained
the move as prudent financial management. ``It was basically a
business decision to see that we get the best deal possible for the
city,'' Leal said.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; sh1  &LR; Tangle of Politics
</P>
<P>
   Still, observers said, it is impossible to separate business
considerations from the tangled politics of the city's relationship
with BofA.
</P>
<P>
   A year and a half ago, North Carolina's NationsBank bought San
Francisco's BofA and took its name. After originally promising a
``merger of equals,'' the new owners treated the old BofA as a
junior partner and forced out many of the California bank's top
executives, including former Chief Executive David Coulter.
</P>
<P>
   City officials, including Mayor Willie Brown and Board of
Supervisors President Tom Ammiano, questioned how much the
acquiring bank would remain committed to the San Francisco
community once it was headquartered across the continent. And the
bank's attempts to impose its culture on its tradition-bound
acquisition touched off controversies over such matters as the mass
departure of senior female managers of the old BofA.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; sh1  &LR; Hard-Nosed Approach
</P>
<P>
   That history ``makes it easier now to be a little hard-nosed''
in negotiating the city's banking business, said Mary Callanan, who
was San Francisco treasurer from 1980 to 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Leal herself has raised nonbusiness issues in her dealings with
BofA. At the beginning of the year, for example, she wrote to the
bank asking for information about local job cuts after the
takeover, information she said the city was entitled to ``as one of
(BofA's) largest customers in California.'' The bank supplied the
information several weeks later.
</P>
<P>
   For its part, BofA put a brave face on what may be the end of
its special relationship with San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   ``The treasurer has said for some time she would try to put the
city's banking business out for bid, and we've always said that's a
good idea,'' said BofA spokesman Peter Magnani. ``We expect we'll
win our fair share`` of competitive bids.
</P>
<P>
   Still, BofA has not yet decided whether it will bid on all seven
of the city's banking contracts, Magnani said.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, BofA and the city turned into partners whose
interests became increasingly intertwined. The bank agreed to
handle low-profit businesses, such as cashing welfare checks. The
city, in turn, kept most of its business with BofA.
</P>
<P>
   Prickly Relationship
</P>
<P>
   Like squabbling spouses, the relationship persisted even as the
city and other municipalities were suing the bank for hundreds of
millions of dollars over what they said was fraudulent
mismanagement of municipal bond accounts. That suit was settled in
1998, when BofA agreed to pay the plaintiffs $187 million.
</P>
<P>
   Leal's office expects half a dozen or more financial
institutions to bid on the city's banking contracts. But most
observers expect the main competition will come from BofA, Wells
Fargo and Union.
</P>
<P>
   Union, whose majority owner is Japan's Bank of Tokyo-Mitsubishi,
said it plans to bid on all seven contracts. ``We have the smallest
amount of the city's business,'' said Donna Hodgson, manager of the
bank's government services division. ``We hope when this whole
process is completed, we'll have the largest share.''
</P>
<P>
   Wells Fargo has also girded to compete. Last October, the bank
formed a special government and educational banking division and
made winning San Francisco's business a top priority. Dick
Kovacevich, the bank's chief executive, met with Leal several
months ago, urging her to give Wells Fargo a shot at the business,
the treasurer said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to be aggressive in soliciting the city's
business,'' said Wells Fargo spokeswoman Mary Rodrigues.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the final result, the era when BofA had a lock on San
Francisco's banking business is over.
</P>
<P>
   ``BofA was always very civic minded,'' said former city
treasurer Callanan. ``They were a hometown bank. They were
employing people here,'' she said. When it came time to negotiate
the city's business, ``that certainly was in the back of my mind.''
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Sam Zuckerman at  &LR; szuckerman(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
