 DREAMTIME LANDS NASA DEAL  &HT;     By HENRY NORR 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ NASA is set to name a private company to take
over production and distribution of images from space, and a San
Francisco startup has reportedly won the nod.
</P>
<P>
   NASA Administrator Daniel Goldin and an array of other agency
bigwigs are scheduled to appear Friday at a news conference at
NASA's Ames Research Center in Mountain View, Calif., to announce
an ``unprecedented public-private partnership for multimedia and
space imagery.''
</P>
<P>
   A NASA spokesman declined to provide details, but Space.com, a
Web site that focuses on space-related subjects, this week reported
that the agency has chosen Dreamtime, a little-known San Francisco
company, to produce its film, video, still photography and Internet
programming.
</P>
<P>
   The plan, according to Space.com, calls for Dreamtime to provide
high-definition television (HDTV) equipment to beam video and
stills from the $60 billion International Space Station and the
shuttles that are helping to build it.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the company will be responsible for digitizing and
cataloging up to 40,000 hours of video, 10 million still images and
10 million feet of film from NASA archives.
</P>
<P>
   The move is part of a NASA push to get private companies to
invest in its work.
</P>
<P>
   Dreamtime could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Henry Norr at  &LR; hnorr(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
