<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IPO-OPTICS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 FIBER-OPTICS COMPANIES AT FOREFRONT OF IPO PACK  &HT;     By KELLY ZITO 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Two Bay Area companies dipped their toes into
the empty public offering swimming pool Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   One dog-paddled, the other did the 1,000-meter butterfly.
</P>
<P>
   After first looking for a $16-a-share initial offering price,
Burlingame, Calif.'s CrossWorlds Software on Thursday opened at $10
and edged up an anemic 13 cents by the end of regular trading.
</P>
<P>
   The firm, which makes software for integrating
electronic-business software from multiple vendors, raised about
$40 million.
</P>
<P>
   ONI Systems, a San Jose, Calif., maker of fiber-optics gear,
firmly occupied the other end of the IPO spectrum Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   After boosting its initial price 56 percent last month _ to $25
_ the San Jose firm's stock skyrocketed to $82.56. Its 230 percent
gain was the best-performing IPO in months and helped ONI rake in
$200 million.
</P>
<P>
   Since the Nasdaq Stock Market's multiple swoons in April,
interest in IPOs has been scarce to nonexistent. Of the half-dozen
firms planning this week to sell their stock to the public for the
first time, four lowered their offerings _ some by as much as a
third.
</P>
<P>
   CrossWorlds, which had originally hoped to bring in about $64
million with its IPO, had $19 million in sales last year. But the
company's management has changed in recent months and it faces
stiff competition from the likes of Santa Clara, Calif.'s Active
Software and Sunnyvale, Calif.'s Vitria Technology, which both had
strong IPOs last year.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say ONI's rise reflects investors' continued love
affair with fiber-optics companies, one of the few sectors to
generate enthusiasm as yesterday's shining stars, dot-coms, come to
resemble black holes more and more every day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though the overall market for IPOs has been slow,
communications infrastructure IPOs have remained very hot,'' said
Tim Savageaux, senior research analyst at WR Hambrecht. ``Maybe
they're not as hot as they would have been two months ago, but
they've still been extraordinarily successful.''
</P>
<P>
   Savageaux points to other early highfliers like Santa Clara,
Calif.'s New Focus. Though it fell $3.60 yesterday, the
fiber-optics components-maker gained 155 percent in its premiere
two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   Investors believe fiber optics hold the key to the Web's
potential for becoming a full-fledged communications and commerce
medium because glass fiber handles data much more efficiently than
does traditional copper wire.
</P>
<P>
   ONI also has some big names behind it. Among its shareholders
are Silicon Valley venture capital powerhouse Kleiner Perkins
Caufield &AMP; Byers and Mohr, Davidow Ventures.
</P>
<P>
   Kleiner Perkins Caufield &AMP; Byers, which owns 11 percent of ONI
after the offering, has backed companies including America Online
and Amazon.com.
</P>
<P>
   ONI Systems trades under the symbol ONIS. CrossWorlds' ticker
symbol is CWLD.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Kelly Zito at  &LR; kzito(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
