 PACIFIC BELL, AT&AMP;T RAISE RATES  &HT;     By TODD WALLACK 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Starting Friday, Pacific Bell plans to boost the
price for several optional calling plans and features, including 69
and three-way calling.
</P>
<P>
   The price for basic service and many other calling features
won't change, said Pac Bell spokesman John Britton. But the
increase irked some consumer advocates, especially coming just days
after the company won a $13 million property-tax break from the
state.
</P>
<P>
   The phone company notified the Public Utilities Commission a
month ago of its plans, but the regulatory agency opted not to
challenge the increases.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is absolutely no justification for these increases,''
said Tom Stein, a lawyer for the Utility Reform Network in San
Francisco. ``These custom calling features cost almost nothing
extra to provide. This is pure gravy.''
</P>
<P>
   The rate hikes will affect:
</P>
<P>
   -- Three packages that include Caller ID and other custom
calling features. ``Basic Saver'' and the ``Basics'' will jump $3
to $19.95 a month. The ``Works,'' which also includes voice mail,
will jump $3 to $27.90
</P>
<P>
   -- Three custom-calling features (repeat dialing; three-way
calling; and 69, which is used to call the last person who dialed
your number). The cost for each feature will be 95 cents per use,
an increase of 20 cents.
</P>
<P>
   -- Calling-card calls, which will cost at least 50 cents, up
from 25 cents.
</P>
<P>
   -- Two calling plans (``Saver 60'' and ``Saver Plus'') that
cover calls to numbers farther than 12 miles away but too short to
be considered long-distance will jump. Prices for extra minutes
will jump by a penny each.
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Wirepro,'' an inside wiring maintenance protection plan,
which increases 70 cents to $1.99 per month.
</P>
<P>
   Britton said the inside wiring plan is still cheaper than the
national average, which is $2.52 per month. He also said the price
for individual features, like Caller ID and call waiting, won't
change. But he said the packages are still a better deal, even
after the price increases, for consumers who want several of the
features.
</P>
<P>
   Pac Bell isn't the only company raising rates. AT&AMP;T boosted
rates yesterday for operator-assisted calls and calling cards. Some
examples:
</P>
<P>
   -- Operator-assisted collect and third-party fees will increase
to $4.99, up $1.04, when an automated system is involved. With a
live operator, the price for third-party calls will increase to
$9.95, up from $6.95.
</P>
<P>
   -- Per-minute calls on standard AT&AMP;T cards will increase to 69
cents, up from a range of 30 cents to 59 cents.
</P>
<P>
   -- Service charges for direct-dialed calls using a calling card,
ranging from 30 cents to $2.25, will increase to between 99 cents
and $4.95. Operator-assisted calls, which now cost between $2.95
and $3.45, will now cost $5.50.
</P>
<P>
   Stein called the increases ``sneaky,'' because many consumers
may not be aware of them. AT&AMP;T, however, said it placed
advertisements outlining the increases in newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T spokeswoman Jane Young also said most customers would be
unaffected by the changes because relatively few place
operator-assisted calls. And heavy calling-card users are usually
enrolled in special calling plans with lower rates, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``As always, we encourage people to dial direct,'' she said.
Young also advised consumers to consider buying prepaid
long-distance cards instead of using calling cards to keep bills
down.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Todd Wallack at  &LR; todd(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
