<HEADER>
A2392 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-FCC-NYT &LR;      06-01 0729
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-FCC-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: THE FCC'S OWNERSHIP RULES 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Friday, June 2:
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Communications Commission, under heavy political
pressure, is preparing to loosen rules that limit the ability of
television broadcasters to own other communications properties.
This is a bad idea. There is no evidence that weakening the rules
will help consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the rules exist to preserve something precious and
fragile in a democracy _ the diversity of information that flows
into everyone's home. The commission already has all the power it
needs to grant exemptions where necessary.
</P>
<P>
   One important rule prevents a network from buying another
network. The commission recently invoked the rule to require
Viacom, which recently purchased CBS, to divest itself of UPN, a
newer, financially weak network. Those who want to soften the rule
argue that UPN can thrive only if it combines with another network
with which it can share costs. But turning to CBS to save UPN
creates a bigger CBS, without necessarily preserving a valuable
independent voice for news and entertainment. If the commission can
prove that an independent UPN can survive only by combining with
CBS, then it has the legal power to reverse its earlier ruling and
grant a well-argued waiver.
</P>
<P>
   Another key rule prevents a broadcaster from owning a newspaper
in the same city. The commission appears poised to lift that rule
in large cities, like New York, where joint ownership poses little
threat because several newspapers and television stations coexist.
The immediate issue is the Tribune Co.'s agreement to buy Times
Mirror, which would give the Tribune ownership of newspapers and
television stations in three cities, including New York. There it
would own Newsday, the Long-Island-based daily that circulates in
the city, and WPIX, a television station already owned by the
Tribune Co.
</P>
<P>
   But the argument for relaxing the rule is weak. The commission
can and does grant exemptions in the rare instances where a local
newspaper's sole chance for survival is to be purchased by a
broadcaster. The commission ruled in this fashion to allow Rupert
Murdoch, who already owned a New York television station, to buy
The New York Post. By loosening the rule for large cities, the
commission would in effect grant a blanket waiver without the need
to prove the case. Threats to diversity need not be put on such
automatic pilot.
</P>
<P>
   A third rule, which the commission does not seem prepared to
change, prevents broadcasters from owning stations that reach more
than 35 percent of households in the country. This is a sound rule
for preserving diversity of ownership, even in a time when cable is
eroding broadcast boundaries. Weakening the rule could, for
example, stifle the voice of independent programmers. Programmers
who refuse to conform to the tastes of a huge broadcaster, one
whose reach extends well beyond the 35 percent figure, could find
themselves shut out of too many of the nation's homes to survive.
</P>
<P>
   Any media company has an interest in the commission's decisions,
and The New York Times Co. is no exception. A change in the
commission's rules could affect the business activities of the
Times Co., which owns The New York Times, 23 other newspapers and 8
television stations. But the issue is not the well-being of the
Times Co. or any other company, but rather the preservation of a
diverse group of independent sources for news and entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   The rules that govern concentration in telecommunications are
unlike antitrust laws. In the bottled water and sneaker markets,
mergers are allowed unless antitrust authorities can prove that
added concentration would do harm. If the authorities err, and
permit excessive consolidation, about all that happens is that the
price of bottled water rises and innovation slacks off in the
design of sneakers. But in telecommunications, the threat that
concentration might shut off sources of information is profound.
</P>
<P>
   The commission has no legal obligation to bend over backward on
behalf of the telecommunications industry. Instead, it is charged
with protecting the public interest. Before the commission changes
its rules, it needs to prove that ordinary citizens will benefit
from the change. So far, that case does not exist.
</P>
</TEXT>
