<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 22:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2394 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-MBA-GRADS-SFCHRON &LR;      06-01 1001
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MBA-GRADS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 NEW GRADS WEIGH JOBS AT STARTUPS  &HT;     By JENNIE YABROFF 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Last fall, Heather Zehren-Albinson thought her
future was clear.
</P>
<P>
   She would finish her master's degree in business administration
at the University of California at Berkeley this spring before
heading to work for the New York investment bank where she was an
intern last summer.
</P>
<P>
   Those plans started to unravel when her husband, Tim Albinson,
who graduated from UC Berkeley's Haas School of Business in 1999,
left his investment banking job to start his own Internet-related
company.
</P>
<P>
   With her prospective banking job looking pretty dull by
comparison, Heather caught Tim's startup fever and began
interviewing with startups.
</P>
<P>
   But with the wild gyrations in the stock market, she had second
thoughts. Now she is leaning toward taking the job offer with the
bank.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're taking a huge risk with Tim's company, so for the
stability factor, I'll probably take the more secure banking job,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   For Heather's class of MBAs, the intoxication of being wooed by
fledgling companies is dampened by a sobering turn of events on
Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   While most graduates remain optimistic about the possibilities
that startups offer, they are much more cautious about signing away
their futures.
</P>
<P>
   ``Smart MBAs are kicking a lot of tires before deciding to go
with a startup,'' Albinson said. ``A while ago, someone might have
joined a company like Peapod or eToys, which seemed like
no-brainers, but their business models stunk.''
</P>
<P>
   (Shares of Peapod, which lost $120 million in financing in
March, are trading at around $2, a 78 percent drop-off in the past
12 months. Meanwhile shares of eToys, which hasn't turned a profit,
have dropped 90 percent in the past year to about $5.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Now people are looking at business models more carefully,
checking out the funding, (and) making sure the founders have a
strategy for differentiating their business from the rest of what's
out there,'' Tim Albinson said.
</P>
<P>
   Albinson's startup, Exchangewave, helps online businesses
connect with customers. The company has raised $500,000 in capital
so far and is working on a second round of funding.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get e-mails everyday from friends asking how I'm weathering
starting a business in the midst of the (stock market) carnage,''
he said. ``But I've interviewed 25 MBAs in the past month who want
to come work for us. They're still confident that startups can
succeed.''
</P>
<P>
   While no one denies that the bearish turn on Wall Street has
meant bad news for tech stocks and the startups they finance, this
year's business school graduates are putting the best face possible
on the news.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a good correction,'' said Che Mott, who graduated from
Haas last month and now works for Exchangewave.
</P>
<P>
   Although traditional jobs for MBAs like investment banking or
consulting offer more stability and higher salaries, the lure of
startups remains strong. More than twice as many MBAs from
Stanford's Graduate School of Business started their own companies
in 1999 as 1998, and that trend seems to be continuing.
</P>
<P>
   Sherrie Taguchi, director of the Career Management Center at
Stanford's business school, said 12 percent of the school's
graduates founded their own startups last year, and the number
could be as high as 15 percent for the class of 2000.
</P>
<P>
   High tech and venture capital top the list of industries
attracting graduates.
</P>
<P>
   ``The weaker companies are being impacted by the market,
especially ones without good funding and good revenues,'' Taguchi
said. ``But our students are very thoughtful and do their due
diligence and homework. They know what to look for.''
</P>
<P>
   What business school graduates are looking for doesn't always
include a big paycheck. MBAs going into traditional jobs like
management consulting, investment banking, brokerage and real
estate can expect to make $100,000 to $200,000 a year in their
first year out of school.
</P>
<P>
   Startups offer considerably less, with first-year salaries
starting in the $55,000 range, and entrepreneurs starting their own
companies aren't guaranteed a salary at all.
</P>
<P>
   Taguchi said the top three job criteria that students look for
are
</P>
<P>
   whom they will be working for, how much intellectual stimulation
the position offers and the opportunity for advancement.
Compensation ranks fifth on the list.
</P>
<P>
   That's good news for startups, which can't offer the same
salaries as more established companies. But the use of stock
options by startups to lure employees has lost some luster during
the recent market downturn.
</P>
<P>
   ``Job candidates are becoming more aware that there are a lot of
worthless options out there,'' said Steve Anderson, a consultant at
the Palo Alto, Calif., venture capital firm Kleiner Perkins
Caufield and Byers who works with startups.
</P>
<P>
   Rebecca Pfeifer, who graduates with an MBA from Stanford this
month and plans to work for a high-tech startup, agrees. ``People
are seeing that relying solely on stock options as a get-rich-quick
solution is not a good way to pick a company,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the possibility of lower salaries, less job security and
stock options of uncertain value, MBAs still can't resist the siren
songs of startups. They say the opportunity to help shape a company
and the freedom to create their own destiny are worth the risk.
</P>
<P>
   ``After two years of school, MBAs want a chance to flex their
brains and the skills they've acquired,'' Albinson said. ``Going to
work for an established company, even an Internet company like
Yahoo, gives you very little opportunity to steer the direction of
the business.''
</P>
<P>
   His wife agrees, sounding wistful.
</P>
<P>
   ``There might be more opportunities in banking right now,
because they're losing people to startups. And I will make more
money at a bank,'' she said. ``But part of me really wants to be
involved in the new Internet economy. I want to feel like I was
there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
