<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 23:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2442 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-BRAZILLS0602-COX     06-01 1283
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAZILLS0602-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Brazill's family breaks silence
 &HT;    By William Cooper Jr.
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Polly Powell, the mother of Nathaniel
Brazill who is accused of killing a popular middle school teacher,
spoke publicly Thursday, defending her son and her parenting
skills.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just ask myself is it something that I missed,'' said
Powell, 34, speaking at a news conference held at the Public
Defender's Office.
</P>
<P>
   ``What can a mother do when you try and raise your child the
best you can and something like this happens,'' said Powell,
breaking down and crying.
</P>
<P>
   Her 13-year-old son has been charged by police with first-degree
murder in the fatal shooting of Barry Grunow, a popular Lake Worth
Middle School English teacher on May 26, the last day of school.
Brazill is being held at the juvenile detention center in West Palm
Beach, awaiting for a grand jury to decide what he should be
charged with and whether he should be charged as an adult.
</P>
<P>
   His parents, Powell and Nathaniel Brazill Sr., spoke publicly
for the first time nearly a week after the shooting. They said they
have been silent out of respect for Grunow's widow and family.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Grunow had just passed away and we did not want to
interfere with the family and their time of grief and mourning,''
the boy's father said, clutching a blue leather Bible.
</P>
<P>
   Powell said she also wanted to pay respect to Grunow's widow
Pam. ``One day when some of this cools down, I can go to her house
so I can give her a hug and let her know that I'm truly sorry that
it had to be my child, anybody's child, that takes a life of a
teacher. I feel for her and my heart just goes out to her.''
</P>
<P>
   Powell said her son gave no indication when the day started May
26 that anything might be amiss. For her the day began as often did
_ with her having to leave her Lake Worth home before Nathaniel got
up for school. Her job as assistant food services director at
Bishop Gray Inn, a Lake Worth retirement home, often required her
to leave by 6:30 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Later that morning, she called her son to make sure he was
getting ready to go to school. He was awake, but he wasn't dressed
for school, Powell recalled.
</P>
<P>
   She called back later, when her mother, Everlena Josey, arrived
to make sure her son got off to school. Josey also cares for
Powell's 2-year-old daughter, Ebony, while she and her husband,
Marshall Powell, work. Although Powell moved out in January, he has
since returned.
</P>
<P>
   About mid-day, while she was at work, Polly Powell received a
call from the school, saying that her son was being sent home for
throwing water balloons. She figured he would go to Josey's house.
</P>
<P>
   Brazill did go there, but only to get the key to his family's
apartment, where he got the gun used in the shooting, police have
said.
</P>
<P>
   When Powell came home from work about 3:30 p.m., she hoped to
see her son. She had heard about the shooting at her son's school
from a neighbor and was concerned.
</P>
<P>
   ``Knowing earlier that my son was sent home (from school) all I
wanted to do was find him and make sure he was okay,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   He wasn't there, so she went to her mother's house. He wasn't
there either.
</P>
<P>
   Powell said she assumed their paths had crossed while she was on
her way to Josey's house, so she returned home. Hoping he would
arrive any moment, she took a shower. The telephone rang. Her
sister said to call their mother.
</P>
<P>
   ``People were calling my mother's house saying it was
Nathaniel,'' said Powell, who was told by her mother to head to the
Lake Worth Police Department.
</P>
<P>
   At the police station, Powell asked if her son was being held
there. She said she asked three times before police took her to
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just hugged him, cried and asked him was he okay,'' Powell
said.
</P>
<P>
   She said the police told her not to ask her son any questions.
After two hours at the station, police asked her to leave because
they going to take him to the Juvenile Assessment Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just numb,'' she said. ``It's too shocking to even
imagine. The thought of your child who you know, you raised the
best you can, has taken somebody's life.''
</P>
<P>
   His father, who now lives in Daytona Beach, learned about the
shooting from his sister, who telephoned him from Lake Worth. The
boy's father, a postal worker, was doing volunteer work at his
church, Shiloh Missionary Baptist Church when he got the call.
</P>
<P>
   He said he had seen his son just a few weeks before, while he
was visiting the Lake Worth home of his parents, George and Ida
Brazill. He said he typically keeps up with his son through his
parents and sees him only when he visits them.
</P>
<P>
   Now Powell says she speaks to her son daily. He gets to make two
calls a day, one in the morning and one in the evening.
</P>
<P>
   He's asked her to send him a picture of his family.
</P>
<P>
   Neither parent has asked him about the shooting, they said. They
say they don't want to upset him. Their role, they say, is just to
be supportive.
</P>
<P>
   His father, however, said he believes the shooting was an
accident.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a terrible, terrible accident,'' the elder Brazill
said. ``He never intentionally pulled that trigger.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nate was a child that was playing with something that was
deadly,'' his father said. ``He didn't know the ramifications of
it. And the gun went off. That's it.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither parent wants Brazill tried as an adult.
</P>
<P>
   Both parents describe their son as a bright student, with plenty
of ambition and not a bad bone in his body. He was boy who took a
liking to computers at age 4 while he was in pre-school, his mother
said.
</P>
<P>
   Just last Christmas, she had bought him a Gateway computer as a
gift because ``he had been so good in school and been good with me
through my breast cancer.'' According to his mother, Brazill went
on the Internet and order information about becoming a Secret
Service agent, a career he said he hoped to pursue. She allowed him
about 1 1/2 hours a day on the computer, during which time he like
to play simulated fighter pilot games and other less violent ones.
</P>
<P>
   On the advice of their son's attorney, Assistant Public
Defender, Randy Berman, the parents didn't discuss how their son
got the gun. Police said he took the gun from Elmore McCray's home
in Boynton Beach.
</P>
<P>
   McCray, 75, is the father of the godmother of the young Brazill.
The boy stayed at the McCray house on occasion, his mother said. He
and the elder McCray, whom he called ``Grand,'' would mow the lawn
together and ride bikes, his mother said.
</P>
<P>
   She and her son attended McCray's 75th birthday party on May 13,
which drew a busload of relatives from South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   Several days later, Powell left her son with the McCrays while
she and her mother went to Bishopville, S.C. for five days to look
at property that had been left to the family, Powell said. Powell
returned to Lake Worth late May 23, and her son returned home the
next day, just two days before the shooting.
</P>
<P>
   On the surface, it appears that Powell had a support system of
relatives and close friends who invested in her son's life. But
early her son's life there was domestic problems in the home, court
records show.
</P>
<P>
   Powell has been named in 17 domestic incident reports in the
past six years. The reports detail arguments between her and
Marshall Powell, and fights between her and her previous husband,
Wainford Whitefield.
</P>
<P>
   Despite some of her past problems, Powell said her son was
raised properly.
</P>
<P>
   ``My child wasn't a monster,'' she said. ``I know I did the best
I could. I just pray that everybody realizes that he is a child.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
