<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETWORTH-PENDER-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 NET WORTH: CHINA STILL A SLEEPING STOCK GIANT  &HT;     By KATHLEEN PENDER 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ U.S. mutual funds that invest in China got a
boost from positive news on the trade front late last month. But
the gains evaporated after investors started focusing on the grim
realities of investing in one of the world's least-developed stock
markets.
</P>
<P>
   Even though mainland China has the world's best-performing
markets year to date _ the Shanghai index is up 50 percent and the
Shenzhen index is up 32 percent _ China mutual funds are showing
losses, mainly because most of their assets are in Hong Kong, which
is down 12 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Most investment pros agree that over the long term, China will
benefit greatly from its inclusion in the World Trade Organization
and improved trade relations with the United States.
</P>
<P>
   On May 19, China's entry into the WTO cleared a major hurdle
when the European Union voted to let it in.
</P>
<P>
   And on May 24, the U.S. House of Representatives passed a bill
granting China permanent normal trade relations. The PNTR bill goes
to the Senate this month.
</P>
<P>
   Both of these developments, assuming they gain final approval,
will gradually reduce tariffs and eliminate barriers to foreign
investment, which will increase trade between China and the rest of
the world and strengthen China's economy.
</P>
<P>
   But change won't come quickly, and while many Chinese companies
will prosper in a more open market, others will lose out to foreign
competitors.
</P>
<P>
   Roz Hewsenian, a vice president with Wilshire Associates who
advises pension funds on foreign investments, says the Chinese
people will probably benefit before foreign investors.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lag between when a country develops economically and
when it develops a stock market,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Mainland China lacks shareholder protections such as clearly
defined property rights, accounting standards, disclosure
requirements and market regulation.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you trade in the U.S., England, France, even Taiwan, Poland
or some Latin American countries, the amount of disclosure and
regulation is sufficient that you, as a small investor, can feel
reasonably protected,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Not so in China. ``In terms of market regulation, it ranks at
the bottom of our list of 30 to 35 developing countries.''
</P>
<P>
   That's why many U.S.-based China funds put most of their money
in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
   ``We vastly prefer Hong Kong to mainland China,'' says Jim
Atkinson, managing director of Investec Guinness Flight, which has
funds that invest in both markets.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of the mainland Chinese companies are state-owned
enterprises in smokestack industries. And the transparency
(accounting, disclosure, etc.) is not as high as we'd like,'' he
says. In Hong Kong, ``there's a lot more transparency and less
reliance on smokestack industries. Hong Kong will do well if China
does well.''
</P>
<P>
   He says Guinness is bullish on the region, but not just because
of the WTO. ``The region, particularly (mainland) China, is going
through a transformation that is moving the economy from agrarian
to industrial and post-industrial in a very short time.''
</P>
<P>
   For example, about 10 percent of the people in mainland China
have a fixed-line phone, and almost 5 percent have a mobile phone.
Starting in April, more people signed up for cellular than regular
phones.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't have the legacy infrastructure of old
telecommunications,'' says Chris Legallet, manager of the Newport
Greater China fund. ``That could make them more flexible, more
nimble as an economy going forward.''
</P>
<P>
   Legallet says that most U.S. investors have focused on China's
export prowess. ``They're moving up the value-added scale very
quickly, starting in garments and moving into technology. They have
a highly productive, low-cost workforce.''
</P>
<P>
   But ``the domestic market is still very, very underdeveloped. At
the end of the day, exports don't drive growth, domestic economy
does.''
</P>
<P>
   That, he says, is where the real potential lies. Even in a
slump, China's economic growth far exceeds that of most developed
countries.
</P>
<P>
   China's growth rate in gross domestic product has been
declining, from 10 percent at the beginning of the 1990s to about 7
percent last year. This year's stock market gains follow several
years of big losses.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Gao, co-portfolio manager of the Matthews Dragon Fund in
San Francisco, thinks China has recovered.
</P>
<P>
   Exports grew 39 percent in the first four months of this year,
and the first-quarter GDP grew 8.1 percent. ``We think this will be
the first year since 1992 that the growth rate goes up,'' says Gao.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Matthews, chief investment officer of the Matthews funds,
is also encouraged ``by the emergence of two or three Chinese
companies as globally eligible investments.''
</P>
<P>
   They include China Telecom, the nation's largest cellular
provider; Legend Holdings, the largest PC-maker and distributor in
China; and China Unicom, the second-largest cellular provider,
which is about to go public on the Hong Kong and New York stock
exchanges.
</P>
<P>
   ``If even one Chinese company can earn that sort of
international recognition, we see no reason why a larger number of
companies can't,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   But even China boosters admit that the nation poses very
significant political, economic and currency risks. Foremost among
them are China's record on human rights and its unsettled
relationship with Taiwan, which has drawn threats of war from
Beijing by flirting with the idea of declaring independence.
</P>
<P>
   ``How that's resolved over time is a risk,'' says Legallet,
although he says the two countries ``are becoming so economically
intertwined it's going to be hard for them not to acknowledge each
other.''
</P>
<P>
   China could also get involved in a political skirmish with Tibet
or even Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
   Kate Schapiro, manager of the Wells Fargo International Equity
Fund, just returned from an investment conference in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went to Hong Kong with the hope of coming back really
energized about investing in the region. I'm not as energized as I
thought I'd be,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's enormous potential there. The young generation are
very excited, well educated and more exposed to the rest of the
world through TV and the Internet. The Chinese culture has become
more supportive of entrepreneurs.
</P>
<P>
   ``But there still are structural problems: high debt levels,
regulations and restrictions on investments. They still have a lot
of problems trying to deal with state-owned enterprises. The
banking system is in terrible shape. And they still have to develop
a pension system.
</P>
<P>
   ``The state used to take care of everybody. As more companies
become privately owned, they have to transfer some pension scheme
onto these companies.''
</P>
<P>
   The benefits of WTO, she says, are going to take place over
three to five years. ``Any investor has to have patience and a
fairly long time frame.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Rocco, who follows China funds for Morningstar, has the
same concerns. That's why he thinks investors should avoid funds
that invest exclusively in China or any other country.
</P>
<P>
   ``A single-country fund is just much, much, much, much, much too
narrow for most investors. I would argue that region funds are much
too narrow for most investors.''
</P>
<P>
   However, ``If you want to think of it is a speculative
investment for a small part of a portfolio, that's OK, if you can
handle the kind of volatility you're going to get.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether he would ``gamble'' money in an Internet fund or a
China fund, Rocco chose the former. ``I buy the Internet story more
than I buy the China story,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Atkinson, whose firm also manages an Internet fund, says he
would chose the Net fund ``if I wanted to be really speculative. If
I wanted to be more conservative, I'd go with a China fund.''
</P>
<P>
   Schapiro says, ``I'd put it in a China fund. The Internet is
exciting ... but we don't know yet how anybody's going to make
money on it. In China, there are companies that do make money and I
think you're buying them at a lower valuation than Internet
companies.''
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Kathleen Pender at  &LR; kpender(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
