u f BC-LUCKY-AD-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      06-01 0869
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LUCKY-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKETERS BET ON THE CONCEPT OF GOOD LUCK AS A SELLING TOOL
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ky., Minn.)  By STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Who knew when Barbra Streisand asked the musical
question ``How Lucky Can You Get?'' that Madison Avenue would
provide this answer: You ain't seen nothing yet.
</P>
<P>
   Advertisers and media magnates are celebrating the concept of
good fortune with a lengthening list of products, publications and
pitches centered on the word ``lucky.''
</P>
<P>
   For instance, a magazine named Lucky is being introduced
nationally by Conde Nast Publications. A cool character called Mr.
Lucky is the focus of a quirky series of television, print and
poster ads for the Excite Web site. And the venerable Lucky Strike
cigarette brand is being reintroduced with a big advertising and
promotional push that plays up the iconic Lucky name.
</P>
<P>
   Those newcomers join users of luck as a sales tool like Lucky
Charms cereal; Lucky Dog, a long-distance telephone service
operated by AT&AMP;T; Lucky jeans; the Lucky chain of supermarkets; and
games with ``lucky'' in their names sold by various state
lotteries.
</P>
<P>
   Why are Lady Luck and Dame Fortune becoming almost as popular
with marketers as Britney Spears and Christina Aguilera are with
teen-age music fans?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the state of the U.S. right now,'' said Jeff Weiss,
creative director at Amster Yard in New York, part of the
McCann-Erickson unit of the Interpublic Group of Companies that is
bringing out the Excite campaign for the At Home Corp. ``People are
feeling good.
</P>
<P>
   ``And the advertising has to be about using technology to make
us more human,'' he added. ``People like things that are warm, and
the whole air of `lucky' is warmth.''
</P>
<P>
   John Allen, senior partner at Lippincott &AMP; Margulies in New
York, a corporate identity consulting company owned by Marsh &AMP;
McLennan, echoed Weiss.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's something warm and approachable about words with old
roots like `lucky,''' Allen said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know what `lucky' is, and it's good,'' he added. ``It's
something people want.''
</P>
<P>
   That philosophy helped guide Conde Nast, part of Advance
Publications, in picking Lucky as the moniker for its magazine,
covering shopping for young women.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's that moment when you find something on the racks and
it's beautiful, but you wonder whether it will pay out in the
dressing room,'' said Kim France, editor in chief at Lucky in New
York. ``When it does, you feel you got lucky.''
</P>
<P>
   ```Lucky' feels inclusive and happy,'' she added.
</P>
<P>
   Decades ago, ``Be happy, go Lucky'' was a slogan for Lucky
Strike, which flourished in that pre-filter era. The brand faltered
badly after the '50s, despite adding filtered and light styles to
its nonfiltered offerings. But British American Tobacco, which
acquired the U.S. rights to Lucky Strike in 1995, believes a
revival is possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're working to regenerate a fantastic trademark with a great
pedigree and heritage and authenticity that new brands don't
have,'' said Susan Ivey, senior vice president for marketing at the
Brown &AMP; Williamson Tobacco Corp. in Louisville, Ky., the U.S. unit
of British American Tobacco.
</P>
<P>
   The goal, she added, is to create perceptions of Lucky Strike as
``a free-spirited brand with a sense of humor'' by concentrating on
``the name, the package design, the slogans like `It's toasted' and
`LSMFT.'''
</P>
<P>
   The latter slogan _ which stands for ``Lucky Strike means fine
tobacco' _ is the subject of ads by the brand's agency, Bates USA
in New York, part of the Bates Worldwide unit of the Cordiant
Communications Group. One print ad carries the headline ``We
wouldn't say it if we didn't mean it.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown &AMP; Williamson is also sponsoring a contest with the
``LSMFT'' theme, which will award what is being billed as ``a dream
prize beginning with the letters `F' and `T.'''
</P>
<P>
   As for the word beginning with the letter ``L,'' it is ``very
optimistic,'' said Liv &UR;  &LR; Lane, a spokeswoman for General Mills &UR;  &LR; in
Minneapolis, which sells Lucky Charms. ``So it's no surprise it's
becoming more popular these days.''
</P>
<P>
   As if to keep up with the lucky come latelies, General Mills
periodically changes the shapes and colors of the Lucky Charms
``marbits,'' a company term for the marshmallow bits mixed in with
the cereal. The newest one is ``sparkling rainbows,'' Lane said,
which ``for a limited time have replaced the regular rainbow
marbits.''
</P>
<P>
   The idea of ``lucky'' as a good luck charm predates Lucky
Charms, which was introduced in 1964. There was a 1943 film, `` Mr.
Lucky,'' starring Cary Grant as a suave gambler, which inspired a
television series of the same name, sponsored by Lever Brothers,
that ran on CBS during the 1959-60 season. Coincidentally, Lever
sold a Good Luck brand of margarine from 1948 into the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   Does luckocentric marketing always work?
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a saying that you can't just be good, you have to also
be lucky,'' said Marian Salzman, director at the Brand Futures
Group in New York, a trend-watching unit of Young &AMP; Rubicam Inc.
</P>
<P>
   ``In other words, you can do all the work and preparing and
obsessing,'' she added, ``but without a stroke of luck you won't
get there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
