<HEADLINE>
NEWS FROM THE CAMPAIGN TRAIL  

</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.H., N.C., Texas)   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE STATES
</P>
<P>
   WON'T PLEDGE
</P>
<P>
   Might the days of The Pledge in tax-hating New Hampshire be
over? For years, candidates seeking election there have pledged to
block any new broad-based taxes. In her last two campaigns, Gov.
Jeanne Shaheen, a Democrat, took the pledge and stood by it. Now,
seeking a third term, she says she will not renew her vow. ``This
year I cannot make that same promise, whatever the political
price,'' the governor said this week. Declining to take the pledge
has hurt more than one New Hampshire political hopeful over the
years, but the state now faces a crisis: A court has ordered
officials to find a fairer way to finance education, one less
dependent on local property taxes. Four Republicans, a Democrat and
an independent are expected to try to unseat Shaheen, with at least
three of them campaigning for an income tax to pay for schools.
``New times demand new thinking,'' the governor said. ``I will not
arbitrarily rule out any potential solution to the challenge we
face.''
</P>
<P>
   _ CAREY GOLDBERG
</P>
<P>
   GENDER BREAKTHROUGH
</P>
<P>
   North Carolina, which has never elected a woman to any statewide
office higher than secretary of state, is poised for something like
a breakthrough this year. Two women are the major parties' nominees
for the post of lieutenant governor, and women, including a
third-party candidate for governor, will also be on the November
ballot in four other statewide races. The two nominees for the
state's second-highest office are both state senators: Betsy L.
Cochrane, a Republican, was the first woman to hold a leadership
position in the General Assembly, and Beverly M. Perdue, a
Democrat, has been co-chairwoman of the Senate Appropriations
Committee since 1993.
</P>
<P>
   _ DAVID FIRESTONE
</P>
<P>
   THE REFORM PARTY
</P>
<P>
   NO REFORM LINE IN TEXAS
</P>
<P>
   The Reform Party traces its founding to the political dreams of
the Texas billionaire Ross Perot. But the party will not be on the
Texas ballot in November. A member of its national committee from
Texas, Kelly Abt, said this week that under pressure from
Democratic and Republican leaders, the state had set ballot
qualification hurdles so high that Pat Buchanan, the party's likely
presidential nominee, had been forced to run there as an
independent. But the Reform state chairman, Larry Steele, blamed
Buchanan, saying he could have helped get a Reform line on the
ballot had he put up the money and effort to gather the necessary
ballot-petition signatures. Buchanan, who has squabbled with state
Reform leaders around the country (they consider him a hard-right
zealot, not a reformer), says he decided to run as an independent
because he was not confident of the signature-gathering ability of
the Texas Reform Party.
</P>
<P>
   _ ROSS E. MILLOY
</P>
<P>
   TODAY'S SCHEDULES
</P>
