<HEADLINE>
PROPOSED ROAD-BUILDING BAN WOULD AFFECT MARK TWAIN NATIONAL
FOREST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL GRAHAM  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROLLA, Mo. _ A road-building ban proposed by President Clinton
for federal forests could draw more public attention to how small,
roadless woodlands are managed within the Mark Twain National
Forest in Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   Loggers want roads to cut valuable timber, but some
environmental groups say those roads disturb plants and wildlife
and should be limited in public forests. Recreational users want to
ensure that existing trails and roads are kept intact and perhaps
expanded for all-terrain vehicles, horseback riding and hunting
access.
</P>
<P>
   They will begin making their respective cases regarding
Clinton's proposal at public meetings from 7 to 10 p.m. today and
from noon to 3 p.m. Saturday at the University of Missouri-Rolla.
Foresters will talk about the proposal and answer questions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an access issue,'' said Kevin Elliott, Mark Twain's
deputy forest supervisor.
</P>
<P>
   The Mark Twain National Forest is a fragmented collection of
federal lands in southwest, central and southeast Missouri totaling
1.5 million acres. Most tracts already have roads, and officials
don't expect the Clinton proposal, if enacted, to cause major
changes in forest management.
</P>
<P>
   Yet three Mark Twain tracts with a combined 14,400 acres would
be protected from road building by the rule change. The Forest
Service has no immediate plans for timber sales in those areas, but
long-range log harvesting could be affected. The proposal doesn't
prohibit logging, just road building, but without roads timber
harvest would be difficult.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal would prohibit road building or reconstruction in
those three tracts automatically in the Mark Twain's long range
management plan.
</P>
<P>
   But road building in smaller roadless areas would be open to
public debate.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal dictates that management for roadless areas less
than 5,000 acres shall be addressed when a national forest's
long-term management plan is revised, Elliott said. Much of the
Mark Twain forest falls within that category, and its plan is
slated to be revised next year.
</P>
<P>
   So for Missouri, roads across smaller tracts will be the most
contentious issue, as decisions will be made at the local level
with public input.
</P>
<P>
   ``We may have a spring and want to protect natural values around
it, and it's 20 acres, or we may have a 500-acre area we want to
protect,'' Elliott said.
</P>
<P>
   The measure is not designed to close existing trails and
commonly used roads. But forest officials expect those concerns to
surface, plus opposition from those who want more access and
commercial uses in forests.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're basically opposed to the designation of roadless areas
and anything that limits access to the forests,'' said Cory
Ridenhour, executive director of the Missouri Forest Products
Association.
</P>
<P>
   Limiting timber harvest is wasteful forest management and leaves
older woodlands susceptible to disease and fire, Ridenhour said.
</P>
<P>
   However, the Sierra Club's Missouri chapter favors the ban, said
Ken Midkiff, executive director. The group wants to halt illegal
use of old logging roads not designated as official roads on maps.
</P>
<P>
   Policy-makers will receive comments taken from the public at a
meeting in Rolla on June 24.
</P>
<P>
   ``Very often you can't make both sides happy,'' said Charlotte
Wiggins, a spokeswoman for the Forest Service. ``But the emphasis
we have is having both sides at the table and hopefully they'll
listen to each other.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's proposal could be implemented by next year unless it
is derailed by congressional delays or court challenges.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the 43 million acres affected nationally are large
tracts in the West and they are the proposal's key target. In
addition the policy would defer a decision on logging in the
Tongass National Forest in Alaska for five years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-01-00 2328EDT &QL; 
