<SLUG> BC-HEASTER-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A STRONG ECONOMY IS VITAL FOR CLEAN AIR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   When the Supreme Court agreed this week to expand its review of
the Clean Air Act beyond strictly environmental concerns, some
environmentalists reacted as if their cause is something apart from
economic life.
</P>
<P>
   What the high court decided was to further scrutinize the
statute to determine whether it requires the government to consider
the costs as well as the public health benefits of lowering
pollution.
</P>
<P>
   One activist expressed a sense of betrayal, saying the law's
``bedrock principle'' was focusing exclusively on how air pollution
``affects the health of our children and the elderly.''
</P>
<P>
   The problem with this view is how it ignores the fact that no
society can achieve what's best for its members unless that society
has the economic wherewithal to pay for such public goods as
cleaner air or anything that might enhance living conditions. The
resources necessary to finance these public goods can be gained
only from a strong economy.
</P>
<P>
   Children need parents with jobs, and jobs themselves when they
grow up. The elderly, moreover, need economic support provided by
the taxes that workers generate. Therefore, in the case of this
particular issue, any quest ignoring the need to balance
environmental interests with economic interests is doomed to be
less successful than otherwise would be the case. Without putting
too fine a point on it, it's irrational for environmental activists
to pretend economic considerations aren't critical to bettering the
quality of America's environment.
</P>
<P>
   At least half of all Americans aren't old enough to remember
that the environmental movement began to translate its goals into
realities only after the U.S. economy created the prosperity needed
to finance the job. The task of winning World War II and
transforming the economy from a war machine to a consumer
juggernaut left little time or money to worry about pollution.
</P>
<P>
   Industrial cities were often smoky, smog-shrouded hellholes. A
form of gallows humor in such urban areas was the residents' claim
that the only air you could trust to breathe was ``air you could
see.''
</P>
<P>
   Serious environmental cleanup began only after a quarter-century
of postwar prosperity began to throw off enough extra wealth to
finance environmental improvements that were up to then considered
luxuries rather than necessities.
</P>
<P>
   If the court does decide that economic considerations should
play a part in pollution-law compliance considerations, it also
will be a healthy development in curbing regulatory autocracy.
Common-sense restraint has never been much of a consideration when
it comes to environmental regulatory matters. Congress made the
potential for government abuse much greater over the years by
passing legislation that left it up to the regulators to fill in
the blanks when it came to the details of standards and
enforcement.
</P>
<P>
   If some sort of cost-benefit analysis is mandated by the court
to curb the penchant for overzealousness by regulators and their
environmentalist allies, prospects for the long-term success of
environmental improvement will be enhanced.
</P>
<P>
   It's as simple as shortstopping tendencies to weaken the economy
in the name of improving the environment, because economic success
is needed to finance environmental goals.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-01-00 2331EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
