<SLUG> BC-ALCAN-ALGROUP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CANADIAN ALUMINUM MAKER TO BUY SWISS RIVAL 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOHN TAGLIABUE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ Alcan Aluminium of Canada reached an agreement Thursday
to buy Algroup of Switzerland, after an influential Swiss
shareholder group threw its support behind a sweetened deal worth
$4.7 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Alcan had announced in April that it intended to bid for
Algroup, formerly known as Alusuisse Lonza, after European
regulators scuttled a more ambitious three-way deal that would also
have included Pechiney of France.
</P>
<P>
   The breakthrough for Alcan came after the BZ Group, controlled
by the Swiss investor Martin Ebner, said it would tender to Alcan
shares it controls amounting to 34 percent of Algroup.
</P>
<P>
   The BZ Group made that decision after Alcan agreed to reduce the
amount it would pay with its own shares and added cash to the
offer.
</P>
<P>
   Alcan said it would exchange 17.1 of its common shares, plus a
cash payment and special cash dividend totaling 225 Swiss francs,
or about $133, for every Algroup share. That amounts to a 5 percent
increase on what Alcan had originally offered under the three-way
deal, an Algroup official said.
</P>
<P>
   The plan to unite Alcan, Algroup and Pechiney failed after
European Union regulators objected to the dominant position that
the combined companies would have held in Europe, and Alcan refused
to compromise by divesting itself of European factories.
</P>
<P>
   The BZ Group's support makes it likely that the agreement, which
requires 67 percent of Algroup shares for approval, would succeed.
Approval is expected to be announced at a stockholder meeting in
July.
</P>
<P>
   Executives of Alcan and Algroup said their deal is expected to
bring annual cost savings before taxes of about $150 million. The
three-way combination, originally announced in August, had been
expected to generate savings of $600 million.
</P>
<P>
   Based on 1999 results, the two-way combination would have annual
revenue of $12.4 billion, and would rank second in size to Alcoa of
the United States, the global market leader.
</P>
<P>
   Experts say Alcan and Algroup fit well, since Alcan specializes
in bulk aluminum and rolled aluminum sheets, while Algroup has
increasingly focused in recent years on aluminum parts for the
automobile industry, like engine blocks, and specialized aluminum
packaging for the food and drug industries.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-01-00 2332EDT &QL; 
