<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-INSURANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRUDENTIAL PONDERS STAKE IN JAPANESE INSURER
</HEADLINE>
  By STEPHANIE STROM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ The Prudential Insurance Company of America, the largest
life insurer in the United States, has tentatively agreed to take a
stake in the Kyoei Life Insurance Co., one of Japan's many
faltering life insurers.
</P>
<P>
   The two companies announced Thursday afternoon that they had
signed a memorandum of understanding aimed at giving Prudential
roughly a 20 percent stake in Kyoei, while the Japanese insurer
will receive a cash infusion of up to 30 billion yen, or about $277
million at current exchange rates.
</P>
<P>
   The deal is effectively a rescue package for Kyoei. Its ability
to meet obligations and cover losses was rated among the lowest of
Japan's life insurers as of November. At that time, there was a 70
billion yen gap between what Kyoei had promised to pay
policyholders and returns it received on investments.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kyoei started having financial difficulties and came to us to
see if we could help them,'' said Kiyo Sakaguchi, executive vice
president of Prudential and head of its Japanese operations.
</P>
<P>
   Japan's life insurance companies are all struggling, burdened by
policies sold during the economic boom years that promised a high
rate of return. With the economy mired in weakness for much of the
last decade and interest rates at record lows, they cannot now make
enough on their investments to cover those obligations.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last three years, three Japanese life insurers have
failed, and foreign companies have bought four others. On
Wednesday, Japan's regulators forced Daihyaku Mutual, Japan's
15th-largest life insurer, to quit the life insurance business.
</P>
<P>
   But while Prudential is acting as a white knight, its stake in
Kyoei will not entitle it to a management role. ``Our objective is
not to take over Kyoei but to help them with financial support and
technical support,'' Sakaguchi said.
</P>
<P>
   Prudential would become Kyoei's largest shareholder, however,
and as such, might even play a role in the nascent movement here to
increase the awareness and influence of shareholders in corporate
Japan. ``I do see that trend developing, but it may take a little
while before shareholders here really assert their position,''
Sakaguchi said.
</P>
<P>
   The two companies will also form a marketing joint venture to
sell a combination of their insurance policies as well as other
investment products. Prudential's sales and training model will be
used in hopes of making the sales force more professional.
Traditionally, selling life insurance has been a part-time job for
housewives in Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Prudential will also lend an investment expert to Kyoei to help
the Japanese insurer find strategies to improve its return on
investments.
</P>
<P>
   The companies said they hoped to cut costs and increase
efficiency by eliminating redundant operations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-01-00 2333EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
