<SLUG> BC-DAN-HELP-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOSS'S TRIP INTO TRENCHES BRINGS CHANGE AT JOHN KNOX VILLAGE
CENTER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE STAFFORD  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LEE'S SUMMIT, Mo. _ Fifteen months ago, Dan Rexroth stepped away
from his executive desk at John Knox Village. For a month, he, the
boss, became a front-line certified nursing assistant at John Knox
Village's skilled nursing facility.
</P>
<P>
   He changed diapers, sheets and bedpans, took blood pressure
readings and fed bedfast patients. He commiserated with entry-level
workers about physical and emotional demands. And he saw how
managers get so busy managing that they lose touch with their
employees and their customers, clients or patients.
</P>
<P>
   Rexroth vowed to make changes. The Kansas City Star, which wrote
about his down-in-the-trenches interlude in March 1999, revisited
him last week to find out what happened since.
</P>
<P>
   His initial account elicited reaction from all over the country.
Countless front-line workers said they wished their bosses walked
in their shoes for a while, too. Would it make a difference if they
did?
</P>
<P>
   Here's the legacy of one executive's experience in an
entry-level $8-an-hour job.
</P>
<P>
   Then: Rexroth said he wanted to continue making occasional
nursing assistant rounds to keep his patient-care skills sharp and
stay in touch with the staff.
</P>
<P>
   Since then: He tried to do at least one nursing assistant shift
a month in 1999 but hasn't done one at all in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've only managed to go out and pass out meal trays now and
then. It's something I feel bad about,'' he said. ``I'm committed
to do it, but it just seems like I have more than a full-time job
as it is.''
</P>
<P>
   Then: ``This experience has made me committed to getting the
entire staff at all levels involved in resident care,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Since then: Rexroth realized that ordering his managers to pull
temporary job changes or extra shifts would not be an effective
motivator.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew I had to lead by example, and I think that happened,''
he said. ``A lot of the management staff has begun to voluntarily
help out at meal times.''
</P>
<P>
   One midlevel manager convenes a group of front-line employees
monthly to discuss ways to improve residents' quality of life. One
suggestion was to install heat lamps in the bathrooms.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bingo. We did that _ a great example of listening to the front
line.''
</P>
<P>
   Then: Rexroth felt back strain and other physical stresses from
lifting and moving adult patients. He pledged to buy more lifting
devices.
</P>
<P>
   Since then: The staff helped research, test and select several
new kinds of lifting devices. The health center also beefed up its
lifting training program.
</P>
<P>
   This year, the Missouri Division of Aging is giving the Village
Care Center a best-practices award for its lifting program, ``and
we've had our best year ever with our lowest workers' compensation
and injury claims total on record,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Some pieces of lifting equipment cost between $5,000 and
$10,000. A fund-raising auxiliary and some budget allocations have
bought two-thirds of the equipment he wants.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe this would have happened without me seeing the need
firsthand,'' he mused, ``but an impassioned spokesperson makes a
difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Then: Rexroth saw how difficult it was for nursing assistants to
be constantly reassigned to different patients, different units or
different shifts. At the same time, he saw a demand for more
flexible and part-time shifts.
</P>
<P>
   Since then: ``We haven't fully succeeded in that task, but we're
trying not to move people around as much,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Staffing reassignments are necessary when people call in sick or
when people quit the high-turnover jobs. (Turnover a year ago and
now hovers around 50 percent.) The care center is a 24-hour-a-day,
seven-day-a-week operation, and that requires a lot of staff
juggling.
</P>
<P>
   To help minimize unwanted schedule disruptions, he created
part-time, evening ``floater'' positions for nursing assistants who
are paid a premium ($12 to $15 an hour) to fill in wherever needed.
The new positions are ``immensely popular,'' Rexroth said.
</P>
<P>
   Then: Rexroth saw how transportation problems and family needs
sometimes made it difficult or impossible for staffers to get to
work at odd hours in Lee's Summit.
</P>
<P>
   Since then: He's advertising two new staff positions that will
be part-time, management-level jobs with an unusual duty: support
and solve problems for the front-line staff.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're so focused on taking care of our patients that we lose
sight of taking care of our associates, our people who do the
work,'' Rexroth said.
</P>
<P>
   The new managers will be part social worker, part job counselor
and part human relations expert, Rexroth said. ``They will need to
be good communicators who can both relate to the front line and
promote the John Knox philosophy.''
</P>
<P>
   Then: Rexroth worried that the $8-an-hour starting pay for
nursing assistants was not a livable wage and couldn't attract
good-quality workers.
</P>
<P>
   Since then: John Knox Village top managers took no raises this
year, and channeled the money to staff raises. All employees ``were
moved up a bit'' in pay, he said, but starting wages haven't jumped
appreciably. He remains concerned about that.
</P>
<P>
   Then: Rexroth saw that the nursing assistant job constantly
pulled workers in several directions and that it was hard to
prioritize duties.
</P>
<P>
   Since then: The care center added part-time, minimum-wage
positions for area high school students and John Knox Village
residents to help at meal time and provide other non-nursing care.
</P>
<P>
   ``They do things like give water, make beds, straighten up
rooms, deliver flowers, pass meal trays,'' Rexroth said. ``It's an
immense help.''
</P>
<P>
   The hiring of John Knox Village residents took policy changes.
Previously, that was forbidden. But, Rexroth said, it's a good
match for the residents and care center.
</P>
<P>
   There's no official scorecard for changes made since Rexroth's
job-swap experience. He admits that some of the changes may have
occurred without his input. Some can be credited to others' ideas.
</P>
<P>
   But, in his own words, an ``impassioned spokesperson'' helped.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-01-00 2336EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
