<DOCNO> NYT20000601.0454 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-01 23:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2531 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-RAC-RACECOL-COLUMN-LA     06-01 0904
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-RACECOL-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOLIS AVOIDING ARGUMENT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Alex Solis is taking the high road in the argument over Red
Bullet's loss to Fusaichi Pegasus at the Wood Memorial.
</P>
<P>
   That's the only way to go to avoid a collision with Joe Orseno,
Red Bullet's trainer.
</P>
<P>
   Orseno blamed Solis for Red Bullet's second-place finish at New
York's Aqueduct racetrack, contending the jockey tired the
then-undefeated colt by placing him too close to the pace. After
Jerry Bailey rode Red Bullet to an upset victory over Fusaichi
Pegasus in the Preakness Stakes, an emboldened Orseno kept saying
the Wood defeat was Solis' fault.
</P>
<P>
   Solis needn't worry about criticism from Orseno blemishing his
reputation. The California-based Solis, 36, probably has won more
major races than the New York-based Orseno, 44, has entered.
</P>
<P>
   But Solis deserved to defend himself. He began Thursday by
indicating he didn't want a war of words.
</P>
<P>
   ``He sees it one way, I see it another way. I have to respect
his opinion,'' Solis said during the Hollywood Park races. ``You
know me real good _ I'm never going to put anybody down.''
</P>
<P>
   The Panama-born jockey pointed out that before he rode Red
Bullet for the first time in the 1-mile Gotham Stakes March 19 at
Aqueduct, the son of Unbridled had been slow out of the gate in
both of his starts.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I rode him in the Gotham, he (Orseno) asked me to put him
in the race (early),'' Solis said. He followed instructions _
although Red Bullet was in midpack early in the Gotham, he was
never more than two lengths off the lead before surging to victory
on the outside.
</P>
<P>
   Red Bullet figured to run closer to the pace in the Wood on
April 15. It was a 1-mile race, so the pace would be slower. Also,
in the interim, Orseno had given the colt a pair of
fastest-of-the-morning workouts at Belmont Park, a training
maneuver that's bound to inject early speed.
</P>
<P>
   Red Bullet broke sharply in the Wood and was lapped on front-
runner Country Only through quarter-miles run in 23 1/5 seconds, 46
4/5 and 1:10 2/5. Fusaichi Pegasus and jockey Kent Desormeaux ran
them all down in the stretch and won by 4 lengths.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a little keen to go on,'' Solis said of the early going
in the Wood. ``At the moment I had to make a decision, and being
down inside (near the rail) at the time, I decided to stay where I
was. I wound up being second without ever using him. . . . I never
pushed him out of the gate.''
</P>
<P>
   Solis wasn't going to second-guess himself as Orseno did and
keeps doing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I go into a race with a good plan,'' Solis said. ``When things
don't come out like you want, you don't have days to make a
decision.''
</P>
<P>
   One observer who defends Solis is Bobby Frankel, trainer of
Aptitude, who finished a fast-closing third in the Wood, ridden
then by Brice Blanc.
</P>
<P>
   ``The horse (Red Bullet) was coming off a sharp mile race, there
wasn't much pace in the (Wood), and horses were winning on the lead
that day,'' Frankel said Thursday on a conference call with turf
writers. ``Personally, I just thought he got outrun that day.''
</P>
<P>
   Frankel obviously has confidence in Solis.
</P>
<P>
   After riding Aptitude to second place behind Fusaichi Pegasus in
the Kentucky Derby, Solis will be aboard Frankel's colt again in
the Belmont Stakes a week from Saturday. A victory would end a
frustrating stretch for Solis in Triple Crown races _ since winning
the 1986 Preakness with Snow Chief, Solis has gone 0 for 13 in the
3-year-old classics, including seconds with Captain Bodgit (1997),
Victory Gallop (1998) and Aptitude.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's maturing, he's a horse that's really improving,''
Solis said of Aptitude. ``That's one of the things I liked about
him when he went to the Derby. . . . I strongly believe Aptitude is
a better horse going a mile and a half than any of these horses.''
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, although Fusaichi Pegasus might run in the 1-mile
Belmont, Red Bullet has been withdrawn from the race, so Solis
won't have a shot at thorough vindication.
</P>
<P>
   Orseno announced last weekend that he and owner Frank Stronach
decided to save Red Bullet for big races in the future _ the Aug. 6
Haskell Invitational at Monmouth Park, the Aug. 26 Travers Stakes
at Saratoga and the Nov. 4 Breeders' Cup Classic at Churchill
Downs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want to squeeze the lemon dry,'' the trainer said,
borrowing an old line. ``We want to race him as a 4-year-old, and
if you run in a mile-and-a-half race, that knocks you out for three
months. It's pointless.''
</P>
<P>
   But passing up the Belmont _ and a possible rubber match with
Fusaichi Pegasus _ casts Red Bullet and his trainer as villains
rather than heroes of this Triple Crown season. It was one thing to
be a ``fresh horse'' going into the Preakness after skipping the
Derby. It's something else to be a ``fresh horse'' coming out of
the Preakness by skipping the Belmont.
</P>
<P>
   If your horse runs in only one of the three classics, while
Fusaichi Pegasus withstands the rigors of two or all three, then
you're faced with a couple of possibilities: You have an inferior
horse or you did an inferior training job.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Orseno has claimed instead that Red Bullet would be 2 for 2
against Fusaichi Pegasus if not for Alex Solis. The trainer had an
obligation to run his colt in the Belmont and back up his words.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
