<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-READING-TEST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOURTH GRADE TEST SCORES RISE SUBSTANTIALLY ACROSS NEW YORK STATE 
</HEADLINE>
   By ABBY GOODNOUGH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Fourth graders throughout New York state performed
remarkably better this year in the second year of a more rigorous
reading and writing test, with 59 percent passing compared with 48
percent in 1999, education officials said on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Even in New York City, which has long lagged considerably behind
suburban and upstate school districts, 42 percent of fourth graders
passed the test, up from only 33 percent last year. All of the
city's 32 community school districts noted improvement on the test,
which was introduced last year to help prepare students for new
state graduation requirements being phased in over the next four
years.
</P>
<P>
   Richard P. Mills, the state education commissioner, said the
results bolstered his high-profile effort to toughen standards
throughout the state's schools and to hold students accountable
through more demanding standardized tests. But Mills and other
educators acknowledged that the failure rate was still disturbingly
high, with 41 percent of the state's fourth graders still not
reading and writing at grade level.
</P>
<P>
   ``One significant increase is not nearly enough,'' Mills said in
an interview. ``Everything depends on follow-through over a long
period of time.'' Others cautioned against reading too much into
the improved scores, pointing out that this was only the second
year of the new test. It is not unusual for scores to be strikingly
low in the first year a test is given, then rise in the second year
as students and teachers grow more comfortable with the test.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always advisable to look at long-term trends and not get
too excited about short-term changes,'' said Robert Berne, vice
president for academic affairs at New York University.
</P>
<P>
   Last year's results horrified parents and teachers not only in
New York City, but in many wealthy suburban schools whose students
had always scored exceptionally well. Those districts showed the
same substantial improvement as New York City this year. In
Westchester County, 73.1 percent of students passed this year,
compared with 61 percent in 1999. In Nassau County, the percentage
of passing students jumped to 77 percent from 65 percent. And 71
percent of Suffolk County's fourth graders passed this year's test,
compared with 58 percent last year.
</P>
<P>
   There was, however, one less-than-optimistic note. The sharpest
increases in New York City, which aggregated data by race, were
among white and Asian students, who make up only 16 percent and 11
percent, respectively, of the city's 1.1 million schoolchildren.
The scores of black and Hispanic students in New York City improved
less significantly, with only about 6 percent achieving the highest
level of proficiency.
</P>
<P>
   Education officials shed little light on why the fourth graders
fared so much better this year, saying only that students were
spending more time reading and writing, and that teachers were
finally devising methods that work. In addition, principals have
been ``studying data like crazy'' and determining effective
strategies for helping slow learners, Mills said.
</P>
<P>
   Mills and Harold O. Levy, the New York City schools chancellor,
acknowledged that schools were ``teaching to the test,'' but said
they were doing so only by requiring children to spend more time on
basics.
</P>
<P>
   ``This test is not something you can drill for,'' Mills said in
an interview. ``There is nothing to memorize, unless you count
punctuation and grammar. The only way to prepare for these tests is
to read a lot and write a lot, and certainly there is a tremendous
amount of that going on.''
</P>
<P>
   But other educators said that teachers were spending more time
having their students read short passages for comprehension and
answering questions about them. Those drills, the educators said,
were taking time away from reading full books in some schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can drill kids in reading and writing in ways that don't
develop their literacy skills as much as they should,'' said Norman
Fruchter, director of the Institute for Education and Social Policy
at New York University. ``The more they focus on quick
comprehension of short passages, the more the notion of narrative
and context gets lost.'
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
