u s BC-HKN-DEVILS-STARS-NYT &LR;      06-01 0858
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-DEVILS-STARS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HULL SHOOTS, AND TIES SERIES WITH DEVILS
</HEADLINE>
  By JOE LAPOINTE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ Brett Hull
scored the goal that won the Stanley Cup for Dallas last season and
he leads the tournament this season with 11. A veteran who has
proved he is more than just a shooting star, Hull retains the
finishing touch to break open a game _ and close one, too.
<TEXT>
<P>
   He scored on the Stars' first shot Thursday night in the first
period against the Devils and he scored on their last shot with 3
minutes 16 seconds remaining. They were enough to give the Stars a
2-1 victory and a 1-1 tie in the best-of-7 Stanley Cup finals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hull is probably the best pure shooter in the league,'' said
Devils coach Larry Robinson.
</P>
<P>
   The Devils' goal was scored by Alexander Mogilny.
</P>
<P>
   Games 3 and 4 will be played in Dallas, on Saturday and Monday
nights.
</P>
<P>
   Hull's winning goal came on a play that formed on the left-wing
side. Mike Modano pushed the puck past Brian Rafalski on the
Devils' defense. Jere Lehtinen shot it toward Martin Brodeur in the
Devils' net, and Hull, forcing himself ahead of Scott Stevens,
re-directed the path of the puck. It was only the 17th shot against
Brodeur.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson said he thought the play was offside.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas coach Ken Hitchcock said Hull has changed his style on
the ice from his freewheeling youth because scores are lower and
checking is tighter in recent seasons. Hull is more patient in
waiting for his opportunities and willing to implement other
aspects of the game besides shooting.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a big win for this team.'' Hitchcock said. ``This is a
huge win. We've got our building and our fans, where we get pretty
wrapped up.''
</P>
<P>
   Ed Belfour stopped 27 of 28 Devils shots.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars had only one shot on Brodeur in the first 13 minutes
of the game. And it was not a dangerous looking shot. It was just a
routine push from the left-wing circle from Hull, who took a pass
from Modano after a Devils turnover along the wall. But Hull's shot
eluded Brodeur on the glove side at 4:25, giving Hull the playoffs
lead in goals with 10.
</P>
<P>
   The Devils tied it at 1-1 at 12:42 on a goal by Alexander
Mogilny, who beat Belfour on the glove side with a wrist shot after
Scott Gomez set him up. Gomez carried the puck through the neutral
zone and drew three Stars toward him. As they converged, Gomez
kicked the puck ahead with his skate to his stick and then found
his linemate cutting free into the Dallas zone.
</P>
<P>
   There were several incidents of rough play, and a few included
Claude Lemieux, the aggressive right wing of the Devils. In
addition to a holding penalty at 8:20, Lemieux got away with a head
butt against Jon Sim and with removing the helmet of Hull in a
scrum after a whistle.
</P>
<P>
   The second period saw tight checking by both teams. Patrik Elias
and Petr Sykora, the hot wings of the Devils, occasionally forced
themselves free for odd-man rushes. But even those were quickly
stifled by either Belfour or the Dallas backcheckers. Players for
both sides were rigorous about their positioning and careful about
any gambles so that every mistake _ and there were not many _
seemed to stand out.
</P>
<P>
   Derian Hatcher, the Dallas captain and defenseman, said: ``It
was almost like a chess match. It's been a long time since we've
played a game that strategic on both sides.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, Hitchcock discussed how he expected his team
to respond after losing by 7-3 in the series opener here on Tuesday
night.
</P>
<P>
   ``Losing like we did really boils down to a pride factor within
our group,'' Hitchcock said. ``We can't control how New Jersey
plays, but we sure as heck can control how we play. We have got an
awful lot of pride in this organization. We got slapped pretty hard
and we need to respond in the right way.''
</P>
<P>
   Robinson said Game 1 would not be indicative of the entire
series.
</P>
<P>
   ``You are always surprised to score seven goals against a team
like Dallas,'' Robinson said. ``They pride themselves in being a
great defensive team. What you do is you wash away Game 1. I look
at this as a seven-game series. Each game is a series in itself and
so once the game is over with, let's forget about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the league has tried to tighten up its schedule to get
the playoffs finished earlier, they could go as late as June 12
this time. Gary Bettman, the commissioner of the NHL, has said he
hopes to end next year's tournament when the date of the month is
still in single digits.
</P>
<P>
   On a warm and humid day, Robinson was asked about the length of
a season that begins with training camp in early September.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought it was long when we were playing in May,'' he said,
recalling his career as a defenseman with Montreal. ``So, it is
definitely not the way I think that most people would like it. I
know from speaking to a lot of fans that they say that they find it
hard sometimes watching games when it is in the middle of June. But
there is no way getting around it. It's a long season, long
playoffs. The nice thing about it is when you are playing in June,
it means you have gone a long way.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
