u a BC-NY-BLACK-VETERANS-NYT     06-01 0588
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-BLACK-VETERANS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
2 BLACK SOLDIERS GET BRONZE STARS, FOR WORLD WAR II 
</HEADLINE>
   By SHAILA K. DEWAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ After a wait of 55 years, the extra seconds it took
for New York Gov. George Pataki to fumble with the medals and pin
them to Haywood Campbell's suit coat Thursday did not faze the old
soldier.
</P>
<P>
   Dressed in a dark suit coat with brass buttons, with a baseball
cap perched on his head, Campbell, an 82-year-old veteran of World
War II, stood in the central room of the Harlem Armory on Fifth
Avenue with the help of a metal cane, holding his chin up and
forward in a military pose.
</P>
<P>
   The ceremony was small. Yet, for Campbell and a fellow veteran,
Oscar Osborne Jr., 77, it was significant. They each received the
Bronze Star, a military honor they earned during the Battle of the
Bulge in 1945 but were denied because of their race.
</P>
<P>
   They also received the New York State Conspicuous Service Cross,
and Campbell was awarded the New York State Conspicuous Service
Star.
</P>
<P>
   The overdue decorations came after decades during which history
seemed to have been erased. ``We was fighting right along with the
white buddies,'' said Campbell, a staff sergeant. ``We died
together.''
</P>
<P>
   But at the end of the war, the survivors did not bask in the
glory together. Instead, blacks who had volunteered to fight
shoulder to shoulder with whites found that their discharge papers
did not reflect their combat service, instead listing them as
members of units that unloaded supplies or dug graves.
</P>
<P>
   Black soldiers, normally restricted to labor battalions, had
been asked by Gen. Dwight D. Eisenhower to fight after U.S. troops
suffered 75,000 casualties in the Battle of the Bulge. Five
thousand signed up to join the intense fighting at the front. Many
of the 2,221 who were selected had to give up their ranks and fight
as privates.
</P>
<P>
   Osborne was shot in the arm and, after months in the hospital,
discharged. Campbell stayed on the front until the end of the war.
On one day, he said, his squad captured 22 German troops.
</P>
<P>
   Both men said they were among the first in their companies to
volunteer, Osborne to defend American democracy and Campbell
because of his opposition to Hitler.
</P>
<P>
   Another veteran attending the ceremony, Vincent Malveaux, said,
``If you're called to serve in an integrated army, maybe you'd
better answer the call, because this was what the people back home
were fighting for.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite their valor, neither of the medal recipients relished
telling their children about the war days. ``There wasn't much joy
in talking about it,'' Osborne said.
</P>
<P>
   Although their service paved the way for President Truman's
integration of the armed forces in 1948, they and their comrades
suffered the indignity of what Pataki called a ``direct effort to
suppress'' the heroism of blacks in combat. Veterans at the
ceremony said they were unnoted by journalists, left out of
official accounts and denied access to their records.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew he was upset that he came home as a private,'' said
Frances Cobell of her brother, Campbell. ``He was a sergeant.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1949, an announcement came that anyone who served in certain
units during the Battle of the Bulge qualified for the Bronze Star,
usually given on an individual basis. But the 2,221 Negro
Volunteers, as they have become known, did not receive them.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, on the 50th anniversary of Truman's integration of the
armed forces, five volunteers received their medals at the
Pentagon.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-01-00 2348EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
