A2540 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-BRIDG-LINK-KAN &LR;      06-01 0790
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRIDG-LINK-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LENEXA WOMAN SEES A NEED AND FILLS IT _ WITH CASTOFF CASINO
BRIDGES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LEE HILL KAVANAUGH  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ A 130-pound woman moved four 10-ton bridges
on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Never underestimate what one person can do.
</P>
<P>
   It started four years ago, when Margie Burton of Lenexa was
riding her horse at the John Redmond Reservoir in Kansas and was
surprised to discover that the 16-mile trail ended at a steep creek
bed.
</P>
<P>
   There was no bridge.
</P>
<P>
   Burton jumped off her horse and tried to hike down the slope.
Two steps landed her in deep muck. Anyone using the reservoir's
trails must either slop through the creek beds, or hike to a busy
high-speed road, or ask permission from private property owners to
walk on their land.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, a park ranger at the reservoir, about 110 miles
southwest of Kansas City, told Burton that more trails could be
opened with a bridge. But funds were too tight. The park needed a
donation.
</P>
<P>
   So Burton decided to go shopping _ for a bridge.
</P>
<P>
   What do you think you can do about this? You're just one person.
Leave it alone, a voice kept saying in her head.
</P>
<P>
   A few days later, as she dropped her 81-year-old mother off to
gamble at the Argosy Casino in Riverside, she saw them: bridges.
Four of them, resting near the parking lot with weeds crawling up
their sides, their metal braces gleaming.
</P>
<P>
   The bridges were castoffs from the casino, used in its days of
floating up and down the river. Since 1996, the casino hadn't used
them. They were useless hunks of metal, rusting away.
</P>
<P>
   The bridges are big, 55 feet long; 8 feet, 8 inches tall; and 9
feet, 4 inches wide _ plenty wide for a horse and a rider.
</P>
<P>
   Funny, Burton thought. I never noticed them here before.
</P>
<P>
   First, she called Mike Cunningham, facility manager of the
Argosy Casino. He told her she could have the bridges, if she would
move them. Argosy charged Burton $10 for all four.
</P>
<P>
   Later that day at a truck stop, she spotted a semi-tractor
trailer with a long bed. Off she went to see Art Griffin, vice
president of Belger Cartage Service Inc.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's harder to say no to somebody in person,'' she explained
with a laugh.
</P>
<P>
   Griffin agreed to charge a nominal fee to move the bridges, but
Burton would have to find a crane to hoist them onto the trucks.
</P>
<P>
   So Burton called BSC Steel of Kansas City with the same story,
same request. After estimating the bridges' weight, the company
donated the use of a crane and some operators.
</P>
<P>
   Then she called Gary Simmons, the park ranger at John Redmond
Reservoir, to tell him the news.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gary, I found your bridges,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Simmons didn't speak for several seconds.
</P>
<P>
   ``It took me aback when she told me,'' he said. ``I was thinking
in terms of several months down the road _ maybe _ not several
days. We've been needing these for years.''
</P>
<P>
   The bridges will give the reservoir an additional 14 miles of
continuous trails and make 1,500 more acres accessible. Simmons
expects the bridges to be in use by next spring.
</P>
<P>
   Two of them will be installed at the creeks that blocked Burton
and her horse before: East Hickory Creek and West Hickory Creek,
located on the east side of the dam. They'll put up the third at
the Riverside West recreational area, a campground just south of
the dam.
</P>
<P>
   The fourth bridge is going to Burlington, on the south edge of
the town where a hiking//biking trail is being considered.
</P>
<P>
   ``So many people will benefit from these bridges. Thousands of
hikers, mountain bikers, horseback riders, fishermen and hunters,''
Simmons said. ``...Margie is amazing. All you have to do is mention
what you need to her and she goes out and gets them.''
</P>
<P>
   Simmons couldn't think of anything else the park needs now,
except for more visitors. Last year, 200,000 people used the park.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday morning at the Argosy Casino, the crane creaked and
groaned under the weight of the first bridge. As the crane lifted
the bridge on its side, then onto the flatbed truck, Burton danced
a jig, twirling and prancing, ending with a fit of giggles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look, look, look! This is just great! Amazing how they can
lift this heavy metal up like that,'' said Burton, 50, who is a
competitive endurance horseback rider. Last year, Burton and a
friend, Patti Crawford, 58, organized the American Royal Centennial
Trail Ride from St. Joseph to Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, all the time I was asking people, I kept thinking,
`What can I do? I'm just one person,' '' Burton said. ``Well, this
is an example of a whole lot of one persons. This taught me if we
all do just a little bit we can accomplish great things.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even one person.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-01-00 2356EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
